the average California family saw its real income sink in the
1990s, making it poorer than families elsewhere in the nation,
according to a Federal Reserve report to be released Monday. BY SAM
ZUCKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MESSAGING _ Instant messaging could become bigger than e-mail.
If only it worked as easily. Instant messaging, or IM, has grown in
popularity as fast as e-mail did a few years ago, with more than a
third of online Americans using it weekly, according to Forrester
Research. But many messaging companies complain that the growth and
development of instant messaging is threatened by a lack of
interoperability. Specifically, they blame AOL, by far the market
leader, for resisting initiatives to enable the different systems
to talk to one another. By CARRIE KIRBY.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY _ American Internet users want stronger protection for
their online privacy and sanctions for those who violate it, but
most have little understanding of the mechanisms that threaten it
or the tools by which they could protect themselves. Those are
among the conclusions of a report released Sunday by the Pew
Internet &AMP; American Life Project, a Washington, D.C., nonprofit
group funded by the Pew Charitable Trusts. By HENRY NORR.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL _ Intel Corp. this week is disclosing technical details of
a new processor design that will likely dominate the PC market for
the next seven to 10 years. By HENRY NORR.
</P>
<P>
   BIOSCOPE (COLUMN) _ A panel of scientists at the National
Institutes of Health spent two days last week bemoaning the
conflicts of interests that are growing more frequent in medical
research. Nowadays it's routine for university scientists to forge
ties with private firms. Some take modest consulting gigs. Others
do industry-funded research. In many instances, academics become
entrepreneurs themselves, patenting discoveries and starting firms.
What brought last week's NIH panel together is the sad fact that as
academic entrepreneurship becomes de rigueur, so are the instances
when greed pushes professors to become unethical. COLUMN BY TOM
ABATE.
</P>
<P>
   TECH21 (COLUMN) _ Say what you will about Apple Computer, its
chief executive officer or the Macintosh _ and I've had my share of
problems with all three _ Steve Jobs and company continue to put
the PC industry to shame on several fronts. The latest example is
the Power Mac G4 Cube, a new model that began reaching dealers and
users last week. Analysis of G4 Cube plus discussion of new Palm
handheld. COLUMN BY HENRY NORR.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTING (COLUMN) _ Answers to readers questions regarding
online investing. COLUMN BY HARRY DOMASH.
</P>
<P>
   IDEADOLLAR _ San Francisco entrepreneur Mark Turrell wants to
give you a penny for your thoughts. Actually, he will pay up to
$100 plus 15 percent of future revenues for really good ones.
Through his Web site, IdeaDollar.com, people can submit their ideas
in exchange for gift certificates at online stores. Turrell has
already purchased rights to develop such gems as the laminated
shower poster and talking dinnerware that tells blind people what
they are about to eat. Since December 1999, the company has bought
1,500 ideas and awarded about $8,000 in gift certificates. BY
CARRIE KIRBY.
</P>
