<SLUG> BC-MESSAGING- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY CAN'T WE TALK?  _  AS INSTANT MESSAGING TAKES OFF, AOL RESISTS
COOPERATING WITH THE LITTLE GUYS 
 
</HEADLINE>
  By CARRIE KIRBY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; c &LR; .2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco _ Instant messaging could become bigger than
e-mail. If only it worked as easily.
</P>
<P>
   Internet executive Peter Schoenke spends his workdays exchanging
instant messages about a project with a collaborator who sits in
another part of the office.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of the communication at Broadband Sports, the
Santa Monica company where he works, takes place using America
Online's Instant Messenger. But when he wants to send a quick note
to his girlfriend, Schoenke must turn to a different
instant-message program. And to contact certain friends, he has to
launch a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have too many programs running, it slows the computer
down,'' Schoenke said. ``It would be great if they could all be on
one system.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging, or IM, has grown in popularity as fast as
e-mail did a few years ago, with more than a third of online
Americans using it weekly, according to Forrester Research. Three
million users sign up every month, according to an industry
estimate. Forrester predicts that 46 percent of Fortune 1000
companies will use IM by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But many messaging companies complain that the growth and
development of instant messaging is threatened by a lack of
interoperability. Specifically, they blame AOL, by far the market
leader, for resisting initiatives to enable the different systems
to talk to one another. AOL has as many as 170 million users.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike e-mail or the telephone system, where anyone with a phone
or an e-mail address can contact anyone else, instant messengers
are closed systems, where users can only contact other members of
the same service. Many users end up running two or three IM
programs at once to communicate with friends who use different
systems. It's like having several telephones, each of which can
only talk to customers of AT&AMP;T, MCI or Sprint. Users complain that
it's cumbersome to switch back and forth among several windows, and
running extra software can slow down or crash a PC's system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has clearly disadvantaged us and other independent
companies,'' said Ross Bagully, chief executive officer of Tribal
Voice. His company's IM product, PowWow, has 8 million users.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Voice is one of nine IM companies that plan to come out
with a standard next week that would make it possible for users of
any of their systems to contact one another. The group, called
IMUnified, hopes to implement its interoperability standard by the
end of the year. The group includes Internet leaders such as
Microsoft's MSN Messenger Service and Yahoo's Messenger, but,
conspicuously, not AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Interoperability could become an issue for regulators as they
decide whether to approve AOL's pending merger with Time Warner. In
a hearing last month, the Federal Communications Commission
listened to Tribal Voice CEO Bagully's complaints that AOL is
blocking interoperability for its own benefit. AOL told the FCC
that it is working toward making its system interoperable with its
competitors, but that it wants to move slowly in order to protect
its users' privacy and security. Last week, the FCC asked AOL to
turn over all IM documents created since the merger was announced
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also asked Time Warner to confirm whether its chairman,
Gerald Levin, called IM the most valuable asset of a merged
AOL-Time Warner. AOL's competitors claim Levin said so at a recent
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced 10 years ago as the Buddy List, a part of AOL's
regular service, IM has long been popular with chatty teenagers. In
1996, ICQ introduced a messenger service that anyone could join for
free, and popularity grew. (AOL later acquired ICQ, but the two
systems remain incompatible.) Other companies, including Yahoo and
the Microsoft Network, introduced their own messengers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, proponents say, the medium has the potential to surpass
e-mail in popularity, but not just because it's a faster mode of
online communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the tip of the iceberg,'' said Margaret Heffernan,
chief executive of iCast, a Woburn, Mass., company that integrates
instant messaging with online entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Instant-messaging systems are branching out into other
interactive services like voice chat and file trading, such as MP3
music files. It's also possible to send instant messages to
wireless devices. Airline passengers could soon receive news of
delayed flights by instant messages to their handheld devices.
</P>
<P>
   Heffernan predicts instant messaging will be integrated into
every part of the Internet, business and entertainment, in large
part because of innovations in IM:
</P>
<P>
   -- ICast offers a combination media player and instant
messenger, which enables allows  &LR; users to listen to Internet radio
or watch a Madonna video online and message friends at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   -- Most IM programs let users trade files, such as Microsoft
Word documents or MP3 music files. About 2,000 local bands use
iCast to distribute MP3s of their latest recordings to fans.
</P>
<P>
   -- A program called Aimster makes it possible for users of AOL's
AIM to search one another's music collections and share files,
working much like the controversial Napster file-sharing program.
The difference is that Napster users swap songs with thousands of
strangers, whereas Aimster users trade only with people on their
AIM buddy list.
</P>
<P>
   -- Interactive television systems such as AOLTV let friends
miles apart chat while watching shows together.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tribal Voice's ``white board'' enables users to trade
hand-drawn diagrams or sketches while chatting, promising to make
IM an even more valuable tool for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   IMUnified's plan for interoperability would let users who hold
accounts with several IM services access those accounts through a
single interface. For example, if a user wants to communicate with
friends who are divided among Tribal Voice, Yahoo Messenger and MSN
Messenger, the user could sign up for accounts with each service,
then access them all through Yahoo Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would be considered a temporary fix until the Internet
Engineering Task Force issues permanent standards, which could
happen later this year.
</P>
<P>
   AOL says that while it wants interoperability, it doesn't like
IMUnified's plan for a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coalition is putting more of an emphasis on speed than on
consumer safety, and our focus is on users' security,'' said Trish
Primrose, an AOL spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said the industry should wait for the permanent standard,
which has been mired in a task force committee for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   But IMUnified members say AOL's calls for security are a cover
for what the corporation really wants _ to stall interoperability
and preserve its advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that there are privacy and security risks involved in
using IM. Like e-mail, instant messaging can be used to send spam
and transmit viruses. Hackers have broken into instant messaging
accounts and used them to send forged messages. Conceivably,
letting users communicate with a larger pool of people would
increase the frequency of problems.
</P>
<P>
   But IM's risks are no greater than e-mail's, said Dave Crocker,
an Internet consultant who is co-authoring one of the Internet task
force's interoperability proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Crocker questioned AOL's security concerns, saying, ``What is it
about IM that ought to make it any more dangerous? We certainly
seem to be able to live with the risks that we have with e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, several companies have made it possible
for their customers to send instant messages to users of AOL's
services, only to be blocked by AOL. Last Tuesday, AOL blocked an
IM service called Odigo for the 17th time. AOL says trying to send
instant messages to its customers without its permission is ``akin
to hacking.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 10 percent of the market share by their own estimate,
AOL's unified competitors may not pose the behemoth much of a
challenge. But for AOL, dragging its feet may make it look bad _
especially to those who already see the biggest online service as a
bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may hinder them in shedding the perception of not being a
fair player,'' said Lydia Loizides, an analyst for Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
