HIGH USER ANXIETY OVER NET PRIVACY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By HENRY NORR
</P>
<P>
   &LR; c &LR; .2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
American Internet users want stronger protection for their online
privacy and sanctions for those who violate it, but most have
little understanding of the mechanisms that threaten it or the
tools by which they could protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the conclusions of a report released Sunday by
the Pew Internet &AMP; American Life Project, a Washington, D.C.,
nonprofit group funded by the Pew Charitable Trusts. The study is
based on a phone survey in May and June of 2,117 Americans, of whom
1,017 were Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Project researchers found that an overwhelming majority of
Internet users _ 84 percent _ are concerned about businesses or
strangers getting personal information about them or their
families. An even larger percentage _ 94 percent _ say Internet
firms and their top executives should be punished if they violate
users' privacy online.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only 54 percent said they are concerned about
getting a computer virus when downloading information.
</P>
<P>
   The study has a margin of error of three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Some 86 percent of those surveyed said they favor ``opt-in''
rules that would require companies to ask for permission before
using people's personal information. In contrast, Web advertising
companies favor the ``opt-out'' approach, under which companies
consider themselves free to collect and use personal information
unless users take the initiative to protect their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``opt-out'' approach was just accepted by the Clinton
administration and the Federal Trade Commission during negotiations
with a consortium of Web advertising companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet users want the Golden Rule of the Internet to be:
`Don't do anything unto me unless I give you permission,' '' said
Lee Rainie, director of the research project, in a statement
announcing the report's release.
</P>
<P>
   Only 27 percent of users said they agree with the main
justification offered by Web companies for tracking users' online
behavior: that such information enables them to provide information
tailored to the users' specific interests. Twice as many users _ 54
percent _ said they consider such tracking harmful because it
invades their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   While more than 4 out of 5 Internet users want rules to govern
the tracking of users' activities online, most are apparently wary
of having the government step in. Among those who said there should
be such rules, only 24 percent said the federal government should
set them; half said the people who use the sites should set the
rules, while 18 percent were willing to leave the responsibility to
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, most users apparently don't have much grasp
of how online tracking works. Among Internet users in the survey,
56 percent were unable to identify the primary tracking tool, a
type of file known as a ``cookie.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the anxiety about tracking the study reveals, only
10 percent of Internet users said they have set their browsers to
reject cookies. (The report does not note that disabling cookies
makes it difficult or even impossible to access many popular
sites.)
</P>
<P>
   The full report will be posted at  &LR; www.pewinternet.org. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
