<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
INTEL REINVENTS PENTIUM ARCHITECTURE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By HENRY NORR
</P>
<P>
   &LR; c &LR; .2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
San Francisco _ Intel Corp. this week is disclosing technical
details of a new processor design that will likely dominate the PC
market for the next seven to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The next-generation ``microarchitecture,'' or internal processor
design, will reach users first in the Pentium 4, a chip that will
begin showing up in high-end desktop PCs this fall. During the
following year Intel will gradually move the new design into
mainstream, low-end and notebook PC markets.
</P>
<P>
   The new core design, which the company has dubbed NetBurst, is
Intel's first since it rolled out its ``P6'' architecture in the
Pentium Pro processor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company has dramatically increased clock speeds and
added a variety of new features in its subsequent chips _ the
Pentium II and III and the low-end Celeron _ they have all been
based on the P6 core.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the new design hasn't been a secret _ at the
semiannual Intel Developers Forum in February, the company showed
off a prototype based on it, code-named Willamette, running at 1.4
gigahertz, 50 percent faster than the fastest Pentium III available
at the time. In June it announced the Pentium 4.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, however, the company has offered only scanty
information about the chip's internal design.
</P>
<P>
   That will change when the forum convenes again this week, this
time in San Jose. Some 5,000 attendees are expected, most of them
developers, and they will get an earful about the Pentium 4 as well
as the company's other new chip, the server-oriented Itanium, and
its growing portfolio of networking products.
</P>
<P>
   In an advance briefing for reporters Friday, Albert Yu, senior
vice president and general manager of the Intel Architecture Group,
claimed that the Pentium 4 will be ``by far the highest-performance
processor for desktop PCs'' when it comes out this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Intel chips have delivered more processing speed
than those from competitors such as Advanced Micro Devices, and
that technical lead has given Intel a virtual lock on the lucrative
high end of the PC market. During the past year, however, AMD's
Athlon chip has matched and at times exceeded the performance of
the Pentium III and won support from a number of PC-makers who were
loyal customers of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium 4, Yu said, will have 42 million transistors, up
from 28 million in the Pentium III. Among other technical
enhancements, it will feature a ``front-side bus,'' or data channel
to the computer's memory, that operates at 400 megahertz _ three
times the speed of the same element in the Pentium III _ that will
enable it to transfer 3.2 gigabytes of data per second.
</P>
<P>
   In the NetBurst microarchitecture, the execution of each
instruction is broken down into 20 steps _ four times as many as in
the original Pentium and twice as many as in the P6 core.
Paradoxically, adding extra stages _ a technique known in processor
lingo as ``lengthening the pipeline'' _ can improve overall
performance because it allows designers to simplify the chip's
circuitry, which in turn makes it possible to run the chip at
higher frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   Yu said the Pentium 4 will debut this fall at a speed of at
least 1.4 gigahertz, but he added that the design is ``very
scalable to higher frequencies in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Some instructions will be processed at a much higher rate. Yu
revealed that basic arithmetic operations like addition and
subtraction _ among those most commonly used in program code _ will
be handled in a new ``rapid execution engine'' operating at twice
the frequency of the rest of the chip.
</P>
<P>
   The NetBurst architecture can handle six instructions
simultaneously on a sustained basis, according to Doug Carmean, the
chip's principal architect. Its longer pipeline also gives it more
opportunities to improve its efficiency by shuffling the order in
which instructions are processed.
</P>
<P>
   These new features will improve performance even for existing PC
programs. Developers writing new code or optimizing their previous
products for the new chip will also be able to take advantage of
144 new instructions designed to improve performance on such tasks
as graphics and multimedia processing, data encryption and
compression.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of INTEL21 (9256 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In response to suggestions that today's processors are already
more than fast enough for the tasks most users ask them to perform,
Yu insisted that the benefits of the new chips will be readily
apparent to users, even in seemingly basic tasks such as displaying
Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   The extra performance will be especially welcome, he said, as
users increasingly take on more demanding tasks such as photo
editing, video encoding, speech recognition and processing
streaming media. In the business world, he said, the extra power
will help with e-commerce applications, data mining and
visualization, computer-based telephony and real-time data
encryption.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's press briefing, officials of Santa Clara's Intel
used pre-release PCs with 1.4-gighertz Pentium 4 processors to
demonstrate 3-D animations &LR;  of objects such as a dinosaur, a school
of fish and an armoire.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the moving images were created with Shockwave, an
Internet animation technology developed by Macromedia of San
Francisco. The company said last month that it would add Intel 3-D
technology to future versions of its Shockwave Player, which it
claims is the most widely deployed multimedia player on the Web,
with 137 million users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
