<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7562 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-SFCHRON &LR;      08-21 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYH-DOLE ACT SET COLLISION COURSE FOR U.S. INTERESTS, ETHICS
(COLUMN) &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM ABATE &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
San Francisco _ A panel of scientists at the National Institutes of
Health spent two days last week bemoaning the conflicts of
interests that are growing more frequent in medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays it's routine for university scientists to forge ties
with private firms. Some take modest consulting gigs. Others do
industry-funded research. In many instances, academics become
entrepreneurs themselves, patenting discoveries and starting firms.
</P>
<P>
   What brought last week's NIH panel together is the sad fact that
as academic entrepreneurship becomes de rigueur, so are the
instances when greed pushes professors to become unethical. The
transgression may be suppressing an unfavorable finding to please a
private funder, or in the most extreme case, performing drug
experiments that put human subjects in situations of unacceptable
risk.
</P>
<P>
   The most troublesome thing about these conflicts is that I see
them as the outgrowth of a deliberate national policy _ a policy
that is partly responsible for the prosperity we enjoy today.
</P>
<P>
   This point was brought home to me a couple of weeks ago, when a
wire alert crossed my computer screen. A Bay Area firm had just
gotten government approval to sell a new drug for attention deficit
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The alert met my criteria for business news. It promised to have
a large impact on the company and its shareholders. Best of all, it
was a drug for ADD, a condition that people like to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem. I knew diddly squat about ADD, and
had just two hours to submit my story. With the clock ticking, I
phoned a my &LR; local research university and said: ``Get me an
independent ADD expert!''
</P>
<P>
   You would be surprised how often such reportorial chutzpah pays
off. Soon enough I was on the line with a helpful professor who
started our discussion by disclosing that he was a paid consultant
on the very drug on which I was seeking independent expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, at least I got a quick, cogent understanding of ADD,
how it is diagnosed and misdiagnosed, how current drugs do or don't
work, and how the new drug was supposed to work different or
better. Helpful to the last, the professor ended our chat by
pointing me to another university scientist who, he said, was both
expert and not affiliated with the firm.
</P>
<P>
   I tracked down the second expert and explained my desire for an
independent assessment _ only to learn that this professor also had
a consulting relationship with the company in question.
</P>
<P>
   By then I had no more time to comb the ranks of academe, looking
for the unaffiliated expert. My story quoted the two sources and
noted their relation to the project.
</P>
<P>
   I recount this not because I think the company or the professors
did anything wrong. Likewise, the professors were responding to a
clear national imperative to put their expertise to work in the
economy. Washington beamed this message to academia 20 years ago,
when the Bayh-Dole Act became the law of the land.
</P>
<P>
   This landmark legislation allowed universities for the first
time to patent inventions that flowed from federally funded
research. An article titled ``The Kept University'' in the March
issue of the Atlantic Monthly explained the backdrop for the act.
Factories were closing. Imports were putting Americans out of work.
There was a fear across the land that America was losing its
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   The act was intended to reverse this economic slide by pushing
federally funded research out of academia, where it might do some
good. Along those same lines, many universities enacted policies
that allowed professors to share in the royalties from their
patented discoveries. It became common for academics to license
their own inventions, secure venture capital and start companies to
commercialize their work.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Bayh-Dole succeeded brilliantly. A drive through
Silicon Valley is testimony to its impact. Sun Microsystems, Cisco
Systems, Silicon Graphics and other firms too numerous to count all
trace their origins to some research spawned on a university and
fertilized by venture capital. Every dot-com in creation owes a
debt of gratitude to browser software created in a federally funded
computer research lab.
</P>
<P>
   Although high tech has benefited from Bayh-Dole and, in turn,
catalyzed the Northern California economy, I would argue that the
act has had its most profound impact on biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. High-tech companies can bring out new products in
six to 12 months. Two years is a long product cycle. But it seldom
takes less than five or six years to bring out a new biotech drug.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology represents an attempt to understand the human
body, the most sophisticated living machine we have ever
encountered. To do biotechnology is to reverse-engineer this
marvelous creation.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a game that can be played only with cadres of
graduate students, working in spotless laboratories, using
multimillion-dollar instruments, paid for by a patient university
that isn't going to pink-slip the lab if the experiment takes five
years instead of three.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, I wrote about a report from the California
Healthcare Foundation, a biotech lobby group. The report said 2,500
firms and 212,000 employees derive their livelihoods from
biomedical discovery. And the central, irreplaceable feature of
what the report called ``California's bioscience ecosystem'' were
its research universities.
</P>
<P>
   In short, we have built a world in which conflicts of interest
between academia and industry in biotechnology are unavoidable. I
see no way to turn back the clock to the days of the Ivory Tower,
especially not if you accept my argument that we owe much of our
current prosperity to the Kept University. As employees, as
shareholders, as patients, we have all benefited from the cozy
relationships between academia and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Given that reality, the real questions are which conflicts we
consider minor and tolerable, so that we may continue to enjoy the
benefits of industry-university collaboration? Which conflicts are
impermissible under any circumstances? And finally, how do we
police this situation?
</P>
<P>
   If only we had a few commandments to make it all clear. Of
course, it's not that easy. But here in the center of this
biomedical beehive, at the nexus of the new economy, we must worry
about the moral health of a system that has kept us fat, fed and
happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7563 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TECH21-SFCHRON &LR;      08-21 2133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE INGENUITY CUBED (COLUMN) &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  By HENRY NORR &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
San Francisco _ Say what you will about Apple Computer, its chief
executive officer or the Macintosh _ and I've had my share of
problems with all three _ Steve Jobs and company continue to put
the PC industry to shame on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example is the Power Mac G4 Cube, a new model that
began reaching dealers and users last week, a month after Jobs
unveiled it at the Macworld Expo show. For the last 10 ten  &LR; days
I've been trying out a unit that Apple loaned me for evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   In another couple of weeks I'll have to give it back, and I'm
not looking forward to that day. I've tried out and appreciated
most of Apple's recent models, but the Cube is the one I really
wish I could keep.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of performance and features, it doesn't break
significant new ground. What it offers above all is a quality all
too rarely associated with desktop computers: elegance.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly a matter of appearance. Its design _ a silvery box
about 7.7 inches on each dimension, suspended inside a clear
plastic stand that holds it a couple of inches off the desk _ is as
much a departure from the boring beige box tradition as the iMac.
But I for one find the new model's minimalist styling much more
appealing than the iMac's pudgy curves, and I suspect many others,
particularly in my generation, will feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   It looks particularly good with Apple's sleek new 15-inch
flat-panel Studio Display, which also rests in a clear-plastic
easel-style stand.
</P>
<P>
   But good looks aren't the only virtue of the Cube's design. Its
compactness translates into appreciable savings of desktop real
estate _ a very concrete benefit for those of us who need every
available square inch for our clutter. The new Apple Display
Connector, which sends video signals, electric power and USB data
to the monitor through one cable, also helps thin out the cable
maze that usually accompanies any desktop computer, provided that
you buy one of Apple's latest displays.
</P>
<P>
   (If you prefer to hook up a conventional monitor, the Cube also
has a standard VGA connector; the only people out of luck, until
some third-party developer rises to the occasion, are those who
want to connect flat panels with ``DFP'' or ``DVI'' interfaces _
including those Apple sold until last month.)
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the Cube is quiet _ dead silent, in fact, except for
an occasional soft chirp when it is reading or writing its hard
drive. That's because, like the latest iMacs, it has no fan _ it is
cooled entirely by convection, through a chimney that runs
vertically through the Cube, venting through an oval-shaped grate
on top.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of a busy office, you hardly hear the sound of an
average PC. But in a quiet den or study, the constant hum of a fan
can be an annoyance. You might not even be conscious of it _ we've
all been habituated _ but I bet you will notice the difference if
you try out the Cube.
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, knowing my own housekeeping habits, I was worried
about what would happen if a book or magazine somehow found itself
on top of the Cube's vent. After some experimentation, I'm happy to
report that the answer is ``nothing dire'' _ the machine simply
drops into its low-power ``sleep'' mode.)
</P>
<P>
   Apple has also eliminated the most outstanding shortcoming of
its recent desktop models _ its hockey-puck mouse, which looked
great but was a real pain in day-to-day use. Like Microsoft's
optical mice, Apple's new Pro model works great on almost any
surface. The matching Pro keyboard is also a huge improvement,
except that its cable is too short. Surely, Apple could supply one
that's a foot or two longer, so users would have more flexibility
about positioning their CPUs and monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Cube is not without more-serious faults, too. Most
obviously, at $1,799 without a monitor, it's pretty pricey by
today's standards, including Apple's prices on the iMac and other
G4s. For that amount of money, the machine ought to at least
include more than the 64 megabytes of RAM it now comes with,
especially considering the Mac OS, at its default settings, now
takes up nearly 30 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   I also wish Apple would offer a CD-RW drive _ one that can write
and rewrite discs that can be played in CD-ROM and CD music drives
_ at least as an optional alternative to the standard DVD-ROM
drive. Considering that there's almost no content published in DVD
format except movies, a drive that could be used for backing up,
sharing large files and burning music discs would have a lot more
value to those of us who have no desire to watch movies at our
desks.
</P>
<P>
   But these are all pretty minor gripes, especially when you
compare what the PC industry continues to offer by way of
industrial design. Two years after the introduction of the iMac,
the only change that has spread to other manufacturers is the use
of color _ Compaq and Hewlett-Packard in particular have made
replaceable accent panels made of colored plastic a standard
feature in their consumer models.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, PC-makers still don't seem capable of
creating systems with any real aesthetic appeal. Intel has been
showing off innovative ``concept PCs'' since shortly after the iMac
appeared, but most of them were notable mostly for their weirdness,
and none has made it to market. Several top manufacturers did
attempt last year to follow Apple's example with more-stylish
machines, but none of them quite pulled it off. Indeed, in recent
months Compaq, Dell, Gateway and NEC have all had to abandon
heavily hyped designs that flopped in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Apple, too, has had a few miscues _ I didn't think much of last
year's blue-and-white G3s. But on the whole, the company's record
for combining style and substance is unmatched. That has been great
for Mac fans as well as Apple shareholders; for the Windows world,
well, some PC-maker is bound to get it right one of these years.
</P>
<P>
   PALM VS. HANDSPRING: In the wake of Palm's announcement of its
new entry-level handheld, the m100, several friends and readers
have asked for my opinion about how it stacks up against
Handspring's popular Visor line of low-cost Palm clones.
</P>
<P>
   In a word, my choice is Palm _ at least until Handspring comes
out with new models sometime later this year. When the Visors first
appeared, I gave them a glowing review, because at that time they
had three advantages over their Palm predecessors: They were
cheaper, they were better looking (mainly because they came in a
choice of five colors) and they were more expandable.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't long before Palm matched its licensee's prices,
with a low-end model containing 2 megabytes of memory (first the
IIIe, now the m100) at $149 and an 8-megabyte version (the IIIxe)
at $249. In fact, for those who want to share data between the
handheld and a PC, Palm has actually had a price advantage for some
time, because all its models include a way to connect the devices _
a cradle with the older models, a HotSync cable with the m100 _
while in Handspring's case you have to spend $179 to get a cradle.
</P>
<P>
   (Owners of iMacs or other recent Apple models, take note: Palm's
standard cables and cradles still use a conventional serial port,
and the optional USB kit needed to connect to your Mac is a steep
$39.95. That makes Handspring, which uses USB for its cradles, a
better bet for you.)
</P>
<P>
   As for style, this is obviously a matter of personal preference.
But in my book, first place now goes to the m100, with its gentle
curves, intriguing porthole and optional color faceplates.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves expandability as the one strong card in Handspring's
hand. The slot in all Visor models, known as the Springboard, is a
clever design; Palm's low-end models have no equivalent, and even
at the high end Palm hasn't had a consistent approach to expansion.
(That should change in the future because the company has endorsed
a standard called the Secure Digital card, but the first products
incorporating this slot aren't due until next year.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Springboard is that there just aren't many
modules available for it _ fewer than a dozen in all, according to
Handspring's list
( &LR; www.handspring.com/products/springboardnews.asp &LR; ). And mostly
they're not all that compelling. The list includes a couple of
phone-line modems (which cost almost as much as the Visor itself),
a few games, a $200 electronic version of the Physician's Desk
Reference, a device that turns the Visor into a universal remote
control and some memory cards, one of which also makes the device
vibrate, pager-style, when a calendar alarm goes off.
</P>
<P>
   Of the available Springboard modules, the only one with any
particular appeal to me is the Eyemodule, a tiny device that turns
the Visor into a digital camera. I recently tried one out, and it's
definitely nifty. But at $150 it's not exactly cheap, and with
resolution limited to 320 by 240 pixels, it's more toy than serious
tool.
</P>
<P>
   One of these years, the really interesting modules Handspring
has promised _ cell phones and wireless radios _ will probably show
up. But given Palm's much larger overall market share, it's likely
that the same products or equivalents will also be offered for at
least some Palm-branded models.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of TECH21-0 (9993 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  That's true, for example, in the digital camera case. The
Eyemodule is available only for the Visor, but Palm users who want
to take pictures can turn instead to Kodak's PalmPix camera. It's a
little more expensive ($179) and not nearly as petite, but with
resolution up to 640 by 480 pixels, it can take pictures you are
more likely to have some real use for.
</P>
<P>
   In short, I don't think the Springboard amounts to a decisive
advantage for most users.
</P>
<P>
   There's one other point that differentiates the Visor and the
m100, but I'm not sure which way it cuts. The latter's touchscreen
touch screen  &LR; is made of plastic, in contrast to the glass used in
the Visor and other Palm models. That makes the m100 lighter, and
it makes the screen less likely to break if you drop the unit.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger, the m100's display and Graffiti
writing surface are both appreciably smaller than the Visor's or
other Palm models'. The resolution is the same (160 by 160 pixels
in all cases), so you get just as much information per screen _
it's just shrunken down on the m100. Combined with relatively low
contrast, that makes the Palm pretty difficult to read in some
environments, particularly places _ my living room, for example _
that don't have bright overhead lighting.
</P>
<P>
   But the Visor screen is nothing to write home about, either. If
your eyesight makes legibility an important issue, you would
probably be happier with a color model. (Color isn't just for
pretty pictures, as the vendors' ads imply _ it dramatically
increases contrast, which to my eyes is the most important factor
in the readability of text.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, color and its benefits aren't available at
entry-level prices _ the color Palm IIIc is $399, and the Palm
OS-based color device Sony is cooking up is expected to be even
more expensive. (It's supposed to be announced formally next week
and ship in October.)
</P>
<P>
   The rival Pocket PC camp _ Casio, Compaq and Hewlett-Packard,
all of which offer handhelds based on the Microsoft operating
system formerly known as Windows CE _ has moved almost entirely to
color, and their screens are even better than the Palm IIIc's. Then
again, they sell for even more _ up to $600.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a heavy Palm OS user, whether on Palm or Handspring
hardware, and you're not satisfied with Palm's memo pad as a way to
manage notes and other free-form data, something you might consider
downloading to your device is a program called Info Select for Palm
Organizers, published by Micro Logic of Hackensack, N.J.
( &LR; www.miclog.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the program lets you assemble and manipulate textual
information of any kind in outline format. It has a super-fast and
flexible search function and good support for infrared beaming.
It's also lean enough to be usable on models with only 2 megabytes
of memory _ it takes up only about 100 kilobytes.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm version is based on Info Select for Windows, an old
program that doesn't get much attention nowadays but retains an
enthusiastic, even cultlike, following among PC veterans. If you
have both the desktop and handheld versions installed, you can sync
up outlines between them, though the Palm version doesn't support
all the features of the Windows product.
</P>
<P>
   Info Select for Palm Organizers is $69.95; the Windows version
is $99.95. Unfortunately, there's no free demo version, but Micro
Logic does offer a 60-day money-back guarantee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
