<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET A GOOD TOOL FOR FINANCIAL QUERIES &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  By HARRY DOMASH 
c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &HT;     
<TEXT>
Many thanks to all those who've taken the time to send me your
comments and questions. Here are answers to some of the most
frequently asked questions.
<P>
   Q: Where can I find information on stock splits?
</P>
<P>
   A: When a company splits its stock, it issues additional shares
to current shareholders, resulting in a drop of the trading price.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a 2-for-1 split, you get twice as many shares,
but each share initially trades at half the pre-split price. In
theory, a split shouldn't affect future price appreciation.
However, many investors think splits do matter, and stocks often
rise after the announcement of a stock split.
</P>
<P>
   You can see stock price performance of recent split stocks at
The Online Investor ( &LR; www.investhelp.com &LR; ) by selecting Splits
Performance from the menu on the left. Click on Stock Splits from
the same menu to see a list of impending splits.
</P>
<P>
   You can sign up to get e-mail notification every time a company
announces a stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I find out when an IPO lockup period ends?
</P>
<P>
   A: Typically, a company first going public (Initial Public
Offering) sells a small fraction of its shares actually
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Early investors, venture capitalists, and officers and directors
own the balance. Many of these pre-IPO investors paid much less
than the IPO price for their shares but can't sell until the lockup
period expires.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the share price should drop after the lockup expires
and the additional shares move into the market. You can see a list
of lockup expirations and additional details at IPO Lockup.com
(www.ipolockup.com).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I get closing prices on stocks and indexes from 10
years ago?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DOMASH21 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A: Yahoo ( &LR; finance.yahoo.com &LR; ) has detailed price information,
including open, high, low, and close prices going back to 1984.
First get a quote by putting the ticker symbol into the window and
clicking the get quotes button. Then select ``Chart,'' and finally
click on ``historical quotes.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find information on mutual fund money flows?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mutual funds account for a significant portion of market
capitalization. When investors pour money into mutual funds, the
funds use the new cash to buy more stocks, pushing the market up.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, mutual funds must sell stocks, which depresses the
market, when investors, in total, take money out. Trim Tabs
( &LR; trimtabs.com &LR; ) tracks flows in and out of mutual funds. They
track flows into fund categories such as aggressive growth, growth
and income, etc., as well as flows into specific funds.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily you have to pay to see a current report, but you can
see a two-week-old report by selecting Mutual Fund Trim Tabs on
TT's home page.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need the Acrobat program to see the report. Acrobat can
be downloaded at no charge from  &LR; www.adobe.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I keep track of my stocks and mutual fund
portfolios?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most financial sites provide a portfolio tracker. My favorite
is Microsoft's Money Central ( &LR; moneycentral.msn.com &LR; ). It's
flexible and easy to use. Select Investor, then Portfolio. You'll
have to download special free software to get started.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I misplaced your column on how to find the next Qualcomm
while getting ``great abs.'' How do I get another copy?
</P>
<P>
   A: All of my columns are posted in the Basic Training section of
my Web site:  &LR; www.winninginvesting.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DOMASH21 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Q: How do I find the best Web broker?
</P>
<P>
   A: My favorite site for broker information is OnLine Investment
Services ( &LR; www.sonic.net/donaldj &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's a good site for economic indicators?
</P>
<P>
   A: The White House Economic Briefing Room
( &LR; www.whitehouse.gov &LR; ), provides an excellent display of the latest
statistics released by the U.S. Government covering all economic
sectors. Select Briefing Room, then Economic Statistics, and
finally Economic Statistics Briefing Room.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I find the strongest industry sectors?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many investors pick stocks by first finding the strongest
industry sectors, then picking the best performing stocks within
those sectors. Big Charts ( &LR; www.bigcharts.com &LR; ) lists the 10 best
and 10 worst performing industries for selectable time spans
ranging from one week to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Select Industries on their home page. Clicking on an industry
name displays the 10 best and worst performing stocks within the
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I find a list of competitors for a company I'm
researching?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hoover's ( &LR; www.hoovers.com &LR; ) lists the top three competitors
in their Company Capsule. Many other sites claim to list
competitors, but their lists are far too long and include many
false listings.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the company name or ticker symbol on Hoover's home page to
display the capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do I find out about exchange-traded mutual funds?
</P>
<P>
   A: Exchange-traded funds are similar to index or industry
specific mutual funds, except they trade like stocks. You buy and
sell them as you would shares of individual companies. The best way
to learn about them is to go to  &LR; www.about.com &LR;  and search for
``exchange traded funds,'' and then click on the top listing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
