r f BC-IDEADOLLAR-SFCHRON &LR;      08-21 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDEADOLLAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK OF THE GIFT CERTIFICATES EDISON COULD HAVE COLLECTED &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  By CARRIE KIRBY &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
San Francisco entrepreneur Mark Turrell wants to give you a penny
for your thoughts. Actually, he will pay up to $100 plus 15 percent
of future revenues for really good ones.
</P>
<P>
   Through his Web site, IdeaDollar.com, people can submit their
ideas in exchange for gift certificates at online stores.
</P>
<P>
   Turrell has already purchased rights to develop such gems as the
laminated shower poster and talking dinnerware that tells blind
people what they are about to eat. Since December 1999, the company
has bought 1,500 ideas and awarded about $8,000 in gift
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: You go to  &LR; www.ideadollar.com &LR;  and describe
an original idea for anything _ an invention, a marketing tactic or
even a recipe for world peace. Then you submit it, irrevocably
handing over to IdeaDollar the rights to patent or develop the
concept. IdeaDollar agrees to buy anything you submit. IdeaDollar
pays in gift certificates from its e-tailing partners, currently
limited to Amazon.com and Art.com. The catch? IdeaDollar gets to
set the price: Ideas that score low in originality sell for the
bargain price of $0.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle submitted a couple of ideas for appraisal. The
results:
</P>
<P>
   -- A pair of keyboard gloves, fitted with sensors that allow the
wearer to enter information into a computer simply by moving the
appropriate finger. IdeaDollar ranked this idea 4 out of 10 points,
and paid $1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pre-recorded phone messages: Users could record standard
phrases such as ``Call me, my number is ...'' to be replayed when
leaving a message on others' answering machines. It was ranked 5
out of 10, and paid $1.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of IDEADOLL () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Sell your inspiration for a lousy gift certificate? Turrell
insists that inventors get a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It normally costs you thousands of dollars and several years
to take your idea to market, and if you're lucky you get 7 or 8
percent net profit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone's getting a raw deal, it could be IdeaDollar, which
acknowledges that it will be able to convert very few of the ideas
it collects into money-making products. The company also takes on
certain legal burdens. For example, if IdeaDollar buys a design for
a new microchip, it had better make sure that the idea doesn't come
from an Intel employee who has signed an agreement that all her
work belongs to her employer.
</P>
<P>
   The company is exploring a corporate angle that might be more
promising. It's creating a Web site for Bush Brothers' Baked Beans
where customers can suggest bean recipes or other ideas the company
might find useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are actually some very good customer ideas out there,''
but most companies avoid soliciting customer ideas because they're
afraid of getting sued, Turrell said. IdeaDollar plans to act as a
go-between that would collect customer suggestions for
corporations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
