<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7567 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-GODZILLA-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      08-21 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODZILLA-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-GODZILLA-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    GODZILLA'S FIREY TONGUE IN CHEEK(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In (beginitalic)Godzilla 2000(enditalic), the big lizard with a
chip on his shoulder rises from the ocean and once again smashes
Tokyo to bits.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think they'd put up a fence or something.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, things have changed since Godzilla first romped and
stomped through Japan 45 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the big guy has a new makeup man and a new voice coach.
He looks 20 years younger and a lot meaner, with more teeth and
bigger spikes on his back. His trademark roar is louder than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese haven't been sitting still, either. In this
delightfully campy remake, they've updated their technology and now
use sophisticated computers to track Godzilla. Well, not that
sophisticated. After all, Godzilla is 170 feet tall and spews
radioactive fire. He's not really that hard to spot.
</P>
<P>
   The government is backed up by the Godzilla Prediction Network,
which tries to figure out when the big guy will emerge from the
ocean. It's curiously underfunded and understaffed, considering
Godzilla's frequent forays into town.
</P>
<P>
   Also, at some point, Japanese scientists and military guys
started cursing on camera. With Godzilla squashing their minimalls
every few years, who could blame them?
</P>
<P>
   Other than those updates, Toho Studios worked hard to bring
Godzilla back to life in all his cheesy glory, complete with the
original, scratchy Toho logo as well as the standard-issue
miniature buildings, ineffectual toy rockets and badly dubbed
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   If you're expecting a modern science-fiction movie with
state-of-the-art special effects, you'll be sorely disappointed.
This movie is a tribute to the days before computer graphics
dominated the movies, when two guys in rubber suits stepping on a
fake city and toy cars didn't seem all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Godzilla aficionados will enjoy this one,
which is played for laughs. Some of the dialogue is pulled from
other films - (beginitalic)Dr. Strangelove (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Superman, (enditalic)to name a few - while other lines
offer biting commentary on the monster-movie genre. There's also
some influence from American movies, especially
(beginitalic)Independence Day(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   In a good move, this version of Godzilla has no interest in
being a friend to man or cleaning up the environment. He'd rather
just step on buildings and spit fire, which is what Godzilla does
best.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Godzilla shows up one foggy night and
immediately starts squashing stuff. The Japanese, armed with new,
more powerful weapons, bring the full weight of their military to
bear, with somewhat predictable results.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scientists have discovered a huge rock from outer
space lying at the bottom of the ocean. Once they start fiddling
with it, the thing comes to life and turns into a shiny, flying
computer mouse with a bad attitude. At this point, we get a lot of
N.M. (No Monster) time, as the ship lands on a building and the
scientists scratch their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Godzilla shows up just as a monster pops out of the
ship, and the rumble is on.
</P>
<P>
   The offending monster looks suspiciously like the American
version of Godzilla from the 1998 Matthew Broderick movie. In a
not-so-subtle shot at imitators, there's a lot of dialogue about
the monster trying to steal Godzilla's identity.
</P>
<P>
   But that's impossible. There's only one true Godzilla.
</P>
<P>
   And he'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
