<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7568 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-RESCUE-KAN &LR;      08-21 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESCUE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUER HELPS SAVE 11 CHILDREN FROM BLAZE, MOURNS TWO KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Donald Bradley and Brian Burnes  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Sean Jones helped rescue 11 children
from a pre-dawn fire Sunday. It was the two who died that made him
cry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alexis Brown, 2, and her sister Aliyah Brown, 6, died in the
fire at the Early Childhood Residential Center, a foster home at
3911 Agnes Ave. Authorities suspect arson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody called me a hero. ...I don't feel like a hero,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking I should have found her,'' said Jones, a
father of two girls and a boy. ``But the smoke was heavy and
thick.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyah died later at Children's Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said others could have died if not for Jones. At one
point, he reached into darkness and smoke and felt the edge of a
crib. Inside was a baby whom he rushed outside.
</P>
<P>
   State officials had placed the 13 children _ ages 2 months to 10
years _ in the two-story stone building for their care and safety.
Shortly after dawn, fire officials turned the scene over to police.
The center had become a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police Sgt. Robert Schweitzer would say only that
arson was suspected. Because Jones was at the fire scene at an odd
hour, he originally was considered a suspect. Authorities
questioned him for several hours and determined he was ``a good
Samaritan,'' Police Department spokesman Sgt. Floyd Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators determined that the fire began at the rear of the
building, beneath where the children slept.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 27, who works in home remodeling, had returned to Kansas
City about 5 a.m. from St. Louis, where he had attended a football
game Saturday night. Mike Jones, a linebacker for the St. Louis
Rams, is his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The long drive home was worrisome. Jones and his cousin passed a
bad accident. Once back in Kansas City, Jones drove to his church
to pray. He knew it would be locked, but he knelt on the concrete
steps of the Greater Grace Temple and ``praised the Lord'' for
getting him home safe.
</P>
<P>
   As Jones was turning his car around in the church parking lot,
he saw the fire through windows of the center. Maybe instinct took
over. A great-uncle, uncle and cousin are firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Jones ran to the front of the building, kicked in the door and
found several children on the stairway.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Parks, a worker at the center, was trying to get them
outside. The children were crying.
</P>
<P>
   Jones helped lead them outside. Then, a girl took Jones' hand
and told him her sister was still inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in there,'' the girl said, leading Jones back into the
smoke-filled building and pointing toward a room.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Jones found the baby in the crib.
</P>
<P>
   Outside again, Parks quickly counted heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two babies still in there!'' she shouted.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late, the smoke too thick and the fire too hot.
</P>
<P>
   At midmorning, some of center's staff gathered on a porch across
the street. When asked about the possibility of arson, Cora
Thompson, the center's treatment director, began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just sick,'' Thompson said, weeping. ``Lexie was a
funny little girl who loved to laugh. She would come in while you
were working and demand a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was nearly passed out when firefighters arrived on the
scene at 5:22 a.m., three minutes after an alarm was sounded. The
first company found heavy smoke and fire blowing out the back of
the building. They immediately requested additional personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was under control at 5:39 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis was found by Capt. Tim Bowman, Aliyah by Capt. Russ
Hombs.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, the only adult staying overnight at the center, and Jones
were taken to area hospitals, where they were treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   Forty firefighters battled the blaze. None was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The residential center was operated by the Civic Registration
Council. Thompson said the children were placed there by the
Missouri Division of Family Services. Some had been abused or
neglected. Others came from families in crisis. A staff of about 20
provided programs for speech, language and social development and
various forms of therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The children were a familiar site to neighbors in the area just
south of 39th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Fitzpatrick, who lives across the street, often let her
children play with those at the center. She said the children at
the center were happy and well cared for.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick was awakened by the fire and was on her porch when
the children came out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   She saw Parks frantically count the children and yell for help.
</P>
<P>
   She also heard an older sister of Alexis and Aliyah Brown
scream: ``My baby sisters are in there! Don't let them die!''
</P>
<P>
   Working smoke detectors were found in the building's sleeping
areas. Material loss has been estimated at $100,000 to the
structure and $50,000 to its contents.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving children were placed in other foster homes Sunday,
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
