<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE REIMBURSEMENTS FOR CANCER DRUGS MAY BE REDUCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Kevin Murphy  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ Elderly cancer patients on
chemotherapy take some comfort in knowing that most of the time
they can be treated at a doctor's office rather than at a hospital.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But that may soon become much less common because the Clinton
administration wants to reduce Medicare coverage for cancer drugs
given at doctors' offices. According to the administration, doctors
pay significantly less for the drugs than what they charge
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The impending change has upset oncologists and created a flap in
Congress, with members from both parties joining in protest. Some
lawmakers, including Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri, want to pass a
law to derail the Clinton proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are fighting cancer are waging the toughest battle
of their lives,'' Ashcroft said. ``They should not be burdened
further with the uncertainty of whether they will have access to
life-saving medications.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress have waged a letter-writing campaign urging
Clinton and Donna Shalala, secretary of the Department of Health
and Human Services, to reconsider the cut in Medicare payments.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft and Sen. Kit Bond, a fellow Missouri Republican, wrote
Shalala on Aug. 7. Eighty-nine members of the House from both
parties, including Democrat Pat Danner of Kansas City and
Republican Kenny Hulshof of Columbia, signed a letter to Shalala on
July 28 urging no cut in payments ``in the strongest possible
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has not backed down but is gathering opinions
from the health-care community before directing Medicare bill
payers to reduce reimbursement rates, a spokesman for the Health
Care Financing Administration said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala's office declined comment, saying her views are best
summarized in a May 31 letter to Congress in which she cited
``significant discrepancies between the prices that Medicare must
pay by law and the significantly lower prices at which physicians
may obtain these drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said actuaries estimate the proposed reduction would
save Medicare $2.9 billion over 10 years. She would like to make
the changes effective Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors acknowledge they often pay less for the drugs than what
they bill Medicare, but they say that the difference makes up for
being reimbursed inadequately for the time and expertise of medical
professionals who inject the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Several oncologists from Missouri are among doctors nationwide
who are concerned that reducing Medicare payments for chemotherapy
given in doctors' offices will force more patients to go to
hospitals, where reimbursement rates generally are higher. Doctors
and clinics could no longer afford to give treatments under the
lower rates, they said.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of chemotherapy injections are now given on an
outpatient basis, doctors said. The drugs must be administered by a
doctor or nurse, partly because of the potential for immediate side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole industry _ the doctors, nurses and pharmacies _ is
geared toward outpatient therapy, and that is good for the
patients,'' said David Ota, a cancer surgeon and medical director
of the Ellis Fischel State Cancer Center in Columbia, which is part
of the University of Missouri medical care system.
</P>
<P>
   Ota said the center received about 7,300 visits from cancer
treatments in the year ended June 30, some from patients who came
in from up to 150 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, even for outpatient treatment, tend to be less
convenient, less attentive and more crowded than a private doctor's
office, says the American Society of Clinical Oncology, which is
lobbying vigorously against any changes.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has urged its members to write their
representatives and senators in Congress. Ota and other Missouri
doctors have written Ashcroft about the effect of lowering Medicare
payments, especially at private clinics not adjacent to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dangerous plan that would gravely threaten the
cancer care delivery system on which millions of Americans
depend,'' wrote Christopher F. Sirridge of the Cliffview Hematology
and Oncology centers in Independence and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft says he will introduce a bill when Congress reconvenes
after Labor Day that would try to head off the Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Ashcroft bill would block any cut in drug payments unless
preceded by review with health professionals and government
auditors, and appropriate increases in other reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no response to Ashcroft's proposal, but
Shalala and other officials have said that substantial research has
gone into the decision to consider cutting the Medicare
reimbursements for the cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Congress, as part of its Balanced Budget Act, set
reimbursement rates at 95 percent of the ``average wholesale
price'' of the various drugs Medicare covers. But Shalala said the
formula for measuring those prices is flawed and that a study
showed doctors received from 11 to 900 percent more from Medicare
than what they paid for the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice, which is investigating drug prices,
and the State Medicaid Fraud Control Units have compiled data for
about 50 types of drugs to determine fair prices that the
administration would like to use for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   While many members of Congress reject setting new drug prices
for Medicare, others agree with Shalala that a change must be
explored.
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee chairman Tom Bliley of Virginia, a
Republican, wrote to seven pharmaceutical companies May 4 seeking
details of prices they charge for various drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley said his committee investigation found that some drug
makers apparently set average wholesale prices far above what they
actually charge doctors. The Medicare reimbursement is based on the
wholesale price, so doctors can keep the difference. This
``spread'' creates an incentive for doctors to buy drugs from those
manufacturers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies increase the spread ``in a calculated and
deliberate effort to use this Medicare-funded windfall as a
marketing tool,'' Bliley wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said he understands concern about excessive
reimbursements for some drugs, but he and others said shifting
treatments to hospitals may be even more costly to Medicare because
of the higher overall costs of hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time when we all are concerned about the long-term
solvency of the Medicare program,'' Ashcroft wrote Clinton, ``I
believe it is short-sighted to ignore this possible unintended
consequence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
