<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S GYMNASTICS TEAM IS SURPRISING, BUT UNDENIABLY FAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In hindsight, it had been an intriguing storyline, this
idea of a one-time queen returning to claim her throne.
</P>
<P>
   But in the game that Shannon Miller was playing, we were
reminded Sunday, there are no shortcuts, no Cliffs Notes, no
``Olympics for Dummies''.
</P>
<P>
   If you dare to experience the thrill, you must pay the price.
And while Miller was off for three years _ writing books, giving
motivational speeches, buying a wedding dress _ the meter was
running.
</P>
<P>
   If you dare to dream the dream, you also need to feel the
hunger. And when she needed it most, with the strain of the U.S.
Olympic Gymnastics Trials bearing down upon her, Plano's Vanessa
Atler dug down to the bottom of her soul ... and found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   They named a women's Olympic team here at the FleetCenter on
Sunday night, a team remarkable only in that the announced six
names prompted little, if any, debate.
</P>
<P>
   In Elise Ray, Kristen Maloney, Amy Chow, Dominique Dawes, Morgan
White and Jamie Dantzscher, team coordinator Bela Karolyi appears
to have found the mixture he was searching for. A blend of young
and old, of poise and experience, of veterans from the 1996 gold
medal team in Chow and Dawes, and of fresh-faced newcomers, like
the irresistible, pint-sized White.
</P>
<P>
   With the entire team to be selected by a Karolyi-influenced
committee for the first time, the outcome was ripe for quarrel. But
Karolyi's post-announcement news conference was symbolically brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no discussion and doubt about who are the ones
deserving to be on the team,'' the legendary coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Combining and weighing the results, as planned, of July's U.S.
championships with the trials' scores, the first five finishers all
made the team _ in order, Ray, Chow, Maloney, White and Dantzscher.
Atler's combined score ranked sixth, but Dawes leapfrogged from
seventh place, mostly on the strength of finishing fifth in the
trials' all-around scores.
</P>
<P>
   The two most conspicuous omissions ended up being Miller and
Atler.
</P>
<P>
   As a seven-time Olympic medal winner, Miller, now 23, had every
right to expect Karolyi to validate her royal ticket for Sydney.
But she arrived here under-trained and surprisingly unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   A hairline fracture of the shinbone had cost her three weeks of
valuable repetitions. Miller withdrew from the U.S. championships
last month after strutting her stuff in only one event.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the surrender came even sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no injury,'' Miller said, after her coach, Steve
Nunno, had pulled her from the meet after only two vaults. ``I just
jammed my legs a little. They're stiff right now, and that's why
I'm not going to finish the meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Let them eat cake, the queen was saying. With the team being
picked by committee, Nunno was shamelessly playing his trump card.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw what I could do,'' said Miller, who had to
injury-petition just to get into the trials and then prove her
physical readiness in front of a special panel last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very unfortunate,'' Karolyi answered later. ``I
wish she had started (her comeback) just a little bit earlier, so
that she could have picked up more physical stamina.''
</P>
<P>
   For Atler, the ending was the same, but the story was different.
The Canyon Country, Calif., native, who moved to Plano because she
thought the change of coaches would lift her to the Olympics, had
been near the top of her sport for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old appeared on television in a Reese's Peanut
Butter Cup commercial. There reportedly were deals in the works _ a
book, a cereal box, a public speaking career.
</P>
<P>
   But surgery after the 1999 world championships in China
discovered a bone chip in Atler's left ankle. When the foot still
didn't heal, a second surgery found another bone chip. Atler, too,
lost valuable training time, and she felt the pressure to succeed
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Her Olympic trials were a disaster. Atler wobbled and stumbled,
but mostly she just was not sharp. Her all-around score of 36.924
was better than only two of the 12 gymnasts who finished the meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down in my heart, I knew I wasn't prepared,'' she said,
bravely. ``I think everybody wanted more. But I don't know. I just
wasn't having fun. When the team was announced, I almost had a
sense of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people had sacrificed much to see that Vanessa Atler
made the Olympic team. Her mother, Nanette, had moved to Plano, so
that Vanessa could train with former Russian gold medalist Valeri
Liukin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have the time,'' Atler said, thinking aloud.
``Maybe I'm not into it. There's a lot of things _ all the changes,
the surgeries. It put a lot of pressure on me. And it just wasn't
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Atler said, yes, she was aware that as sixth-place finisher,
under the old system, she would still have made the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess so,'' she said. ``But if I had made it, still, the
performance I put out there was not Olympic material.''
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't her two years at the top, someone asked, have been
worth more?
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently not,'' Vanessa Atler said.
</P>
<P>
   The dream was over. There had been no shortcuts. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
