<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD IS REACHED FOR MOST WORKERS IN PHONE WALKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2rd graf with some workers not going back to work; ADDS 10
grafs at end; CUTS into 2 takes)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two unions representing more than 86,000 striking telephone
workers reached a contract agreement Sunday with the United States'
largest telecommunications employer, Verizon Communications,
indicating that organized labor still has a place in the New
Economy.
</P>
<P>
   Although about one-third of the union locals had still not
signed off on the settlement by Sunday evening, the company and the
union leaders said the 15-day strike was effectively over. They
said union workers in the region affected by the strike _ 12 states
from Maine to Virginia and the District of Columbia _ could return
to their jobs in New York and New England as soon as Monday morn-
ing, although workers in states such as New Jersey and Pennsylvania
are still waiting for their local presidents to approve the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The first task for Verizon will be to try to work down a backlog
of telephone repair and new-service orders that has risen to 90,000
_ one-third more than normal _ since the strike began Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Under the three-year contract agreement, the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers secured numerous concessions from Verizon, which is the
nation's largest provider of wireless and local telephone services,
with 260,000 employees around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The unions secured a 12 percent wage increase, over three years,
for a work force that was already one of the best paid in the
telecommunications industry. The average hourly base pay for a
customer service representative in New York, $26, would increase to
$29.25 in the contract's third year, for example. And in a
new-economy wrinkle, each of Verizon's union workers will, for the
first time, receive a small grant of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   But the broader significance of the agreement, and the reason
the negotiations have been closely watched throughout the
high-technology industry, involves issues that go beyond
traditional wage and benefit concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The unions have won the right to more easily organize workers in
Verizon's wireless division, where fewer than 50 of the division's
32,000 employees belong to a union. The unions also secured
Verizon's promise that union telephone workers will be given the
opportunity to do more work in fast-growing areas like the
installation of high-speed Internet lines _ an activity for which
Verizon has tended to use nonunion contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Those were key points for the unions because wireless and
Internet communications are growing much faster than the
conventional telephone business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contract is a breakthrough not just for our members who
work at Verizon but for workers throughout the telecommunications
industry,'' Larry Mancino, vice president of the Communications
Workers of America, which represents about 72,000 of the striking
employees, said in an interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The unions also secured agreements on several other issues that
reflected worker anxieties in the new economy, which is
characterized by big corporate mergers and an entrepreneurial ethic
in which the shorthand ``24/7'' _ meaning 24 hours a day, seven
days a week _ symbolizes the relentlessness of work in today's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was created by Bell Atlantic's acquisition of GTE Corp.
and through the formation of a wireless venture with Vodafone
AirTouch of Britain. Union employees, particularly in the
Northeast, had been worried about the prospect of the company
transferring work to other, lower-paying parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The union members, especially customer service representatives,
had also sought relief from job stress resulting from long periods
of work with few breaks and frequent compulsory overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon agreed to greater job stability for union members by
limiting the number of employees whose jobs could be moved to a
different region to 0.7 percent of the union workers in a given
geographic area. The measurement would be based on a geographic
area as small as a county, as the unions wanted, instead of an
across-the-board number, as the company wanted.
</P>
<P>
   On job-related stress, Verizon agreed to give customer service
representatives and telephone operators up to five 30-minute
periods each week during which they can do work other than taking
calls.
</P>
<P>
   And mandatory overtime for customer service representatives and
operators would be reduced. For example, operators who are single
mothers will be limited to as few as 7.5 hours a week of overtime
in some areas, down from as much as 20 hours before the strike.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
