<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7576 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-VERIZON-RDP-1STLD-WRI     08-21 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the strike. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verizon (pronounced Vuh-RISE-on) was under various pressures to
settle the strike, which had already lasted longer than the token
walkout that the company had apparently expected. It had come at
the busiest time of year for the consumer telecommunications
industry, when many students are about to return to college and
will require new telephone and Internet access service.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the strike began, the company had also begun a
major advertising campaign to make people aware of its new name.
And lately, concern over the company's earnings have pushed
Verizon's share price near a two-year low. Since the strike began,
Verizon's stock has fallen more than 10 percent. It closed at
$42.4375 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to put this strike behind us and move on,'' the
company's chief executive, Ivan Seidenberg, said in an interview
Sunday. ``I would say that every one of the unions' issues was
legitimate going forward. We've strengthened the fiber of our
company over the long-term with this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen how the agreement will be viewed
elsewhere in labor circles, by other big telecommunications
companies and by Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most wide-reaching contract settlements the
industry has seen,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent analyst of
the telecommunications industry. ``It'll be interesting to see
whether this will result in a more qualified work force or a ball
and chain around the company's leg.''
</P>
<P>
   The unions' right to organize Verizon's wireless division may be
the strike's most significant outcome. The unions won an important
concession allowing them to organize by card check, a process that
allows a given work site to join a union if a majority of its
employees sign cards saying they wish to do so. The process is
faster and less bureaucratic than holding elections.
</P>
<P>
   Under this part of the agreement, the employees at a work
location would join the union if 55 percent sign up through the
cards. The wireless agreement applies only to workers in the strike
region, where about a fourth of the 32,000 employees of the Verizon
Wireless division are located.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would include technicians, customer service
representatives and employees who work as customer sales
representative in the wireless division's retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Making it easier to organize Veri- zon's wireless work force
could have broad implications for the nation's wireless industry,
which is one of the fastest-growing parts of the new economy and
which so far has re- mained a primarily nonunion busi- ness.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no certainty that the majority of workers in
parts of Verizon Wireless that are not cov- ered by the settlement
or at other wireless companies _ or in other high-growth,
high-technology indus- tries, for that matter _ are eager to
unionize.
</P>
<P>
   But some union advocates are opti- mistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the parallel issues are glaringly apparent,'' said
Marcus Courtney, co-founder of the Washing- ton Alliance of
Technology Workers, a Seattle organization affiliated with the
Communications Workers of America. The Washington Alliance has
already organized a small num- ber of employees at companies that
include Microsoft and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make our efforts easier, because it shows that the
largest company in a key high-tech industry is not off limits,''
Courtney said. ``Now we can hold up this example that says, `Your
voice can be heard.'''
</P>
<P>
   And as in the Verizon strike, the future of union organizing
efforts in high-technology companies is not ex- pected to focus on
wages as much as on issues like job security, benefits, overtime,
work-related stress and even stock options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions have been raised,'' said Stanley Aronowitz, a
professor of sociology at the City University of New York who has
studied labor issues. ``In the '30s, no one took work- ers'
complaints seriously until the GMs and U.S. Steels were organ-
ized.''
</P>
<P>
   Already in the wireless industry, where Verizon will try to
compete with other companies that are most- ly nonunion, there are
inklings that organizing can be viable.
</P>
<P>
   At SBC Communications, which will soon operate the nation's
second- largest wireless carrier in a venture with BellSouth, the
same kind of card-check organizing Verizon has agreed to has been
permitted for nearly three years. So far, more than 5,000 of SBC's
wireless employees out of a potential 12,000 eligible are union
members, the CWA says.
</P>
<P>
   And at AT&AMP;T Wireless, the third- largest wireless carrier, the
union won the right last year to card-check organizing, although
elections must be held several days after the cards are gathered _
a potential union impediment not included in the Veri- zon
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
