<HEADER>
A7586 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKL-SPARKS-COMETS-LAD     08-21 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-COMETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS ELIMINATE SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Nicky McCrimmon of the Los Angeles Sparks
sat in a corner, her eyes bloodshot from crying. Teammate DeLisha
Milton sat staring downward, speechless, unable to describe what
was going through her mind. Their team had lost and they couldn't
hide their pain.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks did all they could to try to fend off elimination in
the Western Conference Finals. They came back from a devastating
opener in Houston and played team ball.
</P>
<P>
   They did a great job of affecting two of the Houston Comets'
three big stars.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the least-talked-about players - Brazilian Janeth
Arcain and reserve Tammy Jackson - who dealt the Sparks their
biggest blow of the season. Not Sheryl Swoopes, Cynthia Cooper or
Tina Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Arcain scored the last five points, including the go-ahead
basket with 39 seconds to play, to send the three-time defending
champion Houston Comets to the championship series with a 74-69
victory over the Sparks on Sunday afternoon at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a small group of Comets fans, the season-high crowd
of 13,084 fell silent. They were stunned that the Sparks, the team
that won a record 28 regular-season WNBA games, that defeated the
Comets three times, would not have another chance to play again
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with much anticipation and excitement, starting
with Sparks coach Michael Cooper being introduced as the WNBA Coach
of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks trailed 40-35 at the break, but traded leads with the
Comets in the second half until the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a great position and we just ran up
against the champions, and champions know what to do,'' Michael
Cooper said. ``But I tell you what - if you were to ask (the
Comets) if they would, if they could have played (today), I
guarantee they'll say no, because they have nothing else left to
give. That's why they're champions, because they get it done when
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   After Arcain's shot put the Comets ahead 71-69, the Sparks had a
chance to tie it. But Jackson blocked DeLisha Milton's layup and
Allison Feaster had to foul Arcain to stop the clock. Arcain made
the second free throw to make it a three-point game with 20 seconds
to play, enough time to give the Sparks another opportunity to tie.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika, who had team-high 19 points, came off a screen on
the right side to shoot a 3-pointer, but it fell short. Feaster
tried to push the ball out to Tamecka Dixon at the top of the key,
but Arcain came up with the ball and Feaster fouled her to stop the
clock again. Arcain made both free throws with 12.4 seconds to play
for the decisive margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a lot of people say this is a team that has three
players, but everybody can see now that they have five people that
can play,'' Michael Cooper said. ``Just because those three get all
the publicity, you have the tendency to forget about those two.
That's when those two do what I call a silent sniper job on us -
Jackson coming in getting some key baskets and Arcain hitting some
key baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper scored a game-high 29 points, but Swoopes and
Thompson had only 15 between them. However, it didn't matter with
Arcain scoring 16 and Jackson 12 off the bench. Swoopes had six
assists, often feeding the ball to Jackson in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like coach Cooper said, we followed what we needed for Sheryl
and Cynthia to distribute the ball to the other players,'' said
Lisa Leslie of the Sparks. ``And the other players played well
tonight and that was pretty much the difference. They took shots
they normally don't take and made shots that they normally don't
make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the champs and I tip my hat to them,'' Michael Cooper
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
