<P>
   BOX 1
</P>
<P>
   Politics and religion &QC;
</P>
<P>
   by the numbers &QC;
</P>
<P>
   52 percent of registered voters are more likely to vote for a
presidential candidate who talks about his personal relationship
with Jesus Christ; 25percent would be less likely to vote for that
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Source: December 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gallup Poll
</P>
<P>
   33 percent of American Muslims who are registered voters would
vote for Al Gore; 28percent would vote for George W. Bush; 38
percent are undecided or would vote for a third-party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   64 percent of American Muslims are aligned with the Republican
Party on moral issues (abortion, same-sex marriages, etc.); 56
percent of American Muslims are aligned with the Democratic Party
on social issues (welfare, gun control, universal health care,
etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Source: July 2000 Council on American-Islamic Relations national
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Among Protestant church pastors, 64 percent will definitely or
probably vote for George W. Bush; 15 percent support Al Gore; 21
percent are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Source: July 2000 Ellison Research national poll &QL;
</P>
<P>
   of Protestant ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Americans claim to be a member of a church or a
synagogue. When asked to state a religious preference, only 9
percent say ``none.''
</P>
<P>
   Source: December 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   65 percent of Americans believe ``God's will'' is a major reason
for the nation's success. The racial, gender and generational
differences break down this way: 82 percent of Blacks; 63 percent
of Whites; 72 percent of women; 58percent of men; 74 percent of
those 65 and older; and 59percent of those between the ages of 18
and 34.
</P>
<P>
   Source: April/May 1999 Princeton Survey Research Associates &QL;
</P>
<P>
   for the Pew Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jesus and the presidency
</P>
<P>
   Until John F. Kennedy was elected president, the country was
pretty much run by Protestants, some of whom were religious
privately but not publicly. It was considered poor taste for
candidates to discuss their private religious beliefs openly but
these same candidates, once elected president, supported the
``American civil religion'' and sprinkled speeches with such
phrases as ``God bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry S. cq stylebook cj Truman (1945-53, Democrat) - A Baptist
who hated public displays of piety. His personal letters to his
wife show he was religiously informed, biblical and godly.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight D. Eisenhower (1953-61, Republican) - Had not attended
church as an adult, but as the president, he joined the National
Presbyterian Church and was baptized. He authorized ``In God We
Trust'' on all money (the motto had been in use on some coins since
1908) and the addition of ``under God'' to the Pledge of
Allegiance. Also played golf on the National Day of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy (1961-63, Democrat) - His Roman Catholic beliefs
stirred concerns he would show more allegiance to the pope than the
Constitution. His opponent, Richard M. Nixon, said Kennedy's
Catholicism wasn't a problem, and religion would only be an issue
if an agnostic or atheist ran for president.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon B. Johnson (1963-69, Democra$)V5) filiated with the
Disciples of Christ; attended church at home and at the National
City Christian Church in Washington, D.C., although he sometimes
attended an Episcopalian church with his wife. He liked to quote
Scripture. cq stylebook cj
</P>
<P>
   Richard M. Nixon (1969-74, Republican) - He was raised in a
Quaker church but not much of his religious upbringing showed in
his adult life. In his speeches, he talked about America's faith in
its children, its weapons and in other things rather than about
America's faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald R. Ford (1974-77, Republican) - A churchgoing
Episcopalian who was selected by Congress to replace the resigning
Nixon because of his integrity and character. As a child, the rule
in his house was ``Tell the truth, work hard and come to dinner on
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter (1977-81, Democrat) - A Baptist, he was the first
who talked about his faith openly as a candidate and said he was
``born again,'' a code phrase in evangelical circles for describing
a conversion experience. After that, he used more generalized God
language in public. His beliefs influenced his foreign policy
decisions, and he taught Baptist Sunday school while in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan (1981-89, Republican) - He grew up in a Disciples
of Christ church in Illinois and was a member of Hollywood
Presbyterian Church as an adult. He was most aligned with
evangelicals politically but did not certify his religious
experiences with their language. He was respectful and reverent of
religion. He attended church the least of all presidents, saying it
was too much trouble for the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush (1989-93, Republican) - Brought up in an East Coast
Episcopal parish where the mainline Protestant culture nurtured
faith, but parishioners didn't talk too publicly about personal
beliefs. During his terms as vice president and as president, he
was a vestryman at St. Ann's Episcopal Church in Kennebunkport,
Maine. He is active at his Episcopal Church in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton (1993 to present, Democrat) - A Southern Baptist
who knows the Bible well and can readily quote Scripture. He
attends a Methodist church in Washington, D.C. He has received the
most support and the most criticism from religious leaders. He used
the occasion of a September 1998 interfaith prayer breakfast at the
White House to apologize to the country for the Monica Lewinsky
scandal, but he has not talked much about the details of his
personal faith.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: PBS, Martin E. Marty, Kerby cq cj Anderson, and the
Lyndon B. Johnson Library and Museum
</P>
<P>
   Jesus and the presidency
</P>
