<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-STEPHANIE-AZR &LR;      08-21 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPHANIE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-STEPHANIE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    GIRL WITH AIDS TO HEARING(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KARINA BLAND(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephanie Ray, a 14-year-old fugitive from Wisconsin foster care
who has AIDS, won't be getting on a plane this morning as ordered
by the Waukesha County Juvenile Court last week.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this afternoon, she'll go before presiding Judge
Maurice Portley of Maricopa County Juvenile Court, who has agreed
to hear an emergency petition asking that Stephanie be allowed to
live with her aunt in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The petition was filed on behalf of Stephanie by a Gilbert
lawyer who heard of the girl's efforts to stay in Phoenix on a talk
radio show Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Shick, 32, is a 1999 law school graduate who admits
having little experience with custody law. She called Portley at
home on Saturday and pleaded for the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie, a nationally known advocate for people with AIDS, has
been staying at her aunt's house since last Sunday, when she was
supposed to return to foster care. She refused to go, saying she
wants to live with family here, where she has been vacationing for
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie said Saturday that the hearing gives her hope that she
may not have to go back to what she has described as a chaotic life
in foster care, waiting for her father to do what the court has
ordered, including getting sober, to get her back.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie, who lived in Glendale for four years until she was
almost 12, was born with acquired immune deficiency syndrome. She
was expected to live only a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother died of an AIDS-related illness when Stephanie was 5.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Stephanie was taken from her father in Wisconsin
because of neglect and possible abuse, according to police records
there.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a judge ordered Stephanie back to Wisconsin by
today.
</P>
<P>
   If she was not back on time, Judge Ralph Ramirez said sheriff's
deputies in Arizona would pick her up at her aunt's house and put
her on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie's aunt, Cathy Stelter, is nervous. If the Arizona
judge denies the petition that would allow her to stay, Stephanie
will be in violation of Ramirez's order to be back in Wisconsin by
5 p.m. (3 p.m. Arizona time).
</P>
<P>
   Stelter has told her niece that she will back any decision she
makes, but that if she keeps Stephanie from returning to Wisconsin,
she could be criminally charged with custodial interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so nervous,'' Stelter said Saturday, ``I think I'm going
to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shick works for Wilson Law Offices in Gilbert, where a defense
fund has been set up for Stephanie.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie's flight was scheduled to leave Phoenix just before
9:30 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
