<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-XENOPHOBIA (Dessau) _ Anti-immigrant incidents have
reached a critical point in Germany, particularly in the former
communist east, where a decade of unsettling change has spawned
youths who blame foreigners for taking their money, their jobs,
just about everything. By Roger Cohen. (With map)
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-COMMUNIST-PAST (Warsaw) _ In an interview, the former
head of the Polish secret services talks about the continuing
security risks of hidden collaboration with the former communist
government. He testified against Lech Walesa, the anti-communist
hero and Nobel peace prize laureate, in a trial that charged and
eventually cleared Walesa of collaborating with the communist-era
secret services and reporting on the activities of his friends and
fellow shipyard workers. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and NYT10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-MODERNIZE (Samsat) _ Up and down the Euphrates and Tigris
Rivers in southeastern Turkey, villages inhabited since the
beginning of civilization are being flooded into watery oblivion by
a vast dam system. The destruction is the price of progress. The
Turkish government is in the final years of its largest public
works project, an ambitious effort to quench an insatiable appetite
for electricity, irrigate arid land and bring jobs to this
impoverished region. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT5, NYT6 and NYT7 and map are being sent to
NYT photo and graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORE-LOGGING (Coos Bay, Oregon) _ Logging restrictions in the
Pacific Northwest have hit lumberjacks hard, especially in Oregon's
central coast. But in Coos Bay, they are fighting back. Out of work
loggers are being trained to answer phones for support-services
lines, creating 350 new jobs, and maybe 200 more to come. But that
kind of work is a far cry from the tough-guy work they are used to
and has brought many lifestyle changes. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT11 and NYT12 are being sent to NYT photo
clients)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CANCER (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ How quick action may have saved
the life of Sen. John McCain. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-OPPENHEIMER (Undated) _ Harry F. Oppenheimer, the South
African gold and diamond magnate who used his great wealth and
considerable influence in the fight against apartheid, died on
Saturday in Johannesburg. By Marilyn Berger.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SPY (Albuquerque) _ Of all the unusual aspects of what
is shaping up to be one of the most important espionage case of the
post-Cold War era _ the trial here of Wen Ho Lee, a former Los
Alamos National Laboratory nuclear scientist _ none is more
striking than the fact that it is not an espionage trial at all. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-FUTURE (Undated) _ Disregarding skepticism that the
wireless Internet might never live up to its hype if consumers get
turned off by today's bland offering of applications on mobile
devices with tiny screens, more than two dozen New York wireless
Internet companies have been spawned within what has become a
Darwinian environment for firms solely focused on the Web. New York
is emerging as the nation's center for wireless Internet
applications, financing and advertising. Eager to expunge the
dot-com taint, much of Silicon Alley is reinventing itself,
wirelessly. There is even a new buzzword to describe the scene:
``unstrung.'' By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOGAMES-SHAKEOUT (San Francisco) _ Despite falling revenue
and earnings at Electronic Arts, the world's largest independent
videogame company, the mood at the company's Silicon Valley
corporate headquarters is one of great optimism. Part of the reason
is that executives believe they have emerged relatively unscathed
from a cyclical, and expected, downturn as the industry is moving
to a new generation of consoles. At the same time, executives
assert they have made key investments they say will take the
company to new levels of prominence. Whether they have succeeded
will become clearer in the next 60 days. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and
graphic clients.)
