<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-21lopez-HNS &LR;      08-21 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-21lopez-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Subjective selection process produces best six gymnasts
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   You could call it unfair. You could even call it blatantly
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   But the difference between now and then _ the difference between
committing a crime against the American way and putting together
the best American women's gymnastics team for Sydney, is that this
time everyone knew it would be unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Unfair was in the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Although we don't care to get into the specifics of how the 2000
women's gymnastics Olympic selection process was worded, it went
something like this: Try hard, score high, and we'll tell you if
you make the Olympic team as soon as Bela Karolyi lets us know.
</P>
<P>
   These were trials that ended like so many before, which is to
say with tribulations.
</P>
<P>
   There were tears, heartbreak and so many what-ifs. There were
two days of strained nerves, terrific performances and unfathomable
pressure. There were guts, glory and anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Then, USA Gymnastics president Bob Colarossi walked into a room
underneath the stands at Boston's FleetCenter and read a list of
the Subjective Six, which are not to be confused with the
Magnificent Seven.
</P>
<P>
   Elise Ray, Amy Chow, Kristen Maloney, Morgan White, Jamie
Dantzscher and Dominique Dawes, with Alyssa Beckerman named the
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Shannon Miller-Phillips, the seven-time medalist
with a bum knee. There was no Vanessa Atler, the one dubbed a year
ago as Miller's successor, and who actually scored higher than two
of those who made the list.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was no tea party telling so many talented young
women that all those hours, days, months and years of bouncing
through gyms were all for naught.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly, with Atler scoring in the top six but being left
off the team, the decision smacked of the craziness that happened
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Kim Kelly scored high enough to make the team at the
trials but wound up being bumped from the team when USA Gymnastics
officials called for a special ``training camp,'' which was their
way of saying they wanted the previously injured Betty Okino on the
team instead.
</P>
<P>
   That was unfair. This was not.
</P>
<P>
   This was how Karolyi, Houston's maker of champions, has wanted
to conduct an Olympic trials all along.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was in the rules, and frankly, this will be the
best team USA Gymnastics could take to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike swimming, where the first two athletes to hit the wall
are Olympians _ period _ gymnastics is a sport in which reputation
and style figure as much into medal chances as physical ability.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike track, in which the clock is the only gauge, this is a
sport in which will is tested as much as ability, and judging can
be influenced by political alliances.
</P>
<P>
   It was also at the 1992 trials when former U.S. star Hilary
Grivich fell victim to obviously shady scoring from judges,
finishing eighth by less than a 10th of a point and getting left
off the team.
</P>
<P>
   That was unfair. This was not.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the only chalk you've ever rubbed between your hands has
been in a pool hall, and you couldn't tell a Salchow from a
Yurchenko if your life depended on it, you probably know that no
sport offers pressure like that which comes from teetering on a
four-inch beam with a billion people watching.
</P>
<P>
   It was will and determination Karolyi was watching as much as
the scoreboard this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Atler and others broke when the pressure kept mounting; Dawes,
the three-time Olympic veteran, and Chow, the repeat Olympian,
never wavered. Ray was consistent. Maloney was her usual consistent
self.
</P>
<P>
   And Dantzscher and White, both of whom were considered long
shots by many except for Karolyi, who raved all week about seeing a
certain confidence in their performances, proved him right by
scoring in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a strong U.S. team headed to Sydney, so much
stronger and better than the one that finished a dismal sixth at
the 1999 world championships. This is a team that again stands a
good chance of earning a medal.
</P>
<P>
   The Subjective Six.
</P>
<P>
   It was heartbreaking to see Atler's face when the announcement
came Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   It was sad to watch Miller-Phillips cry when she realized that
not even her fame could overcome a knee injury and inconsistent
performances.
</P>
<P>
   It was too bad the great Dominique Moceanu never had a chance
because of a bone chip in her knee.
</P>
<P>
   It would be impossible trying to console those who came with
Olympic dreams, only to see them quashed by a slip or two, an
ill-timed injury or a nervous bobble.
</P>
<P>
   It was sad watching those who barely missed, like it always is
sad.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't unfair.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7601 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ART-WHEREABOUTS-LADN     08-21 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-WHEREABOUTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTORY SOUGHT FOR CITY`S ART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Little-known fact 1: The city of Los Angeles owns
a multimillion-dollar art collection, with thousands of unique
pieces from oil paintings to bronze busts.
</P>
<P>
   Little known fact 2: Many of the more than 2,000 works of art
are stored in a warehouse with no climate control.
</P>
<P>
   Little known fact 3: Hundreds of works are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, city leaders are calling for an inventory of the collection
and a review of how it is handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not seem relevant to me for the city to own art that
is being locked up in a warehouse somewhere, not being seen, not
being appreciated,'' said City Councilwoman Laura Chick, a leading
displayer of the city's art collection in her council offices as
well as a member of the council's Government Efficiency Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The collection has been amassed during more than 100 years, said
Roella Louie, director of grants, public art and planning for the
city's Cultural Affairs Department. It includes gifts presented to
the city's mayors and other city officials over the years, other
donated pieces, and works of sculpture purchased for public
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how much the collection is worth, or even where all
of it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even venture a guess,'' Louie said.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate students from local universities are trying to
inventory and track down the city's art collection, including
researching the background of the pieces, Louie said. But she said
it is a time-consuming project and they can catalog only about 10
to 15 piece a year.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, some of the pieces are scattered throughout the
city in various municipal buildings and offices. An abstract bronze
sculpture in a fountain at the DWP. Oil paintings of past mayors.
Musical instruments at the Watts Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Chick has several pieces in her City Hall office and displays
posters at her district office in Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am putting the city's art to good public use, and I want to
know that all of it is being used that way. If we own art, then I
want to see that it's put to its maximum and best use,'' Chick
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces of the massive collection that are not on display,
however, sit in a dark downtown warehouse borrowed from the
Department of Water and Power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ideal storage space, but it's the only space we
could get,'' Louie said. ``It's not museum quality - temperature,
light and dust-controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the city began renovating the historic City Hall, the
collection was in a room, ``just thrown in, stuffed in like
somebody's closet,'' Louie said. Since the renovation, which
started about two years ago, the works have been stored in the
warehouse space.
</P>
<P>
   Art museums take pains to make sure the works of art are in
controlled and stable environment. Fluctuating humidity and
temperature, bugs or a leaking roof can destroy irreplaceable
artwork, said Victoria Blyth-Hill, director of conservation for the
Los Angeles County Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art ages just as everything else does and if you don't control
the environment, then you accelerate that aging process and at some
point it can become an irreversible process,'' she said. ``The
damage can be so extreme that there is really nothing that one can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Coupal, president of the statewide Howard Jarvis Taxpayers
Association, said while it is appropriate for a city to have a
municipal art museum, the Los Angeles art collection sounds like
``a case of bad asset management.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to make the decision whether or not these works are
going to be collected or displayed and, if not, they need to
liquidate them, if for no other reason than to make sure they are
well-preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in nobody's best interest to have valuable works of art
deteriorate, either from an art perspective or taxpayer
perspective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
