<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS MUSCLES SPORT TO ANOTHER LEVEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Just when it seemed we had seen Tiger Woods'
prismatic golf game from every angle, we saw it Sunday in a
different light. The genius he exhibited in taking the U.S. and
British Open championships by a combined 23 strokes earlier this
summer was breathtaking, but not as stunning as the manner in which
Woods won his second consecutive PGA Championship crown and third
straight major.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was one stroke behind journeyman Bob May with two holes
remaining despite birdies on three of the first seven holes of
Valhalla Golf Club's back nine. He was playing well, but May was
having a day suitable for framing in the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   Woods didn't get demoralized; he drew even with his playing
partner with birdies on the final two holes. That forced a
three-hole continuation of the high drama and ended with another
high-water mark in Woods' career. The 24-year-old beat May by one
stroke in the playoff to become the first golfer to win three
majors in a single year since Ben Hogan in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that Woods cinched another piece of history on a
Valhalla course that had none to speak of before Sunday. Because
with every swing he takes the multiracial superstar is separating
himself from the game as it was played by Ben Hogan at Oakland
Hills and Sam Snead at Oakmont Country Club and Jack Nicklaus at
Congressional.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is as distinctly different from golf's old guard as
Valhalla is from any of the venerable pre-World War II courses that
previously have hosted the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   He is not about pastel sweaters and exclusionary policies and
well-stocked 19th holes. He has taken golf out of the boardrooms
and the bars and plunked it down in places that were not considered
hospitable to birdies or eagles.
</P>
<P>
   We're not speaking simply of minority households in Compton or
Cypress, where Woods was reared. Much has been made of how Woods,
who is of African-American and Thai descent, has given the game
more color. Less acknowledged is how he also has given the game
considerably more muscle.
</P>
<P>
   To focus on his skin pigmentation is to fail to notice the
6-foot-2 frame carved like an ice sculpture. Woods wasn't as brawny
when he turned pro in August of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years he has worked feverishly to fill out his
frame with 20 pounds of muscle. In doing so, he has added length
off the tee and stamina and sent his rivals scrambling for personal
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Scotsman Colin Montgomerie, whom golf announcer David Feherty
once dubbed ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' in an allusion to his doughy body,
recently became the latest player to follow Woods down the path to
six-pack abs.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing 14 strokes behind Woods at the British Open,
Montgomerie hired a personal trainer. ``When Michael Jordan started
playing basketball, people had to improve to compete with him,''
said Montgomerie, who finished tied for 39th here. ``When Carl
Lewis started running very, very fast, people had to improve to
stay with him. When Pele played (soccer), people had to improve to
play with him. Muhammad Ali was the same. I believe Tiger is from
this town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the world's best athlete playing our game. With all
due respect to the many, many major champions we have had, we have
never had that in golf before.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, one of those major champions had to agree with
Montgomerie. ``You are seeing a phenomenon here,'' Watson said,
``that the game may never, ever see again.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency is to talk about Woods as though he was fashioned
in a laboratory by his mad scientist father, Earl. As has been well
documented, Earl taught the only child of his second marriage how
to swing a golf club when Tiger was 10 months old. When Tiger was 1
year old, he learned how to putt. At 8, he was beating collegians.
</P>
<P>
   His father and mother, Kultida, may have raised Woods to be a
champion, but Woods was the one who made their influence matter.
Marv Marinovich was no less fastidious than Earl Woods in rearing
son Todd to be a superlative quarterback, and all of Southern
California has borne witness to how flawed that plan proved to be.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has become the exemplary athlete that Todd Marinovich did
not because he took his parents' blueprint and continues to this
day to build on it. He re-tooled his swing after winning the 1997
Masters by 12 strokes, thumbing his nose at the maxim that if it
isn't broke, don't fix it.
</P>
<P>
   This refusal to rest on his God-given gifts distinguishes Woods
as much as his power-red golf shirts, his licorice-like flexibility
and his 300-plus yard drives.
</P>
<P>
   He is driven by a compulsion greater than that impressed upon
him by either of his parents. Why else would he have prepared for
this tournament by watching videotape of every shot of the 1996 PGA
Championship, which also was held here? ``Woods wants to be the
best player that ever lived,'' Watson said. ``I think that pretty
much explains it.''
</P>
<P>
   That would certainly explain why Woods isn't merely No. 1 in the
world rankings, he also is easily in the top 3 in range hours
logged.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had a piece of the lead or the lead outright after each of
the first three rounds here, but that didn't cause him to become
complacent. He repaired to the range each night, defying darkness,
to refine a swing that already is picture perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the praise heaped on Woods last week, perhaps none was
more weighty than Watson and Nicklaus saying they watch Woods
carefully to try to learn from his shots. That's like Mozart saying
he listened to Beethoven to learn more about music.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus wondered aloud why nobody rose to challenge Woods at
the U.S. and British Opens. That was before Nicklaus played his
first competitive round with Woods last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sort of understanding why we don't have anybody else
playing that well,'' Nicklaus said afterward. ``He is that much
better than everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Valhalla, a Nicklaus-designed course that opened in 1986, might
grow up to be one of the grand post-World War II courses. Woods,
meanwhile, is launching golf into the 21st century with all the
subtlety of a nuclear blast.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus noted Woods' prodigious length off the tee, his
exceptional course management, his tremendous touch around the
greens and concluded that Woods ``plays a game with which I'm not
familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf insiders quivered in their soft spikes at the historical
significance of such a statement; years ago the celebrated amateur,
Bobby Jones, said the same thing of Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Only time will tell if Woods will surpass Nicklaus' legacy. The
older Woods gets, the harder it will be for him to keep life's
myriad distractions at a distance.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in the ensuing years, there can be no arguing
when the new golfing millennium started. The year 2000 will go down
as the start of a new period of prosperity and happiness for the
game. On the golf calendar, the year of the Tiger has been one
continuous celebration of greatness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
