<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lima critical of Dierker in wake of Astros' loss to Brewers
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Win and almost every problem _ no matter how big or small _
seems to magically disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Lose a game or two _ or 74 in the Astros' case _ and every
little word can spark internal controversy and disharmony.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima has never been speechless. On Sunday afternoon, he had
plenty to say, and most of it pointed toward manager Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everything I do here is wrong. Now I know who's
your friend and who's not your friend,'' Lima said following a 6-5
loss to the Milwaukee Brewers at Enron Field that snapped the
Astros' six-game winning streak. ``When things are not going your
way, they turn their back on you. I've seen that all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who was visibly upset at being removed after only five
innings Sunday, accused Dierker of losing confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the situation during his postgame media session, Dierker
criticized Lima's lack of an inside pitch and failure to hold
runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same things we've talked about over and over and over
again,'' said Dierker. ``He's done some things from Day 1 of the
season. Some games he gets away with it; some games he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   With the scored tied at 5, the Brewers won the game when Henry
Blanco doubled in the go-ahead run off Jose Cabrera (2-3) with two
outs in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real hurt right now, because I know I'm better, and I know
I deserve respect,'' said Lima. ``I feel there's no respect here .
. . like I'm just another guy. I don't have anything against
anybody here. I don't fight with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of Lima's comments, Dierker responded: ``He's stayed
in the rotation all year long. That's some measure of confidence.
All I can say, the record speaks for itself. I know he won 21 games
last year, but this is a long way from last year. We're almost to
September.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima struck out four of the first eight batters he faced before
allowing a run in the third inning. He escaped a bases-loaded jam
in the fourth but ran into trouble in the fifth when the Brewers
scored two runs, one coming on an error by second baseman Bill
Spiers.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker used a pinch hitter for Lima, who had thrown 102
pitches, in the bottom half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't look like he was getting ready to get
straightened out,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Lima disagreed with Dierker's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things are not going your way, they are not going your
way,'' Lima said. ``I pitched inside today and gave up some hits.
Do I have to pitch inside the whole time? It has nothing to do with
pitching inside or outside. Let them say what they want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 4-2, the Astros rallied to take a 5-4 lead
with three runs in the seventh inning on Tony Eusebio's two-run
single and Chris Truby's RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   But Milwaukee scored two runs in its final two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Charlie Hayes singled with one out off Wayne
Franklin, who was replaced by Cabrera. Rafael Belliard followed
with a grounder between first and second that hit Hayes in the
foot. Hayes was called out, and Belliard reached on a single.
</P>
<P>
   Blanco, who went 3-for-5, followed with a double to center field
to score Belliard with the go-ahead run. On the play, center
fielder Richard Hidalgo bobbled the ball momentarily before what
might have been a close play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the game, Cabrera had two wins and had retired 12 of
13 batters, including six on Saturday, since being recalled from
Class AAA New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have been perfect in the field, we would have
won,'' Dierker said. ``But you can't play perfect defense every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Leskanic (4-3) pitched two scoreless innings, striking
out two batters in the ninth for Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The loss overshadowed Jeff Bagwell's 38th home run of the season
and ninth in the past 10 games for the Astros. Hidalgo added his
31st homer.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
