<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woods outduels May to repeat as PGA champion
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The man who made it look so easy so many times
showed Sunday that he can create history the old-fashioned way,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Hard work, hustle and a don't-fail-me-now putting stroke were
Tiger Woods' best allies in the final round of the PGA
Championship. And it was a good thing, because he needed every one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Woods went 8 under par in a 13-hole stretch to nail down his
third major in a row and become the first back-to-back winner in
the PGA in 63 years as he prevailed in a three-hole playoff over
previously unheralded Bob May.
</P>
<P>
   It was a riveting head-to-head battle at Valhalla Golf Club. And
it looked for the longest time like Bob may. But in the end, Tiger
would.
</P>
<P>
   Woods found himself two shots behind after making two early
bogeys in his round. But starting with a birdie on the seventh and
ending with a 20-foot birdie putt on the first extra hole, Woods
did everything he needed to keep pace with May, who provided a
wonderful test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a memorable battle,'' Woods said. ``I enjoyed it. And I
hope Bob did, too. It was a very special day to have two guys
playing at a level you don't see unless you have the concentration
heightened to where it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never backed off from one another. And that's as good as it
gets right there. We played one of the best duels in
major-championship history.''
</P>
<P>
   The win had everything _ elegant shot-making, clutch putts and a
worthy challenger. It even had a final-hole detour through
adventure, drama, cart paths, deep woods, bunker shots and gallery
members who ducked for cover, but not a single shot in the fairway
by either player.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Woods shot a final-round 67 for a 72-hole
total of 18-under 270 and had won his third consecutive major
championship. He and Ben Hogan, who did it in 1953, are the only
players to win three of the four modern majors in the same year.
Woods also ends the jinx of nobody repeating as PGA champ since
Denny Shute in 1936 and '37.
</P>
<P>
   Woods won with style. He birdied three holes in a row _ the
final two in regulation and the first one in the playoff _ then
held on against a game May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I proved to a lot of people that I could handle the
heat,'' said May, who started the day one shot behind Woods and
shot 6-under 66 for the third day in a row. ``Believe it or not, I
don't feel disappointed. I think if you shoot three 66s in a major
championship, you should win. But playing with the best player in
the world, he proved that's not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a good, solid round of golf. It just wasn't quite
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It was plenty to push Woods to the brink. Standing on the 17th
tee, May had a one-stroke lead. It had long since become a
two-horse race.
</P>
<P>
   Woods smoked a drive; May left his in the rough. May proceeded
to make a solid par, but Woods stuffed his sand-wedge approach
inside of two feet for a tying birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Both hit the par-5 18th green in two shots. Woods was on the
right side of the green, May on the left. Both had nasty swales to
conquer to get to the hole.
</P>
<P>
   May putted first and knocked his ball off the back edge of the
green, leaving him 15 feet on his birdie try.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swales out there are pretty big,'' May said. ``So I
thought I had to hit the putt pretty hard. I really was
concentrating on the line. But once you get over the hill, it
starts going downhill, which I didn't pay attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meanwhile, left his big-breaking, right-to-left putt five
feet outside the hole. Both players had downhillers left, and May's
birdie putt zeroed in on the hole like it had eyes. Woods then
calmly knocked in his tester, sending the tournament to a
three-hole playoff, a new format implemented this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the first playoff hole, the par-4 16th, May made a remarkable
par, blasting out of the deep rough short and right of the green to
within six inches.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods would not be denied. He had hit a 7-iron 20 feet right
of the hole, and the putt dived straight into the cup. The one-shot
lead would hold up the rest of the way, although not without some
excitement, particularly on the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Woods yanked his tee shot ``50 yards left of the fairway,'' he
said. The ball hit trees and cart paths and finally skittered
backward through the gallery. He then knifed his second shot into
the left rough and his third into the bunker in front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   May wasn't much better, although he knew he was being given a
grand opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left the door open, which was totally unexpected from
Tiger, to hit a drive like that,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   But May put his drive in the left rough and sprayed his second
shot into the right rough. His approach was on the green, but 25
feet right of the hole in the same swale from which Woods had to
play in the regulation finale. Woods, meanwhile, wasn't upset with
being in the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, he put the shot a foot from the hole, and when
May's birdie try slid by on the low side, Woods had the fifth major
championship of his young career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, you knew you had to execute golf shots,'' Woods said.
``Par wasn't going to win any holes. That made it more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there were eight players within two shots of May and
Woods on the front nine, it became their show on the back nine.
Nobody would finish within four shots of the two front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Woods got off to a ragged start when he bogeyed two of the first
six holes, giving May the lead. The pair was tied at 13-under when
Woods rammed in a 15-footer for birdie at the par-3 eighth, and
when they both parred the ninth, the back-nine stage was set for a
shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Woods tried his best to make a statement on the 14th, rolling in
a 12-footer on the par-3 for birdie. But May had stuck his 4-iron
shot to within five feet and made the putt on top of Woods' to
retain the one-shot edge.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a point when May failed to close the deal, it came
at the 15th. Woods' second shot on the par-4 hooked 20 yards left
of the hole, but he got a good kick off the hill into a closely
cropped collection area. He putted eight feet past the hole but
canned the par putt.
</P>
<P>
   When May missed his five-footer for birdie, the game was very
much in doubt. May, at 17-under, continued to cling to the one-shot
edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had missed and he made his, he'd be three up with three
holes to go and looking pretty good,'' Woods said. ``I felt if I
missed, he would make. And I knew if I made mine, it would make his
a little bit longer. I just stepped up there and buried it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
