u s BC-GLF-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     08-21 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger able to handle heat, even from Cinderella
</P>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger Woods made a whole slew of additional
golfing history Sunday, as if we're supposed to be startled by that
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob May, a man of considerably more modest means and
aspirations, could at least leave Valhalla having made a name for
himself. Whatever, if anything, comes of May, after this fateful
near-miss of a major breakthrough, he'll never be Bob Who? again.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the rich got richer. Goliath did a Houdini and
wriggled free. Yes, Tiger won, and Bob lost. Imagine that. But the
fourth round of the 82nd PGA Championship, extended by three
playoff holes because neither the Chosen One nor the Obscure One
deigned to blink, offered up marvelous theater and, on repeated
occasions, hyperventilating shot-making worthy of anyone who ever
gripped a club.
</P>
<P>
   The route to such a predictable (foregone?) conclusion would be
jammed full of more electric moments and courageous feats _ with a
healthy dollop of duffer comedy interjected at the finish _ than
most entire golf tournaments, certainly the sort Woods has been
sucking the drama from of late.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's conquering-hero Sundays at the U.S. and British Opens
were lazy victory laps, not grueling tests of fortitude. Here at
the PGA, in contrast, he showed us he can handle real pressure,
never mind how utterly improbable would be the source of it.
</P>
<P>
   May, a 31-year-old refugee from a half-decade innocuously spent
traipsing around the European circuit, has never won a North
American PGA Tour event, major or minor. Bob's first foray, in
1994, into the weekly meat grinder that Woods is making such a
mockery of saw him earn $31,079 _ in 31 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Disconsolate if not defeated, he fled across the pond soon
thereafter and didn't return stateside until the current season.
Other than to let the FedEx St. Jude Classic slip from his grasp on
the final day, after he had earlier missed four cuts in five
starts, May hadn't done a single noteworthy thing in seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Until he earned the right to tango, one-on-one, with Tiger on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A stroke separated Woods and May when the afternoon began. A
stroke still separated them when it was over, although for much of
the race it was Woods who found himself playing catch-up. Tiger's
yippy putter let May pry open a two-stroke lead after six holes,
and Woods didn't draw even until 17, when his birdie putt trumped
May's gutsy save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a good, solid round,'' May said. ``It just wasn't
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Good? Solid? Cripes, he posted a 5-under 31 on the backside
under the most extreme duress imaginable, applied by the fastest
tracker to greatness the game has known. But Tiger, being Tiger,
also shot 31, with his 31st swing a right-on five-foot birdie putt
that replied, resoundingly, to May's own 15-footer for a birdie
from the back fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Twice on 18 it came down to Mr. Par 5 vs., as a colleague noted,
``a guy in a hat.'' The latter proved the former's equal the first
time, but he had only one checkmate move in him.
</P>
<P>
   While neither player, both largely spent by then, hit the
fairway on the 75th hole, Woods parlayed a lucky bounce off a
horrid drive into a magnificently salvaged par, although he wasn't
home free until May's 30-footer for birdie, requiring an almost
90-degree break, rolled inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one heck of a battle on the back nine,'' Woods
admitted. ``The fireworks started for both of us. This was one of
the greatest duels I've had in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   By winning it, he entered yet another superstar stratum. Only
Ben Hogan had won three professional majors in the same year until
Tiger completed his 3-for-3 summer sweep. Perhaps more remarkably,
his 72-hole cumulative of 18-under (equaled by May, of course) put
his name in the record books for the lowest scores relative to par
in all four majors.
</P>
<P>
   And he's only 24, competing in a sport men aren't supposed to
fully grasp until their 30s.
</P>
<P>
   On longevity and the sheer volume of his important titles _ 18
Slams _ Jack Nicklaus remains many points ahead of Woods in the
best-ever tally, but even Jack won't argue with the notion that
Tiger has proved himself to be the finest golfer ever relative to
his peer group in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus collected his record stash of championships at the
expense of a series of fabled fellow thoroughbreds, from Arnold
Palmer and Gary Player on through Lee Trevino, Johnny Miller and
Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's lament here this week, a week that saw him formally pass
the torch to Woods as the keeper of the flame when they finally
paired up Thursday and Friday, was that none of the ostensibly
regal lads who should be stepping up to challenge Tiger's supremacy
is doing so, and the PGA's mismatched showdown proved Jack's point.
</P>
<P>
   May deserves hearty applause for throwing his body in front of
the Woods freight train. But where was Ernie Els? Jose Maria
Olazabal? Davis Love III? Justin Leonard? Phil Mickelson?
</P>
<P>
   Why weren't they in that playoff instead of Bob? When will they
stand up and answer the imposing challenge Tiger presents?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
