<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PGA-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER'S TALE STILL GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ They golfed for five hours Sunday at Valhalla
Golf Club, and this is how good they were: literally too much for
one man's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The night before Tiger Woods and Bob May gave this infant of a
course its proper christening, May began to dream about the final
round of the PGA Championship. The dream was abruptly cut off, as
if May had pirated free cable and had his line disconnected. His
subconscious must have known that he couldn't handle _ or wouldn't
believe _ a sneak preview of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played a hole out,'' May said of his interrupted
dream. ``I just kept on seeing holes.''
</P>
<P>
   When the day finally ended, May had actually seen and played 21
holes. And Woods must have seen visions of the men he now stands
next to in golf history. Woods is the greatest player of his
generation and he played like it, winning the championship in a
thrilling three-hole playoff. He has won three majors in the same
year, and three in a row, the first player to do that since Ben
Hogan accomplished it in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   In '53, Woods's father, Earl, was 22. Now Earl's son, 24, has
wiped the dust from dog-eared history books and calligraphied his
name in them. His tag will read something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods . . . golf innovator.
</P>
<P>
   The innovation began long before Sunday, the greatest golfing
day of the year. May and Woods golfed inside and outside the ropes.
Woods began the day with a one-shot lead. May caught him, passed
him, and threatened to make it a three-shot advantage on 15. Woods
tied it on 17, and gave this crowd something to cheer and be
confused about.
</P>
<P>
   Do you root for history? Or do you root for the guy who used to
be Tiger's neighbor?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the gallery chose Woods, probably because they realized
golf has never had a champion like this. If he were a recording
artist, Woods would have overwhelming crossover appeal. He has
brought hipness to golf. He has brought more fans to the galleries,
making them swell even more than they did in the days of Arnie's
Army. In some way, he has changed you, too.
</P>
<P>
   If you are tired of him, you watch to see him fail.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a longtime golf fan, you watch to see him give your
sport a good name.
</P>
<P>
   Woods's name is now referenced in the most unusual places. One
of the characters in ``Shaft'' mentioned him. Last month at Fenway
Park, several hours before Jerry Manuel's White Sox were to play
the Red Sox, the Chicago manager sat in the visitors' dugout and
asked one of his coaches, ``Did you see Tiger today?'' He is the
athlete _ yes, he's an athlete _ that nonsports fans find most
provocative, most relevant, and most interesting.
</P>
<P>
   His father said he would have the social impact of great men
(Martin Luther King Jr. and Gandhi) who changed the way people
thought about worldwide equality and justice. Well, let's just call
that parental exuberance. If you interviewed 100 parents, 95 of
them would promise you that their children could be famous
surgeons. Tiger Woods is not the preacher-poet that King was.
Gandhi stared down British soldiers; Woods simply won the British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   There has been so much commentary about his race and his age and
his commercials that we don't focus on this enough: He is an
incredibly bright and talented golfer. Everyone from May to Jack
Nicklaus has said that, but they have also said they didn't realize
how good he was until they played with him.
</P>
<P>
   May played with him Sunday for those titillating five hours and
got the full Tiger Ensemble. He saw the crowds; saw the drives; saw
the unusual club selections (He's using a 2-iron here? Are you
kidding me?); saw the stare _ especially after Woods birdied 17 _
that reminded you that if you are going to beat this guy, you will
have to come with something extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   May did that. And he did it longer than anyone expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's got to go down as one of the best duels in the
game, in major championships,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   May and Woods, seven years apart, used to play the same southern
California golf courses. Woods was 9. May was 16. The older kid
would play a complete round. The youngster, some new jack called
Tiger, would play nine.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the old days, they played 21 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Their final shots in regulation were putts that could have ended
the tournament. May lined up his putt, tapped it, watched it take a
long journey to the hole (imagine syrup taking its time coming out
of the bottle), and then saw it curl into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Woods made his putt to force the playoff. You knew he would do
that, just as you knew Bill Russell's teams would win in the NBA
Finals. Just as you knew Joe Montana's teams would not lose in the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Woods birdied the first playoff hole, leaving the gracious May
in a trail of playoff pars. After the birdie, Woods became an
interactive golfer: two of his shots went deep into the gallery and
onto a walkway.
</P>
<P>
   So there was Tiger, taking one shot with a man in a red shirt
practically looking over his shoulder. On the other shot, there was
the man in the red shirt again, behind Tiger, mugging for the small
city of photographers that followed Woods for the bulk of the 75
holes he walked here.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after all the emotion and brush with Woods's raging
celebrity, we are left with numbers. Historical numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is the first PGA champion to repeat in 63 years. He holds
under-par records in four majors _ the Masters, British Open, US
Open, and the PGA Championship. And he has those three majors this
year.
</P>
<P>
   He left here Sunday with a silver winner's trophy, $900,000,
respect from and for May, and memories of grateful Kentuckians
singing ``My Old Kentucky Home'' to him on the 18th green. He
should also have the knowledge that the sport will never be the
same. Golfers exercise more often now because Tiger does. Golfers
play better because they don't want Tiger to embarrass them. And
records, even the oldest records, are now vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The achievements of Hogan, Nicklaus, Sam Snead, and Byron
Nelson, still rest on the sport's front-room mantel. But they have
to move a few inches over now. They have to make room for Tiger
Woods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
