u s BC-GLF-PGACHAMPIONSHIP-B     08-21 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS A HISTORY MAJOR 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ From the edge of the Pacific Ocean to hallowed
land in Scotland to America's heartland, Tiger Woods has spent the
summer playing an unprecedented brand of golf that has ushered him
into the pages of history.
</P>
<P>
   But standing on the 18th hole of Valhalla Golf Club Sunday, he
was faced with the harshest reality this game offers: Make the putt
or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Woods never flinched, never lost focus, never questioned his
nerve. When he curled in the birdie putt from 5 feet to complete a
round of 5-under-par 67 for an 18-under 270 total, he set in motion
a three-hole playoff victory over unheralded Bob May in the 82d PGA
Championship to vault himself into an atmosphere never before seen
in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One memorable battle,'' said Woods, who joined Ben Hogan as
the only players in modern history to win three major championships
in a season. ``We never backed off. We went birdie-for-birdie,
shot-for-shot. It was a very special day.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke quietly and his smile had disappeared, proof not that
Woods was unappreciative of the momentous occasion, but that he was
physically and emotionally drained from what he called ``one of the
toughest battles'' he had ever faced on a golf course. May, before
this weekend a virtual unknown who required a special exemption to
get into the event, put up a challenge that people had cried for in
the aftermath of Woods's 15- and eight-shot wins in the US and
British opens earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I proved to a lot of people that I can play under the heat,''
said May. He should have said ``near-flawlessly,'' too, because he
strung together his third consecutive 66 to threaten Woods's walk
into the pages of history. He capped off his splendid round with a
15-foot, double-breaking, downhill putt on the 18th green to force
Woods into a must-make situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expected him to make it,'' said Woods. ``You have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   May, in turn, knew what was coming. ``My caddie (Steve Kaye)
said, `Partner, get ready. We're going to a playoff.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Woods drained the left-to-right breaker to match May with a 31
back side, and off they trudged to the par-4 16th, each of them at
18-under but only one of them stalking history. May was simply
trying to win for the first time on the PGA Tour in this, his
rookie year at the age of 31.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been sudden death, it would have been over quickly, for
Woods found the fairway with a 2-iron on the 444-yard hole, rifled
a 7-iron to 20 feet, and drained the birdie putt to go in front.
But in a new twist, the PGA of America uses a three-hole aggregate
format, so Woods and May, who had saved par at that first playoff
hole from a greenside bunker, went on to the 17th and 18th again.
</P>
<P>
   They were mad scrambles for both. The play for the first time
all day was ragged, but Woods was able to save par after driving
right into the woods at the 422-yard 17th, then at the 18th when he
inexplicably pulled his drive way left, over hills and onto a cart
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left the door open,'' said May, ``which was totally
unexpected from Tiger. I was just trying to hit a good, solid drive
down there.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time all day, May failed miserably. He pulled his
drive well left into thick grass on the hill, had to lay up, then
knocked his third to the right of the pin, some 35 feet away, down
on a lower tier.
</P>
<P>
   Woods missed the fairway with his layup, then found the bunker
with his third shot. No problem, for he had birdied this hole three
times from that sand. And he mastered it again _ a blast to tap-in
range that put the 18th hole pressure this time on May.
</P>
<P>
   He had handled it well all day, but this was too much to ask.
Though his birdie putt tracked the hole all the way, it curled dead
left at the end, leaving the players short par putts that put an
end to one of the most dramatic days pro golf has seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it,'' said Woods, a mind-boggling 49 under in this
summer's three major championship triumphs this summer, ``and I'm
sure Bob did, too.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, though the three extra holes weren't as satisfying as
the first 18 to May, who honed his game the past few years on the
European Tour. He had made a run at a victory earlier in the year
in Memphis, but this was his first time on the big stage. He didn't
disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day one back, he assumed the lead at the par-5
second when he made birdie on top of Woods's bogey, and pushed it
to two shots with a birdie at the fourth. Woods slapped a
birdie-birdie hit on him at Nos. 7 and 8 to take the match even
into the turn and set the stage for a scintillating back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best duels in the game,'' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   That he was on the short end of it was shocking, but there was
May making three straight birdies starting at the 10th, then
another at the 14th to get to 17 under, one ahead of Woods, who had
merely birdied 10, 12, and 14.
</P>
<P>
   At the 402-yard, par-4 15th, one of the most shocking upsets in
golf history appeared sealed. May stared at a birdie putt from 5
feet thanks to a brilliant 7-iron approach, then stole a look at
where Woods had ended up _ behind the green, long with an 8-iron,
his ball coming to rest in a collection area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Misread the putt, misjudged the slope,'' said Woods, who
putted poorly to 15 feet. Yes, a three-shot lead was on May's mind,
but Woods saw things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I made mine, it would make his a little longer,''
said Woods. ``If I missed, I knew he'd make his. Three down with
three to go wouldn't look pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who had nearly putted his way out of the match on the
front nine, is reminding everyone of a young Jack Nicklaus _ that
is, deadly on any putt he has to make. He drained that 15-footer
for par, May indeed missed his birdie chance, and the deficit was
just one.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long, because Woods two holes later scorched a drive
high into the blue Kentucky sky, his ball coming to rest 335 yards
away. He flipped a 60-degree sand wedge at the pin, the ball hit
once, skipped, checked, and came to rest 2 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   He drained it, of course, and was tied at 17 under, taking his
bid for history to the 72d hole in front of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   It is a par-5 that ends 542 yards from the tee, at a green that
has three tiers. With his second shot, May found the left tier,
perhaps 100 feet from the pin. With his second shot, Woods found
the right tier, 30-35 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   May badly navigated his first putt, hitting it too high on a
ridge, and it moved left. ``You see it going left, you know it is
done and over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods's putt was shorter, but also traveled up and over a ridge
and when it came to rest 6 feet above the pin, May figured he had
to make his _ and he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he made it, it really wasn't that big a surprise,'' said
Woods. ``I knew I had to make mine to tie.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. Which was not a surprise, either. At least not to
those who had seen this act at Pebble Beach and St. Andrews this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
