<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BUCCANEERS-BOSl </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS POSITIVELY MEDIOCRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After a game Sunday in which neither team
gave away much beacuse they meet again in the regular-season opener
here Sept. 3, New England quarterback Drew Bledsoe said, ``I think
we did enough good things and showed that we can move the ball and
score some points against their defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's coach, Bill Belichick, agreed. At least he agreed
enough to pull the first-team offense in the first half of a 31-21
loss to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. Beyond that, Bledsoe and
Belichick weren't happy with many other aspects of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have four fumbles, nine penalties, and one blocked
punt, we made too many mistakes,'' Belichick said. ``Though we did
a few positive things, they were overridden by poor plays, costly
individual plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe went 10 for 18 for 77 yards and didn't turn the ball
over. But the Patriots continued their third-down woes, going 4 for
14 (29 percent).
</P>
<P>
   One of the two touchdowns produced by the offense came on Kevin
Faulk's 58-yard second-quarter run, which gave him a slight edge in
the derby to become the team's starting running back.
</P>
<P>
   Also impressive was the play of the first-team defense. Chad
Eaton, Willie McGinest, Chris Slade, Brandon Mitchell, Lawyer
Milloy, Ty Law, Tedy Bruschi, and Tebucky Jones all had superb
games, holding the Bucs to 62 yards on the ground in the first half
and pressuring Shaun King into a tough 8-for-21 performance for 158
yards in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs had two fluke plays go their way, including a touchdown
pass to Jacquez Green in the second quarter that tipped off tight
end Dave Moore's hands and into Green's. The play went for 55
yards. Earlier there was another tip, when Law seemed to nicely
defend a long pass to Green, but he knocked the ball forward and it
landed in Green's hands for a 58-yard catch. The Bucs squandered
that opportunity when they missed a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots evened things when Faulk got loose for his
touchdown run right up the middle with 10:10 left in the second.
Max Lane blocked strong-side linebacker Shelton Quarles while
Damien Woody pushed the nose tackle aside, opening a nice hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't pay much attention to the block or who I
blocked. It was just one play,'' said Lane. A big play.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk's eyes bulged when he saw the opening, and he told
himself, ``Wow. Do not let anyone catch you from behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk, who has had the best exhibition season among the
Patriots' running backs (rookie J.R. Redmond made an unimpressive
debut Sunday, fumbling a punt), believes he can be the No. 1 back.
``I know I can, but I have to prove that to the coaches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bucs defensive tackle Brad Culpepper said, ``The majority of
plays we shut them down, but then they had the big draw play. Last
year we prided ourselves on not giving up the big play. There was a
gap assignment missed on that play that has to be corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense then went to work, swarming fullback Mike
Alstott and forcing a fumble that was scooped up by Law and run in
20 yards for the go-ahead score.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Martin Gramatica kicked a 36-yard field goal to make
it 14-10, Patriots, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's day ended with six seconds left in the first half when
offensive coordinator Charlie Weis summoned Michael Bishop to throw
a Hail Mary pass, which was picked off.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop started the third quarter quite poorly. He dropped back
deep in Patriots territory and had the ball slip out of his hand as
he cocked his arm. Linebacker Jamie Duncan recovered the ball in
the end zone, giving the Bucs a 17-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was setting up a screen pass to J.R.,'' said Bishop. ``J.R.
was out in the flat and I had my hand going forward and the ball
slipped out of my hand. I thought it was a forward pass, but the
official didn't agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 24-14, following another score by the Bucs on a
32-yard pass from Eric Zeier to Karl Williams, Bishop tried to
mount a comeback, finding his former Blinn Junior College teammate,
Shockmain Davis, for passes of 51 and 32 yards, the latter a
touchdown play that pulled the Patriots within 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bucs got a 5-yard TD run from Aaron Stecker to seal the
victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
