<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSATIONAL SIX SELECTED 
</HEADLINE>
 TRIALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The somersaulting sisters of Sydney took their
introductory bow Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at the FleetCenter, where Elise Ray,
Amy Chow, Kristen Maloney, Morgan White, Dominique Dawes, and Jamie
Dantzscher stood hand in hand after being named to the US Olympic
gymnastics team.
</P>
<P>
   But amid a shower of red, blue, and silver streamers at the
conclusion of the US Olympic Gymnastics Trials before a crowd of
16,377 on Causeway Street, there was also a tinge of sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Miller, the most decorated US gymnast in history, was
forced to pull out of the competition following the first rotation,
jamming both knees when she smacked down on the floor attempting to
land the first of two vaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, . . . I wish she would have started just a
little bit earlier,'' said Bela Karolyi, the women's team
coordinator, all but dismissing the chance the 23-year-old Miller
might be named to the team as a second alternate. ``At this point,
we can't consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alyssa Beckerman, who placed eighth in the trials, with last
month's nationals factored into the equation, was named as the
alternate _ somewhat of a surprise because Vanessa Atler finished
sixth overall and was left off the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' said Atler, who ranked 10th overall in Sunday's
final round and was under consideration to make the team as a vault
specialist, ``but when they announced the team and I wasn't on it,
I was kind of relieved. I was messing up a lot of things out there.
It wasn't my day. It wasn't my time. That's OK. I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, hoping to be named to her third Olympic squad, was
upstaged by the bold, athletic Dawes, who now will compete in her
third Games. Miller, Dawes, and Chow were all part of the
Magnificent Seven who captured the women's all-around gold medal at
the '96 Games in Atlanta. In the end, Chow was the best of the
three here, finishing second only to Ray by just over a half-point
(76.839 to 76.205).
</P>
<P>
   Could the quiet, efficient Chow _ getting better with each week
of practice while cutting her pre-med classes at Stanford _
ultimately end up the team leader Down Under?
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a leader,'' said Karolyi, ``and that's Elise
Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who captured the national championship last month, ranked
third on the final day of competition, behind Chow (1) and the
diminutive and spirited White (2). Entering the meet, Ray and
Maloney were viewed as the top guns among the new generation, the
Olympic first-timers expected to assume dynamic leading roles Down
Under. Karolyi wants Ray to be that _ thus his vote of confidence _
but Chow and Dawes, both of them steady, efficient, and strong,
right now appear more capable of fulfilling the leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the men's team, whose rules mandate the top four
finishers in the trials make the team, all six women were
handpicked. As it turned out, the top five finishers made it in
order, with Dawes (No. 7) jumping over Atler (6) for the final
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Atler said she made it clear to everyone that she didn't want to
go to Sydney if asked to go as an alternate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The performance I put out there,'' she said, ``is not like
Olympic material.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Miller's fall, the most dramatic moment of the night was
the strong performance by Dawes (9.037) on balance beam. After
sticking her landing, Dawes hopped from the floor, then jumped back
on stage to blow kisses to an adoring crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, an enthusiastic Karolyi bolted to her corner,
vigorously shook her shoulders, and enveloped her in one of his
patented bear hugs. The formal announcement would come later, but
she had her ticket to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's strong. She's mature,'' said Karolyi. ``She's a very
powerful athlete.'' Just the kind of backbone Karolyi wants, just
in case the kids cower at the foot of Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   The last glimpse the world may have seen of Miller in
competition came at 6:42 p.m. when she skipped backward in obvious
pain after landing her second vault. She returned to the floor 15
minutes later to collect her warm-up suit, the sign she was
surrendering for the night.
</P>
<P>
   When her withdrawal was announced over the PA, the crowd
murmured an audible ``Ahhh,'' and seconds later broke into
respectful applause. Quietly, with little ceremony, the torch was
passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
