<HEADLINE>
RANGERS AVERT RED SOX SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ All the Red Sox magic took a vacation Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. No
Martinez sleight of hand. No managerial masterstrokes. No last-gasp
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   And by the dreary end, no more fleeting hold on first place in
the American League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   A night of great promise swiftly went south, as Sox starter Jeff
Fassero squandered four perfect innings and his teammates reverted
to their punchless ways at the plate, never more so than with
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   The damage: a 6-2 loss to an uncelebrated Texas starter, Doug
Davis, and a Rangers club in free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   The collateral pain was a lost opportunity to creep within two
games of the Yankees, who lost, 5-4, to Anaheim. Mo Vaughn and his
Angels, just two games behind the Sox in the wild-card race, arrive
in town Monday for a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest sequel of a distressing story, the Sox left 10
runners on base. And they stayed flat through the end, unable to
recreate their recent walk-off theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of opportunities,'' manager Jimy Williams said.
``We just couldn't get those hits with guys in scoring position.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point may have come before many of the 32,467 in
Fenway downed their first beverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox loaded the bases with none out in the first inning, as
Jose Offerman legged out an infield hit, Bernard Gilkey was hit in
the right foot by a pitch, and Carl Everett singled to left.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox, unable to overcome their chronic production
shortage, all but let Davis off the hook. Nomar Garciaparra, one of
the league's toughest batters to strike out (once every 11.9 plate
appearances), whiffed on a 1-2 pitch out of the zone for the first
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `Get ahead and either strike him out or get a
double play,' '' said Davis (5-4), a lefthander who entered the
game with a 1-3 record in his last five starts with an ERA of
11.69. ``Preferably, I would have liked to get a double play, but a
strikeout's just as good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox managed a run when Troy O'Leary grounded into a
fielder's choice, allowing Offerman to score. That made it 1-0,
with runners on first and third and two out. But one of last week's
impromptu heroes, third baseman Lou Merloni, hit into a forceout to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance early to do some damage,'' Williams said,
``but . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   A better chance never came, though the Sox squandered a number
of lesser opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' said Merloni, who finally looked mortal
after a remarkable first week back with the Sox. ``We'll come back
(Monday) and put some runs up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers appeared ripe to be swept after losing the first
three games of the series (Texas had not lost a four-game series at
Fenway since the 1975 wonder year). With the worst record (13-23)
in the American League since the All-Star break, the Rangers had
lost 14 of their last 18 games. And there was the questionable
Davis on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   All that, and Fassero looking invincible.
</P>
<P>
   The lefthander, who wore a T-shirt emblazoned with ``Lucky 13''
to the park, briefly electrified the Fenway crowd by hurling the
four stellar innings. He allowed only one ball out of the infield,
a line drive to right that Darren Lewis snared on the run to start
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the 13th batter Fassero faced, Rafael Palmeiro, drilled a
poorly placed slider to left-center for a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more like Unlucky 13,'' Fassero said.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, his golden touch took on some tarnish in the fifth, when
the Rangers erupted for three runs, and lost its sheen altogether
in the sixth, when Texas scored three more. The Rangers knocked
Fassero around for six hits and drew a walk before his night of
great promise ended so unceremoniously.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not distracted by the notion of the four perfect
innings. Maybe if it had gone on into the seventh, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the pitch Palmeiro hit was the only bad one he threw
all night. The seeing-eye grounders and the bloopers were the
killers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero was left to watch from the clubhouse as the Rangers
scored their fifth and sixth runs, which were charged to him. They
scored when Rod Beck, who entered the game with runners on first
and second and none out, gave up a single to Bill Haselman, a
bases-loaded walk to Royce Clayton, and a run-scoring fielder's
choice to Frank Catalanotto.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sox stranded runners in every inning but one, the
fourth, and only then perhaps because no batters reached base.
</P>
<P>
   And Davis baffled them until the end, throwing 141 pitches for
the first complete game of his career and his team's first of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to battle,'' he said, ``and I battled all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   And he won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
