<HEADER>
A7614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-GYMNASTICSTRIALS-     08-21 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DOUBT ABOUT THIS TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 TRIALS-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They didn't need the jury room after all. The team
picked itself. After all the politics and the paranoia and the
predictions Bela Karolyi would choose whomever he wanted, the US
women's gymnastics team going to Sydney is the one that should be
going. The federation didn't have to use the old Bucharest ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``No discussion and no doubt,'' declared Karolyi, after the team
had marched out onto the FleetCenter floor Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. ``The
athletes played out their positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Elise Ray, Amy Chow, Kristen Maloney, Morgan White, and Jamie
Dantzscher were the top five in the combined standings and they
would have been the top five by any subjective standard.
</P>
<P>
   The only question was whether the sixth should be Vanessa Atler
or Dominique Dawes. And if you watched both nights of the trials,
where Atler barely showed up and Dawes kept clawing upward, the
question became moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vanessa is one of the closest to my heart,'' conceded Karolyi,
who had once hoped to build the team around her. ``She is a unique
talent, but talent is not enough. When you represent the United
States, you have to have the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   And Atler didn't perform. Not when she had to. She was in strong
contention after last month's national championships in St. Louis,
but Atler came here out of shape and out of fire. ``It just wasn't
there,'' she admitted. ``Maybe I just wasn't into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the old format, the ``fair'' format, the top six after
nationals and trials would have been on the team. That would have
meant Atler and not Dawes, who came back with medals from the last
two Olympics. But USA Gymnastics has gone the ``fair'' way before
at its trials and paid a painful price.
</P>
<P>
   Gymnastics isn't swimming, where the clock decides the victor.
It's a subjective sport, where judges award points for subjective
things like ``virtuosity'' and ``amplitude.'' Shouldn't the trials
be subjective, too? That was what federation president Bob
Colarossi said, whenever he was asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with a subjective process, at least in America, is
that it provokes lawsuits from the unchosen. The Olympic softball,
cycling, and wrestling teams have already been through arbitration
this year. It would have been easier simply to take the top six
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, but the team would have been weaker for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are not about dreams and soap operas. They are,
finally, about medals. The United States Olympic Committee will
base future funding of its sports bodies by how many medals they
win in Sydney. And this time, USA Gymnastics did not have the
luxury of leaving the team to chance.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, since the Magnificent Seven won gold in Atlanta,
the women's team has tumbled off the mat. They were sixth at the
1997 World Championships, sixth again last year. So the federation
brought Karolyi out of retirement and essentially left the
selection process in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the written procedures were more complex than the
Treaty of Ghent, and even though there was a four-person selection
committee, everybody understood the deal. Karolyi would have the
loudest voice.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everybody agreed with the deal. Ever since he defected
from Romania in 1981, his fellow coaches have regarded Karolyi with
both respect and resentment. But his resume is solid gold.
</P>
<P>
   Until Karolyi turned up, the US women hadn't won an Olympic
medal since 1948, when the rest of the world was still using beams
and floors to rebuild their war-shattered houses.
</P>
<P>
   But since Karolyi has been involved with the national program,
the US women have won three Olympic team medals and were flat-out
robbed of a fourth at Seoul. The record was beyond dispute. Once it
was clear Karolyi would not coach any individual gymnasts, the fear
and loathing subsided. The competition took care of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a one-night thing. The women competed in 16 routines
across four sessions at nationals and trials. Eventually, as
Brooklyn Dodger manager Chuck Dressen used to say, they eliminated
theirselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu and Jaycie Phelps withdrew with bad knees
before the trials even started. Shannon Miller's legs gave out and
coach Steve Nunno pulled her out after one rotation Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
Everybody else made it _ or didn't _ on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, Chow, and Maloney, as expected, were solid. White, who was
second Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, just kept getting better. Dantzscher, whom
many insiders doubted could hold up for four nights, had 14
routines of 9.0 or better.
</P>
<P>
   So when the selectors went behind closed doors, they had only
one decision to make _ Atler or Dawes? Atler had figured to be a
specialist on vault, the team's weakest event. But when the flag
went up Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, she went flat. If Atler can't do it here,
Karolyi shrugged, she won't do it in Sydney. So Dawes, who has done
it twice at Olympus, gets a third shot. No impasse in the jury
room. The team picked itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
