<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER FALLS OUT OF CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
 TRIALS-MILLER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ How much weight does it carry to have won more Olympic
and World Championship medals (17) than any gymnast, male or
female, in history? How much weight does it carry to be the only
American to have won two consecutive World Championship all-around
titles?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Miller, 23, learned that Sunday &UR;  &LR; night when she
literally fell out of contention to make the team to go to Sydney
next month. When she ran down the mat to flip over the vault in her
first routine of the night, she landed on her backside __ just like
she did Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the consequences of the fall were more dire. On
one hand, an Olympic berth was at stake. On the other hand, so was
her health.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches swarmed around Miller as she grabbed her right knee, and
the crowd at the FleetCenter grew silent. But Miller made her way
back to her feet, walked back to the start of the running mat, and
headed with determination back to the vault.
</P>
<P>
   This time she landed on her feet. But minutes later she was
scratched from the meet, and two hours later would learn she was
not going to Sydney. Not with the team, and not as an alternate.
</P>
<P>
   There was some thought that Miller, a two-time Olympian, might
make the team as a sentimental favorite, or to provide leardership
much in the same way John Roethlisberger did when he was named to
the man's team Saturday for his third trip to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But the women's team coordinator, Bela Karolyi, made clear the
selection process was based on points, not sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we could not consider her,'' he said of Miller.
``Unfortunately, . . . I wish she would have started just a little
bit earlier. But I don't know how anybody could consider her after
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is one gymnast who didn't have too much trouble getting
out of competition. After winning a gold medal on the balance beam
and another with the team in Atlanta in 1996, she headed back home
to Edmond, Okla., back to the University of Oklahoma. Last year,
she got married.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, she started persuading former coach Steve Nunno
she was ready to go back to competition, and by January he gave in.
</P>
<P>
   She looked on track to compete in the US Nationals in St. Louis
last month, until she suffered a chipped tibia in her right leg two
weeks before the meet. So she had to perform for Karolyi last
Tuesday here to prove to him she was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   He said OK, and it looked like she was on her way.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, when Miller's dreams of a third appearance
in the Olympics evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who spoke while the meet was still going on, said her
fall was not career-ending and still held out hope she'd be chosen
to be part of the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no injury,'' said Miller. ``I just jammed my legs and
came in a little short. So they're a little stiff right now and
that's why I'm not going to finish the meet.''
</P>
<P>
   And she left the door open for Karolyi when she said, ``They've
seen what I can do, and they saw what I can do Tuesday and Friday.
I'd rather sit out and be healthy if they need me and be ready for
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunno, though, wasn't so optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most disappointing event in our career,'' he said,
adding he has no intention of appealing a decision by USA
Gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to petition any further; we want to be
considered for what we can do,'' he said. ``We've been
rehabilitating and came in here healthy, and we want to walk out
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller might have walked out healthy, but not with a ticket to
Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
