<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN UPBEAT FOLLOWING STRONG START 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SABERHAGEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As a veteran of three major shoulder surgeries, Bret
Saberhagen has resigned himself to a simple rehabilitative fact:
There always will be pain.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Saberhagen can shrug off the stiffness and
soreness. So, after his sixth rehab start in Pawtucket Saturday
night, Saberhagen persevered through a small amount of pain and
pronounced himself ``headed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The righthander pitched five strong innings, throwing 75 pitches
(50 for strikes). He kept his fastball velocity consistent, ranging
between 88 and 90 miles per hour. Saberhagen felt command of his
fastball was a little off but no reason for concern. With one or
two more starts, he expects to improve his sharpness and arm
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan was particularly pleased with the
sharp break on Saberhagen's curve.
</P>
<P>
   Although Saberhagen felt some pinching in his shoulder, the arm
appeared to recover quickly. The pitcher called his brief workout
before the Red Sox played Texas Sunday night a good indicator of
how close he is to reaching the major league level. If the shoulder
rebounds quickly from a tough effort, Saberhagen gets a step closer
to taking the mound in a big league ballpark. ``I just whip it
until I can't whip it anymore,'' said Saberhagen. ``Sometimes it
responds to the challenges. Sometimes it doesn't, that's when you
have the setbacks. I'm just trying to make do with what I have.
Hopefully, I'm able to pitch and get back to a no-pain type
feeling. The doctor said I'd be ready around the All-Star break and
I think with him saying that I tried to get back too quick and had
some setbacks. I was rushing. A normal arm would have been back in
that time. But it's taken a little bit longer because of the stuff
that's happened in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Driven by competitiveness and a desire to help the Red Sox as
they make a final push for the playoffs, Saberhagen will likely
return when the rosters expand Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, he expects to make one or two more starts for
Pawtucket, trying to increase his workload each time. Saberhagen
feels his arm has not yet handled a heavy enough load in game
conditions. After Saberhagen started Saturday, his arm felt very
weak, telling him that he was pushing the surgically repaired
shoulder to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most encouraging sign was his ability to get up and down
five times and get 75,'' said Kerrigan. ``That's a big step. He's
always going to have discomfort in there, but (Saturday) night he
had it to the degree where it was a little more than he was used
to. But to his credit, he fought through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-21 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT-OF-TOWN SCORES GOOD NEWS, BAD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ By the time the Red Sox and Rangers took the field
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at the ESPN-appointed hour, Pedro Martinez already
had taken a shaving cream pie in the face from Texas reliever John
Wetteland, his ex-teammate in Montreal, and the scores from around
the American League already had been dropped into their familiar
slots on the ancient left-field scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It took Martinez much less time to wipe off his face than it did
fans to figure out whether to be cheered or concerned by the
outcomes of the games involving the other playoff contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost? Great. That gave the Sox a chance to pull
within two games of the first-place Bombers in the AL East. (Boston
ended up losing, 6-2, and is three games behind New York in the
East and one behind Oakland for the wild card, tied with
Cleveland). The Sox hadn't been this close to the division lead
this late in the season since 1995, when the Sons of Kevin Kennedy
won the division. Last season, the latest the Sox were that close
to the eventual World Series winners was July 5.
</P>
<P>
   But wait: The team that beat the Yanks, the Anaheim Angels,
started the day just three games behind the Sox in the wild-card
race, and on Friday night had rallied from five runs down in the
ninth inning to beat the Bombers, only the second time in Yankees
history they'd blown a lead of that size in the last inning.
</P>
<P>
   The man who did much of Friday's damage? Mo Vaughn. The former
Sox slugger hit a tying three-run home run off Mariano Rivera, who
now has blown more saves (five) than he did all of last season. Mo
makes his first Yawkey Way appearances of the season the next three
nights, and this time he'll be healthy and hungry, meaning there's
little chance he'll duplicate his woeful showing here last year (3
for 20, 8 strikeouts).
</P>
<P>
   The Sox may catch one break against the Halos. Darin Erstad _
who on Friday night made a game-saving catch reminiscent of Yaz's
robbery of Tom Tresh in Billy Rohr's near no-no in '67, then hit a
game-winning home run in the 11th inning _ has a strained left rib
cage and is day to day. Shiggy is healthy, though _ Angels reliever
Shigetoshi Hasegawa hasn't allowed an earned run in his last 23
innings.
</P>
<P>
   So, were the Sox better off with the Yanks losing and Angels
winning? Better to close the gap on the Bombers, even with the
Angels coming here on a roll and Mo bent on payback?
</P>
<P>
   Switch now to Cleveland, where the Indians smoked Seattle, 12-4,
sending the Mariners to their eighth straight loss. Since the
All-Star break, the M's, leaders of the AL West, are two games
under .500 (18-20).
</P>
<P>
   They haven't been alone in their mediocrity. The White Sox, who
still have the best record in the league, are one game over .500
since the break (19-18). The Blue Jays, who were in a virtual tie
with the Yankees for the division lead, are four games under
(16-20). The A's are at .500, while the Angels are minus two
(17-19).
</P>
<P>
   The contender with the best record since the break? The Sons of
Jimy Williams, who after cleaning up on the Devil Rays and Rangers
are 21-15, with the Indians (20-14) just behind. Did you catch the
stat from the Maniacal One in Sunday's newspaper? In their first 97
games, according to statistician Chuck Waseleski, the Sox did not
win a game in which they trailed by two runs; in their last 22
games, they've done it five times.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians started the week by being swept by the A's, and
finished it by clocking the Mariners, who are only the second team
in history to give up nine or more runs in seven straight defeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day we look like the 1995 Indians,'' catcher Sandy Alomar
said. ``The next day we look like the 1991 Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   The '95 Tribe came within one pitch of winning the World Series.
The '91 Tribe set a franchise record for losses with 105.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we have more days left in the season where we're
the '95 Indians,'' Alomar said.
</P>
<P>
   Better for the Red Sox that the Indians lose and the M's win?
Probably, although the M's are just two games ahead of the A's in
the AL West and could wind up competing against Boston in the
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Sox, the Indians will play 32 games in 31 days
beginning Sept. 1. There will be eight head-to-head meetings
between the teams in 10 days, with back-to-back doubleheaders Sept.
20 and 21.
</P>
<P>
   There probably will be only one survivor. Or they could kill
each other off, allowing a team such as the A's to slip in.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday it was A's 5, Tigers 4, putting Oakland a half-game ahead
of the Sox in the wild-card hunt, although the Sox' loss later on
made it one game again. One minute the A's are running off six wins
in a row. The next, they're dropping six straight.
</P>
<P>
   Their top slugger, Jason Giambi, has an impinged left shoulder,
and gritty veteran Randy Velarde has a strained neck. But the A's
kids have gotten a big lift from Mike Stanley _ you may remember
the name _ who is hitting .359 in his 13 games for the A's since
Dan Duquette cut him loose.
</P>
<P>
   So, an A's loss would have been far preferable . . . except a
Tigers win would have drawn them to .500 and some possible Motown
madness. The Tigers were just five games back in the wild-card
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Confused yet? It won't get any easier in the season's final six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we just have to focus on winning our own games,''
Rico Brogna said. ``There's just so many wild-card teams. Win your
own games, and try to win the division.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
