<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7622 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     08-21 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: GARCIAPARRA'S IN A SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He struck out with the bases loaded and no outs in the
first inning. He struck out with two on and two outs in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very un-Nomarlike night, but it was consistent with
what has been the first slump of a remarkably steady season for
Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, in fact, show this to be the most prolonged slump
Garciaparra has had since May 1997, his rookie season. He flared a
single in the eighth inning and came around to score on a passed
ball for the Sox' second run in their 6-2 loss Sunday night to the
Texas Rangers, but his 1-for-3 performance left him batting just
.222 (10 for 45) in his last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time he's struggled all year,'' said Scott
Hatteberg, the Red Sox catcher and close friend of Garciaparra.
``We're spoiled. He's hit over .300 in 15 straight months. That's
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra hit .388 in July. He's at .279 (19 for 68) in 18
games this month. He has 49 multihit games this season, a total
exceeded only by Angels outfielder Darin Erstad (who is bidding to
set an all-time hits record), but he's had two hits in a game only
twice since hitting a home run and double against the Royals here
Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   All season, he has been hitting over .400 in Fenway Park, but
he's batting just .190 (4 for 21) on this homestand. His two-K game
Sunday night was his first since July 25, and after whiffing just
four times in his previous 16 games, Garciaparra has gone down on
strikes six times in seven games. That's a startling number for a
guy who has fanned just 39 times in 388 at-bats this season and
ranks fourth in the league in the toughest-to-whiff category.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Pedro Martinez said he told Garciaparra he looked
tired when the team was in Anaheim during its ludicrous five-city,
16-game trip. Manager Jimy Williams intended to give Garciaparra a
night off Thursday, but inserted the shortstop as a pinch hitter in
the seventh inning. He popped out with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't play tired,'' Williams said Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. ``He made
a couple of plays the other night that showed me he has as much
life in his legs as he has had all year.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing his postgame meal, Garciaparra made a call on
his cellphone as he quickly dressed, then left the clubhouse, the
phone to his ear. This would not be a night for fielding questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this game is very, very mental,'' Hatteberg said.
``He's been in a groove for so long and has been so confident, that
when things don't click and don't stay that way, you get that
slight panic, not that he's panicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers like Texas lefty Doug Davis, who allowed 10 hits and
seven runs in just 2 2/3 innings last Tuesday against the Yankees,
don't normally handle Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't usually see guys like that get Nomar out,''
Hatteberg said. ``But people struggle, even the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a guy as consistent as Nomar has been this
year. He's been as good this year as I've ever seen him. I know
hitting, and you get spoiled watching a guy like that who makes it
look so easy. But it's not that easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FOSTER-PROFILE-2ndTAK     08-21 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTER-PROFILE-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: date students. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She pushed her point of view in 1987 as a delegate to the state
GOP convention in Anaheim, introducing a resolution to
disenfranchise the Log Cabin Club.
</P>
<P>
   Foster said she was returning to the conference hall when
security guards surrounded her, followed by Anaheim police, who
took her to jail.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal trespassing charges were dropped, and there was a
confidential settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make up for what happened to me, but it was
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a typing and shorthand teacher, made her reputation at
LAUSD as a whistleblower, a promoter of student causes, and a thorn
in administrators' sides. Mostly, she said, they ignored her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember her, oh yeah,'' said former Los Angeles Unified
School District Superintendent Sidney Thompson, who supervised
Foster in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ezola took a position, it was strong. From my position, I
didn't see any leeway for us to adjust to.''
</P>
<P>
   As a new teacher at Jordan High in the early 1960s, Foster said
she was outraged at how federal funds for minority children were
being spent. She went to the U.S. Department of Education, and some
of her claims were vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's work record shows she moved to three high schools, as
well as substituted. She said the district engaged in a vendetta
against her.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, Foster, while teaching at Bell High School,
appeared on a national talk show with school board member David
Tokofsky and talked in strong terms about how the schools were
overcrowded with children illegally in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, she said fliers showed up in teachers' mailboxes
accusing her of being a liar, racist and worse, she said. Students
cried, teachers took sides and fights broke out. For her own
protection, she was locked inside a classroom and neither the
district nor union came to her defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I was escorted out by school police. There was no way
I would go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tokofsky, who followed Foster's activities after their TV
meeting, said: ``It's amazing Buchanan didn't look underneath the
hood, and that he took the skin-deep assessment of her
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of five children raised by a single mom in Houston,
Texas, Foster spent summers at her grandparents' farm near the
village of Maurice, La., where she helped with the cotton crop.
</P>
<P>
   She attended mostly African-American schools but said she never
felt the sting of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she and Buchanan infuriate many by saying states should
be able to fly the Confederate flag over their capitols, a symbol
many say trivializes the horrors of Southern slavery.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas Southern University in the '60s, Foster said she joined
one sit-in at a Houston drugstore but was pulled away at the last
minute by friends who said her mother lacked the means to bail her
out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I felt like most of the others, that I was doing
something good for our race,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Foster had been making the talk show circuits for a while when
Buchanan invited her to speak at a Washington, D.C., event which
led to her being named his national co-chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Days before the announcement she would be Buchanan's running
mate, his sister, Angela M. ``Bay'' Buchanan, who had run for state
treasurer in California in 1990, got Foster to sever her ties with
the John Birch Society, her organization Americans for Family
Values, and a Chatsworth-based bookstore, Trim Tax.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had only ``proud and happy'' memories of the John
Birch Society, a hard-core anti-Communist group.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Aug. 9 - her birthday - Foster; her husband,
Chuck; and the Buchanans went to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat turned to me, almost like a marriage proposal,'' Foster
said. ``He said, `Would you be willing to be my running mate for
the Reform Party?' I said yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
