<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY'S DAY BITTERSWEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ There was that head-to-head win against Colin
Montgomerie in the British Masters last summer and a final-pairing
in the fourth round of the FedEx St. Jude Classic in June, but this
was unlike anything Bob May ever had experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to Tiger and said, `Is this what you get every week?'
And he said, `You got it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He just had stepped out of the fiercest major championship golf
drama in years, yet May wore a smile. He hadn't won, but he had
taken the world's greatest player to the limit. And then even
farther, into a three-hole playoff that May lost despite going
par-par-par.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he hadn't chopped it up. They were scrambling
pars and he didn't give himself good chances to answer Woods's
birdie on the first playoff hole, but they were indicative of the
spirit he had brought to the competition. He knows he may have been
the only one to give himself a chance, he said, but that was
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say he is the best golfer ever to play,'' said May,
``because it wouldn't be fair to a lot of the other players that
have played before him. But he may be, when he is done, the best
player. And I went head-to-head with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the old days.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost like the old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Southern California I was before him, and in some newspaper
articles, (Woods) would say, `I am going to beat Bob May's record.'
Which he pretty much proceeded to do,'' said May, who was an
accomplished junior player and later a collegiate star at Oklahoma
State.
</P>
<P>
   They played in the same junior tournaments, though May was 9
years older and Woods ``was still playing nine holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Their routes went in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   May went on to college stardom, PGA Tour failure, European Tour
success, and graduation through a grueling qualifying school test
back in America.
</P>
<P>
   Woods went to another planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always kept track of him,'' said May, though he wasn't
quite ready for what he saw on the first tee _ a drive that
seemingly wasn't ever going to come down. ``When he hit that tee
ball, over those trees left, I knew it was going to be a different
day today.''
</P>
<P>
   May is not the guy who was supposed to bring down _ or come
close to bringing down _ Woods. That had been a position reserved
for David Duval or Phil Mickelson or Ernie Els. But when he birdied
the par-5 second hole to jump into the lead, people really started
to take note of this guy who had shot a pair of 66s to back up an
opening 72.
</P>
<P>
   He received financial backing from Joe Pesci and Rick Dees
earlier in his career, but ``I haven't talked to Joe in quite a
while,'' said May, who has struggled most of 2000. There was that
tie for second at the FedEx and a tie for 11th at the British Open
last month, but none of his other 16 starts has resulted in any
other Top 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Wild, then, that he would be hearing cheers from thousands of
fans in his quest to stop Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great player and he has a tendency to run away with
things,'' said May, ``and maybe they saw that and said, `Hey, maybe
we are going to have a match on our hands today.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Which they did, highlighted by a riveting back-side bout that
featured a pair of 5-under-par 31s. Only a burp at the par-4 15th
made May shake his head, the lone bad taste in his mouth. He had a
one-shot lead and seemed destined to make it at least two, but he
missed a 5-foot putt for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it, I thought, `Oh, this is going to be a good
putt,' '' said May. ``But it just hung out there left. So that was
kind of surprising to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as surprising as the battle he gave Woods, whose third
straight major championship had been expected to be a breeze
against an unheralded player such as May.
</P>
<P>
   Even the player acknowledged that reality. ``Tiger plays a
different game than we play, but I wanted to go out and play a
good, solid round,'' said May.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked how it felt to shoot 66 three straight days and not
win. May shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are playing against the best player in the world, and he
proved that that is not good enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
