<SLUG> BC-RUN-FALMOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYANS DOMINATE FALMOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALMOUTH, Mass. _ How many Kenyans does it take to dominate one
of the top road races in the world?
</P>
<P>
   Try a slightly stretched baker's dozen _ 14 _ who made Sunday's
28th Falmouth Road Race a virtually all-African affair. The lead
pack,including 14 Kenyans among the 17 runners, took off from Woods
Hole at a sub-4 1/2-minute-per-mile pace, and as it reached the
1-mile mark around Nobska Lighthouse, the elite speedsters had run
away from the 9,000 plodders behind them. For a while they were on
pace to set a course record, but the winner finished seven seconds
off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly the entire 7.1-mile run over seaside bluffs and along
shimmering beaches, even into the last mile, the lead shifted among
five runners. But approaching the last hill at Falmouth Heights,
24-year-old Mark Yatich from Kenya reached down for an extra kick
and pulled away from Joseph Kimani, one of the favorites who has
dominated international road running over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Yatich finished in 31:43, a 4:28 pace, just three seconds ahead
of Kimani, who set the course record in 1996 (31:36). Third in
31:47 was a US runner, Khalid Khannouchi, a 28-year-old Moroccan
who became a naturalized citizen this year. He holds the world
record in the marathon (2:05:42).
</P>
<P>
   At half a mile out, Khannouchi attempted to grab the lead, and
for a time broke out of the pack. But the rest were not far behind,
and as Khannouchi struggled, Kimani kicked past him. With 200 yards
to the finish, Yatich put on his final burst and passed both.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side there was little contest. Falmouth newcomer,
Lornah Kiplagat, 26, beat out fellow Kenyan Catherine Ndereba,
winner of this year's Boston Marathon and former course
record-holder here. Named the top road runner in the world by
Runner's World, Ndereba was trying to win her fourth Falmouth.
</P>
<P>
   But Kiplagat took off at a tremendous pace (she ran 4:56-minute
miles) and slowed down only once on her way to setting a course
record of 35:02. Looking back throughout the race, she never did
spot Ndereba and won by 55 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In third place at 35:58 was another Kenyan, Helen
Kimaiyo-Kipkoskei, who finished just a second behind Ndereba.
</P>
<P>
   Yatich said he had not expected to win, and so ran full out
without trying to strategize. But he felt ``very strong'' as the
course dropped out of the hilly section and hit the flats along the
south-side beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Up the steep hill at Falmouth Heights, Yatich said the speed
work he had done helped him kick into the lead. ``At about 200
meters, I knew I was ready,'' he said. ``There was no need to go
faster before. I was very happy, because for me this is a really
fast time.''
</P>
<P>
   New to Falmouth and just four years into road racing, Yatich
kicked his way into world contention when in 1998 his best-known
performance was a photo-finish loss to the No. 1-ranked runner,
Joseph Korir, at the Bix 7-miler.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplagat has a similar profile. New to Falmouth, and younger
than the top performers, she is the hottest runner on the 10-K
world circuit and has dominated races in Europe, notching five wins
and finishing in the top three seven straight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not expecting to win this race,'' said the two-time
winner of the Los Angeles Marathon. ``But I started fast, and ran
the first 500 meters with the men. The first mile was not easy, but
then I started to get strong on the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiplagat said her technique is to run up hills slowly, to
conserve energy, then kick hard downhill to take advantage of
gravity. ``It was not so easy on the flats, though,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Kiplagat looked back down the course, surprised
not to see Ndereba. ``I was able to control my race,'' she said.
``It's no good running too fast if there's nobody coming close to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason no one was close, she was to find out at the finish,
was that Kiplagat was on a course-record pace.
</P>
<P>
   Run in perfect weather, the race dripped with nostalgia. Johnny
Kelley rode in front as course marshal, and some of the old-timers
who made the race famous were back again.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rodgers, who shares credit for making Falmouth a
world-class event in the 1970s and is widely credited with
popularizing the sport of road running, won the senior division,
beating ancient rival Frank Shorter, whom he has beaten in four of
six Falmouths dating to 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Rodgers, winner of four Boston and four New York
marathons, finished 51st overall with a time of 38.14.
</P>
<P>
   His rival was Milford's Larry Olsen, who led Rodgers at one
point by about 10 yards, only to fall behind by 16 seconds by the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still run to win,'' said Rodgers, who has dropped from 130
to 70 miles of training per week since his halcyon days of the
'70s. Looking out at throngs of admirers along the beach, Rodgers
said he was pleased to see so much intensity still involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he added, ``I was really happy I caught Olsen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
