<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FALMOUTH-BLANCHETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINISHING FIRST SECONDARY TO BLANCHETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALMOUTH, Mass. _ Long before he crossed the finish line as the
men's wheelchair winner in the 28th edition of the Falmouth Road
Race Sunday, Craig Blanchette was already a winner in the sparkling
eyes of 14-year-old Shawn Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship began four years ago when Blanchette, a
world-class wheelchair marathoner, was hosted by the Nelson family
for the first time at the race, a tradition that has continued each
year.
</P>
<P>
   For Shawn's mother, Patty, a member of the town's disabilities
commission, the invitation has special meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Her son has been battling a congenital and rare bone disorder
called ostegenesis imperfecta that has caused more than 80 bone
fractures and resulted in 14 surgeries in which rods were inserted
into Shawn's legs to strengthen his bones.
</P>
<P>
   A freshman at Falmouth High, Shawn uses a wheelchair and a
walker, but, said his mother, ``His attitude has been positive. He
never complained at all or felt sorry for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   For Blanchette, an eight-time world champion and a bronze medal
winner at the Seoul Paralympics in 1988, the $1,000 he pocketed for
winning Sunday had far less meaning than his bond with the Nelson
family, which also includes Patty's husband, David, and their two
other children, Michaela, 6, and Kendall, 3.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old resident of Olympia, Wash., tried a new sport
this year, competing in a three-wheel, hand-powered cycle that he
has encouraged the Nelsons to look into for Shawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been coming to Falmouth for a number of years, nine or
10, and I had been put up with other host families in the past,''
said Blanchette, who has competed in five Boston Marathons,
finishing as high as second. ``But sometimes I had to be put up in
a hotel. Then I was matched up with Shawn and his family and I
discovered we had a lot in common. Last year, my wife, Anita, came
out here and we stayed with the Nelsons for six days.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanchette has talked to Shawn about the importance of good
nutrition to make his bones stronger, and he helped fine-tune the
youngster's wheelchair last year. They've also taken day trips
together, and they e-mail each other to stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn really looks forward to seeing Craig every year,'' said
Patty Nelson. ``He'd really like to get out there and try racing
and he sees Craig do so much. It's been a really positive influence
for him. And I'm not the kind of parent who wants to overprotect
him and not have him try things. I want him to do as much as he
possibly can and form new friendships and Craig has been a role
model for Shawn in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn, who would like to get on the Falmouth course next year,
was at the finish line Sunday to greet Blanchette and the pair
shared some quiet postrace time together inside the VIP tent.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who derives great joy in riding his wheelchair around
the block near his home in East Falmouth and also enjoys swimming,
playing basketball with a friend, and working on his computer,
describes his relationship with Blanchette as ``cool . . . and
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanchette said he also has talked to Shawn about ``enjoying
life and not spending a lot of time worrying about whether he'll be
a great racer someday. I know he enjoys being around it, though,
and I think hand cycling would be something he could try and a good
avenue for him. It's not as technical as wheelchair racing and he
can pretty much sit at the handlebars and let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Patty Nelson, who worked Sunday at the finish line collecting
computer time chips from the athletes, has extended her involvement
with the local disabled community beyond her home.
</P>
<P>
   As a commission member, she said, ``We've tried to make Falmouth
more accessible. We purchased beach chairs so people in wheelchairs
can get to the beach, and right now I'm working on getting a
playground put in for kids who have disabilities at the Teaticket
Elementary School.''
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, she also is hoping that a new medication,
taken through injection every two weeks, and which has been
successful with some OI patients, will help her son, and others.
The friendship and support of a champion wheelchair racer, however,
has provided a tonic that never will lose its potency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fun day,'' said Shawn, with the afternoon sun
glistening off the ocean matching the bright smile on his face. ``I
look forward to it all year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
