<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ARMSTRONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG MAKES SOLID DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Early in the first half Bruce Armstrong came
out of a huddle and took his stance, as he has for 196
regular-season games and countless exhibition contests for the New
England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   All was right in the veteran tackle's football life again.
Finally.
</P>
<P>
   The world of professional football is as tumultuous as it is
violent.
</P>
<P>
   An injury can end a season and so can a fat contract, and the
former University of Louisville All-American had both.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Armstrong was hobbling, wondering if the damaged
anterior cruciate ligament in his knee would hold up. He was
comforted by a $3-million-plus contract and the feeling that he was
a fixture in Patriot Nation _ a 13-year veteran, a six-time
All-Pro, a selection on the Patriots' all-time team. In short, he
felt he was the heart of the team.
</P>
<P>
   While he was able to start all 16 games for the Patriots last
season with the unsturdy knee, he was given the boot when the
season ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' brass figured they needed salary cap room and gave
him an ultimatum: Play for less or take a walk. Armstrong balked.
He had his knee repaired and hoped for a better offer. It never
came.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he accepted a low-ball figure from the Patriots on the
eve of training camp. He returned to the fold so late that his
biographical data in the team media guide was deleted and now has
to be inserted.
</P>
<P>
   All that is history. He is back where he belongs, on the
Patriots' front line. He now can concentrate on football.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the lineup Sunday during the Patriots' 31-21 loss
to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, their first game at Foxboro Stadium
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was warmly received as he left the field. His presence
was welcomed, certainly by the person who will benefit the most,
quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reassuring to have someone like Bruce protecting your
backside out there on the field,'' said New England's franchise
quarterback, who wasn't sacked in the first half, which was when
Armstrong got his playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's knee held up well during his first appearance this
exhibition season. ``It felt pretty good,'' he said. ``It certainly
was a lot better than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between playing with a tore ACL and a repaired
one is confidence. He didn't mind the pain last year. ``Pain is
relative,'' said Armstrong. ``It hurts, but it isn't noticeable, if
that's the right word, when you are out there on the field. What
makes a difference is the stability. You know your knee joint is
going to be stable.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense in the opening half gave the Patriots a 14-10 lead.
New England rushed for 104 yards and the Patriots' lone offensive
touchdown game on a 58-yard run by Kevin Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong likes the new offensive system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that we will stick with,'' he said. ``The more
you stay with it, the more of an opportunity you have to hit the
home run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
