<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-PATRIOTS-MILLEN-B     08-21 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PATRIOTS-MILLEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLEN EARNS HIS STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Matt Millen received a strong endorsement
after working as an umpire in the officiating crew during the
Patriots-Tampa Bay exhibition game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your reactions were good,'' supervisor of officials Jerry
Seeman told the Fox television analyst and former NFL player.
``Anybody who watched the game wouldn't know you weren't an NFL
umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with his biceps bulging from his striped sleeves,
Millen looked more like an ex-NFL player in an NFL umpire's
uniform. But Millen was not doing a farcical impersonation. He took
the apprenticeship seriously, and his positioning and instincts
were more than acceptable during his third-quarter stint
substituting for Ron Botchan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to (former supervisor of officials) Red Cashion
and he told me that if you're not going to have fun, don't do it,''
Millen said. ``I enjoyed it. I can't play anymore, and it's the
next best thing. You do the same reads, you are aware of the same
things. It's third down, and you run through your head what you are
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Full-time officiating is not likely in Millen's future. But this
was not a lark. Millen spent weeks preparing and relished the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   After a 12-year NFL playing career with the Raiders, 49ers, and
Redskins, Millen is hardly a vicarious wannabe. ``I could easily do
this,'' he said. ``All of a sudden you are back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ex-players might not be lining up for what is considered a
thankless task, one in which anonymity signifies competence, and
flair and individuality are suppressed, at best.
</P>
<P>
   But Millen recommends the experience. ``If guys are willing to
do it, especially the interior guys,'' he said, ``part of the whole
thing is a comfort level and not being intimidated in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started reverting back to when I was playing, and getting
right in there. The guys said, `Ref, give me some room.' I told
them not to worry about me. Then I thought, wait a minute, I've got
to give these guys some room.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen has the type of personality that could revolutionize the
official's role, and he is not likely to stifle it. It is the type
of personality more suited to announcing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised by TV's effect on how things are called,''
Millen said. ``It doesn't influence the call, but it's considered _
where the ball is when (the foul) happened. If there was a hold and
the ball is on the other side of the field, or if they held but did
not impede progress, you let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen's instincts worked against him when Adam Vinatieri lined
up a 50-yard field goal attempt late in the third quarter. ``I
said, `He can't make that field goal,' and so I went to the other
side for a punt,'' Millen said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Vinatieri stayed on the field and went for the field
goal, his try bouncing into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Millen's reaction: ``I told you he couldn't make that field
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen seemed prepared for nearly everything _ except a pregame
surprise. ``I woke up at 10 minutes to 6 and went and worked out on
the treadmill and lifted some weights,'' Millen said. ``I came back
to my hotel room, and who do you think was waiting there? Random
drug test.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
