<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BISHOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP MOSTLY IN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Michael Bishop got to play the entire second
half of Sunday's Patriots-Buccaneers game, seven series, and his
effort was up and down in the 31-21 New England loss.
</P>
<P>
   In connecting on seven of 17 passes for 157 yards, Bishop, eager
to be quarterback Drew Bledsoe's backup, threw a 32-yard touchdown
pass to rookie wide receiver Shockmain Davis in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an opportunity to throw Shockmain the ball downfield and
he did his job, he made the catch, he got into the end zone,'' said
Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was also sacked four times for 37 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved the ball, making some good throws, trying to get the
win,'' he said. ``We lost, though. There were ups and downs and I
can't have them keep me from my performance. I can't have them let
me down from doing my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did come out and want to get the win. We're a lot better
team than what we've shown,'' said Bishop of the Patriots, who are
2-2 in the exhibition season, with Carolina on tap Thursday. ``If
we can get everybody on the same page, we can be a good team. If
everything goes right, there's no saying how far we can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's only play of the first half, a Hail Mary pass intended
for wide receiver Chris Calloway, was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty far from the end zone,'' Bishop said. ``I guess
(offensive coordinator) Charlie Weiss wanted to get the ball down
to the end zone, so I went in and I tried to do my job, even though
I was surprised to come in there.''
</P>
<P>
   There were several dropped passes by his receivers. And in the
third quarter, when Bishop tried to throw a screen pass, the ball
slipped from his hand and Jamie Duncan recovered in the end zone to
give Tampa Bay a 17-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw J.R. Redmond in the flat on the right on the screen the
other way and once my hand got started, I lost my grip on the
ball,'' Bishop said. ``I couldn't argue with the referee's call,
but I felt I was going forward on the pass. I really should have
jumped on the ball, but I didn't hear the whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was only a so-so outing for Bishop, and it might have been
the last time the former Heisman Trophy candidate plays in the
exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, known for his ability to scramble when he can't find an
opener receiver, felt he did nothing to hurt his chances, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had confidence when I was throwing short, deep, over the
middle of the field,'' he said. ``It's just a matter of me getting
the ball to the receivers in time and the receivers looking the
ball in all the way and making the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop never gets down on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the ability to play the game,'' he said. ``If I ever
get down on myself, I feel I'm taking something from myself and my
ability goes to waste.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
