<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-     08-21 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSON, OFFENSE MUST GET MOVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe hasn't been turned into
roadkill yet, and certainly that's something the Patriots' offense
can take pride in.
</P>
<P>
   But if this team is to prove its playoff designs aren't
delusions, the offense is going to have to do something a little
more ambitious at some juncture than merely prolong the
quarterback's survival. And so far, though the Patriots rather
sheepishly maintain that they're making progress when in possession
of the ball, it must be impossible to detect with the naked eye,
because both Bledsoe and new coach Bill Belichick pleaded ignorance
Sunday until they could get a gander of the game films.
</P>
<P>
   It must be delayed gratification, for in the immediate aftermath
of the 31-21 exhibition loss to the Buccaneers at Foxboro Stadium,
the only emphatic assessment of offensive coordinator Charlie
Weis's reconstructed attack was a doleful summary from wide
receiver Terry Glenn, who was involved to the tune of one catch for
4 yards during the half that the regulars played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not clicking right now,'' said Glenn. ``We're not
in synch. We're not taking what Charlie has given us and put it all
together. We better get our act together soon or there ain't going
to be no time. I don't know what it's going to take, but we better
get our act together quick or it's going to be a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   The deadline, specifically, is two weeks, when the Patriots and
Bucs open the regular season here. And while Bledsoe insisted,
``I'm looking forward to playing them for real,'' witnesses to
Sunday's debacle couldn't fathom why.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was because the Patriots won the varsity game, 14-10,
before the scrubs took over in the second half. Then again, the
defense produced half that total on Ty Law's 20-yard fumble return
for a touchdown in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it was because the Patriots regulars didn't once turn
the ball over in the red zone. Then again, the Patriots regulars
didn't once snap the ball in the red zone. The lone offensive TD
came on Kevin Faulk's 58-yard burst up the middle on a routine play
that turned into a glorious fluke. Even Belichick conceded, ``Some
plays went for touchdowns that weren't the way anyone would design
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe completed 10 of 18 passes for a modest 77 yards _ 24 of
them to Tony Simmons on the second play from scrimmage, with no
gain longer than 14 yards thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Save for Faulk's TD, the offense's deepest penetration was on
its first possession, which advanced to the Tampa 31 but yielded
only a 49-yard field goal miss by Adam Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   There also were five abominably timed penalties for 45 yards and
a fumble at midfield that killed New England's second possession
and last semblance of a sustained drive.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Bledsoe could allude only vaguely to signs of quality
but was left with this epitaph:
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some good things today. We moved the ball well and
converted a few third downs (two of six) here and there. We had the
one big play with Kevin and we did do some good things. But if we
continue to commit turnovers and penalties, we're not going to
score against anybody. The bottom line is, if we make mistakes,
there's no way we're going to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake about this: The Patriots don't need game
films to realize that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0247EDT &QL; 
