<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-21 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUNNING RACE, FAULK SHOULD BE WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If the criterion is what you do on the
football field and not what somebody hopes you'll do, the Patriots'
running back competition has been decided for now.
</P>
<P>
   With four days to go before the final exhibition game and 13
days to go before the regular-season opener against the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers, it is clear who has earned the starting job. The ball
should be handed to Kevin Faulk, the little running back from
Louisiana State whose presence you at least notice when he's in the
backfield.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean rookie J.R. Redmond might not deserve the job
before the year is out, and it doesn't mean shopworn Raymont Harris
has no place here. It just means Faulk has done more with his
opportunities than anyone else. Is that not what should decide who
plays and who stays?
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do, by the way, with his 58-yard touchdown
run in the first half of Sunday's 31-21 loss to the Buccaneers at
Foxboro Stadium, because that was simply a matter of a perfect
block and a back hitting the hole full bore, as he should.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it was Faulk who did it and not one of the other
backs may be in part attributable to his quickness or it may not,
but it alone is not a reason to give him the ball on Sept. 3. One
would think any back worthy of an NFL uniform could have run
through that massive hole for long yards.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is simply to say that, among Patriots running backs,
Faulk has done the most in the four exhibition games played so far,
both as a runner and a receiver. That doesn't make him Curtis
Martin, but it makes him the best and most productive back they
have at the moment. And I really don't want to hear any noise about
how well somebody else has looked in practice or about Faulk's
vulnerabilities if he plays too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can be an every-down back,'' Faulk said. ``I just
have to prove it to the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   He still may not have won the job, but what can he do? You get
paid to play on game day, and thus far this summer it has been
Faulk who has done the best playing. Admittedly, Redmond hasn't had
as much of a chance, because of a nagging inflamed tendon in his
groin that led to minor surgery in April and kept him out of
practice until two weeks ago and out of a game until Sunday. But
staying on the field is part of the skill of playing in the NFL,
and thus far the rookie has not been able to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, he should sit behind Faulk unless he shows
something Thursday night against the Carolina Panthers that hasn't
been seen in these parts since Martin's departure, because Sunday's
eight carries for 7 yards didn't do anything to take the limelight
from Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   As for Harris, he looked good in the exhibition opener against
the 49ers, but that performance was tempered by the fact San
Francisco is godawful on defense and had seven starters out to
boot. He rushed for 58 yards on nine carries that night, but since
then has gained only 30 yards on 18 carries, an average of less
than 2 yards per rush.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, he has not hit the holes with anywhere near the quickness
or enthusiasm he did that first night. After he sat out more than a
year with a broken leg, slow progress might be expected from
Harris, but he should not be rewarded with a starting job simply
because he once rushed for 1,000 yards years ago in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And Redmond certainly didn't show anything Sunday to justify him
being handed the ball ahead of Faulk, who is averaging 7 yards a
carry (22 carries, 156 yards) and also has had nine receptions for
another 80 yards. Even coach Bill Belichick, who said when he
arrived that Faulk seemed best suited for third-down duty, had to
concede that based on production only one guy has earned a Sept. 3
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's had good production in all the preseason games,''
Belichick said. ``He's shown an ability to make some yards on his
own. The question is, will he continue to do that as an every-down
player? The question is, how effective will he be if he carries as
a regular back?''
</P>
<P>
   Not at the moment it's not the question. At the moment the
question is, how effective has anyone else been in any situation?
The answer to that answers any questions Belichick might have about
Faulk's ability to hold up under the strain of full-time service.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he'll still deserve the job a month from now is anyone's
guess. Whether he is the long-term answer is an even greater
unknown. But what is clear is that, at the moment, Kevin Faulk is
New England's best running back.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, he's earned one thing from Bill Belichick
if the coach does what his old mentor, Bill Parcells, always said
he did _ that is, go by what you see.
</P>
<P>
   He's earned the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
