<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIE-IN-SKY-CONCORDE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCORDE: INCREDIBLY BEAUTIFUL, INCREDIBLY ILL-CONCEIVED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Was there ever an airplane so beautiful to look at? No wonder
the fate of Concorde, now indefinitely withdrawn from service by
British Airways as well as Air France, inspires a twinge of regret
even in the sternest critic of this ludicrous airborne indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   Few critics have been sterner than The Economist which, in the
late 1960s, conducted a campaign against the use of taxpayers'
money on a project that would never recoup its capital costs.
</P>
<P>
   Concorde's commercial life is clearly drawing to a close: even
if flights eventually resume, it will be difficult to rebuild lost
confidence among passengers.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of saying, ``We told you so,'' it is worth examining
the lessons to be gleaned from the airplane's history.
</P>
<P>
   Concorde was an engineer's delight: it took the jet-bomber
technologies that had evolved at the end of the Second World War
and pushed them to the frontiers of the possible, or indeed beyond
the frontiers, given that the aircraft's initial prototype could
not have crossed the Atlantic with a full passenger load.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology turned out to be a blind alley. Glamorous
though supersonic travel seemed to be, it was also so noisy that
most governments banned it over their countries.
</P>
<P>
   At subsonic speeds, the aircraft guzzles fuel. And Concorde's
limited range means that it cannot fly supersonically across the
world's largest body of water, the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the elderly aircraft's technical limits could now be
overcome. Indeed, governments and aerospace companies have
periodically flirted with building a son-of-Concorde, which could
cross the Pacific and carry three times as many passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But a sign of Concorde's commercial failure is that its design
has not been refined and replaced. One reason is that some design
limits are insuperable. A bigger airplane would make a bigger boom;
and more Concordes would do more environmental harm to the ozone
layer.
</P>
<P>
   However, a greater problem than the technology is the market.
Concorde was built in the days when air travel was for the elite.
In fact, it could never have covered its operating costs merely
from chief executives prepared to scrunch into its small body and
pay $5,000 or so to save four hours getting to New York, London or
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   It has become profitable only by dint of clever marketing,
especially by BA, of supersonic travel to tourists such as those
killed in last month's crash.
</P>
<P>
   For air travel has taken off in a quite different direction from
the one that Concorde's engineers and bureaucrat backers expected.
Flying is a mass market, with two-thirds of passengers travelling
for fun, not for business.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, building for the market, understood that capacity
mattered more than speed: its hugely successful 767s fly more
slowly than did the 707 (which in turn flew more slowly than the
VC10).
</P>
<P>
   While Concorde sped off on a flight path to nowhere, the true
advance in air travel has turned out to come from refinements of
large jets, which have grown steadily cheaper and more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   If commercial supersonic travel has a future, it is more likely
to be in the executive jet than the commercial carrier. A smaller
Concorde would make a smaller boom, and enough seriously rich folk
might want something even grander than their own Gulfstream V to
justify the immense cost.
</P>
<P>
   For the great majority of business travellers, however, there
are far better ways to speed up the irksome business of air travel.
One is to invest in ground transport: time can be saved by
unclogging (or leapfrogging) the roads between airports and city
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to improve the management of flights. It is far
easier to end delays caused by air-traffic control than to quiet a
sonic boom.
</P>
<P>
   A third is to dismantle the hub-and-spoke system of routes
which, especially in the United States, compounds travel delays by
forcing passengers to take two or three flights to reach their
destination, any one of which may ruin their journey by running
late.
</P>
<P>
   The technology that will do most to speed up air travel in the
next couple of decades is on the ground, in computers and not in
the sky, however lovely the bodywork. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
