<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLESSED-SILENCE-SC-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHHH!': RETREAT FROM LIFE'S MADNESS TO A MONASTERY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: South Carolina)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 625-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MONCKS CORNER, S.C. _ Visitors who drive over the Wadboo Bridge,
30 miles from downtown Charleston, S.C., soon come upon a majestic
alley of ancient live oaks, the entrance to the monastery of Our
Lady of Mepkin.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight Trappist monks live at Mepkin Abbey, following the
simple Cistercian routine of prayer, scripture-reading and manual
labor that was laid down 900 years ago in France.
</P>
<P>
   To this serene abbey comes an increasing stream of visitors, men
and women of all faiths exhausted by the punishing pace of life and
work in 21st-century America.
</P>
<P>
   These ``retreatants'' usually stay in the abbey between one and
six days. They pray with the monks (attending the first service of
the day, at 3:20 in the morning, if they wish), observe the same
silence as the monks, eat the same vegetarian fare.
</P>
<P>
   The abbey's guest facilities, most with private baths, are full
much of the time, and rooms for weekends are booked solid for the
next six months. Both single people and married couples can be
accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most come for the silence,'' explains Brother Joshua as he
takes day visitors around the church and the grounds. The monks
hope that their visitors will ``find peace, joy and perspective on
life.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the aim of Henry Luce, publisher of Time, and his wife,
Clare Boothe Luce, playwright, congresswoman and diplomat, when in
1949 they gave the Trappists a large part of the property, which
they had acquired in 1936. The Luces are buried in the abbey
grounds, on a placid green hill overlooking the Cooper River.
</P>
<P>
   Monasteries and spiritual centers throughout the United States
find that demand is booming. Type the words ``spiritual retreat''
into an Internet search engine and it will offer you dozens of Web
sites describing centers for Christians, Jews, Buddhists, Naive
Americans, Hindus, New Agers.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot actually go there, you can at least take a
breather from the hustle and bustle by making a virtual retreat in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Click on Mepkin Abbey's (www.mepkinabbey.org) Web site, and you
can link up to the Web pages of many other Trappist monasteries,
including the Abbey of Gethsemani in Kentucky, Mepkin's parent
community.
</P>
<P>
   Gethsemani's Web site devotes a full article to its most famous
monk, Thomas Merton, author of ``Elected Silence'' and other books.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of the Internet is a mixed blessing for the
monasteries of the 21st century. Mepkin's colorful Web site guides
viewers through the abbey's history, philosophy and services; at
least half of the retreatants book their reservations by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   This is wonderful, in its way. Yet the Internet can clash with
the monks' way of life: instead of retreating from the world, they
can hook up with it by going on-line.
</P>
<P>
   So Father Francis, Mepkin's abbot (trained in the 1970s as a
concert organist at the Juilliard School in New York City), keeps a
tight rein on Internet use; only a handful of monks have access to
it. The rest have an upcoming consolation.
</P>
<P>
   The 11,000-square-foot, two-story Clare Boothe Luce Library in
the abbey grounds, due to open next January, will house up to
80,000 theological volumes (all computer-catalogued for
availability through the Internet).
</P>
<P>
   Another building project, a new ``seniors'' wing for the
monastery's many ageing monks, is scheduled to open later this
summer. Mepkin has five middle-aged men waiting to join (reflecting
a trend in Catholicism in which men are treating the priesthood as
a second career). Some people even think that older men make better
monks than young ones.
</P>
<P>
   The abbot is reconciled to the fact that a life of poverty,
solitude and simplicity does not appeal to many young men today. A
week is one thing, a lifetime another. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
