<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-STOLEN-ABORIGINES-ECO     08-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ABORIGINES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA'S STOLEN GENERATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SYDNEY _ When Lorna Cubillo was seven, she and 15 other
aboriginal children were put into a truck by white officials at an
outback settlement in the Northern Territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the truck left Phillip Creek, everyone was crying and
screaming,'' she says. ``I remember mothers beating their heads
with sticks and rocks. They were bleeding. They threw dirt over
themselves. I remember seeing the mothers chasing the truck. And
then they disappeared in the dust of the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gunner had a similar experience when he was six and living
in an aboriginal camp at Utopia Station, a cattle property near
Alice Springs. ``I didn't see the welfare blokes and they suddenly
grabbed me by the arms and dragged me towards the truck. My mother
was there. She was crying and so were her sisters. I thought the
men were taking me away to be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cubillo is now 62 and Mr. Gunner is 52. They are members of
Australia's ``stolen generation'': aboriginal people, estimated to
number at least 55,000, who were removed from their families as
children and put in foster homes, many run by churches.
</P>
<P>
   At the home where she ended up in Darwin, Cubillo was assaulted
by a missionary; Gunner was sexually assaulted at his Alice Springs
home, also by a missionary.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of their kind, they lost all contact with their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Having lived with the traumas all their lives, Cubillo and
Gunner launched a court action against the Australian government
last year, claiming they were unlawfully abducted and that the
government in Canberra breached its duty of care towards them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Australia's six states pursued similar native-child
separation policies for more than 40 years until the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubillo-Gunner action was seen as a test case over an issue
that has caused soul-searching in Australia since a report in 1997
revealed for the first time the full story of the stolen
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The government, led by the prime minister, John Howard, fought
the case and applied early on to have it thrown out of court.
Maurice O'Loughlin, the federal judge hearing it, refused.
</P>
<P>
   That persistence produced hopes of victory among supporters of
the pair. These were heightened when O'Loughlin took the
unprecedented step of asking that his judgment in Darwin on Aug. 11
be shown live on television.
</P>
<P>
   They were disappointed. O'Loughlin accepted the two aborigines'
accounts of their sufferings as children. But he dismissed their
cases, because he found no evidence that the native patrol officers
who removed them had violated the law at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge void,'' he concluded. ``We know that Mrs.
Cubillo was taken away, but we do not know why.'' This is the nub
of where the campaign is likely to go from here.
</P>
<P>
   The Howard government, keen to avoid liability for compensation
payments, has argued that the stolen children were placed in
welfare institutions for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the government sparked widespread outrage
when it submitted to a parliamentary inquiry that the stolen
generation did not really exist, because the numbers of children
involved were small. O'Loughlin slapped that argument down,
pointedly declaring that neither the evidence nor his judgment
``deny the existence of the stolen generation.''
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that, at least until the 1950s, the separation
policies were driven by racial more than welfare concerns: to
assimilate the mainly mixed-race children who were removed, in the
belief that white Australia would eventually triumph and the
aboriginal race would die out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breeding out the color'' was how some officials at the time
described the policy.
</P>
<P>
   The case has become a key one for modern Australia's moves
towards reconciliation with its indigenous people. The judgment,
with its narrow focus on questions of law, has shown how inadequate
the court system is to resolve this issue, with its complex and
painful historical dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the judge concluded that the infant Gunner was not
removed in 1956 against his mother's wishes: he cited as evidence
her thumbprint on a form of request that the boy be given a
``western education.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard has taken the judgment as justification for his
government's refusal to make a national apology to the stolen
generation. But the issue will not go away, and it could bring the
government under more scrutiny as Australia prepares to host the
Olympic Games next month.
</P>
<P>
   The government spent A$10 million ($5.8 million) fighting the
case _ money, say its critics, that would have been better spent
compensating those who were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Another 1,000 compensation cases are in preparation, and the
Cubillo-Gunner one may go to appeal. ``We've been knocked on the
head so many times,'' says Gunner. ``But they will not destroy our
spirit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0086 </DOCNO>
