<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN23-COX     08-21 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: New grand jury should not charge Clinton
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Bill Clinton is indicted and faces potential prison time
after he leaves the presidency for lying under oath about going too
far with Monica Lewinsky, so be it. As all my arch-fiend criminal
friends say, don't do the crime if you can't do the time. (My
arch-fiend criminal friends are into couplets.)
</P>
<P>
   After all, the president got himself into this fix and there is
no reason why an ex-president should be cut any legal slack the
rest of us wouldn't get.
</P>
<P>
   And that is precisely why Clinton shouldn't be charged. Almost
no one else would be in the same circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the mop-up independent counsel, Robert W. Ray, has
impaneled still another grand jury just to cover his own tail if he
decides not to indict. He has already cleared the president and
First Lady in the travel office firings and the matter of the
prodigal FBI files, which, you will recall, were supposed to be
big-time scandals. Maybe Ray would like to be able to plead that a
grand jury made it clear to him indictment would be futile.
</P>
<P>
   Far more typically, however, prosecutors use grand juries to
rubber-stamp indictments the prosecutor was committed to in the
first place. If that's so here, hope the jury summons the gumption
and independence to cool Ray down.
</P>
<P>
   Indictments for perjury and obstruction are usually filed in
circumstances such as Clinton's only if the falsities were
egregious, caused financial or other harm and justice has not
otherwise been done. None of those apply.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lied only when he was finally trapped by what he knew
was a years-long, richly funded and multi-pronged political drive
to get something, anything, on him, and to maneuver him, when the
Monica thing hit the grapevine, with partisan lawsuits meant to
torpedo his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   No one was out anything because he lied about private sex.
(Indeed, you could even make an argument that a gentleman SHOULD
lie to protect his lover.) Remember that the testimony was
eventually ruled irrelevant anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And has justice not been done? Clinton had to pay $850,000 to
get out of the Paula Jones lawsuit that right-wing foundations
filed and bankrolled to corner him. A federal judge has fined him
$90,000 for contempt of court for ``false, misleading and evasive
answers that were designed to obstruct the judicial process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was impeached at enormous personal cost, his presidency
will permanently be knocked down at least one letter grade and he
faces disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   (Another low blow. Seven of the 14 members of the Arkansas
Supreme Court's Committee on Professional Conduct recused
themselves because of past political ties to the president, leaving
the issue to what amounted to a lynch mob. Even then, the
recommendation to disbar was not unanimous, meaning it is being
pressed by a small fraction of the whole panel.)
</P>
<P>
   Letting Clinton skate wouldn't be a case of a double standard in
justice. Forcing him to trial would be. He doesn't deserve that and
the nation doesn't need it.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
