<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7751 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-U.N.-CARTOONISTS-RE     08-21 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-U.N.-CARTOONISTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDDEN HILARITY OF DIPLOMACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ At the United Nations, where one person's joke
can strike 100 other people from 100 other cultures as
incomprehensible, if not offensive, diplomats, ever cautious and
circumspect, take refuge in the universal language of the political
cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diplomats relish the irony of so many political situations,''
said Kamalesh Sharma, India's ambassador to the United Nations.
``In most diplomatic missions in New York, you'll find that a
particularly appealing cartoon is pinned up so that the delectation
can continue for days and days.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, a panel of diplomats _ Sharma among
them _ and American celebrities will choose the winner of a $10,000
prize for the best political cartoon on a United Nations theme.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months hundreds of entries have poured in from around
the world, from Iran to Ethiopia to Cuba, said Ranan Lurie, the
cartoonist and caricaturist who put up the prize money for the
competition, which is sponsored by the United Nations
Correspondents' Association. Shashi Tharoor, Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's communications director, piloted the project through the
organization, telling skeptical U.N. bureaucrats that it was a new
way to ``propagate the message of the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury assembled by Lurie could lend itself to a cartoon. It
is headed by Elie Wiesel and will include seven ambassadors, from
North America, Europe, Africa and Asia; an actor, Jeff Bridges; an
athlete, David Cone; an author, Norman Mailer; Floyd Abrams, the
First Amendment lawyer; James Hoge, editor of Foreign Affairs, and
William J. Rowe, publisher of Times-Mirror Newspapers in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie, who is best known as a caricaturist, says good political
cartoonists need five things: the training to practice ``pure good
journalism,'' professional artistic standards, the ability to
capture personality through caricature, humor and the gift of
condensing all that into a quick message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the good political cartoon is really the smart bomb of
the media,'' said Lurie, who publishes a magazine, Cartoon News
International, for young people. ``The advantage of the political
cartoon versus the written article is that it will deliver in seven
seconds what an article will not deliver in 17 minutes. Once you've
invested your very important and precious seven seconds you become
wiser. You know what is happening in Chechnya. You know what is
happening in East Timor. Besides, a cartoon is good for you, like
ice cream with vitamins. Better than broccoli.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharma said his all-time favorite cartoon dealt with the botched
attempt to rescue American hostages in Iran during the Carter
administration. In the cartoon, tragedy was touched by the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a helicopter whirring away and this GI is throwing
on the ground dozens and dozens of rabbits,'' Sharma said of the
drawing. ``They're all sitting there on the ground cross-eyed,
wondering what they're doing. And a GI on the ground is yelling
through the noise of the rotor: `I said, a  &UR; rapid &LR;  deployment
force!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows what a complex business any item of global
politics is, so a cartoon humanizes it,'' Sharma said. ``After all
the jargon you read in the paper and positions taken and all the
heat which is generated, in the end it says: Look, human beings are
fractious, but if human beings can laugh, there's hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
