<SLUG> BC-R-SOUNDOFMUSIC-SINGALONG-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO YOU REALLY CALL THAT SOUND MUSIC? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In her 1965 review of ``The Sound of Music'' for The
New York Herald Tribune, Judith Crist wrote, ``The movie is for the
5-to-7 set and their mommies who think their kids aren't up to the
stinging sophistication and biting wit of `Mary Poppins.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as the highest grossing film musical of all time
approaches its 35th anniversary, it is about to begin yet another
life _ this time as official, rather than accidental, kitsch. .
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 6, ``Sing-a-Long Sound of Music,'' the audience
participation version of the movie that has been playing to
delirious crowds at the Prince Charles Cinema in London, will make
its debut in New York at the Ziegfeld Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The basic premise is simple: During such deathless Rodgers and
Hammerstein standards as ``Sixteen Going On Seventeen,'' ``So Long,
Farewell'' and ``Climb Ev'ry Mountain,'' moviegoers sing along to
the lyrics, which appear on the screen as subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Singing along, however, is just one of the evening's many
opportunities for self-expression. In London, when Julie Andrews'
fellow nuns ask, ``How do you solve a problem like Maria?'' the
crowd holds up postcards printed with question marks. When Captain
von Trapp (Christopher Plummer) first kisses Maria, they let loose
a hail of party poppers.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees wear nuns' habits and lederhosen; others dress as
Nazis, the Alps (covered in shaving cream) and as representations
of song lyrics _ like wild geese, with cutouts of the moon mounted
on their wings, as described in ``My Favorite Things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Fink, a spokesman for the Rodgers and Hammerstein
Organization, which controls the copyright on the composers' music
and lyrics, thinks such strenuous glee is, for the English, the
adult equivalent of the breathless outbursts at traditional English
Punch and Judy shows. Example: when Julie Andrews cannot find
material to make play clothes for the von Trapp tykes, the audience
yells, ``The curtains, Maria!''
</P>
<P>
   In July, home-grown performances were mounted in Boston and
Austin, Texas. Charmian Carr, who portrayed the eldest von Trapp
daughter, Liesl, was the guest of honor in Austin. Carr, the author
of ``Forever Liesl: A Memoir of the Sound of Music'' (Viking,
2000), recalled that during one scene in which Plummer tenderly
touched Andrews' nose, a chant of ``Get the booger, captain!''
arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hysterical,'' she said. ``There were 1,300 people and
they were sitting in the aisles. It was sacrilegious, but great
fun. It could just be that there are so many people who really do
love the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more cynical. Crist, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's so popular because the world has come to realize
what a really godawful thing the film is,'' she said. ``In 35 years
it's become even sappier. There's a point where it's so bad that it
becomes funny.''
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Mommie Dearest'' and ``Valley of the Dolls,'' this
camp aspect of ``Sing-a-Long Sound of Music'' has made it a hit
with gay viewers. The production began as an entry in the London
Lesbian and Gay Film Festival; the Austin Gay and Lesbian
International Film Festival co-produced the Texas event to benefit
Project Transitions, a nonprofit group that provides hospice care
and housing for AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought it would be fun,'' said Charlotte Hale, the
executive director of Project Transitions. ``Certainly the gay
community liked it, but a lot of mainstream people were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the show is being dizzily promoted as all-family
entertainment. ``Wave your edelweiss!'' reads a press release.
``Cheer the von Trapp kids! Bark at Rolf (the telegram boy)! Boo
the Nazis! Hiss the baroness!''
</P>
<P>
   Camp aside, the movie also seems to have a powerful emotional
effect on a lot of apparently normal people. Even ushers at the
singalongs have been seen to choke up during the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the countless renderings of ``Do-Re-Mi'' and ``My
Favorite Things'' in grade school and in Muzak-filled elevators
have left permanent musical saccharine deposits in the collective
consciousness. Perhaps, like the Kevin Bacon Game, ``Sing-a-Long
Sound of Music'' was a form of cinemania just waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenneth Tynan said that movies are the most dominant
repository of memory we have,'' said the film critic Andrew Sarris.
``I suppose this is just a manifestation of that. Everyone
remembers `The Sound of Music.' You can blast it but you can't
obliterate it, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 0942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
