<HEADLINE>
$ADV23 
 FOR RELEASE: WED., AUG. 23, 2000 
 TV-TONIGHT COLUMN
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: Please check local listings for time and channel. All
times listed are EDT unless otherwise specified.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c. 2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's one and only one show on TV tonight for most viewers:
the final ``Survivor'' episode _ a three-hour tour beginning at 8
on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Once derided as a joke, ``Survivor'' has become a legitimate
phenomenon. It is, as everyone said in the beginning, a cross
between ``Gilligan's Island'' and ``Lord of the Flies.'' But it
also turned out to have more interesting characters and better
drama than many of TV's fictional series. With a little help from
the Internet, where the show is Topic A, ``Survivor'' has also
become the summer's highest-rated series, and a goldmine for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The original 16 castaways have been whittled down to four _ Tagi
Alliance hardcores Richard, Susan and Rudy, and the wavering,
conflicted Kelly. In tonight's episode, two more will be eliminated
before a jury of seven ejected castaways chooses the $1 million
winner from the final duo. And of course there will be challenges,
including fire-walking.
</P>
<P>
   You have to give kudos to CBS and the castaways for keeping the
winner's identity secret all these weeks, despite intense scrutiny
and no doubt a bit of detective work by various media outlets
intent on spoiling the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   One thing CBS can be criticized for, however, is the co-opting
of its news department. First ``Early Show'' newsreader Julie Chen
was drafted to host the godawful ``Big Brother.'' And tonight at
10, after the two-hour ``Survivor'' finale, ``Early Show'' main man
Bryant Gumbel will host an hourlong ``Survivor Reunion'' with all
the castaways, which will get a huge audience but should not be
confused with a news show. (Bryant ought to ask that dumbbell ``I'm
voting in alphabetical order'' Sean to show us his diploma and
prove he's a neurologist.)
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, considering how it looked a couple of months ago,
we'll be sad to see this crew go, especially the lovely Colleen and
the conniving Richard. But of course they're not really going
anywhere. Most of the castaways already have new gigs to capitalize
on their fame. Richard's guest-hosting a radio show in Rhode
Island, and Sean has been named medical correspondent for
``Extra.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Generations,'' Fox at 8: Fox battles ``Survivor''
with the 1994 movie that brought Capt. Kirk and Capt. Picard
together for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order'' duo, NBC at 9: Back-to-back airing of a two-part
crossover episode between ``Law &AMP; Order'' and its ``Special Victims
Unit'' spin-off. When an apparent sexual predator is murdered, the
detectives team up to investigate what is revealed as a string of
unsolved and possibly related killings. (``SVU'' airs first.)
Reruns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``P.U.N.K.S.,'' Disney Channel at 7:30: Young teens steal a suit
that conveys super powers in this 1999 movie. Randy Quaid and Cathy
Moriarty are among the grown-ups. Rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Running Mates,'' TNT at 8: Rerun of last week's well-received
made-for-cable movie starring Tom Selleck as a Democratic
presidential contender trying to pick a vice presidential candidate
while surrounded by strong women _ all of whom he's slept with.
Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wood,'' Showtime at 8: R-rated 1999 film about young men
assessing their romantic pasts on the eve of one's marriage. Omar
Epps and Taye Diggs star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO at 9: Carrie's guilt about Mr. Big
strains her new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' HBO at 10: Richie and Janice fight, and Junior
evaluates his options. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Food,'' Showtime at 10: Tonight's episode is ``Show Me
the Money,'' when some family members invest in a tech stock. Every
other series that has gotten into Internet investing has dealt a
harsh lesson to its characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure,'' Sci Fi at 10: Short-film series tonight offers a
tribute to ``Star Wars'' and is hosted by ``Clerks'' director Kevin
Smith. Offerings include the now-legendary ``George Lucas in Love''
by Joe Nussbaum and one of Lucas' own film-school efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Jack Hanna and
Wyclef Jean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Pro wrestling's
The Rock, and music by Lucy Pearl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: Author
Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Heather Graham
and Dido. Rerun. &QL;
</P>
