<SLUG> BC-ADV. </SLUG>
 FOR SUN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HINES COLUMN 8/20 (sun) &HT;    BUSH, GORE: STATUS QUO ANTE HOOPLA
 &HT;    By Cragg Hines
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CThe conventions are over, and the two major presidential
candidates still face essentially the same task they did before the
lavish infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   Neither George W. Bush nor Al Gore has closed the sale. There's
still some life in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The electorate finds Bush likable and capable of leading but
still has some questions about his grasp of _ and position on _
important issues. Gore is over the hump on the experience issue
(and perhaps even too far over, given his two decades in
Washington), but major questions remain about his leadership
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Strauss, the former Democratic national chairman, put
Gore's problem in a question last week: ``Do they find him
appealing enough?''
</P>
<P>
   Polling over the next two weeks will tell whether the convention
helped Gore truly close that gap. Because as the convention started
and as the four-night miniseries played out, Bush had a decided
upper hand. Overnight polling as the convention closed showed a
predictable bounce for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Republican show in Philadelphia, Bush was
beginning to dominate both the issue and character debate. An
esoteric but revealing scatter graph by the Gallup Organization,
combining issues and character questions, showed a significant tilt
to Bush. Based on polling July 25-26, the graph assesses which
candidate scored better with likely voters on 14 issues and nine
personal characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say there were more dots _ and more important ones _
on Bush's side of the center bar, topping out with the Republican's
better showing on honesty and trustworthiness and his being
perceived as a strong and decisive leader. Gore had a marginal
advantage on what the Democrats see as their iron triangle of
issues: health care, education and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The favorable finding for Bush has been reflected in national
polling and in the important state-by-state Electoral College
assessments. As the Democratic convention ended, independent
analyst Charlie Cook listed only three states and the District of
Columbia, with a total of 52 electoral votes, as ``solid Gore,''
whereas 18 states, with 140 electoral votes, were ``solid Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding in ``likely'' and ``leaning'' states, Gore got to 174,
while Bush surged to 250, just 20 short of the 270 needed to win.
Nailing down just one or two states from the 12 in Cook's ``toss
up'' list could tilt the contest, perhaps irretrievably, against
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Against this at least momentarily inhospitable backdrop, top
Democratic strategists departed Los Angeles honing various defense
mechanisms to get them through to Labor Day and over the next 11
weeks. The snap polls showing a Gore convention bump is a
short-term tonic, but experienced hands know not to take the
numbers too seriously for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' riskiest tack seems to be the attempt to keep
moving forward the date by which Gore can turn the race around. The
favorite marker for Democrats is the prospect of Bush-Gore &QL; 
face-offs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the debates are out there, anything is
recoverable,'' Strauss said. But even he said fellow Gore partisans
may be putting too much faith in the vice president's ability to
deliver a knockout blow in a one-on-one with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   An added segment of the party is banking on Gore's ability,
beginning with his convention speech, to transform the race into an
issues-driven campaign. They take such pains developing this theme
because they know Gore has little chance of besting the
congenitally personable Bush with some misbegotten charm offensive.
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, Bill Clinton's chief strategist in 1992, argues
that Gore should relentlessly lay out his issues and confront Bush
straightforwardly to say: ``We've simply got a different view of
the world here, hoss.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the last day of the convention, Democrats hoped the
meeting had gotten one issue out of the way: President Clinton.
Even such a Clinton defender as Carville said: ``Between now and
November, I think it's Gore's turn.'' Then came the new leak that
special prosecutor Robert Ray was before a new grand jury with
evidence about Clinton in the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates were outraged, hoped for a backlash, but remained
wary. Just days before, Democratic national chairman Ed Rendell had
said, perhaps presciently, of Republicans: ``These guys want this
election to be about Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
