<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Democrats struggling to find hero
</P>
<P>
   By CLAY ROBISION
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the City of Angels, even a fallen angel could
be a star last week, particularly for a Texas Democratic Party
fallen on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Cisneros' ability to quicken partisan pulses with a mere
sprint through the Democratic National Convention was testimony to
the obvious. Despite an extramarital affair and a federal
indictment, the former San Antonio mayor and Clinton Cabinet
officer is still a commanding presence for many Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who recently returned to Texas to launch a new
business venture, may yet run for statewide office, although almost
certainly not in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Texas Democrats can find a potential hero in
damaged goods speaks more about the disrepair of their party than
about Cisneros. Their once-dominant party is struggling, simply to
find someone who can win a statewide office under its &QL; 
banner.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats haven't pulled that trick since 1994, and they aren't
likely to this year. The best they can hope for in November, as
Gov. George W. Bush carries Texas in the presidential race, is to
hang on to their slim majority in the Texas House, perhaps regain a
one-vote margin in the state Senate and, maybe, watch Bush's
national bid fail.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Democrats are running or hope they will be during
this rebuilding era for their party. Some wannabes are new, some
have been wannabes for a long time, and others may already be
has-beens.
</P>
<P>
   But without touting Cisneros, which is not the purpose of this
discussion, none has the former mayor's proven star quality.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to predict a Democratic lineup for 2002, when
most statewide offices, including governor and one U.S. Senate
seat, will be on the ballot. That lineup may be affected by three
key events _ this fall's presidential race, the struggle for
partisan control of the Texas Senate and the new congressional
district lines after the Legislature and the courts complete next
year's redistricting chore.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is elected to the White House, Republican Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry will be promoted and will be an incumbent governor running
for a full term two years from now. That not only would discourage
other Republicans from challenging Perry, it also could discourage
some Democrats. If Bush loses his presidential bid, the 2002
governor's race could be wide open because Bush already has said he
wouldn't seek another term.
</P>
<P>
   If Perry moves up to the governor's office and Democrats regain
control of the Senate, a Democratic state senator will be selected
interim lieutenant governor by his colleagues. That, in turn, could
change some of the jockeying for lieutenant governor two years from
now.
</P>
<P>
   And some Democratic members of Congress who find themselves in
unwinnable districts after redistricting may be more willing to run
for statewide office. U.S. Rep. Ken Bentsen of Houston, for that
reason, is considered a potential Senate candidate, and he was
visible among Texas delegates in Los Angeles, hosting breakfast and
passing out T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Republican U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm will be formidable if he seeks
re-election in 2002. There has been some speculation that he won't,
but it may be wishful thinking among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Many expect wealthy Laredo businessman Tony Sanchez Jr. to run
for governor as a Democrat in 2002. Sanchez is not widely known,
but if he runs, he will have one essential ingredient _ money _
and, as a Hispanic, will have an edge in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Former Comptroller John Sharp, who lost a tough lieutenant
governor's race to Perry two years ago, would like to run again for
that office _ or perhaps for the Senate. Former Land Commissioner
Garry Mauro, who was clobbered by Bush in the 1998 governor's race,
also wants to run again for something. But he may already have had
his last chance.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hobby of Houston, another wealthy businessman who lost a
close race for comptroller two years ago, is believed to be eyeing
another statewide race.
</P>
<P>
   And the plaintiffs' lawyers will almost surely find and fund
someone to challenge Attorney General John Cornyn, who has been
fighting their legal fees, particularly in Texas' tobacco suit. Two
mayors _ Kirk Watson of Austin and Ron Kirk of Dallas _ are often
mentioned as prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, who pride themselves on their diversity, are
concerned that women don't figure prominently in the early wannabe
list. A possible statewide candidate is state party chair Molly
Beth Malcolm, who has been getting national attention attacking
Bush's Texas record but won't say whether she is interested in
running for elective &QL; 
office.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL; 
END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
