<HEADER>
A7822 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN0822-COX     08-21 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Same school, different eras, new unease
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Why is it considered natural, laudable and
an affirmation of family tradition when kids go to their parents'
old colleges, yet if they end up at the same high school, everyone
gets uncomfortable?
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: look at George W. Bush. He went to Yale like his
father and grandfather and it's considered part of a heritage. But
because he also went to the same prep school as his father, people
snicker about how WASP and preppy and weird that seems.
</P>
<P>
   From the students' point of view, going to the same school is no
bargain, either. They are regaled with stories from the school's
past predating their birth, stuff they could care less about that
happened in a milieu they visualize as being around the time the
Civil War ended and Elvis was on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   And they fret about running into anyone who might still be on
the job after all those years.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, they are confronted with the nagging fear that
maybe, by following this all-too-familiar path, they face an eerie
yet real risk of _ worst of all fates _ Ending Up Like Their
Parents. That somehow, by walking these same overfamiliar halls and
sitting in the same rooms, they might be warped into the same shape
as the parental units.
</P>
<P>
   It makes one shudder.
</P>
<P>
   Now that my kids are at my old high school, I've been
considering these issues.
</P>
<P>
   From the front, the school looks familiar. The same red brick
and concrete stairs as when I was there. Lounging on the steps are
students in ripped jeans and shorts. Given the inexplicable
currents of nostalgia in kids' fashion, the scene is far, far too
familiar for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   What if I need to go to the assistant principal's office? I am
sure to look guilty. Just out of reflex. As it is, when I venture
on campus, I sneak past the main office or pick up my stride to a
jog when passing the attendance office.
</P>
<P>
   I already know many of the routes students take when they skip
out of class and most of the more common destinations the kids aim
for after they escape. How do I explain such knowledge to the kids?
``Well, that's what people tell me,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   I know the nooks where one can kill time unobtrusively if
somebody with a score to settle is roaming the halls looking for
you or if you've slipped away from student assemblies. Is this
valuable information to be shared, or something best kept to
yourself, lest it be used for evil rather than self-defense?
</P>
<P>
   And there are larger issues here, too. This is America. We are a
mobile society. On the go.
</P>
<P>
   Finding yourself in the same neighborhood after 30 years is
considered suspect in our culture. A sign of failure or lack of
ambition. No matter how many places you've seen between sessions.
</P>
<P>
   And demographically, it is a bit abnormal. Last year, 16 percent
of the adult population packed up and moved, according to the U.S.
Census Bureau. And that number represented a historic low. And
we're even more mobile here in Florida, the Moving Van State.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is continuity of experiences between generations a very
American concept. It's pre-rock'n'roll. Pre-modern. Sorta medieval.
Things just are not supposed to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   I've attempted to allay the kids' concerns by dropping them off
unobtrusively and not right in front of the school. Somehow this
feels better. And I agree. But I also quickly remind them that I
had walked to this school under my own power.
</P>
<P>
   Uphill. Both ways.
</P>
<P>
   They roll their eyes and run off. The Old School Problem isn't
so easily dispelled.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
