<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-MUSI     08-21 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-MUSIC0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing around on the Web
 &HT;    By Mary Jo DiLonardo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Long gone are the days of painful piano lessons in
Mrs. Crotchety's parlor. No more glowering looks and accusations
that you haven't been practicing. No more ominous ticking of the
dusty metronome as you struggle to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the wonderful world of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   With a couple clicks of the mouse, you can soon be tickling the
ivories or strumming a guitar without ever having to leave the
comfort of your home. Music education has jumped on the Internet
bandwagon offering online instrument lessons _ via video, sound
and/or text _ and how-to-play-music software.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Internet's most prominent music sites, Guitar.com
offers a huge library of video guitar lessons _ both from music
instructors and from well-known musicians such as B.B. King and
Richie Havens. The site also features chord and scale generators to
help players tune their guitars.
</P>
<P>
   Rock legend Havens recently called Guitar.com one of his
favorite Web sites. ``I go here and learn,'' he said. ``They have
tablature, guitar chords and teachers that you can hook into and
learn from directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bradshaw often uses his Web site, www.cyberfret.com, as an
additional resource for the 65 guitar students he teaches each week
in Columbus, Ohio. The Web site, however, is designed primarily for
people learning the guitar on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guitar has traditionally been an instrument that people have
taught themselves,'' says Bradshaw. ``Now they have a very powerful
tool that can help them learn: the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw uses computer technology even with traditional
in-person students. He uses a computer to play background
accompaniments for songs that students are playing. With the
computer, he says, he can change the key, tempo, or even style of a
song, unlike playing along with a CD.
</P>
<P>
   One great advantage to using online technology is the
availability of multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students can watch a technique being demonstrated over and
over, or even at different camera angles,'' Bradshaw explains.
``They can listen to examples, or play along with a virtual band.
Related material can be easily accessed through linking to other
pages within the site, or to Web sites anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere around 1,500 people visit Vision Music
(www.visionmusic.com) each day for guitar instruction, says site
creator and instructor Mark Stefani who lives in Tualatin, Ore.,
just outside of Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers everything from an ``eye test'' to help
first-year students assess their abilities and figure out where
they need work, to a database of articles on technique, motivation
and practice. In addition, it is the host for ``Jam Central
Station,'' a round-the-clock online jam session for players of all
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stefani says his site can be a supplement for students
taking traditional music lessons, he sees it as a broader
educational tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that it was serving a unique purpose in providing
musicians around the world who couldn't afford private lessons an
opportunity to learn and to be inspired,'' he says. ``This group
numbers in the thousands, including retired folks on a limited
budget, kids, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the online instructional sites are accessible
whenever you get the urge, some offer actual lessons at explicit
times.
</P>
<P>
   At www.RiffInteractive.com, students log on to a chat session at
a specific time and join 20-30 other students for guitar lessons.
An interface allows the instructor to send out music notation,
pictures, and sound and video clips. While these group lessons are
free, one-to-one lessons _ via NetMeeting's two-way streaming video
_ are $40 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Then every lesson is archived in a database for students to call
up at will.
</P>
<P>
   The main demographic for the online lessons are men age 16-35,
according to Riff Interactive's Steve Roeder. He says plans are in
the works for similar sites teaching drums and keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Music teachers can stake out a spot to create their lessons and
instantly post them online for their students at sites like
NotationStation.net. They can use a free online notation service
(notation is a way of writing out musical notes) provided and send
students to their own personal area on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Then students have the tools to compose, edit, print and listen
to music, along with the ability to input notation through the
keyboard or mouse, or from a live instrument via MIDI files.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of NotationStation.net is for teachers to extend
their reach beyond the classroom,'' says founder Nathaniel Weiss.
``Kids are using computers all the time, and this provides an
immersive, collaborative environment to make the music they learn
in school come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to getting music instruction online, there's plenty
of software available that allows would-be players to learn at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for any instructor to do is to get people to
practice,'' admits Laurie Arthur, president of PlayPro, a company
that manufactures instructional music software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practicing by yourself is pretty boring. With PlayPro, there's
always a band behind you and it's much more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the people who usually take traditional music lessons _
kids and teenagers _ the audience for educational music software is
much broader, says Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole pool of people out there who'd love to play in
a band or just get their chops back but their schedule just doesn't
allow private lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   The quickest students have made it through the software program
is three months, says Arthur. On average, it takes the average
person about six to nine months to complete the instructional
program. The software ranges from $49-$89.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has its plusses and minuses, says guitarist and
country singer Keith Urban, who appears in a series of video
lessons at the House of Blues Web site (www.hob.com) . Urban, a
highly respected player who has worked with Garth Brooks and the
Dixie Chicks, was a self-taught guitar prodigy by the age of 6. He
laughs that he never had access to an instructional video as a kid
_ much less online lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't know technically how to do something you had to
find your own way and it created a lot of originality and your own
style,'' says Urban, whose downloadable video lessons include a
how-to for classic country ``chicken picking.'' Chicken picking is
a style of playing that's popular with country musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is some advantage to being able to see people show
you certain things. There are some things that you really know how
to do them or you won't be able to do it,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   Though technology has its positives, Urban's sure some things
won't change. He says, hopefully, ``I don't think technology will
ever overpower creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there's one other thing technology can't help you do.
</P>
<P>
   ``From almost 30 years of dedicated teaching I've learned that
you can't make people practice,'' Stefani laughs. ``The only thing
you can do is to hopefully inspire them and fuel the flame that
flickers within.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
