<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool running
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   When you're hot, you're hot _ but you should have some say in
the matter. Consider then the Convair 900 ``Prestige'' Evaporative
Air Cooler ($300; www.convair.net.au). Not to be confused with
conventional air conditioners, evaporative coolers employ a
contrary, environmentally friendly means to comfort-zone ends. Air
is drawn through a large, wet filter pad by a powerful (and
distinctly audible) fan, a process similarly seen in nature when
air is cooled when it passes over an ocean or large body of water.
The Prestige holds up to four gallons of water and has a tank gauge
to monitor consumption. As a self-contained, free-standing unit
requiring only an AC power source, the Convair 900 Prestige does
not require permanent installation of gaudy bulk. It can be wheeled
to any room as needed, including the storage shed during the
off-seasons. Essentially a humidifier, the Convair Prestige is
innately less effective in extremely humid climates, but when it's
simpatico with the environment, the Prestige is very cool.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   ONE SHARP DVD PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   I've always been an early adopter. I'm too young to have jumped
on the bulkiest, most-expensive Beta VCR, but when CD players were
introduced, I hustled out and picked up an awkward, heavy,
way-too-expensive, top-loading monolith of a unit. It wasn't long
before I'd broken my oath not to duplicate my album collection on
disc, either. So when consumer DVD units began appearing, I took a
deep breath. This time, I'd be the smart one. I'd wait 'til they
were out a while, 'til the price dropped. Well, it might be time to
jump in. Having lived with Sharp's DV-770U DVD Player ($300;
www.sharpelectronics.com) for a few weeks, I am impressed. Okay, I
don't have anything (except VHS) to compare it to, but Sharp's
Digital Gamma Correction (which enhances picture quality by
adjusting color values in dim areas according to picture
brightness) and Digital Super Picture (it increases the sharpness
of images) sure seemed to render a crisp, clear picture in the day
and too far into the night. It sports all the standard DVD features
(Dolby Digital sound, noise reduction, audio CD compatibility) and
a remote control that looks like it could operate the USS
Enterprise. Watch long and prosper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dale Roe
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
