<HEADER>
A7829 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-SAVVY0822-COX     08-21 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep track of financesBy Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I've heard of Web sites that keep track of your financial
information but haven't found any. By giving them your logins and
passwords they can display your balances from different banks,
mutual funds and other accounts on one Web page. Do these sites
exist, or is it just wishful dreaming?
</P>
<P>
   _ Derek Marks, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Derek, your dreams have come true! We found all kinds of
Web sites that keep track of your financial information, securely.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: I set up my checking account and two credit cards within
minutes on two Web sites. Give AltaVista MyAccounts a try at
myaccounts1.altavista.com. You'll first have to register with
AltaVista, then create a MyAccounts login. Another option is MyCiti
(myaccounts.myciti.com). I was thrilled to see that all my
financial records could be accessed via the same online service.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: It's important to note that you first should create an
online account with your bank, credit card company or financial
institution before trying to add them as a site.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Next, create an account with one of these financial
tracking services. They'll ask some personal info, and in two
minutes you're ready to add sites. Pick from banking, credit cards,
bills, investments, personal finances, etc. For instance, I
selected banking and got a long list of banks that allow online
banking. I clicked on a link for my bank, was prompted for the same
name and password that my bank originally asked for and, viola! My
account showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Jeez, she started clicking ``add site'' like crazy. Next
thing I knew she had it all set up. Now, she just has to log in
once and she gets all her financial info in one nifty little
package.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Two companies behind this technology are VerticalOne
(verticalone.com), an Atlanta-based company, and Yodlee
(yodlee.com/solutions). Both let you create a financial tracking
account. Interfaces vary, but they both let you set up an account
with a few clicks. What's really cool is they have a hand-held
solution. It's a Windows application that lets you push your
financial info to your Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If you have a Palm VII, a zippy way of getting your
financial info is to download the AccountMinder application
(accountminder.com). Sync the new app on your Palm, create an
AccountMinder account, set up your financial info and you're ready
to rock and roll. Pop up the antenna on your Palm VII, log in to
AccountMinder and your account balances are in the palm of your
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: All transactions were secure, easy and took no time to set
up. For a list of other sites using this type offinancial tracking
software, click on the Yodlee.com link.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
