<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BASEBALL0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `WSB' a few hits short of being a real winner
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sega Sports has created a problem for itself.
</P>
<P>
   So good is the company's product line _ which set the industry
standards with the classics ``Virtua Tennis'' and ``NFL 2K'' _ that
it is criticized when its sports games are not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   That is the case with ``World Series Baseball 2K1,'' which was
released only a few weeks ago. The game has been routinely
criticized for not having a manual defense option. In other words,
the computer plays defense for your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``WSB'' is the first baseball title for Dreamcast and has better
graphics than all of its competitors on PlayStation and Nintendo
64. The national anthem before the game is a nice opening, with the
exception of the overhead shot of the stadium showing nothing but
empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   The first amazing detail you notice is the starting pitcher
kicking around on the mound, causing dust to fly into the air. The
players resemble their lifelike batting stances.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plays just make you gasp. The first baseman dives
for a ground ball _ automatically _ then he makes a toss to the
pitcher at the base for the out as he falls head-first into the
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   When your team hits a homer in front of the home crowd,
fireworks go off. After a victory, teammates give each other
high-fives on the field in stunning detail.
</P>
<P>
   But it is simply too hard to overlook the automatic defense. A
ball is hit right up the middle, and your pitcher won't even stick
his glove out for it _ turning an easy out into a single. When a
fly ball is hit, the outfielders seem to wait forever before
getting a jump. The automatic defense is bound to cost you at least
one or two runs per nine-inning contest.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching on ``WSB'' requires unbelievable patience. It requires
four rapid _ and sometimes confusing _ controller movements in a
row. First you choose the pitch, then start the pitch. As the
pitcher goes through the windup, you pick a location. Finally, you
have to press a button again to determine the energy meter. It
takes maybe a week of intensive play to get the process down.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, hitting is _ by far _ the best part of the game.
You control a circle in the strike zone that determines where you
want to focus your swing.
</P>
<P>
   The replays during the game make no sense. For instance, on a
single hit to center field, what you will see sometimes is the ball
going by the pitcher, with the center fielder picking it up and
tossing it to the cutoff man.
</P>
<P>
   On replays where guys are thrown out, sometimes it will end
before the tag is made.
</P>
<P>
   ``WSB'' didn't arrive in stores until after the All-Star break,
which does have one major advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The rosters are updated through about late May, with players
such as rookie sensation Rafael Furcal of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the players' real-life attributes are represented
in the game, some are not. For instance, the computerized Greg
Maddux can throw fastballs up to 95 mph. While we're discussing
shortfalls, the play-by-play announcer is both repetitive and
annoying.
</P>
<P>
   ``WSB'' was a notable effort that fell short of expectations. It
is still worth purchasing if you own a Dreamcast, but the baseball
title clearly ranks behind PlayStation's ``Triple Play 2001'' (EA
Sports) and Nintendo's ``All-Star Baseball 2001'' (Acclaim) as far
as overall game play. Expect a much better product from Sega Sports
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
