<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World War II game isn't merely for history buffs
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Software reviewer Dave Basinger said ``Combat
Mission'' is an excellent PC game, even though he doesn't know much
about World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He knows who won, and he's happy with the results. So all the
game maker's claims about historical accuracy and weapon
authenticity are lost on him. All he knows is that he likes playing
the combat simulation, and that's good enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really, really good game,'' said Dave. ``It took a
little while to grow on me, but now that I've figured it out, I'm
really into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave said that if it weren't for school and chores, he would be
doing combat quite a bit more in the coming months. As it is, he
will have to put first things first and play this game when and if
he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only been playing for a couple of weeks, and I can see
how addictive it can be,'' the 15-year-old said. ``Unfortunately,
my parents don't let me play as much as I would like to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Combat Mission'' is a WWII tactical warfare game for one to
two players. It combines depth of story line with ease of use in
3-D battlefield environments. According to its maker, the 3-D
effect is not just to look good; rather it improves the accuracy of
the simulation for game play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty fun and easy to play,'' Dave said. ``The graphics
aren't all that great, though. I guess that's the only downside to
it, but after you play it for a while you really don't pay that
much attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game takes players from Normandy in 1944 to Germany in 1945
on WWII's two Western fronts. Players can choose to play either
side of the conflict and battle across historically accurate plains
and villages or into the woods and cities.
</P>
<P>
   If gamers are unhappy with the scenarios, they can use the
program's editor to change the settings to suit their preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Players command a force as small as a platoon or as large as a
reinforced battalion. Each man and weapon is kept track of for
maximum realism.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the game play is, Dave said the sound effects are
what really sold him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine gun fire and other sound effects were awesome,''
Dave said. ``It was like a good movie soundtrack.''
</P>
<P>
   `COMBAT MISSION'
</P>
<P>
   Maker: Big Time Software
</P>
<P>
   Format: PC
</P>
<P>
   Price: $45
</P>
<P>
   Dave's grade: A-minus
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
