A7837 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NETWATCH0822-COX     08-21 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Survivor' sites ensure you never have to be off island
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We know where you'll be this Wednesday night, oh yes
we do. You'll be with the rest of your fellow ``Survivor'' addicts
parked comfortably on your couch watching the big three-hour season
finale of the desert island drama. You will be watching, hoping and
praying that Richard, the biggest rat on the island, hasn't
manipulated his way into becoming the million-dollar sole survivor.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who believe you have better things to do on
Wednesday nights, ``Survivor'' is CBS' surprise blockbuster hit
that has lured more people than anyone imagined back to the former
Tiffany network to see how a group of strangers initially divided
into two tribes is able to survive not only the rigors of island
life, but the rigors of coping with one of the most disparate
collections of personalities ever assembled on network television.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Survivor'' may have brought CBS back from the dead, it
has also resurrected one of the most wonderful things about the Web
_ personal fan pages devoted to TV shows. Whether you are a diehard
fan or somebody who desperately needs to catch up before the big
finale on Wednesday, check out the fan pages devoted to all things
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Survivor'' fan pages are so refreshing, particularly to
those of us who follow Internet goings-on. They're well-designed,
informative and fun sites built by fans who just want to have a
little fun with their favorite TV show.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the best ``Survivor'' sites is SurvivorSucks.com
(www.survivorsucks.com). It describes itself as ``A fan site for
those who love to hate `Survivor' on CBS.'' A word of warning
before you surf on over, though: some of the language might not be
suitable for younger ``Survivor'' fans, as the site's title clearly
indicates. However, that said, it's still a great guilty pleasure
for adult fans. (Several Web executives secretly admit to being
addicted to this site but asked not to have it included in articles
written about them or ``Survivor.'')
</P>
<P>
   You'll appreciate the effort that went into this site _ the
tongue-in-cheek episode commentaries and the news section, which
features clear-eyed analysis of who will be forced to grab his or
her backpack, turn in the torch and get off the island.
</P>
<P>
   Bonus points to the site designers for putting this in text that
has to be highlighted to be read, so the people who want to be
surprised can stay in suspense.
</P>
<P>
   The message boards are filled with comments from people who
clearly think the show is hilarious and want to share their
opinions with other fans.
</P>
<P>
   If you love the show, you'll love this site. The sarcastic
analysis and commentary from the site's creators keep fans coming
back for more. Hopefully the site will stay up for a while _ even
after Wednesday's finale.
</P>
<P>
   Another surprisingly good ``Survivor'' site comes from CBS
itself. Up until now, CBS has been fumbling around in the dark
trying to find a Web strategy or anything that will draw users to
its site.
</P>
<P>
   With its mini-``Survivor'' site
(www.cbs.com/network/tvshows/mini/survivor), CBS scores big.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes the inevitable show summaries, video of the
tribe members talking about their experiences, an opportunity to
vote for the next person to get the boot and cast profiles.
</P>
<P>
   We could probably do without the merchandizing section, but who
can blame CBS for wanting to cash in on the show's runaway
popularity?
</P>
<P>
   CBS makes up for its shameless product pitches with a very cool
interactive map of the island that's definitely worth a look
(www.cbs.com/network/tvshows/mini/survivor/island/fsetflash.shtml).
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the parody sites. Ed Bain's Pop Corn Culture site
(homestead.icast.com
</P>
<P>
   /edbain/files/SURVIVOR.htm) offers up a short film that runs
well on a 28.8k bps modem that poses the question: What would
happen if the ``Survivor'' cast was sent to Russian space station
Mir instead of the island?
</P>
<P>
   And, if you think you have what it takes to become a survivor
yourself, or are wondering how those dreadful people got there in
the first place, check out TC Conway's application for ``Survivor
II'' (www.tcconway.com
</P>
<P>
   /AboutTC-App.asp).
</P>
<P>
   CBS isn't taking applications any longer, but it is amusing to
see what you need to do to get yourself marooned on an island.
</P>
<P>
   As the late comic Jimmy Durante used to say, ``everybody wants
to get into the act'' when it comes to ``Survivor.'' There are tons
of articles and essays on the show from almost every entertainment
site you can think of. Everyone seems to have an opinion, but be
sure to check out Linda Stasi's New York Post essay on the show.
(www
</P>
<P>
   .nypostonline.com/entertainment/35143.htm).
</P>
<P>
   She used to hate ``Survivor,'' she writes. ``Now I just hate the
survivors ... literally and figuratively. What I really hate,
though, is that the show is actually just a mirror of modern
corporate life.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what a lot of us have secretly been thinking all along,
and truth be told, that's probably why we watch. Thank goodness for
the fan sites that remind us to lighten up _ it's just a TV show,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
