<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMEZONE0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Perfect Dark' fun, but expect action rather than a story
 &HT;    By Vox Day
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Perfect Dark'' is a sequel of sorts to
``Goldeneye,'' the game that brought computer-style 3-D action to
the Nintendo 64 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   While it combines nearly every annoying marketing element in the
book, ``Perfect Dark'' is simply an excellent action game.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the ability to network between machines, video games
have lagged well behind computer counterparts in the multiplayer
3-D action game first demonstrated in ``Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   While computer gamers have had a mind-boggling array of
player-modified weapons, levels and characters to choose from,
along with up to 15 teammates and opponents, video gamers have been
stuck playing with at most three opponents while peering at a
screen divided into two or four parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect Dark'' changes none of that; it's a function of the
hardware technology, not the software. But it does provide a
training facility that, in its willingness to stack the odds
against you with AI-controlled simdroids, provides a fair
approximation of the pulse-rate-lifting stress and excitement that
multiplayer action does.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 different challenges in the training section, and I
found myself still playing them long after I would have finished
playing most games.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I still haven't gotten to the real game itself. I
guess that's really beside the point, since the story line is the
usual mishmash of silly alien conspiracy stuff that has plagued so
many games ever since the ``X-Files'' was first televised.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, is in keeping with tradition _ one of the many
admirable things about ``Doom'' was its refusal to pretend that it
had any plot or story line. ``Perfect Dark'' might as well have
done the same. It's all about the action, you see.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics are good, with windows that shatter, walls that
show damage and good lighting effects. There are many weapons,
ranging from clip-emptying burst fire machines to single-shot
silencers and remote mines.
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite is to have an autofiring Cyclone in each
hand; this seems to do the trick quite nicely on most enemies. I'm
impressed with this game, mostly because I really didn't expect to
see action this exciting on a single-player system setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect Dark'' is not nearly perfect, but it will certainly
give any action gamer his or her money's worth. P.S.: You need the
4-megabyte expansion pack to play the solo missions.
</P>
<P>
   `PERFECT DARK'
</P>
<P>
   Format: Nintendo
</P>
<P>
   Price: $59.99
</P>
<P>
   Ages: 12+
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 (of 5)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
