<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nifty search engine vindicates ad-saturated Net software
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is inevitable, I suppose, that our society will
commercialize anything and everything remotely capable of bearing
up under it.
</P>
<P>
   Race cars are so plastered with advertising you can scarcely see
the paint. Athletes are walking (or running, or jumping or
whatever) billboards. Speaking of billboards, I see we now have
mobile billboards, dragged around town on trailers.
</P>
<P>
   So I probably shouldn't be surprised or shocked by
commercialized software. I was, however.
</P>
<P>
   A company called IWare makes a product called uWare, the beta
version of which I blithely mounted on my computer without really
knowing what it was about, other than assurances that it would
enhance my Internet experience.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, it might do that, but I was about to rip it out
by the roots before I discovered that. For the most part, it is
nothing more than an advertising carrier for a host of
e-businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The program produces a new taskbar at the bottom of the screen.
Its chief features are a set of Touch Tiles and a long panel of
rotating ads for various e-businesses. The Touch Tiles it comes
with are also e-businesses. Clicking the tiles or the long panel
will take you to the specified e-business site.
</P>
<P>
   There are a herd of them, all of which have paid IWare something
to be included in uWare. Among them are eBay and AutoNation,
Harley-Davidson and Cigar Aficionado magazine, all sorts of things.
I have not seen one, however, that I care to visit.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a tile called Deals, featuring specials that Iware
has arranged for the benefit of its audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Touch Tiles can be thrown out and replaced by items of your
own choosing. I don't see any way to get rid of the long panel,
however. Incidentally, the program says ``uWare updates daily,''
which I presume means that every day when you log onto the
Internet, the program goes scurrying off in search of newly signed
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The program, of course, is free. My indignation would be
boundless were it not.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost boundless anyway until I discovered the Search
tile.
</P>
<P>
   This is a multiengine search so nifty that I am contemplating
allowing the entire mess to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   This feature has both a ``content'' search and a ``product''
search, although it's hard to see why you couldn't find products in
a content search. Whatever the case, it employs seven of the most
popular search engines to answer your queries.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that impressed me is its exactitude. I asked it for
``blackpowder cartridge.'' Every choice it presented fit that
parameter.
</P>
<P>
   No cartridge without blackpowder, no blackpowder without
cartridge. No duplicates. Very nice.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you are a shopaholic, uWare may be just the ticket
for you. In that case, go to www.uware.com and download your own
copy of the beta release.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
