<TEXT>
<P>
   Colony Wars III: Red Sun, short on plot, heavy on carnagec. 2000
Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Your name is Valdemar, and you're slogging away in some future
dead-end job when a regal, bald general appears in a dream and
reveals that you are the Chosen One. For what have you been chosen?
Well, from there it gets a bit hazy. Consistently vague and random
visions may ultimately distract you from the only tangible goal of
Colony Wars III: Red Sun ($30; www. midway.com; for the
PlayStation), which is to kill everything you see. If you accept
the limitations of this objective going in, then you will be free
to appreciate the game for what it is: an enjoyable, intergalactic
shoot-em-up. With aurally and visually pleasing lasers, explosions
and spaceships, ``Red Sun'' is the gaming equivalent of a good
summer blockbuster, with a thundering, cinematic soundtrack to
match. Technically above average, ``Red Sun'' graphics feature few
rough edges, and although the close-ups of Valdemar and friends are
downright creepy, most of the full motion video scenes are
stunning. Plot junkies may find ``Red Sun'' inferior to the first
two Colony Wars episodes, as the mystery of the Red Sun is never
especially compelling. But if you relish the thought of laser
cannon carnage on its own terms, then ``Red Sun,'' with its 50-plus
missions, could be a lovely way to (after) burn an hour or six.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeremy Egner
</P>
<P>
   ($40; www.activision.com; for the PlayStation), which is a game
simpatico with the recent summer blockbuster, which in turn is
based on an immensely popular comic and cartoon franchise.
Unfortunately, the game is merely another means to brand name us
with X-Men; it has little to do with the film. In fact, it only
vaguely resembles a modern video game in the first place. Mutant
Academy is a well-drawn, well-animated 2-D fighting game _ and
that's it. There's no adventure akin to a movie plot, just the
various super-anti-heroes duking it out in a face-to-face,
side-scrolling romp. Even on the aging PlayStation console, most
fighting games are known to contain so much more than flat-action
eye-candy, such as three dimensions. Nevertheless, X-Men Mutant
Academy is a very good 2-D fighting game complete with trademark
super-moves and painful powers of mutant punishment. But it's the
weakest member in the grand amalgamation scheme of console,
cartoon, comic and cinematic extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially reinventing the ``First Person Shooter'' genre,
Warren Spector's ($40; www.eidosinteractive.com; for Windows and
Mac) blends a deep and completely malleable role-playing story line
with the traditional wander-and-frag games of death and
indiscriminate dismemberment. In the game, produced by Texas' Ion
Storm and ported to the Mac by Austin's Aspyr Media Inc., cause and
effect decisions concerning in-game characters and environments
directly affect this feature-rich game. Deus Ex gives gamers the
opportunity to customize skills and skill levels with a suite of
``nanotech augmentations.'' This enhances, as an understated
example, one's strength or combat prowess while forgoing the
slippery skills of stealth or, visa versa, making the game as
frenzied and violent or intensely subdued as desired. Breathtaking
``real life'' visuals and a wholly immersive world of exhausted
chaos promise to make Deus Ex the new benchmark for digital
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Based on a venerable Dungeons &AMP; Dragons-style pen-and-paper
game, Vampire: The Masquerade _ Redemption ($45;
www.activision.com; for Windows) drops you into an immersive 3-D
world where role-playing, action and puzzle-solving are well
balanced. That's the good news. Creeping about in the shadows as
the undead anti-hero Christof and hacking away at one's enemies or
drinking the blood of one's victims is sinister fun. The
smooth-running landscapes and special effects are detailed and
atmospheric. The controls are intuitive (toggle between third and
first person), the cinematic cut scenes are lovely and the
characters who join your party are interesting and even helpful.
But the most highly anticipated aspect of the game, storyteller
mode, in which one player builds and controls a world as the game
is running, disappoints in that it requires a sure hand at the helm
_ something difficult to find in the twitchfest of the Internet _
and generally degenerates into a free-for-all. But given the right
circumstances _ a well-built local network game with all the
players physically in a room together _ Vampire has the potential
for transcending even its worst glitches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Stafford
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
