<SLUG> BC-TECH-SEAMAN0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The incredible Seaman lives on your very own TV screen
 &HT;    By Troy Oxford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About 20 years ago I ordered Sea Monkeys from an ad I
saw in a comic book. The advertisement depicted a quirky humanoid
family living happy aquatic lives. When the package arrived, I
opened it eagerly and tried to bring life to these ``advanced''
beings in a powdered form.
</P>
<P>
   My excitement faded within a week, and these ``beings'' sadly
turned out to be tiny brine shrimp. My dreams of interacting with
my very own seahorse-riding people were left unfulfilled _ until
now.
</P>
<P>
   Sega recently created a new life form for my Dreamcast, and it
delivers everything it promises. This life form is named
``Seaman,'' and it's a milestone for video game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   Using a microphone that is included and your controller, you
raise, nurture and interact with a creature that would make Darwin
start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of living in a foul-smelling fishbowl, Seaman resides on
your TV screen and depends on you to reach adulthood. Following
daily routines of maintaining his environment, providing him with
food and talking to him will result in the evolution of Seaman.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out as a strange tadpolelike creature, Seaman will
evolve to a snobby fish/man who amazingly recognizes many of your
words. He asked me when my birthday was, acknowledged what I said,
and informed me of some celebrities that had the same birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Although rude and apathetic at times, Seaman is fun to interact
with. You can tickle him, pick him up out of the water and even
flick him in the nose if he becomes too obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   This simulation is not for everyone, however.
</P>
<P>
   Those impatient folks who want to bring Seaman to adulthood in a
couple of days will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution is a gradual process, and the results will be more
satisfactory if you follow the general guidelines and attend to the
fishy fellow.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth noting, ``Seaman'' requires a Visual Memory Unit, or
VMU, with 64 blocks of memory available.
</P>
<P>
   The strange concept, advanced voice recognition and narration by
``Star Trek'' veteran Leonard Nimoy make ``Seaman'' one of the
outstanding titles for the Dreamcast. I only wish I could feed him
those darned Sea Monkeys!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
