<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Copy your books, don't kill them
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Photocopying bound materials has always been an awkward affair
and often a damaging one to the originals. Enter Minolta's
BookScribe 2000 ($9,995; www.minoltausa.com), a digital face-up
book copier that eliminates the need to squash your precious tomes
flat and upside down. The BookScribe is ideally suited to law
offices, libraries, accounting firms or any place with old ledgers
and antiquated hardbacks _ especially those that are falling apart
at the seams. A single top-down scan allows for a separate print of
either left or right page or a double-page spread on a single
sheet. The BookScribe 2000 boasts simple operation for
high-quality, digital printing _ and with no distortion thanks to
the imbedded curvature correction capacity. The BookScribe is also
adjustable, allowing even thick volumes to be scanned without spine
damage. And if you're really gung ho about transferring that
ancient registry to the digital age, the BookScribe 2000 is
PC-ready and upgradeable to act as a digital scanner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   NOTE TO SELF: PRESS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Inclined to talk to yourself? The VN180 Digital Voice Recorder
($79.99, 90-minute version; $99.99, 180-minute version;
www.olympusamerica .com) is for people who like to take verbal
notes as they move through their day. This Olympus hand-held device
can hold up to three hours of audio. There are three folders in
which you can store as many as 180 messages each: one for personal,
one for business and one for a built-in scheduler. The recorder has
up to 20 verbal alarms to remind you of important events. The user
also can set the sensitivity of the built-in microphone, which has
a voice-activated option. Along with the earphone and headphone
jacks, we would have liked one more feature: a USB or infrared
connection that would allow messages to be easily downloaded into a
computer or other Internet device. Still, for less than $100, this
little gadget is competitive with good personal tape recorders and
has a lot more features.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
