<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anime is one of the world's favorite exports. But how did this
art form develop?
 &HT;    By Yina Liang
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Pokemon.'' ``Sailor Moon.'' ``Dragonball Z.'' ``Card
Captor Sakura.'' ``Gundam Wing.'' ``Hello Kitty.'' ``Tenchi Muyo.''
</P>
<P>
   What do all these popular cartoons have in common? They were
made in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese animation, or anime (a-NUH-may), has grown very popular
in the past few years. It has invaded our TVs, video stores and
even the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Japan produces more animation than any other country.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Akins, the creative director at Cartoon Network and
executive producer of Toonami, a popular group of anime programs,
says about 150 new episodes of anime are produced every three
months in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   So how did it all start?
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pearl, an anime expert who operates anime Web sites,
explains that modern anime began in the late 19th century when
Japanese graphic artists began copying the bubbles, dialogue and
serialization of Western comic strips.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese called the comics ``manga'' (mahn-gah), which means
``random pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1940s, the success of American animated movies such as
``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs'' influenced some Japanese
graphic artists to experiment with animation. However, World War II
interrupted the Japanese development of this new form of
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, while Japan was still recovering from the war, a man
named Osamu Tezuka introduced a manga called ``Mighty Atom.'' It
was inspired by the cartoons of Walt Disney.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, ``Mighty Atom'' became the first anime. It was released
a year later in the United States as ``Astro Boy.'' The success of
this animated ``Mighty Atom'' brought about a whole new industry
for Japan, producing one hit series after another.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these shows were based on popular manga; others were
original or adapted from books or other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, the family tree of anime has developed into
branches of diverse themes while keeping a similar style.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese artists gave birth to action and adventure shows like
``Speed Racer'' in the '60s, science fiction and robot shows like
``Captain Harlock: Space Pirate'' and ``Mobile Suit Gundam'' in the
'70s and soap opera and comedies like ``Maison Ikkoku'' and
``Ranma'' in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   By the '90s, the popularity of animated features and videos
embraced an even larger worldwide audience. Shows that were made
for children, such as ``Sailor Moon'' and ``Pokemon,'' also
attracted teenage and adult fans.
</P>
<P>
   The most distinct features of modern anime are intricate plots,
a wide variety of topics and styles, and detailed art.
</P>
<P>
   Akins explains that ``boys are attracted to the action and
robots, and girls are attracted to anime's strong female
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   In just a century, what began as an imitation of Western art has
evolved into one of the largest graphic entertainment industries in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about anime, visit these Web sites:
www.geocities.com/MotorCity/Speedway/2523/index.html
</P>
<P>
   www.anipike.com
</P>
<P>
   www.hyperguide.com/tezuka/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
