<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore grabs nomination
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, when Vice President Al Gore accepted the Democratic
presidential nomination, he promised to fight for America's working
families. In his speech, Gore said he would improve health care for
poor children and senior citizens, cut taxes for working families
and fight for better public education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his vice presidential pick, Sen. Joe Lieberman, then
left the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles to campaign
along the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gore and Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush have agreed to debate on television three times this fall.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN SUB DRAMA UNFOLDS
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that Russian sailors might be saved from a sunken
submarine faded last week. Bad weather and a huge hole in the boat
blocked rescue attempts for days. The nuclear-powered sub, the
Kursk, sank quickly in the Barents Sea following at least one
explosion. The 118 submariners on board were performing naval
exercises at the time.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Russia refused offers of help from other countries.
Later the Russians allowed Britain and Norway to send rescue ships.
No one knows for sure how long the submarine's oxygen supply could
last, but some Russians said they didn't expect to find any
survivors on board.
</P>
<P>
   COED TEAM ROCKS SOFTBALL
</P>
<P>
   Boys and girls on the same softball team might not seem like a
big deal. But it is a big deal when the Little League Softball
World Series title is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Five 16-year-old boys in Arizona joined a girls' softball team
this summer after their boys' baseball league disbanded. The coed
team played well and made it to the Softball World Series
tournament in Kalamazoo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Now tournament officials and other teams are crying foul.
Critics say the boys have an unfair advantage and could hurt the
16-year-old girls. Some teams are refusing to play the Arizona
squad.
</P>
<P>
   The national Little League board of directors will meet this
week to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
