<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: OK, I give up. I've searched everywhere on
and off the Web for a foley fork, a cooking utensil I'm starting to
think doesn't exist anymore. I'm sure your older readers will
remember their grandmothers using a foley fork to cut lard into
flour.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Foley is a brand name, not a generic name. The fork you
described is indispensable (meatloaf to Bisquick). A four-tine
pastry blending fork is available in the King Arthur Baker's
Catalogue ($3.95 plus shipping and handling). The tines and the
short handle allow your wrist to do the work. Call (800) 827-6836
or visit www.kingarthurflour.com to order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My fiance and I are marrying next June and want to dispense
with some of the less ``PC'' traditions _ namely, the
bouquet/garter toss. We're planning an evening wedding, so my
fiance came up with the idea of releasing fireflies to symbolize
good wishes. I know that you can order butterflies for release at
weddings _ can you do the same with fireflies? How much does it
cost (we're on a very tight budget)?
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Price is not the object _ availability is. According to the
nation's premiere firefly researcher, University of Florida
professor James Lloyd, firefly numbers are decreasing and there is
no commercial source for them. What's going on? Dropping water
tables and pollution certainly contribute to the diminishing
firefly population. Increased urbanization and resulting ambient
light keep the remaining fireflies from efficiently using their
light to find mates and procreate. Lloyd would prefer
well-intentioned couples contribute to firefly research rather that
attempt a release. Q: Where may I purchase buckwheat hulls such as
those used in pillows when they were in fashion?
</P>
<P>
   _ J. D. Reed
</P>
<P>
   A: You must be getting a jump on holiday gifts. Remember,
buckwheat hull needs to be free of mold and dust in order to make
good pillow stuffing. Buckwheat hulls are sold by retailers such as
James Farrell &AMP; Co. ($40 for 18-pound bag, $30 for 10-pound bag,
shipping included), 506 Second Ave., 3100, Seattle, WA 98104, or
call (206) 623-1993 to order. On the right coast, Birkett Mills
sells them at www.thebirkettmills.com or (315) 536-331. A 5-pound
bag is $8.95, plus shipping, and a 44-pound bag is $39.50, plus
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband and I have bet on your answer. What actor played
Eldin, the painter redoing Murphy Brown's apartment? I say it was
Oliver Platt. My husband can't remember the actor's name but he is
sure it wasn't Oliver. If I win, he has to take me to Jamaica for a
week, and if he wins I have to wash his car once a week for the
next three months. Please let me be right!
</P>
<P>
   _Lenora M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Get out the bucket, Lenora, you are in the car-washing
business.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pastorelli played Eldin Bernecky, the ever-present
painter-cum-nanny. By the by, Oliver Platt looks like Pastorelli's
long-lost brother.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a number of baseball caps. Wearing these caps has
resulted in their becoming soiled and in need of cleaning. I have
tried soaking to no avail. Do you know a way to make the caps clean
as new?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Logan
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe not clean as new, but much cleaner. Test them for
colorfastness, then pick up a Ball Cap Buddy for less than $3. This
frame keeps your cap in good shape through a washing machine or
dishwasher cycle. Cleaner than those gentle soaks.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
