<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SELLERS GIVE COLLEGE BOOKSTORES A RUN FOR THEIR MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   College life looks and feels different today than it did even a
decade ago. Typewriters, pay phones, and library research are out.
Laptops, cell phones, and Internet research are in.
</P>
<P>
   But students continue to lug around as many heavy, hardcover
textbooks as their predecessors ever did _ and pay more for the
privilege. Full-time students routinely spend hundreds of dollars
on texts at the beginning of each semester, only to sell them for
cents on the dollar four months later.
</P>
<P>
   As would-be scholars return to school in the next few weeks,
though, a handful of Web sites are vying to break the near monopoly
campus bookstores have enjoyed for generations. The sites make it
surprisingly easy to comparison shop for textbooks online and even
get the tomes delivered to your doorstep (or dorm room) in time for
the first class.
</P>
<P>
   The technology involved isn't cutting edge, but it is useful. In
short, the sites troll a bunch of online booksellers checking price
and availability of the texts you want, then create an express
checkout with your retailer of choice.
</P>
<P>
   To test the services, I looked up the required reading for a
trio of randomly selected fall classes at local universities. Then
I compared both the new and used prices at the campus store with
those online.
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, the bookstores more than held their own. In
every case, the on-campus price was better than most of the ones at
online sellers _ quashing the oft-repeated grumble about colleges
gouging their own. The old alma mater looks especially good when
you consider shipping and handling charges at online sellers, not
to mention the extra time and hassle involved.
</P>
<P>
   Students, though, don't buy dozens of copies of the same book;
they must concern themselves only with the single lowest price they
can find. In that regard, the book-search sites were useful.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the searches turned up at least one text that could be
had for less than the going rate on campus. How much less, and how
easy the search was, depended on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of students and the parents who fund them, then,
here's a rundown of the sites tested:
</P>
<P>
   --www.addall.com is probably my all-around favorite. It's simple
(books only), comprehensive (checks 41 online sellers), fast
(promises to complete all searches in 25 seconds or less), and ad
free (no banners). The prices it tracked down tended to be good,
too.
</P>
<P>
   You can search for books directly from the home page, unlike
some of the others, which make you click a couple of layers deep
before starting a query. And you can search by title, author,
keyword, or ISB number.
</P>
<P>
   Once you do get a list of books, Addall.com presents them from
lowest cost to highest and includes nice details such as shipping
costs, sales tax, and number of days until the book can be in your
hands. Not all the sites were as complete.
</P>
<P>
   My only complaint: It would have been easier if new and used
books were separated into different lists. I was able to figure out
which were which, but it would've been simpler if I didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   --www.bookfinder.com doesn't work with as many stores as
Addall.com and it isn't quite as simple to work with, but it does
include a handful of retailers that specialize in rare and antique
books. College students might not find that terribly useful, but
book lovers in general might.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, among the eight sellers Bookfinder.com checks for
new books are giants Amazon, Barnes &AMP; Noble, and Powell's Books (a
sprawling independent retailer in Portland, Ore., that bills itself
as ``the largest used and new bookstore in the world''). So you're
still likely to find whatever you need on Bookfinder.com.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest irritant with this site is that it doesn't include
shipping and handling charges in the lists it provides. And, in my
searches at least, it did include a handful of wrong titles along
with the ones I wanted.
</P>
<P>
   --www.dealtime.com found the best prices among the sites tested,
but only because it included one seller they didn't: elgrande.com.
Otherwise, the prices it found tended to be in line with those of
the others.
</P>
<P>
   If the elgrande.com prices are legitimate, you'll probably find
a few good deals by going through this appropriately named
book-hunting service. Regardless, the site is helpful and easy to
use.
</P>
<P>
   As with addall.com, you can search by title, author, keyword, or
ISBN. And the results include shipping costs, time until delivery,
and _ in the case of overseas booksellers _ conversion of prices to
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion turns out to be important, since dealtime.com
surveys quite a few international sellers. But it also surveys the
big domestic players, so you'll get plenty of options.
</P>
<P>
   --www.ecompare.com is a shopping-comparison service for a
variety of things, books among them. That's not necessarily a bad
thing, as long as the book search is comprehensive and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, it is. Ecompare.com surveys 25 sellers of new
books and usually finds competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   The site's biggest strength is its simplicity. You can search by
title, author, keyword, or ISBN, and the results are a thing of
beauty. It simply lists bookstore, price, availability, and
shipping costs, and limits the list to one from each bookstore.
Most of the others were more jumbled and more difficult to
navigate.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't search used books at all, though, which is a
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   --www.mysimon.com made a name for itself during the holidays
last year as a comprehensive ``shopping bot,'' or shopping search
engine. Books are one of the many things it will shop for in your
stead.
</P>
<P>
   In a different twist, you can tell Mysimon.com that you want
hardcover, paperback, or audio books. And once you have a list,
retailers are shown with their reliability ratings from Gomez
Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   You can also pare down the final list by ``merchant services''
you want, such as international shipping or acceptance of Discover
Card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
