<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED FUNDS AREN'T LIKELY TO SMOOTH INVESTOR'S BUMPY RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I invested in March, just before the big market drop, and
now I have negative returns. I am considering American Century
Income and Growth fund and Invesco Dynamics fund, as well as making
a small investment in Marsico Focus fund. I want moderate
investments, as I have only eight or nine years for an investment
time frame. Would I be wiser to consider a group of Vanguard index
funds, or just add more to the Index 500 position?
</P>
<P>
   S.R., Chattanooga, Tenn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're unhappy with the bumpy ride, chances are it won't
improve much with the three funds you suggest. All, of course, have
attractive records, but two of them would significantly increase
your risk level. Let's take them one by one:
</P>
<P>
   --Marsico Focus, like all of the so-called focus funds, has a
compact portfolio of 38 stocks, as of the last report from
Morningstar Mutual Funds. It produced a 51.3 percent gain in 1998,
its first year, and followed with 55.3 percent last year. This
year, it is off 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of its holdings are solid and well-established
companies, but the very fact that its portfolio is concentrated in
so few stocks adds an extra element of risk. Most funds have 100 to
122 stocks, and poor performances by a few of them can be more
easily offset than in a fund holding fewer investments. Like all of
the funds you now hold, Marsico Focus has a portfolio dominated by
large-cap stocks, so the move would not take you away from the
large-cap investments.
</P>
<P>
   --Invesco Dynamics has a portfolio of mid-cap growth stocks and
boasts a 13.7 percent year-to-date total return. The fund tends to
focus on health and technology issues and has produced strong
returns in recent years, gaining 23.3 percent in 1998 and 71.8
percent in 1999. But the gains come with an expensive portfolio,
which has an average price-to-earnings ratio of 52.9.
</P>
<P>
   It could be an attractive holding if it represented a small part
of an otherwise diversified portfolio, but like Marsico Focus it
should hardly be a major holding in a portfolio you want to
characterize as moderate. But by adding a mid-cap element to your
portfolio, it would improve overall diversification.
</P>
<P>
   --American Century Income and Growth is a different matter
entirely _ a solid, well-established, value-oriented fund that has
been running nearly in tandem with the Standard and Poor's 500
Index in recent years, or at least a whole lot closer than most of
its peers in the value universe can claim. This is the only one of
the three funds you suggest that could truly be considered part of
a moderate portfolio. And including it would give you a foot in the
value segment of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Would an amalgam of these funds and those you already hold be
better than an all-index portfolio? My take is that it would have
more upside potential and, accordingly, more risk.
</P>
<P>
   I'd split my bets, sticking with the Vanguard Index 500 position
as your core holding. Then, put $5,000 in American Century Income
and Growth fund, taking the money from the Janus Worldwide account.
I would then divide the remaining $10,000 in Janus Worldwide,
leaving $5,000 where it is and putting the other $5,000 in Janus
Overseas. The latter is more purely an overseas play, mostly
invested in international stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Janus Worldwide, in contrast, holds a little more than 30
percent of its assets in large-cap domestic stocks _ pretty much
the same fare you have covered with your position in Vanguard Index
500. Until late last year, Janus Overseas was running behind the
Standard and Poor's 500 Index; since then, it has been leading it.
This is the point of real diversification, to be in different
markets that will operate in different market cycles.
</P>
<P>
   As for the final $10,000, I would divide it evenly among the
three riskier funds you have been considering.
</P>
<P>
   The only fund we haven't discussed is Janus Mercury, which you
already have and which is somewhat akin to the Marsico and Invesco
funds, holding a fairly compact (but not focused) portfolio of 72
large-cap growth stocks, with major concentrations in service and
technology issues and with a heavier-than-normal diet of
Internet-related stocks. Its price-to-earnings ratio is a heady
52.9, but these stocks drove it to a 1998 total return of 55.8
percent, followed by a 96.2 percent gain this year. As this is
written, the year-to-date return is a negative 2.7 percent. Given
the current climate, I wouldn't worry about that 2.7 percent loss,
but given its focus on expensive stocks in risky market sectors, I
would limit your investment here to $3,333.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I need $1,500 a month. Where should we invest to
reduce our tax liability? I will have to start drawing from the 457
and IRA accounts at age 70 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   C.S., Arlington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two basic avenues you might explore to reduce
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   --Move into a municipal bond fund that holds securities that are
free of both state and federal taxes. A good choice might be the
Fidelity Spartan Massachusetts Municipal Income fund, which wins
top grades from Morningstar Mutual Funds and has a current tax-free
yield of 4.94 percent.
</P>
<P>
   --The other investment vehicle likely to reduce your tax
liability is stocks _ either a portfolio of common stocks or a
mutual fund, particularly a stock index fund. Since there is
relatively little turnover within index funds, they do not tend to
produce high levels of capital gains, and the dividend yield from
stocks and stock funds is currently very low.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at your portfolio, which shows no stock investments
(unless some of the 457 plan is in stocks) I hesitate to suggest
that you go into stocks in a big way. Some people simply don't like
the element of risk that comes with stocks. If you are one of those
people, stick with the municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But if I were in your shoes, I would put about $169,000 in the
municipal bond fund, taking the money from the Scudder GNMA
position, the CD, and the rest from the proceeds of your real
estate sale. That would leave you with $110,000. I suggest you then
transfer $100,000 of it to a money market fund, such as Fidelity
Cash Reserves. Then, invest the remaining $10,000 in shares in
Fidelity Spartan 500 Index fund, which simply seeks to track the
results of the Standard and Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you instruct Fidelity to move $3,000 a month from the
money market fund to Spartan 500 Index fund. This procedure is
called dollar-cost averaging, and since that sequence of
investments would spread your investment over 36 months (presuming
5 percent average returns from the money fund) it would offer some
protection against a short-term market downturn. (If there is a
price dip, your later purchases would be at lower prices, and each
purchase at lower prices would bring your average cost per share
down.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. I am interested in the assumptions you make in calculating
long-term growth in an investment account. In a previous column,
you projected the growth of a $500,000 account with $10,500 annual
contributions and 10 percent annual investment returns to
$1,532,563. I come up with $1,464,214. Where have I gone wrong?
</P>
<P>
   V.M., Burlington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You made your calculations based upon annual contributions
made on the final day of each year. My calculations were based on
120 monthly contributions of $875, each made at the end of the
month, and with monthly compounding, using the actual number of
days in the month. For example, in your tally of the growth of the
questioner's 401(k) contributions, you posted $10,500 as the
balance at the end of the first year; in my calculation, the
balance at the end of the first year was $10,994. However, I have
tried adjusting a number of less critical presumptions to come up
with $1,532,563, and I can't duplicate it; I probably garbled it.
The number should have been $1,523,623.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
