u f BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-21 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALERS SLOW TO EMBRACE ELECTRIC-GAS TOYOTA PRIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anara Guard says Toyota Motor Corp. isn't making it easy to do
the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton, Mass. resident currently drives a 15-year-old Jeep
Cherokee with 84,000 miles on it. She needs a new car, and she and
her husband are seriously considering buying the new electric/gas
hybrid Toyota Prius, which gets 52 miles to the gallon in the city
and runs 90 percent cleaner than the average car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're greens _ we recycle and we try to do the right thing,''
she said, explaining her interest.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been easy getting behind the wheel of the Prius
(pronounced Pree-us) for a test drive. Guard has been reading about
the revolutionary car for more than six months now, but she says
neither Toyota nor its local dealers have been responsive to
requests for information or a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why you have made it so difficult for
consumers to purchase your vehicle!'' she said in a July 31 e-mail
to Toyota. ``My older car is getting more rickety by the day. If
Toyota cannot provide me with some assistance, I will be purchasing
another vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard's story is troubling. The Prius, as well as its hybrid
cousin the Insight from Honda, are cars that could revolutionize
the way Americans drive. With gas prices high, oil markets
unstable, and automobiles the leading cause of air pollution, the
arrival of the hybrids could not be more welcome. Consumers should
be encouraged, not discouraged, from taking a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota officials attribute most of Guard's problems to bad
timing. She started asking questions about the Prius in April and
May, before Toyota was ready to provide many answers. Her requests
for a test drive, prompted by ads and news articles on the car,
came before local dealers received a test-drive vehicle and
training on the new car.
</P>
<P>
   The test-drive vehicles arrived in New England one month late,
at the end of July. Several dealers I called now seemed geared up
for customers, but they said the hybrids, despite their gas savings
and environmental benefits, are not easy sells because of their
unfamiliar technology, high cost, and scarcity.
</P>
<P>
   The Prius and the Insight are both being manufactured in Japan
and shipped to the United States in limited quantities. Honda hopes
to sell 6,500 Insights this year, while Toyota, despite rumors of
stepped-up production, is sticking with its plan to ship 12,000
vehicles to the United States over the next 12 months. That's about
1,000 cars a month for some 1,200 dealers, a paltry number that may
explain why some dealers aren't too excited about the Prius yet.
Nine of the 71 Toyota dealers in New England have chosen not to
sell the car.
</P>
<P>
   The slow pace of Prius production is understandable from the
standpoint of a manufacturer uncertain whether the concept will
take off, but it's frustrating for consumers accustomed to
immediate gratification.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's Web site says an order placed today should yield a
Prius in November to mid-December, or about three to four months. A
Honda spokesman said the wait for Insights is one to two months.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do customers have to order a hybrid and wait, they also
have to pay a premium. Toyota says it is losing money on each Prius
it sells, but even so, the car is expensive. At $20,400, the car
has many attractive standard features (air conditioning, power
windows and locks, an eight-year warranty, and a free roadside
assistance plan), but the five-passenger vehicle is comparable in
size to the much cheaper Echo or Corolla. The Insight may be an
even tougher sell. The hatchback seats two but costs $18,800, or
nearly $20,000 with air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the long wait for a car and the high cost, Albert Gray,
sales manager for Ira Toyota in Danvers, Mass., said he would
characterize consumer interest in the Prius as ``low to medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smenton, business development manager at Boch Toyota in
Norwood, Mass., said consumers interested in the Prius are the type
who want to be the first on their block with the latest gadget. He
expects the customer base to change as production increases and
customers learn the advantages of hybrid technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing the first stages of a revolution in the car
market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a car so different, Toyota decided to sell it differently.
The company felt Internet users were its most likely target market,
so it used its Web site (http://prius.toyota.com) to steer initial
customers to dealers who would actually place the orders. The
Internet referral process is still in place, but customers can now
go directly to a dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota also wanted consumers to take the Prius for a day-long
test drive rather than the standard 20-minute spin around the
block. But most dealers I contacted said consumer interest is so
strong they can't spare their test-drive vehicle for that long.
Some will rent their Prius for $60 a day, however.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota officials are generally pleased with Prius sales so far.
As of last week, Toyota had 3,100 confirmed orders. Close to 2,000
customers have placed orders for the Prius sight unseen, without
even taking a test drive, said Ernest Bastien, vehicle operations
manager with Toyota in Torrance, Ca.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, which was the last of Toyota's 12 sales
territories to receive test-drive vehicles, 215 cars have been
ordered. Four have been delivered so far. Acton Toyota has sold the
most, but 49 of the 62 dealers selling the Prius have sold at least
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're thrilled with the results we're getting,''
Bastien said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Guard isn't giving up. Her calls to Toyota customer service
were finally answered late last week and she plans to take a test
drive sometime this week. She's not certain whether she'll end up
buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay a hefty price and wait months and months,'' she said of
the situation. ``I think that's asking a lot of consumers. You have
to be sure that this is the only vehicle you want.''
</P>
<P>
   A disconcerting recall
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janet Bruno of Woburn, Mass. got a letter last month from
General Motors that scared her. The letter said the company had
learned of a ``condition that can cause the driver's air bag in
your car to deploy unexpectedly, without a crash, as you start your
car or during normal driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Even scarier, as far as Bruno was concerned, was the news that
it would take GM at least six months to assemble the necessary
parts to repair the problem. ``General Motors needs to move to
alleviate this situation now, not starting in six months,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   GM blames its air bag problem on corrosion of the air bag's
inflator wiring. The company said it has received 115 reports of
bags deploying in noncrash situations, prompting the letters to the
268,000 owners of 1995 and 1996 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supremes and
1995 Buick Regals.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Martin, a GM spokesman, acknowledged the letter would be
disconcerting. But he said the company felt it had to alert
customers now rather than later. He said it will unfortunately take
time to inventory the necessary parts and said the risk of injury
is small if drivers take the necessary precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said drivers should sit the proper distance from the
steering wheel and immediately pull over and call Oldsmobile for
emergency assistance if the air bag light on their dash comes on
and doesn't go off.
</P>
<P>
   In 60 of the 115 incidents, Martin said drivers suffered minor
injuries. ``There was nothing more serious than that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But every time she gets behind the wheel of her car, Bruno
worries. What if she's driving down the highway when the air bag
deploys? What happens if she loses control and hits other cars?
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' she said. ``I'm petrified to drive
the car.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; Ends &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Priceline feedback. I'm looking for consumer feedback, pro and
con, on Priceline's new bid-for-gasoline option. Contact me using
one of the methods below.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
