<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7861 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      08-21 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING IT SIMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an age of smart money and savvy deal-making, it's good to see
someone look into a television camera and say: ``So, what's a
stock?''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at the beginning is beneath a lot of people today.
They figure we're all on Step 5 or 6 in the workbook, way past the
basics, and into a serious relationship with a sector fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stock is a little piece of a company,'' Julie Stav says in
the national PBS debut of her television show ``Get Your Share.''
She explains how Home Depot was ``cut up into 600,000 pieces in
1981, selling for $12 each,'' and that if someone had invested
$1,000 back then, the person would have $1.3 million today.
</P>
<P>
   That's a stock all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``A client said to me, `What's an IRA?' and she had one,'' says
Stav in a phone interview. ``I said, `Good for her!' People confuse
lack of information with lack of intelligence. When people say, `I
have a really stupid question,' I tell them that those are my
favorites. Always ask. That's how you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Stav has lived the axiom. The 47-year-old Calabassas, Calif.,
stockbroker and financial planner came to the United States from
Cuba in 1967 at age 14, knowing no English. She was classified as
``mentally retarded'' at a Los Angeles high school because of the
language barrier. The experience steeled her resolve to go to
college and become a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had English coming out of those kids' ears,'' she says of
her years as a first grade teacher in an inner city school, ``and I
taught the rest in the language they knew best.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how she approaches the market: ``I'm always teaching. I
want it to be fun. I want you to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stav did not ``get it'' easily and had to take her broker's
license exam three times. ``I studied at night after work at my
kitchen table while my kid was asleep.'' She pursued the brokerage
career after a divorce in 1986 left her ``with 33 cents in my
checking account.''
</P>
<P>
   She began that career by holding free financial seminars in
libraries, beauty shops, and storefronts, reaching out to Latinas
with the basics and helping them form investment clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were people just like me, managing their household
budgets and married to tradition-bound Latin men. Many of the
people I met were afraid of the stock market. I told them to relax.
I wasn't selling anything. I didn't care if they ever saw me again.
I love watching the light bulbs going on. It's like teaching a kid
to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Her TV show, available in Spanish and English, might seem
pedestrian to the cognoscente, but she gets the information across.
</P>
<P>
   One of her props is a three-drawer bureau, representing money
management. She explains that day-to-day expensese come out of the
top ``underwear drawer,'' as she pulls out boxer shorts decorated
with dollar signs. Long-term retirement and college funds are in
the bottom ``itchy blanket drawer,'' and stock market investments
are in the middle, feeding top and bottom.
</P>
<P>
   She believes in the power of small money, encouraging people to
get into the market for as little as $5 or $10 a month, going with
a discount broker or online trader. She advises people to sell when
a stock drops 10 percent, and knows that runs counter to the more
traditional advice to ``buy and hold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If holding is your thing, fine,'' she says. ``But I say don't
marry a stock when your money can be working elsewhere. This is my
recipe for the market. I'm not claiming it's the only one, or the
best. It's like my recipe for paella _ it's one way to do it, and I
know it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds are fine too, she says, but for the passive
investor. ``Buying individual stocks is for people who want to
drive the car. Mutual funds are for people who want to sleep in the
back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Too simplistic? Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally kicking butt,'' she says. ``Little old ladies
come up to me and say they feel empowered. So do men, but they're
not as quick to admit they don't know something.''
</P>
<P>
   With her frankly bleached hair, she's heard every dumb-blonde
joke in the book, but doesn't care: ``Honey, I know I'm not dumb _
and I know I'm not blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   She just might do for the market what Julia Child did for
bouillabaisse. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
