<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-COMMENT-NETSHOPPING-B     08-21 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-NETSHOPPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING ON THE INTERNET IS KILLING SERENDIPITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the old days, shopping for books and music could be
difficult. We'd trek to the outlets that claimed to physically
contain the works of our favorite artists. But often we didn't see
what we wanted once we arrived, so we'd have to flag down a
salesperson, or make a special order.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the days of Internet shopping, and the world's
inventories were made accessible in the click of a mouse. Nothing
was out of stock, very little too esoteric to be found, and if we
wavered between choices we could seek advice from experts who were
happy to offer recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for consumers of the most portable, affordable arts and
entertainment _ music, books, even videos _ this brave new consumer
experience is missing something.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the chance that as we head into the world music
department seeking a Nathan and the Zydeco Cha-Chas CD we will hear
and fall instantly in love with the hip-shifting merengue of Juan
Luis Guerra. Lost is the opportunity to browse the titles of a
favorite author and stumble upon an intriguing work by an
unrecognized writer on the shelf directly above.
</P>
<P>
   Because for all its ease, Internet shopping does not offer the
element of serendipity, the happy chance that put the joy into
non-Web browsing.
</P>
<P>
   There can be little doubt that the Internet has been a boon to
the arts, basically by providing low-cost, global exposure. Through
the Web, musicians can distribute their music everywhere via MP3
technology. Painters and other visual artists show to potential
buyers, albeit in reduced form, through online galleries. Midlist
authors can reach readers in the hinterlands thanks to Web
superstores such as Amazon and Barnes and Noble.com. Documentary
films may be getting a new shot at life via Internet distribution,
say reports from the latest Sundance festival, and independent
films (such as ``The Blair Witch Project'') have clearly benefited
from Internet buzz and from online festivals, like the Yahoo
Internet Life fete.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest benefactors in the Internet shopping spree
have been the most easily consumable arts. Books now make up 24
percent of all Internet sales, and music in the forms of CDs or
tapes, 19 percent, according to a recent survey by Arbitron/Edison
Media Research. The main reasons for these sales are convenience
and selection. Whatever you want, you can find it on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you shopped the inventory,'' says Don
MacKinnon, president of the Seattle-based Hear Music, which sells
CDs online and in its 18 North American stores. ``Now we all have
the same inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   The consumer mindset has been further changed by the Web's
round-the-clock access. As Paul Capelli, the senior public
relations manager for Amazon, points out, ``If you go back five
years people would say, `Stores open at 10 and they close at 6, so
I shop between 10 and 6.' Now people are saying, `Why can't I shop
at 11 at night?' ''
</P>
<P>
   No reason at all, say Web retailers, who have gotten very good
at giving consumers what they want.
</P>
<P>
   These sites are also becoming surprisingly adept at figuring out
what we are likely to want next and offering it to us in an
increasing variety of ways. The most basic is that which compares
our purchase history with those of other consumers, such as the
window that pops up to announce ``Readers who bought this book also
bought . . .'' on Amazon or the recommendations on CD Now that
combine personal buying history with the users' ratings of various
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   As this kind of advance marketing has grown more subtle, it has
sought to discover not only what we buy but how people develop
tastes and loyalties, and now aims at duplicating that process,
which for Internet retailers has largely meant adding more human
input. On the Web, that translated first to customer reviews, which
Amazon began posting in 1996, and more recently to options such as
purchaser groups, which offer the user the opportunity to see what
others in various cities or ZIP codes have bought.
</P>
<P>
   Although this marketing is consumer driven, relying on the
voluntary input of thousands of shoppers, the next wave of Web
marketing is beginning to think for itself. Increasingly sites are
promoting specific items through a blend of explicit and implicit
data, says Lisa Allen, a senior analyst with Forrester Research, an
independent Internet and emerging technologies research firm. In
other words, she explains, the latest technologies factor in not
only her recent purchases of mysteries and world music, but also
what other Web sites she has visited and how long she has viewed
each one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such chains of logic cannot answer all our needs. No
matter how sophisticated such technology becomes in determining
what we believe we want, it can't figure out what we would like if
we stumbled across it by chance.
</P>
<P>
   In brief, in a decision-driven, logic-driven model, there is no
room for serendipity. ``When people talk about the brick and mortar
retail experience they say, `Well, you can touch the fabric,' ''
says MacKinnon, whose business was recently acquired by Starbucks.
``But the beauty is you have this peripheral vision, you see things
and they intrigue you. You would walk into a little bookstore, and
you'd go to Pynchon and find Barbara Pym or Poe. There is no
peripheral vision on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some exceptions, of course, and these involve a return
to a more traditional model, in which we shopped at a particular
store because we trusted the store's point of view. That store
didn't offer everything, but we knew it was likely to have what we
wanted. And as Web sites all increasingly offer everything, we as
consumers may begin to seek out the more discriminating.
</P>
<P>
   This trend has already started on some book and music sites,
although the tastes being touted are more likely to be celebrities'
(as on Radio SonicNet) than experts' or fans'. Most notably, the
reintroduction of a more humanely scaled chaos can be seen in
online visual arts sites. Such sites are more likely to re-create
the concept of a global gallery, perhaps in part because their
products are less easily quantifiable. ``Viewers who bought Picasso
also bought Bracque . . .'' makes little sense in a field that
relies less on cognitive connections about which the average buyer
has scant knowledge. However, by using this format, the site risks
missing out on the consumer who really wants an olive green,
couch-sized oil painting and can't spare the time to browse.
</P>
<P>
   It is the targeting of such time-pressed consumers that
continues to make logic-based suggestions the marketing mode of
choice. As Allen puts it, traditionally, ``merchandisers have
talked about the art of retail. Online it becomes more the science
of retail.'' All of which threatens to involve us in an
increasingly closed circle, in which all that we are ever offered
is anything that we have ever previously bought. And while such a
fate is not unthinkable for more pragmatic purchases, to those of
us who see ourselves as supporters of the arts, even in a small
way, it is terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are books you want to touch, you want to see,'' says
Sanj Kharbande, general manager of Wordsworth, an independent
bookstore in Harvard Square that also sells through its Web site.
``I can throw up an excerpt, and an interview with the author,''
says Kharbande. ``But there are some books you have to pick up and
have a reaction to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Clea Simon has written about arts and media for the American
Prospect, The Boston Globe and The New York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
