<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-21 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO EXCITE, NOT RECITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been enough for Al Gore to be his own man. Did he
also have to be his own speechwriter?
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what possessed a campaign saddled with a
less-than-engaging candidate to cede to the vice president the
crucial task of crafting a message meant to energize the
electorate. Aides reportedly whittled Gore's initial 12,000-word
opus to a more manageable 5,700, but no amount of editing could
insert inspiration into a speech so sorely lacking in it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the reassurance they needed from their party's
presidential nominee, jittery Democrats heard all their fears
reinforced the other night when Gore delivered an earnest and
thoroughly plodding acceptance speech at the Staples Center in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Those who bemoan the fact that the national political
conventions are no longer where the real decisions get made suffer
a misplaced nostalgia for back room deals and cigar-chomping power
brokers. Richard J. Daley is dead; may he rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the early primaries have reduced modern
conventions to scripted party infomercials and well-oiled stage
productions, but there is value in a pep rally. It can ignite the
passions of those inside the hall who will hold the signs, stuff
the envelopes and get out the vote in November. It can engage the
imaginations of those watching at home who find fewer and fewer
reasons to vote with each election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman understood the power of a pep rally. It was not
his grudging endorsement of affirmative action in an otherwise
lackluster speech that mattered nearly as much as the Connecticut
senator's simple boyish delight in finding himself _ the son of a
Jewish baker _ on the Democratic ticket as a vice presidential
candidate. His core message _ ``Is this a great country or what?''
_ resonated with any parent who ever beamed with pride at the
family's first college graduate, with any immigrant who ever
purchased his own home, with any child who ever won an elementary
school spelling bee.
</P>
<P>
   There will be time enough in the fall for voters to sort out the
many conflicts between Gore's views and Lieberman's more
conservative positions on affirmative action, school vouchers and
abortion rights. A pep rally is about presenting a unified front
against the opposing team.
</P>
<P>
   The man at the top of the ticket missed the moment entirely,
choosing to outline the specifics in his playbook instead of
singing a rousing chorus of the team's fight song. Sure, policy
should trump personality, and competence should count more than
charisma. Voters want and need to know how Gore would save Social
Security and Medicare. But not in August. Not while they are
watching TV in their vacation rental at the beach or at the lake.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mystery whom Gore thought he was connecting with the
other night with his talk of targeted tax cuts and budget
surpluses. Does he really think that there is a policy wonk bloc in
the crucial mid-Atlantic and Midwest swing states? The Republican
nominee's speech in Philadelphia _ written for him, not by him _
was short on specifics but long on evocations of the kind of
America he envisions. Won't it be ironic if Texas Governor George
W. Bush is the one to call Al Gore to account in this campaign for
his lack of ``the vision thing?''
</P>
<P>
   No one moment should cripple a campaign. No single speech should
define a candidate, but too often they do. Remember a stumbling Ted
Kennedy in 1980 unable to explain why he wanted to be president?
Remember a bloodless Michael Dukakis in 1988 unwilling to concede
that he would want to strangle anyone who raped and murdered his
wife?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is an accomplished debater, a skill that will highlight
his command of policy issues in the presidential debates Bush has
agreed to participate in this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore should have a humming economy on his side and an electorate
that, by any measure, is better off now than it was eight years ago
when the Clinton-Gore ticket reclaimed the White House for the
Democrats. His record outshines Bush on the issues that the
majority of voters consistently identify as the most important this
election year. On education, health care, and the environment, Bush
is vulnerable to charges that in Texas he has not done nearly
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Gore may yet prove to be a commanding presence at a campaign
podium. The Democrats can only hope that vacationing Americans went
out for a late movie Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
