<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MUSEUM-WONDERLAND-KAN     08-21 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-WONDERLAND-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSE OF `WONDERLAND':ST. LOUIS ART MUSEUM'S FREE EXHIBIT BRINGS
INTERACTION WITH CONTEMPORARY WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ALICE THORSON  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   ST. LOUIS _ There's art that hangs
decorously on the wall, and there's art that stands sedately on a
pedestal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And then there's the art in ``Wonderland,'' a multi-sensory
extravaganza of strobe lights, Discmans, rushing and trickling
water, electronic music, wall-spanning videos, chickens, sheep, PVC
pipes and enormous amounts of pungent spices _ orchestrated,
variously, by 10 contemporary artists bent on provoking a sense of
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   In the six weeks after it opened July 1 at the St. Louis Art
Museum, the exhibit attracted 62,000 visitors. ``This already is
one of the top 10 attended shows in the past 10 years,'' said the
museum's director, Brent Benjamin, in a recent interview, ``and
it's not even two-thirds of the way through its run.''
</P>
<P>
   It continues through Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   It was Benjamin's idea to suspend the museum admission charge
during the run of ``Wonderland'' as a ``millennium gift to the
city.'' He also saw the free-entry policy as a way to encourage a
broad audience to experience contemporary art. Clearly it is having
the intended effect. The crowds also bear out the message Benjamin
says he's been picking up from St. Louisans: ``They want the museum
to challenge them.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the enjoyment of ``Wonderland'' is to watch museum
visitors young and old interacting with the exhibit's diverse
expressions.
</P>
<P>
   An audio piece by widely exhibited Canadian artist Janet Cardiff
requires viewers to strap on a pair of headphones and a pouch with
a portable CD player and head out of the museum for a walk on the
wooded grounds. On a hot August weekday, parents and children and
dozens of senior citizens gamely lined up for their turns, and
could be seen pausing along the path, per Cardiff's instructions,
to examine the fallen trees and vistas that caught the artist's
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Although it must be said that after 15 minutes of this,
Cardiff's voice begins to feel like a self-important gnat in the
ear, the experience is a memorable one. The exercise of squaring
and comparing one's own sensations and reflections of the walk with
Cardiff's account of the stroll she took several months earlier is
absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview, the exhibit's curator, Rochelle
Steiner, said she ``set out to make a show that would have the
ability to operate on many levels'' _ to have something for both
the art specialist and the novice.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner, who came to the St. Louis Art Museum from the Walker
Art Center in Minneapolis in 1996, spent three years working on
``Wonderland.'' The exhibit ranks as one of the ``most ambitious
exhibitions of contemporary art in the museum's history,''
according to the accompanying catalog. Seven of the 10 pieces on
view are brand-new commissions for this show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all addressing the idea of space, how space might be
organized and how we as viewers are affected by our space,''
Steiner said. ``Each makes a surrounding or an environment that
gives us this sense of wonder.''  &LR; brkhel:Stop, look, listen,
participate
</P>
<P>
   Although this international exhibit does not pretend to be a
survey of what's happening in contemporary art, it does pick up on
certain contemporary art trends. The artists exhibit a high degree
of inventiveness with materials, they embrace electronics and
digital technology, and they tend to cast viewers as active
participants in their works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Thematically most of the works cue off nature or architecture or
a combination of both.
</P>
<P>
   Danish-born Olafur Eliasson leads off the exhibit with a
20-foot-high geodesic dome he erected over the Neptune fountain in
the museum's main hall. Strobe lights illumine the dome's darkened,
mirrored interior, endowing the movements of perambulating viewers
with a jerky, stop-action quality. It's damp inside the dome from
the rushing water of the fountain _ and somewhat disorienting, due
to the pulsing lights and the kaleidoscopic effect of the
all-surrounding mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Eliasson's dome typifies the spirit of this show: It contains
nothing overtly threatening or combative but carries just enough of
an edge to provoke new responses to the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the special exhibition galleries, even the most jaded
consumer of TV violence stops dead in their tracks at the spectacle
of a young woman, clad in a fetching blue frock and red shoes,
strolling in slow motion down an urban street and stopping
periodically to smash in the windows of parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   Put up to this mischief by Swiss video artist Pipilotti Rist,
the woman employs a metal facsimile of a long-stemmed ``red-hot
poker'' flower as her instrument of destruction and moves in time
to a seductive electronic soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time she is alone, but other pedestrians
occasionally appear in the frame. A policeman who sidles into the
picture provides a moment of tension, but relief comes when ``he''
turns out to be a she, who smiles at the ecstatic vandal and raises
her hand in salute before sauntering on.
</P>
<P>
   This urban ramble is the topic of one of two color videos by
Rist projected on adjacent walls. Tilting, twirling and
consummately sensuous views of the garden whence the ``flower''
weapon came make up the second projection and set up an underlying
nature//culture opposition within the work as a whole. But the
piece also percolates with new ideas about the old equation of
woman and nature and about the nature of woman's power.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rist, Ernesto Neto has enjoyed a good deal of exposure
recently in a long list of international biennials and other big
global shows. For ``Wonderland,'' the Brazilian artist created a
full gallery installation employing his signature nylon fabric,
which stretches tentlike across the ceiling and dips down in the
form of rounded stalactite ``columns'' filled with aromatic spices.
</P>
<P>
   In her selections for this show, Steiner didn't confine herself
to artists with big resumes. ``Wonderland'' serves as a
high-profile introduction for Minneapolis-based Bill Klaila, who
responded to the invitation with a piece called ``Virtual Bog.'' In
a darkened gallery filled with the sound of crickets chirping, the
artist has projected a digitized bog image onto the floor.
Periodically its surface shivers with the plop of virtual water
drops, activated by viewer footsteps.  &LR; brkhel:Reduced means,
heightened sensations
</P>
<P>
   Newark, N.J., artist Steven Hendee, who creates faceted
environments out of foam board and gaffer's tape, also gets a boost
from appearing in the international context of ``Wonderland.'' Some
have compared the feel of Hendee's luminous architectural
environments to cathedral interiors. But standing within his
``Abandon.exe'' is also like finding oneself physically occupying a
three-dimensional drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Hendee's piece exemplifies this exhibit's overall embrace of
reductiveness. The works here offer a real departure from
installations of the last decade that bombard the viewer with lots
of stuff, idiosyncratically organized.
</P>
<P>
   The shift is particularly obvious in German artist Gregor
Schneider's ``Totally Isolated Guest Room, ur 12,'' part of an
ongoing project that involves constructing, then excising and
exhibiting, rooms and passages in his house in Rheydt. At the
recent ``Carnegie International'' exhibit in Pittsburgh, Schneider
showed a cluttered and complex ensemble of rooms. In St. Louis, he
is represented by a simple four-walled space containing only a bed,
a radiator and a stool.
</P>
<P>
   In this same reductive vein, New York artist Teresita Fernandez
offers the equivalent of a three-dimensional minimalist painting in
her ``Landscape (Projected).'' Narrow PVC pipes form a maze pattern
on the floor of this austere lime-green-painted chamber, which the
artist illumined from above with a circular fluorescent light
fixture.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is otherworldly. While speaking the formal language
of abstraction, the piece takes its cues from formal gardens, and
viewers are free to meander within it.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles artist Jennifer Steinkamp takes abstraction into
four dimensions with her red-painted, X-shaped corridor with
rounded corners. The crossing pathways culminate in two narrow
vertical video projections featuring what appear to be perforated
rollers or psychedelic conveyor belts in motion. A clanky
mechanical soundtrack reinforces the factory allusion, while the
hypnotic visuals speak to contemporary art's unapologetic embrace
of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th and final piece, if one follows the route through the
exhibit traced by the accompanying handout, is a temporary farm,
created on the museum's grounds by Atelier Van Lieshout, a
collaborative founded by Joep van Lieshout of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Although human in scale, the farm is modest in size, consisting
of several wood and aluminum structures including a tool shed, a
minimally equipped farmhouse, a rabbit hutch, a chicken coop, a hut
with pen for sheep and a low, curving shelter for pigs. There also
is a vegetable garden at the site, which was planted by local
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   When temperatures permit, the animals are brought up daily from
the nearby zoo. When fully stocked, the farm features chickens,
roosters, sheep and rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed through the art lens, one is struck by how alluringly
basic and no-nonsense this setup is, and by its total immersion in
questions of practical design rather than style. ON EXHIBIT THE
SHOW: ``Wonderland'' WHERE: The St. Louis Art Museum, 1 Fine Arts
Drive, St. Louis WHEN: Hours are 1:30 to 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays, and 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. Wednesdays through Sundays. Closed Mondays. The
exhibit continues through Sept. 24. HOW MUCH: Free. FOR MORE
INFORMATION: (314) 721-0072, Ext. 204
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7889 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BRADBURYAT80-KA     08-21 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BRADBURYAT80-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFTY YEARS OF FANTASY:AT 80, BRADBURY'S STILL THE MASTER OF
SCIENCE FICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   Ray Bradbury has lived long enough
to see the future _ and to see some of his own writings come true.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The master of science fiction, fantasy, the supernatural and
many other genres celebrated his 80th birthday Aug. 22, but dreams
and imagination have kept him young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm about 12 years old,'' Bradbury said in a
recent telephone interview from his Los Angeles home. ``I'm getting
my work done, and that's the important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite having penned such classics as Fahrenheit 451
and The Martian Chronicles, Bradbury is at work on two novels, a
book of essays, a poetry collection and a screenplay. The novels
include From the Dust Returned, which features a family of vampires
introduced in his short stories in the early 1940s, about the same
time Anne Rice was born.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's ``Vampire Chronicles'' are among the many modern works
derivative of Bradbury. Author Lucius Shepard's blend of science
fiction and fantasy probably couldn't exist without him. Even TV
shows such as ``The X-Files'' owe him a debt, with their focus on
what may _ or may not _ be ``out there.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bradbury, though, life in the
once-futuristic-sounding and now-real year of 2000 has its pros and
cons. Here is a man who has made an uneasy truce with modern
society _ a society he helped create.  &LR; brk:Burning questions
</P>
<P>
   In 1951 Bradbury published Fahrenheit 451, a grim vision of a
future in which books were burned to prohibit the spread of
dangerous ideas. The novel's ``firemen'' were charged with keeping
the bland citizenry from reading things that weren't good for them
_ indeed, to prevent reading of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they immersed themselves in technology that is now
commonplace: They wore ``seashell'' ear pieces that pumped music
into their heads. Giant, interactive TV screens filled four walls
of their living rooms with insipid programming.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Now we call the seashells Walkmans. We dive into
``virtual reality'' devices, including home theater systems that
can make seeing movies in the family room seem like a religious
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury reflects on how elements of Fahrenheit 451 have come
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese claim I invented the seashell radio you put in
your ear. They came to my office about 20 years ago and they had
one of the first of the portable earphone devices and they clapped
it on my head and they cried, `Fahrenheit four five one! Fahrenheit
four five one!'
</P>
<P>
   ``But (Walkmans) have improved life in some ways. At the beach,
for example, people would show up with their ghetto blasters and
rule the day, but now we have the earphones you put on, and life is
much quieter.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the virtual reality people call me Papa. They say they
read it in the (short story) `The Veldt' and they read it in
Fahrenheit, then they created it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury concedes, though, that such things can do exactly what
they did in the novel: Cut people off from one another and provide
the mind with empty diversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends how it's used. If you use it for `Jeopardy,' you're
in trouble, because that's stupid. But there are documentaries
concerning the history of the world and its peoples that are quite
wonderful, which didn't used to be available on TV or anywhere
else, and they've all come on the market in the last 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees computers as useful but views the constant marketing and
updating as suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst development is the power struggle of the computer
people, the Internet people and the email people to get you to use
things you may not need.'' Sci fi or fantasy?
</P>
<P>
   ``The World's Greatest Living Science Fiction Writer'': Decades
ago, publishers of Bradbury's works began to paste this audacious
phrase across his book covers.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he concedes only one of his novels was unadulterated
science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure, I don't write science fiction; I write fantasy. I've
only written one science fiction novel, and that's Fahrenheit. The
Martian Chronicles is fantasy. My books about my childhood,
Dandelion Wine and Something Wicked This Way Comes, are pure
fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, more than the ``hard science'' fiction of
contemporaries like Isaac Asimov or Arthur C. Clarke, Bradbury's
Martian Chronicles (1950), put the romance in space flight. It
fired the imaginations of the scientists who birthed the Space Age
only a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury's Mars stories worked because they were about people,
not machines, as noted in The Encyclopedia of Fantasy, edited by
John Clute and John Grant:
</P>
<P>
   ``The planet's habitable terrain is not scientific, and the
Earth civilization that settles it is locked into a
mid-20th-century middle-American mindset seemingly untouched by
technological advance. ... The collection succeeds marvelously as a
fantasia on the immutability of human nature, its individual
episodes being linked by recurring images of sacrifice and
loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, 50 years after Bradbury's collection, humans still haven't
walked the face of Mars, and his disappointment is palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get up there, but it's taking a long time. We should
have stayed on the moon and used it as a base and then moved on to
Mars. But most politicians in Washington have no concept of space
travel. There are very few who care about it. Now that the Cold War
is over, we don't have pressure from Russia. I wish China would
announce plans of going to Mars. That would immediately galvanize
us and we would move to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've seen a lot of good things. Landing on the moon was
the greatest event in the history of the world, and it was
wonderful to be alive when the greatest thing that ever happened
happened.''  &LR; brk:Society's growing pains
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury may think of himself as but an overgrown boy, and as an
optimist. But he emphasizes that, if we are to flourish in the
future, we must work for change.
</P>
<P>
   His grumbles range from the pedestrian to the political.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, one of his classic short stories, ``The Pedestrian,''
seems more relevant than ever, even after half a century. In that
story, a lone walker struggled against a vehicle-obsessed society
in which walking was viewed as deranged. In our world, the
omnipresence of automobiles puts pedestrians and bicyclists at an
extreme disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get in the way. You're an obstruction. Especially if
you're on a bicycle; it's very dangerous now,'' said Bradbury, a
cyclist who now only rides ``out in the desert,'' not in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got too many cars, and the driver of a car is a samurai
warrior; he expects instant obedience from everyone else. ... The
fastest we could go until a hundred years ago was on a horse. Now
the aesthetic of speed has taken over and anything that interferes
with that is an irritation.''
</P>
<P>
   As for politics, he thinks it's absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign has gone on for a year now, which is ridiculous.
We've been screaming and yelling and jumping up and down for 13
months. That's too long. Everyone would be delighted if Bush and
Gore came on TV and said, `We're not going to have any more
speeches or debates or anything for two solid months; we'll give
you a rest.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one thing he wants improved, it's America's
educational system, which he said is failing. Fortunately, he
opines, both political parties are talking a good game this year.
Now if they'll only back it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now ... we're bringing up a nation of morons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury can't help seeing the irony: Way back in Fahrenheit
451, he wrote about the dangers of censorship, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't teach reading and writing, you don't have to
have censorship. You don't have to burn books because nobody will
read them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he keeps writing, and thus believes that someone will be
around to enjoy books. He's just finishing From the Dust Returns,
which will be published for Halloween 2001.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like great fun: The main character is Timothy, who was
the rather ordinary boy in a family of supernatural creatures in
``The Homecoming,'' the first story in Bradbury's first book,
1947's Dark Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to finish it. It's taken me 55 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long time, to be sure. As Bradbury fans know, though,
he's usually worth the wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
