   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SKIN-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Skin cancer is the most common of
all cancers. Melanoma, the most serious form, accounts for 4
percent of skin cancer cases but causes 79 percent of skin cancer
deaths, according to the American Cancer Society. While the chances
of recurrence are small after a melanoma has been removed, doctors
say the case of Sen. John McCain shows that these assurances are
not always well-founded. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   POSTCARDS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Long before the digital camera and
other fast means of sending images, there were postcards. For
travelers who buy them to keep, postcards continue to be the most
popular souvenirs. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEWS-COMEDY (Undated) _ Riffs on race, on the difference
between the sexes, between blacks and whites, styles of music,
young generation and old _ all of that, if delivered with just the
right balance of irony and insight, can be hilarious. Riffs on
child abuse cannot. That about sums up the problem with ``The
Original Kings of Comedy,'' a half-hilarious, half-tiresome concert
film showcasing four piping-hot African-American comics. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LARKIN-REVIEW - Review of Patty Larkin's ``Regrooving the
Dream.'' By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-MOUNTAINS (Mount Washington State Park, N.H.) _ In the
stoic, steep White Mountains of New Hampshire, a soot-belching,
coal-fired steam locomotive has been plying Mount Washington cog by
cog since 1869. The world's first railroad to a mountaintop, the
Cog Railway still operates, taking tourists to a spectacular
summit. By BETSY DELDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-PROMOTIONS (San Francisco) _ In an ostensibly apolitical
event like the Olympics, athletes wrap themselves in flags.
Prosperous American viewers, tuning into NBC, eat that stuff up.
And if, during the festivities, they're subliminally motivated to
eat some properly accredited burgers, too, so much the better.
Those are the ideals, the allegiances promoted by the Olympics:
Sing the Star-Spangled Banner and eat whatever is being promoted.
By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The number of reports of bears
breaking into cars and stealing food is on the rise this summer at
the Yosemite National Park. But the problem isn't with bears. It's
with careless people. Given an opportunity for a cookie, bears just
can't resist the temptation. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   X-GAMES (San Francisco) _ Bicycle stunt star Dave Mirra will be
going for his 12th gold medal Tuesday in the X Games' final event.
But there's an inescapable air of inevitability right now around
the 26-year-old nicknamed ``the miracle man.'' Mirra is the only X
Games athlete to win a medal in every event he has entered. By
MICHELLE SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Affirmative action prepares
those who are disadvantaged to be able to compete with those who
are not. That is elemental fairness, the basis of the great
American ideal of equal opportunity for all. Without it, we cannot
have a just society. Anything that goes beyond that to slot
Americans on the basis of race or gender is inimical to that ideal.
By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (San Francisco) _ In this age of prosperity,
Republicans and some Democrats propose ``privatizing'' Social
Security. Privatization would allow participants to invest in the
stock market on their own, or invest in Social Security trust
funds. But such schemes raise too many questions: Who will make
investments for the Social Security Administration? How would the
government select stocks? How will gains or losses affect benefits?
By DAVID STEINBERG.
</P>
