<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-FIRESTONE-JOHNST     08-21 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-FIRESTONE-JOHNSTON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILIAR TERROR ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Monday, Aug. 21, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By MOIRA JOHNSTON    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ Will we never learn? As the Firestone tire recall
gives rise to a national storm of fear and blame, I fall into a
funk of deja vu. I've been here before, terrified by defective
products, seeing evidence of corporate callousness, and hearing the
inevitable righteous cries for change.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, I stood huddled with three terrified children and
another mother on the shoulder of Interstate 5 in California's
Central Valley, all of us shaking as we stared at a 16-inch tear in
the wall of the Firestone tire that had blown out, almost killing
us. I felt shock and rage as I learned, at the gas station we
limped to, that this tire was notorious for failing. I found later
that the accidents were often precisely like ours: a blowout in the
rear left tire of a Ford station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Galvanized by a mother's fury, I wrote a magazine article on the
Firestone 500 tire that spurred, in 1978, congressional hearings
and the largest tire recall in American history. Firestone, nearly
bankrupt, was saved with a buyout by the Japanese tiremaker
Bridgestone.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about the current case _ Firestone's recall of 6.5
million tires on Aug. 9, six months of growing complaints and
lawsuits, and a federal investigation _ makes me remember the
lessons of 1978. The Firestone 500 case taught me that too often it
takes needless deaths to rouse us to anger and make us demand
reform.
</P>
<P>
   It takes images like the tangled wreck of a Texas couple's Ford
Explorer in 1997 to force the class actions, federal investigations
and congressional hearings that lead to the recalls and repairs _
of regulations, as well as of manufacturing practices.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the lessons penetrate deeply into a corporation's
memory and conscience _ its DNA _ human frailty and expediency will
likely prevail again. Now, there are complaints that 62 deaths are
linked to failures of Firestone tires on Ford Explorers, and this
has again turned a simmering problem into a scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the 41 deaths attributed to the Firestone 500 by
government investigators were 14,000 complaints from disgruntled
tire owners, their trunks full of failed, ripped, blown 500's _
like me, alive by luck. Now, as in that scandal, drivers have
complained, and dangers were known but not acted on quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   The 500 was the product of a hidebound industry adapting
antiquated equipment and mindsets to try to catch the wave of
steel-belted radials sweeping in from Italy's technologically
superior Michelin. Firestone has had 22 years to improve the
manufacture of steel-belted tires, and today's parallels alarm me.
</P>
<P>
   I see the same corporate smokescreen, made even more dense by
the symbiotic involvement of two companies. Proof does not come to
light because confidentiality is often the condition of the
settlements that grieving families choose over the prolonged pain
of a trial, though it is in the courtroom that evidence can be
exposed and the finger of guilt pointed publicly by a jury.
</P>
<P>
   I also see the same old tire-industry culture that perpetuates
low technology, the same blame-the-consumer attitude, the same
penny-pinching prorated tire replacement policies. And, above all,
the same willingness to let cascading reports of dangerous problems
pile up. Even as Ford was replacing the suspect tires on its
Explorers in overseas markets last year, the problems were kept
from the American public.
</P>
<P>
   As Ford tries to focus the heat on Firestone, as Firestone
argues that Ford and its customers trade safety for the smoother
ride of underinflated tires, the basic issue must not be obscured:
Firestone tires are failing. The results, given the tendency of
sport utility vehicles, like the Ford Explorer, to roll over in
highway blowouts, are even more lethal than those from the
Firestone 500.
</P>
<P>
   As the machines in our lives fail more rarely, consumers have
shifted their vigilance and cries of concern to issues of communal
well-being like the health of watersheds and salmon stocks. But
there are still failures in products, too, and they must not go
unpunished, unfixed or unremembered.
</P>
<P>
   (Moira Johnston is the author of ``Spectral Evidence: The Ramona
Case'' and ``Takeover.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
