<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-DEMS-POPULISM-JU     08-21 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-DEMS-POPULISM-JUDIS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POPULIST AL GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Sunday, Aug. 20, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JOHN B. JUDIS    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does a populist appeal have resonance in prosperous
times? In his acceptance speech at the Democratic convention, Al
Gore defined the difference between Republicans and Democrats in
strict populist terms. ``They're for the powerful, we're for the
people,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   This appeal, if updated, can be effective, even when people are
doing well economically. One commentator compared Gore to William
Jennings Bryan, the firebrand of 1896, but the proper comparison is
with Franklin Delano Roosevelt. Bryan's populism was the politics
of an embattled minority, the last cry of Western small farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, Roosevelt revived populism as a majority politics
of the new urban working class. By identifying Democrats with the
common man and Republicans with the ``economic royalists,''
Roosevelt and his successors controlled Congress for 44 of the next
48 years and won eight of 12 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The constituency for Roosevelt's populism has not disappeared,
but it became bitterly divided after 1964, largely as a result of
civil rights struggles and the birth of the new left.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ronald Reagan, Republicans were able to create a new
conservative majority by combining their well-to-do base with
disenchanted white Democrats in the South and Midwest who blamed
Democrats for their falling incomes and for rising crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's political achievement has been to revive the
perception that Democrats represent the people while the
Republicans represent special interests and the wealthy. Clinton
did this by forcing Democrats to abandon the post-1960s attitude on
crime and welfare that had turned off these swing voters in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore now has an opportunity to build on what Clinton has
achieved _ to restore in full the older populist majority, but not
on exactly the same terms as Roosevelt did.
</P>
<P>
   America's ``common man'' has changed: he _ and she _ are more
likely white-collar than blue-collar and more likely to live in
suburbs than cities. And this populist majority, for the most part,
doesn't want government expansion. These voters want to preserve
existing social programs like Social Security and Medicare, and
they want new, but modest, programs to help their families thrive
in the new economy. But they are skeptical of large-scale programs
that could lead to higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   What they fear is that government will become more responsive to
the powerful rather than to them _ a fear evidenced in the
popularity of maverick politicians like Ross Perot and John McCain
and in the continuing support for campaign finance reform. Gore
seems to understand this. His acceptance speech was long on
defending his own modest initiatives against the threat of ``big
tobacco, big oil, the big polluters, the pharmaceutical companies,
the HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   His populism could also help where he needs it most, in
energizing the Democratic base and attracting swing voters in
battleground states of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   As Ruy Teixeira and Joel Rogers demonstrate in their book,
``America's Forgotten Majority,'' these swing voters don't live in
Cleveland's upscale Shaker Heights, but in neighboring Lorain
County. They are middle-income whites, most of whom have not
graduated from college. Once Democrats, they backed Reagan in 1980
and 1984, but gravitated to Clinton and Perot in 1992 and 1996.
They have proved responsive to a populism directed at special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in the Lorain County district now represented by
the Democrat Sherrod Brown, Reagan won by 19 percent in 1984. But
in 1992, Clinton won 38 percent of the vote; Bush, 35 percent; and
Perot, 27 percent. In 1996, Clinton won 46 percent; Bob Dole, 39
percent; and Perot, 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was because of the shift away from the GOP among these voters
that Clinton took Ohio and Michigan, as well as Missouri and
Pennsylvania, in the last two elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gore begins at a certain disadvantage with these voters, who may
be put off by his sometimes aloof manner. But a populist approach
could help him overcome his lack of personal appeal. He might not
convince these voters that he is a more relaxed guy than his
opponent, but if he can convince them that he is on their side and
that Bush is not, he may well be the next president.
</P>
<P>
   (John B. Judis is the author of ``The Paradox of American
Democracy.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
