<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7904 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX     08-21 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The best laid plans . . .
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ ``Come on over to the Cape,'' Gail insisted,
``and we'll have a working holiday. Mornings, I'll paint while you
write. Afternoons, we'll go to the gym. Then, it's cocktails on the
patio and evenings free to do whatever welike.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounded like a perfect plan. We should have known better.
</P>
<P>
   The first morning neither of us stirred before eight, and
breakfast beside the kitchen window took forever - birds to watch
and ideas to swap. It was after nine before we made our way to her
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing with that canoe paddle?'' I ask across the
desk my hostess has so kindly deeded over to me for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beach scene,'' she answers from the other side of her work
table. ``What areyou doing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking for my glasses. I've searched my luggage twice but no
luck.Probably left them at home beside the hammock,'' I confess.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, we call a one-hour eyeglass place over in Hyannis
that assures us all will soon be well. If I'll give them the name
of my eye doctor back in Ohio, they'll ask him to fax a copy of my
prescription. I drive over, pick out frames, and before I can say
``astigmatism'' they'll have me back among the sighted and working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds too good to be true,'' I mutter to Gail as wehead for
the car.
</P>
<P>
   It was. Nothing involving distance, electronics, and more than
two humans, is ever simple. ``Your doctor's office is closed on
Wednesday,'' the man with the pinstripe suit and too-long
fingernails informs me after we have fought 12 miles of tourist
traffic on Route 6 to get to his One-Hour Eyeglass place.
Hesuggests we try again the next day. I want to suggest he get a
manicure.
</P>
<P>
   Thwarted in an earnest attempt to work, Gail and I decide to
make the best of an otherwise wasted day by wheeling into Sam
Diego's for burritos, beans, and a margarita or two as we rethink
our game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Getting such a late start could be counter-productive, so rather
than risk it, we head for the local video store where 30 minutes
later we discover there's not a thing in the entire New Release
section that sounds the least bit Interesting. Gail says it's
because the generation gap has left us with an aversion to green
hair and machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Through a process of elimination, our only hope seems to be a
Tom Cruise thing called ``Magnolia.'' We'd much prefer something
with Redford or Newman,but we've seen all of their stuff so many
times we can recite the dialogue. That explains how we came to get
stuck with one of the worst pieces of celluloid ever to click its
way out of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It was awful watching a bunch of uglied-up folks snorting white
powder up their runny noses and living out any sensible person's
worst nightmares. And the writers, assuming there really were any,
seemed to have been so fascinatedwith their discovery of the ``F''
word they used it twice in every sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Tom, the guy we paid the bucks to see, spends the whole film in
serious need of an attitude adjustment and a shampoo. What's worse,
the whole thing makes no sense- even before it starts raining frogs
- literally. And it runs THREE HOURS with Jason Robards taking the
entire time to die.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, we're pretty sure, will be a much more creative day,
but just in case the guy with the fingernails doesn't come through,
we have an alternate plan - scratch the gym and take a boat to
Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   We'll call it research.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
