<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-JOAN-ALLEN-FAIRCHILD-     08-21 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOAN-ALLEN-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL POLITICS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients o ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By SUSAN WELSH 
 (Color art is available.) 
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    ``Sex-crazed homewrecker'' is not exactly the description that
comes to mind when one thinks of Joan Allen, an actress who has
brought sexual repression to a new level of artistry.
 &HT;    Yet in her new movie, ``The Contender,'' she portrays Sen. Laine
Hanson, a politician who is first seen in flagrante delicto on her
desk and is later accused of committing adultery with her best
friend's husband.
 &HT;    More damning still, she's said to have engaged in carnal
shenanigans that would make Monica Lewinsky look like Rebecca of
Sunnybrook Farm.
 &HT;    Early in the film, Hanson, an Ohio Democrat, is asked by the
president (played by Jeff Bridges) to take the office of vice
president after the death of the incumbent. But in a plot twist
laden with allusions to the Hill-Thomas hearings and the Clinton
scandal, her enemy, a powerful Republican congressman (Gary Oldman,
looking very unlike himself), dredges up some eye-popping sex
photos from her past.
 &HT;    Writer-director Rod Lurie began work on ``The Contender'' at the
height of the Lewinsky affair, and he wanted to comment on an
aspect of it that he thought was being overlooked.
 &HT;    ``I told my wife,'' he recalls, ''`Clinton is going to get away
with this, because he's a man, and because we don't have many
negative feelings about male sexuality. But female sexuality is a
totally different story.'''
 &HT;    For Allen, the role offered an opportunity to break the glass
ceiling that has hovered over her career. Over breakfast on a hazy,
sweltering New York morning, the willowy 45-year-old actress,
looking cool and self-possessed in a simple sleeveless black dress,
sums up the role's appeal: ``Instead of being married to the
senator, I am the senator.''
 &HT;    Despite being one of the most highly regarded actresses in
Hollywood, she has, until now, played mostly wives _ but wives who
are singularly good at hiding roiling passion beneath a placid,
controlled exterior.
 &HT;    She won Best Supporting Actress nominations for her turn as a
loyal but sexually frustrated Pat Nixon in Oliver Stone's epic
``Nixon,'' and the following year for playing a Puritan whose
bottled-up ardor drives Daniel Day-Lewis astray in ``The
Crucible.''
 &HT;    Allen's uncanny ability to convey raw emotion without emoting
may make her the ideal choice for a film that tests the somewhat
hazy American boundary between the public and the private. And as
it happens, Lurie dreamed up ``The Contender'' expressly as a
vehicle for her.
 &HT;    In 1998, when Allen won a best supporting actress award from the
L.A. Film Critics Association for playing a love-starved June
Cleaver clone in ``Pleasantville,'' Lurie, a former critic who
describes himself as ``an obsessed fan of Joan's,'' asked if he
could present it to her.
 &HT;    Extemporizing at the podium, he found himself saying, ``I should
write a movie for Joan Allen, because if Joan agrees to do it, then
it's going to be a good movie.''
 &HT;    During the dinner that followed, Allen expressed genuine
interest in the idea, and shortly afterward, Lurie began work on a
screenplay.
 &HT;    ``I had no clue what I was going to write _ not the vaguest
idea,'' he says. ``I knew that I had one mission, and that was to
write a character to which Joan Allen could not say no.''
 &HT;    Allen, who researched the role by watching tapes of Gerald
Ford's confirmation hearings and by spending time with Arkansas
Sen. Blanche Lincoln, says she connected with Laine Hanson's core
of integrity.
 &HT;    ``It's what you would like politics to be if it really worked,''
she says, while acknowledging that ``the character is not
completely lifelike.''
 &HT;    Indeed, Hanson is almost a fairy-tale liberal: She is pro-choice
and pro-campaign finance reform, wants the death penalty abolished,
thinks all guns should be confiscated and believes that selling
cigarettes to minors should be a federal offense. Oh, and she's an
avowed atheist.
 &HT;    But unlike some of her celebrity neighbors on New York's
famously liberal Upper West Side _ where she maintains a low
profile with her husband, actor Peter Friedman, and their
6-year-old daughter, Sadie _ Allen prefers to keep her own views
private.
 &HT;    ``Rod is the political animal, and I'm the actor,'' she says.
``He wrote the part that way, and I did it.'' She herself would
``never, ever, ever'' want to run for office. ``That's why it was
so fun to play a politician,'' she says, ``because it's so
antithetical to my nature.''
 &HT;    Early press screenings had Oscar-watchers buzzing about Allen's
strong shot at a statuette. Allen remains wary of the hype, but she
confesses that when the movie was picked up for distribution by
DreamWorks, her heart beat a little faster.
 &HT;    ``I knew how much they were going to back it,'' she says, ``and
I had a moment like, `God, this could really change me.' I sort of
panicked, quietly. I said to my husband, `I like to take the
subway. I like taking the bus. I'm kind of anonymous!' But I've
sort of calmed down about that now.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Susan Welsh is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
</P>
