<HEADER>
A7931 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-TIGER-WOODS-RETAIL-FA     08-21 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGER-WOODS-RETAIL-FAIRCHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GRAND SLAM SUMMER, TIGER (RE)TAILS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ANNMARIE DODD 
 From WWD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Tiger Woods has already printed his name in golf's record books;
his British Open victory made him the youngest player to complete
golf's career Grand Slam.
 &HT;    His impact on fashion, however, and the aesthetic of his
namesake Nike Golf apparel line are just starting to break out from
behind his black-and-red-on-Sundays signature.
 &HT;    Not even Nike's marketing brawn could have picked a better time
than spring 2000 to relaunch a collection in the summer Tiger won
both the U.S. and British Opens.
 &HT;    For Nike, the Tiger Woods Collection is positioned as the most
upmarket component of the company's overall $1.3 billion apparel
offerings. And like the golfer, the Tiger Woods Collection has
grown up, focusing on better-quality fabrics and more sophisticated
silhouettes and colors.
 &HT;    And for most, Tiger's accomplishments and popularity signal the
promise and reign of golf's next generation.
 &HT;    ``Tiger's impact on society and culture is phenomenal,'' said
Stuart Scott, an anchor for ESPN'S SportsCenter. ``People who don't
know about golf, and those who don't care about golf, they care and
they watch Tiger.
 &HT;    ``His attention to fashion goes with his respect for the game,''
Scott said. ``He is one of the most impeccably dressed golfers on
the tour. Even his Sunday thing, the black and loud red, has become
muted. To me, this is a sign of his maturity.''
 &HT;    Golf retailers, too, have taken careful notice. According to
Mark Sanchez, vice-president of merchandise for American Golf
Corporation, which operates 325 private and public golf facilities,
the Tiger Woods Collection will vault to one of the top three
apparel resources in AGC-operated shops by year's end.
 &HT;    Stuart Lucas, CEO of the 24-unit mall-based Golf America, is
bullish on the line.
 &HT;    ''(The Tiger Woods Collection) is so much better than it was two
years ago; Tiger is so much better than he was two years ago,''
Lucas said. ``Both things are happening at the same time and it's
super for business. He's such a dynamic personality, and he looks
fabulous in clothes.''
 &HT;    Asked how the Tiger Collection was checking, Lucas said, ``Our
stores average 1,700 square feet, so how we allocate our square
footage is very important. If you're not performing, we may take a
pass on you next season. We're not taking a pass on Nike Golf.''
 &HT;    And Woods' line from Nike isn't only for the democratic
demographic. The Tiger Woods Collection will debut next month at
the venerable Congressional Country Club in Bethesda, Md.
 &HT;    ``Our members can't stop talking about him,'' said Darcy Ryan,
Congressional's lead merchandiser. ``I believe the line is a
classic look, but it's still youthful enough to appeal to our
younger members. Before this current season, it just didn't seem
classic and traditional enough. And those are the big buzz words
around here.''
 &HT;    David Hagler, Nike Golf's director of apparel, confirmed that
one major department store group is considering adding the Tiger
Woods Collection to its golf and sportswear floor for spring 2001 _
the first sign that the department store channel may again be ready
to embrace the lifestyle sport. Also among the 500 green-grass
accounts for the collection are Pebble Beach in Monterey, Calif.,
and Doral Golf Resort and Spa in Miami.
 &HT;    So dominant is Woods that during the final round of the British
Open, he was on screen an amazing 35 percent (one hour, 22 minutes)
of the three hour, 54 minute broadcast.
 &HT;    The Nike swoosh on Tiger's hat was visible 22 percent of the
time, according to Sponsorship Research International. That kind of
television exposure, which keeps other apparel-backed PGA Tour
stars off the screen, is causing some competitive companies to
re-think sponsoring golfers.
 &HT;    Said one executive: ``It makes me wonder what our company is
getting for the money.''
 &HT;    Still, the success of Nike Golf's Tiger apparel was not a slam
dunk.
 &HT;    Originally launched as an ill-fated Nike Golf Sport line in
1997, it did not achieve widespread acceptance with either
green-grass accounts or traditional retailers. The styling was
aggressively young, an obvious effort to attract younger, hipper
golfers instead of the game's core audience.
 &HT;    Said Hagler: ``Nike has been seen as an outsider in golf; that
wasn't the best strategy for us.''
 &HT;    While golf retailers have reported a spike in sales in the Nike
golf ball that Tiger uses, measuring Tiger's impact on Nike Golf
apparel, even now, is more difficult.
 &HT;    Said American Golf's Sanchez: ``We cannot get the (Nike) Tour
Accuracy Ball in our shops quick enough. Most of that is strictly
because Tiger switched to the Nike ball. People want to try it.''
 &HT;    ``Whether or not Nike Golf is selling lots of shirts because of
Tiger is debatable,'' said Adam Barr, business reporter for the
Golf Channel, based in Orlando. ``The problem with any endorsement
is that you cannot tell how many people actually watch and then go
buy. Nike wouldn't keep going with the collection if it was
tanking. Tiger is probably having a bigger effect than we know
right now.''
 &HT;    Said Sanchez, ``Tiger has lift on the apparel side.''
 &HT;    Instead of marketing to trend-hopping teens, Nike is courting
core golfers and the game's establishment. ``My opinion is that
that makes the apparel more saleable to the average consumer,''
Sanchez said.
 &HT;    Nike Golf's Tiger Woods Collection centers around shades of
chianti, black, charcoal, azure blue, sage green and white for
spring 2001. Silhouettes include a button-front jacquard knit with
engineered stripes and an aggressive hemming detail on the shirt's
bottom and sleeves, $72 suggested retail price.
 &HT;    There's also a short-sleeved viscose/mercerized nylon V-neck
knit with contrast tipping at neck, hem and sleeves, $100 suggested
retail. Knits in Nike Golf's sportier and khaki-based Tour
Collection start at $50 suggested retail.
 &HT;    ``We are not abandoning the young customer,'' Hagler said. ``We
can appeal to them with specific pieces in the line. But the
sport's core 30-to-50-year-old players, where the bulk of the
market's money is spent, are not influenced by hero worship like
teens. We're always looking to change as much as we can, but we
want to operate from inside the game, rather than be outside.''
 &HT;    Woods meets with the design staff four times a year to review
seasonal deliveries. Hagler and design staff are scheduled to meet
with him this week to review the spring 2001 line and preview fall
2001 between rounds at the Buick Open at Warwick Hills Golf &AMP;
Country Club, Grand Blanc, Mich.
 &HT;    ``Bright red doesn't merchandise well. We learned that and
switched Tiger to a more muted tone of chianti,'' said Hagler.
``When redoing product, we went into a classics range, but at the
same time we wanted to push Tiger's line as the more
fashion-forward offering. We will look to trends going on in men's
sportswear to pick up cues where to take Tiger.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Annmarie Dodd is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
</P>
