<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-4000(     08-21 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-4000(4Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERNS ABOUT PIPELINES GROW AS MAJOR ACCIDENTS INCREASE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By NEIL STRASSMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Miller's 15-year dream of carving a piece of paradise out of
East Texas bottomland near Greenville was lost last March to
500,000 gallons of gasoline that poured across fields and down a
creek bed beside his land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole place smelled like a refinery,'' he said. ``You
could have tossed a match in the creek, and it would have caught
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the gasoline that spilled from the ruptured, underground
Explorer pipeline can be cleaned up, Miller says, the land is no
longer the rural sanctuary that his family treasured.
</P>
<P>
   Pipelines are safer than trucks, barges and tankers for shipping
oil and gas, but concerns about the aging, infrequently inspected
lines are mounting as the number of major accidents increases.
</P>
<P>
   Urban neighborhoods, ranchers and farmers have organized to
block proposed lines from passing through their land. Congress,
federal regulators and watchdog groups are moving to protect
heavily populated regions and the environment. The federal Office
of Pipeline Safety, an arm of the Transportation Department, has
been sharply criticized as ineffective and vulnerable to pipeline
industry influence.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board,
which investigates pipeline accidents, put it bluntly in a speech
last December to the Association of Oil Pipe Lines, a Washington
pipeline trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The products in your lines _ if they escape _ pollute and
kill,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten people, including five children under the age of six,
suffered a fiery death Saturday when a natural gas pipeline
exploded at the Pecos River near Carlsbad, N.M. They had been
camping and fishing on the river. The fire was so intense that sand
melted into glass and some concrete on a nearby bridge turned to
powder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three people were killed in a Jan. 14 Garland, Texas, house
explosion when natural gas leaked from a cracked 4-inch gas main in
an alley behind the house. The line had been scheduled for repair.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed or injured in the Greenville accident, but the
outcome was deadly a year ago when 250,000 gallons of gasoline
spilled from a broken pipeline in Bellingham, Wash. After a flicked
cigarette lighter sparked a fire in a gasoline-saturated creek, a
huge fireball swept downstream, killing two 10-year-old boys and a
fisherman and injuring eight others.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS A DANGER
</P>
<P>
   Texas, with 250,000 miles of pipelines, has had more accidents
in the past 15 years than any other state. State officials say that
75 percent of the accidents are a result of contractors
accidentally digging into pipelines. But when Texas adopted a
call-before-you-dig program in 1998, it was the last state in the
continental United States to do so. The program has reduced the
number of pipeline accidents nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer pipeline is well-marked in the Dallas/Fort Worth
Metroplex, but at least three times in the past 15 years it has
been damaged in construction accidents. The line runs through
Grapevine's business district, following the Cotton Belt rail line
north of Dallas Street to a tank farm in Southlake, across from the
new Grapevine High School stadium on Texas 26. The tank farm has
been a relatively safe facility with few problems.
</P>
<P>
   A branch of the pipeline then heads east, carrying jet fuel to
D/FW Airport, and another branch continues to a tank farm just
north of downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to be concerned about the line, but the city
doesn't regulate it,'' Grapevine Mayor William D. Tate said. ``When
you are moving fuel under pressure, there is always a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Sands, Explorer vice president of operations, says the
company has a good safety record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a philosophy to maintain the highest levels of safety
and integrity: If in doubt, shut down,'' he said. ``We have had
some third-party damage.''
</P>
<P>
   In Addison north of Dallas on June 19, 1985, a backhoe punctured
the line, sending a geyser of flames 100 feet into the air. Flames
seared the top of an adjacent 12-story office building, and the
fire spread underground. Neighboring shopping malls were evacuated.
One person mowing grass nearby was burned.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 1997, a half-mile north of Grapevine High School on
the Southlake side of Texas 26, a contractor struck the line with a
tree-planting machine. No one was injured and no fire broke out,
but 2,500 gallons of gasoline was spilled.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, 1999, a contractor working along William D. Tate
Avenue in Grapevine, near a half-dozen fast-food restaurants,
punctured the airport fuel line. About 4,250 gallons of jet fuel
spilled, but without causing injuries or fire.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of the largest environmental disasters to hit North
Texas in decades, the high-pressure 28-inch Explorer pipeline split
open March 9, releasing a half-million gallons of gasoline and
50,000 gallons of the toxic additive MTBE, methyl tertiary-butyl
ether. Pushed by heavy rains, the fuel washed 25 miles to Lake
Tawakoni, which supplies Dallas with as much as 220 million gallons
of drinking water a day during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the MTBE contamination of Tawakoni, Dallas water
officials waited until last week to begin using the lake again.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE GAO THROWS A PUNCH
</P>
<P>
   Explorer's line is just one of at least a dozen underground
pipelines that crisscross the Dallas/Fort Worth Metroplex, carrying
natural gas and refined petroleum products such as gasoline, diesel
and jet fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In the Metroplex, fuel is stored in tank farms, groupings of a
dozen or more large steel tanks, often painted white. The pipelines
mostly follow railroad rights of way and often pass near schools,
hospitals, businesses and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Many pipelines in the Metroplex have had breaks, most often when
construction crews dig into a line. But corrosion, operator errors
and faulty valves and gaskets are also common factors in accidents,
safety officials say. Similar problems affect nearly all U.S.
pipelines, many of which are decades old and infrequently
inspected, the officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, more than two-thirds of all pipeline accidents
resulting in fatalities and injuries are caused by breaks in
natural gas lines, according to a General Accounting Office report
released in May. The report, requested by Congress, censured the
Office of Pipeline Safety, calling it weak, inefficient and slow to
adopt reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO investigation also found that hazardous-liquid pipelines
_ which make up about 11 percent of the nation's 2.2 million miles
of pipeline _ have eight times as many major accidents per mile as
natural gas lines and account for half the property and
environmental damage caused by pipeline breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Eight bills to renew the nation's pipeline safety program have
been moving through Congress. One of those, the King and Tsiorvas
Pipeline Safety Improvement Act, sponsored by Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., is named after the two boys who were killed in the
Bellingham accident.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the bills seek additional enforcement authority for
the federal pipeline safety office. They seek tougher inspections
and better operator training and call for more investment in
accident-prevention research.
</P>
<P>
   The bills include additional measures to protect heavily
populated regions and areas especially sensitive to environmental
damage. Pipeline operators would be required to release accident
data to the public under strong community right-to-know provisions;
states could get more authority over interstate pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SPILL DROWNED DREAM
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a robust man with close-cropped graying hair, has spent
15 years preserving his 370-acre spread 20 miles downstream from
the Explorer spill. His land is home to deer, game birds and other
wildlife. He dredged a lake, stocked it with bass and catfish and
lives with his wife and two sons above his workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lifelong dream to raise my children in a natural,
unspoiled environment,'' he said, walking through a dense stand of
hardwoods along East Caddo Creek. ``We have done our best to create
an oasis in the farmland. This spill has made me sick in the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Miller distilled his own drinking water, filtering
the brown creek water until it was pure.
</P>
<P>
   Tests since the accident have found varying amounts of MTBE in
samples of the water. ``Everything we worked for is ruined,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller wants Explorer to clean the soil along the narrow,
flood-prone creek bed. After the spill, the creek overflowed and
the MTBE-laced gasoline poured across about 70 acres of his land.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE is used in a third of the country's gasoline to cut smog
and reduce toxic tailpipe emissions. The water-soluble compound has
been found to ruin lakes and groundwater and is considered a
possible carcinogen. The federal government is phasing out its use.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said it is unclear what, if anything, Explorer will do to
remove the MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stinks, actually,'' he said of Explorer's response.
</P>
<P>
   Explorer is monitoring the creek for contamination and has
removed some sediment, said Jim Sieck, the company's environmental
manager. ``He (Miller) needs to let us know what his concerns are,
and we will address them.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE PIPE, MORE PROBLEMS
</P>
<P>
   The number of major pipeline accidents _ those involving a
fatality, an injury or more than $50,000 in property damage _
jumped from 191 in 1989 to 276 a decade later, according to the GAO
report.
</P>
<P>
   In 2,241 major accidents during those 10 years, 226 people died
and 1,030 were injured, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The additional accidents are related to a 10 percent increase in
pipeline miles, more people living near pipelines, and larger
shipments of oil and gas, pipeline safety officials told the GAO.
But from 1990 to 1998, the pipeline safety office decreased its use
of fines for pipeline companies' violations of safety regulations
from 49 percent of enforcement actions to 4 percent, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Hall, the transportation safety board chairman, has sternly
criticized the pipeline office's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nowhere today the sense that the Office of Pipeline
Safety is in charge, or that its regulations, inspections, its
assets, its staffing and its spirit are adequate to the task,''
Hall said in the December speech to the pipeline association.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline safety office ``does not have a good record'' of
responding to the safety board's recommendations, he said, ``and
industry influence has a great deal to do with this.''
</P>
<P>
   The perception that industry influences the pipeline safety
office, which sets construction standards and oversees maintenance
for interstate pipelines, may be traceable to the pipeline industry
user fees that fund the agency, said Patricia Klinger, an agency
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pipeline operators pay into a fund, and people tend to
view our relationship a certain way,'' she said. ``We do have to
work with industry to inspect their pipelines and facilities, and
we have to do a cost-benefit analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency needs a larger staff, resources and enforcement
authority, Klinger said, but is responding quicker to safety board
recommendations, issuing written replies to the board within 90
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want communities and the states more involved because they
understand local concerns better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A CALL FOR ACTION
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Railroad Commissioner Tony Garza isn't eager for the
state to have more pipeline responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all we can say grace over,'' Garza said. ``We have
to be as aggressive as possible in our oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas has 150,000 miles of intrastate pipelines, 80,000 miles of
interstate lines and about 20,000 miles of production lines, far
more pipeline miles than any other state, said Mary McDaniel, the
Railroad Commission's assistant director of pipeline safety.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' 1,654 pipeline accidents since 1985 are more than three
times higher than the state with the next highest number,
California with 495 accidents. The amount of hazardous liquid
spilled in Texas is slightly more than three times the 10.5 million
gallons lost over that same period in Oklahoma, the state with the
second highest amount of spillage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Texas, the numbers can look bad, but we're
under the national average for accidents per mile,'' McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   In urban areas, most pipelines are well-marked, especially at
intersections and along rail lines. Usually, a post or piece of
colored tubing bearing the company name and a warning against
digging is planted in the ground. The warnings are important
because accidental damage is the leading cause of pipeline
accidents in the state, McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the National Pipeline Reform Coalition, a new
watchdog group, say that across the nation, pipelines must become
safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want adequate regulation, safer pipelines and fewer
fatalities and injuries. We want to stop polluting the
environment,'' said the coalition's president, Bob Rackleff, a
county commissioner in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Rules do not require replacement of aging pipelines, and except
for interstate natural gas pipelines, no federal rules govern land
use and pipeline routing decisions, Rackleff said. ``The rules are
terribly weak.''
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Pipeline Safety protects the interests of the
pipeline industry ``as a matter of policy,'' Rackleff said. The
agency inflates the role of damage from weather and geological
forces and ``third-party damage'' from unauthorized digging,
underplaying corrosion, bad valves and gaskets, material failures
and insufficient maintenance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, the Colonial Pipeline, one of the nation's largest,
has twice contaminated the Rappahanock River in the past 20 years,
each time fouling the drinking water of Fredericksburg, Va., for a
week, said City Attorney Jim Pates, a coalition member.
</P>
<P>
   ``It failed 30 miles away, and we lost the entire public water
supply for a city of 22,000 and had to haul water in,'' Pates said.
``The Office of Pipeline Safety had no interest in us, and we saw
that we were on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-inch line failed in 1980, spilling 97,000 gallons of
heating oil, and in 1989, spilling 220,000 gallons of kerosene,
Pates said.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline flaw that caused both spills still exists: The pipe
was stressed by its own weight while it was transported on
railcars, Pates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line is still defective and a threat to the city,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline industry is working hard to get an improved federal
safety program, said Ben Cooper, executive director of the
Association of Oil Pipe Lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the issues resolved,'' Cooper said. ``Our main goal is
the operation of a safe pipeline system.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING THE LONGHORN
</P>
<P>
   In south Austin and across a wide swath of Texas, residents and
ranchers are fighting a proposal to ship gasoline from Houston to
El Paso in the dormant 50-year-old Longhorn Pipeline that once
carried crude oil from West Texas oilfields to Houston. The line
crosses the Edwards Aquifer and the Colorado River, two vital water
sources, said Brigid Shea, an environmental consultant and a former
Austin City Council member.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers worry about their land and animals, Austin residents
are concerned about schools and neighborhoods, and environmental
advocates want to protect endangered species habitat, Shea said.
They are trying to force the federal government to require an
environmental impact statement, an assessment of potential damage,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line is old, and there are few safeguards,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the nearly 30-year-old Explorer line, even with more modern
safeguards, such as a coating and cathodic protection (an electric
charge put in the ground to reduce corrosion) still broke apart on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   The transportation safety board, which is investigating the
Explorer accident, has completed some metallurgical analysis on the
carbon steel pipe whose wall is slightly thicker than a
quarter-inch, said Jack Fox, the lead investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer line was last inspected in 1997, Fox said. Explorer
has inspected a 212-mile portion of the line between Greenville and
Tulsa since the March break.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chipkevich, the safety board's pipeline investigations
director, said the agency is getting company records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very early into this. We have six more months of
gathering information and testing,'' he said. ``In the past, we've
had problems associated with corrosion that are time-dependent, and
without adequate testing, some lines have failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Explorer, which has cleaned 50,000 tons of soil northwest of
Greenville and is sampling water, expects the cleanup to last
several more months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make it right, as best we can,'' said
Explorer's Sieck. ``We're going to remove every bit of soil that is
suspect. I really don't know how long it will take.''
</P>
<P>
   MTBE levels in Lake Tawakoni have dropped significantly since
the spill, well below the state MTBE taste and odor standard of 15
parts per billion. Tawakoni-area cities have been using the lake's
water for nearly two months, but Dallas only agreed to resume using
the water last week.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup has cost Explorer $6 million, plus $4.5 million to
inspect the line. Dallas has sent Explorer an initial bill for $8.3
million to cover some of the cost of a new water pipeline from Ray
Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   The repaired Explorer pipeline resumed operation March 15, six
days after the spill, carrying MTBE-laden gasoline to Chicago. As a
precautionary measure, the line is operating at 80 percent of its
normal pressure, Sieck said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellingham pipeline has not reopened since last year's fatal
fire; it's the longest pipeline closure in U.S. history, said Carl
Weimer, executive director of Safe Bellingham, a group of area
residents concerned about pipeline safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no regulation or citizen oversight that guarantees
this pipeline will be safe in the future,'' Weimer said. ``It's
more than a Bellingham issue, it's a national issue. Regulations
need to be changed to make everyone safer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
