<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-LIEBERMAN-FAITH-HNS &LR;      08-21 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-FAITH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EXPERTS SAY RELIGION WON'T KEEP LIEBERMAN FROM DOING HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By J. MICHAEL PARKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman doesn't drive a car _ or
even ride in one _ on Saturdays, the Jewish Sabbath. That would be
unnecessary work.
</P>
<P>
   But if public safety or a human life is at stake, he will work.
</P>
<P>
   During the impeachment case against President Clinton last year,
the Connecticut Democrat attended Saturday sessions of the Senate
by walking the five-mile round trip from his Georgetown house to
the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   But even with a national election at stake, Lieberman, the
Democratic nominee for vice president, won't be campaigning on
Saturdays. He once skipped a state nominating convention when it
occurred on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   He is careful to eat kosher foods. He wears a yarmulke _ a
skullcap _ whenever he prays, but only when he prays.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's choice of Lieberman as his running mate has drawn
intense nationwide interest to his religious faith and practice.
Lieberman, the first Jewish candidate on a national party ticket,
is a devout Orthodox Jew.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of living a political life within the confines of
Orthodox Judaism, with its strict adherence to the 613 laws in the
Book of Leviticus, may seem rigorous to non-Jews, but Jewish
leaders say the compromises Lieberman will face won't be overly
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Should he become vice president _ or president _ Lieberman won't
be confronted with stark choices between his faith and the national
interest, these Jewish leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   And should such a conflict emerge, none of these observers
suggested that he might be guided by the state of Israel or a
rabbi. Nor does the American public seem worried about it _ in
sharp contrast to the suspicions of many Protestants in 1928 and
1960 that Catholic presidential candidates Alfred E. Smith and John
F. Kennedy might take orders from the reigning pope. Kennedy
finessed those concerns and became president; Smith didn't and
lost.
</P>
<P>
   But many Americans do have a newfound curiosity about Orthodox
Judaism. What is it? Why does it impose so many restrictions on its
members? And what relevance does this ancient religion have in the
modern world?
</P>
<P>
   It is the most traditional, observant segment of Judaism, said
Rabbi A. James Rudin, senior interreligious affairs adviser for the
American Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   It's also by far the oldest, dating about 4,000 years to
Biblical times. Judaism's other major branches, the Reform and
Conservative movements, were born in the 19th century and have
become the major strains of American Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, most Orthodox Jews were either elderly or
were immigrants from Europe,'' Rudin said. ``It was so closely
associated with Europe, and people thought, `That's what your
grandparents are.' People thought that American culture would make
it almost impossible to survive and Orthodox Judaism was going to
die with that generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it didn't die. It's alive, and it's growing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Jews joined the movement from the inner cities to
suburbia, which meant they began to live far from their synagogues
for the first time. Many began to drive to Sabbath services,
believing it was better than not attending worship at all.
</P>
<P>
   It was during this transition that Rabbi Aryeh Scheinberg moved
from Brooklyn, N.Y., to San Antonio to become the leader of
Congregation Rodfei Sholom. Its story of survival was similar to
the national trend: moving to rejoin a congregation that was
beginning to scatter, it solidified its membership and preserved a
community of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, if I were going to worship with Orthodox
Jews, I could have worshiped in a telephone booth,'' Scheinberg
said. ``Now we have about 150 people coming every Sabbath.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to build a step at a time. In the Southwest, where
there weren't any large Jewish population centers, there were great
gaps in observance, knowledge and practice. We had to reach out
with education and be very patient. We accepted Jews of all
backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheinberg's San Antonio synagogue was deteriorating badly, and
most members already had moved well beyond walking distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see a reason to dismiss a commandment given to us by
God. We had a decision to make: Move to the suburbs where the
members live, or face having to drive to shul (the synagogue) on
the Sabbath,'' Scheinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   They moved, although it took several years. In 1991, the
congregation built a new synagogue in a quiet suburban enclave, and
today about 60 percent of its members live within walking distance.
Their closeness has given them a vitality that wasn't there 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking to shul has a tremendous salutary effect. Everyone
else is riding and we're not only walking as families but talking
with each other. It's a wonderful time out,'' Scheinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dependent on machines all week; we're beeped, called on
the phone and drive around in cars all week, but one day of the
week we become independent of all those machines.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Samuel Stahl of Temple Beth-El, a Reform congregation in
San Antonio, said Orthodoxy has gotten a bad rap in some quarters
as being ``too rigid and inflexible,'' an image that's belied by
Lieberman's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shown that it's possible to be faithfully Orthodox yet
open to change. Most rigidly observant Orthodox Jews don't really
understand the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said lifelong Orthodox Jews such as Lieberman ``represent
the best of Orthodoxy.'' They're open to working with the other
movements of Judaism, while many of those who have converted to
Orthodoxy tend to shun Reform and Conservative Jews, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of Orthodoxy is showing up in the increasing number
of Jewish schools, because they offer a sense of certainty and
transcendent truth in a chaotic, mobile, changing world, Rudin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty or 40 years ago, most American Jews wanted to be fully
American. Now we are fully American, and we don't have to give up
anything in our religious heritage to be that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said many Jews feel the need for an authoritative
expression of values, which the Torah provides, or want the strict
discipline which relieves them of the burden of having to wrestle
with too many moral decisions.
</P>
<P>
   At its most visible level, being an observant Orthodox Jew in
modern America means patronizing only kosher restaurants, asking
for kosher foods on airplanes, not playing sports or even turning
on lights or electrical appliances on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means your religious convictions really shape your life,''
Rudin said.
</P>
<P>
   But first and foremost, an observant Orthodox Jew believes the
Torah _ the first five biblical books (Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus,
Numbers and Deuteronomy) _ literally are the word of God, given to
the ancient Israelites through Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, it's immutable; it cannot be reformed or
changed, although it can be reapplied according to new realities.
For example, you don't use a cell phone on the Sabbath for purely
personal reasons, but if it's necessary to save a life, you have to
use it,'' Scheinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The commandment to protect and preserve human life is primary,
so breaking the Sabbath is not only allowed but required if a life
is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``A physician who is on call may drive his car, and a person
who's injured may ride in an ambulance on the Sabbath,'' Stahl
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Jews in the armed forces have no conflict with military duties
on the Sabbath because they're serving their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're meant to live by the laws, not to die by them,''
Scheinberg said, adding: ``Jewish religious life is practical and
workable. It's both timeless and timely. If the Torah is the word
of God, it's workable in every generation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact J. Michael Park by e-mail at
jparker(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
