<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7964 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      08-21 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOCIAL SECURITY `REFORM' WOULD HURT WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID STEINBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At 65, Social Security is old enough to be
retired, or at least privatized. That's what critics of the system
_ who don't need the benefits _ would insist.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans and Democrats in this presidential year,
altering or modifying Social Security poses political risks. Pols
know that older Americans vote. Younger citizens protest or
demonstrate rather than vote.
</P>
<P>
   Political wonks say Social Security is ``the third rail of
American politics. Don't touch it.'' When reporters asked Ronald
Reagan about Social Security in the first press conference after
his re-election, Reagan vowed he would never tamper with it.
</P>
<P>
   When Franklin Delano Roosevelt signed the Social Security Act on
Aug. 14, 1935, during the Great Depression, he said, in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, a hope of many years standing is in part fulfilled. We
can never insure 100 percent of the population against 100 percent
of the hazards and vicissitudes of life, but we have tried to frame
a law which will give some measure of protection to the average
citizen and his family . . . against poverty-ridden old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, during our continuing prosperity, Republicans and some
Democrats propose ``privatizing'' Social Security. Privatization
would allow participants to invest in the stock market on their
own, or invest in Social Security trust funds. Who will make
investments for the Social Security Administration? How would the
government select stocks? How will gains or losses affect benefits?
</P>
<P>
   In a lecture at the Institute for Health and Aging at the
University of California at San Francisco three years ago, adjunct
professor Shirley Chater, who was commissioner of Social Security
from 1993 to 1997, said that ``trust fund interest will be
sufficient to pay all benefits through 2020.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of Social Security privatization cite the system in
Chile, where workers pay 10 percent of their salary into an
individual retirement account. If they want to retire at an earlier
age, they contribute more. Coverage for survivors adds 3.5 percent
more. Health coverage costs an added 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In her lecture, Chater reported that most Chilean workers ``hire
financial consultants who charge fees of 3 percent to 5 percent to
explain the confusing options.''
</P>
<P>
   The administrative costs of Chile's privatized Social Security
system add up to around 15 percent of revenues, Chater said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government program,'' Chater noted, ``costs less than 1
percent. To put that in real numbers, the Social Security
Administration spends little more than $3 billion annually to run
the largest social insurance program in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatizing Social Security will increase the inequities and
risks,'' said Pat Ox, professor and co-director of the Institute
for Health and Aging. He cites what has happened in the United
Kingdom, where older investors were victimized by unscrupulous
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The Gerontological Society of America warns that ``older women
are as liable to be poor in 2020 as today's older women unless
Social Security reformers focus more attention on protecting
women's interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other constituency, women rely on Social
Security for the lion's share of their retirement income,'' said
Syracuse University economist Timothy M. Smeeding. ``And as a
result, women have the most to lose or gain from impending reform.
Older women living alone are at greatest risk.''
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Gerontological Society urges policymakers and
reformers to be cautious about trading the system's basic insurance
protections for a risky, insecure privatized system, adding, ``the
rewards of privatization are questionable and probably not a good
deal for most women.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gerontological Society acknowledges that Social Security
reform may be necessary, but at the same time, is concerned how
proposed reforms will affect older women.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Estes, director of the Institute for Health and Aging,
who is on sabbatical to write a book about entitlements,
participated in the Gerontological Society study. ``The challenge
and opportunity facing policymakers,'' Estes said, ``is to explore
ways to strengthen, not weaken, the national retirement system.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Steinberg is a journalist and author who contributes to
the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
