<HEADER>
A7966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-21 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EQUALITY BEGINS WITH SOUND EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It is no surprise that affirmative action was
actively discussed at the recent Democratic National Convention.
The issue has had its ups and downs over the years, but it has not
gone away because it has become a shibboleth with multiple
definitions. Today, in some quarters, it has taken on iconic
stature.
</P>
<P>
   To many black Americans it has come to stand for the minimum
infusion of fairness required to redress grievous past wrongs and
to enable minorities to partake fairly in the benefits society has
to offer, whether in jobs or education, or other aspects. This can
best be facilitated by some forms of preferential considerations
for the offended classes, providing goals for integration and
timetables for their attainment.
</P>
<P>
   Critics saw in the practical implementation of some affirmative
action programs the establishment of quotas. Quotas led to the
perception that unqualified people attained positions on the basis
of race or gender rather than ability. There was a white men's
backlash, and the call of reverse discrimination was heard
throughout the land.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some points in the dispute have been refined,
and adjustments have been made here and there in the implementation
of governmental policies, which stirred up a strong reaction among
those supporting affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Sen. Joseph Lieberman _ criticized last week for
his stated reservations about racial preference programs _ spoke
out on behalf of affirmative action, proclaiming in his speech to
the convention ``mend it, don't end it,'' without specifying what
he would alter. Vice President Al Gore evinced no reservations in
his own speech, forthrightly supporting affirmative action without
saying more about what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have disdained rigid quotas and by far the larger
national consensus opposes their imposition, as well as those of
preferences and set-asides. Quotas have come to stand in the wider
public's perception as the institutionalization of an unfairness
today to make up for historic wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   When Mario M. Cuomo was governor of New York, he issued an
executive order for affirmative action in the state work force. He
offered an eloquent rationale for the necessity for affirmative
action to level the playing field for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But he was once asked: How will we be able to tell when
affirmative action programs have worked and would no longer be
required as a remedy? As best I remember, he responded to the
question but did not answer it.
</P>
<P>
   Absent explicit or implicit quotas, how could Cuomo possibly
have answered the question put to him? Unless the races and the
genders are represented according to their numbers in all desirable
occupations and activities, how can you know that the war has been
won? And that's the abiding problem with some of the affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary and for argument's sake, why shouldn't there be
more African-American teachers than proportionality would provide?
If there were too many black teachers, that would mean that there
would be too few white. The absurdity of racial quota symmetry is
self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   My support for affirmative action is focused on making sure that
every one in America has an equal chance to compete for society's
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   My policy comprises outreach programs to recruit minorities into
occupations in which they are underrepresented because entry has
been denied them or they did not possess requisite qualifications.
Training programs have to be established to help qualify people for
the good jobs and positions _ programs that would be open to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   In that our school systems are notoriously unequal, contributing
mightily to handicapping minorities, massive efforts have to be
made, and extra funds made available, to bring those schools up to
standard levels.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the affirmative action that I support puts its efforts
into preparing those who are disadvantaged to be able to compete
with those who are not. That is elemental fairness, the basis of
the great American ideal of equal opportunity for all. Without it,
we cannot have a just society. Anything that goes beyond that to
slot Americans on the basis of race or gender is inimical to that
ideal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
