<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE FRINGE: 17,000 SHOWS IN 23 DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH _ It's New Year's Eve squared, and lasting almost a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Every August, the Scottish capital puts on no fewer than five
international festivals celebrating jazz, opera, theater, film, and
dance. But those festivals are dwarfed by the sixth: It's the
Fringe, which began as a small iconoclastic alternative to the more
formal affairs but over the last 53 years has evolved into the
world's biggest arts festival.
</P>
<P>
   In 23 days, the Fringe stages 17,000 performances of 1,350
different shows of theater, comedy, dance, and music.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Royal Mile, the city's most famous thoroughfare,
jugglers perform, a Dixieland band plays, mime artists stand
perfectly still for hours, African drummers pound out intoxicating
rhythms, unicyclists dart in and out of the crowds. It's almost
dizzying.
</P>
<P>
   There is a symphony, some would say a cacophony, of different
languages, as the Fringe attracts performers and audiences from all
over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, a young Australian walked down the Royal Mile
with a huge inflatable Godzilla on his back _ piggyback gone
monsterback. No one paid him any attention. At the Fringe, he was
more the rule, not the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Like William Wallace, the Scottish revolutionary rebel of
``Braveheart,'' the Fringe organizers are rebels who revel in their
sometimes subversive approach to art. The Fringe began in 1947 as a
protest against the staid traditional theater being staged by the
older festival.
</P>
<P>
   George Wyllie, a sculptor and performance artist, remembers
doing a show called ``Rabbie's Rocket,'' which he described as ``an
existential experiment in sending shortbread into space.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom McGrath, a playwright, said he remembers ``standing on my
head chanting `Hello Edinburgh!' then being shaved with an egg and
a rusty nail'' during one production.
</P>
<P>
   Genres come and go. In 1978, there were 39 mime shows in the
theaters and clubs. Today, the only mimes are performing on the
street for free.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Revell, a comedian, said one night he took in a Garrison
Keillor concert, then was attacked by three thugs outside a fish
and chips shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sort of the sublime height of Garrison Keillor followed by the
extras from Trainspotting,'' said Revell. ``The full gamut of the
Edinburgh experience.''
</P>
<P>
   For performers, Revell said, ``you can have a lot of fun or it
can be hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the valuable thing is being able to go somewhere for
three weeks with something where you've got a potential audience,''
he said. ``It gives you an opportunity to stretch where you are and
take a chance. If people go up there convinced of fame and fortune,
they're making a big mistake. Obviously it's nice if you get lots
of critical acclaim, but you have to have another reason for going
other than using it as your invite to the party. The opportunity
for experimentation is very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can succeed at the Fringe, you can succeed anywhere,''
said Alistair Moffat, who was the Fringe's administrator between
1976 and 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Emma Thompson got her start here, as did the comics who
would later form the Monty Python comedy troupe. Billy Connolly,
the Scottish comedian, became a star here. Robin Williams appeared
here in 1971 with a California college troupe in ``The Taming of
the Shrew.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, a similar group from Fitchburg State College put on
their version of ``The Tempest,'' and high school students from
across Maine are due to put on Shakespeare works next week.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gudgin, the Fringe's director, said this year's festival
has ``artists from Hollywood to Hong Kong and everywhere in
between.'' In the various theaters, clubs and bars are 60
children's shows, 264 comedy shows and revues, 72 dance shows, 340
musical gigs, 51 operas and musicals, 39 panel discussions, 479
stage shows, and 45 visual art exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Some are good, some are awful, some are weird and painful to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Fringe is famous for launching or reviving the careers of
comedians. Rich Hall, an alumnus of American television's
``Saturday Night Live,'' has found new fame here with his alter
ego, Otis Lee Crenshaw, a singing Tennessee jailbird. Hall's shows
are sellouts, and he is widely expected to win this year's award
for best comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Lee, who wears a Confederate flag bandanna and puts down
his Budweiser only when he plays the piano, says his family was so
poor that ``blues artists used to come to our house when they had
writer's block.''
</P>
<P>
   As Otis Lee put it, ``To call my family white trash would be an
insult to Styrofoam.''
</P>
<P>
   After his show Wednesday night, Hall signed copies of his CD,
which includes a love song about prison rape called ``He Almost
Looks Like You,'' and explained why he likes playing the Fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audiences are great, real smart. They want you to push the
envelope. They expect you to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everybody loves the Fringe. In Rutherford's, a
working-man's pub sandwiched between several of the artsy venues,
the bartender said he and his customers hate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nightmare for a month,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   But most people here seem to thrive on the buzz generated by the
Fringe and the other festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Walker, a feisty monarchist who argues with his
independence-minded customers behind the Waverly Bar he has run for
as long as the Fringe has been held, said August is magical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else in the world does a city have a party for a
month?'' asked Walker. ``You're not going to get me in one of those
weird plays, and certainly not that show where those two
Australians expose themselves. But, for the buzz, there's no place
like Edinburgh in August.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen is chief of The Boston Globe London Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
