<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-US-POWER-BOS &LR;      08-21 1571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-POWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S STATUS AS NO. 1 IS NOT ALWAYS POPULAR ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The United States is the largest exporter in the
world. It is the largest importer. It has the lowest unemployment
rate among developed nations. It is expected to have the highest
rate of economic growth in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. The US defense budget is billions bigger
than the next six largest defense spenders combined. The nation can
put a half-million men and women in the field in days to fight
halfway around the world; as a comparison, the Western Europeans
are trying to cobble together a force of 60,000 to intervene
locally for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And American movies, soft drinks, fast food, dance fads,
fashions, and even language have gone worldwide, providing the
staples of the first truly global culture.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make America's adversaries and even some of its
allies say . . . Enough!!
</P>
<P>
   For years, as the United States has reigned as the only
superpower and has enjoyed an economic expansion that now has
lasted 115 months, that ``Enough!!'' has been a whisper, uttered
privately, politely, even sheepishly. But now a Canadian writer is
issuing a full-throated scream that will be startling to American
ears _ but familiar to foreign observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of an American century extends far beyond material
production,'' writes James Laxer, professor at York University's
Atkinson College in Toronto. ``At its core is the idea that the
United States is the potent source of values and culture that have
been taken up by much of the world and that those who resist the
norms of American civilisation will do so in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Laxer's book, ``Stalking the Elephant: My Discovery of
America,'' a Viking Book distributed by Penguin Books Canada, is to
be published early next month. At its heart is Laxer's view that
``there has never been a global power like America, armed not only
with weapons that can destroy every person on the planet, but also
with a culture that has penetrated the hearts and minds of
foreigners more deeply than any culture ever has.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion, expressed somewhat more gently, is a staple of
American domestic political rhetoric at the beginning of the 21st
century. Republicans and Democrats alike cite American political,
military, and economic superiority, and last week's Democratic
National Convention here was replete with talk of the opportunities
that American power presents.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans believe, moreover, that American power is at
worst a benign, and at best a beneficial, influence around the
globe, presenting the world with a compelling example of prosperity
amid diversity, standing as a symbol of the virtues of popular rule
and remaining an obstacle to tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   But American power isn't always as popular abroad _ and many
American foreign-policy thinkers are growing worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the dominant theme we hear from every foreign leader
who has been here for the last several years,'' says Leslie H.
Gelb, who as the president of the Council on Foreign Relations
often plays host to visiting presidents and prime ministers. ``Most
of these conversations are off the record, and so they are frank.
But I cannot think of a foreign minister or prime minister who
hasn't made this kind of point.''
</P>
<P>
   This resentment has been building for several years as American
productivity, job creation, and personal income have soared. ``This
is a serious foreign-policy challenge,'' says Lee M. Hamilton, the
former chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Committee and the
director of the Washington-based Woodrow Wilson Center. ``But it's
something most Americans aren't aware of. Those who are aware of it
don't like to talk about it. And the solutions aren't easy for a
country that wants to assert its own interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern is gradually penetrating the walls of Capitol Hill.
``This is a very dangerous situation,'' says Senator John F. Kerry,
a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. ``We need to
bend over backward to find new ways to reach out to the world that
counter this remarkable abundance we have. We need to be more open
and overreaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry believes the United States should consider providing more
technical assistance abroad, taking a more aggressive approach
toward alleviating the debts held by developing nations and dealing
with what he calls ``the huge agenda that is inviting a tremendous
backlash even among our best allies.''
</P>
<P>
   This comes at a time when the nation is contemplating the
deployment of a missile-defense system and when Americans are
increasingly skeptical that the United States should be playing a
prominent role internationally.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, in the middle of the Cold War, in the heydey of foreign
aid and at the beginning of the Vietnam buildup, only 18 percent of
Americans said they believed the United States should mind its own
business internationally and let other countries get along the best
they can on their own, according to the Gallup Organization. When
the Pew Research Center asked the same question in its own survey
last year, the figure had nearly doubled, to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Democrats who gathered here last week for their
quadrennial political convention expressed worries that the new
American determination to deploy a national missile defense would
only reinforce the resentment of other leaders and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   A US intelligence report leaked to The New York Times this month
said that if the nation does move forward with a missile defense,
China and Russia would respond. But it isn't only the nation's
rivals that are wary. American allies are also unsettled by the
notion of a missile defense. And experts on both sides of the
missile-defense question are troubled by efforts to deploy
so-called Star Wars technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dramatic example of the United States not caring
about what others think _ or even about treaties we don't want to
keep anymore,'' says Representative Martin F. Meehan, a Lowell
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Resenting American power and prosperity is not a new phenomenon,
of course. Simon Bolivar, who liberated much of Latin America from
Spanish rule, once complained that ``the United States seems
destined by providence to plague Latin America with misery in the
name of liberty.'' Nearly two centuries later, Canadian Prime
Minister Pierre Elliot Trudeau, in a remark that would provide
Laxer with the title of his book, would say: ``Living next door to
you is in some ways like sleeping with an elephant. No matter how
friendly or even-tempered is the beast, if I can call it that, one
is affected by every twitch and grunt.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other periods of world history dominated by one
nation with overwhelming power, other countries are not forming
alliances to offer a balance.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the 16th century, at the height of the Golden
Age of Spain, the French, Turks, and some of the German
principalities formed an unlikely alliance to oppose the emperor
Charles V. In the 17th century, when the Dutch were strong, the
English and French moved together to blunt the Dutch influence. The
19th century brought several shifting alliances, one of the most
colorful being the Dreikaiserbund, the loose alliance between
Germany, Austria-Hungary, and Russia to counter the power of
France.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like that is occurring now.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors reinforce the power of American influence in the
21st century. The first is the nature of the economic prosperity
that the nation has enjoyed in recent years; it was fueled by high
technology, a form of industrial (or, some analysts say,
post-industrial) power that does not respect national boundaries.
The second is the collapse of the Soviet Union and of the communist
bloc; now no political adversaries block the advance of American
culture or corporate influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without ideological adversaries _ those who actually threaten
its way of life _ American capitalism has lost all its
defensiveness,'' Laxer writes. ``It is fully itself again, as it
has not been since the 1920s. There is an unselfconsciousness today
in the American insistence that the unabashed individual pursuit of
great wealth is the engine that drives humanity forward to an ever
more materially prosperous future.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that the American influence is bad. ``There
is an acceptance of American power now, but more: a reliance on
American power,'' says Lawrence Goldman, an Oxford University
historian and a longtime student of American culture and politics.
``We depend on the American guarantee. There is almost a sense of
satisfaction that we can count on the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But being on top places the United States in the awkward place
of being in the middle _ between those who would like less American
engagement and those who would like more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what we have to offer is actually quite welcome and
attractive,'' says Richard N. Haass, who was special assistant for
foreign affairs to President George H.W. Bush. ``And this is
impossible to get just right. Some people might resent American
unilateralism. But they would be the same people to speak up if the
United States suddenly didn't show strong leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David M. Shribman is chief of The Boston Globe Washington Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
