<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MUSIC-CROSBY-BOS &LR;      08-21 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MUSIC-CROSBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING WHEN IT WAS ROCK FOR CAUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year is the 15th anniversary of Live Aid and the 10th
anniversary of Amnesty International's ``Human Rights Now!'' tour.
These events have largely gone unnoticed by a media obsessed with
Christina Aguilera's navel and 'N Sync's dance moves, but they form
the backbone of an ambitious four-hour documentary about musical
activists and their causes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Stand and Be Counted'' documentary, produced by rocker
David Crosby and adapted from his book of the same name, debuts on
the Learning Channel Monday night and Tuesday from 9 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gripping journey from the civil rights movement
(featuring comments by Joan Baez) through George Harrison's concert
for Bangladesh (1971), the No Nukes benefits (1979), the first
Amnesty International Secret Policeman's Ball (1980), then Live Aid
and Farm Aid, and on to the Beastie Boys' Tibetan Freedom Concerts
in the late '90s and the recent Jubilee 2000 movement (spearheaded
by U2's Bono) to cancel Third World debt.
</P>
<P>
   The performance footage is powerful, the artist interviews are
often poignant, and the consistently selfless tone makes this an
essential unsensationalized viewing experience for people who still
feel that music can matter and not be a prefabricated MTV product.
</P>
<P>
   As Crosby says, introducing the program, ``Nothing blows up, no
one takes their clothes off, and there are no car crashes. But it
shows courage, a depth of character, and a generosity of spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The editing is a bit choppy (too much jump-cutting from one
concert to another), but there's a laudable attempt at covering a
wide variety of issues. Crosby, who spent four years gathering film
footage and interviews, covers topics ranging from Native American
persecution (Buffy Sainte-Marie is shown singing ``Bury My Heart at
Wounded Knee'') to Don Henley's fund-raising for the preservation
of Walden Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary goes to great length to establish historical
links among Henry David Thoreau and the social leaders who read his
work (including Mahatma Gandhi and Martin Luther King Jr.) and the
artists who were also energized by his writings about nature and
passive resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s generation is given ample air time, but so are younger
activists such as Adam Yauch of the Beasties and Michael Stipe of
R.E.M. As comedian Robin Williams says in the show: ``There was a
time when people were very worried that (the younger generation)
was not going to kick in. But these people are doing as much work,
if not more.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's debatable in the new Me Generation of music
celebrities, but some of the more established artists are here to
remind them that music, ultimately, should serve a higher purpose
than fame and riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is selling records the end of all existence? I don't think
so,'' says Bonnie Raitt. ``Not to mention that we get
overcompensated. . . . We owe it to give the money back and spread
it around.''
</P>
<P>
   As Carlos Santana adds, ``It doesn't matter how many zeroes you
got on your check. You still don't have the `one,' you know. That
`one' is when you know in your heart you're doing something that
benefits life and people on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Santana goes on to challenge the cynicism that set in after the
Bangladesh concert when it was revealed that most of the money
never made it to the starving people for which it was intended.
``It doesn't mean we should be cynical,'' he says. ``It means we
should do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Such idealism is a reminder of the music industry's most noble
sentiments. Many of the artists also get extremely emotional when
talking about their causes. Harry Belafonte recalls how he ``didn't
understand black indifference to what was going on in Africa''
during the Ethiopian famine that led to Live Aid. ``So I took the
question to artists on a moral basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Sting gets choked up when remembering his show in Santiago,
Chile to support mothers whose sons had ``disappeared'' due to the
military junta's death squads. On the song ``They Dance Alone,''
Sting is shown dancing with some of the mothers. He describes it as
``probably the greatest, most powerful moment of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention is also paid to lesser-known activists such as Victor
Jara (the Chilean folk singer whose fingers and tongue were cut off
by the military to silence him) and Sarajevan cellist Vedran
Smailovic who, in the spring of 1992, played for 22 straight days
outside a bakery where 22 civilians _ including his brother and
neighbors _ had been killed by mortar fire. More shells fell around
him as he performed _ and a camera captured it for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the musical footage is superb _ Eric Clapton performing
``Layla'' at Live Aid in Philadelphia, Peter Gabriel singing ``In
Your Eyes'' at an Amnesty benefit in Buenos Aires, George Harrison
doing ``Bangladesh'' in New York, Rage Against the Machine ripping
through ``Bulls on Parade'' at the Tibetan Freedom Concert in
Washington, D.C., Radiohead playing an Amnesty show in Paris, and
Bono and Daniel Lanois doing U2's ``One'' at the Lincoln Memorial
to support Jubilee 2000 (with President Clinton in attendance).
</P>
<P>
   Sting offers an acoustic ``Message in a Bottle'' at the Secret
Policemen's Ball in London in 1980; and Bruce Springteen, Sting,
Gabriel, Tracy Chapman, and Youssou N'Dour join for Bob Dylan's
``The Times They Are A-Changin'' during Amnesty's Human Rights Now!
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier protest songwriters such as Woody Guthrie and Phil Ochs
are also covered in this documentary. As Jackson Browne says in
summary, ``There are a lot of people who don't want to know about
political things _ and that's fine. They have a right to feel that
way. But I would never let that stop me from talking about what is
happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
