<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Lost Legends of New Jersey'' by Frederick Reiken
(Harcourt, $24). A coming-of-age novel, set against the backdrop of
the much-maligned Garden State.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Mass'' by Dick Lehr and Gerard O'Neill (Public Affairs,
$26). Two Globe reporters untwist the story of how the FBI and
Boston's leading Irish mobsters came to serve each other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Royal Family'' by William T. Vollmann (Viking, $40). A
sprawling novel set in San Francisco's wealthiest and sleaziest
demimondes, combining writerly dazzle with elemental humanity.
</P>
</TEXT>
