<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      08-21 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
!! 1/2 ``The Cell'' It spends most of its time trying to live up to
its dazzling visuals, including a series of brilliantly surreal
landscapes of the imagination. Jennifer Lopez (who revels in more
costume changes than any therapist in film history) is a psychic
researcher who rides a mind-control device into the dark recesses
of serial killer Vincent D'Onofrio's brain to rescue one of his
victims. There isn't enough story to go with the striking decor,
but the film does cover its hallucinatory bases. (R) 
 
!!! ``Girl on the Bridge'' For a while, it connects us magically to
the tradition of European film at its most intoxicatingly romantic.
A washed-up carnival knife-thrower (Daniel Auteuil) finds new life
for his act after talking a would-be suicide (Vanessa Paradis) into
becoming the target for his sexually symbolic daggers, and the two
click. The film's inspiration level vanishes like a gambler's
charmed streak about two-thirds of the way through. Still, when
it's on, it's really on. (R) 
 
(FR) !!! ``Godzilla 2000'' This latest saga about the big
radioactive lizard proves that you can take the boy out of Tokyo,
but you can't take Tokyo out of the boy. He's back in all his
cheesy glory, complete with badly dubbed dialogue, dragon breath,
the all-important guy-in-the-rubber-suit look, and the
indispensable stomp-out-a-scale-model-of-Tokyo finale. (PG)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``I'm the One That I Want'' Stand-up comic Maggie Cho was
traumatized when TV execs cast her in what was to have been the
first network sitcom about an Asian-American, then canceled the
show for (in their words) not being ethnic enough. Fully recovered,
she comments on this and other absurdities with rude, freeing,
wickedly honed yet ultimately big-hearted wit in this triumphant
capturing of her one-woman stage hit. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!!! ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' The laughs just keep coming
in Spike Lee's concert film of comedy's biggest touring act. Not
since the glory days of Richard Pryor and Eddie Murphy have we had
such a screenful of raucous, sharp-eyed, liberating comedy. Steve
Harvey, D. L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer, and Bernie Mac put
the black back in black comedy _ and Lee's unobtrusively brilliant
camerawork captures the audience chemistry, too. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
