<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7982 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-CULTURE-BOS &LR;      08-21 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTIONS BETWEEN ECONOMICS, CULTURE GET A WORKING OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CULTURE MATTERS 
How Values Shape Human Progress 
Edited by Lawrence E. Harrison and Samuel P. Huntington. Basic
Books. 348 pp. $35. 
 
THE TWILIGHT OF AMERICAN CULTURE 
By Morris Berman. Norton. 205 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Know why in a certain cannibalistic foreign country economists'
brains go for $2.39 a pound but anthropologists' cost $15? The
answer is the only punchline in ``Culture Matters: How Values Shape
Human Progress,'' because that's the only joke in this serious,
challenging, and ultimately enlightening book exploring why there
are haves and have-nots in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In 22 chapters, various scholars and authors debate whether the
cultural aspects of a people make a difference in their level of
economic development. But chapters with titles like ``Cultures
Count'' and ``Why Culture Matters,'' as well as the book's title
itself, give away the overwhelming conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are a few dissenters _ Jeffrey Sachs with an ``it's
inconclusive'' view, and a couple of anthropologists who still
cavil at drawing any conclusions based on a population's values,
for fear of an odor of racism _ the vast majority of contributors
agree cultural values shape futures. They're just now sure how much
_ in relation to political or geographic factors, for example _ or
how at all to determine cause and effect.
</P>
<P>
   As co-editor Lawrence E. Harrison, of Harvard University's
Academy for International and Area Studies, notes up front,
increasing numbers of those who study the jaggedly uneven
development patterns worldwide are following paths forged by Alexis
de Tocqueville, who saw American culture as particularly friendly
to democracy; Max Weber, who put religion at the root of
capitalism; and Edward Banfield, who studied poverty and
authoritarianism in southern Italy and contrasted that region with
the more prosperous north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Culture Matters'' could be a valuable textbook, though its
individual chapters are for the most part easily digestible and
even entertaining, only occasionally dense. In an apparent gesture
to political correctness, a couple of chapters on women were
included, one not by an academic but by a journalist, and they seem
a bit off the topic. A section on anthropology _ apparently there
for diversity's sake, because anthropologists are the skeptics on
this topic _ is also uneven. One scholar argues weakly that
parenting practices are not to blame for low achievement. Yet the
University of Chicago's Richard A. Shweder offers a lively and
inviting rebuttal to others' arguments (it's his joke, above;
punchline found in Chapter 12) and provocatively notes that
developed countries where abortion is prevalent should be placed in
the most child-unfriendly group on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The other co-editor, Harvard professor Samuel P. Huntington,
notes that this book and a 1999 symposium called the Cultural
Values and Human Progress project were largely the work of
Harrison. Harrison's overview sets the world stage, as it were:
Only 1 billion of our 6 billion fellow men and women live in
advanced democracies, and 4 billion live in what are classified as
lower-middle-income countries or worse.
</P>
<P>
   George Mason University professor Francis Fukuyama, while
emphasizing the importance of virtues like truth-telling and
meeting one's obligations in building a successful society,
acknowledges that really understanding the relationship between
values and progress, ``providing an empirical map of the sources of
actual cultural rules, is a project for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   No solutions are contained herein. Nevertheless, a lot is agreed
on.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Grondona, a Buenos Aires journalist-professor-author,
identifies 20 ``cultural factors'' that determine where a nation
will rank. They include religion, ``lesser virtues'' like tidiness
and respect, how people view time and dissenting opinions, their
level of general optimism, and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Other authors prefer six or 10 identifying cultural measures,
but the point is the same: Traditional values and habits determine,
at least heavily influence, outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Generalities abound, though there are enough exceptions that
scholars still have plenty to fight about. Almost all advanced
democracies are in temperate zones, most poor ones in the tropics.
But Singapore and Hong Kong are in tropical zones, so perhaps
Confucian influence does have a positive effect. What explains the
differences between Guatemala and, say, Costa Rica, or between
Haiti and Barbados? Why do Chinese and Japanese minorities excel in
otherwise poor communities? Why do Islamic countries lag behind in
North Africa and the Mideast?
</P>
<P>
   David S. Landes, an economic historian at Harvard, says the
values that pay off ``may sound like a collection of cliches _ the
sort of lessons one used to learn at home and in school when
parents and teachers thought they had a mission to rear and elevate
their children. Today, we condescend to such verities, dismiss them
as platitudes. But why should wisdom be obsolete?''
</P>
<P>
   He strikes on a point that could have been made even more
forcefully: If economics were not so shoddily taught, little
respected, and widely misunderstood, there probably would not be as
much of a debate about culture, and about politics for that matter.
As Landes puts it, a ``zero-sum worldview is central to the theory
of a universal peasant culture.''
</P>
<P>
   A wickedly refreshing, slashingly honest assessment of Latin
America and its elite groups is offered by Carlos Alberto Montaner,
identified in the book as ``the most widely read columnist in the
Spanish language.'' He may want to hide out for a while, after
identifying ``politicians, the military, businessmen, clergy,
intellectuals, and leftist groups'' as being overwhelmingly
responsible for poverty and injustice on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   And Daniel Etounga-Manguelle, Cameroon-born head of a
development institute, does sort of the same thing for Africa,
suggesting that, rather than another economic adjustment plan, the
continent may need a cultural adjustment program.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Orlando Patterson has a clear and sensible critique of
some of the current, foggy thinking on the subject. ``The liberal
mantra, still frequently chanted, that cultural explanations amount
to blaming the victim,'' he says, ``is sheer nonsense.'' In fact,
Patterson proposes that cultural factors, affecting children from
the instant of birth, can even explain the controversial findings
of Herrnstein and Murray's ``The Bell Curve,'' which found that
intelligence varies among races.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Glazer, professor emeritus of education and sociology at
Harvard, reviews the ups and downs that cultural explanations have
had as useful measures of people's ability to prosper, but he's
cautious. As is Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lucian W.
Pye, who says: ``We are dealing with clouds, not clocks, with
general approximations, not precise cause-and-effect
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morris Berman's ``The Twilight of American Culture'' has
something in common with ``Culture Matters'': They both use that
seven-letter word in the title. Similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know whether Berman, who teaches part time at Johns
Hopkins University, is serious in this brief screed on how stupid
he thinks Americans have become (alas, people riding buses aren't
reading books). My grandfather, back in the 1950s, used to say,
``The country's going to hell in a handbasket,'' and that just
about sums up Berman's view.
</P>
<P>
   Except that, utopian at heart, he blames commercialism and
corporate culture for ruining a great country. And he proposes what
at first appears to be a bizarre remedy: We all become monks and
ignore the poisonous influences around us.
</P>
<P>
   Only toward the end do we find out that Berman is really just
talking about thinking independently, being true to your own
beliefs, and the kinds of things that he suggests only he and a
handful of others do _ but that in fact more millions of Americans
practice daily than he knows.
</P>
<P>
   This grumpy baby boomer lives in Washington, D.C., and he
listens to a lot of National Public Radio. His heroes are Lewis
Lapham of Harper's magazine, perhaps the nation's premier cynic;
author Don DeLillo; and lefty filmmaker Michael Moore _ though at
least he eschews political correctness and has no use for France's
Jacques Derrida. Excerpt: ``The whole statist configuration of
hierarchy, specialization, and bureaucracy emerged fairly recently
_ about six thousand years ago _ and has to be constantly
reinforced and legitimized.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of amusing thoughts on science fiction and
the history of technology amid the gloomy predictions. But just
when it seems Berman might want to literally blow it all up, you
find him saying, ``Before I start to sound like the Unabomber, . .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Oops, too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-CANDIDATES-BOS &LR;      08-21 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-CANDIDATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING POLITICS WITH THE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intent on stressing substantive differences with George W. Bush,
Bill Clinton told cheering Democratic convention delegates last
week that this was a ``big election'' because the chasm between
candidates is ``so profound.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet on one hot-button issue, many observers say the two sides
are in virtual lockstep. With three major combatants in the
nation's culture wars closely tied to the race, the assault on sex,
violence, and sensationalism in the entertainment industry is now
very much a bipartisan venture.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady hopeful Tipper Gore gained fame _ and infamy in
certain quarters _ for leading the battle for warning labels on
music. Lynne Cheney, wife of the GOP vice-presidential nominee, is
a former head of the National Endowment for the Humanities who
waged ideological combat against what she viewed as pervasive
political correctness in the arts and culture.
</P>
<P>
   It was, however, Al Gore's selection of running mate Joseph
Lieberman _ a tireless cultural warrior who has teamed with social
conservatives like William Bennett in targeting everyone from shock
jock Howard Stern to ``gangsta'' rappers _ that is the clearest
signal yet that Hollywood is an awfully inviting target.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great achievement or great failure of the Democratic
Leadership Council . . . is that they're trying very hard to
co-opt, in part, the Republicans on the culture war,'' says Wendy
Kaminer, a fellow at the Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study.
``I think for many people who are running for office, declaring
their disdain for sex and violence in the media . . . is like
saluting the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert O`Neil, the former University of Virginia president who
heads the Thomas Jefferson Center for the Protection of Free
Expression, thinks the political zeitgeist is ripe for targeting
movies, video games, TV, and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have expected that these would have been major issues
regardless of who the nominees of the major parties were,'' he
says. ``This is a time to blame national ills of various sorts on
media and entertainment, partly because there are no other easy
scapegoats and (because of) high anxiety these days about new
media.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Political punching bag &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although there is broad consensus that parents need to monitor
their children's exposure to Internet porn, misogynistic music, and
big-screen bloodlettings, some First Amendment advocates are very
uneasy about entertainment's emerging role as a political punching
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``These censorship crusades are quite cyclical,'' says Marjorie
Heins, who heads the Free Expression Policy Project for the
National Coalition Against Censorship. ``There may be some
differences ideologically in terms of what Lynne Cheney would want
to censor and what Al and Tipper Gore want to censor. But I'm not
aware of any significant differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who spent time as the combative conservative on CNN's
``Crossfire,'' was once called ``the leading policy assassin for
the right-wing culture warriors,'' by the liberal The American
Prospect magazine. At the National Endowment for the Humanities,
she got into flaps over several projects that she felt gave short
shrift to the virtues of Western civilization, earning a reputation
among critics for politicizing the agency and the arts.
</P>
<P>
   In a piece that appeared in The Wall Street Journal in 1995,
Cheney called for withdrawing government funding for the NEH and
the National Endowment for the Arts, writing that ``the American
people deserve to understand . . . why their money supports artists
who submerge a crucifix in urine and hang out in morgues.'' She was
also one of many signers of a highly publicized ``Appeal to
Hollywood'' asking that entertainment producers ``establish certain
minimum standards for violent, sexual, and degrading material for
each medium, below which producers can be expected not to go.''
</P>
<P>
   According to news accounts, Tipper Gore joined the fight over
entertainment standards in the mid-'80s after being outraged by
some blatantly sexual lyrics in a Prince song. The founder of the
Parents Music Resource Center, Gore is best known for parental
advisories that warn of music not intended for tender ears.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Raising PG Kids in an X-Rated Society,'' Gore's
crusade made her a lightning rod and in one oft-publicized remark,
Frank Zappa called her a ``cultural terrorist.'' Today, some of her
critics think more kindly of Tipper's labeling campaign, but she
remains a powerful symbol of a bruising cultural skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Lieberman who has compiled the most extensive record
and rhetoric on the subject, pushing for the V-chip TV filtering
device and rating systems for violent video games and asking the
FCC to examine broadcast television's ``increasingly salacious
content.'' With the Media Research Center, a conservative watchdog
group that has targeted TV shows from ``WWF Smackdown'' to
``Dawson's Creek'' for excessive violence and sex, he has lobbied
the networks to restablish ``the family hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Also a signatory to the ``Appeal to Hollywood,'' Lieberman has
joined Bennett to dispense ``Silver Sewer'' awards to ostracize
such cultural polluters as Howard Stern, Marilyn Manson, and Jerry
Springer. In a 1999 column for The New York Times he coauthored
with Senator John McCain, Lieberman railed against ``the
entertainment media's romanticized and sanitized version of
violence'' that is part of ``the toxic mix that's turning too many
of our kids into killers'' and asked the industry to develop
``comprehensive codes of conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the traditional coziness between Democrats and Hollywood
_ as evidenced by the parade of such stars as Barbara Streisand and
Warren Beatty at last week's convention _ some observers are not
surprised that their ticket would so eagerly embrace the
traditionally Republican family values platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore had really invented the Internet, there would have
been a V-chip,'' says Kaminer. ``I don't see Al Gore as a friend of
the First Amendment, especially when it comes to sex and violence
in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN senior analyst William Schneider singles out baby boomers as
a crucial bloc in the campaign. Hoping that their own sex, drugs,
and rock 'n' roll days will not be visited on their children, they
are nervous parents and swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign's been all about values and religion,'' says
Nina Crowley, executive director of Mass M.I.C., an organization
dedicated to free expression in music. ``I think it's a real vote
getter. I think there are so many parents out there who are afraid
their kids are going to get shot at school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every election is about the incumbent,'' says Schneider,
offering another theory. ``Bill Clinton's distinction is that he is
the first president to come out of the culture of the '60s _ the
Elvis-loving, womanizing, non-inhaling president,'' he says. ``For
the Democrats at least,'' beating up on the dregs of pop culture is
``an effort to evade the Clinton problem. It's de-Clintonization.''
</P>
<P>
   Some free speech experts say it's also a way to encourage debate
about a legitimate issue: the entertainment industry's eagerness to
churn out smut and slime because of the simple fact that they
sell. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Noise ``oils democracy'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment does not immunize the media from
criticism,'' says Fred Schauer, the Frank Stanton Professor of the
First Amendment at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. ``Given
the enormous pervasiveness of the mass media in all forms, I cringe
even more when this huge segment of the world we occupy is not
subject to public discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is effective to make noise,'' adds Peggy Charren, the
founder of Action For Children's Television. ``Noise is what oils
the democracy. The important thing is . . . just make sure the
government isn't there with a stick.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the relatively short leap from what Schauer calls the
``critics'' to the ``policymakers'' that worries the entertainment
world. Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, calls Lieberman ``a very good friend'' and ``a wonderful
man,'' but warns that if he ``is suggesting that the government be
involved'' in regulating movies, ``he is on a very dangerous
path.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, The Thomas Jefferson Center gave Lieberman a ``Muzzle''
award for abridging free speech because he threatened legislative
action to get some networks to broadcast rating codes. It's the
mixing of persuasion and muscle that Heins views as both dangerous
and disingenous on the part of public officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not just jawboning,'' but using ``this bully pulpit to
try and impose coercion,'' she warns. ``The legislation keeps
coming. Real censorship does happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
