<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINING UP FOR `ROADSHOW' RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hummels are a joke among the experts on ``Chubb's Antiques
Roadshow.'' The cute collectible figurines may be lovable, but
they're not worth much. And there are so many of them. ``Roadshow''
appraisers get tired of being asked to examine them.
</P>
<P>
   But there are exceptional Hummels, and appraiser Gary Sohmers
knew he was looking at one Saturday, during the ``Roadshow's''
daylong appraisal marathon in Boston. This was not your average
Hummel, he said, but a ``very, very limited edition'' figure of an
F-84 jet airplane, all the more unusual for being ``very male.''
</P>
<P>
   Sohmers, of WexRex Collectibles in Framingham, Mass., estimated
the macho Hummel's worth at between $2,000 and $3,000. He and its
owner, an Air Force veteran, were taped chatting about the item in
a segment that may air in one of two Boston episodes of
``Roadshow'' scheduled for January.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Roadshow'' is PBS's highest-rated prime-time program.
Saturday's event drew 7,000 people who came carrying all sorts of
treasures (and trash) by hand, as well as by baby carriage, grocery
cart, dolly, pet carrier, luggage, Radio Flyer, and wheelbarrow.
Tickets, distributed free early last month, were marked with
appointed times. Every 90 minutes volunteers herded a fresh group
into line to wait their turn. The lines moved quickly. The waiting
area was air-conditioned. There was a place to buy drinks and
snacks. The room was full of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Generalist appraisers took a quick look at people's items and
handed out tickets marked `furniture'' or ``jewelry'' or one of two
dozen other categories. Volunteers then escorted people into the
appraisal area and directed them to one of the specialty appraisal
tables set up around the perimeter. In the middle of the room, crew
members moved about taping interviews with those who'd brought
items deemed ``Roadshow''-worthy, while volunteers attempted to
keep everybody else out of camera range.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name is Fred,'' said Troy (reporters covering ``Roadshow''
events are asked not to use participants' last names or hometowns),
who was carting a nearly life-size bronze casting of Pheidippides _
the first, but not the last, person to collapse after running a
marathon. ``Fred'' was appraised at $20,000 to $30,000. However,
Troy was taped for the show because of a box of toys he'd brought
along, plastic figures from the 1940s, of the Lone Ranger, Tonto,
General Custer, Wyatt Earp, and others. Appraiser Leila Dunbar of
Sotheby's said the toy company reissued the figures just last year,
which meant that the value of originals such as Troy's dropped from
$250 each to $150. Dunbar said it was a good example of how
reissues can affect the collectibles market.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the appraisal area Leigh and Leslie Keno looked
at furniture and held court for admirers, including Anthony, 15,
who shyly asked each twin brother for his autograph. He said he had
been eager to attend the event to learn more about antiques. He was
clearly thrilled to be in the presence of so many well-known
appraisers, especially the charismatic Kenos, ``Roadshow's''
fair-haired stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to see them on the show,'' said Pamela, a 40-ish woman
who was waiting for one of the Kenos to appraise a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so enthusiastic,'' her sister, Evelyn, added.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sisters' turn to be enthusiastic when Leslie Keno
said their cherrywood chair was made in Rhode Island around 1780,
and that the set of six chairs might fetch $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on there were more than enough valuable items
and stories to keep the appraisers interested and the
``Roadshow's'' producers happy. Most participants seemed pleased
too, if only to be part of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there were many who were disappointed, but some
managed to laugh about it. Book appraiser Ken Gloss of the Brattle
Book Shop in Boston examined a small leather-bound book and broke
the bad news to its owner. ``These are very common,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, don't tell me that,'' she said. ``I told my friends we
were going home in a limo.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
