<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEAMSTERS-GOP-BOS &LR;      08-21 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTER HEAD'S TIE TO GOP RUNS DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN AND SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Teamsters official under fire for his local's
hard-nosed tactics became the dominant figure in negotiating labor
contracts with Hollywood studios in part through an alliance he
forged with the Weld-Cellucci administration.
</P>
<P>
   Recent interviews and documents released by the administration
of Governor Paul Cellucci on Friday show that the state in mid-1993
acquiesced in giving George W. Cashman's Local 25 sole authority to
negotiate with the studios and filmmakers who were planning to
shoot movies in Massachusetts and needed drivers for their sets.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Weld-Cellucci administration was moving to
back Cashman's effort to have a Hollywood-style sound studio built
with state funds on the campus of Bunker Hill Community College,
less than a mile away from Local 25's headquarters in Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the administration appropriated $150,000 to a private
firm headed by Cashman to pay for a study of the feasibility of
establishing a sound studio in Massachusetts. Although the study by
Arthur D. Little Inc., a Cambridge consulting firm, raised
questions about the economic viability of the facility, the
administration went ahead the next year and approved a $13.5
million bond issue to finance the construction.
</P>
<P>
   The sound studio still has not been built, but the backing of
Cashman's request _ while it was killing a proposal for a similar
facility to be built with private funds _ indicates that the
administration was building an alliance with Cashman.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cashman was appointed by then-governor William
F. Weld to a seat on the Massachusetts Port Authority's board of
directors. According to sources, the administration had previously
offered the job to another Teamsters official. However, that
official turned it down when he was told he would be expected to
vote for Stephen Tocco _ then head of the state Office of Economic
Affairs, and widely regarded as having an anti-labor record _ as
executive director of Massport.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of being named to the Massport board in July 1993,
Cashman was voting with other Weld board members to appoint Tocco
to the job and to fire five appointees of then-governor Michael
Dukakis from their positions at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Those political ties, which resulted in Cellucci gaining Local
25's endorsement for governor in 1998, have made Massachusetts
unusual among states with unionized labor seeking to attract
filmmakers. Here, the governor has been involved in mediating
disputes between the controlling local and the movie studios, even
while advisers were urging Cellucci to follow an example set by New
York politicians in the 1980s. At the time, officials suggested
studios avoid filming there until the Teamsters were more
compromising.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, officials who were part of the
Weld-Cellucci administration said they believed that Cashman, who
was elected head of Local 25 in late 1991 on a reform ticket, was
intent on making changes inside the union and establishing a new,
positive image. Cashman accompanied Weld on a trade mission to
Hollywood in late March and early April 1993 during which he
impressed studio executives, as well as state officials, with his
pledge that the Teamsters wanted to cooperate in the effort to
persuade more filmmakers to work in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take much to see the handwriting on the wall, that
the (Weld-Cellucci) administration believed there was much to be
gained by aligning itself with Cashman,'' said one now-retired
labor official who was on the trade mission. ``The question is now
whether George has lived up to all the promises he made about
having the Teamsters turn over a new leaf.''
</P>
<P>
   John Birtwell, Cellucci's spokesman, says the governor continues
to support the decision to back Cashman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a mixed blessing,'' Birtwell said of the ties
between Cashman and Weld and Cellucci. ``Certainly, dealing with
the Teamsters is better now than it was before 1990. But it's also
not the optimum that everyone would hope . . . To us, the needle
points to a qualified success.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several moviemakers have complained to the
Massachusetts Film Office and the Department of Economic
Development about high fees that must be paid to Teamsters drivers
and crew chiefs, and about the heavyhanded tactics that Teamsters
officials periodically use when studios seek to reduce the costs. A
federal grand jury, investigating allegations of extortion of movie
executives by Local 25 officials, has in recent months subpoenaed
records from several Hollywood studios, Local 25, and the
Massachusetts Film Office.
</P>
<P>
   Birtwell defended the governor's dealings with Cashman and Local
25, pointing to the success Cellucci has had in mediating disputes
between the union and the producers of ``The Perfect Storm'' in
1999 and ``The Love Letter'' in 1998. However, Birtwell suggested
that Cashman and Local 25 might have to do more to combat the image
that emerges from the film office's records that were released
Friday. Those documents indicate that the union is not interested
in compromising on its benefits-laden contract in order to
encourage studios to film in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents were several letters between Lou
DiGiampaolo, Local 25's chief movie negotiator, and the producers
of the film ``Summer Catch,'' which was filmed in North Carolina in
recent months even though it revolves around collegians playing
baseball in the Cape Cod League in Massachusetts. DiGiampaolo
refused to compromise on contract-provided benefits for Teamsters
crew members _ a guaranteed 75-hour work week with guaranteed
overtime after each eight-hour workday for all drivers, a minimum
$2,500 a week for a Teamsters crew chief, James P. Flynn, and meal
and living allowance for all drivers if the film was shot outside
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have films like that, that are so part of our lives
here, deciding to film outside the state,'' Birtwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman's Local 25 has been authorized by the Teamsters
International in Washington since late 1993 to negotiate the
union's contracts with moviemakers who are seeking to shoot films
in Massachusetts _ as well as the three northern New England
states.
</P>
<P>
   However, for at least a year before, Joint Council 10, which
represents Teamsters locals throughout New England, had been
competing with Local 25 for the right to be involved in the
negotiations as well, according to documents released Friday by the
Cellucci administration.
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. DeRusha, principal officer for Council 10, argued that
drivers from other Teamsters locals should be used on film
productions that were being shot in their areas, and not solely
members of Local 25. In addition, DeRusha said since DiGiampaolo
and Flynn, Cashman's two top lieutenants with the movie industry,
both had arrest records, there was reason to question Cashman's
claim that he represented a break from past Teamsters tradition.
</P>
<P>
   DeRusha's request in June 1993 to Linda Peterson Warren, then
head of the state Film Office, to intervene and allow Joint Council
10 to make its case with the Weld-Cellucci administration, was
turned aside.
</P>
<P>
   According to a memo she sent to Tocco on July 13, she had been
informed by the union's international in Washington that Teamsters
president Ron Carey, whom Cashman had supported in the 1991
election, had ruled that Local 25 had the authority to negotiate
contracts for all movies filmed in Massachusetts and the northern
New England states. Pending written notification, which came weeks
later, Warren wrote that only Local 25 would negotiate with
filmmakers seeking Teamsters contracts to shoot movies in
Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
