 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ Developing: Russian navy officials
on Monday abandoned hope of finding any men alive inside the sunken
nuclear-powered submarine Kursk, and began discussions about the
dangerous task of inspecting the craft's interior with a camera
before removing the bodies or salvaging the sub first. By Patrick
E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ On Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who has
been engulfed by political turmoil as he tries to negotiate peace.
A top aide quit Monday, after criticizing Barak. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-U.S. (Hong Kong) _ A senior Clinton administration
official said Monday that Congress was not likely to approve a
landmark trade agreement between the United States and Vietnam this
year. But the official, Robert L. Mallett, said the administration
had dispatched him to Hanoi to reassure Vietnamese officials, and
to ``keep the drumbeat going for economic reform.'' By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-SPY (London) _ The British police on Monday arrested a
former British spy, David Shayler, as he returned home after three
years of self-imposed exile in France. Britain said Shayler broke
the Official Secrets Act by alleging that British agents plotted to
kill Moammar Gadhafi in 1996. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline to kum, Wis.) _ George W. Bush's campaign day; he
talks about education. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum, Iowa) _ Al Gore's campaign day; he talks
about tax cuts. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-DELAYS (Washington) _ The U.S. transportation secretary,
Rodney Slater, met with airline executives, union leaders and
airport officials Monday to discuss ways to improve airline travel
by reducing flight delays and cancellations. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-COLOMBIA-DRUGS (New York) _ Officials announced on Monday the
extradition of a suspected Colombian druglord charged with
laundering millions of dollars in drug-money and exporting tons of
cocaine. By John Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Public school enrollment nationwide
breaks another record, continuing a decade-long trend, according to
U.S. Education Secretary Riley. Using census figures, he sees no
end in sight: he predicts public school rolls will nearly double
over the next 100 years, to 94 million from 53 million, putting new
pressures on schools that are already cramped and crumbling. By
Jaques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ Ledeall: A day after Verizon
Communications, formerly Bell Atlantic, reach agreement with unions
representing 50,000 striking workers, talks continue CWA union
officials representing 37,000 workers in the Middle Atlantic
states, including New Jersey. Assessing the financial cost and
other impacts for Verizon of the contract settlement with its
unions. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-AMERICA-INTERNET (Undated) _ The Internet revolution has
definitely come to Latin America. But whether the businesses and
jobs spawned by that revolution have helped the region begin to
wean itself from economic dependence on the United States and other
outsiders is considered a matter of debate. Starmedia, one of the
biggest and most successful Internet companies in Latin America,
has branch offices in seven countries and millions of subscribers
throughout the region. But its headquarters are in New York. Its
$450 million in funding came from investors in the United States.
Its stock is listed on the Nasdaq but not on any exchange in Latin
America. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Detroit) _ Developments in the Firestone tire
recall. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI (Undated) _ Whitman has agreed to buy rival Pepsi bottler
PepsiAmericas Inc., putting together the second and third-largest
Pepsi bottlers in the United States. The $331.7 million deal
further consolidates the Pepsi bottling system, as Pepsico pushes
for system that models Coca-Cola's.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NAMES (Undated) _ Because virtually all of the catchy
Web addresses ending in ``.com'' have already been claimed, a
growing number of companies have begun to realize that there is
money to be made in helping owners re-sell the names that they no
longer want or need. By Sabra Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINE-LOVEBUG (Singapore) _ Philippine prosecutors on
Monday dismissed all charges filed against Onel de Guzman, a former
computer college student accused of having released the ``I love
you'' computer virus that crippled e-mail systems worldwide in May.
By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-TELECOM (Toronto) _ Telus, Canada's second-biggest phone
company, has agreed to buy wireless provider Clearnet
Communications for $4.48 billion in cash, stock and assumed debt.
(Staff byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Gail Collins' ``Public Interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Friedman is on vacation.
</P>
