<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   NOTE TO COX EDs: All political copy has a WAN category of
National.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ HANNIBAL, Mo. - Al Gore's campaign riverboat steamed into
Mark Twain's boyhood home Monday night with a message drawn from
the legenday humorist: news of the death of Gore's presidential bid
has been greatly exaggerated. Gore's trip along 400 miles of the
Mississippi River ended with the vice president having erased the
commanding lead Republican rival has held in public opinion polls.
But Gore still has a long way to go. (Shepard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB _ MOSCOW _ The latest developments on the 118-member
crew of the Russian navy sub Kursk, which is sitting at the bottom
of the Barents Sea about 350 feet below the surface. A Norwegian
dive team managed to open two of the escape hatches to find that
they were both flooded, confirming the grim reality that the entire
crew is dead _ and likely has been since the accident happened more
than a week ago. Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SIDE _ ATLANTA _ Russian President Vladimir Putin's
handling of the submarine crisis _ including his failure to
interrupt his vacation and his reluctance to quickly accept
international help _ may damage Putin's reputation for competence
and decisiveness, hurting him politically, an Emory University
professor says. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-PREPARE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ South Florida is
entering the teeth of the hurricane season. You can expect at least
the threat of a hurricane, with everything that triggers that, at
least once in the next three to four weeks. Perhaps you'll be
looking at a hurricane warning as early as Thursday, if Debby aims
our way. Perhaps not. Now is not the time to panic. But it is time
for this: all those things you were supposed to do in May, but
didn't? Do them now. If Debby, or any other storm, comes our way in
the coming weeks, and you wait until a watch or warning has been
issued, you can expect to be fighting for plywood, batteairlines to
discuss problems with air travel. (Malone, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE _ WASHINGTON - The company that owns a 30-inch pipeline
that exploded and killed 10 campers in New Mexico Saturday was
warned by federal officials three years ago that its workers had
not been trained to accurately determine whether the pipeline was
in danger of corroding. Developing. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-ECHO _ WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley
releases his fifth annual Baby Boom Echo report on national and
state trends Monday in Henderson, Nev. It will say that rising
enrollments (53 million this year in K-12) set a record, and Riley
will claim that this shows that educating the children of baby
boomers requires federal subsidies for school modernization,
renovation and repair and for the reduction of the number of
portable classrooms parked on school grounds. This launches a
week-long drive by the administration to build support for
``building better schools'' before the Republican Congress returns
for the final weeks of nose-to-nose negotations with the Democratic
president over the budget for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
(Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NOTE TO COX EDs: A separate lead will move for each Cox state.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN_ SANDWICH, Mass. _ Getting such a late start
could be counter-productive, so rather than risk it, we head for
the local video store where 30 minutes later we discover there's
not a thing in the entire New Release section that sounds the least
bit Interesting. Through a process of elimination, our only hope
seems to be a Tom Cruise thing called ``Magnolia.'' (Schuett, Cox
News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Why is it considered
natural, laudable and an affirmation of family tradition when kids
go to their parents' old colleges, yet if they end up at the same
high school, everyone gets uncomfortable? Case in point: look at
George W. Bush. He went to Yale like his father and grandfather and
it's considered part of a heritage. But because he also went to the
same prep school as his father, people snicker about how WASP and
preppy and weird that seems. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LEVIN _ ASPEN, Colo. _ Time Warner Chairman and CEO Gerald
M. Levin will give the keynote address at the sixth annual Aspen
Summit, a tech conference. Levin will speak on ``Content,
Convergence and the New Communications Marketplace.'' (Geewax, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category Business, subcategory
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available now.COXNET PTECH0819 _ There is a human side to
some of the automated greetings we hear in everyday life. A look at
some of the people behind the he computer plays defense for your
