<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0822-COX     08-21 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KURSK CREW DECLARED DEAD, WHILE PLANS FOR SALVAGE COMMENCE
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW - Russian and Norwegian officials broke off rescue
operations and declared the 118 crewmembers of a wrecked Russian
submarine dead after confirmation came Monday that the vessel was
entirely flooded.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said he would ask for
international help to raise the 500-foot Kursk submarine from the
frigid depths of the Barents Sea, and recover its two nuclear
reactors, a process that is expected to take months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our worst expectations are confirmed. All sections of the sub
are totally flooded and not a single member of the crew remains
alive,'' Russia's naval chief of staff Mikhail Motsak said in a
televised statement.
</P>
<P>
   The news devastated family members of the Kursk crew especially
hard. Many had traveled for days to Murmansk, the northwestern port
city where the sub was based, only to be met with waves of
contradictory information given by the government and tides of
rumor about the cause of the Aug. 12 accident _ which is still
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prayers have gone unanswered,'' cried Vera Polivaeva,
whose nephew Alexei was one of those aboard the sub.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian divers invited to participate in the rescue attempt
after one week of failed Russian forays succeeded Monday in opening
the rear escape hatch of the vessel. This was the only portion of
the Oscar-class submarine that officials thought might not be
flooded.
</P>
<P>
   However, divers reported that the compartment underneath the air
hatch was completely filled with water, eliminating the final hope
that a human could still be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no hope for survivors. It has been determined it is
time to terminate the rescue operation,'' said Lt. Col. John Espen
Lien, a spokesman for the Norwegian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   A British rescue mini-submarine was not used because the divers
determined there was no point, officials said. The Norwegian divers
found no sign of radiation leaks Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While Moscow initially refused to accept Western aid to rescue
the crew, Russian officials made clear that the salvage operation
needed to retrieve the nuclear reactors and the crew members'
bodies could not happen without outside help and financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Wednesday, the first meeting to discuss the salvage
operation will be held,'' said Klebanov, the Russian official in
charge of the situation. ``It will be an international project. We
shall have to ask for help. No country on its own would be able to
perform it.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway said its diving team would send a remote-controlled
camera down to film the interior of the submarine and help the
Russians decide how to plan the salvage operation, and perhaps lend
clues to how the fatal accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officers have said the most likely sequence of
events for the disaster was that there was a first explosion,
either from inside the vessel or caused by a collision. This
wrecked the front of the sub, sending it straight into the sea bed.
The impact led to a detonation of the Kursk's torpedoes ripping
large parts of the hull apart. The crew, Russian military officials
believe, died immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Water almost instantly flooded the submarine's hull up to the
fifth or sixth compartments. The crew in those sections died almost
instantaneously and the submarine became uncontrollable,'' Klebanov
said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members have stepped up already strong criticism to what
they say has been an inefficient and callous response by Russian
authorities to their tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first news we heard was from you,'' Vladimir Blazhkin, the
father of one of the crew members, told Russia's private NTV
television station, his voice coarse and breaking as he struggled
to hold back tears. ``We did not even know if our son was on the
sub until you published the list. His commanders did not tell us
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He was joined in his strong criticism by the Russian media on
Monday. ``To what depths of cynicism you must sink to lie so
blatantly,'' the daily Moskovsky Komsomolets said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kremlin has been shattered by its own cynicism,'' said the
newspaper Novaya Gazeta.
</P>
<P>
   However, an opinion poll released Monday morning suggested that
Putin has not yet suffered major fallout due to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll of 500 Muscovites conducted over the weekend by the
Romir research agency, 50 percent of respondents blamed Russia's
Navy command and Defense Ministry for the loss of the submarine.
Only 17 percent said Putin was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 59 percent of those polled said their attitude to
Putin had not changed because of the crisis. Before the accident,
polls showed Putin's popularity above 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The polling agency did not establish a margin of error for the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian officials, who have contradicted official Russian
statements about the state of the wreckage and criticized the red
tape surrounding the operation, said it was unclear whether
international expertise, if called on earlier, could have saved any
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say. It's something you just can't speculate on. We
had different weather, different conditions,'' said Lt. Col. Espen
Lien.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to turn public opinion, Prime Minister Mikhail
Kasyanov announced Monday that relatives of the crew members would
receive larger-than-average compensation packages for the dead
servicemen, some of whom were as young as 20 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   Civic response to the families' suffering has been tremendous.
Individuals from around the country have sent financial donations
to newly organized humanitarian groups determined to help the
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some remained inconsolable.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can anything help when our son is underwater, underground
for good,'' Blazhkin said.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.janes.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.government.gov.ru/english/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
