<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPROVAL OF VIETNAM TRADE DEAL NOT LIKELY THIS YEAR, U.S. OFFICIAL
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ A senior Clinton administration official said Monday
that Congress was not likely to approve a landmark trade agreement
between the United States and Vietnam this year. The official,
Robert Mallett, said the administration was sending him to Hanoi to
reassure Vietnamese officials and to ``keep the drumbeat going for
economic reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett, the deputy secretary of commerce, predicted that the
deal, signed in Washington on July 13, would be approved by
Congress regardless of how many seats each party gains or loses or
who wins the presidency in November. Neither Republicans nor
Democrats, he said, will seek to kill an agreement that has great
potential benefits for both countries.
</P>
<P>
   But Mallett also said that carrying out the deal would be as
arduous as the four years it took to hammer it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some talk about foot-dragging in Vietnam,''
Mallett said in an interview here during a stopover on his way to
Hanoi. ``If you're going to have foot-dragging, then their economy
is not going to improve. Economic reform must be a front-burner
issue for Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Mallett said he would raise with Vietnamese
officials is the protection of intellectual property. Although
Hanoi has passed laws protecting copyrights, he said it was not
enforcing them adequately. He also plans to discuss labor
conditions, which were not addressed in the trade deal but have
been an issue because of Vietnam's reputation for sweat-shop
factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cannot expect to be a member of the group of trading
nations and pretend that labor doesn't matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mallett was sanguine about the prospects for trade
between the United States and Vietnam. He said U.S. exports to
Vietnam could grow to between $800 million and $1 billion a year
within two years of the ratification of the deal. That compares
with $291 million last year, and only $4 million in 1993, the year
before President Clinton lifted the trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Vietnamese products would gain improved
access to U.S. markets, with the average tariff on Vietnamese goods
falling to 3 percent from nearly 40 percent. In return, it would
open itself to U.S. banks, insurers and retailers, though on a
somewhat slower timetable than in the recent trade agreement
between China and the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The long road the China trade bill is taking through Congress is
one reason the Clinton administration is unlikely to push the
Vietnam pact before the end of the year. With Congress facing a
crowded calendar and an impending election, administration
officials said the White House was pouring its resources into
winning Senate approval of permanent normal trading relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the delay, the Vietnamese government is already
starting to carry out provisions of the agreement. Hanoi, for
example, recently issued a license to American International Group,
a U.S. insurer, to sell life insurance. Under the terms of the
deal, the government does not have to allow wholly foreign-owned
insurance companies to operate in the country for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implementation is a legitimate concern, but in some ways, the
Vietnamese have been going much faster than the agreement
requires,'' said Frederick Burke, a lawyer with Baker &AMP; McKenzie in
Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said his fear was that Vietnam would try to set up
non-tariff barriers, similar to those erected by Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vietnamese just introduced a law that requires people on
motorcycles to wear helmets,'' he said. ``But some people here are
saying that only Vietnamese-made helmets are appropriate for
Vietnamese heads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
