<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AIRLINE-LAWSUITS-HNS &LR;      08-21 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-LAWSUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PASSENGERS SUE AMERICAN AIRLINES OVER DRY ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Stands for AIRLINE-TRAINING)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two passengers have sued American Airlines,
claiming flight attendants on two separate flights gave them dry
ice to treat aches. Both plaintiffs said they suffered burns from
the ice packs.
</P>
<P>
   Safi Nairobi, a San Francisco-based commercial photographer,
said her burns were so severe that the pilot of her San
Francisco-bound airplane was diverted to Denver, where she was
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   A nearly identical incident happened on another American flight
last August, according to a separate lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Raising questions about the training flight attendants get at
American, the nation's third-largest carrier, Nairobi's lawyer,
Charles A. Bonner, said: ``In the most positive light, someone is
grossly negligent. In the worst light, they're just outright
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   An American Airlines spokesman said the airline does not comment
on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Nairobi's said she was injured Aug. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Armin Khalili, who also lives in the San Francisco area, said he
suffered injuries from dry ice on an Aug. 17, 1999, flight after
requesting ice for a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   After being seated on a flight from Chicago, Nairobi claims she
was handed an ice pack wrapped in cloth, which she placed on her
sore back before falling asleep. When she woke up an hour later,
her back felt warm. She got up and it was wrinkled and numb to the
touch.
</P>
<P>
   Nairobi showed her injury to a flight attendant, who said, ``Oh,
my God, you've been burned,'' according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   After a doctor on board looked at the injuries, the captain
decided to land in Denver, where Nairobi was treated at several
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year later, Bonner said Nairobi still has a scar on
her lower back the size of a pancake, and may have damage to her
nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears like she's permanently branded by this dry ice,''
Conner said. ``She has a scar that she will probably go to her
grave with.''
</P>
<P>
   The degree of Khalili's injuries are not specified in the
lawsuit, and his lawyer did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint asserts that Khalili ``continues to suffer
residual injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Perkins, consumer advocate for the American Society of Travel
Agents, said the alleged injuries were unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never, ever heard of this particular situation,'' Perkins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said when it comes to safety, American has ``a
better-than-average reputation'' among major airlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
