<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-CHRYSLER-MINIVAN     08-21 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CHRYSLER-MINIVAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHRYSLER SPIFFS UP ITS STAPLE MINIVAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When DaimlerChrysler set out to redesign its best-selling
minivans for 2001, creating the fourth generation of a vehicle line
that began with the 1983 introduction of the Plymouth Voyager and
Dodge Caravan, an old adage came to the minds of everyone involved
with the project:
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite hot new competition from Ford Motor Co. and the
Japanese, the DaimlerChrysler minivans remain the company's
bread-and-butter vehicles, selling at a rate of more than 500,000
annually in North America and 600,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for instance, the company sold 504,000 of them in
North America, more than twice the sales of the nearest competitor,
the Ford Windstar. Since their 1983 introduction, more than 8.3
million have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the competition had been making inroads, and
DaimlerChrysler had seen its share of the minivan market fall from
well over 80 percent to just 40 percent last year _ and only 33
percent in the biggest segment of the market, vans priced from
$20,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   And as any business school graduate knows, every product has a
life cycle. That's one of the first lessons taught in Business 101,
with, invariably, the buggy whip used as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler last redesigned its minivan lineup in the mid-'90s, so
the end of the current life cycle was nearing. Since then, Toyota
has introduced its new Sienna, Honda its all-new Odyssey, Mazda the
new MPV and Ford an updated Windstar, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, DaimlerChrysler found itself with the oldest minivan
design on the market, which isn't where the company thought it
should be if it wanted to maintain dominance in the segment it had
discovered, defined and ruled for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you change a product that is still the favorite among
consumers, and which, by most observers' standards, really wasn't
broken?
</P>
<P>
   Very carefully, DaimlerChrysler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent 32 months and $2.8 billion to change everything about
the vehicle,'' said Ken Nelson, a DaimlerChrysler minivan platform
engineer, who helped introduce the newest vans to the automotive
news media during a national media rollout last week in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers count on us to be the leader in this segment, so we
came up with a new list of firsts,'' he said. ``Over the first
three generations, we had created 38 firsts in the segment, so here
we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Styling, understandably, wasn't drastically changed. There are
new angles and creases in the exterior, new headlights, taillights
and grilles, but overall, the new vans look much like those of the
previous generation.
</P>
<P>
   But there are changes through and through, including some of
those new firsts _ such as the industry's first power rear
liftgate.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors introduced the first sliding passenger doors for
minivans in the early '90s, something that took Chrysler a while to
catch up with. But the new minivans, due out this fall as 2001
models, will be offered with the power liftgate, which allows mom
or dad or even the kids to open and close the tailgate with the
mere push of a button.
</P>
<P>
   And just like the power sliding doors on each side of the new
minivans, the liftgate will automatically stop in its tracks if it
detects an obstacle. A DaimlerChrysler engineer demonstrated his
faith in this technology by standing under one of the liftgates as
a colleague pushed the button on the remote control to close it. It
worked.
</P>
<P>
   This feature will be available only on long-wheelbase versions
of the new minivans. It is a standalone $250 option, except on the
Town &AMP; Country Limited, where it is a standard item, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be offered on the short-wheelbase models because of
space limitations in the cargo area. But two-thirds of all
DaimlerChrysler minivans sold are the long-wheelbase versions.
</P>
<P>
   Other firsts include such convenience items as a pull-up cargo
organizer in the rear floor, with compartments that can hold six
filled paper grocery bags; cup holders attached to the outboard
middle-row seats with a special mechanism that holds the drink
level even when the seat is tilted forward to allow access to the
third row; and recessed hooks on the backs of all the seats to
suspend plastic grocery bags so the groceries don't spill out and
roll all over the floor.
</P>
<P>
   As for the third row of seats, DaimlerChrysler decided against a
seat that folds completely into the floor like the ones in the new
Mazda MPV and Honda Odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the new Dodge and Chrysler minivans will be available
with an optional 50-50 split rear bench seat that can be removed a
half at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the 110-pound weight of the full bench seat in last
year's vans, each half of this seat weights just 55 pounds and can
be removed or reinstalled by almost anyone strong enough to lift
it, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the engineers on hand for the media presentations said
his 12-year-old daughter can do it. With just one-half of the third
seat removed, two bicycles can be fitted into the cargo area,
standing up.
</P>
<P>
   More firsts include electric motors mounted inside the sliding
doors to allow for easier manual operation if necessary, and
automatic latching devices that finish closing the liftgate or
sliding doors if they don't fully latch on the first try. Mom
doesn't have to get out of the driver's seat and walk around the
vehicle to finish closing the door.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard has a new, heavier padding, but it's still flat
and large enough to hold two Happy Meals, DaimlerChrysler said.
</P>
<P>
   An optional three-zone temperature control setup allows the
driver, front passenger and rear passengers to set their own
climate comfort levels in some uplevel Town &AMP; Country models,
another first.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the hood has been raised one inch for better visibility
of it from the driver's seat, creases have been added in the side
sheet metal to give the design a ``pulled tighter'' look and add
definition, and the Dodge Caravan models have a distinctive large
new grille that ``makes the vehicle recognizable as a Dodge from a
full football field away,'' a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Headlights are 50 percent larger and 80 percent brighter, and
the center high-mounted stop lamp has been moved from the middle of
the liftgate to the top, above the rear window.
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel disc brakes will be standard on all-wheel-drive
models _ another exclusive for the class _ and the nose of the vans
has been extended an inch and made 47 pounds heavier for better
energy absorption in the event of a collision.
</P>
<P>
   Head-injury protection has been added in the roof, and new
child-seat tethers and anchors are standard. Chrysler's optional
integrated child-safety seats continue to be offered with the new
models.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the changes are cosmetic or safety related; performance
also has been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   The base 3.3-liter V-6 engine has been increased to 180
horsepower from last year's 158; the 3.8-liter V-6 now turns out
215 horsepower, up from 180; and on the uplevel Town &AMP; Country, a
3.5-liter, 230-horsepower engine borrowed from the Chrysler 300M
sedan will be added to the lineup next spring.
</P>
<P>
   All the engines are designed to run on regular fuel, too.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen models will be sold for 2001 _ nine with front-wheel
drive and five with all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   They include four trim levels in Dodge Caravan badging, and five
under the Chrysler name _ two short-wheelbase models called Voyager
and three long-wheelbase versions with the Town &AMP; Country
designation. (For 2001, the Plymouth Voyager becomes a Chrysler as
DaimlerChrysler continues its phaseout of the Plymouth brand name.)
</P>
<P>
   As before, the minivans will be priced from the upper teens to
the mid-$30,000s. This will allow DaimlerChrysler to continue its
dominance of the lower end of the minivan price scale, where it
holds a 67 percent market share of vans under $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the upper end of the scale, minivans priced over $30,000,
DaimlerChrysler hopes to hold onto _ or even improve _ its current
50 percent market share. All-wheel-drive versions of the Town &AMP;
Country are expected to be influential in this effort, because most
of the competitors don't offer all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The company says that, adjusted for additional content, the
pricing of the new minivans remains the same as the 2000 models
they replace.
</P>
<P>
   That means that where new and better stuff has been added,
consumers will have to pay for that; but there are no price
increases on the base vehicles when compared with similarly
equipped 2000 models.
</P>
<P>
   The absolute top-of-the-line model is the all-wheel-drive Town &AMP;
Country Limited. It costs $37,790, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler minivans are made in Windsor, Ontario; St.
Louis; and Graz, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
