<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-CHRYSLER-SEDANS-     08-21 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CHRYSLER-SEDANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHRYSLER GIVES ITS SEDANS A NEW BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler wants you to forget the Ford Taurus, Honda
Accord and Toyota Camry, and instead buy one of its two all-new
midsize sedans: the 2001 Dodge Stratus and Chrysler Sebring.
</P>
<P>
   During a national media introduction for the cars in Seattle
recently, DaimlerChrysler officials suggested these sedans will hit
the mark with consumers where the previous-generation Dodge and
Chrysler midsize sedans failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   The company needs to become a player in this market, because
even with money rolling in from DaimlerChrysler's popular minivans,
trucks and sport-utility vehicles (including the Jeep products),
financial success in today's auto industry requires that a company
have significant sales of traditional cars, too. They still make up
50 percent of all new-vehicle purchases.
</P>
<P>
   And if coupes rather than sedans are your forte, then
DaimlerChrysler has two other brand-new models for you to choose
from: the Dodge Stratus and Chrysler Sebring coupes. Unlike the
practice of most other automakers, which generally use the same
basic car to create sedan and coupe versions of a particular model,
DaimlerChrysler has coupes that are different from sedans of the
same name.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the sedans are designed and built by DaimlerChrysler,
with domestic engines, while the coupes are designed and built by
Mitsubishi, DaimlerChrysler's Japanese partner, with Mitsubishi
engines.
</P>
<P>
   The sedans certainly look a lot better than their predecessors,
whose bulk of sales primarily was to rental-car and corporate
fleets. Although the new sedans are built on the same basic chassis
platform as before, DaimlerChrysler says the components are all
new, from the larger, standard 15-inch tires to the sleek new
rooflines.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Stratus and Sebring sedans are essentially
the same car, there are enough styling differences to make each one
appear to be a different vehicle. The biggest differences are in
the grilles, and the Chrysler model, as is to be expected, looks
more elegant, while the Dodge version is sportier-looking.
</P>
<P>
   The styling is impressive on both, clearly an improvement over
the sedans they replace _ the 2000 Dodge Stratus and Chrysler
Cirrus. The Cirrus nameplate is gone for 2001, as Chrysler tries to
create a new image for its midsize sedan, renaming it to carry the
same designation as last year's similar-sized Sebring convertible
and coupe models.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably a good move, since the Cirrus never caught on
with consumers. And perhaps the company should have come up with a
new name for the Stratus, since it isn't all that popular with
consumers, either.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer perceptions of blase styling, mediocre performance and
questionable quality have kept the Stratus and Cirrus off most
people's shopping lists. But after seeing _ and driving _ both of
the new sedans and coupes, I have to say that perhaps they are
worth at least a look if you are in the market for a car in this
size and price class.
</P>
<P>
   The sedans come with an enhanced safety cage body that
DaimlerChrysler says will protect the vehicles' occupants much more
than before; it includes improved impact absorption, particularly
in the vehicles' front end. There is an available side-curtain air
bag ($350, offered on all models as a stand-alone option), designed
to help protect front and rear outboard occupants in the event of a
side impact. And in the trunk, there is a glow-in-the-dark safety
release to allow anyone trapped inside to get out without help.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those changes, there are many more improvements and
upgrades that enhance safety as well as styling, road handling,
ride, and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Two engines are offered, including the four-cylinder from last
year and a new V-6 that has increased horsepower. Both have
double-overhead-cam arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The base engine is a 2.4-liter four-cylinder rated at 150
horsepower and 167 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   But the star of the line is the 2.7-liter V-6, which cranks out
200 horsepower and 192 foot-pounds of torque _ a substantial
increase over last year's 2.5-liter V-6 with 168 horsepower and 170
foot-pounds of torque. Even with the extra power, the engine gets
10 percent better fuel economy than last year's, DaimlerChrysler
engineers say.
</P>
<P>
   All Stratus and Sebring sedans come with a four-speed automatic
transmission. EPA estimated fuel economy for the V-6 is 20 miles
per gallon in the city and 28 on the highway. For the
four-cylinder, the ratings are just slightly better: 21 city/29
highway.
</P>
<P>
   The Stratus, particularly, is value-priced. A well-equipped
four-cylinder model _ with just about everything the average buyer
would want, including power windows and door locks _ is just under
$18,000, while a V-6 model with the same amenities would be under
$19,000. There are no stripped-down models available; power windows
and door locks are standard throughout the line.
</P>
<P>
   The sedans are built at DaimlerChrysler's Sterling Heights,
Mich., plant.
</P>
<P>
   As for the coupes, they are built by Mitsubishi at the Diamond
Star Motors plant in Normal, Ill., and come with a choice of either
a 147-horsepower, 2.4-liter four-cylinder or a 3.0-liter,
200-horsepower V-6. Last year's coupe models carried 2.0-liter
four-cylinder or 2.5-liter V-6 engines.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, a five-speed manual transmission is
available with either engine. In the past, only a four-speed
automatic was offered with the coupes' optional V-6. The manual
with the V-6 offers the best performance for people who want to
really drive these cars.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want an automatic, there is even an optional
four-speed auto-stick transmission that allows the driver to shift
gears manually, or to let the car do it automatically, without
having to use a clutch.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said it chose to develop and introduce these new
coupes because the market for such cars has remained steady at
about a million sales annually for the past several years, and that
figure is expected to hold for several more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 75 million baby boomers who have had minivans and
SUVs, but many of them now want something different, such as a
sporty coupe,'' said Gary Kanarek, a marketing executive for
DaimlerChrysler's coupes.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, there are many buyers in the 25-35 age group who
are looking for ``cutting-edge vehicles with better image and
styling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sportiest model is the Stratus R/T version, which even has a
throaty exhaust note.
</P>
<P>
   Prices will run from the low- to mid-$20,000s for well-equipped
coupe models.
</P>
<P>
   The new Stratus and Sebring coupes and sedans go on sale late
this month; an all-new Sebring convertible will arrive late this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
