<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-CHEVY-CORVETTE-H     08-21 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CHEVY-CORVETTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW CORVETTE WILL PUT A SMILE ON YOUR FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chevrolet Corvette has always been a smile maker, but the
new model they call the Z06 is so much fun that it will put the
biggest, goofiest smile in the world on the face of almost anyone
who drives it.
</P>
<P>
   I test drove the car for just a week and I'm still smiling. But
there were times as I cruised around in this 'Vette of 'Vettes that
my devious little mind was trying to figure out a way that I could
keep it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, all the practical arguments against such a car were there,
and reason prevailed. I might want a Z06, I might think I need one,
but I know I don't really need it and, worst of all, can't really
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   One of my friends firmly believes that the biggest market for
cars such as the Z06 are bored, middle-age professionals. He is a
self-admitted bored, middle-age professional, so I suppose he knows
what he's talking about. He had a Corvette _ not a Z06 or even one
of the other, lower-priced C5 (fifth-generation) models but an
earlier one _ and he finally gave it up for a more practical
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But I could tell he was lusting after the Z06 when I showed it
to him, and I might have created a monster just letting him see it.
</P>
<P>
   If he shows up at home with a Z06 anytime soon, his wife
probably will hunt me down and blame it on me. But, hey, don't look
at me. The Z06 has that effect on people.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure: It's a real car, designed for serious
driving. I don't advocate speeding or any such illegal behavior,
but it is definitely difficult to behave in a Z06, because it likes
to run. Its acceleration is so brisk that it is downright
exhilarating, almost breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   So if you do buy one, make sure you have a safe place lined up
to take it for some serious driving _ like a race track or other
closed course that is off the public highways.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is a Z06, you might ask? It's the latest and greatest
Corvette ever, a high-performance edition of the C5, which is just
now reaching the market as a 2001 model.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with the special, racing-inspired LS6 5.7-liter V-8
engine, rated at 385 horsepower and 385 foot-pounds of torque, and
a six-speed manual gearbox, the Z06 goes from zero to 60 mph in 4
seconds flat. That's what the manufacturer says, but I've talked to
people who say the car will beat that by a 10th of a second or
more, depending on who is driving it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some say that the Dodge Viper R/T, whose published
zero-to-60 performance is 3.8 seconds, is hard pressed to beat a
Z06 at the hands (and feet) of a good driver.
</P>
<P>
   Just like other C5 models _ the latest generation of Corvettes,
which debuted in 1997 _ the Z06 is vastly improved over previous
'Vettes, including the popular, limited-edition ZR1 models of the
'90s. It's easier to get into and out of, for one thing. It doesn't
rattle when you hit bumps in the road like most older 'Vettes do.
</P>
<P>
   But best of all is the road handling, which is greatly improved
over the previous generations because of the 50-50 front-to-rear
weight distribution created by the front engine/rear transaxle
arrangement of the C5. Half of the weight of the drivetrain is up
front, where the engine is mounted, and the other half is at the
rear axle, where the transmission is.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few laps around the racetrack, first in a C4 and then in
a regular production C5, quickly showed me the difference when I
had an opportunity to drive the new Corvettes for the first time in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   I had the C5 over 150 mph on the back straightaway, but I
couldn't get the C4 going that fast _ at least, not comfortably.
And the C5's awesome brakes were another factor in getting the car
going fast on that track; you have to brake hard to take the next
turns at the end of that straightaway, or you'll run off into the
grass. The C5 was up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't had the opportunity to drive the Z06 on a racetrack
yet, but I did find out that the Z06's brakes are every bit as good
as Chevrolet bills them to be. Some nut changed lanes and stopped
right in front of me one day, forcing me to jam my foot hard on the
Z06's brakes and hold it there to keep from hitting his Ford
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   A companion riding with me was impressed. ``I don't think any
other car's brakes would have stopped us in time,'' she said as we
sat there shaking from the near-death experience. Thank you,
Chevrolet, for great engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the Z06 is like driving a race car, and that makes sense
because the vehicle is racing-inspired. Chevy's literature on the
Z06 says it is a ``production vehicle that's ready for the
racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   List price is $47,500, including transportation; but with
limited availability and expected high demand, these cars probably
will be hard to get. That means you probably can expect some steep
dealer markups, although not all dealers will do that.
</P>
<P>
   The Z06 designation was chosen to honor the efforts of the
``father of the Corvette,'' the late Zora Arkus-Duntov _ Corvette's
first chief engineer _ who in 1963 created the original Z06
package, Chevy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original Z06 package was intended to make the then-new
Sting Ray race-ready right out of the showroom, and today's Z06 has
been developed with the same concept in mind,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Z06 is the only Corvette to get the new LS6 engine, but
even that name is a blast from the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LS6 designation is another expression of appreciation for
the accomplishments of earlier Corvette engineers,'' Chevrolet
said. ``In 1971, Zora Duntov's team created a special 425-hp
big-block V-8 for the Corvette _ again with racing in mind. It was
second only to the legendary full-blown L88 racing engine that was
available from 1967 to 1969. Despite the fact that only 188
Corvettes were sold with the LS6 engine, it occupies a special
niche in Corvette legend.''
</P>
<P>
   The new LS6 is based on the 5.7-liter LS1. But Chevy said that
its aluminum block has been modified for better management of
crankcase pressures and speedier return of oil from the upper part
of the engine during high-speed operation, and the engine also has
a more-aggressive camshaft profile to take full advantage of the
additional air that the new intake manifold provides.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the improvements that led to the LS6 engine have also
been incorporated into the LS1 for the other two Corvette models
for 2001, allowing it to have five more horsepower _ now up to 350
hp.
</P>
<P>
   At least part of the extra cost of the Z06 comes from its
special exhaust system, which is made of titanium, a precious
metal.
</P>
<P>
   The system is 50 percent lighter than the stainless steel
exhaust on other C5s.
</P>
<P>
   Other differences between the standard C5 and the Z06 include
improvements in the suspension, and the car carries larger tires.
The Z06 comes with a larger front stabilizer bar, stiffer rear leaf
spring and revised camber settings.
</P>
<P>
   And there are Z06-specific forged-aluminum wheels, which are an
inch wider than those used on the coupes and convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the regular C5, the Z06 does not have the Goodyear
run-flat tires that allow the Corvette to drive up to 50 miles
after a tire loses its air. Because of those tires, Chevy doesn't
even put a spare tire and jack into the Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   There is no spare in the Z06, either, so Chevy puts an emergency
tire-inflator kit in the back in case you get a flat.
</P>
<P>
   Some special styling touches also help to differentiate the Z06.
They include the twin mesh front grilles, as well as side scoops
with mesh inserts just in front of the rear wheels. Even the seats
have a special fabric, with the Z06 logo on the top front of the
bucket seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Z06 comes only in a hardtop model; no convertible is
planned. And for 2001, the Z06 is the only hardtop model offered.
Gone is the regular hardtop model from 2000, which carried a base
price of $39,350, the lowest among last year's 'Vettes.
</P>
<P>
   Other Corvette models offered for 2001 are the coupe, at $40,475
(including transportation), and the convertible, at $47,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
