<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-REVIEWS-COMEDY-H     08-21 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEWS-COMEDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;     SOME `KINGS' ARE FUNNY; SOME AREN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a funny thing about comedy. Riffs on race, on the
difference between the sexes, between blacks and whites, styles of
music, young generation and old _ all of that, if delivered with
just the right balance of irony and insight, can be hilarious.
Riffs on child abuse cannot.
</P>
<P>
   That about sums up the problem with ``The Original Kings of
Comedy,'' a half-hilarious, half-tiresome film showcasing four
piping-hot African-American comics. Directed by Spike Lee in a
straight-up documentarian style, the film is a blow-by-blow rehash
of a Charlotte, N.C., arena gig in which the quartet offers caustic
observations on black life and white cluelessness.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong or innately offensive in such humor: Much
of it will pop your gut, regardless of your skin color. Steve
Harvey's astute racial analysis of ``Titanic,'' for instance, would
make a fine doctoral dissertation on the impoverished
self-preservation instinct among white haute bourgeoisie. (``What
black band do you know woulda kept playing while the ship went
down?'' he asks. ``Can you see Kool and the Gang ... ?'')
</P>
<P>
   But while the sleek, sharp Harvey hits his marks with precision,
the film's humor is far from consistent, often repetitive and
sometimes so laden with profanity that any verbal nuances get lost
in the crush.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey is funny. Cedric the Entertainer, an effusive pillow of a
man dressed in a sleeveless mobster suit, is funny. His tributes to
reggae music (``I had peanut but-tah/No jahm!/No jahm!'') and
doddering church ladies are among the film's highlights. Less
amusing are D.L. Hughley and Bernie Mac, who mistake foul language
for lacerating wit (what George Carlin might have done with Mac's
pointless spin on a four-syllable word) and graphic sex talk for
gender insight.
</P>
<P>
   Hughley does have his moments, including a few stinging
observations on the African-American experience. Eating disorders
get a workout: ``White folk get anorexia. ... Black folk, when we
get anorexia, it's an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Mac goes off in one of his mumbling, whack-the-brats
tirades against children, there's little to do but wait it out.
Here's his motto for a Bernie Mac day-care center: ``I will (mess)
your kids up'' (a kid misbehaves, he'll clock him in the head with
a hammer). Here's his word for an effeminate 6-year-old:
``faggot.'' And here's his assessment of whites and blacks: ``We're
the same. Only we do s--- different.''
</P>
<P>
   All four comedians boast resumes packed with TV gigs, Harvey and
Cedric with ``The Steve Harvey Show,'' Hughley with ``The
Hughleys,'' Mac in scattered shows, cable specials and films. So
none of them qualifies as a scrappy upstart. They're not exactly
unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lee shows us little of their offstage lives, preferring to
record the group's Charlotte gig with few interruptions and scant
cuts. An off-hour poker game and a few hi-jinks on the basketball
court are as close as the film gets to personal revelation.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Original Kings of Comedy'' isn't about revelation.
It's about grabbing a bat and swinging, hard, at a pinata stuffed
with race and sex. ``Fun is fun. Jokes is jokes,'' says Bernie Mac.
``It ain't nothin' to be ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe sometimes it is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
