<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-ABORIGINE-ART-BOS     08-21 2015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ABORIGINE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (i and s coding)  
 OR ABORIGINES, OLYMPICS A REMINDER OF WHITE OPPRESSSION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Gathered in a city park, re-creating a fire ceremony
they called the oldest ritual known to humans, a group of
Aboriginal activists gave voice last week to their smoldering
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have waged an undeclared war against our people,'' said
Isabell Coe, a veteran Aboriginal leader. ``We want to end this
war. This is about peace and justice. This is what we want, and
this is what our fire represents.''
</P>
<P>
   She then led 30 people, an equal number of Aborigines and white
supporters, in placing green eucalyptus branches on the fire.
Fragrant plumes of smoke framed her as she hugged each participant.
</P>
<P>
   Coe is the woman behind an Aboriginal ``tent embassy,'' which
has occupied Victoria Park near central town Sydney since July. The
encampment is a ragtag reminder of the plight of Australia's first
people, a tiny, downtrodden minority on a continent they once had
to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As the world turns to Sydney for next month's Olympic Games, Coe
and other Aboriginal activists hope to use the attention to win
global support for their cause and, in turn, shame the government
into making concessions ranging from limited sovereignty and cash
reparations to a full apology for what Aborigines call the
genocidal policies of the past.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident, therefore, that the tent embassy, a
collection of 30-odd tents around a light pole where Coe has hung
the red, yellow, and black Aboriginal flag, went up in a prime
location on the route from downtown to Homebush Bay, the Olympic
site. Nor is it coincidence that another Aboriginal protest, a
human chain, is planned at the airport around the time the Games
begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world will be on our doorstep for the first time in the
history of white Australia, and probably black Australia, too. All
we want to do is educate the world about the truth,'' said Jenny
Munro, chairwoman of Sydney's Metropolitan Local Aboriginal Land
Council, a leading organizer of the planned Olympic protests.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters on both sides is the fact that Australia's
favorite Olympian and best chance for a gold medal, world 400-meter
track champion Cathy Freeman, is an Aborigine.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginal leaders have been torn between wanting to stage
dramatic protests for the two-week Olympiad, from Sept. 15 to Oct.
1, and fearing they might diminish ``Cathy's Games.'' Several
months ago, a leader promised violent uprisings and ``Burn baby,
burn'' at the Olympics, only to soften his stand under pressure
from his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   For white Australians, Freeman's enormous popularity in this
sports-crazed nation has forced a reexamination of attitudes toward
a people often stereotyped as drunken layabouts or pathetic
primitives. Those attitudes are directly challenged by bus shelter
ads throughout Sydney for Qantas Airways. They show Freeman's face
and the words, ``The Spirit of Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Australia's Aborigines has echoes of both the
Native American and the African-American experiences. But in many
ways their struggle is as distinct as the flora and fauna that
flourish here and nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Aborigines arrived here, probably from
Southeast Asia, 50,000 years ago. Then over time they spread out
into perhaps 600 tribes, with different dialects and languages.
They roamed the land for 50 millennia, hunting, gathering, etching
art into rocks, and telling stories of the Dreamtime, when
``creation ancestors'' formed the physical and spiritual worlds.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed in 1778, 18 years after Captain James Cook, the
explorer, claimed Australia for Britain. Eleven ships arrived in
Sydney bearing 1,500 people, half of them convicts from overcrowded
British jails and the rest soldiers and free settlers. Clashes
began almost immediately, and British guns trumped tribal spears;
most encounters ended disastrously for the Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to understand that, unlike the Native
Americans, Aborigines didn't have anything the white settlers
wanted,'' said Andrew Markus, an authority on aboriginal history
and associate professor at Monash University in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans had the convicts, so they didn't need labor. The
Aborigines didn't cultivate food or have commodities, so they
didn't have that to offer either. Almost from day one, Europeans
saw Aborigines as excess to requirements, and that has affected all
dealings and attitudes since.''
</P>
<P>
   Killings and other crimes against Aborigines often went
unpunished. It was not until 1962 that Aborigines won the right to
vote, and they have been counted in the census only since 1967. It
was not until 1992 that courts recognized that Aborigines owned
Australia before whites arrived.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR;  there are 500,000 Aborigines in Australia, about the
same number as when the Europeans landed, while the overall
population has topped 19 million.
</P>
<P>
   By almost every measure, Aborigines are at the bottom of
economic and social scales of one of the world's richest nations.
Life expectancy is 20 years below the rest of the population,
infant mortality is five times higher, and Aborigines are 20 times
more likely to be imprisoned at some point in their lives. National
unemployment fell to 6.3 percent last month, the lowest level in a
decade, but the official Aboriginal jobless rate was four times as
high. Aboriginal leaders say the true rate is 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most Aborigines live in remote settlements. But in the Sydney
neighborhood of Redfern, an Aborigine slum of several hundred
families, a 10-minute drive from downtown, the center is ``The
Block,'' an urban war zone of decrepit two-story homes awash in
angry graffiti. A burned-out car rusts on a sidewalk, and abandoned
houses are bricked up lest drug addicts use them as shooting
galleries.
</P>
<P>
   One  &UR; afternoon &LR;  last week, a young Aborigine woman in a Reebok
sweatshirt walked to a white van, where she exchanged a used needle
for a clean one. Then, in the middle of the sidewalk, she paused
and rolled up her sleeve. With a stony nonchalance, she injected
herself with heroin she had purchased from a nearby open-air drug
market. A crowd of young men huddled in an alley. Across the
street, three older Aborigines sat drinking beer and watching the
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the part of Sydney that doesn't exist,'' said Doug
Dixon, 43, an activist who grew up in Redfern. ``They want visitors
to take the ride from the airport to the Olympics, and maybe
downtown. They don't want you to see any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Olympics approach, an issue that has generated much of
the passion is the suffering of Aborigines from what is known as
the ``stolen generation.'' From the early 1900s to as late as 1970,
the government encouraged young indigenous people, particularly
those with lighter skin, to be taken from their families and raised
in orphanages or by white families. Estimates of the number of
children affected range from 30,000 to 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was Cecil Bowden, 60, who was taken to a children's
home with an older sister and younger brother when their mother
died in childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was taken,'' Bowden said, ``my father was fighting for
Australia in the Second World War. I had a lot of family who could
have taken us until he returned, but we didn't have rights even to
our own children.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden remembered terrible beatings at the hands of white
caretakers for small or imagined infractions. He remembered seeing
his father turned away, empty-handed, when he came home from war
and tried to claim Bowden from a boys' home.
</P>
<P>
   The policy has become a rallying cry for Aborigines seeking an
apology, and perhaps cash reparations, from the government of Prime
Minister John Howard. For many, the unrequited desire to hear
Howard say the word ``sorry'' has taken on almost mythic
importance. The issue got a boost last month when Freeman, who had
been relatively silent on political issues as she gained athletic
fame, criticized the Howard government for its refusal to apologize
and revealed that her grandmother was a member of the stolen
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, though, has been steadfast in refusing to apologize,
offering only ``regrets,'' interpreted here as modest sympathy, not
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not willing to apologize for things my government and my
generation of Australians didn't do,'' he said earlier this year.
Observers said the government also is concerned that a formal
apology might open the way for billions of dollars in financial
claims. Howard also has rejected calls to negotiate a treaty with
Aborigines, saying such agreements are only appropriate between
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's minister for Aboriginal affairs, John Herron, inflamed
the debate when he challenged use of the term ``stolen
generation,'' saying that by some estimates the policy affected
only 10 percent of Aborigine children.
</P>
<P>
   Aborigines reacted angrily to what they called an insult of
semantics, particularly since Herron ostensibly represents their
interests. Senator Aden Ridgeway, the only Aborigine in Australia's
Parliament, said in an interview that Herron's comments were ``like
denying the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Herron did not respond to requests for an interview, but
government officials staunchly defend their treatment of
Aborigines. About $1.5 billion is being spent this year on
programs, mostly involving health, education, housing, and economic
development, for Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   They also say Aborigines have been given title to more than 15
percent of the continent, although most of the land is in the
remote and inhospitable Northern Territory. The government also has
set up a nearly $1 billion land fund for urban Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, a conservative who came to power in 1996, apparently has
not suffered for his stands. Polls have shown a majority of
Australians agree with him, with one survey finding that 62 percent
reject the idea of an apology for past wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that white Australians have been moved by
the stolen generation reports. Some 200,000 joined a march for
racial healing in June across the Sydney Harbor Bridge, the largest
demonstration here since the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge march came after it was widely acknowledged that a
decade-long effort called Reconciliation had not achieved its goal
of a racially united Australia. The hope, perhaps naive in
retrospect, had been that black-white relations could be fully
mended in time for next year's 100th anniversary of Australian
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond apologies, the Aborigines' bid for compensation dimmed
this month when a federal court ruled against two members of the
stolen generation seeking compensation in a test case. The judge
said they had failed to show the government had not acted in their
best interests.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Olympic organizers have tried desperately to avoid
the controversy and to appease aboriginal interests. They are
flying the Aboriginal flag at the Olympic site, cosponsoring an
indigenous culture pavilion, giving Aborigines a major role in an
Olympics Arts Festival, and incorporating the boomerang, an
Aboriginal hunting tool, in the official Olympic logo. The first
Aborigine gold medalist, women's hockey player Nova Peris-Kneebone,
was chosen as the first runner to carry the torch on Australian
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, most Aborigines say the Olympic spotlight on
Sydney is too good an opportunity to miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some good will and good intentions,'' said
Ridgeway, an Aborigine who is a member of Parliament. ``But it's
one thing to embrace the icons of aboriginality and it's quite
another to embrace the people and the rights to which they are
entitled. Some people may resent it, but we are going beyond good
will gestures and demanding more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
