<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8055 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-OBERAMMERGAU082     08-21 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-OBERAMMERGAU0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A troubling look at the world's most famous Passion Play
 &HT;    OBERAMMERGAU: The Troubling Story of the World's Most Famous
Passion Play, by James Shapiro. Pantheon; 238 pages; $24.
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The legend states that the Oberammergau
Passion Play has been staged every 10 years since 1634, the town's
way of showing their gratitude for being spared the ravages of a
plague.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 19th century, the Oberammergau event, a religious
spectacle that lasts more than seven hours per performance, with as
many as 700 of the villagers of Oberammergau in the cast, was part
and parcel of the Grand Tour of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But since World War II, there have been increasing problems with
the production, more or less because the Passion Play has always
proclaimed that the Jews killed Jesus, thereby reflecting the
traditional anti-Semitism of the Bavarian Alps. (It hasn't hurt
attendance; this year, more than a half million visitors will see
the Passion Play in Oberammergau.)
</P>
<P>
   The idea of generational guilt is one of many that Columbia
University Professor James Shapiro examines in maladroit fashion in
his new book about the past and present of Oberammergau.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book, Shapiro circles wonderingly around the
startling discovery that rural Germany has always been to Jews what
the American South was to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oberammergau ``is narrated in a cool, formal voice, rather as
if it's a transcription of an academic paper. What one misses more
than anything else is a feel for the place; Shapiro's book would
have been immensely improved if he'd just taken Travel Writing 101.
</P>
<P>
   He never tells us what Oberammergau looks like, where the town
is in relation to the mountains, etc. The book proceeds in a sort
of semi-intellectual vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   He does tell us, with a vague air of ``gotcha'' that the
supposedly pious villagers have had _ gasp! _ children out of
wedlock and that, at one time in the mid-19th century, about one
out of every six villagers was illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, Shapiro's book is still of some interest, if only
for its portrait of the town's tortured attempts to find some road
back from its Medieval anti-Semitic past and recent anti-Semitic
past _ Hitler praised the Passion Play for its portrayal of ``the
whole muck and mire of Jewry'' _ by attempting to ameliorate
protests by people they undoubtedly regard as tiresome professional
Jews who have had them on the defensive for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Oberammergau, of course, isn't about to cop to their
enthusiastic embrace of Nazism. The official guidebook says only
that ``in 1939 war broke out, and the village was completely cut
off from its friends abroad and had to play its part in the total
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the modern tension derives from the inevitable conflict
between the essentially Catholic villagers and the essentially
Jewish disputees. As Shapiro says: ``For all the ecumenical
attention to a shared spiritual heritage, the play forces Jews and
Christians to face the painful fact that they read differently, and
that a single version of the founding story of Christianity cannot
be comfortably shared. Matters now have been scraped down to bare
bone, to irreconcilable differences.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those areas where live-and-let-live has to come
into play, or everyone ends up at the barricades. Shapiro
acknowledges that the script now in use at Oberammergau conforms to
the doctrine advanced 35 years ago by Vatican II.
</P>
<P>
   And that should be the end of that, but, because of the play's _
and the town's _ undoubted anti-Semitic history, they and it are
held to a standard very few religious pageants could withstand.
</P>
<P>
   All the village has to sell is itself and its tradition. There
is almost no local industry except for the Passion Play once every
10 years, and the woodcarving that is sold to the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But Shapiro neglects basic reportorial duties in favor of a
discursive sweep over four centuries of anti-Semitism that could
not be that surprising to anyone who's been there, or has read some
books. Since we are given to understand that the play is the
financial engine that supports the town, would it have been so
difficult to find out exactly what kind of stipends are paid to the
villagers?
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the fact that the book seems to have been written by
a man who doesn't get out much, and it begs nearly as many
questions as it answers, ``Oberammergau `` provides some revealing
glimpses of a town trying, in what seems to be good faith, to
straddle 400 years of tradition without giving further offense to
the Jewish faith or betraying what they regard as their
forefathers' blood oath.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
