<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8058 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MORRISPART2-0822-COX     08-21 1897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRISPART2-0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite cancer, writer realizes how lucky he is
 &HT;    Jim Morris is the outdoor writer for the Dayton Daily News.
Morris, 55, spent the past three years battling non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma. In a two-part series, he recounts his struggle and shares
his insights about this fight for his life. Last week, he wrote
about his diagnosis and first round of treatment. In today's final
part, Morris writes about the stem cell transplant he underwent to
kill the cancer.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jim Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - I sought the advice and experiences of others who
had gone through the stem-cell transplant procedure to battle
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. But as helpful as those chats were, I still
had to consider just what would and could happen to me.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, this is what did happen:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In August 1999, the doctors put a catheter in my chest. No
more IVs in the arms or backs of my hands. All drugs went in and
blood went out through this twin-tubed port. I walked around with
these tubes hanging out of my upper left chest. And they had to be
kept sterile all the time.
</P>
<P>
   (At first, we had a nurse visit our house every day to change
the dressing and give me injections of a drug to help rebuild my
blood cells. Later, my wife handled the caregiver chores.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  I went to the James Cancer Hospital in Columbus in
mid-September for apheresis, the process that extracted the healthy
``baby'' cells from my blood. These were frozen and reintroduced to
my body later. They ran my blood through a centrifuge and then put
it back in my body.
</P>
<P>
   The process took only a couple of hours for me, but it can take
a day or so. I remember as I was lying there, hooked up to the
machine, there was a teen-age girl in the bed next to me who was
absolutely terrified of the process and of having needles stuck
into her arms. I hope she is OK now.
</P>
<P>
   The general idea (and this explanation is with a journalism
degree, not a medical diploma) was to knock my immune system
totally down with high-dose chemo, get rid of any possible cancer
cells lurking about, and then build my system back up with my own
healthy blood cells. Even I know that practically eliminates the
chance of rejection, as it might from a donor transplant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  I received a 24-hour drip of the high-dose chemo to kill the
cancer. Beforehand, I wondered: Could my body stand that? The other
chemos I'd had were supposed to be mild in comparison. There was my
heart condition and diabetes to think of. Was I up to it?
</P>
<P>
   I did face a few rocky days during the high-dose chemo phase
because of my reaction to a certain drug. I once mentioned chest
pain and there were more doctors at my bedside than I had bedside.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  I developed a rash over most of my body that at times would
itch so badly it was probably the single greatest discomfort I had
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  I stayed in the hospital for about five weeks after the Oct. 8
cell transplant, followed by a short outpatient stay in a nearby
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  I had no view at all. My hospital-room window looked out on a
solid brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was boredom. But, you know, the hospital staff
doesn't really give you time to get bored. And, frankly, I didn't
get as much sleep as you'd think.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses and techs were always taking my temperature, blood
pressure, blood sugar and pulse. The middle of the night meant
nothing to them. And there was this very dedicated medical student
who felt she just had to give me the once-over every day at about 5
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The James is a teaching hospital, so I saw a variety of doctors
and students every day, or, rather, they saw me. There was an
attending physician in charge of my case and I saw her every day.
There was also a resident who made rounds early in the morning,
accompanied by a group of doctors on fellowship or whatever.
Usually there were five or six _ I called them ``the glee club.''
</P>
<P>
   They came in for their daily look, and every once in a while
there would be something new, some new ailment to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Between the doctors and nurses, the staff was top-notch.
</P>
<P>
   I was in a 12-bed transplant unit, each of us with our own
rooms. Conditions were kept sterile as possible. Visitors had to
wash their hands and leave any open food containers outside the
room. But there were no gowns, masks or sterile tents. I guess all
that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't allowed to touch the floor. If I got out of bed, which
I was encouraged to do, I had to wear slippers. I was expected to
take a shower and walk daily, even when I was hooked up to an IV
(which was most of the time).
</P>
<P>
   As that doctor at my first interview put it, ``I want my
patients up and around. I'd rather have them sitting on the side of
the bed puking their guts out than lying in bed all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much of that, fortunately. All patients are
different, but with the anti-nausea medicines they put in the
chemo, I had very little nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the mystery rash, my biggest problem was with the food.
I'll tell you right now I don't intend to bash all hospital food,
but for me it was not a good experience. But you also have to
consider, I had just gone through high-dose chemo for a week and
was on a low-fat diabetic diet. So you'll just have to excuse me
when I tell you nothing looked, tasted or smelled even the least
bit appetizing.
</P>
<P>
   It's really a wonder they let me leave the hospital. They
closely monitor your intake and output. My digestive track was a
balance between laxatives and medicine to accomplish the opposite.
Meanwhile, I got by on a fruit, Jell-O, yogurt and a little milk
and cereal.
</P>
<P>
   My tastebuds still have not returned, even months later, but
then that has also helped me drop a considerable amount of weight.
There are a few silver linings.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the five weeks seemed to go by quickly. I probably
didn't think that at the time (especially that first week), but as
I look back now, it wasn't all that long. Once I left the hospital
and the short outpatient stint in early November, the process was
over. There were no followup visits. Everything is being handled by
my local oncologist.
</P>
<P>
   As I have had no bad scans or checkups, I have to believe in the
system. I'm not so foolish as to say I am cured, but I am coming
back. Aside from the condition discussed in the accompanying
article, my strength is returning. I'm casting my lures just as far
as ever, but my nature walks aren't quite as long or uphill.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of a person going through a transplant can be a
frightening thing. As long as you realize every person's case and
reactions are different, it helps to talk to someone who has been
through it. I found a couple of successful stem cell transplant
patients who helped me along the way.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other factor you should consider when going through
the process of a transplant. That is the effect your condition is
bound to have on your family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Pat, has been with me every step. She went on my doctor
visits and spent as much time with me in the hospital as possible.
My son, who lives in Indiana, took a week off of work to help me
through the hardest parts. My daughter, who lives in Virginia, and
brother, who lives in Florida, called every day. My cousins were on
the phone or in the chairs in my room. My friends visited, called
and sent cards (no live flowers were allowed in the room). That
support is something no medicine, hospital or doctor can do for
you. It's called love. There is no substitute.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago my friend Mickey Davis died of cancer. A
few months ago my friend Wally Nelson died of cancer. Those two
deaths and all of the others I hear about now really bother me. I
don't get over them like I might have in the past. I think of them
and This area quickly would become saturated, and water pressure
would build up outside your basement walls and under the floor. Any
cracks or air pockets in the concrete or the seams between concrete
blocks would allow a path for the water to seep into the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest key to a dry basement is keeping rainwater away from
the foundation. If you've had problems with basement moisture after
a rain, go outside and see what's happening on your roof and in the
yard around the house the next time a downpour occurs.
</P>
<P>
   I did that this spring and found a pool forming between my west
wall and the slope alongside my neighbor's driveway. It's going to
take some excavation to give the water a path away from the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, though, working with the gutters and downspouts
will be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Look for leaks in gutters and downspouts and pay particular
attention to seams and connections. Look for sagging spots or areas
where so much water hits the gutters that they overflow. Sagging
spots in gutters are often the sites of overflows.
</P>
<P>
   You usually can fix minor leaks around seams with caulk designed
for gutters. Adding a strategic support strap or nail will correct
a minor sag.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of each downspout, attach some kind of extension
or splash guard that directs water leaving the downspout at least
three feet away from the house. If your basement is chronically
damp, releasing the water even farther away might help.
</P>
<P>
   If the gutter and downspout system is sound, periodically clean
the gutters to keep leaves and other debris from interfering with
efficient water flow.
</P>
<P>
   Check that water that enters the gutters flows smoothly through
the downspouts. Clogged downspouts often can be cleared by
directing a powerful stream from a garden hose through the top
opening.
</P>
<P>
   The soil adjacent to your foundation should slope away from the
house at a rate of at least an inch of drop per foot. Concrete
patios, porches, walks and other solid surfaces also should slope
away from the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   If you do any landscaping or gardening, make sure you don't
create raised areas that cause water to flow back toward the house.
Grass or ground covers with thick root systems planted next to the
foundation also help control water.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check for more serious problems. Once you've dealt with
surface rainwater runoff, dampness problems should be greatly
reduced. But they might not be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   To correct persistent seepage problems, start by sealing all
visible cracks with concrete patching compound or hydraulic cement.
Hydraulic cement is a putty-like material that can be used to plug
a leak.
</P>
<P>
   After following manufacturers' directions for patching compound
or hydraulic cement to seal cracks, cover walls and floors with a
waterproofing paint. Make sure the paint you select is a
waterproofer, not just a sealer, and that it is rated for use below
grade _ that is, below the ground level. And follow all application
instructions, especially wall-preparation instructions.
</P>
<P>
   If all these steps fail, you might have a problem that needs a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Waterproofing contractors can install a sump pump to pump
underground water away from the foundation. Or they can excavate
around the foundation to add water barriers to the outside of the
basement wall or add underground pipes called drainage tiles to
help direct water away from the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact James Cummings at jamescummings(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
