<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OFFICIALS ABANDON HOPE OF FINDING SURVIVORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian navy officials on Monday publicly abandoned
hope of finding any men alive inside the sunken nuclear-powered
submarine Kursk, and began discussions about the dangerous task of
inspecting the craft's interior with a camera before removing the
bodies or salvaging the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our worst fears are confirmed,'' said Vice Adm. Mikhail
Motsak, chief of staff of the Northern Fleet. ``All the
compartments of the submarine are flooded with water. None of the
crew are still alive,'' he said, according to the RIA-Novosti news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said 118 people were aboard the Kursk when
explosions sent the 490-foot vessel plunging to the floor of the
Barents Sea while on maneuvers on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian divers who broke through a hatch to get inside found
no signs of life and said they believed there were no survivors.
``The divers have determined that the submarine is full of water,''
said Norwegian Capt. Rune Fredheim. ``That is sad.''
</P>
<P>
   When a camera was lowered through the partially opened hatch for
a preliminary look, it registered images of what appeared to be a
sailor in the ninth compartment, where normally five to six sailors
are stationed.
</P>
<P>
   With the fate of the crew now clear, Russian officials are
turning their efforts to removing the submarine's nuclear reactors,
which the officials have said were shut down immediately after the
accident. The cause of the crash remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise development Monday, military officials speaking
not for attribution told Russian news agencies that a chunk of rail
from a British submarine had been found on the seabed about 1,000
feet from the wreck of the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   Although some reports have indicated that a collision might have
caused the accident, both the British and U.S. governments have
emphatically denied that any of their submarines were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mystery over the accident, on Monday there were
again reports from military sources that distress signal buoys not
of Russian origin were spotted by one or more of the first Russian
ships that arrived on the scene on Sunday. The buoys were not
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   A previous report about the buoys, which had been denied, said
they were green and white _ not the colors of the Russian navy _
but officials on Monday did not describe them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-21 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE BEAR TRUTH: THE CRITTERS LOVE PEOPLE FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Given a choice, some bears would rather rip your
car apart in search of a cookie than munch on unlimited numbers of
berries nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, bears broke into eight more cars in parking at
the Yosemite National Park, all in the search for people food. That
brings the total to 35 cars broken into this summer at Yosemite,
with the total number of bear incidents in the park up to 406 and
counting.
</P>
<P>
   How would you like to return to your car and find a bear sitting
in the back seat, eating your cookies? The bears often just bash a
window and climbs in, searching for goodies.
</P>
<P>
   These episodes are occurring even with ripening black berries
and fallen apples now available in Yosemite Valley and all across
the alpine zone of California's mountain country. It turns out that
once a bear has tasted people food, they will ignore the natural
stuff in order to satisfy an addiction to butter, ice cream,
chocolate cookies, Swiss Miss and Tang, and other goodies, wherever
they can get them.
</P>
<P>
   They can feed this obsession even if it means breaking into
homes. On the outskirts of McCloud on the flank of Mount Shasta, a
bear invited itself into the home of Pam Cornett last week and
proceeded to search for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rather hot so just before I went to bed I left the
dining room window open,'' Cornett told Gene Eagle of the Mount
Shasta Herald. ``Just before six this morning, I got up to go to
work and I heard this noise. I opened my bedroom door and there was
a big bear standing in front of the microwave.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cornett hid in the bathroom, the bear took its time rummaging
about, pulling the microwave on to the floor. It then left through
the open window.
</P>
<P>
   In thousands of encounters in California this summer, bears have
been interested solely in people food, and not people. According to
the state Department of Fish and Game, there have been no
documented bear-caused injuries in the past two years. Yet the
bears make the rounds at Yosemite campgrounds and many other camps
like post office drivers making their daily pick-ups. It's easy for
the bears since new, innocent arrivals show up every few days who
are easy to pick clean and are often shocked at seeing a Volkswagen
With Hair.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers at Yosemite and elsewhere have attempted to break the
food-raiding cycle by requiring food storage in bear-proof food
lockers at drive-in campgrounds and in food canisters for
wilderness hikers. It hasn't worked at the park because visitors
keep stashing food in their cars and don't keep their camps clean.
Some even bait bears in with food, because for many, seeing a bear
can validate a summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   In bear country near Tahoe, along the west flank of the Sierra
Nevada and in the Cascade and Shasta-Siskiyou ranges, food-raiding
bears also make the rounds at rural cabins and mountain homes. As
long as bears can find garbage, dog food, bird seed or outside
freezers to raid, the cycle will continue.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to stop the episodes is to bear-proof homes and
campgrounds, and this can only be accomplished by keeping anything
a bear might desire secured and out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   With no people food available to steal, they will go back to
what nature intended _ eating grass, leaves, insects, berries,
apples and acorns from spring to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't with bears. It's with careless people. Given
an opportunity for a cookie, bears just can't resist the
temptation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
