<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BICYCLIST RIDES FOR ANOTHER RECORD IN X GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bicyclist Dave Mirra will be riding for his 12th
medal Tuesday in the final event of the X Games.
</P>
<P>
   Mirra, 26, is the only X Games athlete to win a medal in every
event he has entered. Saturday's win in the bicycle park
competition _ in which he pulled an unprecedented double back-flip
_ was his ninth consecutive gold-medal effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's consistent,'' said Mat Hoffman, who has been competing
against Mirra for more than 13 years. ``There are a lot of great
riders out there. But there are only a few who can go out and turn
it on every time they compete. Dave is one of those guys, and he
proves it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed Mirra's steady, high-quality riding that keeps him
on top of the standings. In the 1999 vert event, he did not end up
with the top score of the competition _ Jay Miron's second run was
the high score by a full point _ but Mirra won anyway, based on two
strong runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the total package,'' said Ryan Nyquist, a friend who
rides with Mirra. ``He's got flair, he's got tricks and he's got
style. He's probably the best rider out here right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the most decorated, all tattoos aside.
</P>
<P>
   Mirra _ known as the ``Miracle Man'' _ and skateboarder Tony
Hawk are the most medal-adorned of all X Games competitors, each
winning their 11th medals Saturday, Hawk in the vert doubles, Mirra
in the bicycle stunt park competition. Mirra has the chance to take
over the lead Tuesday in the finals of the bicycle stunt vert
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The run of success leaves even Mirra shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' said Mirra, of Greenville, N.C.. ``I think I've
been riding really strong and I feel like I've got the crowd
support behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   He is riding with something of a bulls-eye on his back
considering he is both the guy everyone wants to be like and the
one they all want to beat. At least at this event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition is getting pretty fierce out there,'' Nyquist
said. ``People have what it takes to be that good. They just have
to go out there and do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1514EDT &QL; 
