<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-PROMOTIONS-HNS &LR;      08-21 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PROMOTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE REAL COMPETITORS BEHIND THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Richard Quick didn't appear to be setting up a
punch line as he answered questions about the nutritional
supplements taken by many of the swimmers he coaches at Stanford
University. He was talking quite seriously, describing how he'd
found a man with a doctorate to advise the athletes, how he hoped
to get this expert to Sydney next month to help the whole Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   Just as soberly, a reporter asked whether large quantities of
supplements, even taken under supervision, might pose long-term
health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Quick said, ``but no one asks questions about an
athlete walking across the street to buy something from McDonald's
that might kill them later.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he realized that he had trod on the mother of all corporate
sponsors. With a wry grin, Quick corrected himself: ``I probably
shouldn't have said McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   The keepers of the Olympic flame take certain allegiances very
seriously. Their commitment to keeping politics out of the Games
never really stuck. Their promises to ferret out
performance-enhancing drugs have been all bluster. But their
devotion to their commercial partners _ that is sacred. It stands
like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   The myth of the apolitical Games was crushed in 1980 with the
American-led boycott. Or was it in 1936, when Jesse Owens'
abilities were used as a rebuke to Hitler? Or was it during the
years when South Africa was excluded for apartheid?
</P>
<P>
   All of those political intrusions began with good causes. But in
1968, Tommie Smith and John Carlos thought they had a good one, and
they were asked to leave Mexico City for raising black-gloved fists
during the awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The latest political tussle involves former Cuban athletes
barred from the Games because their old country will not release
them from their ties to the island. A kayaker in the States and a
track star in Spain want their freedom. Cuban officials argue that
their country supported these athletes, nurtured their skills, then
saw them lured off by richer lands as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee laments these developments
but does not take responsibility for creating them. If the Olympics
really stood for boundary-free competition, then why not allow
athletes to compete for any country that grants them citizenship,
instead of requiring a three-year wait after that for ``sports
citizenship'' to change?
</P>
<P>
   Like the NCAA, the IOC is protecting its teams (nations) rather
than the athletes. Certainly, the fears about rampant free agency
among Olympic athletes are legitimate, but only to people who care
which country won which medals.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC does nothing to discourage the national pride attached
to individual accomplishment. Opening Ceremonies, with countries
marching behind their flags. Awards ceremonies, set to national
anthems. They are all part of the Olympic show, which looks so
great on TV.
</P>
<P>
   But in places like Sierra Leone, which lost native Eunice
Barber, a world-champion decathlete, to France, how well does this
stuff play? The networks covering the Games probably don't care;
Sierra Leone isn't much of a target audience. And if the networks
don't care, why should the IOC?
</P>
<P>
   The IOC does pretend to care about doping, just enough to
varnish the Games. Before every Olympics, officials brag about a
new testing mechanism. Then the Games end with very few cheaters in
the bag, giving the illusion of a clean event. Afterward, the truth
comes out.
</P>
<P>
   The latest gimmick is an alleged test for EPO, a drug purported
to enhance endurance. But the combination urine and blood tests
will not be able to detect, beyond reasonable doubt, anyone who
used the substance more than three days before competition.
Cheaters will slip through.
</P>
<P>
   Far less porous are the contracts for broadcast rights. The IOC
does not let an inch of video beam its way out of the host city
unless it was properly bought. The Internet, that rogue of the
media, will not be allowed to carry footage from Sydney. Only NBC's
Web site has permission to show the slightest bit of tape.
</P>
<P>
   Given the wiles of Internet entrepreneurs, I'd be willing to bet
they could break down any barrier. But not this one. The IOC brings
all of its power to protecting these rights, and when the IOC
applies all of its power, nobody gets away with any nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, in an ostensibly apolitical event, athletes wrap
themselves in flags. Prosperous American viewers, tuning into NBC,
eat that stuff up. And if, during the festivities, they're
subliminally motivated to eat some properly accredited burgers,
too, so much the better. Those are the ideals, the allegiances
promoted by the Olympics: Sing the Star-Spangled Banner and
foreswear Burger King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
