<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-SPECIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIEN SPECIES HAVE ECOSCIENTISTS IN A QUANDARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Released; originally moved 8/11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Giant American bullfrogs are marauding through the
mud ponds of British Columbia, while a scheme that critics claim
amounts to ``ethnic cleansing of fish'' may soon eradicate
countless trout from a Rocky Mountain lake that is one of Canada's
most famous landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   It's adding up to a rough summer for aquatic species in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Although not directly connected, the devastation wrought by
aggressive ``alien'' bullfrogs and the controversial plan to
restore the bull-trout to its original habitats in Alberta _ after
first annihilating the ``introduced'' breeds that have taken over _
represent two sides of a dilemma that is plaguing even relatively
pristine Canada: What to do when outside species upset nature's
balance?
</P>
<P>
   For now, little is being done to combat the surge of bullfrogs
in British Columbia. But at Banff National Park in Alberta,
scientists are preparing to take an ambitious, activist approach,
seeking to turn back the ecological clock by large scale slaughter
of fish brought there by humans _ perhaps using massive
electroshocks or poison _ to allow the return of the bull-trout.
</P>
<P>
   But first the frogs.
</P>
<P>
   There are few things more Canadian than agonizing over the
prospect of being swallowed by the big neighbor to the south. But a
researcher at the University of Victoria has gathered evidence that
the threat is only too literal for indigenous Canadian frog species
inhabiting the ponds and small lakes of British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   American bullfrogs, brought to the region over the years as
stock for frogleg farms or as living ornaments for garden ponds,
have lately started wreaking havoc on native species. They are
devouring smaller Canadian tree frogs and red-legged frogs at
alarming rates, says frog researcher Purnima Govindarajulu, who has
charted the invasion in a study that started in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullfrog is a handsome frog, but such a predator,''
Govindarajulu said of the bug-eyed, banjo-voiced critter that has
become amphibian enemy No. 1 on Vancouver Island. ``When their
population expands, it expands very quickly _ about five kilometers
a year in the Victoria area.''
</P>
<P>
   Local frogs, having no experience of the big bullying American,
become easy prey for the invader, which has taken over scores of
lakes and ponds in southwestern regions of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Govindarajulu said the first American bullfrogs were brought to
the region in the 1930s by aspiring frogleg farmers or pond owners
seeking an exotic addition to the cattails and lily pads. Over the
past few years, for reasons not yet understood, the newcomers have
started gorging on their fellow frogs at a rate that could wipe out
the two most common local species.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure if there's been a new introduction of
bullfrogs, or if something else changed,'' said Govindarajulu _
who, in keeping with an activist trend among some ecoscientists, is
monitoring the bullfrog populations in three of the lakes in her
six-lake study, while systematically killing off the bullfrogs in
the others to see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at how effectively we can control them,''
Govindarajulu told the Canadian Press news agency. ``Or if we can
control them.''
</P>
<P>
   High in the Rocky Mountains, meanwhile, a plan to save one
species of fish by destroying others is winning praise from
environmentalists but drawing flak from anglers, animal lovers, and
taxpapyer groups.
</P>
<P>
   With its turqoise waters ringed by spectacular snowcapped peaks,
Moraine Lake in Banff National Park is one of Canada's great
natural treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the kind of fish living beneath that beautiful, clear
water are not representative of the original ecosystem,'' said
Charles Zinkan, director of mountain national parks for Parks
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas of how to manage national parks in both Canada and the
United States have changed drastically in recent years. Until a
decade or so ago, there was nothing unusual about Banff's practice
of stocking lakes with outside species more pleasing to anglers. As
a result, native bull-trout populations have been all but destroyed
by brook trout and rainbow-cutthroat trout hybrids. Not a single
bull-trout presently survives in Moraine Lake.
</P>
<P>
   But under a new mandate, Parks Canada is seeking to restore
Banff and other national parks to their original state as much as
possible. For Moraine Lake, that means bringing home the
bull-trout. But park officials believe the more vulnerable species
will survive only if competing trout are ``removed from the natural
equation,'' as Zinkan delicately put it.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the poisons, electrical jolts, and giant drag nets
come in. Those are some of the methods being weighed by Parks
Canada to eradicate the introduced species. But a plan to blast the
brook and rainbow trout to oblivion with dynamite was recently
withdrawn after a huge public outcry.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists applaud the concept of bringing back the
bull-trout. ``It would be nice to keep a few lakes in their natural
state for long-term reference,'' said David Schindler, a University
of Alberta ecologist and one of Canada's foremost wildlife experts.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics call the government scheme preposterous, even
cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Real Fishing magazine blasted the plan as ``trout genocide,''
animal rights groups maintain it will cause suffering for the
targeted trout, while the Canadian Taxpayers Federation called it
an appalling waste of public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tax dollars for the ethnic cleansing of fish,'' fumed
federation director Walter Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Nontheless, the eradication program may begin this fall. Once
all the other trout are killed, there will be a wait of four years
_ basically, to ensure they stay killed _ before the bull-trout are
reintroduced from the handful of mountain lakes in which they still
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are removing trout and putting in trout,'' said Craig
Ritchie, editor of Real Fishing. ``You end up with the same thing _
trout in a lake.''
</P>
<P>
   But the government believes the project serves an ecologically
noble end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to restore an indigenous population, to bring a
lake back more closely to what it was,'' Zinkan said. ``There seems
some public misunderstanding of that concept.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1526EDT &QL; 
