<HEADER>
A8069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-CAMP-0827-COX     08-21 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMP-0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A JOURNEY TO CAMP ARROWHEAD
 &HT;    For Sunday, August 27
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUXEDO, N.C. _ It's 583 miles from our house in the Washington
suburbs to the Blackfoot Lodge, the small clapboard cabin that my
son Robby and seven other boys called home for two weeks in August.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled against the verdant bosom of the Blue Ridge Mountains,
Camp Arrowhead is in that part of western North Carolina where
blacktop roads wind like a frightened copperhead through dark misty
hollows of folklore and dreams, a place where buckwheat is a
staple, not a health food, and chainsaw sculpture is a recognized
art form.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in a scented forest of hickory, oak and loblolly pines,
Camp Arrowhead is a rustic resort for energetic young patrons with
a passion for racing barefoot across fields of grass, plunging into
a bracing lake or sliding down a muddy slope.
</P>
<P>
   There is no television.
</P>
<P>
   Water guns and CD players are not allowed. Video games are
verboten.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the rules are simple and few: start each day with a
fresh pair of socks; end with a soap and water shower; and in
between have as much fun as you possibly can.
</P>
<P>
   What better elixir for the weary soul of a young boy bristling
at the straight-jacket strictures of suburban life?
</P>
<P>
   Boyhood, Mark Twain once said, is a state of undeclared war on
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have imagined how fiercely civilization would fight
back?
</P>
<P>
   And yet, ever onward it advances, pressing its relentless march
against the joys of boyhood with its restraints and restrictions,
test scores and standards, and the general muddle of contradictions
inherent in a society that wants its sons to be strong, though
sensitive, enthusiastic, but not exuberant, always competitive but
never combative.
</P>
<P>
   Our journey from that world to Camp Arrowhead took Robby and me
along high mountain ridges where wild hawks soared above the tree
line and into damp shaded valleys of cold water streams.
</P>
<P>
   I held the screen door as he walked out of a small roadside
store, carrying a brown paper bag of peanuts, crackers and a
freshly cut wedge of soft yellow cheese, the perfect banquet for
our twilight travels through rolling corn fields and lush leafy
patches of pumpkins, cabbage and summer squash.
</P>
<P>
   We passed long hours in the car playing ``Who Wants To Be A Five
Dollar Millionaire,'' our own low-stakes version of the more
popular TV game, with Robby earning four dollars _ ten cents at a
time _ by scoring in age-appropriate categories like motor
vehicles, current events and the history of rock and roll.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no greater faith, no greater inclination toward
forgiveness, than that of a 9-year-old boy riding in the back seat
of his father's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``When will be get there?'' He believes I know.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know the way?'' He thinks it must be hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, are we lost?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, son,'' I reply in my most consoling voice, pulling the car
to a halt on the dust and gravel shoulder while I take my bearings.
``We're just...off the map.''
</P>
<P>
   It must strike him as an odd distinction. But he shrugs and
accepts it, never doubting that we'll eventually reach Camp
Arrowhead, as, eventually, we do.
</P>
<P>
   Check-in goes smoothly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Robby stakes out a bunk and gets his briefing at the camp
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   There, a little guy who resists sitting still with every bone in
his body when the math tutor drops in, listens with rapt attention
as the camp nurse instructs him to check his sleeping bag for
spiders _ and his body for ticks _ each night at bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   There's a quick father-son handshake, an even quicker hug, and
Robby turns and ambles off across the broad sloping lawn toward
Blackfoot Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   I brush the peanut shells off the back seat of the car, then
slip behind the wheel for the long drive home.
</P>
<P>
   As I wind my way up the dirt road leading from Camp Arrowhead, a
cool breeze blows across my face, a goodbye, of sorts, from the
Blue Ridge Mountains, and a gentle reminder that no season lasts
forever. Not summer, certainly. Not even boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be e-mailed at: Bobdeans(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
