<SLUG> BC-SCANDALS-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURKING WITHIN THESE SPECIALS: IDEAS FOR BETTER SPECIALS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: 2 Fact boxes below. In both cases, `Tonight' refers to Tues.,
Aug. 22.)) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delegates and protesters of the Democratic National Convention
might've found tonight's offerings on the Travel Channel handy a
couple of weeks ago. Tonight, they'll just be able to watch what
they've missed.
</P>
<P>
   Presented under the umbrella title of ``Travel Channel
Secrets,'' ``L.A. Scandals'' and ``Los Angeles _ Life on the Edge''
purport to present less prominent sides of our city. ``Life on the
Edge'' could use more edge, but offers some intriguing glimpses
into the city, while the only thing scandalous about ``Scandals''
is how lame it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life on the Edge'' offers the Bizarro-World tour of L.A.,
eschewing Hollywood Boulevard and Rodeo Drive in favor of
Necromance, a shop where you can buy real human skeletons, and
Skeletons in the Closet, the L.A. Coroner's now-popular gift shop.
It stops at the beaches only long enough to take in an
early-morning workout, called Optimum Boot Camp, run by a drill
instructor, and to watch schools of tiny fish called grunion mate
in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Visits to CalTrans and ATSAC, which try to keep the city's
traffic in motion, are more enlightening than you might imagine.
It's hard to imagine, though, that it takes such a high-tech system
simply to get our cars moving in the beleaguered spurts that they
do (ATSAC, it's revealed, will trick up the city's stop lights and
slow us all down in order to help buses behind schedule catch up).
Hard to imagine, however, anyone outside the city would find these
segments as fascinating as Angelenos will.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything on ``Life on the Edge'' is particularly obscure _
The Magic Castle is a fairly legendary monument, and Wacko is just
one of the novelty shops in the Los Feliz/Silver Lake area _ but
chances are good that no matter how long you've lived in L.A.,
there'll be something here you didn't know about.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck with ``L.A. Scandals,'' however, a cut-and-paste
job that retreads stories so embedded and rehashed in the area's
history that most Angelenos could've knocked off this special, just
working off the tops of our heads. Bugsy Siegel, William
Mulholland's aqueduct, the Black Dahlia, Marilyn Monroe _ they're
all given cursory once-overs so bland it's hard to imagine any of
these stories once seized our interest (the biggest shock: no
O.J.). ``Chinatown'' is invoked (apparently, the documentarians are
unaware that the story is fiction) as is former police chief
William Parker, as we're given a tour of Parker Center that's
fairly irrelevant to the subject at hand (second-biggest shock: no
Rodney King).
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse is the purplish prose emanating from the
vaguely hard-boiled narrator's mouth: L.A., he tells us, is ``where
a chrome-plated typewriter's chrome-plated tales become a writer's
bread and butter.'' Monroe's crypt, we're told, holds more than her
body: ``Sealed inside are the secrets of her death.'' Maybe they
should stick this documentary in there, too, where no one can get
hold of it. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``L.A. Scandals.'' &QL; 
What: Self-explanatory documentary. &QL; 
Where: Travel Channel. &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Los Angeles _ Life on the Edge.'' &QL; 
What: Travelogue through quirkier, less famous L.A. attractions. &QL; 
Where: Travel Channel. &QL; 
When: 10 tonight. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-SKIN-CANCER-1STLD-WRI     08-21 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-CANCER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MELANOMA VICTIMS REQUIRE FREQUENT CHECKUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: ADDS details about McCain's melanomas in 5th graf)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In December 1996, Don Pawliczak noticed a mole
that had been on his left arm for about a year was growing and
becoming flaky. He went to the doctor, who removed the mole and
told Pawliczak it was melanoma. Pawliczak didn't panic. He wasn't
even sure what melanoma was.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor told him to keep an eye out for more
suspicious-looking moles. About a year later, Pawliczak was shocked
to discover a lump the size of a baseball under his left armpit.
Malignant melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed it would spread internally,'' said Pawliczak,
a 38-year-old software designer who lives in Goshen, N.Y. ``I had
no clue how deadly it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Skin cancer is the most common of all cancers. Melanoma, the
most serious form, accounts for 4 percent of skin cancer cases but
causes 79 percent of skin-cancer deaths, according to the American
Cancer Society. The organization predicts that 47,700 new cases of
melanoma will be diagnosed in the United States this year. Close to
8,000 people will die from it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who had a melanoma removed from his
left shoulder in 1993, had two more _ one on his left temple and
one on his left arm _ excised on Saturday as well as lymph nodes in
his head and neck. McCain has stressed the importance of having
frequent checkups and detecting such cancers early.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the chances of recurrence are small after
melanoma has been removed, said Dr. Gary Lyman, director of the
cancer center at Albany Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   But as the news about McCain illustrates, ``these assurances are
not always well-founded, and no one has a crystal ball. Melanoma
isn't the most common cancer, but it is the most deadly skin cancer
and one where early diagnosis is extremely important,'' said Lyman,
who outlined several high risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major factor has to do with skin composition,'' he said.
People with fair skin and blond or red hair are more likely to
develop this type of cancer because they have less of the pigment
melanin in their skin to provide a natural protection from the sun.
People with dark skin, however, are not immune to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   A second risk factor is having been exposed to the sun for long
periods of time, particularly early in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of the sun damage you get you get before the
age of 20,'' said Dr. Mitchell Singer, a dermatologist in
Schenectady. ``It just takes 40 years to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   People who work outdoors or who spend a lot of time at the beach
or participating in outdoor sports are also at higher risk of
developing skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A family history of melanoma and the presence of certain types
of moles also raise the risk. Most people have moles, and almost
all moles are harmless. But there are some warning signs that
melanoma could be developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any mole that appears or changes in size, shape or appearance
should be immediately brought to a doctor's attention,'' said
Lyman, adding that people should watch for moles that have ragged
edges or uneven coloring and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   About half of all melanomas occur in people over 50. However,
younger people are being diagnosed with the disease more often. In
fact, melanoma is one of the most common cancers in people under
30.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society recommends a skin examination every
three years for people between ages 20 and 40 and every year for
anyone 40 and older.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to regular checkups by dermatologists, Lyman also
stresses the importance of self-examination, particularly for
people with high risk factors. ``Know your skin,'' he said. ``Know
what moles you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Melanoma often appears on the lower legs of fair-skinned women
and on the trunk of fair-skinned men but it can occur other places
as well. People with darker skin can develop this cancer on the
palms of the hands, soles of the feet and under the nails,
according to the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   While wearing sunscreen offers a measure of protection from the
sun's burning rays, some doctors are concerned that it also gives
people a false sense of security that leads them to spend more time
in the sun, said Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a fully resolved issue but most dermatologists would
recommend limiting the amount of time you're in the sun,
particularly during the hottest part of the day,'' he said. ``Use
sunscreen but don't let it fool you into thinking you're fully
protected because you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can see the sun, the sun can see you,'' said Singer.
``Most of the sun you get is inadvertent. It's not from a day at
the beach. It's from walking to the car from the mall or mowing the
lawn for a half hour without sunscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pawliczak, who underwent 12 months of chemotherapy and has been
cancer-free since March 1999, said he spent most of 1998 indoors.
Now he works in his garden outdoors _ wearing plenty of sunscreen.
``I've gotten over the fear and now I'm just more cautious,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-WHITE-MOUNTAINS-HNS &LR;      08-21 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-MOUNTAINS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHITE MOUNTAINS ARE ALIVE WITH FUN FOR FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BETSY FELDSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT WASHINGTON STATE PARK, N.H. _ In the stoic, steep White
Mountains of New Hampshire, a soot-belching, coal-fired steam
locomotive has been plying Mount Washington cog by cog since 1869.
The world's first railroad to a mountaintop, the Cog Railway begins
at a remote spot five miles off curvy and steep Route 302.
</P>
<P>
   We had made reservations in advance so we knew what to expect:
Tickets cost $44 for an adult and $30 for a child for the
three-hour round-rip. A newly renovated wooden car with huge glass
windows, pushed by an old-fashioned coal-fired steam locomotive,
was warming up. About 10 passengers walked up the stairs to the
single car.
</P>
<P>
   Steven, our brakeman, in a two-piece blue uniform and a ponytail
hanging on his back, greeted us and described the three-mile route.
The train started at an elevation of 2,700 feet and then climbed up
to the summit of Mount Washington at 6,288 feet, traveling at only
3 mph.
</P>
<P>
   On the way up, the real work in the locomotive was in the hands
of the engineer and the fireman who keeps shoveling coal. Each
locomotive consumes a ton of coal and a thousand gallons of water
on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Steven's job is pretty simple on the way up. He sits and enjoys
the view. On the way down, he works hard, using the brakes and
keeping the engine and car together.
</P>
<P>
   It was cloudy, but we managed to enjoy the view. The trees got
smaller and smaller, seeming to grow sideways, slowly disappearing
above the level of neighboring mountains. My 11-year-old daughter
Michelle described them as ``shrinking like aging people.'' My
husband, Don, and I took turns going to the front of the car,
shooting pictures and gasping at the increasing elevation.
</P>
<P>
   On the steepest part, called Jacob's Ladder, the train travels
at a 37.4-degree angle. One side of the car is 14 feet higher than
the other. We were encouraged to stand up at this point, but my
family gingerly sat in the secure seats.
</P>
<P>
   Near the summit, the lodge appeared as a ghostly vision among
the clouds. Had it been sunny, we were told, we could have seen a
stupendous view of not only New Hampshire but surrounding states.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached the top, we could barely see out the door. The
temperature was 56, with wind chill it felt like 27. After bundling
up, we went out to discover the lodge had a cafeteria, a museum, an
observatory and even a gift shop. We had 20 minutes before the trip
down.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle insisted on buying a stuffed moose wearing a black
T-shirt saying, ``Mount Washington State Park, elevation 6,288
feet.'' I paid $13 for the memento. My husband was sitting
patiently, observing all the tired hikers and visitors in the
lodge.
</P>
<P>
   On the descent, Steven the brakeman was busy making sure our car
didn't detach from, and ram into, the locomotive. There were two
wheels that he took turns steering, in between using a foot brake.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was a smooth ride down. We happened to catch sight
of a few hikers, who were waving, as we took a turn.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the lodge, where the trip had begun, the engineer
pulled the shrill train whistle, alerting everyone of our approach.
The clouds began getting darker and rain started to trickle.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire slogan ``The road less traveled'' should
encourage others to add this region to their list of destinations.
It is less traveled.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   THE RESORT
</P>
<P>
   Driving slowly along the woodsy road, our eyes lit up as we
approached the beautiful White Mountain Hotel and Resort, set
beneath Whitehorse and Cathedral Ledges in the White Mountain
Forest, down the road from Echo Lake State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Secluded, yet just minutes away from North Conway, a quaint New
England town with more than 120 shopping outlets, restaurants and
other bustling attractions, the three-story resort offered 80 guest
rooms, including 11 suites.
</P>
<P>
   We took the elevator to the third floor and headed to our lovely
L-shaped suite, elegantly furnished with a king-size bed with a
large modern bathroom on one end, and a couch that opened to a
queen-size bed on the other. The suite included other amenities,
such as a big-screen color television and a small refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The best part was the huge picture window. We had our own
private view of Cathedral Ledge, a very steep, sheer rock cliff
whose mountain ledges attract hikers. We were told that
occasionally a wedding ceremony takes place on top.
</P>
<P>
   There were two parking lots at the resort, one specifically for
hikers only, and the other for hotel guests.
</P>
<P>
   The mini-suite would be our home for the week. We paid $139,
without tax, a night. We freshened up and headed down to the Ledges
Dining Room, the main dining room, furnished with Queen Anne-style
tables and chairs, white linen tablecloths and fresh flowers, known
for superb cuisine and spectacular panoramic views.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room was surrounded by glass windows facing the
mountains and even a view of the outdoor pool. A musician was
playing old Broadway tunes on a baby grand. My family relished the
moment. We toasted to our vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   AMUSEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   At Story Land in Glen, we stepped down into the individual swan
boat ride on the pond. The theme park, geared to young children,
primarily those under 48 inches. The cost for each person was $18.
</P>
<P>
   Even though our legs were a little long for this ride, powered
by my feet pushing the swan-boat's pedal like a bicycle, my
daughter and I smiled from ear to ear and sang a chorus of ``It's A
Small, Small World.'' Enjoying the cool breeze, and light splashes
of water, we sat back and watched visitors sitting in Cinderella's
Pumpkin Coach on their way up to Cinderella's Castle on top of the
hill.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, a diehard fan of The Great Escape in Lake George,
N.Y., and Disney World in Orlando, Fla., fell in love with Story
Land.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Story Land, which opened its doors in 1954, there
were all types of houses and buildings reflecting various fairy
tales. Everything from Humpty Dumpty sat on a wall to the Three
Little Pigs.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ALONG THE GORGE
</P>
<P>
   We decided to take a short hike through the Flume, a natural
gorge extending 800 feet at the base of Mount Liberty in Franconia
Notch State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a short bus ride from the Gilman Visitor Center, we then
began the ascent on the trail.
</P>
<P>
   Cost for the flume was $7 for adults; $4 for children 6-12; and
free for children younger than 6.
</P>
<P>
   There were huge rust-colored rocks with water splashing down. We
passed all types of flowers, ferns and mosses surrounding the
trail, which got steeper, turning into narrow steps along the
rushing waters of the flume.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding waterfalls were a constant thrill along the way. One
in particular, Avalanche Falls, is the climax of the walk. The
45-foot waterfall created a crescendo of sound as Flume Brook
entered the gorge.
</P>
<P>
   There are intermittent benches, places to take out the bottled
water, shoot a few pictures and contemplate the natural beauty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
