<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The articles described below moved MONDAY,
AUGUST 21, 2000, in the 'l' news file. The material was filed by
The New York Times Syndicate for use by LIFEBEAT clients.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement
with the Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM STOREROOMS ARE LIKE ATTICS, FULL OF TREASURES AND JUNK
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS-STOREROOMS-LIFEBEAT _ Beneath the great galleries of
paintings, sculptures and objects on display in any major American
art museum exists another world the general public never sees. It's
a locked-up, dust-free, climate-controlled world where paintings
are hung close together on floor-to-ceiling sliding metal frames,
where Old Master drawings, rare prints and centuries-old textiles
are stored in long, flat boxes lined with acid-free material, and
where the temperature is kept at a constant 70 degrees, with 50
percent humidity. This is the museum's storeroom _ its basement,
although these days it's not always located underground. By Roland
Flamini.
</P>
<P>
   AT YOUR SERVICE, MADAM
</P>
<P>
   VACATION-BUTLER-LIFEBEAT _ Two minutes after I'm shown into my
panelled room at the luxe Lanesborough Hotel in London, where even
the bathtub and toilet have mahogany accents and the rugs are set
flush into the parquet floor, the doorbell rings and I meet my
butler. Dark suit, pearl gray striped tie, warm smile. ``My name is
Christopher,'' he says pleasantly. ``May I unpack for you? By Joan
Scobey.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of butler Christopher and friend are available
on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEPRESSION IN PREGNANCY, SERIOUS BUT TREATABLE
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANCY-DEPRESSION-LIFEBEAT _ Gina Tretter, a 35-year-old St.
Louis dietitian, became so profoundly depressed after the Caesarean
birth of her long-desired daughter, Katie, that she swore to her
husband, ``We're never doing this again.'' Although antidepressants
finally brought her out of it, she wouldn't take the risk of having
another baby for four more years. What changed her mind was her
doctor's promise that if she became depressed again _ even during
her pregnancy _ she could go back on the medication. By Lois B.
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of Gina, Katie and Brian Tretter and Elaine
Marshall are available by calling Phyllis Collazo of the New York
Times Rights and Permissions Dept. at 212-556-1243.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUNGLASSES AND VITAMINS CAN PROTECT YOUR EYESIGHT
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-EYES-LIFEBEAT _ For some, the first sign is a ``wavy''
telephone pole, or a venetian blind with ``blank'' spots where a
few slats should be. Or you may notice a loss of central vision.
Such troubles can signal a sight-robbing disease called macular
degeneration, affecting some 13 million people over the age of 50.
By Lorie Parch.
</P>
