<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-EYES-LIFEBEAT-700-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNGLASSES AND VITAMINS CAN PROTECT YOUR EYESIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.  
 By LORIE PARCH  
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
 World rights  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some, the first sign is a ``wavy'' telephone pole, or a
venetian blind with ``blank'' spots where a few slats should be. Or
you may notice a loss of central vision. Such troubles can signal a
sight-robbing disease called macular degeneration, affecting some
13 million people over the age of 50.
</P>
<P>
   Age-related macular degeneration, or AMD, affects the retina,
causing progressive vision loss. Typically, it starts with loss of
sight at the center of the visual field, so sufferers immediately
lose the ability to read. AMD rarely leaves its victims completely
blind; in most cases peripheral vision remains. There are two kinds
of AMD: 90 percent of sufferers have the ``dry'' form, which is
slow-progressing; the remaining 10 percent suffer from the ``wet''
form of AMD, in which sight loss tends to be severe and rapid. It's
caused by the growth of abnormal, leaking blood vessels beneath the
retina.
</P>
<P>
   There's no cure or treatment for dry AMD, and the only treatment
for wet AMD until last April was laser therapy to cauterize the
bleeding vessels _ an imperfect method that leaves blank or black
spots in the vision. Now some wet-AMD patients are candidates for
Visudyne, a new light-sensitive injectable drug used with cool
laser treatment to destroy the problematic blood vessels and avoid
damaging the retina.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous advantage,'' says Dr. Lylas G. Mogk,
director of the Visual Rehabilitation and Research Center at the
Henry Ford Health System in Grosse Pointe, Mich., and coauthor
(with her daughter) of ``Macular Degeneration: The Complete Guide
to Saving and Maximizing Your Sight'' (Ballantine; $14.95). ``But
it doesn't stop new vessels from growing, so in most cases you'll
need to keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing body of research points to the importance of adopting
some simple, healthful habits to help prevent AMD:
</P>
<P>
   WEAR YOUR SUNGLASSES
</P>
<P>
   The latest word in protection is melanin. In powdered form, it's
used by some sunglass manufacturers, including Code Melanin-XP and
Chanel, to coat lenses and block not only UV rays but also blue
light (aka High Energy Visible, or HEV, light). ``Research seems to
point to blue light as one of the culprits (in AMD),'' says Mogk.
``You always hear that UV is the bad guy _ it does promote
cataracts _ but UV light doesn't get to the retina.'' Blue light
does.
</P>
<P>
   SEE YOUR DOCTOR
</P>
<P>
   Factors that affect your risk for AMD include sun exposure, a
family history, fair skin and/or light eyes, smoking and a diet low
in antioxidants. Hypertension and a high-fat diet may increase risk
as well. Everyone over the age of 40 should visit an
ophthalmologist every two years. If you're 50 or older, annual
visits are advised.
</P>
<P>
   EAT YOUR GREENS
</P>
<P>
   Kale, collard greens and spinach contain lots of lutein, a
carotenoid antioxidant that seems to have a protective effect on
the macula in people at high risk for AMD. Taking lutein _ in food
or supplements _ may help, says Dr. Alfred Kulik, an
ophthalmologist in private practice in New York and New Jersey.
``We're not talking about reversing loss, just potentially slowing
it down.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKE YOUR MULTIVITAMIN
</P>
<P>
   Vitamins A, C and E have also been anecdotally linked to a
reduced incidence of AMD. Stores today carry special multivitamins
and ``eye supplements'' containing antioxidants and lutein
(Ocuvite, ICaps, Centrum), but, cautions Dr. Nathan Congdon,
assistant professor of ophthalmology at the Wilmer Eye Institute at
Johns Hopkins, ``There's not much evidence that an eye vitamin is
more beneficial than a standard multivitamin.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION:
</P>
<P>
   American Academy of Ophthalmology: www.eyenet.org. Macular
Degeneration Foundation: www. eyesight.org; (888) 633-3937.
</P>
<P>
   (Lorie Parch writes for ``Town &AMP; Country'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
