<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-2TAK     08-21 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: SHIELDING THE BODY FROM ALLERGIC REACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Brown University student who knew she was allergic to peanuts
died after dining on chili that, unbeknown to her, had been
thickened with peanut butter. A friend faces the same risk if she
inadvertently eats celery. A Minnesota school boy who had been
playing in a field with friends barely survived being stung by
angry yellow jackets. A Pennsylvania man with a known allergy to
bee stings died while snorkeling after being stung by jellyfish.
And a New York health care worker had to find a new career after a
near-fatal reaction to the latex in surgical gloves and medical
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   All are or were among millions of Americans at risk of
developing an anaphylactic reaction, an extreme and potentially
fatal allergic response. The immune system evolved to protect
people from foreign organisms that could threaten their health and
life.
</P>
<P>
   In ordinary allergies, the immune system reacts to innocent
substances like pollen, dust mites or cat dander grains as if they
were foreign invaders. But if allergies are a sign the immune
system has run amok, anaphylaxis resembles a wildly out-of-control
immunological riot. It is a systemic reaction that can kill within
minutes by shutting off the airways or causing a precipitous drop
in blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Allergic symptoms that can lead to anaphylaxis include itching,
hives, swelling of the throat, asthma, a drop in blood pressure,
irregular heart rhythm, nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps and loss
of consciousness. If the reaction is not halted with epinephrine
(adrenaline) and emergency treatment, it can be lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, several hundred people succumb to anaphylactic
attacks, the American Academy of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology
says, because they fail to use epinephrine as a first-aid measure
or fail to use it soon enough. Further deaths result when victims
fail to seek professional medical help after using epinephrine,
which suppresses the attack for only about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1 percent to 2 percent of the population risks
anaphylaxis from foods or insect stings alone. Others may be
affected by penicillin or sulfa drugs, fish and shellfish, milk,
soy, wheat, eggs or sulfites used as preservatives. And some
experts say that as many as 62 million people could be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   While children often outgrow allergies to milk, soy and eggs,
allergic reactions to peanuts, tree nuts and shellfish tend to be
lifelong. People with asthma, those who are highly allergic or who
suffered a previous anaphylactic attack are especially vulnerable
to future anaphylaxis.
</P>
<P>
   Step One: Prevent Exposure
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the offending substance is by far the best way to cope
with a possible anaphylactic attack. Anaphylactic reactions don't
result from a first-time exposure, and most people experience a
warning reaction that clues them in to their vulnerability. After
eating a few walnuts, for example, their mouths may feel itchy and
their throats a little tight. Or after being stung by a bee or wasp
they may develop a more widespread reaction than just local
swelling, pain or itchiness. Such reactions are warnings that the
next exposure could be lethal.
</P>
<P>
   People with serious food allergies must be extremely careful
about what they eat. They must learn all the different names or
descriptors applied to the food to which they are sensitive and
must check labels on packaged foods to be sure that food was not
included in any form. Eating out can be very risky. While they may
ask the food server if the dish they are considering contains nuts,
a nut oil might have been used in preparing it and that may not be
mentioned. Some people are so sensitive that simply inhaling
invisible airborne particles from someone else's meal or snack
could precipitate an attack, which is why some airlines have
decided to stop serving peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   People who have experienced an allergic reaction to the venom
from an insect sting have a 30 percent to 60 percent chance of
suffering a similar or worse reaction the next time they are stung.
Since insect stings are likely to occur when a person is far from
medical care, avoiding being stung is especially critical. This
means wearing protective light-colored clothing during activities
that could expose them to stinging insects, wearing shoes outdoors,
keeping food and garbage covered and letting someone else dump the
garbage, and not using scented detergent, shampoo, conditioner,
hairspray, body lotion, lipstick or any cologne. It may also be
advisable to stay out of waters that harbor jellyfish because there
is sometimes a cross-reaction between the stings of jellyfish and
insects.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know they are allergic to insect stings,
immunotherapy through injections of tiny doses of the offending
venom is now possible and up to 97 percent effective. Immunotherapy
should be administered only by a board-certified allergist with
proper emergency equipment at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Half a million people each year experience an allergic reaction
to medications administered in hospitals, and many more cases occur
outside hospitals. Penicillin and its derivatives are the main
culprits, accounting for as many as three-fourths of the documented
deaths from anaphylaxis in the United States and occurring mostly
in people with no history of allergic reactions to penicillin. They
may have become sensitized by previous treatment or even by eating
meat or poultry from animals that had been treated with
antibiotics. Other drugs that can cause anaphylaxis include sulfa
drugs, allopurinol, medications for seizures and abnormal heart
rhythms, muscle relaxants and even nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory
drugs like aspirin and ibuprofen. Sometimes vaccines,
antihypertensive drugs, insulin, blood products and dyes used in
X-ray examinations cause anaphylaxis.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who experiences an allergic reaction to a medication
should find out what drug was the likely cause and what class of
medications it belongs to because other drugs in that class may
have the same effect. Then they must be sure to tell every medical
and dental practitioner about their drug allergy. They would also
be wise always to wear a medical identification bracelet to inform
medical personnel of their allergy if they are unable to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Latex allergy has skyrocketed with the increased use of
protective gloves by members of the health professions and possibly
with the wider use of condoms and dental dams to prevent
transmission of AIDS and hepatitis. While repeated professional
exposure is the most common precipitant of latex anaphylaxis,
sometimes patients who have had multiple operations are also at
risk. To reduce the chance of becoming sensitized to latex, buy
lined gloves for household chores and avoid using powder or
cornstarch on rubber gloves or applying an oil-based hand lotion.
Wear a medical identification bracelet and inform all medical and
dental personnel before treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Lifesaving Treatment
</P>
<P>
   Epinephrine should be injected at the very first inkling of a
severe allergic reaction, because anaphylaxis can kill in minutes.
Taking an antihistamine is not adequate to stem a potential
anaphylactic attack, and waiting until you are sure the attack is
life-threatening can mean waiting until it is too late. Thus,
everyone who is at risk of anaphylaxis should carry a ready-to-use
syringe of epinephrine at all times (or, in the case of a small
child, it should always be carried by an accompanying caretaker,
teacher or counselor). An allergic person's family members, friends
and, in the case of children, teachers and caretakers should know
how and when to administer it.
</P>
<P>
   There are two versions of self-injectable epinephrine; both
require a doctor's prescription. The Epi-Pen and Epi-Pen Jr. (for
children weighing 22 to 45 pounds) is a spring-loaded auto-injector
that, when placed against the outer thigh, even through clothing,
injects a dose of epinephrine. Each pen contains one dose. Epi-Pens
are made by Dey Laboratories in Napa, Calif. The second device,
Ana-Kit by Bayer Laboratories in Spokane, Wash., is a preloaded
syringe that can deliver two injections.
</P>
<P>
   Epinephrine counters anaphylaxis by relaxing respiratory
muscles, constricting blood vessels, stimulating the heart and
reducing swelling. Each dose lasts only 10 to 20 minutes. It is a
first-aid measure only, not a replacement for professional medical
care, which should be obtained on an emergency basis. As many as
one-quarter of people who experience anaphylaxis will have a
recurrence of life-threatening symptoms within hours of the first
attack. Thus, further treatment with antihistamines and other
medications is often necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects of epinephrine include palpitations, rapid
heartbeat, sweating, nausea and vomiting and respiratory
difficulty. People with cardiac arrhythmias should consult their
doctors about when to use epinephrine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
