<HEADER>
A8097 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BOOKS-EYMAN0822-COX     08-21 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reissued novels offer insight into Civil War
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Two fascinating reissues by nearly
forgotten writers, both published by the University of Alabama,
have arrived. The first, ``The Battle-ground'' is a novel of the
Civil War by Ellen Glasgow, a writer who spent her life (1873-1945)
in Richmond, Virginia. She was a good friend of Marjorie Kinnan
Rawlings, among others, and won the Pulitzer Prize for ``In This
Our Life,''1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Battle-ground ``is the first in a reprint series called
Classics of Civil War Fiction. The book was originally published in
1902, when the ground was still thick with people who remembered
the Civil War very well indeed. It's realistic on the surface,
romantic underneath, a clear precursor of Stark Young's ``So Red
the Rose,'' as well as Margaret Mitchell's ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Mitchell's famous ending is just a harsher
transposition of Glasgow's: ```We will begin again,' she said, `and
this time, my dear, we will begin together.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the same series is Upton Sinclair's ``Manassas `` written in
1904, two years before Sinclair wrote ``The Jungle,'' the book by
which he is still remembered. Sinclair was as much a reformer as a
novelist and invariably wrote out of a didactic impulse;
``Manassas'' is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   It follows Allan Montague, a young Southerner who moves to
Boston with his father, where he meets Levi Coffin, the founder of
the Underground Railroad. Coffin takes him to hear a speech by
Frederick Douglass, who provides Montague with a Pauline moment.
</P>
<P>
   Allan goes back to the South to free slaves and eventually finds
himself at the battle of Manassas.
</P>
<P>
   There's something slightly kitschy about Sinclair _ his
fictional heroes are always meeting famous people, in the manner of
docudramas or Herman Wouk _ but he was a passionate man, and
``Manassas'' retains a surprising amount of interest, mainly
because it's rigorously unsentimental _ at one point, a helpless
old woman is butchered.
</P>
<P>
   Both these books are $19.95 and worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``A certain ruthlessness and a sense of alienation from society
is as essential to creative writing as it is to armed robbery. The
strong-armer isn't out merely to turn a fast buck any more than the
poet is out solely to see his name on the cover of a book, whatever
satisfaction that event may afford him. What both need most deeply
is to get even.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nelson Algren
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
