<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-CYPRESS0822-COX     08-21 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYPRESS0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A delightful time lollygagging around the shores of Sarasota Bay
 &HT;    By Mary Thurwachter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ It would have been easy to drift off for a
late-afternoon rocking-chair nap under the mango, oak and palm
trees at The Cypress.
</P>
<P>
   But then we would have missed happy hour at the small
bed-and-breakfast overlooking Sarasota Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story, tin-roofed house is tucked between two
condominium complexes.
</P>
<P>
   We had picked out a chair, begun to rock and take count of the
few dozen sailboats docked in the bay. There was a wisp of a breeze
to keep us cool.
</P>
<P>
   One of the owners, Robert Belott, a former commercial
photographer in New York, appeared with a drink menu.
</P>
<P>
   The mango margarita sounded tempting, but we opted for a Cypress
Squeeze (citrus juices _ mostly orange _ vodka and a slice of
orange or lime).
</P>
<P>
   The other owners _ Robert's wife, Nina, and their friend Vicky
Hadley, former New Jersey teachers, appeared minutes later with
lively conversation _ and a couple of Robert's scrumptious homemade
pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   It was a delightful afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hadley said the three quit their jobs, pooled resources and
bought the house in 1995. They spent a year and a half fixing it
up, adding a deck and transforming it into a bed-and-breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take us long to determine that Robert has a good time
in the kitchen. His drinks were inspired, his pizzas (mozzarella
and tomato and garlic and pepperoni) were among the best we've
tasted, and his full-course breakfast (juice, coffee, fruit salad,
mango/cranberry muffins and mushroom and tomato omelets) were good
enough to get him a job at any fine restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The owners' good taste in art and antiques was evident in every
room. There was an old piano and an interesting collection
ofstringed instruments and a four-seater ice cream table on the
cafe sun porch. Beautiful c to serve breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The guest rooms are themed to elicit the charm of a bygone era.
The Martha Rose Suite has a balcony with a view of the gulf, French
mansion bed, plantation armoire, sitting area with loveseat and
Corinthian marble coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   The Essie Leigh Key West Room has a front porch facing the bay,
separate entrance on the side of the inn, pewter and brass bed,
Spanish pine side tables and antique oak chest.
</P>
<P>
   The two-bedroom Elizabeth Brittany Suite has a Victorian theme
with antique brass bed and oak high-back bed, rare bird's-eye maple
armoire, 19th century oak secretary, empire marble top dresser and
1800s burled walnut roll-top desk.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed in Kathryn's Room, which has a view of the gardens in
back of the house. The room was furnished with a Ralph Lauren
high-back wicker bed and side tables, oak vanity sink and Art Deco
mirror, sitting area and private bathroom with a Jacuzzi tub.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, we spent a few hours a block away at The Marie
Selby Botanical Gardens, which has more than 20,000 colorful
plants, many collected in the wild on scientific expeditions to
tropical rain forests. We especially enjoyed seeing the thousands
of orchids.
</P>
<P>
   We also walked up Palm Avenue, a block away, to check out the
art galleries, antique stores, and curiosity shops in the historic
arts and theater district.
</P>
<P>
   Other nearby attractions include the Mote Marine Aquarium, the
Sarasota Jungle Gardens, the John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art,
the Asolo Theater Company, the Van Wetzel Performing Arts Hall and
shopping at St. Armands Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's waterfront restaurant, less than a mile from the inn,
serves up spicy Maryland-style crab cakes, garlic mashed potatoes
and a very good seafood gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: marythurwachter(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   The Cypress, 621 Gulfstream Ave. South, Sarasota. Phone: (941)
955-4683.
</P>
<P>
   Web site: www.bbonline.com/fl/cypress/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Directions: From West Palm Beach, a 170-mile drive that takes
about 3 1/2 hours. Take SR 710 (Beeline Highway) west to
Okeechobee. Take SR 70 west to Arcadia, then SR 72 west into
Sarasota. When you get to downtown Sarasota, you'll see the
Bayfront Marina area on the right, at Ringling Boulevard. Make a
left turn. Take the second right onto Palm Avenue. The parking area
is in the middle of the block on the right side, between the
Versallies and Essex condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations: Four rooms ranging from $150-$200. Rates are
based on season. Each room has queen-size beds, hardwood floors,
oriental rugs, fresh flowers, ceiling fans and cable TV. Gourmet
breakfast and afternoon social hour with hors d'oeuvres and
refreshments included.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Selby Botanical Gardens: 811 S. Palm Ave., Sarasota,
34236. Phone: (941) 366-5731.
</P>
<P>
   The 8 1/2 acre gardens is known for its living collection of
more than 6,000 orchids. Hours: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily except
Christmas. Admission is $8 for adults, $4 for kids 6-11. Admission
includes all outdoor gardens, Tropical Display House, the Museum at
Selby Gardens; plant, book and gift shops and the learning center.
</P>
<P>
   Web site: www.selby.org/
</P>
