<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POSTCARDS HAVE A LONG HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Long before the digital camera and other fast
means of sending images, there were postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of postal cards were printed, with a broad appeal,
depicting global landmarks, holiday themes and vacation
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers who buy them to keep rather than send, postcards
continue to be the most popular souvenirs. Deltiology is the formal
name for postcard-collecting.
</P>
<P>
   The first American postcard depicted the main building of the
Inter-State Industrial Exposition in Chicago in 1873. It was later
sold as a souvenir in 1893 at the Columbian Exposition in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Postcards began as illustrations on government-printed postal
cards (with an imprinted 1 cent stamp) and privately printed
souvenir cards (a 2-cent stamp was applied).
</P>
<P>
   By 1898, American printers began making the ``private mailing
card.'' Writing was not allowed on the address side of the card.
Some printers left a wider border on the side or bottom of the
picture side so a short message could be added.
</P>
<P>
   The term postcard replaced private mailing card in 1901.
Individuals began having black-and-white photos printed on paper
with postcard backs, but writing was still not permitted on the
address side until the printed vertical line down the middle of the
address side was added in March 1907. The address went on the right
side and the message on the left side of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early cards were printed in Germany, where
lithographic processes were ahead of America's. But with World War
I, postcards came mainly from England and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1915 and 1930, most of the postcards were printed in the
United States. To save ink, the view was framed by a white border.
Black-and-white cards were often hand-tinted.
</P>
<P>
   Advancement in printing techniques between 1930 and 1944 made it
easy to print on cards featuring a high rag content that produced a
linen-like finish. This surface allowed the use of vivid and
brilliant dyes for coloring. Sets and series also were printed
along with the popular French-fold cards. Political humor cards of
World War II were among the best cards of this era.
</P>
<P>
   Photochrome cards, which remain the most popular today, and
three-dimensional images soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   Postcards also have been printed on such unusual surfaces as
metal,
</P>
<P>
   leather, wood, plastic, velvet and silk.
</P>
<P>
   Some antique postcards can fetch big prices at the auction
block, while others can be found for pennies at yard sales. Supply
and demand, condition, rarity, the sender, receiver and signature
all help determine the value.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Ingraham Heins writes weekly about items in, on and
around the home. Write to her c/o Details, Features Department,
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
