<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LORD WAS NOT READY TO TAKE ME'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PHIL RECORD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a previous column, I told you how I had helped two younger
men pull an unconscious man from the shallow waters at Half Moon
Cay, a tiny island in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   All of us had been cruising the Caribbean on the Holland America
Line ship Zaandam. We were spending the last day of the cruise,
Aug. 4, splashing and sunning on the pristine beach.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as we placed the man on the beach, his eyes opened and
he coughed up water. But his face was a deep purple, and his eyes
were fixed. A doctor and nurse, who also were fellow passengers,
quickly arrived and took over his treatment.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I later watched as members of a first-aid team
removed the stricken man to the ship, which was anchored offshore.
His complexion had improved considerably after they got an oxygen
mask on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Many on the beach wondered if he would be OK. A number of us
watched for several hours to see if a helicopter would arrive to
remove the man to a hospital in Nassau, but one never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Later, on returning to the ship, I was unsuccessful in attempts
to find out what had happened to the man. Ship personnel explained
that because of privacy regulations, they could not release any
personal information about a passenger. I found this understandable
but frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   The man was still on my mind as we disembarked the next morning
at Fort Lauderdale, Fla. I really hated leaving without knowing the
stranger's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as Pat and I prepared to board our flight back home, we
saw the familiar faces of Zaandam passengers in line. Pat took the
window seat and I the middle one. I recognized the woman who took
the aisle seat as having been on the Zaandam.
</P>
<P>
   After a few remarks about our experiences on the ship, the woman
said, ``My husband was the man who nearly drowned yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   I was stunned. ``Where is he?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting behind you,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   I turned around and saw the familiar face of the man who had
appeared to be so near death 26 hours earlier: Myron J. Croft, 75,
of Wichita, Kan. I immediately noticed how the blue eyes that had
seemed so lifeless the day before now sparkled with life.
</P>
<P>
   Croft said he had been retired from the grocery business for
several years. I explained to Myron and his wife, Nelda, that I had
been one of the three men who had helped pull him from the water.
</P>
<P>
   As we chatted happily, a man sitting one seat away from Myron
introduced himself as the doctor who had ministered to him on the
beach. It was the first time that the Crofts had seen him since the
near-calamity. The doctor said he was a family physician from
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   It was a happy reunion of strangers brought together by a
near-tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Crofts had already met the two men who had done the heavy
lifting in the water. Ray Eldridge of Seattle had dropped by the
infirmary on returning to the ship. (I don't know why I didn't
think of doing that.) That evening, Chris Reichle, 44, of Lubbock
had visited them in their stateroom.
</P>
<P>
   I checked on Myron last Tuesday. He said he still had a little
water in his lungs, but his doctor in Wichita had assured him that
his body would absorb the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, I'm feeling fine,'' he told me. ``The doctors
aren't sure what caused me to pass out in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembered being suddenly stricken while playing in knee-deep
water with his 8-year-old granddaughter. He recalled falling face
forward into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I knew I was gone, I waved my hand,'' he recalled.
``That's the last thing I remember until they put me on the
stretcher'' on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Myron said he considers himself a religious person who strives
to help others. (He helps support a boy from an impoverished family
in Bolivia and a girl from a poor family in Brazil.) He doesn't
think it was a mere coincidence that so many people were there to
help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord was watching over me that day,'' he said. ``He sent
me all the help I needed when I was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord was not ready to take me. And I was not ready to go.
He still has some plans for me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Former Star-Telegram ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to
the Star-Telegram and the newspaper's professional in residence in
Texas Christian University's Department of Journalism. He can be
contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
