<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-21 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE HAVE SEEN THE REAL AL, AND HE IS ...
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we know why Al Gore doesn't want to return a significant
portion of the federal budget surplus to the taxpayers: He wants to
spend it all on government programs that he claims will solve
virtually every problem known to humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Gore could add a few songs to that speech he delivered at the
Democratic National Convention the other night and take it to
Broadway as a revival of ``Promises, Promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has a politician succeeded in promising so much to so
many in a speech that took less than 51 minutes. It might have
taken longer if the vice president had bothered to take a breath
between promises or paused to savor the delegates' admiring chants:
``Go, Al, go!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's old running mate, Bill Clinton, has officially been
dethroned as the promise king of American politics. Clinton can't
talk fast enough to jam more than three dozen policy proposals _
The Associated Press counted, I didn't _ into such a constricted
block of time.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sounded like Clinton on fast-forward. At moments when the
president would have used up precious time chewing his lower lip
and/or conjuring up an occasional lump in his throat, the Slick
One's would-be successor opted to step on the accelerator and drive
home a few extra pledges of government intervention in the daily
business of the people.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore crowd likes to chide George W. Bush and the
Republicans for wanting to ``spend'' the surplus on tax cuts for
all Americans _ even though they must know full well that returning
money to the people who handed it over the government in the first
place is not ``spending.''
</P>
<P>
   No, ``spending'' is what Gore has in mind for virtually every
dollar that the government collects from the taxpayers. He says he
wants to use the surplus to pay down the debt, but that's a ruse _
once the money is committed to governmental spending programs, it
will be easy enough to say, ``Oops, nothing left for debt
reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   If you cut taxes _ if you don't snatch the money out of
taxpayers' wallets to begin with _ then the compulsive spenders in
Washington won't get the chance to fritter it away.
</P>
<P>
   Gore paid lip service to the idea of tax reduction by graciously
offering ``targeted'' tax cuts _ which means that certain
politically favored groups and individuals will get to keep small
portions of their hard-earned dough but can only spend the money
for purposes that Gore considers worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted tax cut is not a new idea, of course. Democrats
have been running this scam for a long time because it allows them
to claim that they support tax relief when in fact they support no
such thing.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, almost none of the ideas thrown at the wall
by Gore in his speech were new. He didn't sound much different from
George McGovern, Hubert Humphrey or Michael Dukakis, to name a few
liberal losers of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   The purported premise of the Clinton-Gore administration was
that Bill and Al were ``new Democrats'' who renounced the tired old
liberal dogma that voters rejected in five of the six presidential
elections preceding Clinton's first win in 1992. It wasn't so long
ago that Clinton stood before the American people and declared:
``The era of big government is over.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Clinton's vice president _ the very same vice president
who claimed a few years back that he had ``reinvented government''
_ now strides to the podium to accept his party's presidential
nomination and calls for a veritable avalanche of new government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic spinmeisters had predicted that their nominee's
convention speech would showcase the ``real'' Gore _ as opposed,
presumably, to those ever-evolving versions of the ``real'' Gore
that had been showcased in other venues. If the latest Al is really
Al, then we finally know who and what he is: an old-time liberal
Democrat who believes that the American people are helpless victims
yearning to be rescued by the government.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought liberalism was extinct.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
