<P>
   DEMS-DEBATES (Canton, Mo.) _ Continuing on his Mississippi River
trip that will wind up in Hannibal, Mo., Vice President Al Gore
accuses Texas Gov. George W. Bush of trying to duck meaningful
debates. Bush insists he is looking forward to the encounters. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MILITARY (Milwaukee) _ In a speech to the Veterans of
Foreign Wars convention, Texas Gov. George W. Bush proposes a $310
million program to renovate schools on or near military bases. This
is the latest of the Republican presidential nominee's proposals
related to education and improving life in the military. By JOHN W.
GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-DELAYS (Washington) _ During a summer of frequent flight
delays and cancellations, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater
meets with airline executives to look for ways to make planes run
on time. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ Houston and San Antonio are
joining in a lawsuit challenging a Virginia law restricting how
state residents are counted for redistricting purposes, arguing
that federal funding for minority programs would be sharply
curtailed if Texas adopted the same restriction. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INVISIBLE-MAN (Undated) _ University of Texas scientists have
discovered a procedure to make skin temporarily transparent,
allowing doctors to see up to five times deeper into the body.
Although the technique has not been tested on human skin, the
biomedical research team says the process could lead to
improvements in diagnostic and therapeutic procedures that are
limited by a laser beam's inability to pass through tissue. By TODD
ACKERMAN.
</P>
