<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALWAYS REPUBLICAN? NO, TEXAS IS ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM WRIGHT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lufkin Daily News' publisher emeritus, Joe Murray, made an
intriguing argument in a recent column, ``Who lost Texas? Exploring
the question of when the Lone Star State began turning Republican,
Murray concluded: ``Deep in its heart, Texas has always been
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably he was not referring to those 60 years between
Reconstruction and 1928, when Texas majorities never once voted
Republican. That fact Murray probably passes off as a six-decade
hangover from the Civil War. Perhaps it was.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even a casual review of Texas history reveals some
startlingly progressive democratic views among the state's earlier
icons and trendsetters. Our legendary hero Sam Houston, a
Jacksonian Democrat, openly opposed secession and supported racial
inclusion for Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Popular Gov. James Stephen Hogg was one of the nation's original
trustbusters. He broke up monopolistic price-setting by railroads
and other corporations, championed one of America's earliest state
antitrust laws, and originated the Texas Railroad Commission to
protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Weldon Bailey, Sam Rayburn's boyhood inspiration, was
essentially a Democratic populist in spite of his dalliance with
Standard Oil. And Gov. Jim Ferguson, for all his digressions,
championed legislation protecting homes from foreclosure and modest
homesteads from state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Texans blazed a trail of equality for women in 1924 when Lone
Star voters elected Miriam Ferguson governor. Prior to that year,
no state had elected a female chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth remembering also that, in more recent years, Texas
became the first state to ratify the Equal Rights Amendment. Texas
history and Texan sentiment represent, I'd argue, a rich blend of
conservative and liberal sentiment not far aberrant from national
norms.
</P>
<P>
   When the same voters can elect two U.S. senators with views as
different as those of Ralph Yarborough and John Tower, who's to put
any confining ideological label on them?
</P>
<P>
   Murray cited the last 12 presidential elections as evidence that
Texas voters were closet Republicans all along who just recently
``came out of hiding.'' Looking at the same data, I think a better
argument is that Texas was the quintessential swing state, not to
be taken for granted by either party.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Texas has been _ except for the last two
presidential elections _ a remarkably reflective barometer of
national sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous 16 election cycles _ 1928 through 1988 _ Texas
voters chose exactly as the nation did on all but one occasion.
That was 1968, when our state gave its nod to Democrat Hubert
Humphrey even though Richard Nixon won nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Our increasingly heterogeneous state has become a fairly
representative microcosm of America.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Texas is becoming more Republican. Democrats still hold
a slim margin in the state's delegation to the U.S. House and in
the state Legislature. There are more and more GOP officials in
statewide offices, however, and in local courthouses _ no doubt
about that.
</P>
<P>
   Texas ceased being a one-party state a few years ago. This
change began, I guess, when Tower went to the U.S. Senate in 1961
and stayed for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Back when this was called a ``one-party'' state, the Texas
Democratic Party had a split personality. Its conventions through
the 1940s and '50s were anything but love fests. They were brawls.
</P>
<P>
   Trouncing and denouncing intraparty rivals was, for the party
activist, much more fun than beating the Republicans in November.
Winning a Democratic primary was, in the hackneyed phrase of
journalism, ``tantamount to election.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to Joe Murray's original question: What did make Texas
and other Southern states become two-party battlegrounds? Lyndon B.
Johnson thought it might be his and fellow Democrats' championing
of civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson sadly prophesied, in fact, when his 1964 and '65 Public
Accommodations and Voting Rights bills became law, that he'd just
forfeited the solid South to the Republicans for the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   I think it was something else, too: prosperity. We Democrats
fooled around and made conditions prosperous enough that folks
could afford to be Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   When a good ol' boy gets a big enough mortgage, he's entitled to
one Republican yard sign to show his neighbors that he's arrived!
</P>
<P>
   But it works the other way as well. If Democratic policies make
Republicans, then Republican policies make Democrats. The GOP
Congress will turn thumbs down on enough things that people want
and need that folks will start thinkin': ``Hold on, now! If we're
gonna keep livin' like Republicans, we'd better start votin' like
Democrats again!''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
