<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GROWING-TEETH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS GROW TOOTH BUDS IN BIRD EMBRYOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spelling the possible demise for the phrase ``as scarce as hen's
teeth,'' a team of researchers at Harvard Medical School and
elsewhere has succeeded in making chick embryos grow tooth buds.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a rehearsal for Jurassic Aviary _ the earliest birds
like archaeopteryx sported menacing rows of teeth along their beaks
_ but rather a test of new knowledge about how organs are generated
in developing embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Mice are often used to study mammalian development, and teeth
are easy to work with because they grow well outside the body.
Researchers at Harvard and elsewhere figured that a natural
substance known as BMP4, which plays a central role in the
development of mouse teeth, might be absent in birds, and that
suppression of the gene that makes it might be the reason why
modern day birds do not have teeth.
</P>
<P>
   By inserting BMP4-laden beads into the jaw region of chick
embryos, they showed that tooth buds would develop, Dr. Richard
Maas and colleagues report in today's issue of the Proceedings of
the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, birds have retained the basic genetic apparatus for
developing teeth, even though they ceased to grow them some 60
million years ago. But through a genetic change that occurred at
that time, they ceased to produce the vital BMP4 protein at the
embryo's tooth-formation stage.
</P>
<P>
   In mice, two classes of cells are generated which swathe the
tooth buds in layers of dentin and enamel. This did not occur with
the tooth buds in the treated chicks, presumably because birds have
lost the ability to make these two substances.
</P>
<P>
   Maas said there had been brisk progress in understanding tooth
formation in the last six years, largely because of ``knock-out
mice.'' These are strains of mice in which a single gene has been
deleted. Finding strains that are completely or partly toothless
helps identify genes that are vital for tooth development.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging picture is that teeth develop through genetically
signaled interactions between two sheets of embryonic cells, known
as the epithelium and the mesenchyme. First the epithelium signals
the mesenchyme, then the mesenchyme induces the epithelial sheet to
bud into it. Within this bud a tooth develops. BMP4, short for bone
morphogenetic protein number 4, is a major factor in the initial
formation of the bud.
</P>
<P>
   So far at least 25 different genes have been found to be
involved in the development of mouse teeth. Probably all of them
have counterparts in people. After a knock-out mouse lacking the
gene known as Msx1 was found, a human family also lacking the gene
was identified. But people lacking Msx1 are only partly toothless.
Their primary teeth are fine, but they fail to develop the second
set that replaces the milk teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The bioengineering of human teeth is more complicated than mouse
teeth since people live much longer and need more durable teeth.
The fact that the second set develops later is an exception to the
fact that most organ development occurs exclusively in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question of whether the factors discovered by
tooth biologists might someday be useful in generating new teeth in
humans. ``Maybe you could stimulate yet one more round of
replacement if you understood how these pathways worked,'' Maas
said.
</P>
<P>
   If other organs develop in a similar way, the organ-shaping
genes discovered by embryologists may one day help to repair
damaged organs or even generate new ones in the laboratory, perhaps
using the versatile stem cells that seem to be part of each organ's
natural repair kit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have entered an era where we can understand organ fates
based on molecular principles,'' Maas said. ``The field is clearly
headed in the direction of organ regeneration. If you understood
all the different pathways you could hope to influence organ
development.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
