<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PSYCHE-TRAITS-NYT     08-21 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PSYCHE-TRAITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK SIDE OF QUIRKS IN BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Dr. Anna Fels is a psychiatrist in Manhattan.) 
 By ANNA FELS, M.D.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the many odd experiences of being a psychiatrist is
discovering that seemingly benign traits can have a dark and even
pathological side to them.
</P>
<P>
   A characteristic that we would typically dismiss lightly in
everyday life _ a tendency to procrastinate, a hot temper, or a
fastidiousness about details _ sends up a red flag for a
psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Is this simply a quirk or is it part of a more pervasive
behavioral pattern? And if it is the latter, should it simply be
considered the person's style or could it be part of a disorder in
need of treatment? At times what appears to be a minor eccentricity
can afford a glimpse into a large and unsuspected landscape of
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Shyness is a case in point. I had always thought of shyness as a
sweet, even endearing quality. But that was before I first met
Alonzo in the waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   I saw an elegant, if conservatively dressed, man in his early
30s. As I shook his hand and introduced myself, he flashed me a
tense smile but did not meet my eyes. In my office, Alonzo stared
into the middle distance and haltingly told me why he had come to
see me.
</P>
<P>
   He was an accountant at an established firm, and he had recently
been passed over for a promotion, despite his history of
outstanding work. His boss had taken him aside to explain the
problem: He made clients uncomfortable. Alonzo was at a loss as to
how to begin to address this issue.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the consultation, I knew just what his boss was
talking about. Alonzo's replies to my routine questions were terse
to the point of being monosyllabic. The conversation never flowed.
It lurched from statement to statement. The few times when he tried
to expand on a point, Alonzo would suddenly break off, look at me
searchingly and lapse into silence. I realized that I, too, was
becoming uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   In themselves, these feelings of anxiety did not surprise me.
Transiently experiencing the same symptoms as a patient is a
well-documented phenomenon in psychiatry. Depressed patients can
leave therapists mildly enervated; angry patients can leave them in
a slow burn. Actually, such elicited feelings are often used as
handy therapeutic guideposts. But what amazed me in this patient
was the intensity of the sensations I was beginning to share with
him. I felt increasingly self-conscious as my words hung in the
air. It was painful.
</P>
<P>
   As I questioned Alonzo further, it became clear that his
symptoms of shyness infiltrated his life outside of work as well.
He rarely ventured beyond his small circle of friends, and his
girlfriend complained about his reclusiveness _ he always preferred
for them to sit home. Alonzo rarely picked up the phone, preferring
to communicate by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   To the outside world, Alonzo was a highly competent professional
with some social awkwardness. But the pervasiveness and intensity
of his symptoms suggested that he had crossed the diagnostic
Rubicon from a simple occasional shyness to a severe, chronic
shyness across a multitude of situations.
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatric terms for shyness of this intensity, social
phobia or social anxiety disorder, may appear to bestow a slightly
pompous, pseudo-medical sound to a common human trait. But a large
body of research has demonstrated that such symptoms do, in fact,
define a seriously debilitating condition.
</P>
<P>
   Like Alonzo, people with this disorder often lead difficult and
diminished lives. The emotional toll of the disease is huge.
Studies have shown that a majority of people with social phobia
have difficulty reaching their educational and professional goals
or even maintaining employment. They can be more likely to depend
on others financially and to try to relieve anxiety with alcohol
and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of the very recessiveness of the symptoms that
define social phobia, until recently psychiatrists remained largely
unaware of the diagnosis. And for many people, social phobia is
still experienced as a perplexing series of private defeats.
Explaining to patients that they have a defined illness often
causes relief.
</P>
<P>
   When I described the syndrome of social phobia to Alonzo at the
end of the consultation, he listened with a look of incredulity.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for the first time in the session, as he slowly considered
what I had said, he looked me directly in the eye. For a long
while, we sat there together in silence. But it was a comfortable,
shared silence as we both contemplated the long, difficult road he
had traveled alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
