<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEN MOTHER JOINS PROTEST AGAINST SCOUTS' BAN ON GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Cub Scout den mother from the San Francisco
Bay area joined demonstrators across the country Monday to protest
the Boys Scouts' ban on homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations in 36 cities and 21 states, mostly lightly
attended, came two months after the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the
Boy Scouts' right to exclude gays, dashing activists' hopes that
the courts would accomplish what public pressure has failed to do.
</P>
<P>
   The 6.2-million-member Scouts view homosexuality as contrary to
their pledge to be ``morally straight.''
</P>
<P>
   When she retired from her high-tech management job to raise her
son Will, Jan Tyler never expected to find herself helping stage a
protest against an organization she and her family have long
revered.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cub Scout den mother from Mountain View protested
outside the San Leandro office of the San Francisco Bay Area
Council of the Boy Scouts of America.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the day of protest is the Petaluma, Calif., group
Scouting for All and its co-founder, 15-year-old Eagle Scout Steven
Cozza. He and his father, Scott were in Texas to lead a delegation
to the doorstep of Scouts national headquarters in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, who said she has never before been an activist, explained
that as the mother of a 7-year-old boy she was trying to raise
according to her values and as a leader of his Cub den, she had to
take part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find ourselves in the weird situation now where in order to
be participants in scouting, we feel we are being disrespectful to
people we love and respect,'' Tyler said. ``It's a little like
being a Nazi and saying to my Jewish friends, `I hope this doesn't
offend you.''
</P>
<P>
   Scouting for All hopes to add steam to its 3-year-old campaign
to get the BSA to change its anti-gay policy. Scouting for All has
gathered 52,000 signatures on a petition on its Web site. The
organization lobbied Rep. Lynn C. Woolsey, D-Calif., to introduce a
bill in Congress seeking to revoke the federal charter of the Boy
Scouts of America.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dybeck, spokesman for the San Francisco Bay Area Council
in San Leandro, said his chapter serves 46,000 boys in Alameda and
San Francisco counties. ``We respect the right of Scouting for All
to protest the decision of the U.S. Supreme Court, as I'm sure they
respect our right to continue to focus our resources, time and
energy on serving the youth and families through a high-quality
scouting program,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
