<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     08-21 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Aug. 22. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
warnken(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ As divers gained entry to the wreck
of the nuclear submarine Kursk and declared it completely flooded
and the 118-member crew dead, Russian Defense Minister Marshal Igor
Sergeyev said in a nationally televised interview Monday that the
military might have made mistakes in how it responded to the
disaster. But he defended the armed forces, saying the institution
had been robbed and stripped in recent years and he disclosed new
information to support the strong suspicion of Russian military and
civilian leaders that the Kursk collided with another submarine
that also suffered severe damage, but managed to escape undetected.
By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Embattled Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, struggling for political survival, suffered a new blow
Monday when a longtime ally and aide resigned. (Summary from wires)
By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-WORKING-FAMILIES (Washington) _ Through the four days of
the Democratic National Convention last week, it was impossible get
through a hour, much less a day, without hearing the words
``working families.'' Neophyte candidates in obscure congressional
districts talked about them in their brief nonprime-time
appearances; the party's platform championed their needs; and the
presidential nominee himself took up their cause and continued to
pound the theme as his campaign steamed down the Mississippi River.
And it's not a matter of coincidence; the phrase was the result of
weeks of research and focus groups, and the campaign is making sure
that voters remember it. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ In the lexicon of the high-technology
companies that are reshaping the economy, terms like stock options,
profit sharing, and overtime loom large. So it no small wonder that
the contract agreement reached by Verizon Communications and its
unions, which makes provisions on these issues and many more, has
raised eyebrows. While the direct effect is almost impossible to
gauge, the apparent consensus about the settlement is that the
unions came away as winners and, perhaps, as meaningful
participants in the New Economy that was ready to leave them at its
margins, according to analysts. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHINA-RICE (Undated) _ In a stunning result from what has
become one of the largest agricultural experiments ever, thousands
of rice farmers in China have doubled the yields of their most
valuable crop and nearly eliminated its most devastating disease _
without using chemical treatments or spending a single extra penny.
Under the direction of an international team of scientists, farmers
in China's Yunnan province implemented a simple change in their
rice paddies. Instead of planting the large stands of a single type
of rice, as they typically have done, the farmers planted a mixture
of two different rices. With this one change, growers were able to
radically restrict the incidence of rice blast _ the most important
disease of this most important staple in the world. Within just two
years, farmers were able to abandon the chemical fungicides
previously widely used to fight the disease. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RACE-GENES (Undated) _ Scientists have long suspected that
the racial categories recognized by society are not reflected on
the genetic level. But the more closely that researchers examine
the human genome _ the complement of genetic material encased in
the heart of almost every cell of the body _ the more most of them
are convinced that the standard labels used to distinguish people
by ``race'' have little or no biological meaning. They say that
while it may seem easy to tell at a glance whether a person is
Caucasian, African or Asian, the ease dissolves when one probes
beneath surface characteristics and scans the genome for DNA
hallmarks of ``race.'' By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-TRADE (Undated) _ In a startling four-team trade that
ends the Patrick Ewing era in New York, the Knicks send the veteran
center to Seattle and in exchange receive forward Vin Baker from
the Sonics and forward Glen Rice from the Los Angeles Lakers. Ewing
played for 15 seasons in New York, often with distinction and
always with remarkable effort. But in recent seasons, his injuries
mounted, as did the sense that he was unable to adjust to being a
secondary player in the team's offense. By Mike Wise.
</P>
