<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEVELOPMENT, TECHNOLOGY BRINGS CHANGE TO FRUIT GROWERS
 &HT;    With LABOR. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By SHANNON JOYCE NEAL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Jim Miller's Redlands orchard used to
sit among dozens of farms in the shadow of the Colorado National
Monument, a national park. Now, suburban homes line the road.
</P>
<P>
   Peaches have been grown in the Grand Valley for more than 100
years. The last century has changed not only how the crop is
harvested, but the product itself. Smaller trees, different
pesticides and changing labor pools have transformed how farmers
grow their peaches.
</P>
<P>
   A major difference starts with the actual trees, said Harold
Larson, a fruit pathologist with the Colorado State University's
Orchard Mesa Research Station. Trees are smaller, closer together
and so laden with fruit many need to be propped up with supports
once the harvest nears.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter trees mean easier harvests, Larson said. Pickers can
now work almost entirely from the ground, using shorter ladders
when needed.
</P>
<P>
   The chemicals used to keep the trees pest-free and healthy have
shifted as well.
</P>
<P>
   Growers used to spray the trees with pesticides such as sulfur,
arsenic and nicotine, Larson said. Technology has replaced those
chemicals with less toxic pesticides that only need to be used once
or twice a summer. And some pests can be lured into traps with
chemicals that mimic those bugs produce in the mating season.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban sprawl creates a separate problem for farmers like
Miller. The pesticides can drift in the air, Miller said, wafting
into neighboring homes.
</P>
<P>
   While the homes may be closer to the orchards, the sense of
community that once characterized the harvest has all but vanished,
said Harry Talbott, whose Orchard Mesa farm is one of the largest
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 1950s, when the whole town would come out for the
harvest, both Talbott and Miller said they can rarely find local
workers to pick and prune in the orchards. Local students would
rather work in the packing shed or even at a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year, I hired 24 high school students to pick cherries.
They couldn't pick a ton a day,'' Miller said. The next summer,
migrant workers from Mexico picked more than three times the amount
of the high school students. This year, Miller said, he paid
pickers by the hour rather than the pound, marking a subtle change
in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Peaches themselves have changed in response to consumers, who
now tend to eat a few peaches a week rather than canning dozens at
once.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest has spread to nearly the entire summer, giving
customers about three months of fresh peaches. Growers have shifted
from the traditional Elberta, an even-colored peach that separates
easily from its pit for canning, to tastier varieties that have a
more reddish tint and clings to the pit.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Joyce Neal writes for the Daily Sentinel of Grand
Junction, Colo. Her e-mail address is sjoyce(at)gjds.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
