r w BC-LABOR-POULTRY-$ADV03-     08-21 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-POULTRY-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHICKEN WASN'T ALWAYS AN EVERYDAY MEAL
 &HT;    With LABOR. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By JOHNNY JOHNSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ It was in 1928 that Herbert Hoover's
presidential campaign coined the slogan ``a chicken in every pot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 20th century, a chicken dinner was a
delicacy for most Americans. But over the years, improvements in
breeding and technology have created a poultry farming industry and
made chicken one of the main protein sources for the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just wasn't really a market for poultry meat'' in
Hoover's day, said David Alders, a local poultry producer for
Pilgrim's Pride. The main purpose of chickens back then was to
produce eggs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone did want to make a meal out of a spare chicken, the
bird would have to be caught, killed, plucked, dressed, cut up and
cooked.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of consumers could buy a whole chicken at
the market, but they still had to dress, cut and cook it.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, people could buy only the cuts they desired. Better yet,
restaurants specializing in cooked chicken by the piece appeared,
and then became ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   America has gone from producing 34 million chickens in 1934 to 7
billion in 1994, and per-capita consumption has risen from less
than one pound to more than 81 pounds over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   These changes were made possible by radical improvements in the
poultry industry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest changes has been in the birds themselves.
Chickens have been engineered to yield more meat, especially white
meat, in a shorter time, Alders said. Most people don't even think
of today's chickens as once having been a specific breed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has transformed the poultry farm almost as
completely, slashing labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I operate a seven-house broiler farm, with no permanent help,
other than my 13-year-old son, and still have time to do many other
things,'' he said. ``That would have been unheard of several years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Alders raises about 140,000 chickens a year. In the early days,
feed and water had to be put out manually, which was very
time-consuming, he said. Even after the invention of automated
</P>
<P>
   chain troughs, which could deliver feed throughout a house, feed
had to be manually distributed for baby chicks, which could not yet
reach the troughs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many new houses are allowing growers to automatically
distribute feed on paper during the ``brooding stage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other advancements include automated water and climate control
systems, Alders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have computers that run fans, heaters and foggers,'' he
said. ``I never have to turn anything on manually.''
</P>
<P>
   Alders said automated ``chicken catchers'' that herd grown
chickens from the houses onto trucks for market are already being
advertised in many poultry magazines. Those could eventually cut
labor costs by 60 to 70 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Johnson writes for The Daily Sentinel in Nacogdoches,
Texas. His e-mail address is jjohnson(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
