<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-RETIREE-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BABY BOOMERS RE-INVENTING NOTION OF RETIREMENT
 &HT;    With LABOR. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By DOUGLAS KALAJIAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Retirement, which barely existed at the
dawn of the 20th century, could evolve quickly in the 21st under
the influence of the Baby Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War veterans were probably the first group to get
pensions, but retirement still wasn't even a dream for small-town
shopkeepers and farmers as the 20th century approached. Few had to
worry long: average life expectancy was 49 in 1900, and only about
one in 25 Americans was 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for old-age security had become standard fare for labor
organizers and social reformers by the end of World War I, but they
were little heeded.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, the Crash of 1929 made retirement an unwelcome
reality for millions. The Great Depression spurred more than a
dozen states to enact old-age plans among other relief measures,
but most were restricted to the truly poor, and few paid enough to
live on.
</P>
<P>
   President Franklin Roosevelt proposed ``cradle to grave''
economic security, and Congress passed the Social Security Act
overwhelmingly in 1935. It took nearly two years to set up the
system before Ernest Ackerman, a streetcar motorman from Cleveland,
became the first person to apply for benefits. He got a lump-sum
payment: 17 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Today, older people are a force in American society like never
before. Already, one in eight Americans is 65 or older, and by 2030
it will be one in five.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to decades of strong overall economic growth and the
flowering of public and private pensions, the 65-to-74 agemedian
net worth, $190,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to medical progress, older people can actively enjoy
their wealth. More than 72 percent of retirement-age Americans say
they are in good or excellent health, and a 65-year-old can expect
to live another 17.7 years.
</P>
<P>
   So barring an economic shock, the Baby Boomers who changed
America in the '60s are poised to change it again as they enter
their own 60s, a milestone just over five years away for the
generation's leading edge.
</P>
<P>
   One survey found that eight in 10 intend to keep working in
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leading-edge Baby Boomers are likely to work at least 20
hours a week,'' says Charles F. Longino Jr., professor of
gerontology at Wake Forest University in North Carolina. ``They'll
be returning for second careers. They'll be going back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be much more mainstream to get up and go,'' said
R. Alan Fox, editor and publisher of Where to Retire magazine. ``It
will be like going away to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for The Palm Beach Post. His e-mail
address is doug(underscore)kalajian(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
