<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ice Cubes and Ice Ages
</P>
<P>
   A tray of ice cubes is something of a closed system. Left on the
kitchen counter on a hot summer day, the ice turns to liquid water.
Put back in the freezer, the liquid water turns back to ice. But
the number of water molecules in the tray remains more or less
constant (unless, of course, a couple of cubes are plopped into a
drink).
</P>
<P>
   This basic fact is a key to understanding how icy the earth got
in the last ice age 200 centuries ago. As the earth got colder, the
ice thickened and spread, with a corresponding drop in the amount
of water in the oceans. While how far the ice sheet extended is
fairly well known, a reliable measurement of the sea level at that
time would allow calculation of just how thick it got, and when.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers from the Australian National University in
Canberra, analyzing sediment cores from an area off the continent's
northern coast that was partly exposed back then, have made what is
considered the first such reliable measurement. The sea level, they
report in the journal Nature, reached its low point of 425 feet to
440 feet below the present level from about 22,000 to 19,000 years
ago. That means that the volume of land-based ice at the time was
at its maximum _ roughly 12 million cubic miles more ice than
exists now.
</P>
<P>
   While the research does not show how all that ice was
distributed, it does indicate that the ice sheets reached some
level of equilibrium and stability. But the data also shows that
19,000 years ago, the ice lost its stability rather quickly,
perhaps due to major climate change. About 10 percent of the ice
melted away in just a few hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare in the Sky
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers can get as excited as first-time parents when they
discover new objects in the solar system. It just takes a lot
longer to name them. The International Astronomical Union this
month approved names for several moons of Uranus, some of which
were discovered in 1997. The union is the international authority
for names, and only offers approvals every three years.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike moons of other planets, which are named for characters
from classical mythology, most of the names from Uranus' moons have
been taken from Shakespeare. The new names continue this tradition,
with Caliban, Prospero and Stephano, among others, joining Ariel,
Oberon, Titania and others in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomical union also approved names for various other
bodies and features in the solar system, including Petit-Prince for
the tiny satellite orbiting the asteroid Eugenia and Lolita, Cupid,
Don Quixote and other love-struck names for features on Eros, the
asteroid that is currently being studied by the Near Earth Asteroid
Rendezvous spacecraft. The group also approved the naming of a
60-mile-wide crater on Mars for Carl Sagan.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenic and Old Wood
</P>
<P>
   The use of pressure-treated lumber for decks, playground
equipment and other structures has become widespread, and with good
reason. The chemicals added to the lumber, often chromated copper
arsenate, or CCA, help it withstand the effects of insects and
fungi far longer than untreated wood.
</P>
<P>
   But CCA contains, among other things, chromium and arsenic, both
of which are toxic. So one concern is what happens when old
pressure-treated wood is disposed of. Manufacturers warn against
burning it, but undoubtedly some old wood makes its way to
incinerators where the arsenic, in particular, forms very small
particles that may not be trapped by pollution control equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers at the University of Florida say they have come
up with a technique that may make the incineration of treated
lumber less of a problem. By introducing limestone into the
incineration process, the researchers say, the arsenic forms much
larger particles, which wind up in waste ash.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers note that their work is only in the laboratory
phase, and much more research must be done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
