<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Md., Iowa, Calif., Ohio)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONSEQUENCES: Hysterectomy and Risk of Incontinence
</P>
<P>
   About 600,000 women a year have hysterectomies in the United
States, usually only after a long and difficult consideration of
the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is something else for them to think about: women who
have had hysterectomies have a substantially higher risk of having
urinary incontinence in later years, a new study reports.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The Lancet, the researchers say it appears that women
who have had the surgery have a 60 percent greater risk of being
incontinent by the time they are 60. The onset, they said, can be
well after the surgery, since most women who have hysterectomies do
so in their 40s or 50s.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is the second most common major surgical procedure
for women, said the researchers, from the University of California
at San Francisco. Most of the time, it is done to treat
noncancerous but painful conditions like fibroids.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers based their findings on a review of 12 previous
studies. They said it was unclear why the incontinence set in so
long after the surgery, but noted that incontinence caused by
childbirth also tended to begin later.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author, Dr. Jeanette Brown, said in a statement that
women contemplating hysterectomies need to weigh the difficulties
of incontinence with their current levels of discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   TREATMENT: Report Questions Antibiotics for Earache
</P>
<P>
   With rates of resistance to antibiotics growing in this country,
many doctors have long advocated a more measured hand when it comes
to dispensing the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new study suggests that when it comes to one of the
conditions for which antibiotics are often dispensed _ children's
earaches _ the treatment may be of little value.
</P>
<P>
   A study sponsored by the federal Agency for Healthcare Research
and Quality has found that almost two-thirds of children with acute
otitis media, or middle-ear infection, recover from pain and fever
within 24 hours of diagnosis _ without antibiotics. And 80 percent
recover in one to seven days, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Of the children given antibiotics, up to 93 percent recover
during the first week.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that amoxicillin, long a staple of
ear-infection treatment, was about as effective as newer, more
expensive antibiotics and caused fewer side effects. And for
children 2 and older, the report said, there appeared to be no
difference between taking a drug for five days or for seven.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on a review of studies done of children age
four weeks to 18 years, from 1964 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 million episodes of acute otitis media occur in the
United States each year and are routinely treated with antibiotics.
The report notes that in other countries, like the Netherlands,
doctors prefer a method known as ``watchful waiting'' in children
over 2. Only if the infection does not clear up in one or two days
do they administer an antibiotic.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of resistance to antibiotics in the Netherlands is
about 1 percent. In the United States, it is about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: Simpler Monitoring Device for Diabetics
</P>
<P>
   For many diabetics, the task of monitoring their blood-glucose
levels is an onerous one.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of diabetics need to take blood samples several times a
day by piercing their fingers _ a time-consuming, somewhat painful
practice that makes some patients less diligent than they should be
about monitoring their conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent study suggests that things may become easier.
Writing in the journal Diabetes Technology and Therapeutics,
researchers said diabetics might one day be able to monitor glucose
levels by passing a beam of infrared light through the skin. The
researchers are from Ohio State University and the University of
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Although earlier studies had suggested that the technique might
work, this was the first to prove it reliable, said the lead
author, Dr. Gary Small of Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Because various molecules in the blood, including glucose,
absorb differing frequencies of light, the scientists were able to
measure the concentration of glucose in the diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it will be some time before diabetics will be able to
benefit. Researchers need to develop much smaller and less
expensive monitoring units than the ones used in the test (they
hope to produce models about the size of a portable CD player and
costing about $500).
</P>
<P>
   OUTCOMES: Ear Implants May Offer Social Benefits
</P>
<P>
   Cochlear implants have been used for almost a decade to help
thousands of profoundly deaf children, but some two-thirds of
insurance companies are often unwilling to pay, citing a lack of
evidence that the devices are cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
   A new study, however, reports that over the course of a deaf
person's life, the implants can save more than $50,000 in costs
associated with the disability. It also found that the devices,
used in children who are not helped by conventional hearing aids,
have made a difference in the lives of the children using them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cochlear implants in profoundly deaf children have a positive
effect on quality of life, at reasonable direct costs, and appear
to result in a net saving to society,'' researchers at Johns
Hopkins University wrote in a recent issue of the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers based their conclusions on a study of 78
families of deaf children.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cost of the implants is well over $10,000, the cost
to society of someone who develops profound deafness as a young
child is believed to be over $1 million, the report said. The
figure includes special education and reduced work productivity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
