<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CORRUPTION-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      08-21 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRUPTION-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CORRUPTION TRIAL MAY HINGE ON A SINGLE SPANISH WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ When is a fix not a fix? Perhaps when it's an
``arreglo,'' a word that earns 15 column inches in the Oxford
Spanish Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   As a verb, ``arreglar'' can mean to repair, mend, tidy up, take
care of, deal with, sort out. The word, or one of its derivatives,
is heard dozens of times on audiotapes that federal prosecutors
have entered as evidence in a public corruption trial involving
five men with close ties to the Webb County district attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The ambiguous meaning of the word is a nuanced detail upon which
attorneys for one of the five defendants hope they can trip up the
prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   FBI translators transcribed the tapes into written, bilingual
renderings in which, defense attorneys asserted in opening
arguments, the word arreglo nearly always is translated into the
English word ``fix'' _ as in fixing a case.
</P>
<P>
   The five are accused of using their relationships with the
district attorney's office to solicit $200,000 in bribes from
criminal defendants on promises of reducing or dismissing those
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors say the men conspired to fix 32 drug, weapon
and drunken driving cases from 1992 through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants include two employees of the local district
attorney's office, a bail bondsman and the father and brother of
sitting District Attorney Joe Rubio. The recently re-elected Rubio
has not been charged and has said he knew nothing of such alleged
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are not building their case around debates about the
precise meaning of arreglo. Rather, they argue that fixing, as in
``taking care of'' or ``arranging,'' was carried out with only one
result in mind: the buying and selling of justice in the South
Texas city of Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of clarity surrounding the meaning underscores the
question that jurors must ponder: Were the defendants selling
justice, or simply trying to expedite cases in an overloaded court
system?
</P>
<P>
   Along with hours of direct testimony, the 16-person panel of
jurors and alternates has listened to snippets of more than 100
conversations taped by FBI informants.
</P>
<P>
   The stories those tapes tell are laced throughout with indirect
references to the alleged crimes. The banter heard is a combination
of Spanish and the Texas-Mexico dialect of the border that
effortlessly glides from Spanish to English and back again.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors played the tapes in the cavernous, 90-year-old
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, from jurors to U.S. District Judge George Kazen,
strained to hear. Even native speakers of border Tex-Mex who
listened from the gallery admitted they were flummoxed, largely
because they could not hear the taped conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors then outfitted trial participants, including the
jury, with headsets that, presumably, made the conversations easier
to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors listened intently, following along with the transcripts,
the 4-inch-thick documents perched on their knees.
</P>
<P>
   Kazen has stressed to the panel that the tapes _ not the
FBI-prepared transcripts _ are the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   So how will jurors, all residents of a county that is 94 percent
Hispanic and where the Tex-Mex dialect is common, interpret arreglo
and the charges that have been leveled against the defendants?
</P>
<P>
   Was one of the accused, bail bondsman Jesse Castaneda, arranging
for criminal suspects to get out of jail on bond under law, or was
he ``fixing'' the case in a sinister sense?
</P>
<P>
   A wise listener will pay attention to the larger conversation,
said Houston-based Ramon de Villar, who has served on the board of
examiners of interpreters for the federal court system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words have to be used in context,'' de Villar said. ``It's not
an exact science. It's not mathematics.''
</P>
<P>
   Arreglo as a noun, for instance, usually means arrangement. It
also can signify plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   While Chinese has dialects that are radically different, Spanish
is more uniform, de Villar said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Americas, inconsistencies tend to arise around themes
that didn't exist when European conquistadors brought their
language here.
</P>
<P>
   This is evident in the automotive field and technology, de
Villar said, where different words can be used to convey the same
concept. It also is found in the courts, particularly because not
all Latin American countries have grand juries, jury trials or even
the concept of innocent until proven guilty.
</P>
<P>
   In courtrooms where interpreters simultaneously translate, much
time is lost because, as de Villar said, about 30 percent more
words are needed in Spanish to say the same thing in English.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela of Brownsville
conducts guilty-plea hearings in Spanish whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always with the consent of everyone present, and the
court interpreter is repeating everything to the court reporter in
English,'' Vela said.
</P>
<P>
   The unorthodox proceeding is a time-saving alternative, Vela
said. Otherwise, the judge, who is fully bilingual, would have to
question the witness in English, wait for the interpreter to
translate it to Spanish, wait for a reply, then move back into
English.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio-based lawyer George Shaffer was born in Mexico City
and has practiced criminal law in Texas for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   He said he sometimes enjoys an advantage over his opposing
counsel on the half-dozen occasions when he has taken issue with a
court interpreter's phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just lose something in the translation, or the
emphasis comes out differently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of arreglo, he said, ``It's certainly a term that
could be ambiguous. It's not fair to say that it always means one
thing and not another.''
</P>
<P>
   As the trial in Laredo proceeds, that will be for the jury to
determine.
</P>
</TEXT>
