<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPM     08-21 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ''separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of chemical weapons experts, a photo of a fusion
reactor, photos of a person holding a space sail plus an
illustration, a photo of a bus with gas cylinders, and a photo of a
person using a dental laser are available on Newscom or by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  
 c. 2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEMICAL WEAPONS CLEANUP
</P>
<P>
   Weapons experts at the Deseret Chemical Depot in Tooele, Utah,
are racing to destroy the last of 27 million pounds of poison gas.
</P>
<P>
   About 33 percent has been incinerated, but the clock is ticking.
Aging artillery shells filled with lung-searing mustard gas and
paralyzing sarin nerve gas have begun to leak. As a precaution,
containers stored outdoors were recently moved into earthen
``igloos.'' These enclosures proved their worth in June, when three
155 mm artillery shells began leaking mustard gas. The gas did not
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Not all releases have been contained inside the plant, which is
located about an hour's drive from Salt Lake City, site of the 2002
Winter Olympics. In May, a baby-aspirin quantity of sarin leaked
from the incinerator after an emergency shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one was injured, the airborne release proved
embarrassing for Judge Tena Campbell. In April, she ruled against a
lawsuit that sought to close down the plant. The suit was filed by
environmentalists who feared an accidental incinerator release
might occur.
</P>
<P>
   The Tooele installation is the largest of eight poison gas bomb
stockpiles in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   GAS TANKS LIGHTEN UP
</P>
<P>
   Buses that run on compressed natural gas would be more
attractive if they would lose some weight. Empty, a typical
300-gallon fuel system for a bus tips the scales at about 3,400
pounds, according to French tank maker Ullit.
</P>
<P>
   The company says that the same system using its newest plastic
tanks weighs only 1,250 pounds. The interior of the tank is a
thermoplastic liner, surrounded by a carbon-fiber and epoxy matrix.
</P>
<P>
   Ullit says that 33-gallon tanks can be pressurized to 250 bars
100,000 times, without showing any sign of damage. Corrosion-proof,
they always look new. The lightweight tanks will make their North
American debut in Mexico City this year.
</P>
<P>
   NEW FUSION REACTOR HEATS UP
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a practical fusion reactor have heated up following
the startup of the National Spherical Torus Experiment, housed at
the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   NSTX is smaller and uses a lower magnetic field than earlier
devices. ``The modest magnetic field allows simplified and flexible
designs that ease upgrades,'' says a lab spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrahigh temperatures inside fusion reactors cause lightweight
isotopes of hydrogen to fuse into heavier helium, thus releasing
massive quantities of energy. Unlike fission or atom-splitting
reactors, fusion reactors create virtually no radioactive residue.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrogen isotopes are also plentiful in seawater, and relatively
easy to extract. If tests are successful, the lab will propose
building an advanced spherical torus device that would be fueled
with deuterium and tritium. It would be built in the space vacated
by the lab's historic Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor, which is being
dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   GROW YOURSELF A NEW LIVER
</P>
<P>
   Here's a breakthrough worth toasting. Doctors at New York
University School of Medicine have grown liver tissue from bone
marrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a significant amount of functional liver
tissue, up to 40 percent in one case,'' says Neil Theise, who led
the research team.
</P>
<P>
   The finding has broad implications for transplant surgery. Stem
cells in marrow might be coaxed to grow into any organ. And donors
don't reject their own tissue.
</P>
<P>
   SAILING INTO THE COSMOS
</P>
<P>
   NASA's first interstellar probe will borrow the technology that
brought Christopher Columbus to the New World _ the sail.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of catching the ocean breezes, the sail will capture
sunlight by driving a spacecraft to our nearest neighbor, Alpha
Centauri, which is 4.3 light-years away. ``Thin, reflective sails
could be propelled through space just as the wind pushes
sailboats,'' says a spokesman for the NASA Advanced Space
Transportation program based at the Marshall Space Flight Center in
Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   To catch enough energy for the trip, the sail will span about
one-quarter of a mile. Carbon fiber is the top candidate for
sailcloth. The unnamed probe is scheduled to launch in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   STICK A LASER IN YOUR MOUTH
</P>
<P>
   The luxury-car price tags on dental lasers are a big part of the
reason only one in five dentists has adopted the painless tool.
</P>
<P>
   A dual-power laser could make it more economically attractive
for dentists to switch. Developed by NASA and two private
companies, the laser uses the same hardware to produce two
wavelengths of light. One is useful for drilling teeth, the other
for cutting gums. These two separate lasers now cost about $25,000
and $38,000, respectively. The dual-action laser will sell for
$30,000. FDA approval is expected sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
