are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the days begin to get shorter and twilight starts to come
closer to dawn, the Popular Mechanics test fleet continues to
mature. Here's how these vehicles are faring:
</P>
<P>
   SUBARU LEGACY OUTBACK LIMITED
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you don't realize how popular a certain car is until
you've got to find yours in one of those Silverdome-size mall
parking lots. Here in the Northeast, at least, there are an awful
lot of Subaru Outbacks. Now that we're conscious of that little
fact, we can't help but notice them all around us as we drive ours.
And as we drive ours day in and day out, we understand why the car
is so popular here.
</P>
<P>
   The Outback is a highly competent, all-season, all-weather road
guerrilla. The car is innocuous enough to slide through traffic
without attracting unwanted attention. It's utilitarian enough to
securely swallow whatever you might need to port home from Ikea
_what doesn't fit inside straps to the roof rack. And since the
rear seats fold almost flat with no hassle, those seatbacks go up
and down like a Duncan yo-yo as demands warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Folding those seatbacks fully flat, however, usually doesn't
seem worth the effort: The three rear headrests must be removed and
stowed somewhere, and the seat bottoms, when tumbled up and
forward, force the front seats upright and forward. The gain in
real cargo volume is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Those rear-seat headrests, however, have become a sore spot for
some of our shorter drivers who find rearward vision totally
lacking when all three of those headrests are in place atop the
seatback.
</P>
<P>
   Another sore spot for everyone is the front seatbelts. From day
one, the seatbelts had fairly lazy retractors, and both driver and
passenger would often slam their doors on the seatbelts because
they were hanging out of the car. Eventually, both front seatbelts
lost their latch positioning buttons as they got crushed in the
door. That means that each time you put on the seatbelt, you've got
to fish around to find the latch that has slid down the belt to the
floor. Both belts have been replaced under warranty. So far their
retractors have a little more snap than the originals did.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, despite the cars lack of verve, we remain
impressed by its comfort, handling and sure-footed stability. And
so far not one squeak, rattle or bolt out of place.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don Chaikin
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ S500
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked us recently what it was like driving an S-Class
Mercedes. It's like driving a bank safe on wheels. This is a car
that feels as if it were carved out of a single billet of solid
steel. We'd even use the phrase ``tanklike'' except that it would
be a disservice to the S500. It feels as solid as a tank, yes, but
it's as nimble and agile as any sport sedan you're likely to run
into, very different from an Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   It's also fast, thanks to its 302-hp V8 engine and five-speed
automatic transmission. Here's a car that wants to act like half
its size and weight.
</P>
<P>
   In the December 1999 issue, in our judges' citation for the
S-Class Design &AMP; Engineering Award, we said that you could make a
case for the S500 being the best car ever made. After spending
several months and almost 10,000 miles in the car, we still feel
that way. But, of course, no car is perfect and the S500 is no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   We've driven right through the recommended service interval and
a date with the dealer's service department is imminent. One thing
we'll ask them to check is the climate control system. In cold
weather, we've had to set the temperature control on 78 to keep the
interior comfortable. Now that it's turned warm, a 63 setting is
needed to keep it cool. Definitely not normal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Oldham
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA AVALON XLS
</P>
<P>
   Avalon is kind of a no-name brand of six-passenger sedan and a
Johnny-come-lately to the market. Its styling lines can be called
eye-catching only because they are different. Its angular surfaces
contrast sharply against the smoothly rounded bodies of competitor
sedans like a Ford Taurus. But Avalon is more than just a different
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Word has gotten around, if you gauge appeal by the number of
cars sold. In Avalon's case, sales in the first half of 2000, with
its new body shape, doubled the level of a year ago. More
impressive, Avalon is currently outselling many of the more
familiar full-size six-passenger sedans _ cars like Bonneville,
Crown Victoria and both Chryslers.
</P>
<P>
   For our part, the popularity is no surprise. Avalon offers full
six-passenger roominess in a cabin as quiet as some of today's most
expensive sedans. One key to the low noise level is the smoothness
of the drivetrain, especially the engine noise levels. In
car-to-car comparisons with its peers, Avalon should rank near the
best in noise control. That holds true even when matched against
many models of the pricey breed.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly 15,000 miles of mixed city and highway driving, the
Avalon still maintains this blend of smoothness and quietness. Only
on the roughest roads will the body show some sign of flex. Even
then, rattle and shake are minimal and brief.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is commensurate with the Avalon's size and power.
We ran a consistent 23.9 mpg, with a high of close to 25 mpg during
steady freeway drives. Plus, the Avalon thrives quite nicely on a
diet of regular-grade fuel, a bonus in these days of higher pump
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising is the almost $90 we had to fork over for a scheduled
10,000-mile maintenance and checkup. The work was performed at
McInerney Toyota dealership in suburban Detroit where the charge
included $47.20 for labor. Labor was essentially a simple change of
oil and filter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Dunne
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN LS
</P>
<P>
   The more we drive the Lincoln LS in our test fleet, the more we
appreciate it. When was the last time anyone could say that a
Lincoln _ any Lincoln _ was fun to drive? Probably not since the
1939 Lincoln Zephyr model was introduced. The ad copywriter for the
LS said it all: ``Wood. Leather. Adrenaline.''
</P>
<P>
   We do have one bone to pick. The engineer who decided that the
automatic transmission should start in second gear all the time
should be shot. This idiotic strategy makes the LS feel lethargic
around town and in normal driving. Even under full throttle, the
transmission starts in second. Why? In fact, with this shift
strategy, why have a first gear at all?
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co., builder of the Lincoln, claims the ``American
Luxury'' position for the Lincoln LS. Hey, Ford, Americans are into
acceleration. Give the car back its first gear so it has some guts
coming off the line at a stoplight.
</P>
<P>
   Once under way, the LS comes into its own and it is quick and
extremely responsive. You can carve up a twisty road or a freeway
off ramp fender to fender with your friend who owns the BMW 540i
for half the price.
</P>
<P>
   To us, the LS is exactly the right size. Then again, we didn't
have to sit in the back seat. A couple of our passengers claimed
the legroom was tight. We didn't notice. We were too busy having
fun driving this thing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Oldham.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
