<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOMANDO-COLUMN-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOMANDO COLUMN: POLICING YOUR PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Illustrations showing two computer displays of the
systems are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 By KIM KOMANDO 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With new malicious and devastating computer viruses popping up
all the time, it's easy to forget that viruses aren't the only
security threat on the Internet. Thanks to high-speed Internet
services like cable and DSL, you could also be vulnerable to a
direct attack by computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you need to know.
</P>
<P>
   A unique IP address _ a series of numbers in a special format _
identifies every computer connected to the Internet. When you
connect using a modem, your Internet provider assigns you an IP
number called a dynamic IP address, which you keep for the duration
of that session. However, with cable and DSL connections that are
always on, you typically keep the same IP address as long as you
have that service. This is called a static IP address, and this is
where the security risk comes in.
</P>
<P>
   If a hacker knows that you have a static IP address and an
always-on connection to the Internet, he can use that information
to attempt access to your computer at any time.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Windows whiz, you can change various settings in the
Networks control panel to sufficiently tighten security on your
computer. However, it's much easier to install so-called firewall
software to handle matters for you. (Firewall refers to any
combination of hardware and software designed to prevent
unauthorized access to a system through the Internet.) In addition,
these types of programs provide you with extra capabilities you
wouldn't otherwise have.
</P>
<P>
   NORTON
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorites is Norton Internet Security 2000 Family
Edition by Symantec (www.symantec.com). A capable firewall is just
the beginning of this family friendly package. The software also
includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A privacy-control feature that lets you manage Internet
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Norton's famous antivirus software.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ability to block banner advertising on Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Filtering software to help keep the kids out of inappropriate
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ability to set up multiple users, so different family
members have access to different resources from the same computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Personal Edition leaves off these last two family-type
features. If your primary interest is simply a firewall without the
extras, you also can buy Norton Personal Firewall as a separate
product.
</P>
<P>
   MCAFEE
</P>
<P>
   McAfee Software (www.mcafee.com), another well-known name in
utility software, offers a pair of products that provides the same
sort of functionality as Norton Internet Security 2000 Family
Edition. These are McAfee Firewall and McAfee Guard Dog.
</P>
<P>
   McAfee Firewall does what any good firewall should _ it blocks
unauthorized access, prevents stealth programs from being planted
on your computer and stops programs already on your computer from
secretly accessing the Internet without your knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   McAfee Guard Dog offers a few unique and interesting features.
For example, while many programs of this type allow you to block
online chatting completely, Guard Dog lets you allow chatting while
blocking out any objectionable words. However, even the best
filtering software isn't completely foolproof. Give a teen-ager a
couple of hours in the middle of the night, and he might be able to
find his way into a few risque sites the filtering software didn't
catch. With Guard Dog, you can set allowed-access times for each
user on the system. That means you can tell Guard Dog to allow
Junior access only between 3 p.m. and 6 p.m., for example.
</P>
<P>
   MORE BLOCKAGE
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for an easy, yet powerful, ``set it and forget
it'' firewall, BlackICE Defender from Network ICE (www.networkice.
com) may be just what the doctor ordered. Network ICE develops
security software for major corporate networks and has used that
same technology to create its consumer product. Once you install
the software, it works quietly in the background, blocking out any
unauthorized access and keeping a record of any suspicious
activity.
</P>
<P>
   ESafe Desktop from Aladdin Knowledge Systems (www.esafe.com)
delivers on the promise of a true all-in-one personal firewall and
Internet security package. It's a nice product for beginners and
experts alike. That's because during system configuration, you have
two options. You can use a wizard to answer a few simple questions,
letting eSafe Desktop default to its most common options. Or you
can dig right in and fine-tune the software to your exact needs.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting feature is the use of what eSafe Desktop calls
sandboxes. A sandbox is an operating environment for a specific
application, such as your Web browser or e-mail program. The
settings for the sandbox determine what can and can't be done using
that particular application. What's more, you can create different
sandboxes for the same application, and assign each sandbox to a
different user.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even though you and the kiddies may use the same
applications, you can limit what they're able to do with those
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, knowing which resources to allow or not allow for any
given sandbox could be trouble for anyone lower than expert level.
To simplify this, each sandbox has a learning mode. In that mode,
eSafe Desktop makes a record of what resources are used. Then, when
you switch out of learning mode, only the ``learned'' resources are
available.
</P>
<P>
   How about an easy-to-use personal firewall that provides
excellent protection and best of all doesn't cost you a penny?
ZoneAlarm from Zone Labs (www.zonealarm.com) offers exactly that.
The program provides protection both from intrusion through the
Internet and intrusion from other computers on your network. You
can set separate security levels for each of these, too.
</P>
<P>
   Are you a Microsoft Outlook user who's not totally satisfied
with the script-virus patch? ZoneAlarm includes a special feature
that can automatically quarantine script-type e-mail attachments
without entirely blocking access to executable attachments.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features of ZoneAlarm is that it's available for
free download for personal use from the Zone Labs Web site.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed Internet access is great. I couldn't even imagine
going back to an analog modem. However, just as with so many other
things, the greater the benefit, the greater the risk. When it
comes to surfing the Internet, you can do it as fast as you want,
just don't do it without protection.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
