<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-REVI     08-21 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MAN BEHIND THE GENIUS': SHAKESPEARE, STILL HIDING FROM THE
BIOGRAPHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare is in the singularly fortunate position,'' Auden
once observed, ``of being, to all intents and purposes,
anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a documented record exists of his publishing history, his
real-estate transactions and his involvement in assorted court
cases, the man himself has successfully eluded the prying eyes of
biographers and historians for four centuries. Almost nothing is
known of the years between his childhood in Stratford and his
appearance as a young man on the London theater scene, and his
personality, vaguely sketched by contemporaries like Ben Jonson as
being courteous, pragmatic and mild-mannered, remains enigmatic as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Barrels of ink have been expended in debating the playwright's
love life, his sexuality and the emotional arc his plays suggest he
traveled _ from youthful exuberance into darkening melancholy and
existential doubt, toward something approaching acceptance and
reconciliation. And yet for all the Sturm und Drang, no biographer
has shed any real light on how this small-town boy with no more
than a grammar school education became the author of masterworks
like ``Hamlet,'' ``Othello'' and ``King Lear,'' and in doing so
permanently transformed the course of Western literature.
</P>
<P>
   The new biography, ``William Shakespeare: The Man Behind the
Genius,'' by Anthony Holden _ the author of earlier books on
Tchaikovsky and Laurence Olivier _ is no exception. Though breezily
readable, the book offers no new facts about the playwright's life,
adds nothing to our appreciation of the plays or poems and indulges
in copious _ and often irresponsible _ speculation. Because so
little is known about Shakespeare, all of his biographers have been
forced to venture into the hazy realm of conjecture, but unlike,
say, Samuel Schoenbaum and Park Honan, Holden does not tell the
reader when he is extrapolating from the facts or offering a
theory; instead, he cavalierly presents subjective opinion as
recorded truth.
</P>
<P>
   He writes, for instance, that both Shakespeare's ``parents were
illiterate,'' though this is a matter of some debate, and he
similarly asserts, with little supporting evidence, that the
playwright was secretly reared as a Catholic, and that his
``Catholic indoctrination in childhood ran deep, whatever the
subsequent falling-off in his beliefs.'' Like a number of previous
biographers, he also suggests that the young Shakespeare worked as
a tutor ``in a noble, wealthy and illicitly Catholic household in
Lancashire.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden goes on to suggest that a teen-age Shakespeare was
strong-armed into marrying the older Anne Hathaway after she became
pregnant, and that he became a lackadaisical husband and doting but
absent father. He moved to London during his children's infancy and
spent the next 25 years there leading an independent life. His
return to Stratford in 1611, Holden implies, was not the happy
homecoming many biographers have portrayed: The restless
Shakespeare, he writes, bought a pied-a-terre in London and spent
considerable periods of time there until ``failing health finally
drove him back to his family for good.''
</P>
<P>
   As for other controversies in Shakespeare scholarship, Holden
contends that the Sonnets ``should not be taken _ as they so often
are _ to suggest that Shakespeare himself was homosexual.'' He
looks at the usual suspects identified as the so-called ``Dark
Lady'' of the Sonnets (including a married woman named Jeanette
Davenant, who gave birth to a child, believed by some to be
Shakespeare's illegitimate son), but concludes that it is perhaps
best, in Anthony Burgess' words, to leave the Dark Lady
``anonymous, even composite,'' an icon of ``some of the commonest
experiences known to men.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on in this biography, Holden wisely observes that ``we
must remain ever vigilant against too readily reading the poet's
own sentiments into those of his characters.'' But he then proceeds
to do exactly that, uncovering autobiographical clues everywhere he
looks. He describes ``The Merchant of Venice'' as a parable
exploring Shakespeare's ``lifelong ambivalence about money, with
especial reference to the usury which had so haunted his stricken
father.'' He writes that the Sonnets, ``Othello'' and ``The
Winter's Tale'' make it ``hard to resist the conclusion that the
poet capable of evoking the `green-eyed monster' in such violent
language must have experienced its unique horrors himself,'' and he
further suggests that an adulterous love affair might have spurred
the playwright to the bravura writing in ``Antony and Cleopatra.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden adds that the playwright's grief over the death of his
11-year-old son, Hamnet, in 1596 ``becomes a recurring strain in
his work, through `Hamlet' to `The Winter's Tale,''' and that his
``preoccupation with his daughters'' _ ``sharpened by years of
guilty absenteeism'' _ surfaces in the plays from ``Lear'' onward.
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of highly speculative observations linking
Shakespeare's life and art are about the only form of original
literary criticism Holden has to offer in this book. Clearly
insecure about his own ability to render critical appraisals,
Holden tends to confine himself to expressing bland platitudes
(Shakespeare achieved ``a level of intelligence, honesty, wit and
humanity unmatched in any other era'') or summarizing the opinions
of others. When on the rare occasion he attempts to assess a play
himself, the results verge on the laughable. Of ``Titus
Andronicus'' he writes: ```Titus' has always been notoriously hard
going for both cast and audiences; if not laughed off the stage, it
requires extra paramedics to cope with the number of fainting
spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the strongest portions of this book have to do with
Holden's depictions of the theatrical world in which Shakespeare
came of age. He does a nimble job of sketching in the rivalries of
the day, as well as the fashions in writing, which Shakespeare both
exploited and transcended. He gives the reader a succinct overview
of the historical backdrop to the playwright's life, while also
providing insights into how political developments _ and changes in
the theater _ might have affected Shakespeare's writing.
</P>
<P>
   None of this has the hard-earned specificity of serious
scholarship, but instead feels fuzzily atmospheric and
impressionistic. In fact ``Shakespeare: The Man Behind the Genius''
is perhaps best read not as a work of biography, but as a kind of
historical novel starring a playwright as its conquering hero.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WILLIAM SHAKESPEARE: The Man Behind the Genius'
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Holden
</P>
<P>
   367 pages. Little, Brown &AMP; Co. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
