<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HATE-CRIME-1STLD-WRIT     08-21 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIME-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIF. COLLEGE STUDENT CHARGED WITH COMMITTING A HATE CRIME
AGAINST GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: FIXES spelling in 8th graf, Gatos not Gates, and 13th
graf, word not work.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A college student has been charged with a hate
crime after allegedly calling two men standing in front of a Los
Gatos, Calif., hair salon ``faggots'' and assaulting one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ellsworth, 21, a senior majoring in business economics at
the University of California at Santa Barbara, was arrested early
Friday morning and charged with battery and interference with the
exercise of civil rights. He was booked into the Santa Clara County
jail and released four hours later, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Gatos police spokesman said it was the first time in at
least 12 years that an alleged hate crime had occurred in Los
Gatos.
</P>
<P>
   Both charges are misdemeanors, but the civil rights charge falls
under the state's hate-crime statute, increasing possible
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth and his attorney, Joe O'Sullivan of San Francisco,
denied the charges Saturday. Ellsworth said he was shocked to learn
that Los Gatos police had made the charges public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea of the severity of the situation,'' he said when
contacted by a reporter. ``In my opinion, I was just defending
myself.'' He claimed one of the alleged victims had punched him
while the other held him in a headlock.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth said he was too stunned to provide further details.
But he said he never used the word ``faggots'' or said anything at
all, and he said he had no hostility toward homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Los Gatos/Monte Sereno Police Department
statement, the alleged altercation occurred a few minutes before 2
a.m. Friday in front of the hair salon.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the victim, who was not named, was talking to his
brother about ``career plans after graduation from cosmetology
school'' when Ellsworth and two other men approached them and
called them ``faggots.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth allegedly attacked the victim, injuring his jaw and
knees, police said, adding that the three men then fled but
Ellsworth was stopped and arrested soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   According to O'Sullivan, the word ``faggots'' may have been used
but not by Ellsworth.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan confirmed that the young man had fled the scene, but
said the alleged victim and his brother pursued him and then
attacked him, chipping one of his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client walked away,'' O'Sullivan said. ``These two
individuals who were apparently gay went after him because they
were bigger. My client ran. They chased him. He made a stand and
that's when they engaged in the fighting and the police rolled up.
If any pejorative words were used, they were not used by Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth declined to say who might have used the derogatory
word. Nor would he comment when asked if he believed he had been
mistakenly identified.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, the Santa Clara County Sheriff's Office
reported 11 hate crimes of all kinds in 1999 in the county,
excluding San Jose. That city's police department reported 43 in
1998, the last year for which it had data.
</P>
</TEXT>
