<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8172 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WRITING-PHYSICIAN     08-21 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WRITING-PHYSICIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY DOCTOR THE AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD MARKEL, M.D.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each year it seems that more and more physicians are putting
aside their stethoscopes for word processors. The most casual look
at publishers' book lists or major magazines and newspapers
demonstrates that an increasing cadre of doctors is writing
best-selling works of nonfiction, novels, plays, motion pictures
and essays. Even professional conferences are being held to
encourage physicians with literary aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been writing about their patients since at least
the time of Hippocrates. For most of this vast stretch of time, the
writing was confined to an audience of other physicians, and the
main goal was to inform them about the natural history of disease,
but today's era is characterized by the presentation of medical
narratives to large lay audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The mass appeal of this literary genre is hardly surprising.
What could be more central to the understanding of the human
condition than a reflection on the diseases to which we are all
susceptible? Perhaps more to the point, doctor stories are dramatic
with clear beginnings, middles and ends.
</P>
<P>
   To many observers, the practice of medicine and the writing of
books seem disparate, despite exemplars like the
playwright-physician Anton Chekhov and the poet-pediatrician
William Carlos Williams. Those who practice these dual crafts
fervently defend how complementary they are. Dr. Sherwin B. Nuland,
the National Book Award-winning author of ``How We Die,''
explained:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a surgeon who has been at this calling for a very long
time, and even the least introspective of us cannot escape without
having developed an entire steamer trunkful of experiences,
impressions, philosophies and musings on the human condition,
values and ethics. Writing brings everything forward. It enables us
to recall things as they were experienced by us while they were
happening; it enables us to find out what we think, often for the
first time; it is a process that is totally honest if we are
willing to allow ourselves to feel those emotions that are coming
forth from preserved memories and then scribble the accompanying
words down, uncensored.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Verghese, an internist who wrote the AIDS memoir ``My
Own Country,'' said of the dual roles: ``To me, they're a seamless
enterprise. I'm really struck by how much of what I learned in
medical school has helped me to be a writer, and how much of what I
learn as a writer helps my thinking as a physician. They are very
parallel disciplines. When you take a patient's clinical history,
what is that but a story? What makes a good doctor is that he or
she takes the story down well, sees the links and makes the
connections toward a diagnosis. That's also what writing is
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent medical journals regularly feature personal
essays by physicians about their experiences. The best-known
column, ``A Piece of My Mind,'' has run in The Journal of the
American Medical Association each week for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Roxanne Young, who has edited this series since 1984, said she
receives more than 400 submissions a year from doctors around the
world, even though only about 10 percent make it into print. These
stories have been widely anthologized and taught in medical
schools, and have inspired two books of collected essays.
</P>
<P>
   What compels busy physicians to reveal their thoughts and
feelings to a readership of more than 400,000 clinical peers? Young
believes that the simple act of writing is a catharsis, a part of
the self-healing process that allows doctors to confront troubling
issues _ fear, failure, guilt _ and to resolve them from within. It
is also a means to honor a patient for helping them to come to
grips not only with death but with life.
</P>
<P>
   As more physicians take to the pen, professional conferences
have sprouted to bring them together for readings of their work,
lectures and workshops on the rewards and pitfalls of being a
doctor-writer. The largest such symposium held so far was the
Narrative Matters conference sponsored by the health policy journal
Health Affairs and the W.K. Kellogg Foundation this past March.
</P>
<P>
   It brought together leading physician-writers in the United
States with interested editors and policy makers. More than 70
participants discussed the parallels of creating literature and
doctoring.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fitzhugh Mullan, a pediatrician who wrote ``Vital Signs,'' a
memoir about overcoming cancer, organized the conference with
specific goals in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give the genre a clearer and more prominent
role,'' . Mullan said, ``to stir the pot of the narrative essay as
it relates to medical practice and health policy. I really believe
that amidst the increasingly powerful quantitative science that
exists today, human observation remains and should remain an
important force in the forming of opinion in the national dialogue
on health matters.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most serious debates in the field has to do with
confidentiality. Since antiquity, doctors have promised patients
not to discuss their individual cases, except with other doctors,
both as a means of protection and to encourage frank patient-doctor
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   When writing about a particular patient, most doctor-writers
will change the name and identifying details. But sometimes
mistakes are made. In 1926, Dr. William Carlos Williams heard a
remarkable story about a person while on his medical rounds. As was
his habit, he wrote it down quickly as it was told to him without
changing any of the details. Several months later, when he sent the
story off to a magazine, he forgot to change the subject's name.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams recounted in ``The Autobiography of William Carlos
Williams,'' the subject recognized himself immediately and promptly
brought a lawsuit against the physician for what was then the
princely sum of $15,000. Williams settled for $5,000, an amount
that equaled his annual salary, and never made that mistake again.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants in the Narrative Matters conference argued for
obtaining written permission or informed consent and even showing
the article or essay to the patient before publishing it. Many
others argued that such steps were not necessary, provided that the
author changed the obvious identifying features and at least asked
for oral consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My patients haven't been particularly aware of or worried
about my writing about them,'' Mullan said, ``but many colleagues
have expressed concern since I have written about my life in
medicine. Not infrequently, I have had friends say in my presence,
be nice to Fitz or you'll wind up in his next book. They are only
half-kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   This points up the problem that the art of writing is
cannibalistic in nature and the telling of great stories often
fails to meet the medical profession's ethical standards of
studying patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nuland observes that there is no possibility of considerations
of ethics, confidentiality or even loyalty to participants, only
what the writer feels is the truth of what he is describing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I change the names, and never consider the consequences of the
text that results from the process,'' he said. ``Others have
written that all writers ultimately betray those who are their
subjects, but they would betray themselves if it were otherwise.
Writing is not an exercise in discretion, it is an exercise in
truth. In this sense, the story belongs to the storyteller, because
he is the truth seeker.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in medicine who believe in the power of stories and
the importance of communicating them to a wide audience, there
seems to be agreement with Chekhov, who in 1888 wrote to his
publisher: ``I have two professions and not one. Medicine is my
lawful wife and literature is my mistress. When I get tired of one,
I spend the night with the other. Though it's disorderly, it's not
so dull and besides, neither loses anything through my
infidelity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
