<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8185 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-THEODOREWHITE-BOOK-11     08-21 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEODOREWHITE-BOOK-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSIC BOOK ON 1960 CAMPAIGN CHANGED POLITICS AND JOURNALISM
FOREVER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JEFF GUINN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No less an authority than David Halberstam believes that ```The
Making of the President 1960' changed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore White's seminal work on campaign politics won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1961, stayed on the bestseller list for 56
consecutive weeks; although it is out of print (except for a $45.95
library edition from Buccaneer Press), you can find hardcover and
paperback editions in most used bookstores. To read it, some of
today's most distinguished journalists and scholars insist, is to
hold history in your hands _ and to understand how we arrived at
today's exhaustive presidential campaign process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy White showed every other journalist how to write about
presidential politics,'' declares Halberstam, himself a Pulitzer
Prize winner and author of history-defining books like'' The Best
and the Brightest'' and ``The Powers That Be.'' ``He took something
everyone knew a little bit about and showed how all the pieces fit
together _ primaries, using TV, everything behind the scenes. It
was a major upgrade intellectually that educated his readers, too.
The book transformed my own ambitions. Think about it _ he took a
story where everybody already knew the ending and still made it
read like a cliffhanger.''
</P>
<P>
   But White's book was far more than a primer for aspiring
political journalists. It was a guidebook for a whole new way of
waging political campaigns that would dramatically change America's
electoral system. In ``The Making of the President 1960,'' White
showed prospective candidates how to run modern, media-saturated
campaigns, and showed state officials how to get their states more
influence in the presidential process.
</P>
<P>
   White's book, says presidential-campaign scholar Paul Boller of
Fort Worth, made a definitive impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it changed the way newspapers and magazines and books
presented campaign coverage,'' says Boller, whose own book
``Presidential Campaigns'' (Oxford University Press, paperback,
$15.95) is in its third printing. ``It changed the perception, and,
eventually, the importance, of state primaries. White was the first
one to demonstrate how a candidate could use the primaries to win
the nomination, instead of relying on bargaining for delegate votes
at the convention. That was just a huge thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no exaggeration to say that if you hate the drawn-out,
state-by-state presidential campaign process that glorifies
political strategy and campaign operatives, and reduces the
elections' significance to that of a horse race, Theodore White
deserves some of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``That campaign he wrote about, 1960, was a turning point in
American politics even without his book,'' Halberstam says. ``TV
was becoming more of a force, Kennedy proved how the primaries
could be a tool to getting your party's nomination. People would
eventually have figured these things out anyway. But (White's book)
captured it all and made it easy to understand. So he was a part of
the process of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to White's book, most voters and politicians considered
state primaries a sideshow to the real nominating events _ national
conventions. Major-party nominees were chosen by powerful insiders
behind closed doors or, on occasion, on the convention floor by
delegates. Front-runners for the nominations rarely wasted time on
primaries; in 1956, Democratic front-runner Adlai Stevenson,
following tradition, didn't plan on actively campaigning in the
country's few primaries. But when dark-horse opponent Estes
Kefauver did campaign and won 84 percent of the vote in New
Hampshire, Stevenson was forced to spend money and time in the
remaining primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Few members of the media paid any attention, as Stevenson
coasted to the nomination as expected. But Massachusetts Sen. John
F. Kennedy did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy decided he would use the primaries to win the
nomination, since he wasn't all that well-known nationally,''
Boller says. ``White was there to write about how he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, 16 states had presidential primaries. Kennedy entered,
and won, just seven. He used the Wisconsin primary against
Minnesota Sen. Hubert Humphrey to prove to party movers and shakers
that he could win votes in farm communities, and he contested West
Virginia, again opposing Humphrey, as evidence that a Catholic
could carry a heavily Protestant state. Though his primary
victories earned Kennedy only 134 delegate votes of the 761 he
needed to win the nomination, his point was made with party
heavyweights, and he was nominated on the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   White, a former Time magazine correspondent who turned to a book
about the presidential election during a low point in his career,
provided detailed accounts of these primary battles in 1960. His
compelling descriptions of the inner workings of the campaigns
intrigued the national media, which had provided scant coverage of
them. Beginning in 1964, reporters began blanketing primary states
for the first time, and more candidates began taking them
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   This had a twofold effect. Candidates who wanted to bypass the
party power structure and benefit from increased media attention
began entering more primaries, and more states wanted to hold
primaries of their own. In 1964, only one state added a primary,
increasing the total to 17 state presidential primaries, but there
was ``five times the media coverage'' compared with four years
previously, according to Halberstam. By 1972, 21 states had
primaries. In 1980, the number had jumped to 36. In 2000, there
were 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wanted a piece of it,'' recalls author/playwright
Larry L. King, who worked on the Kennedy/Johnson campaign staff in
1960. ``White had shown why primaries ought to get a lot of
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   As more states added presidential primaries, the power to
nominate swung from party power brokers to voters. The old
tradition of multiple convention votes and behind-the-scenes
bartering for delegate support abruptly ended. Since White's book
and the subsequent expansion of the state primary system, neither
major party has taken more than a single vote to determine its
nominee for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``George McGovern in 1972 was the first real example'' of the
change, Boller says. ``The party bosses certainly didn't want him,
but he came into the Democratic convention with a majority of the
delegates already pledged to him, so he got the nomination. (Maine
Sen.) Ed Muskie was supposed to be the shoo-in nominee. But
McGovern did with Muskie what Kennedy did with Humphrey _ faced him
in early primaries and beat him. That made the media label McGovern
the front-runner, and that is what he stayed. The strategy he
followed was in White's book, and he obviously read it.''
</P>
<P>
   With McGovern's surprising success, White's books _ he wrote
``Making of the President'' accounts of the 1964, '68 and '72
elections as well _ became not just must-reads, but guidebooks for
a slew of presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Democrat Jimmy Carter mapped out his successful
campaign ``by reading books,'' Richard Reeves wrote in
``Convention.'' ``His reading began with Teddy White's `Making of
the President' series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(White) laid it all out,'' Boller says. ``In his first book,
he showed Kennedy deciding how television could be crucial, Nixon
making the mistake of promising to campaign in all 50 states _ he
got ill and looked terrible, which hurt him in the TV debates with
Kennedy. Certainly I remember (Carter campaign manager) Hamilton
Jordan saying he studied White's books and used what was in them
for Jimmy Carter's successful campaign in 1976.''
</P>
<P>
   Former House Speaker Jim Wright says colleagues itching to run
for president ``devoured'' White's books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in the '60s and '70s, many wanted to emulate the
appeal of John F. Kennedy, and they surely dipped into `The Making
of the President,''' Wright says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   As a result, White became not just a chronicler but a powerful
figure himself. After ``The Making of the President 1960'' won the
Pulitzer, White's personal attention was sought by almost every
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember (campaigns) asking if Teddy White was free on a
certain day, because they wanted him to come to their
announcements,'' Halberstam says. ``Having him take your campaign
seriously enough to cover it was a signal to everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   And if White's books made him a power broker, some observers
felt he was not an entirely objective one. A Harvard graduate like
the Kennedys (though, unlike them, White attended on a scholarship
made available to impoverished applicants), White certainly felt
closest to the Kennedy camp. His ``Making of the President 1968,''
which chronicled Richard Nixon's defeat of Democrat Hubert
Humphrey, was dedicated to the memories of John and Robert Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   White's liberal leanings were well-known in the Nixon camp, says
historian Irwin Gellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon never trusted White,'' says Gellman, whose next book,
``The Apprentice,'' will delineate Nixon's career from 1952 through
January 1961. (It is the second in a projected three-book series.)
``There are 20, 30 letters from White asking for personal time with
Nixon, but it was never given. Of course, White could still travel
on planes with Nixon during campaigns, could still talk to his
staff. But personal access to Nixon was denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gellman adds, ``White is a beautiful writer, and though
his 1960 book is flawed _ he never really understood the nature of
Nixon and Kennedy as Cold Warriors _ he opened up everyone's eyes
to how campaigns operated.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam says ``definitive books about presidential campaigns
began with White's. ``The Making of the President 1960'' made it
possible for Joe McGinnis to write ``The Selling of the President
1968'' about Nixon's campaign, then Tim Crouse wrote ``The Boys on
the Bus'' about media coverage of presidential campaigns, then
Richard Ben Cramer with ``What It Takes'' about the 1988
Bush-Dukakis campaign. Those are all great books, in some ways
better than White's, and that's only right, because the pupils are
supposed to learn from and eventually surpass the master.''
</P>
<P>
   White proved that newspapers could fascinate readers with
``information about little things,'' Halberstam adds. ``He wrote
about what John Kennedy said to his wife on the morning of the 1960
election. He explained why Nixon misunderstood TV. He showed we
should put the good stuff into daily copy, the stuff we previously
only talked about at the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the only source for behind-the-scenes
details instead of just straightforward news accounts, White's book
was also the only mainstream book about the 1960 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't recall any books about any previous campaigns,
though I guess there were some,'' Boller says. ``Otherwise, there
were biographies of presidents but nothing much until they'd left
office.''
</P>
<P>
   That too, of course, has changed. In the first eight months of
2000 alone, major publishers have printed more than 50 politically
themed books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to do it now,'' King says.
</P>
<P>
   Before his death in 1986 at age 71, White used his final book to
express some regrets concerning what he had helped bring about.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential primary system, he declared in 1982's ``America
in Search of Itself,'' his last book, exhibited ``the madness of a
good idea run wild ... the number of primaries has grown from 14
(in 1956) to 36 (in 1980), exhausting candidates, attendant press,
and public interest alike. Special interests, from the most greedy
to the most idealistic, pour more money into politics than ever
before, finding the primaries the most vulnerable point in the
American process.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
