<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAH'S-HOTEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROOM WITH A RIVER VIEW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. Art available) 
 
 
Story and Photos by ERIC NOLAND  
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAUGHLIN, Nev. _ Location is everything. Even here.
</P>
<P>
   In this sweltering gambling town along the Colorado River,
Harrah's hotel and casino is situated at a natural cove, which is
bracketed by buoys that limit watercraft to speeds that don't
produce wakes (and sometimes, the little devils actually abide by
it).
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a day on which the mercury bubbles above 120
degrees can be mitigated with a plunge into a roped-off swimming
area along the Colorado _ with minimal threat of propeller
lacerations.
</P>
<P>
   Sand has been trucked in to cover the mud along the river's
edge, creating a private beach so popular that room keys are
mandatory for gaining access to it.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's, at the extreme south end of the Laughlin strip, has
several other features working in its favor. Prominent among them
is William Fisk's Steakhouse, an attempt to enhance the fine-dining
options in an area known chiefly for its pig-out buffets.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take any chances with the menu items _ there are no
fewer than nine offerings of beef or lamb among 16 entree choices _
but it does them well. (Prices average in the upper $20s.) And the
wine list features a nice range.
</P>
<P>
   But probably the restaurant's finest attribute is its wide,
arched windows that face east. Time your dinner for sunset and
you'll get quite a show, as some of the desert hills are draped in
deep, dark shadows, while more distant mountains are fired in
brilliant shades of red, orange and purple.
</P>
<P>
   It's an elegant, intimate setting, with white tablecloths and
attentive service that isn't impressed with itself. The restaurant
even takes a stab at maintaining respectable decorum by having the
semblance of a dress code (no beachwear or flip-flops), and most
diners seem thrilled to have an excuse to put on resort wear.
</P>
<P>
   A stay at Harrah's in June was marred only by some troubles with
the room. Or rooms.
</P>
<P>
   We were first issued keys to a room that was already occupied _
difficult to say who was more startled when we barged in. We were
then assigned a different room, but late in the evening found that
our keys wouldn't open the door _ and it took three maintenance men
and a door jack that looked like a medieval torture device to
finally get it open. On to another room, which deviated from the
preferences specified on our reservation, but it had to do for a
night. The fourth room was perfect. Through all the moves, we felt
lucky to have lost nothing more than a swimsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the swimming cove and the restaurant, Harrah's Laughlin
was found to have several other attributes:
</P>
<P>
   _To conform to a south-of-the-border theme, according to
spokeswoman Madeleine Weekley, ``exposed slump blocks'' were used
in the hotel's construction. An ancillary benefit is that the thick
walls seem to knock down all noise from neighboring rooms. You
sleep soundly here.
</P>
<P>
   _Unlike most hotels on this strip, Harrah's takes full advantage
of the river's presence, having its pools and spas on a patio that
overlooks the water. One pool-spa complex is for families, the
other for adults only.
</P>
<P>
   _An entire tower of rooms is designated for adults only, too,
and you even have to sign a pledge to that effect when you check
in. Enforcement must be difficult, though, because a number of
squealing little ones were encountered running in and out of rooms
on the various floors we stayed on. At checkout, we heard another
guest complaining about this; the front-desk staffer said security
needs snitch help when there are abuses.
</P>
<P>
   _The casino has a no-smoking section. ``We're a very Southern
California-friendly resort,'' said Weekley. ``We felt it fit very
well with our (target) market.''
</P>
<P>
   _Harrah's, a couple hundred yards removed from the strip, is not
connected to Laughlin's River Walk, so you don't have to contend
with parades of looky-loos traipsing through the pool area, for
example. Getting to the other casinos, however, is as simple as
hopping a water taxi. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
IF YOU GO &QL; 
For a Sunday-Tuesday stay in June, we paid $46 per night for a room
overlooking the river. As in most gambling cities, room rates vary
drastically depending on demand and time of year or week. Harrah's
Laughlin information or reservations: (800) 427-7247;
www.harrahslaughlin.com on the Web. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
caption: One of the primary appeals of Harrah's Laughlin is a quiet
swimming cove along the banks of the Colorado River. The sandy
expanse is the only private beach along Laughlin's casino strip. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
