<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8189 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-ROUTE66-LADN &LR;      08-21 2685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUTE66-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET HIP WITH THIS TIMELESS TRIP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients.) 
(Eds: Fact box below. Art available.) 
 
 
Story and photos by ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OATMAN, Ariz. _ The burro stepped abruptly into the center of
the roadway, oblivious to the approaching car that was forced to
slam to a halt. Then the beast, a descendant of the animals that
did all the heavy lifting for miners working the Black Mountains in
the early 1900s, belligerently stood its ground, staring down the
driver over the hood of the car. It didn't budge until a pedestrian
noisily shooed it away.
</P>
<P>
   The burro, which had taken its defiant stance smack in the
middle of Oatman's main street, undoubtedly just wanted a carrot or
an apple. But with a little imagination, you could discern a deeper
message in that posture and that expression:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wanted predictability, you should have stayed on the
interstate and not wandered through here. This road's different.
This is Route 66.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just a strip of asphalt, a highway that once stretched
2,278 miles between Chicago and Santa Monica, but over the years it
has been examined in literature, celebrated in song, psychoanalyzed
on screens both small and large.
</P>
<P>
   It was supplanted by a sleek, safe, nondescript interstate
highway in the 1960s and '70s, and became a ghost road for the 15
or so years after I-40 was completed, a period during which neglect
killed many of its eccentric little roadside settlements and
severely crippled others. But when America was swept up in a wave
of nostalgia in the late-'80s, Route 66 seemed to find its way to
the crest, and some travelers suddenly decided they just weren't in
that big a hurry after all. They came looking for its remnants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Route 66 always was a media road,'' said Tom Snyder of
Ventura, author of the ``Route 66 Traveler's Guide'' (St. Martin's
Griffin). ``From the first, promotional work was done in Oklahoma
in the late '20s and early '30s. Then (John) Steinbeck comes down
the road and makes it famous. Then songs and movies featured it,
because writers, producers and directors drove that road coming
west.''
</P>
<P>
   This is probably why every Route 66 guidebook is written in an
east-to- west narrative. That, after all, was the direction
followed by the Joad family in Steinbeck's ``Grapes of Wrath,'' by
songwriter Bobby Troup as he sped along with his wife and started
composing a little ditty about how you can ``get your kicks on
Route 66,'' and by Martin Milner and George Maharis (Tod and Buz)
as they bummed from town to town in their Corvette in the '60s TV
show ``Route 66.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who grew up in Southern California, however, Route 66
is infused with entirely different overtones. This was the route of
family vacations to the Grand Canyon, or to summer visits with
relatives in the Midwest. It conjures up memories of being rousted
in the dead of night, and sleeping against a back-seat window of
the station wagon, because ``we've got to get across that desert
before it gets hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, random stretches of 66 can be found all the way across
California, but some of them are nothing more than suburban
thoroughfares cluttered with Burger Kings and big-box stores, while
others are essentially frontage roads that closely parallel the
interstate.
</P>
<P>
   To get a truer feel for Route 66 _ and those vacation trips of
old _ it's best to embark on a section that wanders through open,
long-neglected country. Two such stretches can easily be
incorporated into a Laughlin, Nev., trip.
</P>
<P>
   On the journey to or from the Colorado River gambling city,
simply duck off the interstate in the midst of the Mojave Desert
(at Ludlow eastbound, at Mountain Springs Road westbound) and take
a swing south on 66 through such last-gasp towns as Amboy and
Essex. Or follow another stretch of the old road through Fenner and
Goffs, just west of Laughlin off U.S. 95.
</P>
<P>
   Also, on a day trip from Laughlin, you can wind into the Arizona
hills to the former mining town of Oatman _ perhaps continuing on
that desolate route to a lunch stop in Kingman, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   You may not get where you're going in any particular hurry, but
you're sure to get in touch with a fascinating strip of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   When you exit eastbound I-40 at Ludlow and strike out on the old
road, you'll bounce along a pock-marked stretch of ancient asphalt,
passing an abandoned auto-repair shop and the dilapidated Ludlow
Cafe. Within a few miles, the interstate can no longer be seen,
heard or sensed. You'll get 70-some miles of that respite on this
detour.
</P>
<P>
   Now (ITAL)this(END ITAL) is a highway with character. Route 66
was never particularly straight. It borrowed shamelessly from
survey work already done for the Santa Fe rail line, which had
sought low ground and locations where there was precious water for
its steam engines.
</P>
<P>
   The interstate lies along an elevated bed and was cut
arrow-straight. Route 66 follows the natural contours of the
desert, dipping through washes, curving around mountains. It's a
road much more in touch with the landscape, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   The old road cuts through a valley between the Bullion and
Bristol mountains, and the rugged beauty of the desert is revealed
fully. Dust devils erupt on the dry lakes to the south. And it's
not unusual to come over a rise, as we did, and surprise a crow
pecking at some road kill on the center stripe.
</P>
<P>
   Along Route 66, it's particularly fun to look for ruins of old
service stations, coffee shops and motor courts, which were once
essential to motorists but shriveled up when various segments of
the road were bypassed.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 miles from Ludlow, watch for a lone, scraggly tree that
stands in the middle of an open area on the north side of the road.
This is no mere turnout; it used to be an entire town. It was
Bagdad, christened by railroad officials trying to come up with a
name suitable to the oppressive climate but apparently unaware that
the capital of Iraq has an ``h'' in it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a thriving railhead at the turn of the 20th century, as
the yields of nearby mines were collected and hauled off, but it
expired in the late 1960s, and vandals have since reduced it to a
few patches of asphalt, broken glass and rusted auto parts. When we
stopped here, the wind was whistling mournfully through that lone
salt cedar tree, but the mood was broken when the engineer of a
passing freight issued a friendly blast from his horn.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles farther on, in Amboy, Roy's Cafe was open for
business, but the experience wasn't particularly pleasant. The
counter man, drinking beer from a long-neck bottle at midday on a
Sunday, at first ignored us, then cheerlessly sold us a couple of
1-ounce bags of potato chips for $1 each. Then he bristled when a
flash photo was taken of the cafe counter.
</P>
<P>
   Although the experience shattered our reverie, it was just as
well. While it's a delight to get in touch with Route 66 and what
it used to be, the simple highway has been terribly
over-romanticized, such that its many shortcomings are forgotten in
all the nostalgic rhapsodizing.
</P>
<P>
   The little businesses along Route 66 were often manned by
reclusive, sometimes sullen desert rats who may have resented the
fact that their livelihood was dependent on the Griswolds and their
ugly green station wagon. The accommodations were often rough, the
food mediocre and the mechanics larcenous.
</P>
<P>
   The road itself, meanwhile, was extraordinarily dangerous. One
lane in each direction, broken yellow stripe down the middle _ and
all those undulations into desert washes and curves around
mountains. It was not unusual to check the oncoming lane and find
it clear, pull out to pass a truck or a car towing a trailer, and
have an oncoming vehicle suddenly pop up out of one of those dips.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Amboy, a corrugated tin roof flapped in the wind above a
long-closed cafe and gas station in Essex. We preferred this to the
cafe we found open in Amboy.
</P>
<P>
   A general cantankerousness remains in these crumbling
settlements, though. Because souvenir-hunters have replaced the
family tourist caravans of old, many of the ruins are surrounded by
chain-link fences, some topped with barbed wire. In Essex, one
junkyard that might have been somebody's home bore signs
prohibiting not only trespassing but parking as well.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Oatman proved to be considerably more hospitable.
It is a 30-mile drive from Laughlin (15 miles south on Arizona 95
from the Laughlin bridge, then 15 miles into the mountains after
turning left on Boundary Cone Road).
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, this part of the old highway was bypassed in 1952
when Route 66 was rerouted through lower ground to the south. Until
then, travelers had to coax their jalopies along steep, treacherous
switchbacks and over 3,550-foot Sitgreaves Pass in the Black
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Oatman, a thriving gold-mining town in the early 1900s, awaited
the survivors. Now it sells carrots to tourists. Huh? The
vegetables (25 cents at the General Store) are for the wild burros
that freely roam the main drag.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go off into the mountains at night but come into town
first thing in the morning,'' said Shirley Burrous, manager of a
shop selling Route 66 memorabilia. ``They spend the afternoon on
this side of the street, where the shade is, and they leave in the
evening when the tourists leave.''
</P>
<P>
   A popular stop for visitors is the Oatman Hotel, where Clark
Gable and Carole Lombard sneaked off for a honeymoon after their
marriage in 1939. Their room is preserved much as it was then _ a
real dump. But privacy was as elusive for Hollywood stars then as
it is now.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch of road east of Oatman is truly godforsaken. It's
said that local residents used to have to back up these hills in
reverse gear, because the fuel systems in their Model Ts were
gravity-fed. Imagine being a cross-country traveler cresting a hill
only to have a rear bumper barreling toward you. Fortunately, the
only road hazard we encountered was a coyote dashing for cover.
</P>
<P>
   At the ruins of a former tourist business called Cool Springs
Camp (which appears to be none of the three), we encountered a
father-son party of German tourists, Adolf and Michael Lange of
Nuremberg, rattling along in a rented RV.
</P>
<P>
   They had been picking their way along old 66 from Williams,
Ariz., 163 miles to the east, and admitted a keen interest in the
highway's place in American history. They were positively
fascinated to hear that my dad had driven this very stretch of
mountain road on his own western migration in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   In Kingman, 30 miles beyond Oatman, it seemed only fitting to
have lunch in a non-chain restaurant along Route 66 _ preferably
one with a big plastic steer on the roof. We found exactly this at
Dambar Steakhouse, where the menu features a picture of Andy
Devine, the perpetual cowboy sidekick and Kingman's favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   It serves third-of-a-pound burgers with something called cowboy
beans, and the waitress arrives at the table with a basket of
buttermilk biscuits. It's the kind of place with sawdust on the
floor, old pictures and license plates on the wall, and local
law-enforcement fellows sliding into one of the booths on a lunch
break.
</P>
<P>
   On the return, if you don't want to retrace your steps through
Oatman and descend to the river on another old stretch of 66, jump
on I-40, then reach Laughlin via the River Road along the west side
of the Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In either event, reflect on a shameful chapter in California
history as you cross the river.
</P>
<P>
   During the Depression, as Dust Bowl refugees poured west looking
for work, patrols of badge-wearing thugs formed ``bum blockades''
here, according to Snyder's book. They would detain and often turn
back families that couldn't show they had sufficient money (usually
$100), the fear being that these desperate souls might be a drain
on the state's economy. Federal marshals ultimately had to step in
to stop the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Folk legend Woody Guthrie wrote about those unfortunate days in
his poem ``Do Re Mi'':
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL)``They think they're goin' to a sugar bowl
</P>
<P>
   But here is what they find
</P>
<P>
   The police at the port of entry say
</P>
<P>
   You're number 14,000 for the day.''(END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   There are no impediments now. If they're so inclined, travelers
can zip across the bridge and haul their disposable cash up to the
gambling halls of Laughlin, or rent fishing gear or a Jet Ski on
the river ... or hurry down that straight, seamless, profoundly
boring interstate highway and stop at some nameless minimart to buy
a microwaved snack, hastily eaten. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
IF YOU GO &QL; 
GETTING THERE: Route 66 followed various courses in eastern
California and western Arizona as engineers twice redirected it to
achieve a straighter route to Los Angeles. Here are some options
for exploring it in conjunction with a Laughlin, Nev., trip.
</P>
<P>
   _Eastbound from Barstow: Exit I-40 at Ludlow, turn right, then
left onto Old 66. This is a delightfully desolate loop through the
desert. Just past Essex, take the left fork to drive an ancient
segment through Fenner and Goffs, then head north on U.S. 95
(leaving 66 behind) and reach Laughlin via Nevada 163. Or, if you
prefer, you can take the right fork just past Essex (this was a
later incarnation of 66) and return to the interstate, continuing
on to Laughlin on a more conventional route.
</P>
<P>
   _Eastbound from Laughlin: Cross the bridge at the north end of
town and endure the spectacularly uninteresting strip town of
Bullhead City, Ariz., as you head south for 15 miles on Arizona 95.
Turn left at Boundary Cone Road. After about 12 miles, you'll veer
left onto Route 66 toward Oatman, and can continue on to Kingman
(30 miles beyond Oatman) if you wish.
</P>
<P>
   _Westbound from Kingman: Follow Old 66 to Oatman and slightly
beyond, then veer left, staying on 66, toward Topock and the river.
You'll regain I-40 on the Arizona side, then return to Laughlin
along either of two routes that parallel the river (Arizona 95, or
the River Road in California and Nevada).
</P>
<P>
   _Westbound from Laughlin: Multiple options. You can reverse the
direction of the first option, or take the River Road to I-40 west,
then exit onto U.S. 95 north. This was once 66. Turn left at
Arrowhead Junction toward Goffs (you'll still be on 66), and follow
this route about 85 miles to Ludlow. One final option: from I-40,
you can take just the southern dip of 66, exiting at Mountain
Springs Road, turning left onto 66, and following the old highway
75 miles to Ludlow, through Essex and Amboy.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL TIP: Route 66 used to be liberally peppered with roadside
businesses, but nearly all of them were reduced to ghostly hulks
when the various bypasses were completed. Thus, while driving this
road, you're not likely to find many opportunities to purchase gas,
food or even water. And there are no call boxes. Even the
60-or-so-mile stretches in eastern California and western Arizona
can be pretty forbidding _ especially in the event of a breakdown.
It's advisable to gas up on the interstate and carry an ice chest
holding food and water.
</P>
<P>
   OFF THE SHELF: One of the best guides to the highway is the
``Route 66 Traveler's Guide'' (St. Martin's Griffin; $12.95), by
Tom Snyder, founder and director of the US Route 66 Association.
Another informative book is ``Route 66: A Guidebook to the Mother
Road'' (USDC Inc.; $19.95), by Bob Moore and Patrick Grauwels. If
you're so inclined, the latter book will advise you on when to set
your car's trip-counter odometer at zero, then will give you
precise commentary on the positioning of old rest stops and
long-abandoned roadside businesses _ but these directions only
apply to westbound travel. All guidebooks to Route 66 are written
in this east-to-west narrative. Key advisory: A version of the
Moore-Grauwels guide ostensibly is configured west to east, but
don't be fooled (as we were); it's a fraud. The chapters were
merely positioned in reverse order. The book opens in California,
but it starts in Needles(!), headed west, not in Santa Monica,
headed east. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
