<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-CARS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET YOUR KICKS WITH THESE CLASSIC CARS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients.) 
(Eds: Sidebar to Route 66 story. Art available.) 
Story and Photos by ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   photo caption: A classic-car exhibit at the Riverside Resort in
Laughlin, Nev., can generate inspiration for a Route 66
exploration. A 1941 Ford pickup truck on display might have climbed
the hills of nearby Oatman, Ariz., before that section of the old
road was bypassed in 1952. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAUGHLIN, Nev. _ There's probably no better way to get in the mood
for a Route 66 exploration in western Arizona and eastern
California than to visit the classic-car exhibit at the Riverside
Resort, at the extreme north end of Laughlin's strip.
</P>
<P>
   Here is American highway travel from its glory era: Detroit
gas-guzzlers and sports cars from the 1950s and `60s, with flashy
colors, black-vinyl seats and acres of shiny chrome.
</P>
<P>
   Corvettes? They are numerous, from '54 through the first year of
the Sting Ray ('63) and on up. Also T-birds, Camaros, Mustangs,
Malibus, Galaxies, even a '58 Dodge Custom Royale, with a two-tone,
red-and-white paint job and tail fins so prominent they could
probably pick up HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are what I remember best in that era,'' said Don
Laughlin, 69, founder of the resort and ... well, the town. ``You
get a real education about cars. It takes you back in time and lets
you feel young again.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not solely an exhibit. The hotel is licensed as a car
dealer, and most of the restored classics on display have been
placed on consignment by their owners. The cars _ and a lot of
vintage motorcycles, too _ are displayed in two exhibit rooms (one
at the front of the hotel, the other on the second floor). There is
no charge to look at them.
</P>
<P>
   Don Laughlin personally owns a half-dozen of them, he said,
including one from what could be described as Route 66's ``Grapes
of Wrath'' era: a '31 Ford Roadster. ``I get it out a couple of
times a year,'' he admitted, ``drive it around for a week or two
and then put it back.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the cars is sure to resonate with baby boomers who can
recall striking out across the desert on long-past family
vacations. It is a '55 Chevy Nomad station wagon _ a two-door, at
that. If you peer through the windows, you might even notice the
vintage, stainless-steel ice chest in the back. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
