<P>
   GORE _ HANNIBAL, Mo. - Al Gore's campaign riverboat steamed into
Mark Twain's boyhood home Monday night with a message drawn from
the legenday humorist: news of the death of Gore's presidential bid
has been greatly exaggerated. Gore's trip along 400 miles of the
Mississippi River ended with the vice president having erased the
commanding lead Republican rival has held in public opinion polls.
But Gore still has a long way to go. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB _ MOSCOW _ Russian and Norwegian officials broke off
rescue operations and declared the 118 crewmembers of a wrecked
Russian submarine dead after confirmation came Monday that the
vessel was entirely flooded. Russian Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov
said he would ask for international help to raise the 500-foot
Kursk submarine from the frigid depths of the Barents Sea, and
recover its two nuclear reactors, a process that is expected to
take months. ``Our worst expectations are confirmed. All sections
of the sub are totally flooded and not a single member of the crew
remains alive,'' Russia's naval chief of staff Mikhail Motsak said
in a televised statement. (Coker, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire.
