<P>
   PIPELINE _ WASHINGTON - The company that owns a 30-inch pipeline
that exploded and killed 10 campers in New Mexico Saturday was
warned by federal officials three years ago that its workers had
not been trained to accurately determine whether the pipeline was
in danger of corroding. Developing. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-ECHO _ WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley
releases his fifth annual Baby Boom Echo report on national and
state trends Monday in Henderson, Nev. It will say that rising
enrollments (53 million this year in K-12) set a record, and Riley
will claim that this shows that educating the children of baby
boomers requires federal subsidies for school modernization,
renovation and repair and for the reduction of the number of
portable classrooms parked on school grounds. This launches a
week-long drive by the administration to build support for
``building better schools'' before the Republican Congress returns
for the final weeks of nose-to-nose negotations with the Democratic
president over the budget for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
(Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
