<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOXER-WRITER-2TAKES-N     08-21 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXER-WRITER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDOMIR  
</HEADLINE>
 
A CUT MAN TURNED WRITER ROLLS WITH THE PUNCHES By RICHARD c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   F.X. Toole is an erudite and profane character with a seemingly
apocryphal life: actor, teamster, salesman, bartender and
bullfighter. He added one more trade in 1979 _ boxing trainer and
cut man _ and has stuck with it since.
</P>
<P>
   Yet prominent boxing folk cannot place Toole or remember his
corner work. One promoter wondered if he was a scam artist. Another
said that if he were any good as a cut man, he would be known. They
could not recall him even when told of a sideline that surely makes
him stand out in their raffish universe.
</P>
<P>
   Toole writes fiction, a craft that he quietly pursued when he
wasn't stopping blood coming from fighters' noses. His first book
of short fiction, ``Rope Burns: Stories From the Corner,'' is to be
published next month by Ecco Press, an imprint of HarperCollins.
</P>
<P>
   The book has received lavish praise from the novelists Joyce
Carol Oates and James Ellroy, each of whom has also made detours
into writing about boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unique,'' Oates said during a telephone interview.
``He's a born storyteller who uses the language of the ring.'' She
described his prose as an ``an elevated colloquial American
English.'' In its review, Publishers Weekly said that his writing
was ``as tight as a well-laced pair of gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the widely known trainer Lou Duva has never heard of
Toole, and chuckles at the idea of a corner man moonlighting with
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the cut men I know can't speak English, let alone write
it,'' Duva said, ``because they've got mouthpieces in their
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bob DePhillipis, who manages three fighters Toole claims to
have assisted, said he had never heard of Toole until he was
offered this description: tall, lean, short white hair, 70 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Jerry Boyd!'' he said. ``He's been around the world
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd invented F.X. Toole to shield his boxing life (which has
brought him psychic fulfillment but no riches) from his writing
(which had until recently brought him only rejection). He did not
want anyone in boxing to view him as anything but a corner man or
to be recognized for sucking up his gym buddies' lives and
conversations for his short stories and novellas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want anybody to know what I was doing,'' Boyd said
during one of several rollicking telephone interviews from Los
Angeles. ``And F.X. Toole lets me write determinedly
Irish-Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's lack of literary success made it easy to maintain his
secret. ``I've failed at everything,'' he said. ``I failed with
every woman, I failed as a father, I failed as a writer. I was a
bullfighter, but I wasn't good enough to be a matador. I wrote, but
I wasn't a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd refused to divulge his writing to his ``boxing daddy,'' the
trainer Dub Huntley, until a few months ago, when a book review by
F.X. Toole appeared in The Los Angeles Times. ``He told me
something about it, but I didn't believe him,'' said Huntley, a
former middleweight with failing vision who uses Boyd as ``my
eyes.'' ``I didn't think nothing of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boyd's luck turned last year when Zyzzyva, a literary
journal in San Francisco that he discovered in Writer's Market (a
sourcebook of publishing opportunities), published one of his
tales.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Junker, Zyzzyva's editor, said, ``My first thought was
that he was a little like Hemingway, and I didn't know if that was
good or not. But quite clearly it was more than that. He's enough
of a naif not to know about strategies or to disguise or call
attention to the act of narration.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd celebrated the $50 sale with a dram of malt whiskey and
some dark chocolate. ``My fondest dream was to get published in a
literary magazine,'' he said. ``Think of the Sistine Chapel, with
the fingers of God and Adam about to touch _ that's my story. The
odds against me being published and talking to you about it are
greater than the odds against the existence of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Nat Sobel, a Manhattan agent who trolls literary magazines in
search of talent, read the story and wrote Boyd to ask if he had
more to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised I hadn't heard of him and wondered if F.X. was
a pseudonym,'' Sobel said. He sold ``Rope Burns,'' five short
stories and a novella, plus a future boxing novel to Ecco for a
``high five-figure sum.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Halpern, Ecco's editorial director, showed the collection
to people at the publishing house who disliked boxing. ``Their
reaction,'' he recalled, ``was immediate and intense: `How does a
corner man learn to write?'''
</P>
<P>
   (Answer: he takes one college writing course, attends no
workshops, reads voraciously, absorbs the way boxing people act and
talk, and writes long after there is any legitimate hope of being
published.)
</P>
<P>
   Ecco is so certain of the quality of ``Rope Burns'' _ and of
Boyd's impetuous personal magnetism _ that it has ordered an
unusually large first printing of 50,000 copies and is sending him
on a six-city tour. HBO is also negotiating for the rights to turn
three stories into movies, Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Rope Burns'' is inhabited by cynical and sentimental trainers,
heroic boxers and slimy promoters, familiar archetypes flavored
with Boyd's ring-savvy, story structure and use of dialect. His
stories are essentially about love _ a love of pure boxing, a love
between boxers and corner men, and a love among corner men _
conveyed in gentle, graphic and occasionally violent terms. But
that love rarely equates with joy.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing may be corrupt, but when done right, Boyd sees magic.
``Some people say boxing is a metaphor for life,'' he said. ``I
think life is a metaphor for boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd grew up in Gardena, Calif., south of Los Angeles, the son
of an Irish immigrant father and a mother who was raised in rural
Ventura County. His mother's culinary legacy lives on in her son
the recreational pie baker. ``People grovel when you come in with a
pie,'' he said. ``It's better than being published.'' (He baked a
gooseberry pie for Junker, who called it ``exquisite.'')
</P>
<P>
   He started acting in high school and graduated from Los Angeles
City College with a drama degree in 1951. He joined the Navy
Reserve and was posted at Floyd Bennett Field in Brooklyn, N.Y.
Through friends he had made on Broadway, he began to take nighttime
acting courses in 1953 under Sanford Meisner at the Neighborhood
Playhouse in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider Sandy one of my writing teachers, particularly for
dialogue and giving your characters freedom,'' he said. ``You must
know your characters well enough to turn them loose.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was smitten by Meisner's technique, though not
by the actor's life; he became more fascinated by bullfighting. He
said he made it to Mexico, married and had a daughter. But his
bullfighting resume included being gored three times. The bulls, he
said, were learning more than he was.
</P>
<P>
   Needing money, he and his family returned to Los Angeles, where
he began a long series of blue-collar jobs to support his family.
He would eventually marry and divorce three times and father two
sons. Mostly, he tended bar. ``I was close to the seven deadly sins
at all times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, nearly 50 years old, he followed a personal passion for
boxing and tried to become a fighter. He trained and fought, but
when his nose was broken and his teeth bashed in, he chose the
safer route of becoming a corner man. He later received a license
from the California State Athletic commission.
</P>
<P>
   And he continued to write, intermittently and unsuccessfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd submit things and I'd be destroyed when they were
rejected, but then I'd crawl back to the typewriter to do some
more,'' he said. ``This went on for years and years, and it hurt so
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-to-late 1980s, he said, he quit writing altogether to
focus entirely on boxing. His boxing profile is as modest as the
boxers he has worked with, among them Jesus Salud, a former junior
featherweight champion; Antoine Byrd, a super middleweight; and
King Ipitan, a heavyweight, with whom Boyd had a falling-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy with boxing, but I kept writing in my head,'' he
said. ``I rejected it like I'd caught my wife cheating on me, like,
`I love you, now leave.''' But after complications from heart
surgery in 1988, he said, his religious faith was reawakened along
with his ardor for writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night, sitting in bed, I looked across the wall and saw a
story,'' he said. ``I got to the point in my life that if I can see
the story, I can write it. It's not mystical, just something that
seems to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, while living in Missouri, he suffered a heart
attack. In bed, he said, fearing death, he remembered a final task:
tacking a new ending onto the novel he was rewriting. He said he
ignored the heart attack and slept until morning: ``I woke up and
climbed the hills to force the heart to work to see if I was
dreaming. I had a little wine, a cigar and had sex. Then my heart
began to hurt again, so I said if I'm going to die, I'm going to
finish the novel, so I spent a few hours putting it together, and
told the woman I was living with, `Baby, let's go to Springfield,'
and they inserted two stent implants.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's survival has positioned him for an unanticipated
publishing deliverance, one that will come under the pseudonym F.X.
Toole.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I have written all these years if the process isn't
as rewarding as it is, as much as it hurts?'' he said. ``When
you're on a roll, baby, there ain't nothing like it, like a guy who
can throw six or eight punches in a row and come out unscathed,
then can do it again and again. When I'm writing, I can get blown
up, blown up to the ceiling. The muse taps you on the shoulder and
it's love at first sight; if you don't follow, you look at yourself
like a punk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
