<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   After a cool dawn, breezes from the south will deliver
seasonably warm conditions to most of the Northeastern states on
Tuesday. High pressure moving off the Middle Atlantic Coast will
promote abundant sunshine near the coast. Sunshine will mix with
increasing clouds over the interior Northeast during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of thundershowers will weaken early Tuesday over
the central Great Lakes and northern Ohio Valley. Farther west, a
jet stream disturbance will produce a cluster of thunderstorms
across eastern Nebraska and Iowa that will spread east during the
afternoon. Damaging winds are possible with some of the storms in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will linger over a large area from the southern
Plains to the interior West. Most areas will stay dry, however
afternoon thunderstorms will develop over many mountain peaks in
the southern and central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WINTER IN AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Snow driven by 45-mph winds whitened Mount Washington, N.H., on
Sunday morning. At an elevation of 6,288 feet, the summit of Mount
Washington rises above all other peaks in the Northeast, exposing
it to frequent harsh weather. But, snow in August is unusual. On
average, an inch of snow falls on Mount Washington in August only
once every 10 years. Elsewhere in the the Northeast, temperatures
fell below freezing early Monday in a few protected valleys from
Pennsylvania to New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
