<HEADER>
A8213 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN23-COX     08-21 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP's 'inclusion illusion at least sets a goal
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his speech in Los Angeles last week, Jesse Jackson dismissed
the abundance of black and Hispanic faces on the stage at the
Republican Convention as an ``inclusion illusion.'' Others
suggested that there might have been more minority faces up on the
stage in Philadelphia than out on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   There was truth to both observations. While the GOP may
officially oppose what it calls ``quotas,'' there's no question
that party leaders wanted a certain number of minority faces
broadcast on the nation's TV screens, and that those faces were far
out of proportion to their actual number and influence in the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than an expression of hypocrisy, however, perhaps it's
best to look at that radiant picture of diversity from Philadelphia
as the stating of a goal. George W. Bush clearly understands that
the Republican Party's image as the home of disgruntled white guys
wasn't going to work. In marketing terms, he needed to reposition
his product, and the convention was the unveiling of his new ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That says something reassuring about this country. The
bitterness, anger and defensiveness that has marked the GOP through
most of the '90s simply hasn't washed with a large majority of
Americans. We have proved a more tolerant and accepting people than
some in the GOP had anticipated. Bush understands that if his
party's angry tone had continued, it would have cost the
Republicans control of the House and perhaps the Senate, and would
also have denied them any real chance of regaining the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures out of Philadelphia also said something reassuring
about Bush. As governor of Texas, he has never indulged in the type
of mean-spirited politicking practiced by men such as Jesse Helms,
Dick Armey and other prominent Republicans in Congress. In that
display of personal decency, he is much like his father.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's also true that as governor of Texas, Bush has
seldom confronted those within his own party who do indulge in
race-baiting, gay-bashing and the politics of personal destruction.
Within his concept of leadership, it is apparently enough that he
himself refrains from such behavior. He has shown little interest
in steering the rest of his party away from that approach. In that
too, he is much like his father.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rub. If Bush remains content to serve merely as
his party's mask of reason and tolerance, while behind that mask
the party continues to operate as it has in the past, the promises
implied in that rainbow of faces at the Republican Convention will
never be made real. Nor will the party succeed in reaching out to
the black, Hispanic and immigrant populations that make up an
increasing percentage of the national electorate.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to acknowledge the difficulty of making that
transition. The modern Republican Party has been built on Richard
Nixon's so-called ``Southern strategy,'' which exploited the
resentments of many in the traditional white majority toward the
gains of those perceived as outsiders. Those voters by no means
constitute the majority of Republican voters nationwide, but they
do represent a significant chunk of the party, and in some states
and congressional districts their influence is enormous. If you can
account for the fact of Jesse Helms any other way, I'd like to hear
it.
</P>
<P>
   Making the promises of Philadelphia real would require the
Republicans to wean themselves of dependence on that voting bloc.
And elected officials who have built careers on appealing to that
segment of the population aren't going to change willingly, in no
small part because men like Tom DeLay and Georgia's own Bob Barr
share the attitudes they exploit in others.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those difficulties, however, that transition is
inevitable. Over the last quarter century, as our country has grown
more tolerant of diversity in all its forms, the number of voters
motivated by fear and resentment has declined, while the number of
minority voters has increased. The effectiveness of the GOP's
``Southern strategy'' has been further eroded by the remarkable
prosperity the country is enjoying at the moment. It's harder to
feel resentful when you've got a full belly, a nice house, steady
work and prospering kids.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, of course, can manage to nurture resentment in even
the best of times. And I must confess to feeling a guilty little
pleasure at their expense as I watched the events in Philadelphia.
Did the fans of Jesse Helms and the boys, the ones who have seen
the Republican Party as their protector, dismiss those diverse
faces on the stage as just an ``inclusion illusion?'' Or did they
sit there simmering in rage, watching ``their party'' being taken
over by ``those people'' just as ``their country'' has been?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
