<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0822-COX     08-21 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST-TIME LEADER IN REUTERS/ZOGBY POLL
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore, helped by a convention bounce, sprung into a narrow
lead over George W. Bush on Monday, the first time he has led in
the Reuters/Zogby poll. The survey, conducted Friday through
Sunday, found Gore leading Bush 44-41 percent. But with a 3
percentage point margin of error, the race was still a statistical
dead heat. The Green Party's Ralph Nader polled 5 percent and the
Reform Party's Pat Buchanan 2 percent, with 7 percent still unsure.
In a two-man matchup, Gore led 47-43 percent. A week ago, Bush led
Gore 43-40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIFICALLY, HE THINKS IT A GOOD MOVE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said that his surge in polls following the Democratic
convention is evidence that voters want a campaign based on issues
rather than images. ``I do think that from the reaction of the
crowds, the risks I took to talk specifics has paid off,'' he said.
New polls suggest the race between him and George W. Bush has
tightened since last week's convention. Several voter surveys
indicated the race is in a dead heat; 10 days ago Bush led by 10
points or more.
</P>
<P>
   BEATING THE DRUM FOR MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to slow Al Gore's post-convention gains in the polls,
George W. Bush is taking multiple swings at the Clinton
administration on military affairs, proposing to spend $1.3 billion
on pay raises, schools near military bases, and veterans' health
care. ``We are going to restore morale in the U.S. military,'' Bush
told the Veterans of Foreign Wars in Milwaukee today. In addition,
he pledged ``orderly and timely'' withdrawal of troops from Bosnia
and Kosovo, saying the administration has committed the nation to
military confrontations that lack a direct national interest.
</P>
<P>
   INVASION OF DEMOCRATIC TERRITORY
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a pair of new TV spots, George W. Bush and Dick Cheney
plan to visit 16 battleground states between now and Labor Day.
Most of those states have not been won by Republican presidential
candidates in the past two elections. Democrats have taken
Wisconsin and Iowa, Bush's stops Monday, since 1984. Today, Bush
will visit Illinois and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ROLLING ON THE RIVER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Joe Lieberman were wrapping up their 400-mile boat
and bus tour down the Mississippi River in Hannibal, Mo., Mark
Twain's boyhood home. They advocated targeted tax cuts to help the
middle class pay for child care, elder care and college tuition. By
contrast, George W. Bush favors an across-the-board tax reduction
whose chief beneficiaries would be the upper-income people who bear
most of the income tax burden. Said Gore: ``I want the tax cuts to
go to the people who have the hardest time paying taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL FOCUS ON FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   As a measure of the electoral prize that Florida holds, both Al
Gore and George W. Bush will make post-convention visits to the
Sunshine State, and both campaigns are enlarging their presence
there. Gore will raise money for the Democratic Party at a friend's
home in Fort Lauderdale on Wednesday night and campaign in south
and central Florida on Wednesday and Thursday. Bush will raise
money for the Republican Party at a private home in Miami on
Thursday night and campaign in Miami on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL'S STILL OUT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has made education a major focus of his campaign
speeches and is running two new education ads this week. Since Bush
took office in 1994, the Lone Star state has given schools more
money, tougher classes, help with troubled students and pay raises
for teachers. But among educators, policy-makers and parents in
Texas, and beyond, there's no clear consensus about how much credit
he deserves. Critics say many reforms began before he took office
and others were pushed by Democrats in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   A RECORD IN TAXPAYER FUNDING
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore last month became the first presidential candidate to
receive $15 million in taxpayer money for nomination expenses. Gore
agreed to limit his spending to $40.5 million in exchange for
matching federal funds, and so received an additional $673,000 in
July, bringing his total to $15.3 million, short of the ceiling of
$16.9 million. George W. Bush, who declined matching funds so he
could spend as much as he could raise, set his own record in July
by breaking the $100 million mark for fund-raising. Four years ago,
Republican Bob Dole received $13.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A RECORD IN PRIVATE FUNDING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's fund-raising total broke the $100 million mark
in the final month before receiving the Republican presidential
nomination. And he spent $9.6 million in July, bringing his total
spending to $97.2 million, according to records filed with the
Federal Election Commission. The old record for fund-raising in a
single presidential race belonged to Ross Perot, who took in $72.8
million for the 1992 general election, nearly all of it from his
own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGE TO CORPORATION COOPERATION
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Boston has scheduled a hearing for Wednesday
in a lawsuit brought by Green Party candidate Ralph Nader and
voters challenging corporate financing of the upcoming presidential
debates as illegal political contributions. Plaintiffs include
Susan Sarandon, Phil Donahue and other Nader supporters. Under
rules of the Commission on Presidential Debates, candidates must
poll at least 15 pecent in order to participate, shutting out Nader
and the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ULTERIOR MOTIVE KISSED OFF
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore insists his and wife's Tipper's electrifying kiss and
heavy embrace just before his acceptance speech last week was a
spur-of-the-moment emotional thing, not an effort to create a new
image. That's what he told TV interviewers this morning on NBC's
``Today,'' ABC's ``Good Morning America'' and CBS' ``The Early
Show.'' He denied the unabashed public show of affection was an
attempt to cast off an image if being ``wooden.'' He said the
public talk about the kiss has surprised him: ``Somebody said, `Are
you trying to send a message.' I said, `Actually, I was trying to
send a message to Tipper.' ''
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES AREN'T HISTORY YET
</P>
<P>
   There still are several late primaries to sort out. Today,
voters head to the polls in Alaska, Oklahoma and Wyoming. The
hottest congressional race of the day takes place in Oklahoma's 2nd
District, a historically Democratic stronghold in the northeastern
corner of the state that has trended Republican in recent years.
There are tight races on both sides to replace GOP Rep. Tom Coburn
, who term-limited himself and is returning to his medical practice
after three terms in the House. After Tuesday, it's Minnesota and
Rhode Island on Sept. 12 and Washington state Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   YES, VIRGINIA, THEY'RE SLUGGING IT OUT
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are plunging into Virginia's Senate race this week
with $1 million in TV attack ads. The Republican shelled out
$570,000 in ads for challenger George Allen, and the Democrats
responded with a $438,000 outlay on behalf of two-term incumbent
Charles Robb. The dueling ads, airing through Thursday, revolve
around taxes, one of the major themes in the Nov. 7 Robb-Allen
contest, as well as the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
