<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8219 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OREGON-MOUNTAI     08-21 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OREGON-MOUNTAINS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYWAYS OF THE BLUE MOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 27)  
(Editors: Also see TRAVEL-OREGON-RDUP) 
(Editors: A 560-word guide for accommodations and restaurants
appears at end of 2nd story.) 
 By DENISE FAINBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing the sidewalks are cement,'' observed the
stranger as I passed him on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at him inquiringly. ``Or they'd be rolled up!'' he
explained, guffawing.
</P>
<P>
   He had a point. Apart from him, his wife and me, only a single
family strolled down the main drag of Baker City, Ore., at six
o'clock on a Sunday evening in July. Possibly all the inhabitants
were at dinner. That didn't prevent me from admiring the dignified
Victorian buildings _ banks, hotels, homes _ that had been erected
in the raw Wild West, and were now flanked by broad leafy streets
and backed by the ragged Blue Mountains. The town of 10,000 in this
northeastern corner of Oregon is quiet now, even bucolic, but it
wasn't always that way.
</P>
<P>
   I was on a three-day exploratory jaunt through the Blue
Mountains, a range so variously defined that even many Oregonians
have never heard of it. Geologically, they are considered to spread
from the snow-capped Wallowas near the Idaho border to the gentle
Ochocos in central Oregon. In popular parlance, they extend simply
from the Washington line south to Baker City, where they are
sometimes called the Elkhorns. This semantic confusion tends to
keep them terra incognita outside the state, which is not all bad.
</P>
<P>
   The first people besides the resident American Indian population
to pass this way in any numbers were the Oregon Trail emigrants,
who must have been relieved to find this watered valley after their
desert crossing. Then gold was discovered in the 1860s. An
enterprising settler built a toll road from the Oregon Trail to the
Powder River running below the mountain range, and Baker City was
born. It grew to serve the miners and the ranchers who followed _
and a rowdy bunch they must have been. The railroad came through in
1884, bringing in the merchants who built dignified monuments to
prosperity on the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   In one of these, the Geiser Grand Hotel, I found my supper. The
Geiser was built in 1889. Sitting prominently on a corner in the
center of town it featured the most modern innovations, including
electricity and even an elevator. The spacious dining room retains
an aura of relaxed elegance, and the menu concentrates on steaks
and Northwestern fish. I had a yen for fish and chips, and theirs
turned out to be pleasantly light, so I followed it with a piece of
chocolate-hazelnut torte.
</P>
<P>
   Replete, I returned to the Grant House Bed-and-Breakfast, which
I'd selected at random (it is currently closed while the owner,
Diane Pearson, is on an extended trip to Russia). Grant House too
dates from the 1880s. Pearson, a school librarian, has brought in
some family heirlooms: a floral wool carpet and her childhood
piano, which with the solid Mission-style furniture and myriad
Russian nesting dolls, or matryoshki, create a calm, welcoming
atmosphere. The three cozy guest rooms upstairs are named after
local mines; Pearson had just returned from Siberia with the dolls
and a Russian exchange student _ gratifying to me as a former
teacher of Russian _ and we all had a jolly conversation over tea.
</P>
<P>
   It was so comfortable I found it hard to leave, but the
mountains were calling; and I did, after a breakfast of fresh fruit
and homemade muffins. First I decided to see the mountains as the
early emigrants would have, from the National Historic Oregon Trail
Interpretive Center just east of town.
</P>
<P>
   The rounded hills east of Baker City are barren and dry,
enlivened only by black rock and sagebrush _ not too different from
the previous several hundred miles the pioneers would already have
endured. Some of the early diarists note their poor impression of
fabled Oregon. The interpretive center, opened in 1992, sits on
Flagstaff Hill just above a section of the old trail, whose ruts
are visible in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the main exhibits lead the visitor along a path
featuring scenes of life on the 2,000-mile trek. Actual diary
entries and explanatory plaques detail the realities of the
journey, and the hardships. Of these, disease and accidents were
the worst: in some years, 10 percent of emigrants died on the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the Blue Mountains rose impressively behind a wagon
encampment, where a volunteer in pioneer costume offered me a
biscuit freshly baked in campfire embers. The old trail was a
pencil line through the sagebrush below.
</P>
<P>
   The sun was already hot, but I decided to walk down along the
four-mile interpretive path loop. Signs advise the visitor to wear
a hat and carry water. Sage thrashers and families of grasshopper
sparrows quarreled in the brush. On the valley floor a replica
covered wagon stood beside a scrap of original trail. One could
imagine thirsty emigrants trudging through, gazing at the
evergreen-clad mountains and goading their oxen on, hoping to make
camp along the cool and leafy Powder River. They would have passed
here in late summer or early fall, when the desert was at its
hottest and driest.
</P>
<P>
   They would have proceeded northwest past the town of La Grande,
aiming for the pass at Blue Mountain Crossing. I, having the luxury
of a car and paved roads, would follow a somewhat different route.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Oregon's Scenic Byways join to provide a driver's view _
a brief sketch, as it were _ of these mountains. The tour is about
145 miles long, and as it connects with I-84 at either end, it's
possible to do a loop: explore the highlands, then return on the
Interstate to visit the few small cities _ Pendleton, La Grande,
Baker City _ strung on it like beads on a chain.
</P>
<P>
   Starting off, I drove 12 miles north to Haines to catch the
northern end of the Elkhorn Scenic Byway (Forest Service Road 73).
It looped up through farm and meadow and forests of vanilla-scented
ponderosa pine, and soon I was driving through thick, solemn stands
of spruce and fir. The air, decidedly hot down on the plain, was
aromatic and fresh. There was hardly another vehicle on the road.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 miles on I came to Anthony Lake, wrapped in firs and
pine at 7,100 feet. In winter a modest ski resort opens here to
accommodate the cognoscenti familiar with the area's dry powder.
Now, on the Fourth of July weekend, the campground was just opening
for the season. A couple of dozen people lolled about the
pocket-mirror alpine lake _ fishing, picnicking or gently floating
in rubber rafts. Across the water rose the cone of Gunsight
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   I observed snow melting into rivulets feeding the lake and
decided it was not time for a swim. Some of the picnic tables were
neatly ensconced in snowbanks. Cloudless skies invited a walk on
the graveled milelong circumference trail. Wild violets bloomed
beside the path. I passed quiet children and quieter fishermen; sat
on a rock and watched trout jumping; and on completing the circle,
stretched out lazily in the sun. Driving again, along the
switchbacky mountain road, I skirted the North Fork John Day
Wilderness Area _ 170,000 acres of uninhabited forest, canyon and
lake. Many trails thread through this primitive area, including the
23-mile North Fork John Day River Trail through the canyon, and the
equally long Elkhorn Crest Trail. A few old miners' cabins are
handy in case of inclement weather. I had to come back here, I
decided, cut loose from the car and dive into the magnificent
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1804EDT &QL; 
