<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8221 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OREGON-BLUE-MO     08-21 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OREGON-BLUE-MOUNTAINS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: magnificent wilderness.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My time now was limited. I joined the Blue Mountains Scenic
Byway at Forest Service Road 53 and paused at the Bridge Creek
Wildlife Area. The Forest Service acquired this tract of meadow and
open woods as a winter feeding range for elk (the elk were using it
anyway, annoying the ranchers). Up a short trail, a stand of pines
overlooked hundreds of square miles of the John Day River drainage.
</P>
<P>
   It was late in the afternoon. A bluish haze hung over the
valley. The sun beat down, raising a sweet-oniony smell from the
hundreds of mariposa lilies in bloom. I bent down to sniff one, and
discovered a tiny azure butterfly inside, which was immediately
joined by another. For half an hour I soaked in the sun and
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Presently it dawned on me that, not having brought a tent, I
would have to find a place to sleep. I meandered on a few miles to
the hamlet of Ukiah, population 245. A month earlier the town would
have been ringed with meadows of blue camas flowers, whose roots
were a traditional Indian staple.
</P>
<P>
   Ukiah lies in a saucer-shaped depression between mountains and
looks like the set for an episode of ``Wyatt Earp.'' The short main
street is flanked by low plank buildings _ a couple of general
stores, a cafe, a Mexican restaurant _ and the Antlers Inn. The
sides of the inn were literally covered with antlers of deer, elk,
moose and even caribou, reminding me that here big game is
plentiful and hunters even more so. Rough wooden signs offered
``Rooms'' and ``Drop-In Showers, $5.00.'' It looked intriguing, but
no one answered my knock.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly I followed the rushing Grande Ronde River 35 miles down
on Route 244 to the town of La Grande. On I-84 I turned northwest,
following the approximate route of the emigrants' crossing amid a
wagon train of semis. At the top of the pass, a herd of elk browsed
along the highway _ their summer feeding grounds?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, as if a curtain had dropped, the panorama of a
blood-red sunset on the vast brown Columbia Plateau opened up _ a
sobering view for weary pioneers. Soon I pulled into the city of
Pendleton and checked into the clean but plain Vagabond Inn (a
motel that has since changed hands and is now called the Economy
Inn).
</P>
<P>
   East of Pendleton on the Umatilla Indian Reservation is the new
Tamastslikt Cultural Institute. The museum, right next to the
Wildhorse Casino Resort, was opened in 1998 by the Cayuse, Walla
Walla and Umatilla tribes. It's the newest of the five Oregon Trail
Centers, and its focus is the culture of the Columbia Plateau
tribes and the Oregon Trail's impact upon them.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning I drove out to the reservation. The round
wood-and-stone museum stands on a level plain fronting the
foothills. Within, a temporary exhibition hall contained children's
illustrations _ some on brown paper cut to the shape of a deer hide
_ of Indian folk tales. In the main halls the coyote materializes
as a silhouette on walls and in folk stories emanating from tape
players, running like a spirit guide through the tribes' story.
</P>
<P>
   Replicas of a winter lodge, an early missionary church and a
trading fort anchor the narrative. The history winds through the
introduction of the horse, the trappers and missionaries, then the
huge influx of settlers and confinement to reservations. It was
interesting to trace the changes in tools, dress and ornaments:
from the traditional stone, bone, shell and hide, to glass beads
obtained through trade with the Spanish and English, to woven cloth
and metal goods.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy, too, was how these Old World goods were adapted:
beads, for instance, being worked in native and French-influenced
patterns not only for personal adornment but also for decorating
the horses of which the Northwest tribes were so passionately fond.
Exhibits on the present and future of the tribes cover Indian
salmon recovery projects, efforts for economic growth, and hopes
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Two things made a strong impression on this particular visitor.
First, learning that the horse, so dramatically involved with the
economy, culture and mythology of the tribes, only reached the
Columbia Plateau in the early 1700s. The famous Nez Perce
horse-breeders noted in the journals of Lewis and Clark had had
just a century to hone their skills.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the process by which the original 800-square-mile
Umatilla Reservation was reduced to the present 172,000 acres, or
269 square miles, as the settlers' hunger for farmland grew. First
acreages were whittled away; then came ``allotment,'' in which
tracts were allotted to individual tribal members, and many ended
up sold off to non-Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In the cafe I bought a glass of huckleberry juice, then drove an
hour back up to the mountains for a last look. A large grouse
observed me with nonchalance on the quiet Scenic Byway. A detour
due to repaving was a blessing: along a dirt road, a camas meadow
was in late bloom, like a hyacinth-blue lake.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STOP &QL; 
Getting There
</P>
<P>
   From Portland, take I-84 approximately 150 miles to Heppner
Junction, where the 145-mile Blue Mountains Scenic Byway begins on
State Highway 74. After 45 miles, at Heppner, the exceedingly
well-marked Byway continues along Willow Creek Road and Forest
Service Road 53 to Ukiah and the North Fork John Day campground.
From there take the 106-mile Elkhorn Scenic Byway (Forest Service
Road 73) east to Anthony Lake and Haines, or, on 73 and Route 7,
south to Baker City.
</P>
<P>
   Or, from Boise, take I-84 to Baker City, and follow the route in
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the high country roads are blocked until mid-June.
Summer and early fall offer fine weather, though nights can be
cool, even cold.
</P>
<P>
   A free guide to the Oregon Scenic Byways is available from the
Oregon Tourism Commission in Salem; (800) 547-7842;
www.traveloregon &QL; 
.com. One helpful Web site showing the routes is
www.tripcheck.com/general/scenicbyways.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations
</P>
<P>
   The Grant House Bed-and-Breakfast in Baker City, is currently
closed. My room was $55.
</P>
<P>
   The Geiser Grand Hotel, 1996 Main Street, Baker City, Ore.
97814, (888) 434-7374 or (541) 523-1889, has 30 rooms, a restaurant
and saloon. Doubles are $89 to $199.
</P>
<P>
   At the Economy Inn previously the Vagabond Inn), 201 Southwest
Court Avenue, Pendleton, Ore. 97801, (541) 276-5252, singles are
$37, doubles $50.
</P>
<P>
   Campsites are available in the mountains, some free and some at
$5 to $8. Contact the Wallowa-Whitman National Forest, at (541)
426-5546, or the Umatilla National Forest, at (541) 278-3716.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Geiser's Grand Hotel and Restaurant in Baker City is open for
breakfast, lunch and dinner, serving hearty regional meals. Dinners
run $15 to $25 without wine.
</P>
<P>
   Como's Italian Eatery, 39 Southeast Court Avenue, Pendleton,
(541) 278-9142, serves Italian dishes, including as homemade
polenta; lunch and early dinner. Lunch specials, $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   What to Do
</P>
<P>
   Hiking trails abound; maps and information are available from
the Wallowa-Whitman and Umatilla National Forests. Outfitters offer
pack trips, rafting, fishing.
</P>
<P>
   For skiing, call the Anthony Lakes Mountain Resort, (541)
856-3277. Further information is available through the Eastern
Oregon Visitor Association Web site, www.eova.com or the Baker
County Visitor and Convention Bureau at (800) 523-1235.
</P>
<P>
   History buffs may enjoy the mining towns of Granite and Sumpter
on Forest Service Road 73 west of Baker City. Both had their heyday
in the late 19th and early 20th centuries; Sumpter has a small
narrow-gauge railroad and the nearby Sumpter Valley Railroad Park.
</P>
<P>
   The National Historic Oregon Trail Interpretive Center, five
miles east of Baker City on Route 86, (541) 523-1843, is open 9
a.m. to 6 p.m. from April 1 to Oct. 31, and 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. from
Nov. 1 to March 31. Open daily except Christmas and New Year's.
Admission, $5; children and seniors $3.50; or $10 per carload.
</P>
<P>
   Tamastslikt Cultural Institute, (541) 966-9748, is seven miles
east of Pendleton on I-84 (Exit 216), and is open 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
daily except Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's. Admission is
$6, $4 for seniors and students, ages 5 or younger are free.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
