<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PIPELINE22-COX     08-21 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PIPELINE COMPANY WAS WARNED OF CORROSION PROBLEM
 &HT;    530&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The company that owns the natural gas pipeline that
exploded Saturday, killing 10 campers in New Mexico, was warned by
federal officials three years ago of potential corrosion problems
on the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, federal inspectors said they found that employees
of El Paso Natural Gas Co. did not know how to accurately judge the
effectiveness of systems designed to protect the pipeline from
corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the National Transportation Safety Board, which is
investigating the explosion, said it may be months before they will
know what caused the 50-year-old pipeline to rupture six feet
underground. Five adults and five children died when fire from the
pipeline swept up the Pecos River, where members of two families
were camping. Two other persons were in critical condition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials did not respond Monday to telephone inquiries
about the 1997 warning. There is no reason to assume that the
problem cited in 1997 by federal officials contributed to the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Records of the Office of Pipeline Safety, the federal agency
responsible for regulating more than 1.2 million miles of pipelines
through which natural gas and hazardous liquids such as gasoline
and diesel fuel flow in America, show that El Paso Natural Gas has
experienced 40 pipeline ruptures since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline carries a significant portion of natural gas used
in Arizona and southern California, said a spokeswoman for the
Office of Pipeline Safety.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``letter of concern'' addressed to El Paso Natural Gas Co.
on March 27, 1997, the Office of Pipeline Safety said it had
learned company technicians had not been given instructions in how
to accurately determine whether a system designed to prevent
corrosion was working.
</P>
<P>
   Corrosion is one of the chief reasons for pipeline failure,
especially in older lines, federal statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   The corrosion-prevention system cited in the letter consists of
an underground wire which carries a weak electric current through
the soil near a pipeline. The current on the wire is supposed to
neutralize natural electrical processes involved in corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline companies are required to periodically measure
electrical conditions in the surrounding soil to make sure this
``cathodic protection'' system is working properly. However,
underground probes used to measure the soil's electric charge are
often inserted several feet away from the pipe itself, explained
Donald Deaver, a Houston engineer and pipeline consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the soil between the probe and the pipe can
affect readings and must be taken into account, Deaver said.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter to El Paso Natural Gas, Office of Pipeline Safety
official James C. Thomas said company technicians had told his
inspectors they were concerned about possible errors caused by
these soil conditions but did not know how to calculate
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the error source is unknown then we must conclude that
the levels of protection on the pipeline are also unknown,'' Thomas
said in the ``Letter of Concern'' to El Paso Natural Gas. ``They
may be too high or too low.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Deaver said that if the current flowing through the cathodic
protection wire is too low, the wire will fail to protect the
pipeline from corrosion. If it is too high, it can cause the
pipeline to start cracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having an accurate cathodic protection measurement is
extremely important to knowing that you have the proper amount of
current on that wire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Klinger, a spokeswoman for the Office of Pipeline
Safety, said Monday she did not know how El Paso Natural Gas had
responded to the 1997 warning letter. However, she said that if the
problem was not corrected, the company would be subject to fines.
</P>
<P>
   A pipeline reform organization created in the aftermath of a
gasoline pipeline explosion that killed three persons last year in
Bellingham, Wash., sent condolences to the families of the victims
of Saturday's explosion.
</P>
<P>
   However, the organization, SAFE Bellingham, said its efforts to
get Congress to enact stronger pipeline safety laws had been
opposed by the natural gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tragic and incomprehensible that this industry is
fighting our efforts to improve pipeline safety by spending money
on lobbyists in Washington, D.C. when they should be spending money
to ensure their pipelines do not threaten public safety,'' said
Carl Weimer, executive director or SAFE Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics compiled by the Transportation Department's Office of
Pipeline Safety, the agency that regulates the pipeline industry,
show that corrosion has been the most common reason for ruptures in
large, cross-country natural gas transmission lines this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the web: http://www.safebellingham.org
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
