<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OREGON-ROUNDUP     08-21 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OREGON-ROUNDUP-$ADV27-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS AND INDIANS MINGLE AT THE PENDLETON ROUNDUP IN OREGON
</HEADLINE>
 By SUSAN G. HAUSER  
 (for release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After singing the national anthem at the opening ceremony of the
Pendleton Round-Up in northeastern Oregon last September, all the
men in the grandstands returned their cowboy hats to their heads
and everybody settled back down into their seats. The rodeo
princesses were introduced over the loudspeaker, and a small herd
of quarter horses streaked out from a far corner, each in full
gallop and bearing a member of the royal court. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holding the reins in one hand and waving furiously with the
other, the local beauties in matching cowgirl garb, with fringed
leather vests and trousers, tan boots and gloves, managed to keep
their western hats _ and their smiles _ firmly attached while their
horses leaped over a fence and sped around the perimeter of the
large outdoor arena. They came to an abrupt halt in a perfect line
in front of the main grandstand. With not a hair out of place, the
four Round-Up royals continued to smile and wave, acknowledging the
accolades of the crowd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I figured I was not the only one impressed by the dexterous
performance of the cowgirl court. Over by the chutes, which would
be spewing out snorting bulls and broncs for the next four hours,
the professional cowboys were probably wondering, ``Now, how can I
top that?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, they found a way. Starting with bareback bronc riding,
and then getting bounced and bruised through steer wrestling, bull
riding and other feats of skill and stamina, the more than 500
cowboys who made their way from every corner of the continent to
this Oregon town demonstrated once again that the Pendleton
Round-Up _ with this year's event, Sept. 13 to 16, marking the 90th
year _ is one of the best rodeos around. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the largest four-day rodeo in the world, though it doesn't
quite compare to the likes of the Calgary Stampede in Alberta,
Canada, or the National Finals in Oklahoma City, 10-day events with
huge prize money. But in Pendleton, with more than $250,000 at
stake, and altogether more than 50,000 fans watching, this is where
many a world record has been made or broken, where successful
cowboys can walk away a lot richer and where unsuccessful cowboys
can walk away a lot more . . . well, experienced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pendleton Round-Up began in 1910 as a sort of harvest
festival, scheduled in late September to allow the grain farmers
from the rolling hills around Pendleton to complete their season's
work. The events were much the same as at the previous year's
Fourth of July celebration, where farmers and ranch hands, along
with Indians from the nearby Umatilla Reservation, competed in
bronc riding, horse races, greased-pig catching and sack races, and
enjoyed Indian dancing and feasts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting the Pendleton Round-Up apart from any other rodeo is the
fact that Indians from all over the West fully participate in the
four days of rodeo events, which include the nightly Happy Canyon
pageant and the Friday morning Westward Ho! Parade, when colorfully
dressed cowboys and Indians ride horses or wagons. Indian
participation dates from the very first Round-Up and stems from the
congenial relationship between residents of Pendleton and the
Umatilla reservation, eight miles east of town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special Indian events during Round-Up include two beauty
contests, bareback relay races and ceremonial dancing, in full
regalia. The main dancing event is held at 9 a.m. Saturday in the
rodeo arena, with competitions in the war dance, the rabbit dance,
the circle dance and the swan dance.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every mid-September at Round-Up time, an Indian village springs
up near the arena; the crossed poles and tops of 250 tepees can be
seen from the rodeo grandstands. For a week the village is
populated with Umatilla, Cayuse and Walla Walla Indians from the
reservation, as well as visitors from about a dozen other Western
tribes. Adjacent to the village, extending into Roy Raley Park, is
the Indian arts and crafts fair, where jewelry, beadwork, baskets,
dolls, rugs and pottery are for sale, not to mention delicious
frybread smothered with huckleberry jam. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last September, I attended the official opening day, Wednesday,
when the last event of the day (wild horse racing) is followed by
the post-rodeo barbecue supper in Roy Raley Park, next to the
arena. For $4, I loaded up my plate with a barbecue beef sandwich,
coleslaw and beans, then sat in the shaded grass to eat with
hundreds of other rodeo goers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Except for female Indian dancers, relay racers and the rodeo
royalty, all the participants in the Pendleton Round-Up are men.
(This year, however, women's barrel racing is back for the first
time since 1962.) Between events I visited the Hall of Fame, a tiny
museum under the south grandstand, to admire old photographs of
some of the earlier Round-Up stars, women who could break broncs
and hogtie calves with the best of the cowboys. In fact, in 1914
Bertha Blancett came within 12 points of winning the rodeo's
all-around title. Women's events were removed from the program
after the bronc buster Bonnie McCarroll died in 1929 after getting
bucked onto her head. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her death was only one of three in the 90 years of the Round-Up.
But the total of broken bones and bruises has never been tallied. I
counted quite a few rough landings during my day at the rodeo, from
cowboys getting ejected from bulls or broncs, to steer wrestlers
leaping from their racing horses onto racing steers and _ oops,
missing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the roughest event of the afternoon was the brahma bull
riding. These hump-necked bulls whirled and twirled and snorted and
stomped. If they couldn't stomp on a felled cowboy, they took off
after any other breathing creature within sight. A one-ton bull
barreling toward the sidelines could always disperse several dozen
cowboys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But each contestant managed to brush himself off and hurry from
the field, or in some cases get plucked from a furious animal by
the mounted pickup crew.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon I took a break from the rodeo to cautiously set
foot in the Let 'Er Buck Room, the infamous bar beneath the south
grandstand. The first thing to catch my eye was the sign
prominently displayed behind the bar: ``Keep Your Clothes On.
Indecent Exposure Will Not Be Tolerated. Anyone Involved Will Be
Banned From the Premises.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I quickly learned that until just a few years ago it was
customary for some women at the rowdy bar to remove their upper
garments, often while sitting on a cowboy's shoulders. Now former
college football players, disguised as burly cowboys, wander
through the standing crowd (there are no tables or chairs in the
one-room bar) to head off any possibility of indecent exposure. I
decided not to buy a drink (hard liquor only), thereby avoiding the
need to visit the ``heifer room'' (the men's room simply has a set
of bull horns over the door) and possibly having to pass through
the so-called cowboy gantlet. ``You expect to be groped here,'' a
cheerful young woman told me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems this city of 17,125 has always been wild and woolly,
beginning as a frontier town about 20 years after wagon trains of
the Oregon Trail first passed by. At one time as many as 18
brothels and 32 bars could be found within an eight-block radius.
Until 1912 there was no local sheriff to put a damper on the wild
living. The brothels, particularly popular with airmen at the World
War II-era Army air training base in Pendleton, remained in
operation until outlawed in 1953. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, more sedate activities abound in Pendleton, where the
buildings are low, the streets are wide and the sun is hot at
Round-Up time. A good way to beat the heat is to take the Pendleton
Underground Tour and traipse through the tunnels and rooms carved
out by Chinese laborers about 130 years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The original purpose of the tunnels was to provide safe and
speedy delivery of merchandise from business to business during a
lawless period, when robberies were frequent. Eventually, the
underground chambers became convenient places for bars, card rooms
and even a few more wholesome enterprises, such as an ice cream
parlor and a laundry. The Chinese laundry doubled as a bathhouse,
where the price of a bath dropped a penny for each bather who had
used the water before you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Underground Tour is followed by a walk through the Cozy
Rooms brothel, which operated from 1923 to 1953. This part of the
tour is really less about the enterprise than about the madam,
Stella Darby, who was known for her good works and acts of charity.
I happen to know two brothers who Stella raised, rescuing them from
an unhappy family life, and they turned out just fine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compared with brothel browsing, the Happy Canyon pageant is
definitely a G-rated entertainment. With a cast of hundreds of
local residents and members of the nearby reservation, the history
of the Old West is depicted nightly in narrated action at an
outdoor arena adjacent to the rodeo arena. The show has changed
only minimally since it was first produced in 1914. In a way, the
same goes for the cast of characters, because roles in the pageant
are passed on to family members from one generation to the next. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pageant begins with peaceful scenes from Native American
life, later disrupted by a flood of pioneers. The scenes from a
frontier town are mostly slapstick, but work up to the grand
finale, the truly impressive Mounted Quadrille. Four couples on
horseback display intricate equine choreography in a rousing square
dance. Finally, an Indian brave carries the American flag up the
set's mountainside, the band plays the national anthem and the
audience is invited into the dance hall for music and refreshment.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles east of town, on reservation land, is the Wildhorse
Casino, featuring 400 slots, poker, blackjack, live keno, off-track
betting and bingo. It is next to a 100-room hotel and 18-hole golf
course, and it has become a popular destination for travelers
heading east up the long, lonely road from Pendleton into the Blue
Mountains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But not far to the west is the Round-Up arena, where at 1:15
p.m. for four days in a row the boom of a cannon signals the start
of the rodeo. And over the loudspeaker the announcer stirs up the
expectant crowd by intoning: ``There is a battle cry heard
throughout the world, simply known as `Let 'er buck!'''(BBOX) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to find the bunkhouses and chuck wagons &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton is 200 miles east of Portland on Interstate 84.
Horizon Airlines, (800) 547-9308, flies from Portland International
Airport, about 55 minutes nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Round-Up is Sept. 13 to 16. Tickets for the daily
rodeo competition, which begins at 1:15 p.m. and ends around 6
p.m., are $10 to $13. Seats for the Happy Canyon pageant are $6 to
$12. Call (800) 457-6336 to order tickets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   For help finding lodging, call the Pendleton Chamber of
Commerce, (800) 547-8911. When motels fill up, residents also rent
out their guest rooms.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best Western Pendleton Inn, 400 Southeast Nye Avenue, (541)
276-2135, fax (541) 278-2129, has a swimming pool and exercise
room. Double rates in the 69 rooms are $67. During Round-Up, rates
are $134. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 170-room Red Lion Hotel, 304 Southeast Nye Avenue, (541)
276-6111, fax (541) 278 2413, has a dining room, an outdoor pool
and a beautiful view of the Blue Mountains. Doubles: $74; during
Round-Up, $155. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorse Casino Resort Hotel, 72779 Highway 331, (800)
654-9453, fax (541) 966 1717, has 100 rooms next to the casino,
also owned and operated by the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla
Indian Reservation. There's an indoor pool and spa, 18-hole golf
course and RV park. Doubles: $65; during Round-Up, $150.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Working Girls Hotel, 17 Southwest Emigrant, (800) 226-6398,
fax (541) 276-0665, is in one of the bordellos that once flourished
in Pendleton. There are four antique-filled rooms with a shared
bath at $50, and one suite is $70; during Round-Up, rates are $100
and $125, respectively. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A barbecue-beef sandwich supper ($4) is served on Wednesday of
Round-Up week in Roy Raley Park, next to the Round-Up arena; the
Hall of Fame barbecue supper is served in the Safeway parking lot
on Thursday; the cowboy breakfast ($5), with pancakes, eggs and
ham, is served each day at Stillman Park.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cimmiyotti's, 137 South Main, (541) 276-4314, has a dark
cocktail-lounge atmosphere, with good steaks, seafood and Italian
food.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael's Restaurant and Catering, 233 Southeast Fourth Street,
(541) 276-8500, is in a 1904 Queen Anne house that was the home of
Roy Raley, the founder of the Pendleton Round-Up. It is decorated
with contemporary Indian art, and serves seasonal game and produce.
Menu items include smoked quail with huckleberry sauce, brandied
peppered salmon and hickory roasted prime rib. It is open from 5 to
9 p.m. Tuesday to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   What to Do  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton Woolen Mills, 1307 Southeast Court Place, (541)
276-6911, offers free tours Monday to Friday, 9 and 11 a.m., 1:30
and 3 p.m. The company's prized Indian blankets have been made here
for nearly 100 years. Blankets and clothing are for sale at the
mill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Underground Tours begin at 37 Southwest Emigrant, (541)
276-0730. The 90-minute tour of underground businesses and a
second-story bordello is $10, $5 ages 12 and younger. Tour times
vary; during Round-Up week they are offered every 15 minutes from 9
a.m. to 7 p.m. daily. Reservations are recommended. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
