<HEADER>
A8230 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-1stLe     08-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-1stLede-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERNS ABOUT PIPELINES GROW AS MAJOR ACCIDENTS INCREASE
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Updates New Mexico explosion death toll in 8th graf. Updating
1st take only; no other changes.) 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By NEIL STRASSMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Miller's 15-year dream of carving a piece of paradise out of
East Texas bottomland near Greenville was lost last March to
500,000 gallons of gasoline that poured across fields and down a
creek bed beside his land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole place smelled like a refinery,'' he said. ``You
could have tossed a match in the creek, and it would have caught
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the gasoline that spilled from the ruptured, underground
Explorer pipeline can be cleaned up, Miller says, the land is no
longer the rural sanctuary that his family treasured.
</P>
<P>
   Pipelines are safer than trucks, barges and tankers for shipping
oil and gas, but concerns about the aging, infrequently inspected
lines are mounting as the number of major accidents increases.
</P>
<P>
   Urban neighborhoods, ranchers and farmers have organized to
block proposed lines from passing through their land. Congress,
federal regulators and watchdog groups are moving to protect
heavily populated regions and the environment. The federal Office
of Pipeline Safety, an arm of the Transportation Department, has
been sharply criticized as ineffective and vulnerable to pipeline
industry influence.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board,
which investigates pipeline accidents, put it bluntly in a speech
last December to the Association of Oil Pipe Lines, a Washington
pipeline trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The products in your lines _ if they escape _ pollute and
kill,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten people, including five children under the age of six,
suffered a fiery death Saturday when a natural gas pipeline
exploded at the Pecos River near Carlsbad, N.M. An 11th person died
on Monday. They had been camping and fishing on the river. The fire
was so intense that sand melted into glass and some concrete on a
nearby bridge turned to powder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three people were killed in a Jan. 14 Garland, Texas, house
explosion when natural gas leaked from a cracked 4-inch gas main in
an alley behind the house. The line had been scheduled for repair.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed or injured in the Greenville accident, but the
outcome was deadly a year ago when 250,000 gallons of gasoline
spilled from a broken pipeline in Bellingham, Wash. After a flicked
cigarette lighter sparked a fire in a gasoline-saturated creek, a
huge fireball swept downstream, killing two 10-year-old boys and a
fisherman and injuring eight others.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS A DANGER
</P>
<P>
   Texas, with 250,000 miles of pipelines, has had more accidents
in the past 15 years than any other state. State officials say that
75 percent of the accidents are a result of contractors
accidentally digging into pipelines. But when Texas adopted a
call-before-you-dig program in 1998, it was the last state in the
continental United States to do so. The program has reduced the
number of pipeline accidents nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer pipeline is well-marked in the Dallas/Fort Worth
Metroplex, but at least three times in the past 15 years it has
been damaged in construction accidents. The line runs through
Grapevine's business district, following the Cotton Belt rail line
north of Dallas Street to a tank farm in Southlake, across from the
new Grapevine High School stadium on Texas 26. The tank farm has
been a relatively safe facility with few problems.
</P>
<P>
   A branch of the pipeline then heads east, carrying jet fuel to
D/FW Airport, and another branch continues to a tank farm just
north of downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to be concerned about the line, but the city
doesn't regulate it,'' Grapevine Mayor William D. Tate said. ``When
you are moving fuel under pressure, there is always a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Sands, Explorer vice president of operations, says the
company has a good safety record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a philosophy to maintain the highest levels of safety
and integrity: If in doubt, shut down,'' he said. ``We have had
some third-party damage.''
</P>
<P>
   In Addison north of Dallas on June 19, 1985, a backhoe punctured
the line, sending a geyser of flames 100 feet into the air. Flames
seared the top of an adjacent 12-story office building, and the
fire spread underground. Neighboring shopping malls were evacuated.
One person mowing grass nearby was burned.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 1997, a half-mile north of Grapevine High School on
the Southlake side of Texas 26, a contractor struck the line with a
tree-planting machine. No one was injured and no fire broke out,
but 2,500 gallons of gasoline was spilled.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, 1999, a contractor working along William D. Tate
Avenue in Grapevine, near a half-dozen fast-food restaurants,
punctured the airport fuel line. About 4,250 gallons of jet fuel
spilled, but without causing injuries or fire.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of the largest environmental disasters to hit North
Texas in decades, the high-pressure 28-inch Explorer pipeline split
open March 9, releasing a half-million gallons of gasoline and
50,000 gallons of the toxic additive MTBE, methyl tertiary-butyl
ether. Pushed by heavy rains, the fuel washed 25 miles to Lake
Tawakoni, which supplies Dallas with as much as 220 million gallons
of drinking water a day during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the MTBE contamination of Tawakoni, Dallas water
officials waited until last week to begin using the lake again.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8231 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-VIETNAM-$ADV27     08-21 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VIETNAM-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRICKLE, NOT A RUSH, IN TOURISM TO VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 25) 
By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam _ Twenty-five years after the end of the Vietnam
War and a month after the United States completed an historic trade
agreement with its former enemy, tour organizers in both countries
hope that American travelers will finally start to make their way
to Vietnam in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The trade pact, which was signed on July 13, is not expected to
have an immediate, direct impact on tourism. It is mainly intended
to expand trade in goods between the two countries, and to open
Vietnam's backward economy to American investment.
</P>
<P>
   Among Vietnamese tourism officials, the hope is that the
agreement will inspire new confidence in this country among
Americans planning to travel to Asia. Although the country boasts
5,000 years of history, cities and countryside of exceptional
beauty, unspoiled palm-fringed beaches and some of the best food in
Asia, many Americans apparently still see Vietnam as a difficult,
even hostile destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think Vietnam is like North Korea,'' said Doug Reese, the
Washington-based representative for Vietnam tourism, a government
agency. ``People keep thinking about the war. They think Vietnam is
dangerous, that they won't be welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   As most recent visitors to Vietnam will attest, the country is
eager to welcome foreign travelers, Americans in particular, and
the friendliness of the reception can be overwhelming to any
American who remembers the torment of the war.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent nationwide celebration to mark the 25th
anniversary of the country's reunification _ and the defeat of the
American-backed government of South Vietnam _ the Communist
government offered little of the anti-American propaganda that was
once was its daily fare.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the current Vietnamese population was born after the
war, and Vietnamese youngsters avidly enjoy American music and
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Since she began organizing tours to Vietnam three years ago,
Lesley Gonzalez of Asian Pacific Adventures in Northridge, Calif.,
said her clients have yet to report a bad experience. ``All of
their expectations,'' she said, ``are surpassed: the hotels, the
food, the hospitality of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese officials have been disappointed by the sluggish
growth in tourism from the United States. Of the 64,400 visas
reported issued to Americans last year by the Vietnamese Embassy in
Washington, almost 46,100 of them went to Vietnamese-Americans,
many going to see their families, not to spend money at tourist
sites or in hotels or restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, foreign tourism to Vietnam continues to set records.
The country's tourism authority recorded almost 1.06 million
visitors in the first six months of the year, a jump of 18 percent
from the same period of 1999. China, France, Taiwan, Britain and
Japan sent the largest numbers of tourists last year, in that
order.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese had hoped for _ and planned for _ more dramatic
growth. A building boom in the early 1990s has resulted in a glut
of hotel rooms, notably in Hanoi, the nation's capital, and Ho Chi
Minh City, formerly Saigon. According to government figures, the
country's hotel occupancy rate last year was 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One result, for visitors, is that Vietnam can be a bargain.
Comfortable, newly renovated hotel rooms can be had for under $20 a
night in major cities. World-class luxury is a relative bargain as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened five-star Hilton Hanoi Opera _ not to be
confused with the prison down the street that was known to jailed
American pilots as the Hanoi Hilton _ offers rooms for $94 a night
plus 15 percent tax, a rate that includes breakfast, evening
cocktails, butler service and a full gym.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is the fabled Metropole Hotel, a lovingly
restored French colonial gem that is now run by Sofitel, the French
hotel chain. A five-course meal in its Vietnamese restaurant costs
less than $20 with wine, and features a floor show of Vietnamese
dance. Rooms begin at $100, plus tax.
</P>
<P>
   The lag in U.S. tourism may be due less to memories of the war
and more to a practical fact: There are no direct flights between
the United States and Vietnam. Tourism officials in both countries
say that an American tourist influx will begin in earnest only when
the two countries establish direct air connections.
</P>
<P>
   Currently Americans are usually required to connect elsewhere in
Asia with flights of Vietnam Airlines or one of several Asian or
European airlines that fly to Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vietnam Airlines has junked most of its old Russian
fleet and replaced it with new Boeing and Airbus jets, tour
operators say American travelers are wary of flying Vietnam's
national carrier. ``It's important for the U.S. carriers to go,''
Reese said. ``The arrival of the American carriers is like the U.S.
government seal of approval for travel to Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, Northwest and other American carriers have said
they are eager to obtain landing rights in Vietnam. But
negotiations on an air-rights agreement have repeatedly bogged
down. There is optimism in Washington and Hanoi that the trade
agreement signed last month has established an atmosphere of
cooperation that will extend to the landing-rights talks, which are
resuming this summer.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
