<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to make the grade when paying for college
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Just in case you haven't noticed, school has begun
again. That's cause for panic among some parents of teens who are
beginning their last year in high school, SmartMoney (September)
notes.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a parent of a high school senior, but you're not
counting on something like Georgia's HOPE scholarship program and
you haven't saved enough to pay for your child's college education,
calm down, the magazine advises.
</P>
<P>
   SmartMoney lays out a host of options to meet the bills,
information on applying for federal help and a suggestion that you
can negotiate aid packages with some colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Another point the magazine makes is that parents should not
assume their income level will keep their offspring from qualifying
for financial need. SmartMoney says the latest available figures
show 25 percent of students whose parents earned at least $100,000
received grants.
</P>
<P>
   Suited for battle
</P>
<P>
   The legal fight between designer Calvin Klein and clothing
manufacturer Linda Wachner is the hottest news out of the fashion
world. Fortune (Sept. 4) offers a runway view of a feud it says
``is as much about personality as it is about business.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in Fortune: A look at how Microsoft is trying to understand
what makes the under-23 crowd tick.
</P>
<P>
   Netting ordinary people
</P>
<P>
   The Internet long ago stopped being the province of the few. So
for its fourth anniversary issue, Yahoo Internet Life (September)
chronicles how ordinary and some-not-so ordinary people use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among those profiled are 59-year-old smoke jumper Murray Taylor,
fire eater and sword swallower Keith Nelson, sushi chef Jay
Catapusan and matchmaker Rabbi Shmuley Boteach.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Yahoo Internet Life: An online guide to the Summer
Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is ...
</P>
<P>
   In case you're curious, Worth (September) subscribers think
Swissair is the best airline, Morningstar Mutual Funds the best
investment newsletter and NetBank, of Alpharetta, the best online
bank. The annual ranking, with 27 categories of products and
services, is based on a survey of Worth subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding for more
</P>
<P>
   ``The inherent biases in big companies are very difficult to
break,'' says Heidi Miller, explaining why she left her job as
chief financial officer at Citigroup earlier this year to join
Priceline.com. At Citigroup, she tells Working Woman (September),
``it was certainly clear to me that I was not, in the foreseeable
future, going to manage any part of the organization directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting ...
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (Sept. 4) presents its annual survey of closed-end mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   eCompany Now (September) offers advice on how to overcome
corporate infighting and other potential problems when a business
tries to add electronic commerce capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
