<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Aug. 22 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service night
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The United Nations has assembled a
new team of weapons inspectors for service in Iraq. By Barbara
Crossette and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTHS-EXECUTE (Undated) _ If the state of Georgia electrocutes
Alexander Williams on Thursday, as planned, five men who committed
murder when they were 17 will have been put to death this year in
the United States. That is more than in any year since 1954, when
six teenagers were executed in Florida and Georgia. While
proponents say such executions are justified, given the
increasingly heinous nature of juvenile crime, opponents call it
unconscionable. Most juvenile offenders on death row are in
Southern states, while most countries in the world prohibit the
practice. A Special Report by Sarah Rimer and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-THINNING (Flagstaff, Ariz.) _ The Clinton administration
has been sharply criticized for failing to do some things that
would have made this fire season less devastating. One
controversial measure, known as forest thinning, allows more
logging in places where forests have become too dense. But in many
places around the country, environmentalists have successfully
opposed this. We go to a place where such a fight played out
recently. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-IMMIG (Zagreb) _ The chaotic lands of the Balkans have
become the latest gateway to western Europe for tens of thousands
of illegal immigrants from China, South Asia and Mideast countries
like Iran and Iraq, according to Western diplomats, local officials
and the increasing number of refugees who get caught en route. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-TRADE (Undated) _ In a startling four-team trade that
ends the Patrick Ewing era in New York, the Knicks send the veteran
center to Seattle and in exchange receive forward Vin Baker from
the Sonics and forward Glen Rice from the Los Angeles Lakers. Ewing
played for 15 seasons in New York, often with distinction and
always with remarkable effort. But in recent seasons, his injuries
mounted, as did the sense that he was unable to adjust to being a
secondary player in the team's offense. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   DEBEERS-STRATEGY (London) _ De Beers has had to confront
accusations that the company has links to traffic in diamonds from
Africa's war zones. But it has also had to face a much bigger
challenge: that its huge stockpile of diamonds, used to help
control the supply and keep world prices high, had become a costly
albatross. Now, De Beers is using the controversy over so-called
blood diamonds to advance a strategic switch to address its
commercial problems. The plan is to turn De Beers from a stockpile
manager into a branded, high-value diamond-trader that would keep
diamonds from war zones out of the luxury market. Marketing, not
monopoly, would make sure the company maintained its leadership
position. By seizing the moral high ground, De Beers has already
shown signs that its business is turning around. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ As divers gained entry to the wreck
of the nuclear submarine Kursk and declared it completely flooded
and the 118-member crew dead, Russian Defense Minister Marshal Igor
Sergeyev said in a nationally televised interview Monday that the
military might have made mistakes in how it responded to the
disaster. But he defended the armed forces, saying the institution
had been robbed and stripped in recent years and he disclosed new
information to support the strong suspicion of Russian military and
civilian leaders that the Kursk collided with another submarine
that also suffered severe damage, but managed to escape undetected.
By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
</TEXT>
