<HEADLINE>
COACHES HOLD HIGH HOPES FOR WILSON IN SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When all the tumbling, twisting, and tabulating came to
an end Sunday night, America finally had its top dozen Olympic
gymnasts all in a row, ripped and ready for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disputed,'' was one of Bela Karolyi's constant refrains
throughout the women's meet, his characterization of the intense
competition. ``Fiery. Colorful.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is, will there be the glint of gold, silver, or
bronze awaiting the Yanks at Olympus?
</P>
<P>
   From the men's standpoint, head coach Peter Kormann believes his
star athlete, Blaine Wilson, could win the all-around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him better,'' said Kormann, the '76 Olympic
bronze medalist in floor exercise, who grew up swinging from trees
and tumbling in the backyard sandbox of his home in Braintree, just
outside Boston. ``And I've been watching him since the 10th grade.
</P>
<P>
   The men packed their bags Saturday night with Wilson still in
steel-gripped command of his No. 1 position on the club, a
foundation he cemented with first-place finishes in all four rounds
of the nationals and trials. The 26-year-old Wilson is their
undisputed leader, with none of the other five members _ veteran
returnee John Roethlisberger, Steve McCain, Sean Townsend, and the
Hamm twins (Morgan and Paul) _ able to push him from underneath
with any serious pressure.
</P>
<P>
   When the NBC cameras power up in Sydney, the focus will be on
Wilson, his presence and strength personified with the bold iron
cross he strikes on the rings.
</P>
<P>
   The women lack the same spiritual presence at the top of the
pack. They have Elise Ray as their No. 1 performer, but there is a
difference between ranking and role. Ray, talented and bold, has
Karolyi's backing as the unofficial captain, but she is only 18 and
this will be her first trip to the Land of the Rings.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Chow, back for a second time, and Dominique Dawes, a
three-time Olympian, at first glance would seem the better fits to
take charge of the squad. Chow, runner-up to Ray in the trials, has
the numbers for the job. But once away from the uneven bars,
balance beam, vault, and dance floor, she closes up like a day lily
at sunset. There could still be time for Dawes to be the marshal of
the mat, but her numbers were the weakest of the six. At this stage
of her career, she's more of a stabilizing voice than a bold
leader.
</P>
<P>
   A surprise here could be the 5-foot-3-inch, 83-pound Morgan
White, whose spirit and style bring that infectious quotient that
Karolyi loves. She's the closest thing the Yanks have to the pixie,
the adolescent wunderkind that has all but disappeared from the
Games _ much to Karolyi's chagrin _ with new rules mandating that
athletes must turn at least 16 the year of the Games. White turned
17 in June, and doesn't have a driver's license, but has the focus
and ferocity that just might make her grab the wheel in Sydney if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Maloney, knocked out of the No. 2 spot by the charging
Chow, was listing slightly by the end the final round Sunday night.
Jamie Dantzscher, another Olympic first-timer, was for the most
part strong, but she slipped off the balance beam twice in her
final event of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beam's always a little bit of a struggle for me,'' said
Dantzscher, whose place on the team was considered in jeopardy
earlier in the week, with Karolyi sounding as if he favored Vanessa
Atler for her vault skills. ``It had to end on beam, right? But I
figured I did my job on the other three events _ I was hoping
they'd look at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more to the point, there was greater focus on the
faltering Atler, whom Karolyi once believed could be the building
block of the team. But in two days of trials the 18-year-old Atler
couldn't post anything higher than a 9.50 (vault in prelims) and
ultimately got kicked to the curb by the dynamic Dawes.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi sounded heartbroken not to include Atler, but the
decision to go with Dawes was correct. In fact, Alyssa Beckerman
showed some pop on the last day (three scores of 9.55 or better,
fourth overall) that could have justified her being chosen over
Dawes. Beckerman will go as the alternate.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, Jamie Natalie, who ranked fifth overall in
the trials, was chosen as the alternate.
</P>
<P>
   The meet's only moment of true melancholy came early Sunday
night when Shannon Miller elected to pull out after she pancaked
her landing on her first vault and stumbled backward on her second.
She left with two jammed knees and one bruised ego, saying she
didn't want to risk injury, in case her name was called for
Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, a sullen Karolyi said Miller's performance
wasn't sufficient even to make her considered for a berth. More
days in the gym might have been a cure. But with the Games fast
approaching, the trials complete, time marched on without Miller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
