<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      08-21 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER UNDER PRESSURE? HE WINS, ANYWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When Tiger Woods slammed a 3-wood into the
trees on the par-4 12th hole Saturday at Valhalla Golf Club, then
three-putted for double-bogey, he added a slice of intrigue that
had been missing during this summer of his major championship
domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expect him to win,'' said Mark Calcavecchia early Sunday
afternoon, before Woods had teed off with a one-shot lead in the
82d PGA Championship. ``But he's hitting some errant shots and some
double-crosses. If he hits a few of those early, he could be in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia is one of Woods's favorite practice partners, a
good friend, and a PGA Tour veteran who was well aware of the
circumstances surrounding Sunday's final round. Unlike the US Open,
when Woods led by 10 shots, or the British Open, when he led by
six, Woods would have pressure on him in the closing round.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure. It had been missing at Pebble Beach and St. Andrews,
observers cried. Woods had not been challenged, and some wondered
what would happen down the stretch if he were. Calcavecchia
wondered, too, but he didn't lose sight of who it was people were
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not playing as well as he did at the US Open or British
Open,'' said Calcavecchia. ``Then again, he has a knack for being
able to hit the right shot at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some four hours later, Woods produced a flurry of shots that
made Calcavecchia's comment ring true. He had held off relative
unknown Bob May to join Ben Hogan as the only players to win three
major championships in a season, prevailing in a three-hole playoff
after a stirring back-side duel in which each player shot a
sizzling 5-under 31.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Woods earned his fifth major championship by
draining a 5-foot birdie putt on the 72d hole to force extra holes,
then going birdie-par-par in the playoff to better May's
par-par-par. A memorable punch/counterpunch, to be sure, and it
perhaps is what will be remembered. But not to be overlooked is
what paved the way for such theatrics: Woods's mental toughness,
perhaps his greatest attribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have 12 holes and be only two back in a major championship,
you just need to hang around. You know something is going to
happen,'' said Woods, who had bogeyed two of the first six holes to
fall to 11 under, two shots behind his unheralded playing parter.
When he lost a gamble and drove into rough trying to take the
shortcut to the par-5 seventh, eyebrows were raised. Was he feeling
the pressure?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Woods. He was enjoying the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' said Woods. ``As good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the deficit, Woods needed to make something happen,
because May _ whose 56 PGA Tour events had produced no wins and
just one top 10 _ wasn't going away. (itals)The right shot at the
right time.(unitals) Woods, embracing the challenge people had
wished upon him, answered the call with a sequence of shots that
came long before the playoff:
</P>
<P>
   --That third shot to the par-5 seventh, a 60-degree sand wedge
that he had practiced earlier in the week. ``You have done it in
practice,'' Woods said to himself. ``Do it again.'' He pitched to a
foot to stop the bleeding and get within one.
</P>
<P>
   --A ``little 7-iron'' at the 166-yard seventh hole and the
12-foot birdie putt that pulled him even.
</P>
<P>
   --The putt on the par-4 12th. Back down by a shot, he was 15
feet below the hole, knowing May had an easy 2-foot birdie putt. If
he missed, Woods would be down a pair. He made it.
</P>
<P>
   --Having watched May nearly jam it into the jar at the 217-yard
14th, Woods slammed a 4-iron to 15 feet to assure matching birdies.
</P>
<P>
   --Arguably the key shot of the battle, a curling 15-foot putt to
save par at the 402-yard 15th. May was tight, perhaps 6-8 feet
away, and Woods knew if he missed, May would birdie and go up by
three shots. ``If I could somehow dig down deep enough to
concentrate and control all my emotions and nerves and bury that
putt, I just felt that it would make his putt a little bit more
interesting,'' said Woods, who had put one of those
``double-crosses'' Calcavecchia talked about onto his approach to
send his ball sailing long of the green. Woods didn't just make the
putt, he willed it into the hole _ a mystical gift that cannot be
seen, touched, or explained, and one that was previously possessed
only by Jack Nicklaus. ``I just stepped up there and buried it.''
May missed and Woods's deficit remained just one.
</P>
<P>
   --A ground-shaking drive at the 17th that hugged the left side
of the fairway, cut gently, and settled in the middle, a mere 94
yards from the pin. It traveled 328 yards with a ferocity that is
uncanny. The 60-degree sand wedge that followed showed a deftness
equally uncanny. It stopped 2 feet from the cup, set up his sixth
birdie in 11 holes, and put him in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot play defense in golf, so May looked on helplessly,
though part of him couldn't help but admire what he was seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I really got to know Tiger Woods,'' said May, who had
played the course in his sleep Saturday night. ``I woke up and I
was fresh, but I had played golf all night.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no shame, said May, not one ounce of regret.
</P>
<P>
   Not after he made that 15-foot, downhill double-breaker at the
72d hole that forced Woods into a must-make situation that he
naturally made.
</P>
<P>
   Not after he had made par saves from a greenside bunker at the
first playoff hole, the 16th, and from thick rough to the right of
the next green.
</P>
<P>
   And not even after he had failed to take advantage of a Woods
drive that sailed miles left at the third playoff hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never completed my backswing,'' said May, who went left into
thick rough to remove any chance of reaching the par-5 in two, as
he had all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know where his ball was. We thought it went forward
and deeper into the bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   May played his second shot right of the fairway, into rough,
then his third just right of the pin. It hit the slope and rolled
cruelly right, onto a lower tier 30-35 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meanhile, found his drive on hardpan after it had struck
a tree, ricocheted off a cart path, and rolled for many yards, all
the while chased by a marshal who kept the crowd away. A comical
scene to many, but not to the man chasing history.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, had to lay up on a hole he figured to reach in two, but
unlike May, Woods did not put his third shot on the green. Bunkered
in front, he was faced with another one of those ``right shot at
the right time'' moments.
</P>
<P>
   The drama was great, thousands of fans sitting silently in a
golf amphitheater, as Woods disappeared down into the sand, behind
a wall of turf. He had his hands on a sand wedge and his arms
around pressure that has choked many a golfer's skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the easiest bunker shot in golf,'' Woods told
himself, well aware that he had to get it up-and-down. ``Straight
uphill with a lot of green to work with. That is what I had
envisioned and it came out perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoff win didn't come close to matching the magnitude of
his triumphs at Pebble Beach (15-shot win) and St. Andrews (eight),
but it far surpassed them in drama and served as a statement to
those who questioned what he'd do when pressured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two completely different emotions,'' said Woods. ``(The
others) you just needed to keep your heart going and you'd be all
right. Today, you just knew that you had to execute golf shots and
I knew stepping up on 18 that I had to make birdie to win. Par
wasn't going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   He needed the right shots at the right time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
