<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8256 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-LIL-ZANE22-COX     08-21 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIL-ZANE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rapper Zane's `World' widens
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pay attention, because this is how all that screaming major sex
symbol stuff starts: Lil' Zane is standing restlessly at the side
of the Lakewood Amphitheatre stage waiting for his moment. It's
June 17 and hip-hop station Hot 97-5 is marking its fifth year on
the air with a ``Birthday Bash.'' The 18-year-old rapper isn't
scheduled to perform, but he's flashing a row of gleaming teeth and
rocking from side to side nervously like he's the headliner.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the spotlight swings to him, and it happens.
</P>
<P>
   The plain white tank-top is pulled over his head. An hour and a
half each day of running, push-ups and sit-ups is revealed in
rippling fashion below his neck.
</P>
<P>
   The girls lose their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the bash, Zane blushes with both dimples at the
recollection of his, um, ``moment.'' Though, clearly, he is on the
brink of an even bigger one. His single with Atlanta R&AMP;B quartet
112, ``Callin' Me,'' debuted at No. 1 two months ago and held the
position for five weeks straight. (It's currently No. 2). And his
debut CD, ``Young World: The Future,'' is out today.
</P>
<P>
   At the obviously new Buckhead offices of his Worldwide
Entertainment label, in another white Calvin Klein tank top and
Karl Kani jeans with rhinestones down the side (that he insists no
one has yet), the rapper born Zane Copeland says, ``Staying fit is
important to me... and it is only part of the whole plan to get the
world to know `Z.'''
</P>
<P>
   But yes, he eventually affirms, having a newly chiseled chest
has also generated a nice buzz for R&AMP;B singers D'Angelo and Usher.
So it could work for him.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Usher is also an affecting singer who's sold
millions in large part because of the songwriting and production
talents of Atlantan Jermaine Dupri.
</P>
<P>
   Zane arrives with a comparable arsenal. Though the man in his
corner _ Kevin Wales _ doesn't write, the accomplished talent
scout, manager and president of Worldwide Entertainment is still
one of Atlanta's music forces.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring to be in the business since he was 9, Zane introduced
himself to Wales when he was 11, backstage at a showcase featuring
his short-lived rap group Kronic. ``I was so serious about the
industry, even then, that I was reading liner notes to see who was
managing who and all of the people involved behind the scenes,'' he
recalls. ``And I saw K. Wales' name mentioned in the (preteen rap
act) Another Bad Creation CD and (R&AMP;B quartet) Boyz II Men. So I
just stepped to him.'' And they kept in contact.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the former Cross Keys High School student made his bow
as featured rapper on the single ``Anywhere'' by the sophisticated
foursome 112 _ another Wales discovery. It hit the R&AMP;B Top 5 and
112 and Lil' Zane hit the road opening for pop superstar Whitney
Houston last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's booked as a solo act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's all making sense to me why this was the time to come
out,'' says Zane, whose debut is mostly a confidently delivered
party album. ``If I would have come out as a kid, like when I was
with Kronic (its album was never released), it would be hard for me
now. It's hard for people to adjust to kid acts. They don't want
them to grow up. But now I'm coming (out) like a young man.
Somebody the teenage girls who like (teen R&AMP;B singer) Sammie could
like, but mature enough that their moms may look twice, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the women are after him,'' producer Dupri smirks.
</P>
<P>
   But you couldn't tell last Thursday: His college-age and older
female audience was playing it cool outside Buckhead's Plush, the
site of Zane's album release party. A remarkable feat considering
temperatures that day swelled to 99 degrees, and it still felt like
it at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Around 12:30, when both levels of the club were packed, the
object of their desire appeared. Though two young women wearing the
ubiquitous black miniskirts and black bikini tops had not yet
snagged the orange wrist band that would admit them into the
velvet-roped VIP section, VIP No.1 purposefully headed over to
where they were standing. He thanked the two for coming out and
said he'd appreciate it if they would buy his CD.
</P>
<P>
   They don't scream or swoon, but keep their voices low and say
they're just glad to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   But you know by the way they're squeezing each other's hand when
he turns away, inside they are losing their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ON T H E W E B : More on Lil' Zane and Worldwide Records:
www.lilzane.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
