<HEADER>
A8257 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND22-COX     08-21 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsweek casts vote for `Survivor' on cover
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush are scrambling to see who will be the
next leader of the free world, but the big question on many
Americans' minds is: ``What's going to happen on Wednesday's
`Survivor'?''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the grand finale, Newsweek ($3.50) features the
final four on its cover (the photo is not only carefully staged;
hair and makeup stylists were brought in) and talks to Richard,
Rudy, Susan and Kelly about life on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Richard, the corporate trainer viewers either love or hate,
reveals that he has been getting marriage proposals ``and wonderful
naked photos of men. I mean, just insane amounts of positive
contact and two _ literally _ letters saying, `You're evil, I hope
you die.'''
</P>
<P>
   The other remaining cast members tell reporter Marc Peyser they
wouldn't have made it this far if they hadn't banded together.
``Besides living with these people, I had to work with them. So I
thought, 'Oh, boy, we're going to need some teamwork here,''' Susan
says. Susan also jokes that she and Kelly don't belong in Playboy
because they have tattoos. ``We belong in Hustler _and I hear Larry
Flynt pays more!''
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday night's two-hour finale on CBS, the final council
will feature the last two players pleading their cases for the
$1million grand prize before the previous seven people who had been
voted off the island. More than 40 million viewers are expected to
tune in.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trial and errors: What really happened in the Ray Lewis trial
for the Buckhead stabbings? Yes, we know all the defendants were
acquitted of the murder charges, but Atlanta ($3.50) writer Scott
Freeman has dug deeper to offer a compelling postmortem on the
high-profile case. Not only was the result a stunning defeat for
Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard, CNN legal analyst
compared Howard's performance to that of ``the bumbling Inspector
Clouseau of the Pink Panther movies.'' Lewis' attorney, Ed Garland,
blamed the fiasco on political pressures from the mayor's office _
a charge Mayor Bill Campbell denies. But, as Freeman points out,
the NFL star was arrested even though the lead detective did not
want to charge him. And Fulton County prosecutors apparently made a
crucial error in taking ``a street brawl and trying to turn it into
murder with malice....''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Talking the Talk: Editor Tina Brown seems to be on the right
track with Talk ($3.50). Maybe it's because the magazine is looking
a lot like Vanity Fair. The September issue features a cover story
on the celebrity of the month, Nicole Kidman; profiles of Tipper
Gore and Bush brothers George W. and Jeb; interviews with several
of Bill Clinton's past and present advisers about what the
president is really like; a juicy profile of Darcy Lapier, the
widow of Herbalife mogul Mark Hughes and former wife of Jean-Claude
Van Damme; and a compelling true-crime article about the Mark
Biddle murder-suicide in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth a look is Rebecca Johnson's fascinating piece on the
dilemma of the single woman. Most, like 32-year-old Kristin
Whiting, want to get married, but they are much pickier than their
mothers. More and more women, Johnson writes, are choosing to
remain single rather than settling for a man who doesn't meet all
their requirements.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unwedded bliss: The same theme of picky single women is
addressed in this week's Time ($3.50) with a cover shot of the
actresses from the TV series, ``Sex and the City.'' As reporter
Tamala M. Edwards notes, 37 years ago 83 percent of women 25 to 55
were married; by 1997 the figure had dropped to 65 percent. Women
no longer see marriage as a matter of survival. ``Let's face it,''
says novelist Melissa Bank. ``You don't just want a man in your
life. You only want a great man in your life.'' A different view is
offered by Walter Kirn, who complains that whatever it is that
women want in men, it changes annually. In previous generations,
Kirn writes, the only thing a man had to do to attract a woman was
to have a good job and use deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tangled Web: The Internet is one of the best things to happen
to technology, but cyberspace has its dark side. U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($3.50) examines an ordinary week on the Web and finds it
crawling with pornographers and pedophiles, rigged auctions,
stalking, viruses, adoption scams and credit card fraud.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
