<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8265 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-YOUTHVOTE-AZR &LR;      08-21 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTHVOTE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-YOUTH-VOTE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    YOUTH CARE ABOUT ISSUE, SHY AWAY FROM POLLS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``A'' and ``K'' categories)(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    ((For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in their lives, 14 million members of
Generation Y get to vote this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Most won't.
</P>
<P>
   Election observers expect fewer than one-fourth of the
first-time-eligibles to be counted where it counts most, which is
at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, the year the voting age was lowered to 18, half of all
18- to 24-year-olds voted.
</P>
<P>
   To Jason Bellini, a 25-year-old Scottsdale Chaparral High School
in Scottsdale, Ariz., and Georgetown grad who currently works as a
correspondent for MTV's Choose or Lose election coverage, the
absentee youth vote will squander potential swing power in what
could be a close presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1992, young people were credited with helping
Bill Clinton find the White House.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the youth turnout was 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the turnout among 65- to 74-year-olds was 70 percent.
The trend toward electorate shrinkage isn't limited to the young,
of course. In 1960, 63 percent of all eligible voters voted. In
1996, it was 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our generation could really be the jump ball in this
race,'' said Bellini, who spent last week at the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles and has been steadily
interviewing his demographic peers since the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the older edge of Gen Y and the younger edge of
Gen X won't be much of a factor this year, Bellini said, can't be
blamed on apathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people may answer a lot of our questions with, `I don't
know,' but we never hear them say `I don't care,''' he said. ``This
generation genuinely cares about the future of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact: Young adults volunteer for civic and charity causes in
record numbers, making the conspicuous absence of under-30 voters -
a full one-fourth of the electorate - all the more vexing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even inexplicable. Still, we'll try.
</P>
<P>
   As an outreach effort, the following freewheeling youth-vote
discussion employs lots of assertive and edgy boldface type - a
typographical flourish with proven youth appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, young people today say that comparing them to the
class of 1972 isn't quite fair.
</P>
<P>
   They had Nixon, the draft, widespread social unrest and
(beginitalic)Brandy (You're a Fine Girl) (enditalic)by Looking
Glass.
</P>
<P>
   Kids today have, what? That Napster deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics isn't the life-and-death matter it was during the
Vietnam War,'' Bellini said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Well then, perhaps young people can't relate to hot-button
``issues'' of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bellini has found that his peers can generate personal
passion over many of the issues that drive the presidential scrum,
including health care, abortion, education and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Even Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement planning would seem to be the furthest thing from a
20-year-old mind, but Nathan Sproul, executive director of the
Arizona Republican Party, said that George W. Bush's Social
Security plan - by which some contributions are freed up for
private investment - seems to be getting some traction with
Generation Dude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young voters today know what a 401(k) plan is. They're
investing in the stock market,'' said Sproul, 28. ``There's a
different level of consciousness. This is the information age.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison Byrne Fields, creative director and chief strategist for
the non-profit Rock the Vote (which encourages voter registration),
said Gens Y and X have come of age in an era of unprecedented
prosperity but also face the burdensome future of unprecedented
college loan debt.
</P>
<P>
   Many young people already have worked a lifetime's worth of
dead-end service jobs and may be dealing with the psychological
trauma of living up to what Byrne Fields (CQ: {ndash} PREFERS BOTH
LAST NAME) describes as ``the myth of the dot-com millionaire at
24.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in their lives, otherwise lived at the
commercial heart of our popular culture, young people are not the
entire focus of every marketer's attention, and they're miffed
about being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Since the primaries, Rock the Vote had been advocating a
youth-centric debate between the presidential candidates, which
``would be an incredible first step in improving dialog,'' said
Byrne Fields, 30. Such an event seems ``not incredibly likely''
during the current campaign, though Al Gore last week agreed to
participate in an MTV ``town hall'' gabfest.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. To really weigh the campaigns' commitment to youth,
however, follow their money. Specifically, follow the television
advertising dollars, which for this campaign season will flow
primarily to networks that skew 35-plus or older, such as CBS and
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gealy, president of Acme Communications, which owns 10
youth-appeal network affiliates around the country - nine WB and
one UPN - would prefer it not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stations skew 18 to 34,'' he said. ``But the campaigns
over advertise to the 50-plus audience and are totally missing the
younger demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   A demographic, it should be added for irony's sake, that defines
the term ``undecided.'' And, presumably, open to the power of
focused marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the people we talk to won't commit to being a Democrat
or Republican,'' Bellini said. ``They don't want to be
categorized.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Besides, young voters aren't really being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Though political coverage in the mainstream media may chill
younger news consumers, there's a wealth of resources available to
the demographic most likely to consume such digital data. A couple
of content-rich www-dots that cater exclusively to youngish
would-be voters include www.rockthevote.com and the Choose or Lose
subsite of www.mtv.com.
</P>
<P>
   A Rock the Vote bus, touring the country mixing politics and pop
music, is scheduled to visit Arizona State University on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make this stuff seem kind of fun,'' Byrne Fields
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the local level, the Arizona Secretary of State staffs a
special voter-outreach office that concentrates on wooing young
voters. One tactic: greeting cards, mailed to citizens turning 18,
reminding them that it's time to register. Another: public-service
radio announcements, some of which have run during Howard Stern's
brazen morning show.
</P>
<P>
   Young people haven't been indoctrinated in the ritual of voting.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Arizona-born Kids Voting program has been
hand-holding today's 18-year-olds for more than a decade. Many
current first-time voters have been exposed to the voting process
through the program, which now encourages kids in 39 states to
visit polling places with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   No Arizona figures are available, but a Kansas study showed that
Kids Voting alums showed a slightly higher propensity to actually
vote once they turned 18 than their peers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Young people may be confused about or intimidated by the simple
mechanics of voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of questions we get on the Rock the Vote Web site
have to do with process,'' Byrne Fields said. ```How do I go about
registering to vote? How do I get an absentee ballot?' During the
primaries, we were getting phone calls saying, `I want to vote
today, but I didn't register. What do I do?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Young people lack charismatic peer-group role models.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't met Lawrence Robinson, a recent graduate of Corona
del Sol High School and, at 19, the youngest Arizona delegate at
last week's Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson will attend Claremont McKenna College in California
this fall, but he departed for LA having done plenty of
interpersonal politicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my friends are registered,'' he said with a laugh,
adding that most of them are registered Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On a grander scale, the political parties have offered
26-year-old Karenna Gore Schiff and 24-year-old George P. Bush as
ticket touts.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Did any other fortysomething observer wonder, while watching the
Rock make his political debut, how we might've reacted had
Republican strategists offered Baron von Raschke as their youth
ambassador in 1972?
</P>
<P>
   Young people, distracted by rampant consumerism and whatnot,
don't care, period. Plus they're convinced that their one vote
doesn't count for much.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they volunteer with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work for Habitat for Humanity, you see the house being
built,'' Robinson explained.
</P>
<P>
   Added Bellini, ``(Young people) use their energy and optimism
where it will be most effective. For whatever reason, people in our
generation, in large numbers, don't feel that voting is going to
accomplish much.''
</P>
<P>
   There's still time. The registration deadline for the Nov. 7
election is Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at dave.walker(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(602) 444-8625.
</P>
