<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-DECOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By MELISSA WARD AGUILAR 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
You can turn your den into a tropical Pulau Tiga as easy as
castaway Kelly can balance on a log. Even easier if you already
live in a bug-infested dive.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the decorating supplies you need can be picked up at two
stops: a hardware store and a novelty shop.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a ``Survivor'' shopping list:
</P>
<P>
   Sand _ If you go for the clean stuff, buy a bag of Play Sand for
$2 and spread it around on the front porch. But have guests leave
their shoes outside. You know how uncomfortable it can be when sand
gets in the wrong places. Just ask Richard.
</P>
<P>
   Mud _ For a more raucous affair, create a mud pit in the back
yard. Your guests can try out last week's Immunity Challenge, in
which the survivors lathered themselves up with mud, then scraped
it off into a bucket to see who could collect the most.
</P>
<P>
   Tiki lamps _ Pick up a pair of these ($4 a piece) just for the
power trip you'll get when you extinguish them at the end of the
night. For a reality check, mutter something like ``Fire represents
life on the island'' to see how stupid host Jeff Probst must feel
week after week.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Probst look-alike _ Surely you know one you can invite. If
not, rent one.
</P>
<P>
   Bone necklaces _ Give them out as party favors. Or better yet,
wear one and tell your guests you have immunity from cleanup duty.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut cups _ After 13 weeks of watching people eat and drink
from coconut shells, try it yourself. These alone are enough to
mentally transport you to the island; and at $3 a piece, a bargain.
But if you want to take the theme further, Southern Imports has
fishing nets, conch shells, plastic fish, artificial palm trees,
bamboo mats and fake rats. Maybe you can recycle some of the stuff
when ``Survivor II'' goes to the Outback.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
