<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8270 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FLUIDADDICT-TEX     08-21 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLUIDADDICT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAPPENS WHEN A THIRST TO STAY HYDRATED FLOWS OUT OF CONTROL?
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by FLUID ADDICT-BOX)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My name is Jessie M., and I drink too much.
</P>
<P>
   I down a minimum of eight 8-ounce glasses of water a day, three
cups of nonfat milk, three mugs or glasses of green or black tea, a
serving of soy beverage, a glass of purple grape juice or an
occasional glass of red wine, a glass of calcium-fortified orange
juice and, now and then, some pineapple juice for the magnesium.
Plus coffee, although it is dehydrating.
</P>
<P>
   At first I would not admit it. I was in denial. Daily, I would
pour a pitcher full of 64 ounces of water and would not go to sleep
until it was drained. I bought colorful juice containers meant to
fit in lunch boxes and fat bottles of juice that stole most of the
refrigerator shelf space. I had to buy a special iced-tea pitcher
that fit on the refrigerator-door shelf, and nightly I would brew
green tea with a dollop of North Dallas Honey Co. honey and a
squeeze of fresh lemon.
</P>
<P>
   I became a woman obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   It started one day while I was smoking a cigarette and reading
Prevention magazine. Sadly, I am not making this up. While reading,
I suffered a terrible collision of ideas. I had a habit bad for my
health. I wanted to be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   So I arrived at a conclusion: I would start drinking more water.
</P>
<P>
   One drink led to another. I included milk for the calcium, tea
for the phytonutrients, although to this day I'm not sure what a
phytonutrient is. This went on for years. As I aged, I included soy
beverages, believing this would somehow ease me into menopause,
plus fight cancer. Then OJ manufacturers began adding calcium to
their product. I found this irresistible. My bones will thank me.
Magnesium helps absorb calcium, so I started on pineapple juice.
Grape juice or wine helps prevent clogged arteries. I do a little
cranberry now and then as well. You may see where this is heading.
I've had to clench my teeth to stop myself from getting involved
with wheatgrass smoothies. If researchers find one more healthy
thing to drink, I may explode.
</P>
<P>
   One night, I did what thousands of other people around the world
do _ I decided to solve my problem by logging onto the Internet and
searching for my own solution.
</P>
<P>
   I checked an Internet search engine for the phrase ``eight
glasses a day.'' I received 92,400 responses, which roughly
compares with the number of times I visit the bathroom in a given
week. A good portion of those trips are in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   I searched and searched on Web sites. As night fell and the
house grew dark, I hunched before the glowing computer screen.
Then, finally, insight flashed while I peered at www.mayohealth.org
and the health page at www.msn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have a new plan.
</P>
<P>
   Milk, juices and other beverages are about 90 percent water. So
those drinks don't have to be added on top of my 64 fluid ounces of
water. Those healthy beverages can be included, along with clear
water, as part of my daily fluid consumption. Aha!
</P>
<P>
   Plain water must be part of the diet. It is the best thing to
drink because our bodies are about half water. We are not half Diet
Coke, nor are we half Dr Pepper, although we may feel related. We
need to get plain water into our watery selves, but not to the
point that we slosh when we walk.
</P>
<P>
   I can substitute solid food for my calcium and magnesium, and
add more veggies and fruit to my diet to make up for the loss of
green tea.
</P>
<P>
   I understand that I cannot include coffee or alcohol when I add
up the fluid ounces I consume because both are dehydrating. I
understand I cannot include heavily sweetened tea, nor can I
include sodas or any other beverage that would not be nourishing.
</P>
<P>
   I will drink a glass of OJ, a glass of water and a cup of coffee
before work, if I get up early enough. I will drink two 16-ounce
bottles of water at work. I will drink a glass of water when I get
home in the evening, then have a cool glass of tea or a warm mug of
milk.
</P>
<P>
   On my days off, when I'm at home, what the heck, I'll add
another bottle of water or two.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
