<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8271 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-AGGIES-RIGGS0822-     08-21 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-RIGGS0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slocum chooses Farris to start at QB against Notre Dame
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Texas A&AMP;M made it official on Monday. Sophomore
Mark Farris might not have Colby Freeman's feet or Vance Smith's
arm, but he does have something the other two don't, at least for
now: the Aggies' starting quarterback job.
</P>
<P>
   Surprised? Didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Coach R.C. Slocum, already busy putting out fires although the
football season is still about two weeks away, played it safe in
naming Farris as the starter for the Sept. 2 opener at Notre Dame.
Not that there's anything wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Farris might not be blessed with the physical
skills of the other two, but Slocum is counting on Farris' maturity
to help steady A&AMP;M. The last thing the Aggies need when they open
on the Irish's hallowed ground is for the rifle-armed Smith to
launch one that only Touchdown Jesus could catch, or for Freeman, a
redshirt freshman, to suffer extreme fright on a stage a tad bit
larger than the one on which he starred at Brownwood.
</P>
<P>
   So Slocum made it official Monday. There were several reasons
for doing so, not the least of which is the Aggies already have
been beset by several major injuries. Those injuries include one to
projected starting offensive guard Billy Yates, expected to miss
some of the season after breaking his lower leg in a scrimmage
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injuries have made it hard for continuity,'' Slocum said.
``That's something we can't do anything about. On top of that, we
were playing three quarterbacks, and that's something I can do
something about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to solidify things so one guy could get all the
repetitions with the first-team offense,'' he added. ``It's really
hard to rotate all three to get equal reps, and I didn't want to
wait until game week and all the distractions of that. I didn't
want to be standing on the sideline with three guys anxious to see
who's going out on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the best time to get the air cleared and the offense
oiled up so when we go to Notre Dame there'll be no question as to
who's our starting quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   In naming Farris the starter, the Aggies have entrusted the
offense to a player who was rated one of the state's top
quarterback prospects as a senior at Angleton High School. Of
course, that was in 1993, before he opted for a pro baseball career
that reached the Double-A level in the Pittsburgh Pirates'
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to A&AMP;M last season, he completed just six of 16 passes
in five brief appearances _ hardly impressive, but similar to
Smith's resume (five of 14 in five games) and more than Freeman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is still the same,'' Farris said. ``I do the very best
I can on the field and let the coaches decide who starts, and who
gets to play. I have to keep working hard and doing my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said Smith and Freeman will split time at No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum certainly needs someone to step up. The Aggie faithful
are hopeful, as always, but restless after last year's four-loss
season, including three defeats by a cumulative score of 112-6. A&AMP;M
also is unranked in The Associated Press preseason poll, a rarity
during Slocum's 12-year tenure as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran coach says he named Farris not because he's the safe
choice, but because he's the best choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked Mark because of overall performance in the spring
and summer,'' Slocum said. ``With all the things we like to do with
our offense, he gives us the best chance. It was very close ...
very close.''
</P>
<P>
   But also very predictable.
</P>
<P>
   His worst nightmare
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kevin Steele's first year at Baylor hasn't exactly been a
picnic, but nothing has compared to what occurred in practice Aug.
12.
</P>
<P>
   During an inside run drill, defensive tackle Brandon Thompson
crumpled to the ground with a neck injury. He was paralyzed from
the waist down for 15 or 20 minutes, Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a senior from Arlington Heights, was released from a
Waco hospital Wednesday after tests determined he suffered no
structural damage to his spinal cord. Further tests await, and
whether the former tight end plays again is uncertain, Steele said,
although he has returned to practice as an observer.
</P>
<P>
   Steele said seeing Thompson on his feet again, however, is one
of the best sights he's seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the most amazing things I've ever been
through,'' he said. ``I've never felt that way as a coach. No loss
or mistake has ever made me feel like that. It's very frightening,
because it's not in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Not-so-solid Gold(en)
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma State product made the highlight films last week _
much to Bob Simmons' chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' coach didn't know whether to be amused or bemused
by the play of former OSU linebacker Jack Golden. A free-agent
rookie for the New York Giants, Golden got his 15 seconds of fame
on Aug. 11 against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   With the Giants trying to preserve a three-point lead with time
running out, Golden tackled teammate Fred Lewis in the end zone to
prevent him from running out an interception as time expired. The
hit forced a fumble, though, which the Jaguars recovered in the end
zone for a 16-13 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I thought it was, uh, different,'' said Simmons, trying
to be diplomatic. ``I understand what he was trying to do. Jack's a
very emotional player, but you just don't do that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he hasn't discussed the play with Golden _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he comes down here, it will be a topic of
conversation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That might be awhile. Golden has impressed the Giants with his
special-teams play and is expected to make the roster. Lewis,
ironically, was cut Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Leach: I'm staying
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech Coach Mike Leach, a Brigham Young graduate, said he
was so stunned by BYU Coach LaVell Edwards' announcement that he'll
retire after this season that it didn't occur to him that he might
be considered a candidate to replace the 69-year-old legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked by it,'' he said. ``It caught me by surprise to
the extent that I didn't even think of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest easy, Red Raider fans. Tech's first-year coach says he
won't see Lubbock in his rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a great situation here and I plan to stay here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M fans attending road games at Notre Dame, Iowa State and
Oklahoma State, where there are no local affiliates on the radio
network, will be able to hear the Aggie broadcast at the lower end
of the FM band thanks to a low-wattage transmitter at the stadiums.
... Colorado co-defensive coordinator Tom McMahon, 51, has a
malignant tumor on his trachea but has missed only one practice
since the Buffs reported for fall drills despite undergoing
chemotherapy and radiation treatments. ... Top-ranked Nebraska is
blessed with a sizeable stable of I-backs including Dan Alexander
and Correll Buckhalter, but attracting considerable media attention
is junior-college transfer Thunder Collins. ``I think part of that
comes from his name,'' Coach Frank Solich speculated. ``I think the
media is enthralled by that.'' And yes, that's his real first name.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
