<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIR-TRAVEL22-COX     08-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-TRAVEL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SLATER, AIRLINES VOW TO RELIEVE AIR TRAVEL CHOKE POINTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Transportation Secretary Rodney E. Slater announced
plans Monday to relieve some of the nation's air traffic choke
points and to give passengers better information about flight
delays and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Slater, speaking after an emergency meeting with top airline
executives, called for an ``airline quality'' task force to come up
with a more comprehensive report within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   As for the immediate problems at the nation's overtaxed
airports, Slater said that the greatest hope for relief is the
coming end of the vacation season, which has jammed flights and
helped raise the passenger total toward an expected record of 670
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Amid unusually high numbers of electrical storms and labor
problems at United Airlines, the carriers cancelled or delayed
thousands of flights this summer, including 44,000 just last month.
</P>
<P>
   Slater also acknowledged problems with the air traffic system,
saying, ``We don't say everything works well when the weather is
clear.'' He made repeated appeals for more money to modernize
airports, add runways and improve the control system.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Slater hailed what he called a ``cooperative
spirit'' from the emergency meeting. American Airlines, Delta Air
Lines, US Airways, Alaska Air Lines, America West, and Trans World
Airlines all sent their chief executive officers.
</P>
<P>
   United, Southwest and Northwest airlines also sent
representatives, as did top airline worker unions. Slater has more
meetings scheduled this week with consumers and smaller air
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about a collective response,'' Slater said after the
closed session, which lasted nearly an hour longer than the two
hours scheduled. He declined to criticize the industry, which more
than six months ago volunteered to make major improvements in
customer service in order to head off a movement in Congress to
impose a mandatory passenger rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said that results so far have been ``mixed'' in the
voluntary effort. Airline officials repeated their earlier promises
to share more details about flights with the customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a better job,'' acknowledged American Airlines chief
Donald J. Carty, who said that information about flight delays
often does not reach the employees who deal with passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration head Jane Garvey outlined a plan
for using air space more efficiently in the most crowded areas of
the Eastern United States, including the ``choke points'' around
Atlanta, Boston, New York, New Jersey, Washington's Dulles airport
and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would use varying altitudes and angles for landing and
takeoff in these zones, she said. About half the air space
management changes could be immediate, with others planned for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said there has been ``enormous progress'' in modernizing
the computerized air traffic control system, which has long been
called antiquated. However, she said she could not estimate when
most of the overhaul would be complete.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the president of the American Automobile
Association became the latest leader in the travel industry to
suggest privatizing the air traffic control system.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Atlanta Rotary Club, Robert L. Darbelnet called
for privatizing the air traffic control system and urged Congress
to fully fund aviation improvements, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that plan, Slater said he preferred reorganizing the
federal government's system to make it more businesslike.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
