<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-RUSSIA-SIDE0822-COX     08-21 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SIDE0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handling of sub crisis imperil's Putin's political standing,
expert says
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Vladimir Putin was elected president of Russia in
March largely because of his reputation as a decisive and competent
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But that reputation _ and Putin's political standing _ are at
risk following the president's handling of the crisis surrounding
the sinking of the Kursk nuclear submarine, an Emory University
expert said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is coming under ``intense criticism for not coming back
from vacation to handle the crisis personally,'' and for being slow
to accept international help in trying to rescue the sub's crew,
said Tom Remington, an Emory political science professor and an
expert on Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's reputation may be damaged further because it appears
that some of the information Russian authorities disseminated after
the accident was false, Remington said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian spokesmen initially said the sub sank as the result of a
collision, but Western experts said explosions were detected in the
area. And Russian spokesmen also said that tapping had been heard
coming from inside the sub, an assertion equally doubted by Western
experts, who say no such tapping would have been audible.
</P>
<P>
   Remington said the situation is analogous to that faced in 1986
by former President Mikhail Gorbachev, who was fed misleading
information after a nuclear reactor at Chernobyl exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly possible that the military was not giving Putin
correct information,'' Remington said.
</P>
<P>
   But that would not get the president off the hook, Remington
said, because it would show that, ``not only did he make the wrong
call, but it indicates that he is not fully in command of his own
military.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's reputation for decisiveness and competence was built on
his firm prosecution of the war in the breakaway republic of
Chechnya when he was prime minister under President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But even that seeming success now appears in danger. Russia's
military has not won the complete victory that was promised, and
bands of Chechen rebels regularly ambush Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was elected to a four-year term in March, and he still has
time to recover. For one thing, Remington said, he could use the
poor handling of the submarine crisis as a reason to once again act
decisively _ by firing people and asserting control over the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Remington's guess is that heads will roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to distance himself from the chain of incompetence and
cover-ups,'' Remington said.
</P>
<P>
   And Putin is expected to launch an economic initiative this fall
aimed at reforming an economy badly in need of it. Success in that
endeavor could inspire confidence, Remington said, while this or
other failures of leadership could make cooperation harder to come
by and future successes harder to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Enough time remains in Putin's term for either trend to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could still have major policy successes _ or failures,''
Remington said.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: About the professor:
www.emory.edu/POLS/about/remington.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
