<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8278 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FLUIDADDICT-BOX-TEX     08-21 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLUIDADDICT-BOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU WANTED TO KNOW ABOUT WATER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Bodies of water
</P>
<P>
   The human body is, on the average, 50 percent water. Parts of us
are made up of even more water.
</P>
<P>
   Brain, 85 percent water
</P>
<P>
   Lean muscle, 80 percent water
</P>
<P>
   Blood, 80 percent water
</P>
<P>
   Fat, 25 percent water
</P>
<P>
   Bone, 22 percent water
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Water works
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   _ regulates body temperature
</P>
<P>
   _ removes wastes
</P>
<P>
   _ carries nutrients and oxygen to cells
</P>
<P>
   _ cushions joints
</P>
<P>
   _ lessens the burden on kidneys and liver
</P>
<P>
   Water may prevent certain diseases. It can prevent kidney
stones, and one study has shown that women who drank more than five
glasses of water a day had a risk of colon cancer that was 45
percent less than those who drank two or fewer glasses a day.
</P>
<P>
   The International Bottled Water Association says its surveys
show Americans who don't drink enough water complain of at least
one of the following symptoms: frequent tiredness, dry or itchy
skin, headaches, indigestion or lapses in concentration.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   How much to drink?
</P>
<P>
   Divide your weight in half. The answer is the approximate
minimum number of fluid ounces you should drink daily.
</P>
<P>
   The common ``eight glasses of day'' or 64 fluid ounces is the
minimum amount a person who weighs 128 pounds should drink. Weigh
more, drink more.
</P>
<P>
   Why so much? The ``average'' person loses about 10 cups of water
a day to body functions.
</P>
<P>
   Three to four cups of water are derived each day from solid
foods. Because that's such a rough estimate, dietitians say it is
better to count only fluids when figuring your daily intake.
</P>
<P>
   When counting fluids, don't include coffee, caffeinated
beverages or alcohol. They are dehydrating. Milk, juice and a
low-caffeine tea, such as green tea, are about 90 percent water, so
they can be included in a calculation of daily fluid intake.
Nonetheless, daily fluids should include plain water.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   When to drink more?
</P>
<P>
   Increase water intake when it is hot, humid or cold, or when you
are visiting a higher altitude. Water is a regulator that helps our
bodies adjust to climatic change.
</P>
<P>
   Increase water intake as physical activity increases. Drink
water before, during and after exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Sports drinks usually aren't necessary unless you are working
very hard for 90 minutes straight or, if it is particularly hot,
for 60 minutes straight. Otherwise, you may be taking in more
sodium than you need.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   What time of day?
</P>
<P>
   If you are thirsty, you've already started to dehydrate.
Dietitians say it's best to keep the body regularly rehydrated
throughout the day. That means a glass of water upon rising,
several throughout the day, and one before you go to bed so that
cellular function continues properly throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Easy ice water
</P>
<P>
   Fill a water bottle half full of water. Place it in the freezer
overnight. In the morning, top it off with fresh water. You'll have
ice water, and it's a lot easier than trying to get ice cubes into
the bottle!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Why we don't drink enough water
</P>
<P>
   More than half of Americans say they don't drink eight glasses
of water a day, according to a survey by the International Bottled
Water Association.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons they gave:
</P>
<P>
   Too busy _ 21 percent
</P>
<P>
   Don't like the taste _ 13 percent
</P>
<P>
   Prefer other beverages _ 12 percent
</P>
<P>
   Forgot _ 10 percent
</P>
<P>
   Not feeling thirsty _ 8 percent
</P>
<P>
   No bottled water available _ 4 percent
</P>
<P>
   Can't leave their desks for a ``hydration break'' _ 4 percent
</P>
<P>
   Worry about too many restroom breaks _ 2 percent
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Water safety
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration regulates bottled water.
Nonetheless, the Natural Resources Defense Council studied 103
brands of bottled water, and in March 1999 announced that a third
of those contained at least one sample of bacteria or a chemical
that exceeded the industry guidelines, although none so harmful as
to cause a recall.
</P>
<P>
   Also, we can contaminate bottled water ourselves. The Mayo
Clinic says every time you drink from a bottle of water, the
bacteria in your mouth contaminates the water in the bottle. Wash
water bottles in hot, soapy water or run them through the
dishwasher before using them again, the clinic advises.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency regulates the purity and
safety of tap water. It requires public suppliers to notify
residents if tap water is unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet breakouts of water-borne disease occur now and then. The
worst in this country was in 1993 in Milwaukee, where 100 people
died and 403,000 were reported sickened with intestinal disease
when the parasite cryptosporidium got into the city's water supply.
The parasite is resistant to chlorine and ordinary filters.
</P>
<P>
   Cryptosporidium is a parasite from the intestines of
warm-blooded animals. Milwaukee's outbreak is believed to have been
caused from runoff from slaughterhouses into a lake that holds the
city water supply.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Sources: www.mayohealth.org, www.msn.com, Natural Resource
Defense Council, International Bottled Water Association, city of
Fort Worth)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
