<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8280 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-POWER-NNS &LR;      08-21 1912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-POWER-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS USING THEIR CHILDREN AS TRANSLATORS FACE FAMILY POWER
STRUGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
MONDAY, Aug. 21, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: With four photos, of Angel Padilla (NNS1), Maria
Padilla (NNS2), Felix Antonio Rollet (NNS3) and Felix Juan Rollet
(NNS4). 
 By MICHELE M. MELENDEZ  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LORAIN, Ohio _ Angel and Maria Padilla live through the words of
their children.
</P>
<P>
   At ages 13 and 10, their boys speak on their parents' behalf
with doctors and lawyers. They read the mail and answer the phone.
They translate the television news and bottles of prescription
medication. They are their parents' link to the world, because
their parents don't speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Those scenes play across the country among families in which
parents haven't learned English. The adults rely on their children.
In effect, the children run the household, and the arrangement can
leave parents in despair, children in conflict and family roles in
shambles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A really wide cultural gap is developing between the first
generation immigrants and their children,'' said Jason Felch, youth
program director at the International Institute of San Francisco.
``Young people come in and pick up the language and learn the
culture faster than their parents do. Then, you end up having
(children) put into the position of negotiating with the landlord,
answering the door, opening the mail, translating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padillas have lived in the United States off and on since
1991. In 1996, they moved from their native Puerto Rico to this
city of 70,000 about 30 miles west of Cleveland. Maria, 45, and
Angel, 65, have medical problems and said they were in search of a
place where they could obtain better treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in 10 people in the United States was born elsewhere,
according to census estimates for 1998, the latest available.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census offers the most recent figures on language
spoken at home. That year, the primary language of about 14 percent
of the country's population was something other than English. The
children were more likely able to speak English _ 86 percent,
compared with 77 percent of adults.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that children have natural advantages over their
parents in learning a second language.
</P>
<P>
   Even adults who truly want to learn English, and who enroll in
classes to do so, have a tough time because they often revert to
their native language at home and avoid situations where they would
be forced to speak English, said Bonnie Mizenko, director of the
Virginia Beach Adult Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of practice and exposure,'' she said. ``The
young are still impressionable. They are truly bilingual. The
adults have a choice about what they speak, and they tend to
isolate themselves. It's about being anxious about making mistakes
and feeling comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padillas' sons, Felix Antonio Rollet, 13, and Felix Juan
Rollet, 10, are Maria's from a prior relationship, but consider
Angel Padilla their father. They speak English as well as American
boys their age, and said they're used to their interpreting duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought translating for my parents was such a big
deal,'' Felix Juan said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because they do it every day, even on the roughest days.
</P>
<P>
   When Angel severely injured his back in an automobile crash,
needing 46 stitches and four metal disks, his sons had to
translate. When the family hired a lawyer to settle an insurance
claim, the boys tried to decipher the legal terminology. When the
younger son was failing in school, the older son did the talking
with his teacher. They had no choice, the Padillas said, because
the hospital, the lawyer's office and the school could not provide
professional translators.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through an interpreter, both parents expressed sorrow
for depending on their boys so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel bad, because there are things children
shouldn't know about or be involved with,'' Angel Padilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he said, he doesn't always get all the information he
needs to make informed decisions, because the children can't
translate concepts they don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange position for both children and parents, a bizarre
role reversal. At a young age, children are forced to learn adult
responsibilities; their parents' authority wavers as they become
dependent on their young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue that happens with every family we see,'' said
Jane Cook, director of Refugee and Immigration Services of the
Catholic Diocese of Virginia in Norfolk. ``We tell them this is
something that will happen, so that when it does happen they don't
get that upset and they can take steps to prepare for it, such as
telling their children, `You still have to do your chores,' `You
still have to go to school.'''
</P>
<P>
   Angel Padilla said he already gets flak from his older son when
it comes to helping clean the house: ``He says, `I've been helping
you all day (by translating). Isn't that enough?'''
</P>
<P>
   Some adults who depend on children to translate can end up
struggling for control of the family. Children growing up in this
country might favor American independence and self-reliance over
the cultural values of their parents emphasizing family honor and
unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids, even though they're young, they feel strong,'' said
Ngy Hul, director of the Refugee Federation Service Center in
Seattle. ``They are the head of the household. When the parents
want to discipline the children, the children say, `Hey, you depend
on me. What do YOU know?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hul said a Cambodian man dependent on his 12-year-old grandson's
English skills sought help from the center, because the boy had
pulled a gun on him. The man had called the police on his grandson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he wanted his grandson to die, because if he died,
he'd cry for a month. But if (the grandson) lived, he'd suffer
forever,'' Hul said.
</P>
<P>
   The family dynamic _ the way family members relate to each other
_ shifts when the children are so involved with the adult
responsibilities, said Thanh Son (Lisa) Nguyen, director at the
Center for Multicultural and Multigenerational Mental Health
Services in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children might lose respect for the parents, and the
parents feel like they're powerless,'' she said. ``They feel the
family is destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, a clinical psychologist, holds separate group
discussions with foreign-born parents and their children. She
invites parents to communicate openly and freely with their
children and to remember their parental duties. She tells the
children to understand the difficult position their parents are in
and not to lose respect for them.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the influence they wield in the family, some
children know who's the boss.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, Burma native Kim Fwan Wong of San Francisco said he
admires his 42-year-old mother, who works long hours at two
clerical jobs. Even though his mother had been in this country for
two years before Kim joined her in September 1999, Kim has picked
up more English. He said he doesn't resent having to translate for
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect her very much,'' he said. ``It's very difficult for
her here. She wanted me to have a better education.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Ruano of Hialeah, Fla., a Miami suburb, said that even
though she has answered the phone, spoken to visitors at the door
and distinguished junk mail from bills for her Cuban immigrant
parents since she was a girl, she always knew who was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was never an issue,'' said the 24-year-old. ``It was
always, `You're helping out,' not, `You're running the show.' If I
did something wrong, I got punished for it. It never once crossed
my mind that I shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   And even though Ruano works full time, she has remained with her
parents, ages 58 and 56, because she's worried that they won't be
able to manage.
</P>
<P>
   The family fled Cuba in 1980. But while Ruano's parents have
lived in this country for 20 years, they still can't speak English.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents didn't have time to learn the language,'' Ruano
said. ``They were busy trying to make a living, trying to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Those who help parents who don't speak English stress that
parental authority in this country hinges on their knowing the
language.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, parents who do not speak English can miss out on
their children's education. If they cannot communicate during
parent-teacher conferences, they must depend on their children to
be honest about their grades.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Some school districts recognize a language barrier can shut out
some parents from following their children's education. The Los
Angeles Unified School District and other ethnically diverse
districts print report cards in several languages. In L.A., this
includes Armenian, Chinese and Spanish. Even areas where immigrants
and refugees don't comprise much of the population, such as Newton
High School in Newton, Kansas, host bilingual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But translated documents and special meetings don't target a
deep-seated fear of authority among immigrants and refugees, said
Roger Rice, co-director of the Boston-area Multicultural Education,
Training and Advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   He said that parents who don't speak English might not know they
can investigate their child's school. Where English-speaking
parents might confront a teacher, school board member or district
superintendent, Rice said, parents who know neither the language
nor the culture often think, ``The teacher knows best. The school
knows best. Who am I to even ask any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   With that attitude, Rice said, parents who don't speak English
don't learn how school systems work, and their kids ``don't have
that parent advocate who knows what the expectations are, who asks
questions, who helps with the homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, of the Chicago mental health center, said that although
some government and social service agencies offer interpreters, the
need is greater than the availability. As a result, parents who
don't learn English continue to lean on their children, she said,
but ``they can't depend on their children forever.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The Padillas said they don't want to put stress on their boys,
but that it has been extremely hard to learn English. They have
devoted themselves to Our Savior/Nuestro Salvador Lutheran Church,
a bilingual church close to their home where they practice English
in a non-threatening environment.
</P>
<P>
   The church's pastor, the Rev. Steve Behr, said many children in
his congregation translate for their parents. He said that although
the situation ``forces some kids to be more adult than they should
be at their age,'' the experience can end up benefiting them in a
marketplace hungry for bilingual employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kicker is _ it's giving the kids some adult skills at an
early age,'' he said. ``It unfortunately makes a role reversal
where they end up being the parents and their parents end up being
children, many times. And they feel that very painfully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8282 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MEXICO-MEDICINE-N     08-21 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEXICO-MEDICINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOCTOR'S DISCOVERY REVISES THE HISTORY OF MEDICAL IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A medical doctor with a scholarly interest in pre-Columbian art
appears to have pushed back the date of the earliest scientific
medical illustration by several centuries with his study of bizarre
two-faced ancient Mexican figurines known to art historians as the
``pretty ladies of Tlatilco.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon Bendersky, a visiting scholar in the department of
history at the University of Pennsylvania, made the discovery a
couple of years ago when leafing through journals and textbooks on
pre-Columbian art. He noticed pictures of figurines unearthed since
1942 in Tlatilco, which is now part of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Standing 3 inches to 12 inches tall, the figurines, which were
created over a period of 500 years beginning in 1200 B.C., have
short flipperlike arms, flaring thighs, small breasts, wasplike
waists and a somewhat whimsical hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen of the figurines have an even more grotesque feature
_ two faces on a single head. Some have two heads on one neck and
some have two heads on two necks.
</P>
<P>
   Art historians have long considered the two faces to be a
representation of mythical beings. But, as Bendersky scanned the
pages of the documents before him, he was suddenly struck by the
similarities between the monstrous pretty ladies of Tlatilco and a
rare congenital aberration called diprosopus that he had come
across while a medical student.
</P>
<P>
   Bendersky's initial suspicion caused him to embark on what
proved to be a two-year program of research to learn whether or not
his guess could be correct.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, he is convinced that he has identified ``the
oldest scientifically medical images in world history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tremendously exciting to think that the Tlatilco
artists appeared to be the very first to marry art with medical
science,'' said Bendersky, who retired this year as professor of
internal medicine at the MCP Hahnemann University School of
Medicine in Philadelphia..
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in his enthusiasm. Dr. Robert Perlman, editor of
the journal Perspectives in Biology and Medicine in which
Bendersky's article on the figurines will appear in early
September, said he and his peer-review panel found Bendersky's
argument ``throughly convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman added: ``I think it was the Nobel prize-winner Albert
Szent-Gyorgyi who said that discovery consists of seeing what
everybody has seen and thinking what nobody has thought. That's
Gordon Bendersky. Lots of people had seen these figurines before,
but he was the first to think that they might represent human
congenital anomalies.''
</P>
<P>
   Diprosopus is an exceedingly rare  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  birth
defect, with only about 85 cases reported since 1642. The
condition, which invariably results in stillbirth, is caused by
abnormal splitting of primitive fetal organs. It can result in
facial duplication, heart abnor- malities and duplication or
complete absence of a brain. Scientists suspect that excess
embroyologic tissue L plays a role, and that both genetic factors
and environmental stresses early in development of the embryo could
be at work.
</P>
<P>
   After tracking down and examining hundreds of ceramic figurines
and comparing them to photographic illustrations of two-faced
Siamese twins, he concluded that the sculptors of ancient Tlatilco
must have studied cases of diprosopus ``very thoroughly,'' as he
later wrote. The sculptors, he explained, had not let their
imaginations run wild with the creation of figurines with three or
five faces or with faces stacked on top of one another. Instead,
they had strictly limited their ceramic models to naturally
occurring diprosopus _ two faces side by side.
</P>
<P>
   In order to determine whether or not the Tlatilco figurines are
in fact the world's oldest, Bendersky studied other ancient
representations of human deformities, including the morbidly obese
Paleolithic statuette, Venus of Willendorf, a six-toed statue from
Ain Ghazal in Jordan, and a representation of the ancient Egyptian
dwarf Seneb.
</P>
<P>
   Although older than the Tlatilco figurines, these objects fail
to qualify as medical illustrations, Bendersky concluded. In
addition to being crudely schematic rather than drawn from nature,
they are portrayals of a particular deity or person who happens by
chance to have an abnormality rather than being representative of a
disease or deformity so as to provide diagnostic value.
</P>
<P>
   The result, he was able to say, was that the degree of accuracy
in documenting anatomical and pathological features in a human head
does not appear after the Tlatilco figurines for another 2,000
years or more until the 16th century works of Hans Baldung Grien
and Andreas Vesalius, who both did anatomical drawings based in
dissected corpses.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as Bendersky has gone to explain the pretty ladies of
Tlatilco, he has not been able to fathom their cultural meaning.
What could explain the fascination of the early Mesoamericans with
two-facedness? How was it possible that a prehistoric civilization
that had yet to develop the wheel, metal tools, the domestication
of animals and a sophisticated written language could have
developed an extraordinarily acute power of scientific observation?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the answer to that,'' said Bendersky. ``The only
way we might understand it would be to discover a written language
used by these ancient peoples and that, I'm afraid, doesn't seem
likely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
