<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; tab-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-CHAOS-NNS &LR;      08-21 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-CHAOS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL CAMPAIGN VISITS CAN PROMPT FRANTIC PREPARATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
MONDAY, Aug. 21, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By ROBERT J. VICKERS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ When a presidential candidate comes campaigning to
your town, it's an opportunity for people to wave flags, cheer
speeches and show their support.
</P>
<P>
   Advance notice of a presidential candidate's campaign stop _
sometimes as little as 24 hours _ rarely leaves local organizers
much time to prepare. They have to show extreme flexibility,
resourcefulness and patience in arranging a rally, plant tour or
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   When Cuyahoga Democratic Chairman Jimmy Dimora convinced Al
Gore's campaign last month that the vice president had not spent
enough time campaigning in northeast Ohio, the Gore campaign
quickly scheduled a trip to Cleveland, starting a familiar domino
effect for Ohio Democratic Party Executive Director Cindy
Marizette.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first response is to hang up the phone and swear really
loud,'' Marizette said. ``I drop everything I'm doing. It doesn't
matter if the election is tomorrow or two months from now, whatever
I'm working on is put on hold until the visit is completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties use the same game plan. Each campaign stop usually
targets a particular voting group _ such as senior citizens,
minorities or veterans _ to emphasize a proposal or political
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to find a location that dovetails with the message,''
said Robert Paduchik, Ohio campaign manager for Texas Gov. George
W. Bush's presidential campaign. ``That's a challenge sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   National campaign managers both suggest and solicit campaign
stop locations, which must meet a variety of space and safety
requirements set by campaign advance teams and the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   Once the site passes inspection for capacity and security,
arrangements have to be made for volunteers, food, signs, lighting
and staging. Glitches are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Marizette had to integrate a surprise visit from
the vice president into a Democratic celebration that had been
planned before Gore decided to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to figure out how to get his group in and out before our
regular guests arrived,'' she said. ``Changes are just something I
expect to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign can be the source of more nerve-racking
complications.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the problems when President Bush made a campaign stop
in September 1992 at the Lake County Fairgrounds and the theme of
his speech changed four times.
</P>
<P>
   The changes had little impact on the public face of the
campaign, but it sent local campaign workers into a tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign needed an audience of 500 plus, and it was up to
Jim Trakas, Bush's 1992 Cuyahoga County campaign coordinator, to
make sure the cameras saw faces that matched the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``First it was education, so we had to get school kids for the
crowd,'' said Trakas. Calls went out to principals, superintendents
and Republican mayors to help find children, because school wasn't
in session.
</P>
<P>
   They were still trying to round up a young audience when
campaign strategists changed the topic to military policy. That
meant Trakas had to locate veterans while telling the school kids
they were no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you tell people they're going to meet the president and
the next day call back and say they're not, they're not happy,''
Trakas said.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner were the vets invited than Trakas learned he would
have to disappoint them as well. Now the theme was higher
education, and college students were the audience of choice. New
calls to GOP clubs at John Carroll and Cleveland State universities
collected the necessary bodies, but their role was doomed as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally they decided on job creation,'' Trakas said, and
people involved in job training programs were rounded up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty good soldiers,'' he said of the changes local
party workers went through. ``We were honored just to have the
president coming, so we didn't mention any of our frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Any organizer, Democrat or Republican, can tell similar tales in
any state where a bunch of electoral votes are up for grabs. The
ability to make last-minute arrangements will be at a premium for
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   While locals work out local details, a national campaign advance
team solves other problems, like determining how long it takes to
drive from the airport to the rally site.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's eight-member team usually arrives as much as a week
before the event. Gore's team usually spends about four days in the
host area.
</P>
<P>
   The advance teams work out of the local party offices and often
stay in downtown hotels, but sometimes the local supporters place
national campaign workers in the homes of strangers willing to
house them to save money.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Both the candidate and the local volunteers are hoping for good
publicity from a campaign stop, but that doesn't always happen.
Sometimes, rallies are ``stepped on by a bigger story,'' or
complicated by delays, Paduchik said. ``You can't control that
stuff at all. You just have to be able to roll with the punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November mechanical problems delayed Gov. Bush's plane on a
flight from Michigan. Paduchik's job had been to get a crowd to
Cleveland Hopkins International Airport. Now he had to keep them
from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   By the time a candidate arrives and starts working the crowd,
local organizers can relax a little and look on like coaches
watching the execution of their prize plays. But life doesn't
return to normal until the candidate is off to the next stop on the
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so relieved to see him taking off,'' Marizette said of
Gore. ``It usually takes me a day or two to recover mentally behind
a visit like that. It's a stressful experience, but it's rewarding
because I know it's been successful and I've done my job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
