u f BC-PHILIPPINE-LOVEBUG-NY     08-21 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINE-LOVEBUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES AGAINST PHILIPPINE `LOVE BUG' SUSPECT ARE DROPPED 
</HEADLINE>
  By WAYNE ARNOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Philippine authorities dismissed all charges Monday
against Onel A. de Guzman, the 24-year-old college dropout whom
investigators had accused of being responsibile for a destructive
computer e-mail program that wreaked billions of dollars in damage
on companies worldwide in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine justice department said the evidence against de
Guzman did not substantiate the charges filed against him by the
National Bureau of Investigation. Late in June, the bureau charged
de Guzman with theft and with violating a law intended to deal with
credit card fraud after investigators traced the destructive
computer program _ known popularly as the ``I love you'' virus _ to
his Manila apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which emphasized that complex computer networks are
vulnerable to relatively unsophisticated security breaches, also
exposed the inadequacy of Philippine laws to handle instances of
computer hacking. The Philippine Congress subsequently passed
legislation dealing specifically with computer-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The justice department said that since the destructive e-mail
program _ variously called a virus or a worm in news reports _ had
been introduced before the new law was passed, de Guzman could not
be charged with violating it.
</P>
<P>
   And Fernando D. Contreras, vice president of the Philippine
Internet Service Organization, a trade group that promotes use of
the Internet, remarked, ``It was like the Pearl Harbor that caught
us sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the computer program's creator might never face justice,
Contreras said Internet users saw the case as a success if only
because it had ensured speedy passage of the new law and inspired
Internet service providers to take greater precautions against
similar abuses.
</P>
<P>
   De Guzman acknowledged that he might have inadvertently released
the e-mail program, though he did not admit creating it. The
program, which experts said was surprisingly simple, infected
computers with an e-mail message that, when opened, created
numerous copies of itself and then forwarded itself to every entry
in the recipient's list of e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Though ostensibly intended to collect Internet access passwords
and send them back to its originator, the program ended up
overloading computer networks from the Pentagon to the British
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were able to trace the virus to a ramshackle
inner-city apartment where de Guzman was living with his sister and
her boyfriend while attending a local computer college. After first
charging the boyfriend, investigators turned to de Guzman when
teachers at the college notified them of similarities between the
``I love you'' program and one designed to steal Internet passwords
that de Guzman had submitted as a course thesis. The college
rejected the thesis and de Guzman did not graduate.
</P>
<P>
   His subsequent notoriety does not appear to have dimmed his
prospects. Several computer companies have reportedly offered to
hire de Guzman, though he is said to have turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine officials have also sought to use the publicity
surrounding the case to advertise their country's inexpensive
computing talent to high-technology companies abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Philippine president, Joseph Estrada, traveled
to the United States to meet with President Clinton and to seek
high-technology investment. Last week, Callahan Broadband Wireless
said it would invest 3.15 billion pesos, or $70 million, in a
Philippine company providing high-speed Internet services to
businesses in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
