u a BC-PUBLIC-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT RECORD LEVEL NOW, SCHOOL ENROLLMENT EXPECTED TO GROW THROUGH
CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Nev., Tenn., N.C.)   By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government says the nation's elementary and
secondary schools will enroll a record 53 million students this
fall, continuing a decade-long rise, and officials expect that
number to jump to 94 million by the end of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The enrollment figure, released Monday by the Secretary of
Education, Richard W. Riley, includes both private and public
schools and represents an increase of 200,000 students, or 0.4
percent, since last the beginning of last term, and an increase of
6.6 million, or 14.2 percent, since 1990. School enrollment is
expected to continue to rise slightly through 2005, to 53.5
million, and then level off through 2010.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to the baby boom _ which was followed, beginning
in the late 1950s, by a plunge in school enrollment that lasted
almost uninterrupted for nearly two decades _ the school population
is expected to grow without any letup throughout the rest of the
21st century. Enrollment will swell steadily because of rising
births and an unabated flood of immigrants, the report said, citing
census projections.
</P>
<P>
   As graduation rates continue to climb, some colleges will be
swamped by the overflow, at least in applications; college
enrollment is expected to grow by 19 percent, or 2.4 million
students, over the next decade alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a century of growth ahead of us, a crescendo of
children,'' Riley said. ``America's challenge as we begin the 21st
century is to make good choices now, so that we won't be
overwhelmed later.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Riley issues an annual enrollment report at the end of
each summer, his emphasis on the long view was aimed, at least in
part, at the Republican Congress, which has consistently blocked
President Clinton's efforts to make available $25 billion in
interest-free bonds to enable districts to build and renovate
schools. The Republicans have said such responsibility lies with
school districts themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Riley made clear that public school districts, urban and rural,
are already coping with extraordinary growth. In Las Vegas, where
Riley released the report, the Clark County School District has
almost doubled in size over the last 10 years, growing to 208,777
from 105,054. (One of the newest schools, Irwin and Susan Molasky
Junior High School, was named, appropriately, for a builder.) The
Chattanooga, Tenn., schools grew at a similar rate, to 42,292
students from 20,425. And in Greensboro, N.C., enrollment rose by
156 percent, to 61,154 from 23,851.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has estimated the cost of renovating
and repairing existing schools alone at $127 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While every section of the country is expected to be affected by
the growth over the next century, Riley said that western and
southern states would feel such increases acutely. Over the next 10
years, public schools in Texas are projected to grow by 219,000
students, an increase of 5.4 percent; California is expected to add
278,000 students, an increase of 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As overwhelming as the projected growth in school enrollment
appears over the 21st century, it is, by percentage, smaller than
that over the last 100 years: the nation's public and private
schools grew by 31.5 million students, or 147 percent, from 1900
through 2000, as compared with a projection of 41 million
additional students, or 77 percent, from now to 2100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
