<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD FOR THE SURVIVOR PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RENEE KIENTZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Vittles for a ``Survivor'' party take ingenuity and planning.
Anybody can set out Ritz crackers and cream cheese swimming in
jalapeno jelly, but where's the adventure in that?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the series finale airs Wednesday, you hardly have time to
lay in a store of rat, the obvious entree, unless you've thought
ahead. (We hear rodent freezes well; just thaw and roast, a la
Ramona.)
</P>
<P>
   Squirrel, known in Cajun country as ``the other white meat,''
makes a good substitute and is more readily available. Squirrels
frolic in the light of day and, more naive than their furtive
cousins, are easily attracted to backyard feeders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Directions for Squirrels a la King, from ``More White Trash
Cooking'' by Trisha Mickler (Ten Speed Press, $19.95), suggest
soaking dressed squirrel in saltwater overnight.
</P>
<P>
   An hour or two before dinner, wash them rascals (the soaked
squirrels) in two changes of cool water. Throw 'em in a kettle with
enough water to cover. Add two halves of an onion, some celery,
salt, and pepper; then bring to a boil. Skim the surface foam from
the bubbling stew, and let it simmer until done. Drain and dry the
squirrels. Then split them down the back and brown the four halves
in a buttered skillet until golden brown. This is best served with
cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; To serve: Don't just let everybody eat. Make them earn the
privilege. Divide guests into two tribes and issue a challenge.
First tribe to guess the number of calories in a 3.6-ounce portion
of squirrel meat, as determined by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, wins. The other tribe? Let them eat rat-a-touille.
</P>
<P>
   Rat-a-touille
</P>
<P>
   (From the Junior League of Houston's ``Star of Texas Cookbook,''
Wimmer Co., 1992)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 eggplant, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini, quartered lengthwise and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mushrooms, quartered
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 1/2 ounces) tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a large heavy saucepan, layer ingredients in the order given.
Set casserole on burner that has been heated to high temperature.
Reduce to medium, and cook for 10 to 12 minutes or until done. Stir
occasionally. This is better if prepared ahead and allowed to sit
overnight. Serves 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   (FYI: According to the USDA, there are 120 calories and 3 grams
of fat in a 3.6-ounce portion of squirrel.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
