<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-BOSTON-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SCIENTIFIC GETS REPRIMAND FROM SEC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Securities and Exchange Commission has issued a cease and
desist order against Boston Scientific Corp., effectively slapping
the company's wrists after its Japanese unit faked sales of $75
million in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC action did not include a fine. It ended a 2-year-old
scandal that began when the company's finance department uncovered
the fraudulent sales, which involved more than 40 employees,
including the president of Boston Scientific Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific, a Natick, Mass. maker of medical devices,
consented to the order without formally admitting or denying the
commission's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The order does not find any intentional or reckless conduct on
the part of Boston Scientific, and it acknowledges the company's
prompt remedial acts and cooperation,'' the company said in a
statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's order does, however, accuse the company of
failing to maintain an adequate system of controls. It states that
poor tracking of accounts and inventory made it possible for its
Japanese employees to record false sales and boost revenue figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Boston Scientific had appropriate controls in place, they
would have discovered this sooner or prevented it in the first
place,'' said James B. Adelman, the SEC's associate district
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Between January 1997 and June 1998 more than 40 employees of
Boston Scientific Japan and 143 independent distributors became
involved in the scheme, according to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The employees would record sales to distributors who agreed to
participate in the scheme, the SEC said. In some cases, products
were sent to the distributor. In others, they were sent to a
warehouse leased by the company.
</P>
<P>
   The distributors never paid for the merchandise, knowing that
their accounts would later be credited for the amount that was
owed. If asked, however, the distributors confirmed buying and
owing money for the products.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the distributors weren't even in the medical products
business, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Adelman said the SEC decided against levying a fine because the
company took the appropriate steps to remedy the problem and
because it was limited to a single subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific discovered the fraud when installing a new
information management system at the Japanese unit and immediately
reported the fraudulent activity to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, the company publicly announced that it had
improperly booked more than $40 million in sales in the first nine
months of that year. And in February 1999, it issued corrected
financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to installing the new information management system,
the company has taken a number of steps to strengthen its internal
financial controls, said Paul Donovan, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts called the trouble ``old news,'' saying
investors responded when it was announced two years ago and
wouldn't likely have much reaction to the SEC sanction.
</P>
<P>
   They were far more interested Monday in the company's
discussions to buy Medinol Ltd. of Israel, its major supplier of
cardiovascular stents, small tubes used to prop open once-clogged
arteries. Difficulties with Medinol have caused Boston Scientific's
cardiovascular stent revenues to slip.
</P>
<P>
   TheMarker.com, a Hebrew language business Web site, was
reporting Monday that the two companies had come to an agreement.
But Boston Scientific denied the report, saying the discussions are
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific shares closed Monday at $17.81, up $1.44 from
Friday. The company's stock was trading as high as $46 a share two
years ago, before news of the fraudulent sales and the problems
with Medinol began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sanction is just the final chapter on an obviously
disappointing part of the Boston Scientific story,'' said Dan
Lemaitre, medical technology analyst with Merrill Lynch Global
Securities. ``But there's nothing to affect earnings going forward
_ no fine, no changed financial statements _ and the company is
bound and determined not to let anything like that happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
