<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ENVIRONMENT-ACTIVIST-     08-21 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-ACTIVIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FORT WORTH NATIVE DISCOVERS THAT HER `GREENING' WAS IN HER GENES
ALL ALONG
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By LIZ STEVENS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Elizabeth Freese didn't mean to end up in Dallas. For
one thing, she's from a long line of Fort Worth natives. For
another, she was on a quest _ a spiritual journey that took her
places where people who need to contemplate, and can afford the
time to do it, often go: Santa Fe, N.M.; Boulder, Colo.; San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Metroplex wasn't really on her radar.
</P>
<P>
   But fate has a funny way of putting people where they belong,
and, in Freese's case, it was back home in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the 31-year-old Freese launched greentexas.com, a
clearinghouse for North Texas environmental information. The site
centralizes and organizes local environmental activities, news and
resources, providing lists of nonprofit groups and ``green''
businesses locally and nationally. And it links to dozens of other
sites focused on air quality, recycling, green architecture,
sustainable industry, even religion-based environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
   Freese runs the site, an arm of the nonprofit Greater Dallas
Planning Council, as part of her job as an account executive for
the public relations firm Read-Poland. But greentexas.com was her
concept, and the Web site, which has received generally positive
reviews from local activists, has been her project from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Freese's budding environmental career was both unforeseen and
prophesied. She grew up in the privileged enclave of Westover
Hills, in a ``Republican to the core'' culture, she says, where
social activism was not part of the picture _ or, at least, not
during Freese's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say she didn't grow up with an appreciation of
nature _ her grandparents were avid naturalists and her father's
family owns cabins in Red River, N.M. But it wasn't until college
that Freese fully realized that her family _ specifically her
great-grandmother _ had an environmental legacy to boast of.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Hallie Read Hardwicke, founder of the Planned
Parenthood Association of Fort Worth and president of the local
Audubon Society, was among a small group of activists who
encouraged city leaders to set aside a 360-acre wildlife preserve
near Lake Worth. The Fort Worth Nature Center and Refuge has grown
tenfold since then and in 1970 named its new Interpretive Center
for Hallie and Robert Hardwicke.
</P>
<P>
   (The revelation that an environmental gene ran in the family
came as somewhat of a relief to Freese, who thought ``OK. I'm not
insane. I didn't just make this up out of nowhere.'')
</P>
<P>
   In January 1966, Hallie Hardwicke gave a speech at the Fort
Worth Club, one that her great-granddaughter might have written
today, Freese says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservation of our natural resources _ land, air, woods,
water and the wildlife dependent upon these resources _ is our
objective,'' Hallie told her audience, ``and our weapons are simple
ones: informing ourselves as to the grandiose plans of government
agencies and the often shortsighted schemes of many private
investors, then participating at every level of government through
our citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Freese's interest in environmental work grew slowly. She recalls
standing outside a supermarket in Connecticut, as a freshman at
Trinity College, asking shoppers to sign a petition (she vaguely
remembers it having something to do with the cleanup of a Superfund
site).
</P>
<P>
   When she transferred to Barnard College in New York City, the
same school her great-grandmother had attended, her focus drifted
to abortion rights and coordinating student involvement in two
Washington, D.C., pro-choice marches.
</P>
<P>
   Her insulated upbringing, she says, simply hadn't prepared her
for the diversity of ideas she encountered during college. ``It was
all just mind-blowing,'' Freese explains. ``There were so many
dimensions of our cultural or societal reality of which I was just
flat unaware and had just never experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   She graduated in 1991, having rejected the corporate path many
of her classmates chose, and set out to explore both the world and
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living on a trust fund for three years, writing,
painting, doing yoga,'' Freese says. She moved to Santa Fe for a
time and then to San Francisco to study Eastern philosophy. There,
she found herself drawn to the Chinese philosophy of Taoism and its
emphasis on the union of nature and humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Freese's parents have usually supported her decisions, and she's
close to both (talking daily to her mother in Fort Worth), ``but we
definitely get into some fairly heated debates,'' she says. ``We
agree to disagree a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   During those three post-college years of drifting, her folks
``were just hoping I would come out of it,'' she says, laughing.
But the spiritual search was a difficult time for Freese, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working through a lot of anger,'' she says. The culture
of her youth had consisted of what she calls ``an overemphasis to
the nth degree on getting wealth and social status to the detriment
of everything else. There wasn't much room for what's really
fulfilling ... I felt like it had cheated me of a deeper spiritual
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year each in Santa Fe and San Francisco, Freese settled
in Boulder, where a younger brother was attending college. Shortly
thereafter she followed an old boyfriend to Fayetteville, Ark.,
where her environmental work began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, local environmentalists were urging the U.S. Forest
Service to revamp the management plan for the national forest,
including reducing the amount of logging. Freese joined the Sierra
Club and the Newton County Wildlife Association, soon becoming the
latter's de facto spokesperson. She spoke on radio shows and to
Earth Day audiences; she wrote editorials for the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But her activism, she says, was coming from a place of hope, not
hostility. ``I was focused on the positive messages, on the
possibilities,'' she says. ``I didn't get up there to talk about
evil loggers.''
</P>
<P>
   Freese's style doesn't always sit well with some activists. She
has made a conscious decision to work within the system pursuing
change, choosing encouragement more than condemnation. But she sees
both tactics as necessary. ``I think that anger is a very
legitimate, appropriate response to environmental wrongs,'' she
says. ``But it can really burn you out, and I don't think it's
effective ultimately.''
</P>
<P>
   Freese eventually received a master's degree in environmental
communication from the University of Arkansas, dropped the ex-beau
and became engaged to a man whose job search brought them, of all
places, back to the Metroplex. Now she and husband Talley Summerlin
have neighboring offices at Read-Poland, where until recently both
spent about a third of their work week on greentexas.com.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Freese reduced her hours to part time. She'll still
be coordinating greentexas.com, and plans for it to become an
independent nonprofit one day. But she's also starting theology
school with hopes of practicing ``environmental ministry,'' a
movement addressing the moral and spiritual dimensions of saving
the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Her own spiritual moorings, Freese says, are a little more
secure these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so weird, but roots have become more and more important _
being around friends and family no matter how much we disagree on
various things,'' she admits. ``I don't feel like I quite belong
anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
