<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEXICO-MEDICINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOCTOR'S DISCOVERY REVISES THE HISTORY OF MEDICAL IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A medical doctor with a scholarly interest in pre-Columbian art
appears to have pushed back the date of the earliest scientific
medical illustration by several centuries with his study of bizarre
two-faced ancient Mexican figurines known to art historians as the
``pretty ladies of Tlatilco.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon Bendersky, a visiting scholar in the department of
history at the University of Pennsylvania, made the discovery a
couple of years ago when leafing through journals and textbooks on
pre-Columbian art. He noticed pictures of figurines unearthed since
1942 in Tlatilco, which is now part of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Standing 3 inches to 12 inches tall, the figurines, which were
created over a period of 500 years beginning in 1200 B.C., have
short flipperlike arms, flaring thighs, small breasts, wasplike
waists and a somewhat whimsical hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen of the figurines have an even more grotesque feature
_ two faces on a single head. Some have two heads on one neck and
some have two heads on two necks.
</P>
<P>
   Art historians have long considered the two faces to be a
representation of mythical beings. But, as Bendersky scanned the
pages of the documents before him, he was suddenly struck by the
similarities between the monstrous pretty ladies of Tlatilco and a
rare congenital aberration called diprosopus that he had come
across while a medical student.
</P>
<P>
   Bendersky's initial suspicion caused him to embark on what
proved to be a two-year program of research to learn whether or not
his guess could be correct.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, he is convinced that he has identified ``the
oldest scientifically medical images in world history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tremendously exciting to think that the Tlatilco
artists appeared to be the very first to marry art with medical
science,'' said Bendersky, who retired this year as professor of
internal medicine at the MCP Hahnemann University School of
Medicine in Philadelphia..
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in his enthusiasm. Dr. Robert Perlman, editor of
the journal Perspectives in Biology and Medicine in which
Bendersky's article on the figurines will appear in early
September, said he and his peer-review panel found Bendersky's
argument ``throughly convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman added: ``I think it was the Nobel prize-winner Albert
Szent-Gyorgyi who said that discovery consists of seeing what
everybody has seen and thinking what nobody has thought. That's
Gordon Bendersky. Lots of people had seen these figurines before,
but he was the first to think that they might represent human
congenital anomalies.''
</P>
<P>
   Diprosopus is an exceedingly rare  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  birth
defect, with only about 85 cases reported since 1642. The
condition, which invariably results in stillbirth, is caused by
abnormal splitting of primitive fetal organs. It can result in
facial duplication, heart abnor- malities and duplication or
complete absence of a brain. Scientists suspect that excess
embroyologic tissue L plays a role, and that both genetic factors
and environmental stresses early in development of the embryo could
be at work.
</P>
<P>
   After tracking down and examining hundreds of ceramic figurines
and comparing them to photographic illustrations of two-faced
Siamese twins, he concluded that the sculptors of ancient Tlatilco
must have studied cases of diprosopus ``very thoroughly,'' as he
later wrote. The sculptors, he explained, had not let their
imaginations run wild with the creation of figurines with three or
five faces or with faces stacked on top of one another. Instead,
they had strictly limited their ceramic models to naturally
occurring diprosopus _ two faces side by side.
</P>
<P>
   In order to determine whether or not the Tlatilco figurines are
in fact the world's oldest, Bendersky studied other ancient
representations of human deformities, including the morbidly obese
Paleolithic statuette, Venus of Willendorf, a six-toed statue from
Ain Ghazal in Jordan, and a representation of the ancient Egyptian
dwarf Seneb.
</P>
<P>
   Although older than the Tlatilco figurines, these objects fail
to qualify as medical illustrations, Bendersky concluded. In
addition to being crudely schematic rather than drawn from nature,
they are portrayals of a particular deity or person who happens by
chance to have an abnormality rather than being representative of a
disease or deformity so as to provide diagnostic value.
</P>
<P>
   The result, he was able to say, was that the degree of accuracy
in documenting anatomical and pathological features in a human head
does not appear after the Tlatilco figurines for another 2,000
years or more until the 16th century works of Hans Baldung Grien
and Andreas Vesalius, who both did anatomical drawings based in
dissected corpses.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as Bendersky has gone to explain the pretty ladies of
Tlatilco, he has not been able to fathom their cultural meaning.
What could explain the fascination of the early Mesoamericans with
two-facedness? How was it possible that a prehistoric civilization
that had yet to develop the wheel, metal tools, the domestication
of animals and a sophisticated written language could have
developed an extraordinarily acute power of scientific observation?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the answer to that,'' said Bendersky. ``The only
way we might understand it would be to discover a written language
used by these ancient peoples and that, I'm afraid, doesn't seem
likely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
