<HEADER>
A8304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SURVIVOR-AD-COLUMN-AR     08-21 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-AD-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOMENTS' FOR MILK FINDS UBIQUITOUS `SURVIVORS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Calif.)   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The creators of the long-running ``milk mustache'' campaign saw
a natural connection between the need to drink milk and the hit CBS
television show ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We always like to have a fun twist on the nutritional value of
milk and the whole idea of `Survivor' fits,'' said Kurt Graetzer,
chief executive of the Milk Processor Education Program, which
represents milk processors and sponsors the campaign with Dairy
Management Inc., representing dairy farmers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the four remaining survivors of the show will don
milk mustaches in a specially made print ad appearing Wednesday,
the day the final episode of ``Survivor'' is broadcast. The
headline is ``What the last remaining survivor dreams of wearing
tomorrow.'' The winning survivor then is to appear alone in a full
page ad on Thursday in USA Today, and in newspapers and some weekly
magazines over the next week or more, said Sal Taibi, account
services director at Bozell New York, the True North Communications
unit that created the milk mustache campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Like others, ranging from Reebok International to Playboy
magazine, who have sought out the ``Survivor'' cast, the producer
of the milk ads is trying to capitalize on the cast members' 15
minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relevant to everyone because they are in the news, and it
helps us to cut through the clutter,'' said Craig Plymesser, vice
president of milk marketing at Dairy Management Inc. ``We are
picking up on their instant celebrityship, if you will, and using
them to carry the message of milk and the calcium crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the overall estimated $50 million milk mustache print
campaign is intended to piggyback on celebrity and change the image
of milk from wholesome to hip. Some 100 celebrities have worn
mustaches in the campaign since it was introduced in 1995, Taibi
said.
</P>
<P>
   But to keep the campaign fresh, Bozell often uses celebrities of
the moment. This year Bozell ran an ad of the tennis champions and
sisters Venus and Serena Williams. The ad ran the day after Venus
Williams won Wimbledon, and was headlined ``Make ours doubles.''
The Dixie Chicks appeared with mustaches the day after winning a
Grammy Award in March. And a milk mustache ad of the winning
quarterback the day after the Super Bowl is now almost a standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it really works, it's a way, for a moment, of truly
getting a blip on the awareness meter, and then what happens is
that over time, people begin to recognize that milk is a drink for
today's lifestyle,'' Graetzer said. The ads may be short-lived, but
their immediacy and novelty outweigh any drawbacks, Taibi said.
``On the morning after, when everyone is talking about it, we'll
already have that person in an ad endorsing milk. And everyone's
wondering how we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   And that conversation is valuable. According to BSMG, Chicago,
the True North Communications unit that handles publicity for the
milk campaign, some 250 television stations, The New York Times and
The Associated Press did reports about the Super Bowl milk mustache
ads in January. BSMG calculated that the coverage accounted for 29
million viewers or readers, based on circulation and ratings
information.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity is all part of the program, of course. For the
Super Bowl, the milk campaign typically runs an ad of the opposing
quarterbacks of the big game on the day of the bowl, followed by an
ad of the winning quarterback. BSMG interviews the quarterbacks
about the advertising shoot, and then releases the interviews to TV
stations to use during their pre- and postgame coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which Bozell has dubbed its ``moments'' campaign, came
about after the campaign garnered a huge windfall of publicity over
an ad that featured President Clinton and his Republican opponent,
Bob Dole, on the eve of the 1996 presidential election. Coverage of
that single ad led to 189 print news articles and 36 television
reports, accounting for 107 million viewer-readers, according to
BSMG.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bozell has a staff of three people whose jobs resemble
those of reporters more than ad people as they track the daily news
for up-and-coming celebrities, and for a dramatic story like that
of the Williams sisters who trained their whole lives together and
then had to compete against each other at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   While a typical celebrity ad for the milk mustache campaign
could take months, from lining up a celebrity to scheduling the
photo shoot, the moment's ads are turned around in a few days.
Logistics are key and the entire process is lined up in advance and
staged, Taibi said.
</P>
<P>
   For the ``Survivors'' ads, the four remaining survivors were
photographed, together and separately, on a beach in Malibu on
Friday. The group was paid an undisclosed standard group fee.
Individuals are paid a standard $25,000 fee for a few hours work.
As in sporting events, Bozell does not know who the final survivor
will be, and must wait to release the proper ad for publication
immediately after the show is broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   One big advantage of milk's ``moment'' ads is that often Bozell
is catching the star on the rise. That usually means the celebrity
is not yet overexposed and also less likely to turn them down.
Though the mustache campaign is now so much part of the culture
that Taibi says many celebrities consider being part of the
campaign a validation of their status in the pop culture, stars do
turn down the campaign. But so far, Bozell has never been rejected
for a ``moments'' ad, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the moment ads do have an element of risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have a generic ad in our back pocket, and if one of
the people we have doesn't win, we'd just run that generic ad and
no one would know the difference,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
