<HEADER>
A8307 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV27-     08-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITEMS ON A COAST-TO-COAST TRAIL; IMPROVEMENTS IN THE AMTRAK AUTO
TRAIN; A NEW SCULPTURE PARK IN MICHIGAN; AN ENVIRONMENTAL RATING
FOR HOTELS IN COSTA RICA; , THE YEAR 1000 AT HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 25) 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
A Nice Possibility For a Very Long Stroll  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening of the American Discovery Trail, the United States'
first coast-to-coast, nonmotorized trail, will be celebrated on
September 2 in San Francisco, at Crissy Field in the Presidio. The
six-hour event will begin at 11 a.m., with an opening ceremony at 1
p.m. The event will include booths with trail information and the
latest outdoor gear, and appearances by people who have navigated
all or part of the trail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 6,356-mile trail runs from Cape Henlopen State Park in
Delaware to Limantour Beach in Point Reyes National Seashore, about
45 miles north of San Francisco. In the Midwest, it splits into two
branches _ a northern route through Indiana, Illinois, Iowa and
Nebraska, and a southern route through Indiana, Illinois, Missouri
and Kansas. All told, it traverses 15 states and the District of
Columbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along its route, the trail passes through hundreds of small
towns and urban centers like Kansas City, Denver and Cincinnati,
and it leads to 14 national parks, 16 national forests and 10,000
sites of historic, cultural and natural significance. The diverse
terrain includes back-country footpaths, city streets and canal
towpaths. The entire length of the trail can be walked, and many
segments are open to bicycles and horses as well. According to the
American Discovery Trail Society, the nonprofit group coordinating
local efforts to maintain the trail, it is expected that people
living near the Discovery Trail rather than long-distance
backpackers will be the most frequent users. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trail's opening culminates an 11-year effort to select a
route in consultation with local, state and federal land managers,
to create links between existing trails, and to place signs in the
states through which it passes. For information about the trail and
available guidebooks and maps, call the American Discovery Trail
Society at (800) 663-2387, or go to www.discoverytrail.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CHRISTOPHER HALL
</P>
<P>
   AUTO TRAIN HOPING TO QUICKEN DELIVERY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Amtrak Auto Train, which carries automobiles and passengers
between the Washington area and the Orlando area, has opened a new
station at its northern terminal, in Lorton, Va. Its platform is
now long enough to accommodate the entire train rather than half,
which was the case previously, and is expected to reduce the time
needed by Auto Train staff to unload vehicles. New waiting areas
with 450 seats, food service and bigger restrooms are also part of
the building.
</P>
<P>
   The Auto Train operates once a day in each direction, leaving
Lorton and Sanford, Fla., at 4 p.m. and arriving at 8:30 a.m. the
next day. Lorton is 25 miles south of the capital; Sanford is on
the outskirts of Orlando. Each train can handle about 270 vehicles
and has 16 cars for passengers, including three dining cars. The
fare for the 855-mile trip includes a dinner and Continental
breakfast; sleeping car berths cost extra.
</P>
<P>
   The southbound peak season is from mid-October to mid-January,
when an advance-purchase fare for a car or sports utility vehicle,
a driver and one passenger might cost $466 one way. The peak season
northbound is from mid-March to mid-May. Amtrak adjusts fares
depending on demand and the length of advance booking. Auto Train:
www.amtrak.com, or (877) 754-7495. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COSTA RICA GIVES HOTELS ENVIRONMENTAL RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   The Costa Rican Tourism Institute, which oversees the national
tourist board, has created a Web site with a listing of hotels that
have been rated for their efforts to improve the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Each hotel that applies for a voluntary Certificate of
Sustainable Tourism from the institute undergoes a two-day
inspection. In addition to the hotel's ecological effects, the
inspection looks at the impact of the hotel on the quality of life
and the cultural heritage of its community.
</P>
<P>
   The certification program considers the interaction between the
hotel and its habitat; its water, energy and product management
systems; the relationship between the hotel and the local community
and culture, and to what extent its guests are invited to
participate in the hotel's efforts. The hotel is rated from 1 to 5,
with 1 the lowest rating in any category, and each hotel receives
an overall rating.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, www.turismo-sostenible.co.cr/EN/home.shtml,
available in English and Spanish, provides a directory searchable
by province, number of rooms, the hotel's setting and its level of
certification. None of the 46 certified hotels has achieved a 5
over all, but three have earned a 4: Observatorio Volcan Arenal in
Alajuela Province, near the country's most active volcano; Heredura
Hotel, a resort and conference center in Heredia Province; and the
Rosa Blanca Country Inn, also in Heredia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Frederik Meijer Gardens and Sculpture Park, opened five
years ago on the eastern edge of Grand Rapids, Mich., is more than
doubling its indoor space with a 65,000-square-foot expansion. With
the Sept. 15 opening of the two-story addition, the 118-acre
botanical garden and sculpture park will be complemented by three
indoor sculpture galleries, an 850-seat lecture hall with modern
audio-visual equipment, classrooms, a garden shop and a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   The new sculpture complex will open with ``Richard Hunt:
American Visionary,'' exhibiting work by the Chicago artist who is
creating a 25-foot-tall winged column for the Meijer's permanent
collection. That collection includes Nina Akamu's 24-foot-high
``Leonardo da Vinci's Horse,'' the duplicate of her sculpture based
on Leonardo's plans that was donated to Milan last year, and works
by prominent artists such as Alexander Calder (``Polychrome
Lures''), Deborah Butterfield and Marshall Fredericks.
</P>
<P>
   The Frederik Meijer Gardens, 1000 East Beltline Northeast, Grand
Rapids, (888) 957-1580, www.meijergardens.org, are off I-96. Hours
are 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily, except noon to 5 on Sunday. Admission
is $5, $4 65 or older, and $2 ages 5 to 13. A guided tram tour is
$1. All areas are wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RAY CORMIER
</P>
<P>
   AT HARVARD, A SPOTLIGHT ON THE ROMANESQUE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Before and After the End of Time: Architecture and the Year
1000,'' an exhibition that was scheduled to open August 26 at the
Fogg Museum at Harvard University, is an overview of Romanesque
architecture, which preceded the Gothic cathedrals in Europe.
Romanesque was a rediscovery of the masonry techniques of the Roman
empire, characterized by rounded arches, domed vaults and cut-stone
masonry that emphasize the power of mass, space and gravity, rather
than the more ethereal vertical aspirations of the Gothic.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the exhibition are 12 gemstones representing the
ones from which the foundations of the new Jerusalem of John's Book
of Revelation were to be made; they present a striking contrast to
the massive buildings of the Romanesque. The exhibition is
punctuated with examples of expressive, humanistic 12th-century
sculpture from France and Spain. Renderings by the Harvard art
historian Kenneth J. Conant on the 11th century transformation of
the Benedictine abbey at Cluny, France, are being shown to the
public for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely-seen architectural photography by the architect Henry
Hobson Richardson, whose late 19th century Romanesque Revival style
was particularly influential in the United States, is also on
display.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will be at the Fogg Museum, 32 Quincy Street,
Cambridge, Mass., through Jan. 21. The Fogg is open Monday through
Saturday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., and Sunday 1 to 5 p.m.; closed
holidays. Admission is $5; $4 for ages 61 and above; $3 for college
students; free for children under 18 and for everyone on Wednesdays
and Saturdays until noon; (617) 495-9400.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC P. NASH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
