<HEADLINE>
CITIES, COUNTIES CHALLENGE VIRGINIA LAW RESTRICTING HOW RESIDENTS
ARE COUNTED IN CENSUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Houston and San Antonio are joining 13 other U.S.
cities and counties in challenging a Virginia law that restricts
how state residents can be counted in the national census.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument is that federal funding for welfare programs
would be unfairly slashed if Texas adopted a similar restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia statute, now before a federal court, requires that
sampling not be used in the state to supplement the direct count of
individuals. Virginia enacted the law in response to President
Clinton's plan to use sampling to account for citizens, primarily
minorities, who are historically missed by census takers. Sampling
uses a mathematical formula to account for those who were missed.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas cities and other jurisdictions challenging the law
argue that using sampling methods is necessary for a true
population count, which is critical for a fair and accurate
distribution of federal funds for social welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Census Bureau data indicate that Texas missed out on $1
billion in federal assistance following the 1990 Census, which
failed to count 66,745 people in Houston, primarily minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding the patent discriminatory impact and inequity
that result from using inaccurate census data for redistricting
purposes, (Virginia) has enacted a law that requires the use of
less accurate unadjusted data for such purposes,'' argued Brian
Currey of Los Angeles and Karen Wahle of Washington, attorneys for
the local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cities joining the lawsuit are Los Angeles: San
Francisco; Oakland and Denver. The Virginia chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People also has filed
papers with the U.S. District Court in Washington challenging the
state law.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia Attorney General Mark Earley said a head count is
the only way to get a true population figure, adding that
supplementing the result with mathematical formulas would cause
inaccuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers, rather than guesses, have been, and should continue
to be, used to redraw political boundaries,'' Earley spokesman
Randy Davis said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the court case, Virginia is trying to head off a Justice
Department challenge to the state's new law by getting the federal
court's approval of the statute. The cities, counties and local
NAACP are supporting the Justice Department's opposition to the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal Voting Rights Act, Virginia, like Texas, must
get the approval of the Justice Department or a federal court
before the state can put in place a law that affects the political
representation of minorities. Virginia, suspecting that Clinton's
Justice Department would not approve of the new law, has opted to
go to court.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel that will hear the case has not scheduled
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Houston and other proponents of sampling were dealt a blow last
year when the Supreme Court struck down Clinton's plans to use the
method for the count that is used in the federal apportionment of
the 435 House seats among the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   After the court's ruling, the president said he would use
statistics to conduct what will effectively be a second census
count, to calculate population patterns for the doling out of
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republican lawmakers fear Democratic state legislators
will manipulate the statistical result to redraw state district
lines to include more minorities, a traditionally strong voting
bloc for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 Census, conducted by traditional head count, missed 8
million people, including 66,745 in Houston, according to the
Census Bureau. The 1990 Census in Texas undercounted Hispanics by
5.4 percent compared with 3.9 percent for blacks and 2.6 percent
for Non-Hispanic whites and Asians, the bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's total estimated undercount of 3.9 percent that year
was the highest of any major city, while Texas' 2.8 percent was
second to New Mexico's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
