<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FALL-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X X X ... THE WORLD BEYOND.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  The nonfiction lists for October are dominated by biographies and
memoirs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three memoirists pick up where they left off.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Liars' Club,'' Mary Karr chronicled her harrowing and
hilarious working-class childhood in East Texas and Colorado.
``Cherry'' (Viking, $24) describes her junior high and high school
years, leading up to her decision to light out for California.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Hickam grew up half a continent away, in Coalwood, W.Va.
His new ``The Coalwood Way'' (Delacorte, $23.95) continues the
portrait of small-town life the future NASA engineer began in
1998's ``Rocket Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   And Malachy McCourt, who regaled us with stories of his
misbegotten youth in ``A Monk Swimming,'' describes his career in
radio, television and movies and his battles with the bottle and
cancer in ``Singing My Him Song'' (HarperCollins, $25).
</P>
<P>
   The big biographies of the season certainly include James Atlas'
``Bellow'' (Random House, $35). Written with Bellow's cooperation,
it is a candid, detailed and eminently readable life of the Nobel
Prize winner widely considered the finest living American novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Another American icon is treated in journalist Richard Ben
Cramer's long-awaited ``Joe DiMaggio: The Hero's Life'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $30).
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' ``W.E.B. DuBois'' (Henry Holt, $35) carries the black
leader's life from World War I until his death in 1963. The first
volume, published in 1994, won the Bancroft, Parkman and Pulitzer
prizes, making it one of the most-honored biographies of the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe is always interesting, although his new book doesn't look
to be a major addition to his oeuvre. ``Hooking Up'' (Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25) combines reportage on subjects ranging from
the sexual mores of teens to television magazine-show stings with
Wolfe's novella ``Ambush at Fort Bragg'' and a short story.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Deavere Smith, best known for her one-woman plays based on
interviews with people from communities in crisis went to
Washington, D.C., to observe how politicians speak. The result is
``Talk to Me: Listening Between the Lines'' (Random House, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Political specimens more impressive, perhaps, can be found in
this pair of biographies. In ``Founding Brothers: The Revolutionary
Generation'' (Knopf, $26) Joseph J. Ellis, winner of the National
Book Award for his biography of Thomas Jefferson, explores the
intertwined lives of John Adams, Alexander Hamilton, George
Washington and the rest of the let's-start-a-nation gang.
Meanwhile, Texas A&AMP;M professor H.M. Brand takes the measure of
polymath Ben Franklin in ``The First American'' (Doubleday, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Franklin experimented with lightning, but for real sparks you
can't beat opera diva Maria Callas and tycoon Aristotle Onassis.
Nicholas Gage claims access to new information in ``Greek Fire''
(Knopf, $26).
</P>
<P>
   Kingsolver, McMurtry and John Updike have fiction due in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Poisonwood Bible,'' Kingsolver's 1998 novel, has sold more
than a million copies in hardcover and paperback and made her the
hottest name in literary fiction (the book is still on the
paperback best-seller list). Set in southern Appalachia, ``Prodigal
Summer'' (HarperCollins, $26) weaves together three sets of
characters who ``find their connections to one another and to the
flora and fauna with whom they share a place,'' says the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry keeps threatening to quit writing fiction, but
fortunately for us that's all talk so far. His last, ``Duane's
Depressed,'' was his best in years. For the new one, ``Boone's
Lick'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26), he returns to the 19th-century
American West. The story involves an extended family's trek from
Missouri to Wyoming and climaxes with the notorious 1866 Fetterman
Massacre, in which Plains Indians slaughtered some 80 U.S. soldiers
near Fort Phil Kearny in a fight that prefigured the Battle of the
Little Bighorn.
</P>
<P>
   Updike's ``Licks of Love'' (Knopf, $25) collects a dozen short
stories to which the author has appended a novella-length piece
titled ``Rabbit Remembered,'' a sequel to his quartet of novels
about Harry ``Rabbit'' Angstrom. The dead man's survivors
``fitfully entertain his memory while pursuing their own happiness
over the edge of the millennium,'' says the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   England's Beryl Bainbridge fictionalizes the complex
relationship between 18th-century man of letters Samuel Johnson and
his benefactress, Hester Thrale, in ``According to Queeney''
(Carroll &AMP; Graf, $22).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the irrepressible sleuth Kay Scarpetta returns for
another go at the bad guys in Patricia Cornwell's ``The Last
Precinct'' (Putnam, $26.95).
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction titles include the first volume of Arthur M.
Schlesinger Jr.'s memoirs. ``A Life in the Twentieth Century''
(Houghton Mifflin, $27) carries the renowned public intellectual's
story from his birth in 1917 to 1950.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Boom'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) journalist Bob Woodward
tries to explain how our present economic happy days came about.
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan figures in that story, of
course. He moves front and center in Justin Martin's ``Citizen
Greenspan: The Man Behind the Money'' (Perseus, $27.50), which
explores the private man as well as the public life.
</P>
<P>
   Debora Silverman looks afresh at the relationship between two
fountainheads of 20th-century painting in ``Van Gogh and Gauguin:
The Search for Sacred Art'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $50), while
Gary Giddens, much praised for his ``Visions of Jazz,'' examines
the early career of a great American crooner in ``Bing Crosby: A
Pocketful of Dreams _ The Early Years, 1903-1940'' (Little, Brown,
$27.95).
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
