<HEADLINE>
A FALL HARVEST: PUBLISHERS PROMISE BUMPER CROP OF TITLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Admittedly, there's not even a hint of autumnal nip in the air. But
look at the calendar: August is melting away. School has already
started. As far as American publishers are concerned, fall is upon
us.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weeks between now and Christmas have traditionally seen the
bulk of the A-list books for the year _ the novels by big names,
the controversy-provoking polemics, the fat and formidable
biographies.
</P>
<P>
   This year's crop looks fairly impressive:
</P>
<P>
   We'll see novels by Barbara Kingsolver, Gore Vidal, Carlos
Fuentes, Margaret Atwood, Alice Walker and Larry McMurtry (who,
bless him, has spared us another prequel/sequel).
</P>
<P>
   The nonfiction offerings include a new collection by Tom Wolfe
featuring both journalism and short fiction. Also look for a major
biography of literary lion Saul Bellow, part two of David Levering
Lewis' Pulitzer Prize-winning life of civil rights activist W.E.B.
DuBois and Port Arthur native Mary Karr's sequel to her acclaimed
memoir ``The Liars' Club.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's a rundown of titles arriving in stores beginning in
September.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, historical novels seem the rage. Of course,
they have never disappeared, but their number and quality seem to
be on the rise. This may say more about our own dull times than
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   From Doubleday comes Vidal's ``Golden Age'' ($27.50), in which
he continues the fictional chronicle of American history begun in
1973 with ``Burr.'' The new book covers the years from 1939 to 1954
_ World War II and the beginnings of the Cold War _ and mixes
fictional characters with such real-life actors as Franklin and
Eleanor Roosevelt, newspaper tycoon William Randolph Hearst and
Vidal himself.
</P>
<P>
   From the catalog description the plot of Atwood's ``The Blind
Assassin`` (Doubleday, $26) is impossible to fathom _ something
about a woman who drives her car off a bridge in 1945 and a
novel-within-the-novel. But the publisher promises a book that
unfolds ``layer by astonishing layer'' and an ending ``at once
shockingly unexpected and wonderfully satisfying.'' Atwood almost
never disappoints.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of 19th-century composer Robert Schumann and his
pianist-wife, Clara, get fictional treatment in J.D. Landis'
``Longing'' (Harcourt, $26). Landis, whose previous novel was the
well-received ``Lying in Bed,'' claims to have kept closely to the
facts in his reading of one of history's great love affairs.
</P>
<P>
   From England's Kazuo Ishiguro comes ``When We Were Orphans''
(Knopf, $25). The publisher is at pains to assure us that this
novel harkens back in its accessibility to the author's beloved
``Remains of the Day'' rather than to his last book, the dense and
disappointing ``Unconsoled.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1930s, the story involves an English detective who
returns to Shanghai, the city of his birth, to investigate the
mystery of his parents' disappearance years before.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping from the past to the future presents us with two novels
from familiar figures. Ursula K. Le Guin, doyenne of literate
sci-fi fiction, has another in her Hainish cycle. In ``The
Telling'' (Harcourt, $24) an observer from Earth lands in a world
where a monolithic state has abolished the past and reduced every
citizen to a consumer-producer. Think China of the Cultural
Revolution, says the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Caleb Carr, whose best-selling ``Alienist'' and less-selling
``Angel of Darkness'' were set in late-19th-century New York, sets
``Killing Time'' (Random House, $25.95) in that city in the year
2023. America's female president has been assassinated, and someone
has doctored the video footage of the event. New-millen-nium
criminologist Dr. Gideon Wolfe is on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to September nonfiction, we find a political biography
already making news _ historian Herbert Bix's ambitious and
extensively researched ``Hirohito and the Making of Modern Japan''
(HarperCollins, $35). Bix portrays Hirohito as a dynamic emperor
who exerted considerable influence on events of the war years yet
succeeded in projecting an image of passivity.
</P>
<P>
   Hirohito's wartime ally is the subject of Ian Kershaw's
``Hitler: 1937-1945: Nemesis'' (Norton, $35). The first volume of
this biography was widely praised, and the completed work promises
to be the best treatment of Hitler's life in English.
</P>
<P>
   What more could there be to say about Richard Nixon? Biographer
Anthony Summers (``Official and Confidential: The Secret Life of J.
Edgar Hoover'') claims to have dug into the man's public and
private life and produced ``compelling evidence of Nixon's
addiction to intrigue and to money,'' in the words of his
publisher. The book is ``Arrogance of Power: The Secret World of
Richard Nixon'' (Viking, $34.95).
</P>
<P>
   Stephen E. Ambrose, probably the most popular historian working
today, tells the story of the men who built the transcontinental
railroad in ``Nothing Like It in the World'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$28).
</P>
<P>
   Ted Koppel writes about personalities (Slobodan Milosevic),
politics (the Clinton impeachment), personal matters (his boyhood
in England) and more in ``Off Camera: Private Thoughts Made
Public'' (Knopf, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Cartoons aren't just for kids anymore. Cultural critic Ilan
Stavans and illustrator Lalo Alcaraz have combined for the witty
yet ultimately serious ``Latino USA: A Cartoon History'' (Basic
Books, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   In the medical field ``Waging the War'' (Random House, $25.95)
by Robert Cooke promises to be big. It's the story of the
revolutionary theories of cancer researcher Dr. Judah Folkman.
Former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop wrote the foreword.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's ``Arming America: The Origins of a National Gun
Culture'' (Knopf, $30). Historian Michael A. Bellesiles punctures
the myth that gun ownership was widespread in early America. Not
until the Civil War era did guns become commonplace, he argues.
</P>
<P>
   October brings new fiction from established literary figures and
relatively new faces.
</P>
<P>
   Among the former: Alice Walker (``The Color of Purple'') has a
collection of stories based on her life. ``The Way Forward Is With
a Broken Heart'' (Random House, $23.95) is the title.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Fuentes, who, like Walker, could use a hit. ``The Years of
Laura Diaz'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $26) begins, like Fuentes'
masterpiece ``The Death of Artemio Cruz,'' in the state of Veracruz
early in the century. Through the life of Diaz _ artist, political
activist, mother, lover of great men _ Fuentes explores the
troubled history of modern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Armistead Maupin (``Tales of the City,'' ``Further Tales of the
City'') returns after an eight-year absence with ``The Night
Listener'' (HarperCollins, $26), about a writer for a cult-hit
radio show and a 13-year-old boy sexually abused by his parents.
Sounds like heavy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   From Ha Jin, the young Chinese-American writer who won a
National Book Award last year for his novel ``Waiting,'' comes a
collection of stories, ``The Bridegroom'' (Pantheon, $22).
</P>
<P>
   Jane Hamilton, whose first-rate novels (``The Book of Ruth,''
``A Map of the World'') won a much wider audience when Oprah
sprinkled her fairy dust over them, returns with ``Disobedience''
(Doubleday, $24.95), about a 17-year-old youth who stumbles onto
his mother's e-mail affair with a violin-maker.
</P>
<P>
   And for Anne Rice fans there's ``Merrick'' (Knopf, $26.95), a
ragout of witches and vampires set in New Orleans and the world
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   X X X MORE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
