<P>
   DEBEERS-STRATEGY (London) _ De Beers has had to confront
accusations that the company has links to traffic in diamonds from
Africa's war zones. But it has also had to face a much bigger
challenge: that its huge stockpile of diamonds, used to help
control the supply and keep world prices high, had become a costly
albatross. Now, De Beers is using the controversy over so-called
blood diamonds to advance a strategic switch to address its
commercial problems. The plan is to turn De Beers from a stockpile
manager into a branded, high-value diamond-trader that would keep
diamonds from war zones out of the luxury market. Marketing, not
monopoly, would make sure the company maintained its leadership
position. By seizing the moral high ground, De Beers has already
shown signs that its business is turning around. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
