<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TROOPS BACK
</P>
<P>
   The police said British troops will return to the streets of
Belfast for the first time since September 1998 after the shooting
deaths of two men in violence ascribed to rivalries between
Protestant paramilitary units. The men were crossing a road when a
gunman opened fire, a police spokesman said. Although loyalist
groups all support British rule, they are riven by territorial,
political and personality differences.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA: REBEL ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   Guerrillas staged dozens of attacks in a bid to disrupt voting
for the region's representative in Russia's parliament, but killed
nine of their own by stumbling into a minefield, the Kremlin said.
The region's president, Aslan Maskhadov, said guerrillas made 73
attacks; the Kremlin counted 47, which killed three Russian
soldiers. Russian officials said at least half of eligible voters
turned out; the rights group Memorial said wartime conditions made
the vote pointless.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: MILOSEVIC TRAILING
</P>
<P>
   New polls show President Slobodan Milosevic lagging behind the
joint candidate of 15 opposition parties for the Sept. 24
presidential election. A survey by the Institute of Social Sciences
said Vojislav Kostunica, of the 15-party Democratic Opposition of
Serbia bloc, would get 35 percent of the vote and Milosevic 23
percent. The institute interviewed 1,700 respondents from Serbia,
excluding Kosovo. A survey by the Medium polling agency found 30
percent support for Kostunica and 25 percent for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: KILLINGS PROTESTED
</P>
<P>
   People gathered across the country in silent protest against the
killing of two Civil Guards by a bomb believed planted by Basque
rebels. In the Basque region, the police arrested five people
believed to be linked to a cell of the armed separatist group ETA.
The cell's leader and three other rebels died when explosives they
were carrying detonated.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: WALL GUARD JAILED
</P>
<P>
   A former East German border guard commander, Walter Schulze, 52,
was sentenced to two years and four months in prison by a Berlin
court in the shooting deaths of East Germans trying to escape
across the Berlin Wall. Among them was Chris Gueffroy, 20, the last
victim of the shoot-to-kill policy, who died on Feb. 5, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PEDOPHILIA ALERT
</P>
<P>
   A pedophilia scare has broken out after a 5-year-old Tunisian
immigrant was sexually abused and stabbed to death in the northern
town of Imperia and an 8-year-old Italian was sexually abused and
then burned alive in Bari, in the south. Alessandra Mussolini, a
right-wing member of parliament, proposed that pedophiles be
chemically castrated. But the Rev. Gianni Baget Bozzo, a confidant
of the center-right leader Silvio Berlusconi, dismissed it as a
``Nazi'' solution.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: PINOCHET DATE SET
</P>
<P>
   The judge hearing the case against Gen. Augusto Pinochet set
Oct. 9 as the date to question the former dictator and decide
whether he will be tried on human rights violations. Judge Juan
Guzman did not specify where and how the hearing will occur. As a
retired army general, Pinochet, 84, has the right to respond in
writing, but Guzman has said he would rather question him in
person.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: 12 DIE IN CLASHES
</P>
<P>
   A brigadier and a colonel in the Indian Army were among 12
people killed in continuing clashes with rebels in Jammu and
Kashmir, officials said. As the violence continued, shops and
businesses went on strike in the summer capital, Srinagar,
responding to a call by pro-Pakistan separatist guerrillas. Nearly
a dozen groups are fighting Indian rule in the mainly Muslim
Kashmir in a decade-old revolt that has left about 30,000 people
dead.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: VETERANS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   About 100 war veterans rallied in Seoul demanding the return of
South Korean prisoners of war and civilians said to be held in
North Korea. The South has given the North the names of 62 spies
set to be returned on Sept. 2. Seoul has received growing criticism
for failing to win a similar promise of repatriation from
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: CHARGES DROPPED
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors dismissed all charges against a former computer
college student accused of releasing the ``I love you'' virus on
May 4 that crippled e-mail systems worldwide. The Department of
Justice said the charges either did not apply to computer hacking,
or there was insufficient evidence to back them up. Onel de Guzman
acknowledged he may have released the virus by accident but refused
to say whether he was its author.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: REBEL REPORTED OUSTED
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front has replaced Foday Sankoh with a
new leader, Issa Sesay, the rebel group's field commander in recent
months, the government announced. Sankoh has been detained in
Freetown since a peace pact collapsed in May. Little is known of
Sesay, who is in his 20s. The group has yet to confirm the change.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA: PEACE TALKS RULED OUT
</P>
<P>
   Despite pressure from the churches and civil society to find a
peaceful solution to the country's longtime civil war, Angola's top
general said the government will not negotiate with the rebel
leader Jonas Savimbi. Gen. Joao de Matos said peace could only be
achieved if the military offensive continued and weakened the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: PRESS CURBS CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   Two pro-reform publishers, both women, appeared before a
hard-line court to face charges of religious and political dissent,
as Iran's press crackdown approaches its fifth month. Faraneh
Behzadi, publisher of the biweekly Danestaniha, and Fatemeh
Farahmandpour, publisher of the Gounagoun weekly, face charges of
insulting Islam and carrying out propaganda against the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
