<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8325 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' OFFENSIVE LINE FACES HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ You've got a left guard (Jason Andersen)
snapping the ball and a center (Damien Woody) playing left guard.
You've got a veteran lineman (Bruce Armstrong) who just got his
first dose of action at left tackle. You're using this guy here and
there. You've got free agents like Grant Williams and Lance Scott
just returning after missing all of training camp with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Your top draft pick, Adrian Klemm, is still not able to
practice, and veteran right guard Todd Rucci has yet to see the
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offensive line problems won't be solved before
Thursday's final exhibition game, against Carolina. In an area
where there must be some stability, there is very little, with the
regular season less than two weeks off. Is this unsettling for Drew
Bledsoe? He would never say so publicly. But a quarterback needs to
know that the guys in front will protect him, and right now,
Bledsoe can't feel very confident of that.
</P>
<P>
   While there were better things seen from the offensive line in
Sunday's 31-21 loss to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, there were also
bad things. For every great block, like the one Max Lane made to
spring Kevin Faulk for a 58-yard touchdown, there was a penalty
committed. Lane even broke his left thumb, though the injury
doesn't appear serious enough to keep him out of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of guys who played last night and saw
their first action and it wasn't that extensive, so we'll have to
give more time to those players, and I'm not sure if we'll make a
full evaluation based on what we saw last night,'' said coach Bill
Belichick. ``It's hard to say who fits on the offensive line.
That's the way it's going to be in this league. There'll be times
this season when things won't be perfect and you have to make
adjustments based on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what's best for the team. What's worked in our favor
is the versatility and flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are slowly getting their main offensive linemen
back. Armstrong played just one quarter, Williams played about a
quarter, and Scott got in some long snapping and some time at
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has said he may go with as few as eight offensive
linemen when the final 53-man roster is set by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   You would have to think that all five linemen who started in the
Tampa Bay game are locks: Armstrong, Andersen, Woody, Lane, and
rookie Greg Robinson-Randall, who has been a stalwart at right
tackle. Belichick also has spoken well of Derrick Fletcher, who had
been playing left guard and then switched to right tackle vs. Tampa
Bay. If you also give the nod to the comebacking Williams and
Scott, that gives you eight.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Rucci has been recovering from arthroscopic knee surgery
and is beginning to run, though he has yet to practice. Rucci was
the starter at right guard, but has he been replaced? Brent Warren
and Ryan Tujague were cut Monday, but still around are impressive
long snapper Loni Paxton, free agent guard Aaron Davis, and guard
Rob Gatrell. Because Scott can play guard and center, it would
appear that Paxton won't survive.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Gatrell could be put on the practice squad. Klemm, who
also is beginning to run after knee surgery, could be put on the
physically unable to perform list until Week 6 of the season and
wouldn't count against the roster. That goes for Rucci as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe wasn't sacked Sunday, which is a sign of progress, but
he was chased out of the pocket and ran for his life a time or two.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what his line looks like right now:
</P>
<P>
   LEFT TACKLE: Armstrong. Got his feet wet and held his own
against Steve White, the right end for Tampa Bay. He may play up to
a half Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT GUARD: Andersen. Versatility is his strength. Belichick
likes that. Moving him to center to snap in the shotgun formation
is unorthodox and funky. Coaches normally don't like unorthodox and
funky, particularly on the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER: Woody. He could be one of the better centers in the
league if he could only solve this problem with the shotgun. Some
scouts thought Woody would be a terrific guard as well as a center.
Maybe he'll move to guard, with Andersen playing center full time,
if the poor snapping continues.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT GUARD: Lane. Another versatile player. He started his
career as a right tackle but moved to left guard, then left tackle
earlier in the preseason, and now he's in Rucci's right guard spot.
He may be moved again before all is said and done.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT TACKLE: Robinson-Randall. He made his reputation shutting
down Courtney Brown in a Michigan State-Penn State game last
season. He hasn't been mistake-free in the preseason, but the
Patriots are strong in their conviction that they will come out of
the draft with a top lineman, and Randall appears to be it.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher looked strong at left guard while he was the starter.
The Patriots want him to be more versatile, which is why he's being
used as a tackle. He's also been used as a defensive tackle in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Versatility is the word Belichick often uses in describing his
linemen. But at some point he needs to use words like
``outstanding,'' ``terrific,'' and ``superb.'' He seems a long way
from using those superlatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
