<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-MUSIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY MUSIC THAT'S WORTHY OF SURVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Even real-life television must cut to commercials to pay the bills,
but the party of attrition doesn't have to end. Fill those spaces
with a little complementary theme music. Sure, Gloria Gaynor's ``I
Will Survive'' is a nice appetizer, and the ``Gilligan's Island''
theme is cute but obvious.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are a few other options for the host looking to enhance the
at-home island ritual:
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Jungle,'' Guns n' Roses _ A nice first break
just to get everyone into the spirit of Darwinism. The hair-metal
classic is the ``Survivor'' equivalent of Hank Williams Jr.'s
``Monday Night Football'' anthem. ``Are you ready for the Immunity
Challenge?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Tribes,'' Frankie Goes to Hollywood _ The 1984 new-wave
song was originally about the Cold War, but it might as well have
forecast the coming of ``Survivor.'' It also should remind people
that while the show's Tagi and Pagong tribes have now
disintegrated, alliances and loyalties are still precious and
fleeting among those remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naked Guy,'' Randy Newman _ David Letterman said it best a few
weeks ago: ``What's with that naked fat guy on `Survivor'?'' Thank
you for sharing, Richard.
</P>
<P>
   Anything by the '80s pop band Survivor _ The preference would be
the ``Rocky III'' anthem ``Eye of the Tiger,'' but ``Burning
Heart'' and ``The Moment of Truth'' would all work well and be just
as relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rats,'' Pearl Jam _ Ten years from now, will anyone remember
much about ``Survivor'' except that a bunch of people ate rodents
and only one of them got paid for it? Pearl Jam also has a song
called ``Bugs,'' should anyone care to reminisce about the creepy
crawlers living in the sores on Colleen's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord of the Flies,'' Iron Maiden _ A perfect bit of British
heavy metal tension to underscore the walk to the final tribal
council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torched,'' Michael Hedges _ Susan and Richard should probably
start learning the melody to this new-age obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye to You,'' Scandal _ Aside from being a great dance
riff, it's a great song to collect bets to when your party guests'
castaway gets dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC _ ``I've seen the future. I
can't afford it.'' So goes the opening lyric to this 1985 Euro-pop
hit. After Wednesday night, one contestant will crawl off of Pulau
Tiga never having to sing this tune again. How Regis missed this
for his game-show theme music one will never know, but it's an
ideal way to top off a ``Survivor'' celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winner Takes It All,'' ABBA _ A perfect dramatic slice of
fluff to play over the end credits. If the folks at ``Survivor''
piece together a retrospective clip package to end the show, it
would be even more effective cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Can't We Be Friends?,'' War _ A song of reconciliation
that should make a nice accompanying theme to the reunion special
following the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land Down Under,'' Men At Work _ Don't forget next season. A
reminder that next season ``Survivor'' will take place on the
Aussie Outback. &QL; 
X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
