<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-SURPLUS-BARTLETT     08-21 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SURPLUS-BARTLETT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLYING UP THE GORE SPENDING PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, Aug. 22, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By BRUCE BARTLETT    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the Clinton-Gore administration's
proudest economic accomplishment is achievement of a balanced
federal budget. Al Gore would like voters to see him as the
guardian of that legacy and of the budget surplus that has replaced
the deficits of the 1980s and early 1990s. Hence, in his campaign
statements, he makes much of his plans to use more of projected
future surpluses for paying down the national debt than would
George W. Bush. Gore also talks a great deal about the ``cost'' of
Bush's proposed tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a cost to Gore's new spending proposals. One
estimate, by the National Taxpayers Union, puts the dollar size of
Gore's new spending at more than $2 trillion over 10 years _ enough
to take up the entire non-Social Security surplus without anything
leftover for tax cuts. (Both candidates rule out spending the
portion of the surplus attributable to Social Security.) Even the
lowest estimates in the press put the figure at well over $1
trillion, with Gore's tax cuts reducing the surplus by an
additional $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore's initiatives are of a kind that could all too
easily lead to a return of deficits if the budget surpluses don't
materialize as planned. He makes more proposals than Bush for
entitlements _ programs that continue without annual
appropriations. Bush's $1.6 trillion tax cut would also be written
into law as continuing indefinitely. But history shows that
presidents and Congresses are more willing to raise taxes in the
event of a revenue shortfall than they are to cut entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Gore's and Bush's plans would reduce the surplus by
an equivalent amount, assuming that they both got their way with
Congress and kept all of their promises _ something that is of
course unlikely. Because presidents cannot enact programs on their
own, voters know they must look at the candidates' proposals not
only at face value, but also as an indication of their differing
philosophies of government. In this respect, there is a clear
difference between Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore clearly believes that government should direct and control
the use of the surplus that is not allocated to debt reduction,
whether on the tax side or the spending side. He would increase
government spending substantially more than Bush, would cut taxes
less, and would aim more of his tax cuts to specific taxpayer
behavior _ giving parents a tax credit to pay for their children's
after-school programs, for example. It is fair to characterize most
of Gore's proposed tax cuts as this kind of ``tax expenditures,''
little different substantively from direct spending, except that
they go through the tax code rather than the appropriations
process.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush would ``spend'' more of the surplus on
across-the-board tax cuts cuts. Moreover, most of his tax cuts, in
contrast to Gore's, would not depend on taxpayer behavior, but
would be given to all taxpayers in the form of tax rate reductions.
Cutting taxes allows taxpayers to keep more of their money, so that
they, rather than the government, is deciding how to apportion it.
Some may invest their tax savings, and some may spend it, but
either way it will be the taxpayer's decision, not the
government's.
</P>
<P>
   And since the economic stimulus from tax rate reductions is
greater than that from new spending or targeted tax cuts, the net
budgetary cost of Bush's proposals would likely be considerably
less than the gross figure Gore alludes to.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the cost of a presidential candidate's program cannot
be measured solely in terms of its impact on the budget. Many
initiatives could impose large costs on the private sector in the
form of regulations. In this area, too, Gore would seem the
costlier of the candidates. His plans regarding global warming and
health maintenance organizations, for example, would have
substantial costs for private businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whose program costs more is important, but the
``costs'' of federal policies go beyond direct revenue lost or
money spent. The effect on the economy as a whole (and with it,
future tax collections) can be profound, and that is where the deep
philosophical differences of Gore and Bush come seriously into
play.
</P>
<P>
   (Bruce Bartlett is a senior fellow with the National Center for
Policy Analysis.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
