<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8339 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      08-21 0206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, Aug. 22, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-LABOR (Seattle) _ The battle for the allegiance, and the
dues, of 20,000 Boeing Co. workers is intensifying between the
International Association of Machinists and the Society of
Professional Engineers in Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WAMU-BANKUNITED (Seattle) _ Washington Mutual Inc., looking to
make itself as much a major player in Texas banking as it is in
Washington and California, will buy a Houston-based company in a
$1.5 billion stock deal. Seattle-based Washington Mutual will
acquire Bank United Corp., the largest publicly traded Texas-based
financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Virgin. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIE-COLUMN (Seattle) _ On the blockbuster trade that sends
Patrick Ewing to the SuperSonics and Vin Baker to the Knicks, with
various other players from four teams involved as well.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
