<SLUG> BC-CABLETRON-INDUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLETRON ACQUIRES INDUS RIVER NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cabletron Systems Inc. bought little-known Indus River Networks
of Acton, Mass. Monday in a $170 million deal designed to round out
its largest division's product line before a planned public
offering in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron, based in Rochester, N.H., agreed to hand over 4.1
million of its own shares and roughly 1 percent of the convertible
stock in its division, Enterasys Networks, which it plans to spin
off in 2001 or 2002. The deal is based on Friday's closing price
for Cabletron shares, valuing them at $142.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Indus River is a privately held company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as these things go, it's about a middle-of-the-pack
deal,'' said Martin Pyykkonen, an analyst who follows Cabletron for
CIBC World Markets in San Francisco. ``Enterasys is just filling
out a product hole, buying a smaller company rather than taking the
time and money to fill it in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   Indus River makes virtual private network _ or VPN _ computer
hardware. That technology allows companies to securely share
information between a main corporate office and branch offices. It
also lets employees traveling outside the home office gain secure
access to the corporate network through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and their sprawling network of branch offices, for
example, are big clients of VPN systems.
</P>
<P>
   Enterasys develops routers and switches for VPNs and should
benefit from adding Indus River to the mix, Pyykkonen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Smartsearch router is Enterasys' flagship product, but it
would have had to outsource the rest of the VPN process or possibly
lose the business to a competitor,'' he said. ``Now, it will be
able to take VPN orders seamlessly as part of the overall
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Enterasys has 2,200 employees and accounted for about half of
Cabletron's $1.4 billion in sales last year. It reported
first-quarter revenue of $177.1 million, up 5 percent from the
quarter before.
</P>
<P>
   Indus River, tiny in contrast, has 60 employees and posted just
$2 million in sales a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In three rounds of financing, venture capitalists gave Indus
River $28 million in start-up capital between 1997 and 1999. The
MCI WorldCom Venture fund and Novell Inc. were among seven
investors that pledged the final $14 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Its new parent, Enterasys, is one of four units Cabletron formed
in February, reportedly to boost share prices in an effort to keep
pace with rival Cisco Systems Inc. Cabletron said it hopes to take
all four units public and spin them off within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron shares rose $1 after the announcement Monday, closing
at $35.75 on the New York Stock Exchange. Year to date, they have
risen 38 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
