<HEADLINE>
THE DORDOGNE IN THE SOUTH OF FRANCE INCLUDES DOORWAYS INTO
PREHISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (for release Sunday, Aug.  x ) 
(Eds: `Scotts Casles Holidays' in second section is correct)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
Dordogne's Caves
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q. I'd like to visit the prehistoric caves near Les
Eyzies-de-Tayac, France. Can you provide me with information on how
to get a guide? _ Lawrence W. Hitt, New York, N.Y. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. The caves and rock dwellings surrounding the town of Les
Eyzies-de-Tayac, in the Dordogne department, in southwestern
France, contain some outstanding prehistoric remains, many from the
Upper Paleolithic period, which began about 35,000 years ago.
During that period, early man made great strides in hunting,
tool-making and the drawing and carving of figures, especially
animals, which appear on the walls of many of the region's caves.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the sites are within 12 miles north and east of Les
Eyzies. The caves at Font-de-Gaume, Rouffignac and Bernifal are
known for their paintings of bison, horses and mammoths. There are
wall carvings at Combarelles, Bara-Bahau and St.-Cirq. Cap Blanc,
with its 15,000-year-old animal frieze, and Abri du Poisson, which
features the carving of a salmon, are also worth a stop, as is Abri
de Cro-Magnon and Le Moustier.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the sites varies, but is usually $5.60. Hours are
generally from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., closed on Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Tourist Office of Les Eyzies for details: (33 5)
53.06.97.05.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous cave in the area _ Lascaux, about 15
miles northeast of Les Eyzies _ is not open to the public, because
its carved and painted figures, dating from about 20,000 years ago,
are considered too delicate to withstand the carbon dioxide exhaled
by visitors. But you may visit Lascaux II, a faithful replica, some
200 yards from the original cave. Lascaux II is open every day
except Mondays from 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.; until 7 p.m. in July and
August. Admission is $7 ( at 7.17 francs to the dollar), $3.50 for
children under 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Tourist Office of Les Eyzies has a list of English-speaking
guides. A full day costs about $165, excluding entrance fees. Among
the guides are Desdemaine Hugon, (33-5) 53.07.26.04 and Bruno
Eluer, (33-5) 53.51.59.12. Both have their own cars.
</P>
<P>
   A four-hour guided canoe trip down the Vezere River for a
minimum of 15 people is available on Thursdays, Saturdays and
Sundays. The trips, which cost $27, are led by a guide from the
National Prehistoric Museum. Information: (33-5) 53.05.10.11.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, housed in a 16th-century chateau on a cliff
overlooking Les Eyzies, displays weapons, tools and sculptural
blocks. It is open from 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m., and until 7 p.m.
during the summer. Admission is $3; free for those under 18.
Information: (33-5) 53.06.45.45.
</P>
<P>
   STAYING IN A SCOTTISH CASTLE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. I'd like to find some agencies that offer accommodations in
Scottish castles. Can you help? _ Wendy Berilman, Milwaukee  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Scotts Castle Holidays represents several bed-and-breakfasts,
hotels and vacation rentals that are housed in castles. Among them
is Culcreuch Castle at Fintry, near Stirling. Built in 1296 and set
on 1,600 wooded acres, the hotel has 13 guest rooms and costs from
$90 to $114 a person for bed and breakfast. The 16th-century
Ballencrieff Castle at Aberlady, near Edinburgh, is a bed and
breakfast, with four guest rooms, starting at $102 per person.
Information: (44-131) 229 7111, fax (44-131) 229 1777, or visit
www.scottscastles.com.
</P>
<P>
   For groups of six or more, Loyd &AMP; Townsend-Rose represents 25
castles, most of them charging about $300 a person, including
breakfast, dinner and drinks. One of their properties, Myres
Castle, in Fife, is a 16th-century castle with nine guest rooms.
Another, the Tower of Lethendy, in Perthshire, built in 1570 with
additions in 1885, has seven bedrooms. Information: (44-1835) 870
706, www.ltr.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Among the properties managed by the National Trust of Scotland
is Brodick Castle on the Isle of Arran, with two apartments
available for rent, primarily on a weekly basis. Dating back to the
13th century, the castle overlooks Brodick Bay. Prices for an
apartment accommodating four people range from $568 a week to $680
during the summer; the cost is $680 and $833 for the larger
apartment, which sleep six.
</P>
<P>
   The East Wing Flat at the 16th-century Castle Fraser, 16 miles
west of Aberdeen, sleeps five and has a spiral stone staircase
leading to a small turret bedroom. The castle is set in extensive
grounds with formal gardens and trails. Prices range from $424 to
$545, depending on season. Information: (44-131) 243 9331;
www.nts.org.uk.
</P>
<P>
   TOURS OF BELIZE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. My wife and I would like to sign up for an educational tour
of Belize, if possible with a side trip to Tikal in Guatemala. Do
you have suggestions? _ Martin L. Tingay, Sarasota, Fla. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Smithsonian Study Tours is offering a nine-day tour called
Undiscovered Belize: Walks in the Land of the Maya starting Jan.
20. The tour includes treks in the tropical forests of the Maya
Mountains; a 6-mile hike along the Ixchel Tropical Research
Institute's Rainforest Medicine Trail; and snorkeling off South
Water Caye, an island on Belize's barrier reef that is home to
ospreys, green herons and frigate birds. You'll also visit several
Mayan sites, including Che Chem Hah, a ceremonial site on the upper
Macal River; Chumpiate Cave, where you climb wooden ladders to see
a secret, storehouse of Maya pottery, which has been left in its
original location; and, in the foothills of the Maya Mountains, the
Mayflower Archeological Reserve, a classical Mayan site, known for
its carved stele. The cost is $3,325 per person, double occupancy,
excluding air fare. Information: (877) 338-8687.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Audubon Society offers Belize, the Barrier
Reef and Tikal, an eight-day tour, half of which is spent aboard
the Panorama, a 44-passenger yacht. The trip includes a visit to
the Mayan sites of Caracol _ an ancient grouping of palaces, plazas
and pyramids in Belize that are still being recovered from the
jungle _ and Tikal, with its carved stele, ceremonial platforms and
temple pyramids, in Guatemala. The cruise departs from Belize City
on the third day of the tour, and visits several islands off
Belize's Caribbean coast, including Laughing Bird Cay, Half Moon
Cay and Goff's Cay. Snorkeling, bird-watching and a cruise up
Monkey River are among the highlights of the tour. Prices range
from $2,995 to $3,995 a person, double occupancy, excluding air
fare. Information: (800) 289-9504.
</P>
<P>
   &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
