<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a ECOM-DIVERSE-WEB-COMMUNI     08-21 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEB'S USER PROFILE UNDERGOES A BROAD TRANSFORMATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 ECOM-DIVERSE-WEB-COMMUNITY-NYTSF   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 By DAVID KIRBY  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For a long time, the image of the typical Internet user was a
heterosexual white male younger than 40. Although this
characterization was mostly true, the Web is now becoming a
thriving marketplace for a wider range of people.
</P>
<P>
   As the economic and political influence of Asian-Americans,
Hispanics, African-Americans and gay men and lesbians increases, so
does their presence on the Web. Technology is also allowing
millions of people with disabilities to go online. Not
surprisingly, a growing number of sites are serving these
communities as they contour the Web to their own needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian-American community is wired, with a full 69 percent of
Asian-American households connected to the Internet. This is
reflected in the many sites aimed at this community, including
www.aonline.com, a site focusing on culture and lifestyle for
Asian-Americans, produced by A Magazine. Another site,
www.Click2Asia.com, links to shopping, business and travel in the
United States, Japan, Taiwan and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   For the Hispanic market, the site www.zonafinanciera.com
provides banking, insurance, auto and real estate services in
English, Spanish and Portuguese in 21 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Hispanics are looking for convenient ways to send money
home, secure a loan for a family member in Latin America or buy
stock or property there,'' said Greg Keough, a co-founder of the
site.
</P>
<P>
   The site www.starmedia.com is a huge portal that includes
shopping in Spanish, travel services, news from the Americas,
classified advertising and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans are the fastest-growing group online. ``Blacks
are always on the tail end of technology, and we need to get on the
front end,'' said Harry Alford, the president and chief executive
of the National Black Chamber of Commerce. Its site,
www.nationalbcc.com, offers members discounts from major
corporations and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, like www.blackplanet.com, will soon offer college
databases, financial tools and technology classes, said Omar Wasow,
the executive director.
</P>
<P>
   For people with disabilities, the Internet offers perhaps the
greatest promise. With www.wemedia.com, ``for the first time, a
homebound individual can visit the grocery store, stop at the bank
and pick up a new shirt,'' said Mikki Lam, a senior vice president
of WEmedia Inc. The site also offers health assistance and
information about finances, education and sports.
</P>
<P>
   For gay men and lesbians, two large portals, www.gay.com and
www.planetout.com, offer chat, personal ads, shopping, information
on living with HIV, investment tools, news and links to gay-owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay commerce takes a different angle online,'' said Megan
Smith, Planetout's chief executive. ``We're a large community with
specific needs. It's a completely underserved market.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
