<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SUB-RECOVERY-BOS &LR;      08-21 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUB-RECOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERS OPEN HATCH, DISCOVER RUSSIAN SUB FLOODED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Norwegian deep-sea divers finally wrested open an
escape hatch on a sunken Russian nuclear submarine Monday only to
find that the badly damaged Kursk was completely flooded.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sign that any of the 118 crew had survived long
after the still-unexplained accident that sent the submarine to the
bottom of the Barents Sea, trapping the crew on board.
</P>
<P>
   Nine agonizing days after the submarine went down, the rescue
became a recovery. But first, it was time for Russia to grieve.
</P>
<P>
   In a somber broadcast, state television finally broadcast the
names of the crew, which had been withheld by the navy. Defense
Minister Igor Sergyev offered condolences to victims' families, and
acknowledged what his angry countrymen have been saying for days,
that the Russian rescue effort had been flawed.
</P>
<P>
   In the port city of Murmansk, home of the Northern Fleet where
the Kursk was based, relatives overcome with grief collapsed and
wailed as navy officials tried in vain to comfort them. And navy
officers rued the implicit humiliation of Russia's once great fleet
as Norwegian divers accomplished in one day what the Russian
rescuers were unable to do in a week.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, privately owned NTV television showed footage of the
Kursk going to sea, accompanied by the music of the late songwriter
Vladimir Vysotsky, ``Save Our Souls,'' a heartrending ballad about
the desperate last minutes on a dying submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian officials said the divers' grim discovery meant the
rescue operation would be abandoned, but that Russia had asked for
help in recovering the sailors' bodies. Russian television said one
body had already been found near an escape hatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military council of the Northern Fleet is deeply sorrowed
and offers its sympathy to the relatives of the dead,'' said a
statement from the fleet's commander, Admiral Vyacheslav Popov.
``The memory of our comrades in arms will live forever in our
hearts and in the history of the Russian navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Popov and other officials faced growing criticism of their
handling of the crisis after the head of the Norwegian team
complained of excessive Russian bureaucracy, and Russian
politicians accused the Northern Fleet of not properly assessing
the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian media and many ordinary people have criticized
Russian President Vladimir Putin for not responding more quickly to
the loss of the submarine on August 12. Russian officials did not
ackknowledge the disaster until August 14, and played down the
seriousness of the damage to the vessel. Putin, who chose not to
interrupt a vacation on the Black Sea, waited until last Wednesday
to speak about the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Kursk had sunk in the Black Sea, where would Putin have
spent his vacation?,'' chided the Moscow daily Moskovsky
Komsomolets in a banner headline. Indicating that the navy knew the
crew was doomed long ago, the paper reported that navy officials in
Northern Fleet headquarters on the Kola Penninsula had ordered 120
coffins last week, when spokesmen were still saying that the crew
could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Seleznyov, the speaker of the lower house of the Russian
parliament, said military leaders had dawdled in reporting the
disaster to Putin, wasting time that could have been spent rescuing
any surivors.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Sergeyev appeared to confirm that charge. He
said he had received word that the Kursk had missed a scheduled
communication with shore on the evening of August 12, but that he
waited 12 hours, until the morning of August 13, to inform Putin.
But Sergeyev put much of the blame for the failed rescue effort on
a lack of funding that left the navy short of divers and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NTV televsion reported that officers in Murmansk were
upset about their navy's performance, and that some of them were
ready to quit if Norwegian salvage workers, instead of Russians,
were given the task of raising the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   But officials indicated that there was no rush to raise the
Kursk. That task would be complicated by the presence of two
nuclear reactors, which have been shut down but are still
radioactive. Russian navy officials now say that the Kursk has
sustained so much damage _ one report compared the vessel to a body
that has fallen 20 stories, with multiple fractures in every bone _
that it might break up in an attempt to raise it.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say they want to raise the Kursk to determine
what happened to it. Until they know what caused the disaster, the
Russian navy has said other submarines of the Kursk's class will
not be sent to sea. Some have said that an explosion could have
occurred on board during a misfire of a new torpedo being tested,
setting off a larger blast as other ordnance exploded. Norwegian
seismic readings registered two blasts, the first smaller than the
second, late in the morning of August 12. But Igor Sergeyev,
Russia's defense minister, Monday said Russian monitors registered
three explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian officials are holding to the theory that the Kursk
was hit by a runaway torpedo of its own or by one fired by a
foreign submarine, possibly an American vessel, a theory that
Washington denies and no one in Moscow has been able to confirm.
Putin and President Clinton spoke at length by phone on Wednesday,
but both sides said the conversation was about the rescue effort.
Russia turned down US offers of help.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts here have suggested that military officials wanted
to avoid having the Kursk, one of Russia's most advanced subs,
examined by anyone from the West. The newspaper Moskovsky
Komsomolets went a step further, accusing the navy of making sure
that everyone on board died to cover up the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, what was the big secret they were trying to
hide?'' said the paper's defense analyst, Viktor Sokirko.
</P>
<P>
   Hope had been fading for the crew since Saturday, when a navy
admiral said most of the men on board were feared dead. On Sunday,
the Svir hospital ship, which had been set to treat survivors, was
moved into the Kursk's berth in Murmansk harbor, which people in
the port city called a bad omen. At a memorial service at a Russian
Orthodox Church in Murmansk on Sunday, the congregation prayed for
the sailors' souls _ not their survival.
</P>
<P>
   Some names of the victims are still unknown _ for example, the
senior Northern Fleet staff officers and admirals who, analysts
say, must have been on the Kursk to help direct the fleet exercises
in which it was taking part.
</P>
<P>
   The navy has provided relatives with food and a place to stay at
the naval base. Monday, a spokesman said a few psychotherapists
would be brought in to counsel family members. The government also
announced it would provide aid to family members travelling to
Murmansk from around Russia. Until now, most relatives have had to
travel at their own expense.
</P>
<P>
   Family members appeared bitter at the government's response.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've said nothing, except for Putin's statement, and what
good did that do, our sons are still down there,'' Vladimir
Bryazhin, whose son is aboard the Kursk, told NTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably be tears for two or three days, there will
probably be great distress, it will probably be difficult,'' said
Vladimir Navrotsky, chief spokesman of the Northern Fleet, at a
news conference Monday. ``And then they will probably start getting
back to normal . . . and will probably leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway offered to send a robot camera into the submarine to film
the wreck for details that might help future efforts to recover the
bodies or salvage the vessel. A spokesman for Stolt Offshore, the
company that provided the divers, said to send divers in safely,
salvage teams would have to cut a larger entrance, which could be
cause for concern on a badly damaged vessel with nuclear reactors
on board.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is whether the Russian military would allow
foreign divers to go in a submarine filled with what Moscow
considers top-secret technology.
</P>
<P>
   If the robot camera is used, said Norwegian military spokesman
Lieutenant Colonel John Espen Lien, ``We will hand the video to the
Russian authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report)
</P>
</TEXT>
