<HEADER>
A8362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ANTIGENICS-AQUILA-BOS     08-21 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIGENICS-AQUILA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIGENICS TO ACQUIRE AQUILA BIOPHARMACEUTICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antigenics Inc., a biotechnology company specializing in
personalized cancer ``vaccines,'' has agreed to acquire Aquila
Biopharmaceuticals Inc. for about $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Antigenics will pay $4.67 for each of Aquila's roughly 8.5
million outstanding shares, a 5 percent premium over the stock's
closing price Monday of $4.4375 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Aquila strengthens Antigenics's foothold in the
field of infectious diseases and complements its efforts to fight
cancer, the parties said.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila, a Framingham, Mass. company, develops products to boost
the body's immune response. It is testing more than a dozen drugs
to fight infectious and degenerative diseases and some cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our combined technologies will allow us to use many, many
tools in the process of combatting these diseases that have not
been dealt with well traditionally,'' said Garo H. Armen, the
Antigenics chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Antigenics is based in New York but has a biomanufacturing and
research operation in Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The company's lead cancer product is in late-stage clinical
trials for the treatment of renal cell carcinoma. It also has drugs
in earlier stages of testing for other forms of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, expected to be completed in the fourth quarter
of this year, brings with it Aquila's partnerships with some of the
world's leading pharmaceutical companies, including SmithKline
Beecham, Elan Corp. and Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. The deal has been
approved by the boards of both companies but is subject to
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Taunton-Rigby, president and chief executive of Aquila,
said the company has long been undervalued by Wall Street. She
thinks merging with a larger company will bring it the attention it
needs to advance its research and drug development efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combined company will be one of the powerhouses of the
whole field,'' she said. ``I think it will be good for both our
shareholders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
