<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSLIM-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIAS PANEL UPHOLDS $300,000 AWARD TO MUSLIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a significant ruling on religious freedom in the
workplace, the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination has
upheld a 1996 decision awarding $300,000 to a Muslim man who was
forced to stop praying at work.
</P>
<P>
   Lule Said of Quincy quit his job as a security guard for
Northeast Security Inc. of Brookline in 1991 after he said he was
ridiculed and harassed by fellow employees, one of whom trampled on
his prayer rug and kicked it into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Said, who then lived in Boston, was also ordered by company
management not to pray during his 16-hour work shifts, even though
Muslims are required to pray five times per day.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's work force has become more diverse, disputes
over religious liberty on the job have increased 15 percent to 20
percent in the past five years, according to the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, the federal agency charged with
investigating bias.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Muslims, one of the country's fastest-growing
religious groups, have filed numerous complaints in the courts and
with government anti-bias agencies against employers for failing to
accommodate their practices.
</P>
<P>
   In Said's case, Northeast Security had appealed the 1996 ruling
by Commissioner Charles E. Walker to the full three-member
commission. The commission asked Walker to review the damage award
and to consider a 1997 state law requiring employers to accommodate
the religious beliefs of employees. A new hearing was held April
26.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling issued on Aug. 14, Walker upheld his original
findings but allocated the award differently. He reduced damages
for emotional distress caused by harassment and a ``hostile work
environment'' from $300,000 to $250,000, but ordered the company to
pay $50,000 in new damages for failing to accommodate Said's
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case uniquely demonstrates . . . the debilitating impact
discrimination has on an individual's well-being,'' including a
decline in self-worth, Walker wrote in his decision. ``The
resulting fear and demoralization of the employee, who is singled
out, ridiculed, harassed, and ostracized . . . is exacerbated by
management's complicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Brown, the attorney who represented Northeast Security
Inc., said he was disappointed by Walker's latest ruling and said
he had filed papers to appeal it again to the full commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client is distressed by this ruling, which we think is
wrong legally and factually,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Said, a native of Somalia, was a student at Boston University
when he began working as a security guard in 1991, pulling two
16-hour shifts and one 8-hour shift at Franciscan Childrens'
Hospital in Brighton.
</P>
<P>
   As a practicing Muslim, he routinely prayed five times daily for
three to five minutes, facing the Islamic holy city of Mecca.
According to his complaint, Said used a dressing room behind the
hospital's security desk to pray three times during his 16-hour
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint allleged that another Northeast security guard
threatened him and made disparaging remarks about Said's Somali
origin and religion, saying he hated Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   After the co-worker wiped his feet on Said's prayer rug and
kicked it into a corner, Said complained to his supervisor but the
coworker continued to harass him, according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Said, who said the company did nothing to stop the harassment,
was told by the supervisor to stop praying or quit his job. He
ultimately agreed to give up his prayers because he was afraid to
lose his job. Nevertheless, he was demoted to a part-time position,
the complaint stated.
</P>
<P>
   Said, who could not be reached for comment Monday, quit
Northeast and went to work as an accounts manager at State Street
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, in his ruling, said that the religious accommodation
Said requested _ three five-minute breaks to pray during a 16-hour
shift _ was ``reasonable and not overly burdensome'' on Northeast
Security.
</P>
<P>
   He also found that the company failed to meet Said's second
request, ``to be free from unlawful harassment and the elimination
of the religion-based hostile environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker also said that Said, who now lives in Quincy, was
entitled to damages as a result of ``irreverent insults to his
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Welensky, the Boston attorney who represented Said in his
case before the MCAD, called the ruling ``excellent, right on the
money.'' He also said he hoped the ruling would increase awareness
of the need to respect people's faith traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in this country don't understand what Islamic
practice means to most Muslims,'' he said. ``For my client, it was
really the single most important thing in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``bullying'' by fellow workers was bad enough, Welensky
said, but was ``made worse by the employer's failure to take any
corrective action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
