<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-CO     08-21 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Cousin Bubba strikes again
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I was all set to go to the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles last week, but had to cancel at the last
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on my cousin Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   He's the one who hit me in the eye with a rock.
</P>
<P>
   We were playing on a dirt road between his house and mine. I
don't know how we came up with the particular game, but the idea
was to see how close we could throw at one another without actually
hitting each other.
</P>
<P>
   This may have been the only chunking contest I ever won against
Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   I was bending over, in the process of selecting a choice stone.
It was when I looked up that I spied exactly what I was looking
for, a smooth river rock perfect for throwing.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, that's exactly what Bubba had done with it -- threw
it in my direction.
</P>
<P>
   I raised my head just in time to see it coming but too late to
dodge. It smacked me directly in my left eye.
</P>
<P>
   I saw stars. I was stunned. For a moment I didn't know what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw Bubba screaming bloody murder and running toward my
house, and I knew exactly what to do.
</P>
<P>
   I started screaming bloody murder and running after Bubba toward
the house.
</P>
<P>
   My mother met us at the back door. Bubba was crying, saying he
didn't mean to do it. I was crying, saying Bubba was the one who
did it.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba was sent home. I was taken to the doctor. The eye was
throbbing something awful, but otherwise seemed to have suffered no
permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   So the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   But to be on the safe side, he tested my eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   I just knew I was going to be blind in one eye. I was half
right. It turned out I was about half blind in both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The eye test showed I was nearsighted, same as my daddy. That's
when I had to start wearing glasses.
</P>
<P>
   I was in the sixth grade. Things have never been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   I was the only kid in the class with glasses. At first, the
other students treated me with great sympathy, as if I had suffered
some terrible tragedy, almost on a par with the loss of a parent.
</P>
<P>
   I remember one of the pretty girls said she liked the way I
looked in glasses. Funny what you don't forget.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, too, it wasn't until recess that I heard, for the
first time, ``four eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   My cousin Bubba never called me four eyes. My cousin Bubba never
got over feeling that it was somehow his fault that I wear glasses.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason -- I never let him.
</P>
<P>
   My left eye has always been my bad eye.
</P>
<P>
   When I had to have cataract surgery several years ago, it was
because of the left eye.
</P>
<P>
   And when I couldn't go to the Democratic convention in Los
Angeles last week, it was because I had a bad case of the pink eye.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask me in which eye.
</P>
<P>
   Ask my cousin Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
