<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-0822-COX     08-21 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, BUOYED BY POLLS, PUSHES BUSH ON DEBATES, TAX PROPOSALS
 &HT;    650&AMP;adds
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANNIBAL, Mo. _ Vice President Al Gore's campaign riverboat
arrived in Mark Twain's boyhood home Monday night, completing a
400-mile trip down the Mississippi River and demonstrating that
news of the death of Gore's White House bid has been greatly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The Mark Twain riverboat, named after the 19th century author of
``Huckleberry Finn'' and ``Tom Sawyer,'' pulled into this village
on the banks of the Mississippi for a climactic but rain-soaked
rally in which the vice president promoted his tax cut proposals,
targeted to middle class families.
</P>
<P>
   Gore cautioned against ``going back to the old ways of the
past'' _ of tax cuts for the wealthy that he said contributed to
record budget deficits in the 1980s and early 1990s. ``We need to
do the right thing for our kids,'' he said, promising tax relief
``to the people who need it the most.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of Gore's four-day trip with running mate Joe Lieberman
and their wives coincided with:
</P>
<P>
   _ Yet another round of polls showing Gore having closed the gap
with Texas Gov. George W. Bush, his Republican rival for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   _ A suggestion from Gore that Bush is ``procrastinating'' in
accepting the three debates organized by the bipartisan Commission
on Presidential Debates, possibly in order to avoid them
altogether. Bush communications director Karen P. Hughes said the
governor was simply giving himself time to consider more than 40
debate invitations from an array of potential sponsors. ``Governor
Bush is committed to debating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ A complaint from Gore that Bush is trying to ``conceal'' the
details of his plan to privatize a portion of Social Security in
order to avoid any political fallout before the election.
</P>
<P>
   _ A response from the Gore campaign to Bush's charge that U.S.
military forces are ``in decline'' as a result of Clinton
administration policies: Bush's proposed tax cuts would drain money
from a Pentagon budget that has been increasing gradually since
Bill Clinton took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS poll of 954 registered voters over the weekend following
the Democratic national convention had Gore at 45 percent, Bush at
44 percent. A similar poll after the Republican convention gave
Bush 50 percent and Gore 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll had a margin of error of 3 points, meaning the horse
race between Gore and Bush is a statistical dead heat as the two
head toward Labor Day, the traditional beginning of the fall
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Post-convention polls by Newsweek and CNN/USA Today/Gallup
showed similar gains for Gore in the days immediately after his
acceptance of the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters traveling with him aboard the riverboat
Monday that he suspected his rise in the polls is due to the
public's response to his acceptance speech. ``It wasn't negative
and it focused on the issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's voyage down the Mississippi since accepting his party's
nomination in Los Angeles last week has generated a lot of
excitement, something his White House bid has rarely seen this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge now is to sustain what former President George
Bush, the father of Gore's Republican rival, used to call ``the big
mo'' _ the momentum every successful presidential candidate must
catch at some point in their campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign strategists believe the voters are eager for a
discussion of the bread-and-butter issues that the vice president
has talked about in detail throughout the riverboat trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is talking about issues that affect the lives of
working families, and we believe it's going to have some shelf
life,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said. ``Governor Bush's
approach is cotton candy _ it tastes good but lacks substance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOW)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore has had ``the big mo'' before, only to lose it.
</P>
<P>
   After forcefully driving Bill Bradley out of the Democratic
primaries last spring, Gore saw Bush gradually pull ahead in the
White House contest by successfully marketing a limited number of
ideas: cutting federal income taxes, privatizing Social Security
and making public education more accountable with competition
through vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore countered with long laundry lists of initiatives and
aggressively attacked the record Bush had compiled in six years as
governor of Texas. But his strategy backfired: It reinforced
voters's negative views of Gore as a politician who is willing to
do and say anything to get elected.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged as much to reporters shortly after sunrise
Monday on the Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his harsh sounding criticism of Bush earlier this
summer hurt him politically, Gore said, ``Yeah, I think it probably
did.'' Asked why, he replied, ``Because I think people want a
really undiluted focus on the issues. That's what I'm going to give
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the reaction he's gotten from the crowds at his
rallies along the Mississippi River the last four days indicated to
him that ``the risk I took in talking about specifics has paid off
because people appreciate the effort to lift the tone of the
campaign to substance and not just soundbites.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with a laugh, he added, ``Although that in itself is a
soundbite.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the status of the scheduled debates with Bush, Gore
said the alternative proposals advanced by the GOP nominee's
campaign for debates sponsored by other organizations rather than
the debate commission were puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent ... apparently wants to see if he can get away
with some Sunday morning talk show when nobody is watching much and
substituting that for what the American people have a right to
expect, namely, one-on-one debates in prime time when everybody can
hear a good detailed discussion of the issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports the commission's plan to limit the debates to the
Democratic and Republican nominees and any third party candidate
who has at least 15 percent in the major polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he would want to duck that,'' Gore said. ``I
hope that he will reconsider it. I think, actually, that in the end
he'll have to reconsider it. He can save everybody a lot of time by
just going ahead and saying yes, he'll accept the commission
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters asked whether Bush is trying to duck him, the
vice president replied, with an audible sigh, ``I'm not going to
use that word. `` Pressed, he laughingly said, ``I think he's
procrastinating and that he's just taking longer than is necessary
to come to what will soon look like an obvious conclusion _ that
the American people do indeed have a right to prime time
commission-sponsored debates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When reporters suggested to Gore that Bush may not have provided
enough specifics about his major proposals to make a debate
worthwhile, he suggested in turn that his rival is deliberately
avoiding such details in order to forestall any political
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   As a prime example, he cited Bush's proposal to allow Americans
to invest a portion of their Social Security in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who proposed a major privatization of Social Security
in an approach that appears to have a $1 trillion price tag over
the next 10 years is, I think, going to have a hard time making it
to Election Day with the statement that no details will be given
until after the election,'' he said. ``The option of concealing it,
or trying to conceal it until after the election, I expect, will
turn out to be difficult for them to pull off.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also criticized Bush's proposal for a sweeping cut in
federal income taxes, contending that for every $10 it would give
wealthy families, it would provide middle class wage earners a dime
and low income families a penny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that people begrudge tax cuts for the wealthy,'' he
said. ``It's just that it's not fair to put our economy back into
deficits after we worked so hard to balance the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Bush's speech to the VFW convention in Milwaukee
on Monday, in which Bush said the U.S. military is in decline,''
Gore running mate Joe Lieberman offered a rival view.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a senator from Connecticut, told rallies here and
earlier in Quincy, Ill., that Gore has spent his eight years as
vice president ``fighting to keep America's military and make it,
frankly, the best-equipped, best-trained, most powerful fighting
force in the history of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign also issued a press release noting that this
year the administration signed a 4.8 percent military pay hike, the
largest in 20 years, and suggesting that Bush's tax cuts would cut
into the Pentagon's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gore spokesman Lehane: ``Bush talks tough, but he doesn't
have a real plan to keep our military strong. By using up the
entire surplus on a tax cut for the rich, he leaves nothing to
invest in military pay or readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a member of the VFW by virtue of his service in Vietnam,
is scheduled to address the organization Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
