<SLUG> BC-TECH-TV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZDTV RENAMING ITSELF TO TECHTV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ ZDTV, sold to Paul Allen's Vulcan Ventures
investment company last year, is shedding the last vestiges of its
Ziff-Davis heritage and going mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based cable channel, founded in 1998 as part
of the Framingham, Mass.-based Ziff-Davis Inc. media empire, Monday
said it is renaming itself Techtv.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ZD part of our name was no longer appropriate, since
Ziff-Davis no longer owns us,'' said Larry Wangberg, the channel's
chief executive. ``We wanted a more descriptive, more intuitive
name, and we think we've found it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the name change, the channel is positioning its
programs for a wider audience yearning to live the ``digital
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove that it's not just for dweebs anymore, Techtv will add
shows such as Cybercrime (a techie version of the ``Cops''
television show), Internet Tonight (featuring Entertainment
Tonight-style programming), AudioFile (for digital music lovers)
and Money Machine (how to invest in technology stocks).
</P>
<P>
   Within a year-and-a-half, the channel will offer nine hours of
original programming a day, up from the current six hours, said Joe
Gillespie, Techtv's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be to technology what MTV is to music,'' said
Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   About 19 million households have access to Techtv through cable
or satellite television. It is also broadcast over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To help the channel reach more viewers, Techtv is forging deals
with Time Warner Cable, AT&AMP;T, and Charter Communications. Wangberg
estimates those relationships will add 4 million viewers by the end
of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
