<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LONGTERM-CAPITAL-MARK     08-21 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGTERM-CAPITAL-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE FUND MANAGERS APOLOGIZE AND TRY AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Meriwether is ready to apologize, but not ready to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, high-risk strategies drove his hedge fund empire,
Long-Term Capital, to the brink of collapse and unsettled world
financial markets. Now Meriwether, 52, is struggling to raise money
for a new fund and making an attempt to repair his reputation by
apologizing for failed strategies. In interviews appearing Monday
in The Wall Street Journal and The Financial Times, Meriwether
conceded that his strategy had not worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole approach was fundamentally flawed,'' Meriwether was
quoted as saying in the Journal. ``I feel enormous remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rosenfeld, one of his past and current partners, said
Monday, ``I wish we had recognized the faults.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why they were speaking out now, Rosenfeld said:
``Frankly, we thought it might be a good time to tell our story _
one that we have been telling a long time to investors. It's a
point where everything has been taken care of with Long-Term and
everyone paid off. Our new attitude is being more open.''
</P>
<P>
   The public contrition, after two years of mostly silence, comes
a few weeks before the publication of a new book about Long-Term
Capital by Roger Lowenstein, a journalist, titled ``When Genius
Failed: The Rise and Fall of Long-Term Capital Management.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital, with several Wall Street legends and two
Nobel laureates among its advisers, had $7.5 billion in assets in
1997. But bets on the direction of global bond prices went against
them, draining $4 billion from the fund in nine months in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling of Long-Term was spurred in part by Russia's
default on its debt payments, and by the fund's heavy use of
leverage, or borrowed money, which accelerated the fund's troubles.
Ultimately, it took a consortium of 14 Wall Street firms to bail
out the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein describes how Meriwether and his partners wrangled
with the Wall Street firms trying to rescue Long-Term Capital and
how the partners, ``motivated by insatiable greed,'' ultimately
lost the bulk of their personal fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein's book follows another, ``Inventing Money: The Story
of Long-Term Capital Management and the Legends Behind it,'' by
Nicholas Dunbar, which came out earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stavis, one of Meriwether's successors as head of Salomon
Brothers' arbitrage group and an investor in the fund, said, ``It's
been an interesting question why they haven't said anything for two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Meriwether and Rosenfeld, and several other partners, are
operating as JWM Partners from Long-Term Capital's old offices in
Greenwich, Conn. The Relative Value Opportunity Portfolio, as the
new fund is called, is billed as a conservative version of the
former fund.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative, of course, is in the eye of the beholder. The
fund's managers say they will use less leverage, borrowing about
$10 for every $1 invested, as opposed to the nearly $30 to $1
leverage that Long-Term Capital sometimes reached. The new fund
also aims for returns of 15 percent a year, half the 30 percent a
year sought by Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The firm says it has raised $350 million to $400 million since
its inception last December, well short of the $1 billion it would
like. Institutional investors, some of whom were burned by
Long-Term Capital, have largely stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he's the poster child for all that's perceived
wrong with hedge funds _ volatility, risk, exposure,'' said Barry
Colvin, chief operating officer for Tremont Advisors, a consulting
firm for the hedge fund industry, referring to Meriwether.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very hard allocation for anybody to make. If you're
right, you're eking out 15 percent to 20 percent returns. If you're
wrong, how stupid are you? There's a whole lot of downside.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that Meriwether and Rosenfeld have raised several hundred
million dollars at all is testament to either faith or folly. Many
of the investors are former associates of Meriwether from the days
when he ran the bond arbitrage group at Salomon Bros., now a unit
of Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them real money because I believe in what they're
doing,'' said Stavis, now a partner at the venture capital firm
Bessemer Venture Partners. He believes there might be more
opportunity for their strategies now that other firms as well as
Long-Term have abandoned it. Basically, the new fund, like
Long-Term, makes sophisticated bets mostly on the convergence of
the yields of similar bonds around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld said that the Long-Term partners believed that they
were well diversified because they were using different strategies
in different markets around the world, but realized too late that
``there was a thread that ran through all of these trades,''
namely, that during a market crisis too many investors fled from
positions they viewed as illiquid, regardless of their relative
value.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there is still some confidence. JWM charges a higher
fee than the normal 1 percent flat fee and 20 percent performance
fee charged by most hedge funds. JWM, like Long-Term, charges a 2
percent annual fee and a performance fee of 20 percent of profits.
Since its beginning in December, the fund is up about 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite modest returns so far, a July letter to investors said,
``All in all, the prospects for our style of market neutral,
relative value investing remain attractive going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the steep losses at Long-Term Capital, ``We're not blaming
the markets,'' Rosenfeld said. ``Markets do what they do. In
hindsight, we missed this, and we're paid not to miss these
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
