<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LONDON-FRANKFURT-EXCH     08-21 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-FRANKFURT-EXCHANGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSTACLES TO LONDON-FRANKFURT EXCHANGE MERGER STILL REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  By ALAN COWELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Only weeks before shareholders vote on a planned merger
of the London and Frankfurt stock exchanges, British and German
regulators said on Monday that the two bourses had not yet devised
adequate rules to guarantee the financial transparency of what
would be Europe's dominant, transnational stock market by far.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual joint comment by Britain's Financial Services
Authority and Germany's Federal Securities Trading Security
Authority seemed to add to the questions piling up around the
merger, according to British traders who had already questioned the
framework of the proposed new exchange. Many have been skeptical
since reading the initial agreement, which was vaguely worded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a preliminary document saying here are some of the issues
which we need to work out,'' said Brian Mairs, a spokesman for the
Association of Private Client Stock Brokers and Investment
Managers, the representative body of British private client
brokers, who control about one-third of the shares in the London
Stock Exchange. ``It's evidently not enough to sort out all the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Mairs, said, some assurances from the regulators were
encouraging. ``The more transparency the better; we're very
pleased,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The London shareholders are set to vote on Sept. 14 to approve
or reject the merger. Approval needs a 75 percent majority.
</P>
<P>
   In their seven-page document released on Monday, the British and
German supervisory authorities singled out the marked differences
in both the legal and practical approaches to disclosure on the
London and Frankfurt exchanges, which mean, for instance, that
start-ups in Germany face different listing requirements on
Germany's Neue Markt than on Britain's Alternative Investment
Market. Additionally, most large trades in Britain must be reported
to the exchange immediately while many large trades in Frankfurt
are not subject to the same requirement, according to British
traders.
</P>
<P>
   The British and German regulators said, however, in the merged
exchange, all trades would be reported to both regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the proposed merger, London would handle
mostly blue-chip transactions while start-ups and high-growth
company stocks would be concentrated in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authorities note that the legal and regulatory
requirements governing the scope and level of their transparency
arrangements needs further consideration in consultation with
market participants,'' the document said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the regulators had commented publicly on
the planned merger, announced last May. The merger is part of a
Europe-wide scramble for alliances as traditional exchanges are
challenged both by Internet-based electronic trading systems and by
investors' demands for a single bourse that reflects the growing
perception of Europe as a single market. The new, merged exchange
is to be called iX, for international exchange, with corporate
headquarters in London.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' statement said: ``The development of iX needs to
take full account of requirements of market integrity _ in
particular the prevention of insider dealing and market abuse _ and
of market transparency and the protection of investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Davies, the chairman of Britain's Financial Services
authority watchdog, also said the ``overriding objective'' of
British and German regulators was ``to ensure that iX's proposals
take full account of our requirements for market integrity,
investor protection and the prevention of market abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined exchange would far outstrip other European
exchanges with a combined market value of $4.3 trillion, making it
the world's fourth largest after the New York Stock Exchange, the
Nasdaq and the Tokyo stock exchange. Plans for a separate European
transnational exchange, called Euronext, would group the Paris,
Amsterdam and Brussels bourses, trading stocks with a market value
of about $2.2 trillion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
