<SLUG> BC-DOGFISH-BAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGFISH CATCH CURTAILED ALONG EASTERN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fishermen from Maine to Florida will be prohibited for
at least six months from catching the spiny dogfish that millions
of Britons munch in fish and chips _ a move that probably signals
the implementation of a strict quota system for the overfished
shark.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision by the Atlantic States Marine Fisheries
Commission was more symbolic than hard-hitting because most
fishermen have already caught their quota of dogfish this year.
Commission members, however, said their vote Monday sent a message
that yet another fishing stock is quickly declining and in need of
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   But for Massachusetts, which allows fishermen to catch 11 times
the federal dogfish quota within the 3 nautical miles from the
coast that make up state waters, the move could severely damage its
prominence as the nation's largest dogfish hauler.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts joined in the commission vote Monday, in large
part because the state's quota was met last week. But state
officials and fishermen say there are plenty of dogfish and they do
not support stricter quotas on their catch. Some want to allow
fishermen to haul in even more of the shark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closing our fishery this Friday,'' said David Pierce,
acting assistant director for the state Division of Marine
Fisheries and a commission member. ``But this is the one species
where there is just a great difference of opinion over what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The spiny dogfish, which can grow three feet in length, were for
years disdained by fisherman because they clogged nets meant to
catch precious cod or other fish considered more valuable. But the
``trash fish'' gained new popularity in the last 10 years as other
fisheries were depleted. Now, dogfish are heavily fished in state
waters and often make up the majority of fish hauled into seacoast
towns like Scituate.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 55 percent of the 49 million pounds of dogfish landed in
the United States comes from Massachusetts. There are three
processing plants in the state, and in Plymouth, spiny dogfish
account for 96 percent of all fish landings.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic States commission's decision takes effect in
mid-October and will carry through to the end of April 2001. The
commission plans to meet in February to start hashing out how many
dogfish will be caught in the future. Such a plan could take a year
or more to develop. The commission sets fishing practices in state
waters.
</P>
<P>
   While an outright ban is unlikely, the commission has usually
followed closely what the federal government imposes in its waters.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists were quick to praise the commission, but said
a management plan that protects the fish needs to be developed
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a temporary plan,'' said Sonja Fordham, Fisheries
Project Manager for the Center for Marine Conservation. ``If we
don't act quickly, this will be a huge, shameful waste.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
