<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-HNS &LR;      08-21 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. PLANS TO RELIEVE AIR TRAFFIC CONGESTION IN THE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to reduce airline travel delays,
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater announced Monday that the
federal government will ease takeoff and landing rules in the
eastern United States by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said the goal is to ease the air traffic flow at ``choke
points,'' the nation's most congested air spaces, which are located
over a triangle bounded by Boston, Washington, D.C. and Chicago. A
major choke point in that triangle is the space over the
metropolitan New York City area.
</P>
<P>
   The government plans to improve the traffic flow to and from
those congested corridors in part by allowing pilots to fly at
lower altitudes. Airlines historically have resisted lower flight
paths because jets flying in them are less efficient and burn up
more fuel. But the government is asking the airlines to cooperate
in order to cut congestion on these flight paths in time for the
Thanksgiving holiday rush.
</P>
<P>
   Slater announced the plan at a news conference after discussing
travel problems with airline, airport and labor representatives. He
called the meeting ``a necessary first step in resolving some
</P>
<P>
   of the challenges'' faced by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   He also said his department will create a task force to monitor
airline service and report its findings to him within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   June was the worst month ever for flight delays, according to
the Federal Aviation Administration. In that month alone, there
were nearly 50,000 delays of 15 minutes or more. Delays were 18
percent lower in June 1999 and 58 percent lower in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Slater blamed bad weather for part of the problem. He said June
had 19 severe weather days, 12 of which were consecutive. June of
1999 had five such days, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   This spring generally had a higher number of delays. The FAA
tally of delays for April through June is 6 percent higher than for
the same period last year and 37 percent higher than for the same
period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transportation Association, which represents airlines,
has said another factor in the delays is an aging air traffic
control system.
</P>
<P>
   But the FAA and air traffic controllers have said the airlines
may be scheduling too many flights. Citing the growth in the number
of flights, the agency said there were 22,000 flights daily in the
United States last year, about a quarter more than in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said Monday that the aviation system is nearing full
capacity, and that ``we are beginning to tax the system.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
