<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FIRES-THINNING-1020(2     08-21 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-THINNING-1020(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS CONSIDER THINNING SMALL TREES TO HELP STOP BIG FIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Mont., Idaho, Wash.)   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ In a major new foray into wildfire
prevention, the Clinton administration will try to put into broad
effect an experimental effort under way here that is intended to
leave public lands far less prone to the kind of blazes that have
scorched millions of acres of Western forests this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The approach contemplated would aim to reduce future dangers by
thinning small trees from forests and leaving the largest, most
fire-resistant ones. One draft, being circulated by the Forest
Service as enormous fires in Montana and other states continue to
burn, calls for thinning, over 15 years, most or all of the 40
million acres of national forest now deemed at high risk of
catastrophic fire.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated cost of the plan would total $825 million a year,
said an administration official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been criticized in recent days by
conservatives for not doing more sooner to combat the fire threat
in the West through emergency logging measures advocated by the
timber industry.
</P>
<P>
   At least a partial version of that approach could be made public
as early as next month, when Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman are due to report to President
Clinton with a reassessment prompted by the current fire season,
which is on track to become the most devastating in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have declined to say specifically what
may be in the works but they have clearly signaled an intention to
expand significantly the kinds of thinning efforts already under
way here. They expressed open admiration for the experiment being
attempted in the dense Ponderosa pine forests outside Flagstaff,
where a broad coalition of government, industry and environmental
leaders has joined forces behind a costly approach that involves
the removal of many small trees while larger, more commercially
valuable trees are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need to scale this up to a significant level,''
Babbitt said in an interview when asked about the Flagstaff plan,
which was initiated in 1998 with federal support but is so far
being carried out on a very small scale.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have dismissed criticisms of inaction
as politically motivated, but they appear now to be moving toward
adoption of a Flagstaff-style alternative in the hope that it may
prove acceptable to the timber industry and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of the plan's promise, its architects point to what
did and did not happen in June, when one of this year's big blazes,
known as the Pumpkin fire, swept through dense stands of Ponderosa
pine in a section of the Kaibab National Forest not far from this
mountain town.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the experiment, a stand of Ponderosa pines had
previously been thinned to about 10 percent of its former density,
with the largest and most fire-resistant trees among those that
were left behind. And as the architects had hoped, that small
island was mostly spared as flames that had been leaping
uncontrollably from treetop to treetop dropped to ground level as
they reached the test zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have seen from results that are on the ground, if
we can reduce the density of trees, we can have a better chance of
controlling the wildfires,'' said Jim Golden, a forest supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as it has unfolded here, the Flagstaff initiative has
illustrated the formidable hurdles that may yet lie in the way of a
plan that has yet to satisfy fully either side in a bitter debate
and would require that a formula be found to make possible the
harvest of unprecedented quantities of low-quality wood.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the most powerful opponents include environmental groups
that regard the effort as little more than a veil for commercial
logging efforts, which they say should have no place in national
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Though a broad coalition assembled in support of the plan
includes a number of environmental groups, among them the Nature
Conservancy and the Grand Canyon Trust, the opponents have
succeeded in preventing the initiative from being carried out on
anything more than a tiny scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly oppose the project as it now stands and will
litigate again to stop it,'' said Bryan Bird, executive director of
the Forest Conservation Council of Santa Fe, N.M., one of several
organizations that are seeking to block the next step in the plan.
That step would widen the experiment zone from 300 to more than
5,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt, fire experts say, that most Western forests
have become dangerously overgrown, and thinning them could reduce
the risk of a repeat of the current fire season.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, federal officials said that the total amount of land
burned by wildfires this year was already well in excess of 5
million acres, with many blazes in hard-hit states like Montana and
Idaho not likely to be extinguished until the first snows.
</P>
<P>
   But questions about the scope and potential cost of such
projects remain the source of bitter divisions that are likely to
surface even more visibly this fall, as Congress holds hearings
about this summer's fires and begins to weigh any administration
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Among the critics who have attacked the administration is Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. In an Aug. 12 interview with The Seattle
Times, he said that policies that had restricted logging and
thinning of underbrush had ``made the forests much more dangerous
to fire.'' But in an interview, Babbitt said the administration
stood fully behind the thinning approach, and blamed the lack of
progress on legal and administrative maneuvering by the opponents.
``The problem is that we keep getting jammed up, and we've just got
to bust that barrier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As presented in the draft Forest Service plan, a ``projected
treatment schedule'' calls for the thinning of 3 million acres of
Western forests each year by 2004, when the program would take full
effect. Over its proposed 15-year span, the total cost of the
program could top $12 billion, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While that price tag is substantial, the officials said it
should be compared to the cost of fighting this summer's fires,
which is expected to exceed $1 billion, and to the risk of leaving
Western forests in their current fire-prone condition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, that condition is an outgrowth of what most
fire experts now agree were decades of mistaken policy, in which
until very recently, forest managers sought to extinguish virtually
every wildfire. That approach has spared most public lands of the
natural cleansing that a low-intensity fire can provide, while
leaving the dense forests that have resulted increasingly prone to
the kind of intense, fast-moving fires that have burned so much
land this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Future generations are going to damn us if we don't get on
this in a hurry,'' W. Wallace Covington, a professor of forest
ecology at the University of Northern Arizona and a main architect
of the Flagstaff plan, said of what he called an urgent need for
widespread forest thinning.
</P>
<P>
   Covington's approach, which has led to the thinning of some
experimental tracts by as much as 90 percent, aims to restore a
more natural and less-fire-prone condition that scholars say
existed in Western forests before the time of European settlement
in the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   But others argue say that the extent of scientific knowledge
does not yet justify such an aggressive overhaul of existing
woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach is extreme and untested,'' said Sharon
Galbreath, who heads the local chapter of the Sierra Club, which
has expressed deep reservations about the plan. ``This should not
be billed as `If you do this, you save the forests of the West.' If
you do this, you might set back the forests of the West by 100
years.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the debate over thinning in Flagstaff have been
arguments over how much wood should be removed and how much should
be left behind. Those factors strongly affect the cost of any
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   No project can come anywhere close to breaking even unless
loggers are permitted to harvest large, commercially valuable
trees, as timber industry officials and their allies point out. The
industry argues that its ordinary practices are adequate to produce
healthy forests, and would allow thinning to be carried out at a
cost far less than is apparently being envisioned by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts note that many of this summer's largest fires
are burning in areas that have previously been logged, and they
strongly defend the Flagstaff-style approach, of paying loggers
several hundred dollars an acre to subsidize what little they can
earn from selling the low-quality wood they are permitted to
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is the opposite of logging, in that you leave
the best trees behind,'' said Brad Ack, executive director of the
Grand Canyon Partnership, the coalition group behind the Flagstaff
plan. ``What we need to do now is to invest in our forests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-FATE-NYT     08-21 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S THEORY ON SUBMARINE INCIDENT HAS A COLD WAR RING 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-SUBMARINE) 
By   CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian officials' assertions on Monday that the Kursk sank
after a collision, most likely with a foreign submarine, echoed the
kind of suspicions that were common during the Cold War, when on
more than a dozen occasions, Russian and Western submarines banged
into one another.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have long resented the fact that many of the
collisions occurred in or near their waters and, in their view,
amounted to hit-and-run jobs, as American and British spy subs
quickly fled to safety. One Russian submarine was so badly damaged
after colliding with an American boat in 1970 that it almost sank,
the Russian navy contends.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have repeatedly denied that any American
submarine collided with the Kursk, which plunged to the seabed on
Aug. 12. An intense rescue operation ended on Monday when the
Russians concluded that all 118 sailors had died in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said that two American submarines were in
the Barents Sea to monitor a Russian naval exercise that included
the Kursk. But they have said that neither submarine was close to
the Russian vessel. British officials also denied any involvement
on Monday, saying they had no submarines in the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cold War ended, the tenor of the cat-and-mouse game,
in which the submarines chased one another to test the other side's
capabilities, has grown less aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   American officials even called Russian leaders to apologize
shortly after each of the last two collisions occurred, in the
early 1990s. And given the West's efforts to support democracy in
Russia, some naval experts said they could not conceive of a
situation in which American or British officials would attempt to
cover up a tragic accident now.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Friedman, an independent navy expert in New York, said
that he believes the Russian naval officials were trying to deflect
the blame for their own mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the evidence that has surfaced so far, he said it
seemed ``incredibly unlikely'' that the Kursk had suffered a
collision, especially with a foreign submarine. ``There are so many
other possibilities that you would have to rule out before you
focused on something as strange as that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   American navy officials and several experts like Friedman have
said that it was more likely that the Kursk sank after one of its
weapons, like a torpedo, exploded on board.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, Russian navy leaders also have cited the
possibility of a torpedo accident. There also was a chance, they
said, that the Kursk could have struck a floating mine left over
from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But time after time, several Russian officials have brought up
the idea of a collision with a Western sub. And the Russian defense
minister, Igor Sergeyev, said on Monday that a commission of
experienced navy officials had endorsed this view.
</P>
<P>
   He said that after the Kursk shot a buoy to the surface to warn
that it was in trouble, men on two Russian ships detected signs of
a large underwater object ``equivalent in size'' to the Kursk. But
he said a ship designed to survey the seabed could not find this
object later.
</P>
<P>
   Former submariners say that many of the collisions have occurred
because submarines have to navigate by interpreting sounds filtered
through their sonar equipment. When two boats get close to each
other, even a small mistake by one in plotting the other's course
can cause them to collide.
</P>
<P>
   In most of the collisions during the Cold War, the Western and
Russian subs sustained only minor damage, like scratched hulls. The
Western subs generally were under orders to remain undetected, so
they never surfaced to try to aid the Soviet vessels.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious incident, the Tautog, a nuclear-powered
attack submarine, collided in 1970 with a Soviet submarine close to
Russia's Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet vessel, which was also operating under nuclear power,
sustained so much damage, former American officials have said, that
it was reported to President Nixon that the submarine had sunk. It
was only in recent years that enough information became available
in Russia to determine that while the submarine was severely
damaged, it had limped back to port.
</P>
<P>
   The last collisions between American and Russian subs occurred
in 1992 and 1993. In a break from Cold War secrecy, both the Bush
and Clinton administrations disclosed the accidents publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidents also reduced the frequency of the reconnaissance
missions off Russia and ordered American subs to maintain greater
distances from Russian vessels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
