<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATES-HNS &LR;      08-21 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ACCUSES BUSH OF PROCRASTINATING ON PRESIDENTIAL DEBATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANNIBAL, Mo. _ As he concluded a four-day boat and bus trip
along the Mississippi River, Al Gore on Monday accused George W.
Bush of procrastinating on presidential debates and suggested his
Republican opponent does not want to face off in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the final fall stretch of the campaign, Gore
has agreed to three presidential and two vice-presidential debates,
structured by the Commission on Presidential Debates.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission, a nonpartisan, nonprofit corporation that has
sponsored the general election presidential debates since 1988, has
proposed prime time encounters involving only the two major party
candidates and their running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists believe their candidate, a skillful debater,
would best Bush in a series of head-on encounters. But they are not
eager to give national television exposure to Green Party nominee
Ralph Nader, who could hurt Gore with some Democrats if he went
after Gore in a debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not ruled out including third party candidates. Last
week, Bush campaign officials proposed a series of three
presidential and two vice-presidential debates, but said they
wanted to shop around for other sponsors and formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is procrastinating,'' Gore said. ``It is
unprecedented in modern times for the major party candidate to try
and stiff the prime time debate commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Wisconsin, responded to Gore's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be debates. We said we're going to look at all
options and that's what's taking place,'' he said. When pressed as
to how he wanted debates structured Bush remained vague, saying
``I'm comfortable in almost any format.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what I'd like to do is to have debates ... where
people get a sense for what we believe, that's structured so that
both of us are to share our ideas in a way that people will listen
to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore suggested that his Republican rival may be trying to avoid
a direct verbal match at a time when most voters can tune in.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his opponent ``apparently wants to see if he can get
away with some Sunday morning talk show when nobody is watching
much and substituting that for what the American people have a
right to expect, namely, one-on-one debates in prime time when
everybody can hear a detailed discussion of the issues. I don't
know why he wants to duck that.''
</P>
<P>
   In past election years, the debate commission has overseen
forums that included the candidates being questioned by each other,
by a panel of journalists and by voters in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Gore predicted Bush eventually will agree to the Commission's
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have a right in this day and time to be
respected with an adult intelligent discussion of what the major
issues are in a give and take without the slick image makers
intervening,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's latest broadside comes at a time when he has largely
ignored Bush and let his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, lob
the partisan barbs.
</P>
<P>
   The skirmishing over debates came as the Gores and Liebermans
completed their post-convention swing through four key Midwestern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising down the Mississippi on the Mark Twain Riverboat, the
candidates and their wives held their final riverside rally at the
birthplace of the boat's namesake, the 19th century author who
penned the popular tales of boyhood adventure, ``Tom Sawyer'' and
``Huckleberry Finn.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four days, Gore has made his way down 400 miles of
the famed river, holding rallies in small cities and towns in
Wisconsin, Iowa, Illinois and Missouri. These are all states that
President Clinton won in 1992 and 1996 but which so far Gore has
failed to nail down.
</P>
<P>
   A batch of new polls out Tuesday provided more evidence that
Gore enjoyed a bounce from the Democratic convention in Los
Angeles. In a Reuters Zogby poll, Gore inched ahead of Bush 44
percent to 41 percent, strengthening his support among Democrats
and women, two crucial demographic groups where he was showing
weaknesses earlier this summer. Just before the Democratic
convention the same poll had Gore down by three points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of likely voters, conducted Friday through Sunday,
found independent voters, who had favored Bush, now split between
Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Andy Kohut, who directs polling for the Pew Center for the
People and the Press, warned that post-convention surges are
usually ``ephemeral.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohut, who expects to conduct a poll in a few weeks, said Gore
got the same kind of bump that Bush did after his convention in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
