<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-TECH-GODSEY0822-C     08-21 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECH-GODSEY0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Godsey they trust
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Just who is George Godsey, the man whom George O'Leary
has handed the quarterback reins for 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Most Georgia Tech fans know him as the blond guy who signaled in
the plays to Joe Hamilton the past three seasons; the guy holding
the clipboard; the guy standing beside offensive coordinator Ralph
Friedgen; the guy with No. 11 on his back.
</P>
<P>
   A few might even remember Godsey on the field, although they'd
have had to look fast. He attempted 13 passes last season and 19 in
1998. His longest run from scrimmage has been 11 yards and his
longest pass has been 24. He never has scored a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Tampa native's one shining moment came on a busted
play. Against Georgia last season, he recovered Luke Manget's
blocked field-goal attempt on third down in overtime, which allowed
Tech to kick the game-winner on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the 6-foot-2, 207-pound Godsey will be the Yellow
Jackets' starting quarterback against Virginia Tech on national
television in packed Lane Stadium in Blacksburg.
</P>
<P>
   For good or for bad, as Godsey goes, so goes Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Godsey is the second-youngest of five children in a family that
achieves. His oldest sister is a lawyer after attending Florida
State and Florida. His oldest brother played football at the Air
Force Academy and is a lawyer in Atlanta. His next sister is in
graduate school at Purdue. His youngest brother, Gary, is the
backup quarterback at Notre Dame. His mother is a teacher and his
father is an entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say he's an entrepreneur,'' Godsey said
about his father, John, who played football at Alabama. The father
started in the restaurant business, went into liquor sales _ his
product was something called an Island Squeeze _ then tried the
clothing business, then owned a restaurant named the Game Day
Grill, with a television at every table. Now, he's selling
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's who George is. Kind of an entrepreneurial
quarterback. He's not a great runner, his arm isn't the strongest
on the team, and he doesn't have the greatest speed. He lives by
guile and cunning and understands Friedgen's complicated offense
better than anyone else. Maybe he comes by it naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The word on Godsey is he won't lose the game for you, but the
question is whether he can win it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting ready for games, just like Joe did, for
three years,'' Godsey said. ``We took the same number of reps in
practice. It's normal for people to think that a quarterback is
going to make or break a team. But if an offensive lineman misses
an assignment, the play is done. If a receiver runs the wrong
route, the play's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Godsey won the starting job in the spring by the narrowest of
margins. All O'Leary would say was that Godsey earned the starting
job, but only for the first snap of fall practice. From there, it
was anybody's to take.
</P>
<P>
   But Godsey seized the moment over the summer. He worked at
losing weight, dropping from 219 to 207. He worked on his running
and can run two miles in 12 minutes. He ran the 6.2 mile Peachtree
Road Race, the first time he had run more than three miles, in 47
minutes. He lifted weights with his offensive line. He threw and
threw and threw to his receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``George has distanced himself with the others big time,''
O'Leary pronounced about this quarterbacks after one week of fall
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer was big for me,'' Godsey said. ``If the team
developed a leader, it would be at that time. We all worked out
together. I started urging them on. I was telling people what route
to run. People started to look at me as somebody who knew what was
going on. The summer was a maturing process for me. And I really
started throwing the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Godsey says he's heard all the questions, the criticism of his
style, the open wondering if he's the right man for the job. ``It
doesn't hurt my feelings,'' he said. ``I don't take those things
like they're engraved in granite. I've seen worse things written
about other people. I'm fine with all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen has faith that Godsey can do the job. ``We haven't
changed a thing with our offense,'' Godsey said. ``It's very
similar to every year that I've been here. There's the same ratio
of pass to run. Are we going to run the option? Sure we are. Am I
going to roll out? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback says he's comfortable with his mates. ``This
team is closer,'' he said. ``Starting the season, things are going
to go wrong at times, but you won't see this team ducking its
head.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida native agrees that he has inherited a team much
richer and deeper in talent than Hamilton did four years ago when
he began his run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got so many good athletes around me, I just want to get
them involved in the offense, let them do their thing,'' he said.
``I'm not going to go out and beat Virginia Tech by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
