<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8390 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS0822-COX     08-21 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Right end major question for hyped Texas' defense
 &HT;    By Olin Buchanan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas -It's all a matter of weight and see.
</P>
<P>
   That's always been the case for Texas Longhorns defensive end
Jermain Anderson, but the meaning has changed somewhat this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Anderson's two previous football seasons, the main
question about his weight isn't how much it is, but whether he can
pull it as part of an improving defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great opportunity,'' Anderson said after a recent
practice. ``I've had a great summer. I worked out really hard. I'm
happy, and I'm injury free.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not, however, free from the scrutiny and doubt of UT
followers that view right end with concern instead of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Defense is expected to carry Texas _ at least in the early part
of the season _ and with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Hampton and Shaun Rogers might be the best set of tackles
in the nation. The linebackers are proven, the secondary is
experienced and left end Cory Redding has All-America potential.
</P>
<P>
   But right end is a bald tire on Texas' shining new Cadillac _
inspiring held breath and crossed fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray about the ends,'' Texas free safety Greg Brown said.
``I know Cory had a lot of playing time last year and Jermain did a
phenomenal job his freshman year, but this is another season. I
hope they keep showing what they've been showing because we could
be a sight to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson showed enough as a freshman to grab a fair share of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 games he recorded 18 tackles _ four for losses _ and
recorded a sack, two quarterback pressures, an interception, three
deflected passes and a forced fumble. He had a sack and two tackles
for losses against No. 5 Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   But how well he played was overshadowed by how little he
weighed.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was listed as weighing less than 220 pounds, but he
said he often played at less than 210, which is almost emaciated
for a major college lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson played in only five games last season and managed just
one tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors contributed to that decline in productivity.
</P>
<P>
   He was constantly nagged by a wrist injury, personal problems
from his home in Texas City were a distraction and because of his
slight build, Cedric Woodard, more than 70 pounds heavier, was a
more attractive fit at end.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he did everything he could to rectify those
situations.
</P>
<P>
   The wrist, he said, is fine. The problems at home are solved.
The weight?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Anderson is nowhere close to Woodard's 295 pounds, but he
was able to bulk up to 232 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gorged myself,'' Anderson said. ``I ate hamburgers, rolls,
drank a couple of protein shakes every day. I'd eat three times a
day. Back in high school I only ate once or twice a day and I was
playing basketball all the time. I cut down on the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Anderson has been able to maintain his speed and
quickness, his greatest attributes, he still is small for a
defensive end and figures to have problems against powerful running
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is when (opponents) use two tight ends and put one
on him and smash him,'' Texas defensive coordinator Carl Reese
said. ``You've got to see how he does against the run.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Anderson has going for him in that respect is the
schedule, which is infested with pass-oriented opponents. Perhaps
stopping the run won't be that big of an issue after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play teams that will spread out and throw the football
with three wides or four wide (receivers), so you're not having to
stop that run as much,'' Reese said. ``That helps. But to be really
good we have to find someone that can stop the run, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that responsibility won't fall on Anderson alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomores Cole Pittman and Adam McConathy, both boasting
considerably more bulk than Anderson, figure to be involved in a
rotation at right end. And like Woodard a year ago, a tackle could
shift outside against running teams. Or perhaps a newcomer like
freshman Kalen Thornton will make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Those are all viable options, but if Anderson remains the
Longhorns' first option at defensive end, at least his teammates
have confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermain will come out scratching and clawing to do whatever he
has to do,'' Redding said.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Everick Rawls, Anderson's teammate at Texas City High
School, is also optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about Jermain being a weak link because he's too
small,'' Rawls said. ``He has a big heart. I know he can do it
despite his size.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is optimistic, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go out and compete my best with whoever is in
front of me,'' he said. ``I'll give it everything I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Olin Buchanan may be contacted at obuchanan(at)statesman.com or
445-3952.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
