<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8392 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-WAMU-BANKUNITED-SPI &LR;      08-21 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAMU-BANKUNITED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MUTUAL BUYS BANK UNITED OF HOUSTON  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Washington Mutual Inc., looking to make itself as much
a major player in Texas banking as it is in Washington and
California, said Monday it will buy a Houston-based company in a
$1.5 billion stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Washington Mutual will acquire Bank United Corp.,
the largest publicly traded Texas-based financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was something of an incidental market Washington Mutual
picked up in its 1998 acquisition of H.F. Ahmanson &AMP; Co.; while the
real prize in the Ahmanson deal was its huge share of the market in
California, it also had 48 branches in Texas, primarily in Houston
and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be successful, we needed substantially more,'' said Kerry
Killinger, Washington Mutual's chairman and chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Bank United will provide that, with 155 branches, including 66
in Houston, 77 in Dallas-Fort Worth and a handful in Midland,
Austin and San Antonio. Greater size means Washington Mutual's
marketing dollars will be more effective in driving business to its
branches; the combined banks would be third in deposit share in
Houston, fourth in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   After doing three huge deals, each of which about doubled the
company in size, Killinger had said Washington Mutual would take a
breather, doing less with acquisitions and more with internal
growth. One facet of that internal growth strategy is to roll out
dozens of branches, designed more like a retail store than a
traditional bank, at once. Washington Mutual is doing that in
Southern Nevada, and plans to do so in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Killinger said he considered whether to use the same approach in
Texas, but decided instead to make an acquisition and leverage that
with more branches. Bank United was attractive mainly because, with
the Texas landscape dominated by such out-of-state behemoths as
Chase Manhattan, Bank America, Wells Fargo and Bank One, it was
``the only franchise to buy there,'' said Jay Tejera, banking
analyst with Ragen MacKenzie Inc. in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Bank United, like Washington Mutual, also has built a consumer
banking presence with free checking accounts. ``We're in a sense
the Washington Mutual clone in Texas,'' said Bank United President
Barry Burkholder. Too, Bank United is the largest Small Business
Administration lender in Texas and fourth in the nation. Its
portfolio of business loans will help Washington Mutual in its
drive to reduce its balance-sheet dependence on residential
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual is also getting some geographic
diversification from California, into a growing state economy that
is far less oil-dependent than two decades ago. Burkholder said the
proof of that was that when oil prices slumped to nearly $10 a
barrel, ``there was virtually no blip on the landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dissimilar from the Seattle area diversifying out of
aerospace,'' Killinger added.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Washington Mutual has gotten so big, at $185.8 billion
in assets, Tejera said, that it can do a deal for Bank United
($18.2 billion in assets) that helps its position in a specific
market but isn't a bet-the-company proposition like the Ahmanson,
Great Western and American Savings deals. ``It's a comfortable hors
d'oeuvre-sized meal rather than an all-you-can eat buffet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the two companies seemed so obvious and was
considered such a ``wonderful fit, the real issue was whether
(Washington Mutual) was going to overpay for it,'' Tejera said. He
believes it didn't, with a purchase price of less than 1.7 times
Bank United's book value and just slightly over its current trading
price. Washington Mutual said the deal will immediately add to cash
earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual will pay 1.3 shares of its stock for every
Bank United share. Washington Mutual's stock closed at $32.06 a
share Monday, down 75 cents; Bank United's closed at $40.88, down
$1.50.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual said it expects to cut up to 650 jobs in the
deal _ due to close late this year or early next _ but most Bank
United employees will be offered jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
