<HEADER>
A8397 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RAGWEED-0822-COX     08-21 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGWEED-0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allergy sufferers can find solutions, but first make sure
pollution isn't the real problem
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - If the pollution doesn't get you, the ragweed will.
</P>
<P>
   While nicer plants, like your baskets of impatiens and ferns,
have all wilted away in the drought, ragweed continues to thrive.
And even worse, as heat and pollution get worse, it gets more
prolific.
</P>
<P>
   The plants thrive on carbon dioxide and, like other weeds, are
heartier than many plants that wilt in hot and dry conditions, said
Dr. Linda B. Ford, an Omaha allergist with the American Academy of
Allergy, Asthma &AMP; Immunology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragweed is actually a more vigorous plant next to highways and
throughout urban areas,'' she said. And, because it's so happy in
its smoggy environment, it will produce more pollen _ and ``it
won't take as much to make you miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   But as smog alerts continue and the plants release their pollen,
it's hard to distinguish which one is making you miserable. Many of
the symptoms are the same, from itchy eyes to stuffy noses to sore
throats.
</P>
<P>
   However, how you treat the problem can make a big difference.
Trying to treat pollution symptoms with allergy medications _
especially some over-the-counter products _ could leave you, well,
sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, allergy specialists recommend you try to determine
exactly what you're suffering from. It's probably an allergy if you
have no fever, mucous secretions are clear and runny, sneezes occur
in rapid sequence and there's itchiness in the nose, ears and
throat _ especially the roof of the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But if you've been experiencing problems like itchy eyes or
irritated lungs for the past month, the problem is probably
pollution. Ragweed season has only just begun, with the Atlanta
Allergy &AMP; Asthma Clinic starting its official pollen count Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, note the time of day you feel miserable: Ragweed is worse
in the morning and pollution is worse at night.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the problem is pollution, then treat the symptoms
with eye drops and saline nasal spray. A decongestant might help.
But there is no clear solution, doctors point out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being in a house with cigarette smoke,'' said Dr.
Kathleen Sheerin, an Atlanta allergist. ``You can take some steps
to alleviate the irritation but you just can't treat it like you
can with allergies.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is an allergy problem, there's a bevy of treatments that
patients can try.
</P>
<P>
   Mild symptoms can be treated with over-the-counter medications.
The most common are antihistamines and decongestants.
Antihistamines, which often contain chlorpheniramine, work by
blocking a substance produced by the body called histamine _ which
causes many of the allergy symptoms such as itching, sneezing and
runny nose. Decongestants, which often contain phenylpropanolamine
or phenylephrine and pseudophedrine, produce a narrowing of blood
vessels, which leads to the clearning of nasal congestion.
</P>
<P>
   However, be careful when you're using over-the-counter products
with children. Doctors report parents and teachers often complain
that such medications can wind kids up or make them moody or
groggy. In some cases prescription medicines _ such as Claritin,
Zyrtec and Allegra _ may be better alternatives. All come in pill
form for adults, but can also be administered to children in liquid
form. Zyrtec even tastes sweet.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, if you're truly sick of all these medications _ or
you can't tolerate the side effects _ doctors recommend patients
try allergy shots. If used consistently over three to five years,
they can permanently stop the allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
