 PERSONALS: Elton John and Boy George Spar Over Eminem 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Elton John &LR; 's defense of rapper  &UR; Eminem &LR; , who rants against gays,
has raised the hackles of  &UR; Boy George &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   John had called Eminem's ravings ``really hard-core stuff, but
it's intelligent hard-core. It's poetry and also musically
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy George's response, as quoted in the New York Post: ``I am
shocked to hear that Elton John has called queer-baiting Eminem the
most important voice since  &UR; Bob Dylan &LR; .'' Boy George says John may
be using reverse psychology. ``Cool singers or bands hate being
championed by fellow artists they consider uncool, and Eminem will
not take too kindly to being championed by one of the world's most
famous diamond-studded homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WISDOM OF THE AGES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco architect  &UR; John Field &LR; , a man of distinction, was
nonetheless nonplussed to receive notice that he had been named
``to the renowned Wisdom Hall of Fame,'' of which he'd never heard.
A letter bearing a ``50th anniversary wisdom'' seal, from Dr.  &UR; Leon
Gutterman &LR; , ``Wisdom Founder &AMP; President,'' told Field that as soon
as his reply was received, he would be sent an official Wisdom
Honors Invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Personals called the Beverly Hills phone number on the
letterhead to find out what obligations accepting the invitation
entailed. The woman who answered, identifying herself as
Gutterman's receptionist, refused to elaborate, advising only that
the letter's recipient should follow Gutterman's directions in
order to receive a complete Wisdom Hall of Fame package. In the
background, a dog was barking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AGASSI SAYS NO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Actors in Australia are striking, reports the Chicago Tribune,
and  &UR; Andre Agassi &LR;  has turned down a major offer to shoot a
nonunion ad there.
</P>
<P>
   Among the athletes who have agreed to participate in nonunion
commercials: golfer  &UR; Tiger Woods &LR;  and Olympic sprinters  &UR; Michael &LR; 
 &UR; Johnson &LR;  and  &UR; Marion Jones &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest Vanity Fair, which focuses on ``It'' girls and
their cultural counterparts _ really just a way to print an ``in''
list without an ``out'' list _ says the San Francisco-based Webbys
are the ``It'' of awards. The list also says that lists such as
itself are ``it'' Pop-Cultural Objects of Scorn.
</P>
<P>
   _ As to the baby named after an Internet company,  &UR; Don McCunn &LR; 
suggests the company missed the boat when it didn't specify that
the infant wear a vinyl advertising skin _ like the ones on buses _
for its first year. And  &UR; David Kelso &LR;  suggests that Ikea and Nokia
would be lovely names for twin girls. Is this how  &UR; Macy &LR; 
 &UR; Gray &LR;  _ the department store and Poupon mustard _ got her name?
 &UR; Prince William &LR; -Sonoma?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``We had some difficulties collaborating. Of an emotional
sort. &LR; 
 &UR; ... Usually, she's in charge. But if she's in my story, I have &LR; 
 &UR; to stop her all the time. That's direction, that's where the &LR; 
 &UR; word comes from, right? I'm pointing the direction, and this is &LR; 
 &UR; not very pleasant if you go right and I want to point left.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Director  &UR; Lars Von Trier &LR; , of his relationship with  &UR; Bjork &LR; ,
the star of his ``Dancer in the Dark.'' When shooting was finished,
says W, she gave everyone in the cast animal figurines; he got a
rat.
</P>
