<HEADER>
A8399 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-IRAQ-U.N.-1040(2TAKES     08-21 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-1040(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEAM OF U.N. ARMS INSPECTORS SETS SIGHTS ON IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE and STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United Nations has assembled a new team of arms inspectors
that is ready to enter Iraq within weeks, raising the prospect of
another confrontation with President Saddam Hussein over his
weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the new inspection team comes more than two
years after Saddam halted cooperation with a previous group of
inspectors, provoking a diplomatic crisis that culminated in four
nights of American and British airstrikes in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has repeatedly said it will not cooperate with the new
weapons commission, which the Security Council ordered nine months
ago in the hope that it would resolve some objections that the
Iraqis, as well as the Russians and French, had about the previous
commission.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief Iraqi complaints about the previous commission,
headed by Richard Butler, an Australian arms control expert, was
that there were too many inspectors from the United States and
Britain, who, the Iraqis asserted, were really spies.
</P>
<P>
   The new team, with members from 19 countries, is meant to be
more accountable to the U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan. All the
members work directly for the United Nations, not for their own
countries, as before.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Hans Blix, the leader of the new team, is to discuss
the need for access to Iraq with a panel of international weapons
experts who serve as the commission's directors. By Sept. 1 he is
expected to report to the Security Council that the inspectors are
ready to begin work and to tell them that _ barring a change in
Iraq's position _ the Iraqis have continued to reject new
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains far from clear what the United States or other
members of the Security Council will do if Iraq refuses to
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how forcefully the Security Council will push
the new inspections, especially since its 15 members are sharply
divided over Iraq and the economic sanctions imposed on it. The
position of each member is not likely to be clear until debates in
the council begin sometime in September.
</P>
<P>
   The broad economic sanctions were imposed after Iraq invaded
Kuwait in 1990. They are to remain in place until Iraq is certified
as free of prohibited weapons _ chemical, biological and nuclear
arms as well as long-range missiles. Last December, the Security
Council said it would suspend the sanctions if Iraq cooperated with
the new team of arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   If Saddam refuses, the council will have no alternative but to
keep the sanctions in place. It is unlikely the council would call
for the use of force, but in previous confrontations, the United
States and Britain have argued that existing resolutions authorize
military action.
</P>
<P>
   If a confrontation developed, it would focus new attention on
the Clinton administration's policy toward Iraq in the middle of
the presidential election. That policy has come under sharp attack
from Republicans and even some Democrats in Washington, who
complain that President Clinton has not acted forcefully enough to
force Saddam's government to accept the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   If Saddam refuses to cooperate, the administration will be under
political pressure to act forcefully. If the Iraqi leader reverses
course, Clinton's successor could be confronted with the
politically difficult decision of whether to go along with a
suspension of sanctions, which the Security Council has offered as
an incentive to the Iraqis if they demonstrate cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and other officials at the United Nations said they
believe that during this year's election campaign, the Clinton
administration is not likely to press for strong action, even if
Iraq remains defiant.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior administration official said that the Iraqis or
anyone else would be foolish to assume that. Although the
administration has not indicated how it would answer new Iraqi
defiance, the official refused to rule out the possibility of an
``October surprise'' of American military action at the height of a
campaign, should the Iraqis provoke it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be making a severe mistake if they think an election
campaign will affect how we carry out our foreign policy,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, administration officials said they would insist
that Iraq comply with the resolution that created Blix's team or
face an indefinite extension of sanctions. ``It's a mandatory
resolution,'' Thomas R. Pickering, the undersecretary of state,
said in a telephone interview. ``If the Iraqis don't comply, the
sanctions will stay in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the resolution that created Blix's team, those sanctions
can be suspended six months after the Iraqis fulfill a list of
``key'' requirements set by the inspectors and, ultimately, be
lifted once the inspectors conclude that Iraq has come clean and
dismantled its prohibited weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The previous commission had a more comprehensive standard for
declaring Iraq free of weapons before sanctions could be lifted,
offering no interim steps like a suspension for meeting some
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The new inspection organization, officially known as the United
Nations Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission, is led
by Blix, a Swedish arms control expert who previously served as
director general of the International Atomic Energy Agency in
Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Blix completed recruiting and training the 44 arms
inspectors from countries both friendly and not so friendly to the
Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Blix said his first step was to find out what happened to
several hundred sites inspected by the last commission in 1998 _
which could take at least several months.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis have said they believe the United States would never
agree to a suspension of sanctions but rather find another reason
to keep them in place, making cooperation, in their view,
fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have long argued that resuming
inspections inside Iraq _ rather than resorting to force _ is the
most effective way to combat Saddam's efforts to hold on to
nuclear, chemical or biological weapons, as well as long-range
missiles that could deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Pentagon and the American intelligence agencies,
however, there is growing concern that Saddam has used the
prolonged absence of inspectors to continue those efforts. The CIA
sent a report to Congress this month warning that Iraq had already
rebuilt missile and chemical weapons factories since the airstrikes
in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
