<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-KOOP0822-COX     08-21 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOOP0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - In its quarterly financial report Monday,
Austin-based drkoop.com Inc. revealed details of secret
negotiations that could soon lead to its rescue, but also
acknowledged that it is the subject of an inquiry by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Drkoop.com's cash needs are well-known: the company has said
since April that it only has enough cash on hand to make it through
the summer and since then has raised only small sums meant to act
as bridges to permanent funding. But its legal woes, coupled with
its poor financial performance recently, may be also leading it to
negotiate a private placement of stock at fire-sale prices.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for drkoop.com declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is investigating allegations of violations of federal
securities laws made in seven shareholder lawsuits filed against
the company this summer. The allegations relate to, among other
things, large sales of stock by company officers and directors in
February and March, shortly before a pessimistic auditors' report
sent shares plummeting.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has requested information from drkoop.com about the
circumstances surrounding the allegations but said that the inquiry
``should not be construed as an indication by the SEC that any
violation of the federal securities laws has occurred,'' according
to the document. The company also said it is facing a legal claim
for $208,000 from the holder of one of its promissory notes.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, drkoop.com has been operating on a $1.5 million
bridge loan and a $3 million bridge line of credit from
Commonwealth Associates, the merchant bank that is helping the
company find permanent financing. On August 14, drkoop.com dipped
into that line of credit for $400,000, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``Substantially all of the company's assets are pledged against
the notes,'' the filing stated.
</P>
<P>
   The company is seeking to raise as much as $27.5 million from a
private group of investors, offering new stock in drkoop.com priced
at 35 cents a share, a large discount over the current price.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in drkoop.com, which have never traded below 65 cents a
share, have risen sharply since late last week as rumors of a
buyout have resurfaced. They closed at $1.34 Monday, up 9 cents.
</P>
<P>
   If drkoop.com can raise the full amount it is seeking, the new
shareholders would own 78.6 million shares, or more than twice the
amount owned by current shareholders. In addition, the new
shareholders, the placement agent and Commonwealth Associates would
receive warrants to buy another 40.7 million shares at 35 cents a
share, diluting current shareholders' stake even further. These
investors would also receive a majority of seats on the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of the filing of this report, the transaction described
above is being negotiated but is not completed and we cannot assure
you that it will be completed,'' the filing stated.
</P>
<P>
   The company received a waiver from the Nasdaq stock market
allowing it to seek stockholder approval for the deal by mail
rather than in person, which it did. An updated notice is being
mailed to them, the filing stated.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, drkoop.com lost $40.6 million, or $1.18 a share,
during the three months that ended June 30, compared to a loss of
$24.8 million, or 80 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter revenues fell to $2.5 million from $4.7 million
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Andrew Park at apark(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
