<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VERIZON-IMPACT-NYT     08-21 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: LABOR DEAL'S IMPACT ON CUSTOMERS AND COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a phone circuit goes dead and no one is on the line, does it
really stop carrying sound?
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, a similar question could be asked about the
effective end to the strike against Verizon Communications. While
the strike is important for Verizon, the walkout and Sunday's
agreement with two-thirds of the union membership on strike
probably will not have much bearing on the rest of the
telecommunications industry. Even for consumers, the strike's
effect can fairly be described only as minimal.
</P>
<P>
   As for Verizon itself, the company will continue to be penalized
to the tune of billions of dollars of market value for the strength
of its unions.
</P>
<P>
   When autoworkers go on strike, cars stop rolling off assembly
lines. When pilots go on strike, planes stop flying. But when phone
workers go on strike, life pretty much goes on.
</P>
<P>
   That is because modern networks are largely automated. Vandals,
like the two striking workers who were nearly electrocuted on Long
Island last week as they tried to slice a phone line, cut service
to a few thousand customers here and there. But in a backhanded
testament to the power of the machines, those figures paled beside
the hundreds of thousands of Verizon customers who lost
long-distance phone service last week when an obscure piece of
equipment failed in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, Verizon had a backlog of about 92,000 outstanding
requests for repairs. That figure was perhaps twice normal,
implying that about 46,000 of Verizon's 25 million customers in the
strike region were suffering problems that they would not have
otherwise had.
</P>
<P>
   That works out to fewer than two out of every 1,000 customers.
Of course, for each of those customers one problem was one far too
many, and those figures do not include the thousands of people who
were stymied in attempts to sign up for or change phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon's success in serving almost all of its customers during
the strike does not mean that people are unimportant in modern
communications. Without the thousands of managers who filled in for
the strikers, the extent of the service failures would have been
far greater. A network as extensive as Verizon's requires extensive
maintenance, and that requires many people.
</P>
<P>
   Largely, however, lower-level employees are needed at a company
like Verizon because customers want to talk to people. Most
customers do not want to sign up for new phone service online.
Customers with billing questions want a live person on the line
right now, not an e-mail response tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   During the strike, Verizon's directory assistance has been
largely disabled because people meant to answer calls were on
picket lines. If voice-recognition software is ever ready for prime
time, Verizon will surely prefer to lay off thousands of operators.
But while Verizon's unions would certainly block such a move,
consumers would probably complain as well. As it has been, during
the strike many consumers have borne the inconvenience of using a
phone book, the mark of an old economy if ever there were one.
</P>
<P>
   In the big scheme of things, the effect on consumers of the
strike and its partial settlement was and will be quite small.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the unions have appeared to win almost everything
they asked for, much the same could be said of the deal's effect on
the rest of the communications industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it means much for the rest of the industry,''
said Eric W. Rabe, a Verizon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, while the wrangling over the unionization of
Verizon's wireless unit was viewed as a referendum on unions' power
in newer industries, the deal that was reached in the end was not
all that different from those already in place at some other major
wireless operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of wireless, it seems as though what they're talking
about in terms of union organizing might be similar to AT&AMP;T,'' said
Burke Stinson, an AT&AMP;T spokesman. Rabe of Verizon even ventured
that his company had made a better wireless deal than has SBC
Communications Inc., the No. 2 local phone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wireless deal that we made, from the union point of view,
is more restrictive than the deal SBC already had in place,'' Rabe
said.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that the expedited organizing process that Verizon
agreed to covers only about a quarter of the wireless unit's
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the main reason that the Verizon deal is not a
harbinger for the rest of the industry is that Verizon's unions are
stronger, and might just be a lot stronger, than those at any other
phone company in the nation, largely because of Verizon's
Northeastern geography.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Verizon has the toughest unions, so it's very
difficult to extrapolate from what happens here to the rest of the
industry, because Verizon is in a pretty unique position,'' said
Eric Strumingher, a telecommunications analyst at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for BellSouth, Qwest, SBC, Sprint and WorldCom
declined to comment on the settlement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the reticence is that the other companies have
nothing to gain by sticking their nose into what would be
considered a debacle for most of them. The fact is that under
Sunday's deal, with its limits on overtime and its limits on job
movements, Verizon ultimately has less control over its own
business than does just about any other big communications carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is the pace at which they can adapt
to change in the industry and innovate and capitalize on the new
growth opportunities,'' Strumingher said. ``If the Bells didn't
have unions, it's worth a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the strike was starting this month, Verizon announced
new projections for its future revenue and earnings growth. Rabe
said the strike and the new deal would not alter those projections.
</P>
<P>
   But unionization nonetheless carries a big price tag on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a stock is often calculated in terms of a multiple
of the company's expected per-share earnings. For instance,
Verizon's shares closed at about $42.81 Monday, up about 69 cents,
meaning that they are worth 14.63 times the company's expected
per-share earnings of about $2.93 this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Strumingher said that unionization is probably
costing all of the Bell companies ``at least five'' multiple
points. If Verizon's stock were trading at an earnings multiple of
19.63 rather than 14.63, each share would in fact be worth $57.44.
Overall, Verizon would have a market value of about $156 billion
rather than the $116 billion it currently enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   All else being equal, Verizon's earnings multiple probably
suffers by ``a couple of points'' relative even to SBC or the
BellSouth Corp., said Strumingher, because of the strength of
Verizon's unions and the presumed reduction in productivity they
cause. Just two points of earnings multiple costs Verizon about $16
billion in market value.
</P>
<P>
   None of this will come as a surprise to Verizon's senior
management. They know it all too well. Now, there is nothing they
can do about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
