u p BC-BUSH-MILITARY-HNS &LR;      08-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WOULD SEEK $1 BILLION PAY RAISE FOR MILITARY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Lamenting that the next president ``will inherit a
military in decline,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Monday he
will seek a $1 billion pay raise for the Armed Forces and boost
funding for school districts that serve military bases _ with $60
million going to four Texas communities.
</P>
<P>
   In an address to the 7,000 delegates at the national convention
of the Veterans of Foreign Wars, Bush said his ``urgent goal'' as
president will be to ``rebuild the military power of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed the Armed Forces as short on readiness and long on
problems, including low morale, deployment fatigue, inadequate
housing and health care and paltry pay.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal would bolster the $75 billion military pay increase
signed into law by President Clinton last month. It would amount to
a $750 annual pay hike per service member. But inadequate pay isn't
the only issue, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current administration inherited a military ready for the
dangers and challenges facing our nation. The next president will
inherit a military in decline,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the best intentions of those in uniform, Bush said the
military is ``undermined by back-to-back deployments, poor pay,
shortages of spare parts and equipment and rapidly declining
readiness. Our investment in national security is at the lowest it
has been since Pearl Harbor,'' he said to a crowd that included
people who survived that attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall commitments around the world have tripled while our
forces have been reduced by nearly 40 percent,'' he said. Since
Clinton took office in 1992, ``full readiness'' among Air Force
combat units has declined from 85 percent to 65 percent, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were reminded of readiness problems last May, when the USS
Decatur was forced to return to port a month earlier than planned
for lack of funds. Think of it: a guided missile destroyer of the
U.S. Navy turning back because there was not enough money for
fuel,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific fleet, training exercises have been cut back for
the same reason and in the Atlantic fleet, 21 warships need
maintenance that has been delayed or canceled, Bush said. But other
service branches have woes, too, he said. In addition to old
equipment, both the Army and Air Force have had trouble meeting
recruiting goals, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what's said in the political campaign. These are
signs of a military in decline and we must do something about it,''
Bush stated.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway responded that the
administration signed a 4.8 percent military pay raise last year,
and that Gore supports a 3.7 percent increase this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush's proposed tax cuts would use up too much of the
federal budget surplus to allow for increased military pay or
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Chris Lehane noted Gore's service in Vietnam _ an
unstated comparison with Bush's Vietnam-era service in the Texas
Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore volunteered, served and enlisted in Vietnam,'' he
said. ``He has a real understanding based on his own personal
experiences of what type of support our military personnel need and
desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to address the VFW convention Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments to the veterans Monday, Bush said the neglect of
the military extends to the schools that serve 700,000 students who
are dependents of soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of under-funding, many of these schools are run
down and in need of repair. I will ask Congress for $310 million
needed to repair and construct schools that will educate the
children of the men and women who wear our nation's uniforms,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of the National Military Impacted Schools
Association, Bush offered the $310 million to 20 of the neediest
districts so they can upgrade their campuses. Bush's plan would
provide Killeen ISD, which serves Fort Hood, with $17.8 million and
three districts that serve bases in San Antonio _ Lackland,
Randolph and Fort Sam Houston _ with a total of $51 million.
</P>
<P>
   After unveiling his military proposals to the VFW, Bush
journeyed to Des Moines, Iowa to visit a public school and raise
funds at an Iowa GOP-sponsored event. Tuesday he campaigns in
Peoria, Ill., and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thrilled that the governor has proposed this. It's
something we've been asking for for years. We could definitely use
the help,'' said Killeen Superintendent Charles Patterson, whose
district maintains eight campuses on Fort Hood in Central Texas.
Two are in dire need of improvements, he said, including a
1975-vintage middle school with 20 portable classrooms and a
1950-era elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent John Deegan of Bellevue, Neb., who heads the
association for military-impacted schools, also hailed the proposal
and chastized President Clinton for not seeking such funds earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased. President Clinton as commander in chief
has shocked people by not fully funding the impact aid,'' Deegan
said, adding that Congress hasn't bolstered impact-aid programs
that originated in the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's scrambling right now because the buildings are
40-50 years old,'' said Deegan, whose district serves Offutt Air
Force Base. Money used for facilities is usually drained away from
education programs, he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
