u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK SEEKS TO LIMIT USE OF RELIGIOUS PRIVILEGES IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Surprising even some of his closest political
associates and enraging his ultra-Orthodox opponents, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak informed his supporters during the weekend that
he planned to push a ``civil reform'' through parliament that,
among other things, would strip the Jewish religious establishment
of many privileges and powers.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected announcement, coming at a time Barak faces a
fast-approaching deadline in talks with the Palestinians and
several political challenges at home, left much of the country
wondering about his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that he was setting the scene for new elections
and others theorized that he was pressuring the opposition to
support his dealings with the Palestinians, who have threatened to
unilaterally proclaim a Palestinian state by Sept. 13 if a
settlement has not been negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Barak announced his proposal after summoning ministers and
legislators from his One Israel coalition to a meeting late
Saturday. He told them of a sweeping plan that would strengthen the
secular nature of Israeli society at the cost of entrenched Jewish
rights woven into the country's social and political fabric since
its founding in 1948. Israeli commentators said that the plan posed
one of the most serious political challenges ultra-Orthodox parties
have faced in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Barak pledged to introduce a new
constitution guaranteeing a full range of political, social and
religious freedoms that would create greater equality between Jews
and non-Jews. In addition, he promised to dismantle the religious
affairs ministry, introduce a bill allowing for civil marriages
that would be beyond the control of the rabbinate and sponsor bills
promoting the status of women.
</P>
<P>
   He also outlined a ``comprehensive national service bill'' that
would require all young Israelis, including members of
ultra-Orthodox groups now exempted from military service, to sign
up for two years of nonmilitary work directed by the government.
Finally, he pledged to impose a curriculum for all state-financed
schools, including those run by ultra-Orthodox groups, that would
include classes in subjects they have shunned, including civics,
mathematics and English.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's continuing political problems were also compounded
Monday when a second aide in his secretariat resigned. Haim
Mendel-Shaked, one of Barak's old army friends, quit his
administrative post as director of Barak's office. His resignation
was considered a symbolic and psychological setback because Shaked
had been loyal to Barak for many years. He was the second member of
Barak's office to quit following the resignation last week of his
own deputy, Shimon Batat.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts in Israeli newspapers on Monday about Barak's weekend
meeting said that many of those who attended were stunned. The
accounts said this was partly because Barak had kept his plans to
himself before the weekend meeting, compounding complaints that he
had become increasingly isolated from his top officials and
ministers in the weeks leading up to, and since, the deadlocked
Camp David peace talks with the Palestinians last month.
</P>
<P>
   By forging ahead with a peace plan that offered greater
concessions to the Palestinians on Jerusalem and other key issues
that right-wing and ultra-Orthodox parties were prepared to
support, Barak in effect sacrificed his ruling coalition, which
began to disintegrate before he left for Camp David. Now, with
barely 40 of the 120 members of the Israeli parliament still firmly
behind him, he has taken another step, posing a challenge to the
power of the religious establishment, that Israeli commentators
view as politically risky and even quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   These commentators offered several possible explanations for
Barak's move. Some said he had abandoned hope of achieving peace
with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and thus felt free to
adopt domestic policies that would end any prospect that right-wing
and ultra-Orthodox parties that quit his coalition before Camp
David would agree to return to his government.
</P>
<P>
   Others said that Barak had realized that the only chance of
winning support for a peace agreement rested on a re-alignment of
Israeli politics that consolidated the power of secular forces.
Still another view was that Barak, facing the probability of a new
election in the next six months, and increasingly doubtful of
having a peace agreement that could secure victory, had decided his
best chance rested with a bold new plan for reforming Israeli
society from within.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of the Saturday meeting said that it broke up in
disarray, with some of Barak's closest political allies expressing
grave doubts about his proposals, and others vigorous opposition.
One newspaper, Yedioth Ahronoth, said one of the strongest dissents
came from Shimon Peres, a former prime minister who won the Nobel
Peace Prize for helping to initiate the 1993 Oslo accords that
provided the foundation for the current peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper commentators said the changes had no hope of passing
the Israeli parliament, where Barak's government faces a right-wing
opposition galvanized by the concessions on Jerusalem and other
issues that Barak offered at Camp David. Although other prime
ministers from the secular, left-wing political spectrum that Barak
represents have tried and failed to achieve some of these reforms
before, these critics said, none had ever sought to accomplish so
much in one swoop, especially from a weak political position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
