<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINS FOR BOTH SIDES SEEN IN VERIZON SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From wage increases to greater pension benefits to less
mandatory overtime, telecommunications union workers in 12 Eastern
states from Maine to Virginia and the District of Columbia appear
to have been the victors in the strike that ended Monday for more
than half of the 86,000 workers who walked off their jobs 16 days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the unions' agreement with Verizon Communications,
the nation's largest telecommunications employer, with 260,000
employees around the nation, touches many of the hot-button issues
of the New Economy _ including stock options, profit sharing and
the relentlessness of long work days.
</P>
<P>
   As the company tried to bring the remaining 40,000 or so
strikers in several mid-Atlantic states into the fold Monday, labor
and management experts were marveling at a settlement that is
generous by almost any measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge victory for the unions because it shows what
they can do in parts of the economy where they still have
leverage,'' said Paul Osterman, a professor of management at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``But I suppose it remains
to be seen how this plays out in wireless organizing, the most
tantalizing part of the agreement, because that's where unions have
far less leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it was one matter for the Communications Workers of
America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers to
go on strike against Verizon, a company formed by the merger of
Bell Atlantic and GTE. The strike involved workers in the union's
stronghold _ the region formerly served by Bell Atlantic. But it is
quite another task to begin organizing at the company's wireless
division, where fewer than 50 of 32,000 employees around the
country are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the unions won concessions that should make it easier to
try to recruit union members at the unit, Verizon Wireless _ the
issue that was at the heart of the strike. The unions, particularly
the Communications Workers of America, are intent on organizing
workers at the mobile-telephone company, which is operated in a
venture with Vodafone AirTouch of Britain. Verizon Wireless is the
nation's largest wireless carrier, with more than 25 million
subscribers, and it is growing much faster than Verizon's
conventional telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it is too early to gauge how the union effort might
play out with the wireless unit, where organizing is not expected
to begin in earnest for six months or so. The union will no doubt
be pointing to wage disparities between some workers. Customer
service representatives can make no more than $33,000 a year at
Verizon Wireless, but as much as $44,400 for Verizon's union
telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   While the natural inclination of Wall Street is to associate
union jobs with higher costs, some analysts say greater
unionization could have a potentially positive impact in some parts
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, for example, won a concession from the company
allowing their members to perform the entire installation of
high-speed Internet access for customers who sign up for Verizon's
Internet services. (Wholesale installations performed by Verizon
under other companies' names would not necessarily be performed by
union workers, according to a person involved in the talks.) Union
members are expected to be able to complete an installation in
about one day, instead of the two days it can sometimes take when
Verizon uses nonunion contractors to perform some of the tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shorter installation cycle should quicken Verizon's
deployment of access,'' said Joseph Bellace, an analyst at
Jefferies &AMP; Co. who covers companies providing high-speed Internet
access. ``It sort of surprises me that this hasn't happened
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon officials, too, sought to put a positive spin on the
unions' new contract. ``I'm thoroughly confident this will enhance
our competitiveness,'' Lawrence T. Babbio, vice-chairman of
Verizon, said in an interview. ``We've found ways to motivate our
employees on a performance basis that will also reduce churn within
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In another move that could speed Verizon's effort to transform
itself, the company created a profit-sharing plan _ pegged to that
of the chief executive, Ivan Seidenberg _ that would provide
provide payouts of up to $1,000 a year per employee.
</P>
<P>
   And adopting a benefit similar to the nonunion companies that
Verizon competes with in many parts of its business, the company
will hand out a small number of stock options to union members in
an effort to further interest them in Verizon's overall financial
performance and efficiency. Full-time employees will receive a
one-time grant of 100 stock options, while part-time employees will
receive 50.
</P>
<P>
   As union members absorb details of the agreement before meeting
to vote on its approval over the next three weeks, the company and
financial analysts mainly seem relieved that the strike is
effectively over. Verizon said it had a backlog of some 78,000
repair orders, with about 38,000 of these including people with no
service at all and 40,000 with some sort of trouble like static on
the line.
</P>
<P>
   And there is an estimated backlog of 200,000 orders for new
installations of service, which Verizon hopes to clear up in about
a month. This estimate anticipates an increase in orders as
students return to universities along the East Coast in coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how good the agreement looks to the unions, Verizon
nipped the real risk of the strike in the bud by ending it before
it entered into September,'' said Courtney Quinn, an analyst at the
Yankee Group, a telecommunications consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors expressed mild optimism Monday, voting up Verizon's
shares 69 cents Monday, to a closing price of $42.81.
</P>
</TEXT>
