<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HURRICANES0822-COX     08-21 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANES0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take notice: Hurricane season about to enter its busiest time
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - South Florida is entering the busiest
part of the hurricane season _ and it's in your best interest to
take notice. Now is the time to do all those things you were
supposed to do in May, but haven't.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two months without a swirl to speak of, four
named storms have formed since Alberto on Aug. 4. The two weeks or
so on either side of Sept. 10 represent the height of the season,
so you can expect at least the threat of a hurricane at least once
in the next three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you'll be looking at a hurricane warning as early as the
end of the week, if Debby aims our way. Perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   If Debby, or any other storm, threatens South Florida in the
coming weeks, and you wait until a watch or warning has been
issued, you can expect to be fighting for plywood, batteries and
water.
</P>
<P>
   In seven of the last 10 years, at least one tropical storm or
hurricane either made landfall in the Palm Beach County-Treasure
Coast-Glades region or got close enough to spark a hurricane watch
or warning. That means in seven of the last 10 years you've had to
perform at least the minimal preparations.
</P>
<P>
   If you wait, ``all the other folks that haven't made plans are
doing the same thing you are,'' Palm Beach County Emergency Manager
Bill O'Brien said. ``You're going to be busy enough at the final
moments doing the things you have to do then.''
</P>
<P>
   And Keith Holman, O'Brien's Martin County counterpart, said,
``When we talk about storms, they're always somewhere else. It's
always some other time or some other place. (But) everything coming
off the African coast is heading east to west, any of which has the
potential to land in your back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you can be doing now, tonight (there's plenty of
daylight this time of year):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go to the Internet: www.storm2000.com/getready/. If you can do
neither, at least grab one of those hurricane map/tips brochures
the television stations provide at the grocery store, library and
other locations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clear your yard of all that junk that's been lying around for
months: bricks, toys, that rusted-out lawn chair you keep meaning
to throw out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unless your vegetation pickup date is today it may already be
too late to trim trees of loose branches and fronds and drag them
out to the curb. If Debby threatens the region and a watch or
warning is issued in the next few days, crews may not do pickups.
Even if they do, they won't be wanting to collect a lot of
material, so you'll just be creating big piles of potential
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Load up on the batteries, water, canned goods, and other
supplies that will disappear in minutes if a storm approaches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make a list of the last-minute things you'll do; bringing in
lawn furniture and potted plants, freezing water, charging
batteries, etc.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check that you have all the proper mounting equipment for your
window coverings. If not, head to the hardware store now.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unless you're in an area that probably will be evacuated, plan
on riding out the storm at home. Have a safe room in mind. If
that's not an option, be looking for a friend to take you in. If
you insist on leaving the region, remember gridlock is a real
possibility. Leaving now, when there's no direct threat, is just a
waste of time, effort and money, but you can plan your route and
check hotel rooms now. A shelter is an absolute last resort. If
that's your case, check for the nearest one now and know how to get
to it. It won't take your pet, so be looking for a kennel that
will.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you haven't already, make plans for your boat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you live in a mobile home park or condominium, review
hurricane plans and check with managers or neighborhood captains.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you have all the insurance papers and other
documents you'll need should the storm hit. You may want to do a
video-walk around the home to create a record of your belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Email: eliotkleinberg(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
