<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY LEADERS MEET, BUT OFFER LITTLE RELIEF FROM AIR DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beleaguered airline passengers looking for
immediate relief from a summer of record delays and cancellations
received scant hope Monday from a meeting of airline executives,
labor unions, industry groups and the government.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was hastily called earlier this month by
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater to discuss ways of improving
air travel in the face of a growing outcry from passengers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference following the meeting, Slater, flanked by
several of the participants, announced three initiatives but
admitted that none of them would have a significant impact before
the fall, when air travel traditionally diminishes after the peak
summer season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest accomplishment of today's meeting is that we have
stated our shared commitment and expressed our renewed effort _ all
of the participants here _ to improve our service to the American
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said that the meeting did succeed in
setting a more cooperative tone between groups that have tended to
blame each other for recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   For example, airline executives have attributed most of this
summer's difficulties to stormy weather, an antiquated air traffic
system and covert protests by pilots and machinists, especially at
United Airlines, which has had by far the worst on-time performance
of the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers and some government officials have
accused the airlines of scheduling too many flights that leave at
the same times, overwhelming air traffic capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that I found for myself that's different from
anything I have ever experienced is a commitment to really pay some
attention to this issue,'' said David Z. Plavin, the president of
the Airports Council International, a trade association
representing major airport operators, including the Port Authority
of New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But Plavin and others warned that there is no magic solution to
an infrastructure problem that is going to take years to correct.
``It's an evolutionary process,'' he warned. ``That's not an easy
sell to the public but this is enormously complex stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Plavin, the meeting was attended by, among
others, executives from nine major airlines and eight labor unions
representing virtually all airline and airport workers from pilots,
to flight attendants to air traffic controllers. Slater said that
he would host another meeting next week with regional airlines and
consumer advocates, who had complained that they were excluded from
Monday's summit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new initiatives announced Monday, Slater pledged to
make the transportation department work more aggressively to help
the airlines exchange information about practices that improve
customer service. He also appointed a deputy to lead a task force
that will report back to him in 90 days with ideas for improving
the information about quality of service, such as statistics about
on-time performance and lost baggage, that the department receives
from airlines and passes on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Slater said that the Federal Aviation Administration,
which operates the country's air traffic system, had undertaken 20
initiatives to improve the performance at seven ``choke points''
around the country that are often responsible for causing delays.
Many of the improvements, such as redesigning air space around
frequently congested cities like New York, Boston and Cleveland,
will take years. However, Slater said that 11 of the improvements
could be instituted by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. McNally, president of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, said that the changes would not make much
of a difference. ``Everything is a tweak,'' he said in an interview
after the meeting. ``We are just trying to add a few percentage
points to a system that is pretty much maxed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added that the meeting left him hopeful that the
various industry players could begin a new era of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of that will be how fast United can negotiate new
contracts with its pilots and machinists. A portion of Monday's
meeting focused on how to speed up bargaining in the industry,
which often can extend for years.
</P>
<P>
   Since airline workers are prohibited from striking until given
permission by a federal mediator, many workers express their
displeasure by refusing to fly overtime, working to rules, or
calling in sick. United has said such protests by its pilots and
mechanics have forced it to cancel thousands of flights.
</P>
<P>
   The unions have repeatedly denied they have orchestrated any job
actions. Asked at Monday's new conference about the impact the
protests have had on consumers, Robert Roach Jr., vice president of
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
said: ``Machinists never use job actions to aggravate consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
