</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deep in One Part of Texas
</P>
<P>
   Weighing in on Robert Altman's fashion satire, ``Ready to
Wear,'' six years ago, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``Beyond being so slack, the bleached, hazy `Ready to Wear' commits
the cardinal fashion sin: it doesn't even look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics might have a hard time leveling that particular
complaint about Altman's newest movie, ``Dr. T and the Women,''
which opens in a few weeks and stars Richard Gere as a Dallas
gynecologist who ministers to the kind of women (played by Laura
Dern, Kate Hudson and Farrah Fawcett, among others) who wear
rose-colored mink cuffs on their wrists and ostrich-feathered hats
to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Dona Granata as costume designer, Altman, it
seems, has made his true fashion movie. To research the kind of
Texas woman the director was trying to portray, Granata spent time
going to Dallas fund-raisers and taking notes at Stanley Korshak,
the city's well-known upmarket specialty store. In fact, a
saleswoman in bridal wear there ended up with a role in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the young women are very much in the New York black
mode,'' Granata observed, ``but they'll put on some outrageous shoe
or a really big piece of jewelry, and that wouldn't happen in New
York. In Dallas, surgery starts young and diamonds are a girl's
best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are Dior bags, Dior miniskirt suits, stamped leather
jackets from Escada and various outrageously styled numbers from
St. John. Of one especially garish number worn by Laura Dern _ a
fur-trimmed road-sign-yellow cape with matching fur-trimmed
stiletto boots _ Granata said: ``Women were actually buying that.
It's real. I didn't make it up.''
</P>
<P>
   A World of Talent
</P>
<P>
   When New York Fashion Week gets under way in the middle of next
month, this premier showcase for American fashion will feel, well,
slightly less American than usual. ``What we're doing is a kind of
international summit,'' Fern Mallis, executive director of Seventh
on Sixth, which organizes Fashion Week, said the other day. The 10
days of men's and women's shows begin on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday Sept. 16 and throughout the following week, an
unprecedented number of little-known designers from around the
world will show their clothes in Bryant Park, among other sites.
They are coming from Hong Kong, Portugal, Brazil, South Africa and
Nigeria. The five African designers _ one from Nigeria and four
from South Africa _ are the winners of a continent-wide design
competition that had Mark Eisen, a Seventh Avenue designer by way
of South Africa, as a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all been coming and calling and wanting to show in New
York,'' Mallis said.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from this international jamboree, Lizzy Disney, a British
designer, will be part of Moet &AMP; Chandon's Designer Debut show.
Also, the Parisian Nicolas Ghesquiere, the designer for Balenciaga,
will show his line for the Italian label Callaghan for the first
time here as well.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Jacobs, Major and Minor
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists might see it an effort to ward off the
foreign invasion: the quintessentially American designer Marc
Jacobs is holding not one show this coming season, but two.
</P>
<P>
   In September, in addition to his Marc Jacobs line, the designer
will inaugurate his secondary line, which, assuming trademark
issues are hammered out, will be called Marc. (Doom-sayers will
remember that Isaac Mizrahi's ill-fated secondary line was called
Isaac.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're missing a segment of the population because of
our price point,'' Robert Duffy, president of Jacobs' company,
explained. That segment of the population includes the many who see
no reason to pay $800 for a Marc Jacobs sweater.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, Duffy said, will be priced below those of most
secondary lines _ probably below $200 for that sweater. It will
feature knits, shoes and bags, among other pieces. ``It's modeled
after the way people we know dress,'' Duffy continued. ``No one
wears designer head to toe.''
</P>
<P>
   The line will be shown at the Stuart Parr gallery in Manhattan
with the help of Juergen Teller photographs and about two dozen
live models.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
