<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FASHION-FIFTH-AVENUE-     08-21 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FIFTH-AVENUE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING LUXURY TO FIFTH AVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One bright afternoon last week, at the Prada store on
Fifth Avenue, two young women who appeared to share the same
parents and the same attitudes about highly elective surgery,
passed a baby and platform shoes back and forth between them. With
some fall shoes already sold out, they gave up and moved downstairs
to the handbag section. ``I have the Chanel, I have the Louis, I
have the Gucci,'' said the redhead to the brunette, as a saleswoman
showed them a burgundy bowling bag. ``I want tan,'' said the
redhead. ``I need tan.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women seemed to defy the conventional thinking about
just who the Fifth Avenue shopper is. First, as locals, they were
in full command of the English language, and second, they were
spending actual money in a place that displayed not a single Tweety
Bird athletic sock.
</P>
<P>
   While certain New Yorkers continue to lament the downscaling of
the stretch of Fifth Avenue from Rockefeller Center to Grand Army
Plaza _ its amusement-park feeling, the out-of-towners in their
Easy Spirits _ it has become harder to argue that the blocks have
been abandoned to the tastes of those eager to dine at Hooters.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 4, Gucci will re-open on Fifth Avenue at 54th Street
after an extensive 17-month remodeling, unveiling a new limestone
facade, an interior by the architect William Sofield and 13,000
square feet of space in which to sell the label's $800 boots and
chevron mink coats. In December, Louis Vuitton will open a
6,000-square-foot store, about the size of its Beverly Hills
boutique on Rodeo Drive, one block north of Gucci. Both Bergdorf
Goodman and Cartier are in the midst of overhauls. Saks Fifth
Avenue is undergoing a $100 million renovation that will add 40,000
square feet of sales space to the store's flagship, including an
expanded fine jewelry section, when complete in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   What all of this amounts to in the minds of some retailers and
shoppers is that Fifth Avenue is reclaiming something of its
resplendent past. In a symbolic shift, several months ago the
Coca-Cola store on 55th Street _ the first of the avenue's theme
stores, which opened in 1992 _ shut its doors . Its former space is
occupied temporarily by Cartier while it spiffs up its longtime
home, three blocks south at 52nd Street. ``It's still a
world-renowned shopping destination,'' Pat Malone, the president of
Gucci America, said of Fifth Avenue. ``You see the resurgence of
luxury brands here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gucci, long a Fifth Avenue resident, briefly considered joining
the luxury exodus to upper Madison Avenue before deciding to stay
put. It is the sort of logic with which John Slavinsky, the senior
vice president for stores of Louis Vuitton, would not argue.
Slavinsky compared the company's decision to open a store on Fifth
Avenue to its decision to move one in Paris from a quiet street to
the more clamorous Champs-Elysees two years ago. Sales there
increased about 50 percent, Slavinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, Madison is where you put a third store,''
Slavinsky said. (Louis Vuitton put its first New York store in
SoHo.) ``We wanted to be in a place with a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation in the commercial real-estate world that
the Warner Brothers store on Fifth Avenue and 57th Street, a mighty
symbol of Fifth Avenue as theme park, may move well before the
expiration of its lease in five years. The speculation is driven by
the fact that the theme-store business has been slackening (Warner
has closed four stores in 18 months) and that the building housing
its nine-story emporium was purchased in March by Allied Partners,
a development firm. A representative of Allied, which could
theoretically buy out the Warner Brothers lease, would not comment.
A spokeswoman for Warner Brothers, when asked if there were plans
to close the store, said, ``Not that I'm aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, Fifth Avenue started its descent toward lowbrow well
before the theme stores ever arrived _ back in the late 1960s, '70s
and '80s, when discreet stores like De Pinna and Peck &AMP; Peck
stopped selling their establishment tweeds. Peck &AMP; Peck had opened
on Fifth Avenue and 48th Street in 1907, pioneering upscale
retailers' shift from the East 20s and 30s to what was then
considered ``upper'' Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the '90s, with the arrival of Barneys New York on
the Upper East Side, the focus shifted again, this time to Madison
Avenue above 61st Street, where rents in recent years have caught
up to what they are on Fifth, about $600 a square foot, said Faith
Hope Consolo, the vice chairwoman of Garrick-Aug Worldwide, a
real-estate consulting company. The renewed interest in Fifth,
Consolo said, has much to do with a heightened understanding among
retailers of the modern shopper's habits, whether she is from
Westport, Conn., or Duesseldorf. ``There's no pure luxury
anymore,'' Consolo said. ``There's no pure shopper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who shops at Chanel also shops at H&AMP;M,'' she said,
referring to the inexpensive Swedish clothier drawing crowds on
Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Consolo, who bids on store spaces for retail clients, makes it
her business to know how well purveyors of expensive clothes do
once they land on Fifth. The Prada store between 56th and 57th
Streets on Fifth achieves sales four times greater per square foot
than at Prada's Madison Avenue store, Consolo said. She said that
when the men's clothier Ermenegildo Zegna opened on Fifth near
57th, it increased its wholesale business by about 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Tom Cusick, the president of the Fifth Avenue
Association, ``the whole notion that Fifth turned down a mass path
is overblown.'' As head of the association, a group of merchants
and property owners, Cusick would not be expected to say otherwise;
but he does point out that while many spent the '90s whining about
the end of a recherche Fifth Avenue, the decade saw the arrival of
a fair number of high-end stores. Prada replaced a Doubleday
bookstore on Fifth. Fendi took the place of a Hallmark card store.
</P>
<P>
   Giulia Melucci, a publicist at Scribner, who was walking up
Fifth not long ago, felt that merchants like the National
Basketball Association had been gaining on the avenue until
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked past H&AMP;M,'' she said, ``and I saw that big sign
announcing a new Louis Vuitton across the street and I thought,
`What does it all mean?' It means that Fifth is a democracy, not
purely elite, not purely crass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
