<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-NYT     08-21 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TO DEAL EWING TO SEATTLE IN MULTI-TEAM SHUFFLE 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the stoic, 7-foot center who for 15 years hoped
to be the player to bring a National Basketball Association
championship to the Knicks,  &UR;  &LR; was instead on the cusp of being
traded to the Seattle SuperSonics Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old veteran, whose arrival in 1985 revived the
floundering club, was the centerpiece of a blockbuster deal that
included four teams and more than a dozen players, an NBA official
said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer of monster, multi-team deals that involved some of
the game's most prominent players _ Grant Hill ended up in Orlando
while Shawn Kemp was dealt to Portland _ the deal for Ewing may be
the most immense and most complicated. According to the NBA
official, the announcement of the trade was held up in early
evening because the Pistons were re-examining the financial
implications of bringing in so many players. But, the official
said, the deal was not in danger of collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   In the trade, Ewing would go to Seattle, while the Knicks would
acquire forward Vin Baker from the Super Sonics and Glen Rice and
Travis Knight from the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, in turn, would receive Chris Dudley from New York
and Christian Laettner from Detroit. The fourth team in the deal,
the Pistons were attempting to reduce their payroll so that they
could land a top-tier free agent next summer. They would take a
number of role players from the three teams, including Vernon
Maxwell, Lazaro Borrell, Greg Foster, Vladimir Stepania, John
Celestand, Tyronne Lue and David Wingate.
</P>
<P>
   After dealing Baker, the Sonics are expected to sign free agent
power forward Maurice Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dominating post players in the NBA's modern era,
Ewing was the Knicks' No. 1 selection in the 1985 college draft.
They won the pick that season by winning the NBA's first draft
lottery; it was a day that sent long-suffering fans cheering into
the streets of Manhattan with the knowledge that the Knicks would
select the scowling, shot-blocking menace from Georgetown
University. Ewing would lead the Knicks into the playoffs 13
straight years. With him, the Knicks advanced to the Eastern
Conference finals three times. In 1994, the team came within a game
of winning the franchise's first title since 1973, when they lost
to the Houston Rockets in a seven game championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Holder of most major Knicks records, Ewing ended last season as
the 14th-leading scorer in league history. He is fourth in blocked
shots and he played in his 1,000th game last season. Ewing is one
of seven players in NBA annals to spend 15 years with the same
team.
</P>
<P>
   If his longevity was impressive, though, his durability was
wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three seasons, he missed 88 regular-season games
because of injuries _ from a dislocated right wrist to a partial
tear in his left Achilles tendon _ and his production was severely
limited by his health. Ewing's injuries put him out of the 1999
championship series against the San Antonio Spurs, which the Knicks
lost in five games. He began last season on the injury list. Still,
Ewing came back and silenced his critics for most of the regular
season. He started 62 games, dutifully took on a reduced role in an
offense suddenly powered by Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   But as the playoffs came, the old question re-emerged both
inside and outside the locker room: Were the Knicks better off
without Ewing? The plodding half-court style played by the aging
7-footer came to be viewed as a blight to the Knicks' new,
high-octane outfit. Ewing missed two games of the Eastern
Conference finals series against the Indiana Pacers because of his
Achilles problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was scheduled to make $14 million this season, the last
installment of a four-year, $68 million contract signed in 1997.
The Knicks balked when it came to talk of a contract extension
beyond this season, a development that forced Ewing and David Falk,
his agent, to consider other options.
</P>
<P>
   After giving Scott Layden, the general manager, a list of eight
teams he would agree to play for, Ewing waited for the Knicks to
make their move.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months ago, the trade seemed highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for us to get back to the finals, Patrick has to be
part of this team,'' Layden declared when asked if Ewing would be
moved.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed end of the Ewing era begets even more questions for
the franchise's future. Baker, a member of the 2000 U.S. Olympic
team who is coming off two subpar seasons, will fill the club's
need at power forward.
</P>
<P>
   But with no bona-fide center to guard players such as Alonzo
Mourning of Miami and the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal, the Knicks are
at a distinct disadvantage in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   There was much conversation around the league about the Knicks
parting ways with their franchise center, the oft-maligned, aging
veteran who never delivered the championship to New York he so
desperately wanted _ and thus never earned the adoration of the
fans he so desperately coveted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sad,'' O'Neal said when informed of the trade. ``You
always thought Patrick Ewing would retire in New York. That's what
everyone thought.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
