<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STL     08-21 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKESNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN BLAMES MILITARY CUTBACKS FOR FAILURE OF KURSK MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update, rewrite and expand by 1200 words.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Speaking in somber tones and at times struggling for
words, Russia's defense minister, Marshal Igor Sergeyev, on Monday
night defended the military's failure to rescue the crew of the
stricken nuclear submarine Kursk by saying that the armed forces of
the once powerful Soviet empire had been ``robbed and stripped'' in
the last decade and were operating on half the budget they
required.
</P>
<P>
   After divers finally gained entry to the wreck of the Kursk on
Monday and declared it completely flooded and its 118-member crew
dead, the 68-year-old officer said he did not exclude the
possibility that the military might have made some mistakes in the
rescue drama. But ``no principle mistakes were made,'' he insisted,
and he argued that foreign assistance might not have helped to save
the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk went down in 350 feet of water after unexplained but
powerful explosions sundered its hull during military exercises in
the Barents Sea on Aug. 12. Russian officials are investigating
whether it was involved in a collision with an unidentified vessel,
or perhaps struck an old mine or was scuttled by some internal
defect.
</P>
<P>
   In a day marked by expressions of remorse, confession and
resolution to solve the mysteries of the sinking of one of Russia's
most advanced warships, the commander of Russia's northern fleet,
Adm. Vyacheslav Popov, went on television to ask forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the best submarine crew in the northern fleet,'' he
said, adding, with eyes cast downward, ``Forgive the children.
Forgive your sons. And forgive me for not bringing back your
boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev's words were less contrite, and seemed in part an
attempt to quell the political storm that has laid siege to the
government of President Vladimir Putin for not making a more timely
request for Western assistance, and for withholding or distorting
information about the circumstances in which the submarine went
down and the fate of the sailors trapped in its nine compartments.
</P>
<P>
   And with fresh suggestions that a foreign submarine may have
been involved in a collision with the Kursk, Russian officials
betrayed some of the frustration and mistrust that were the
hallmark of the Cold War, even as an extraordinary collaboration
among British, Norwegian and Russian sailors unfolded in the Arctic
Sea _ most famous as a long-running venue for the silent war of cat
and mouse between rival fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who remained on vacation at a Black Sea resort during
most of the frantic rescue operation, made no public appearance
Monday. But Sergeyev, 68, in a nationally televised interview,
announced that all submarines of the Kursk's class would stay in
port until it was determined what caused the explosions that
wrecked the Kursk and sent her crashing into the seabed during
missile- and torpedo-firing maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not excluded that some mistakes were made, but as it
seems to me now,'' Sergeyev said, ``no principle mistakes were
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he added, ``we have to rise above emotions, and
coldly and scrupulously investigate the entire path of making and
carrying out decisions,'' however ``serious the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``the whole reason'' Russia lacked deep-sea diving
and rescue equipment in the northern fleet was the pathetic state
of funding. ``The navy is really in decrepit shape,'' said Mark
Kramer, a Russian specialist at the Davis Center for Russian
Studies at Harvard University. ``A lot of the best people have been
leaving because they don't get paid. Only a tiny percentage of the
navy is at sea at any one time.'' Most ships, he said, ``are in
repairs or left in port to rust.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian sailors are paid $50 to $90 per month and schools in
naval towns last winter complained of 40-degree temperatures in
classrooms, where heat and electricity supplies are often
interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the rescue operation Monday followed fruitless
attempts by Norwegian divers on Sunday to open the rear escape
hatch on the Kursk. A plan to yank the hatch off by force using a
crane was deferred as divers descended again Monday morning and
succeeded first in opening the outer hatch to the escape chamber,
which was flooded and empty, and then the inner hatch to the ninth
compartment, which they also found flooded. The body of a Russian
sailor was reported to be just inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found that the whole submarine is full of water,'' a
Norwegian military spokesman, John Epsen Lien, said in Oslo,
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Russia requested that Norway help recover the bodies, but the
owners of the diving vessel, Stolt Offshore, said it might be too
dangerous for their men to enter the ship. Russian navy officials
said they would try to negotiate a contract to carry out the
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall cooperate with the Norwegians as before,'' said Vice
Admiral Mikhail Motsak, chief of staff of the northern fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In response to criticism that Russian officials waited too long
to seek Western assistance, Sergeyev said that as soon as it became
apparent last Wednesday that the Russian navy desperately needed
help to open an escape hatch on the Kursk, he personally made the
``political decision,'' on the recommendation of Navy Commander
Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, to ask for help and then informed Putin,
who concurred.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev also disclosed new information to support what he
characterized as a strong suspicion on the part of Russian military
and civilian leaders that the Kursk collided with another submarine
that also suffered severe damage, but managed to escape.
</P>
<P>
   He said that at the moment that Russian navy vessels were
identifying the shattered hull of the Kursk at 6:40 p.m. on Aug. 13
_ more than 30 hours after Western sensors detected two explosions
in the area where the submarine was operating _ a second submerged
object, probably a submarine, was detected lying near the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   Russian lookouts on two ships observed a signal buoy, not of
Russian origin, that is used by Western fleets to send emergency
messages by satellite transmission to their command base. Attempts
to retrieve the buoy failed in high seas, Sergeyev said. His
comments confirmed a report Friday from a Russian television
correspondent, Arkady Mamontov, who said that military officials
told him that the mystery buoy was green and white. Russian
emergency buoys, he said, were red and white.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that lookouts spotted the signal buoy, Sergeyev
said, arriving Russian warships detected and ``directly observed
the object itself on the bottom of the ocean that was of equal
height of our submarine. This is a fact.'' Sergeyev then ordered
the navy to send a ``hydrographic vessel with more powerful
equipment'' to search for the mystery ship near the Kursk, ``but
this object was not found.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared from his remarks that, in the early stages of the
rescue operation, Russian navy officials were not only organizing
the attempted rescue of the Kursk crew, but were also seeking to
apprehend a foreign submarine that they suspected was involved in a
collision.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news agency on Monday quoted an unidentified
military official in Moscow as saying that an object resembling
``the barrier of a foreign submarine tower'' had been discovered
lying on the seabed less than 1,000 feet from the Kursk. The
official said it was ``premature to draw any conclusions before
studying the object'' which ``may have been lying on the bed of the
Barents Sea for a long time,'' but the statement was another
confirmation that the Russian military is actively scouring the
seabed for evidence that might shed light on its collision theory.
</P>
<P>
   The American and British governments have categorically denied
that any of their submarines or surface vessels were involved in a
collision with the Russian vessel, but it was also apparent that
both governments were withholding information under their own
longstanding practice of refusing to comment on submarine spying
operations directed at the Russian fleet.
</P>
<P>
   When Russian officials at NATO headquarters inquired whether
``even one ship was there where the accident took place, they told
us no, there were no NATO ships there,'' Sergeyev said, adding that
Russian officials reported back that they overheard ``conversation
that if this incident had happened'' NATO officials ``would never
acknowledge it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrei A. Kokoshin, national security adviser to former
President Boris Yeltsin, said in an interview Monday that ``there
were many cases'' in the past decade ``when our submarines in the
region and foreign subs were coming too close to each other and we
raised complaints several times to the Americans and some other
Western countries even to the point of proposing that there should
be some rules established for this kind of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Kokoshin, now a member of Parliament who has joined those
calling for a parliamentary investigation of the sinking of the
Kursk, said that Russia owes a great debt to Norway and Britain for
assisting in the unsuccessful rescue of the crew, but he added that
even if the investigation proves that the Kursk was not involved in
a collision, a new international agreement on submarine ``rules of
conduct'' should be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be explored,'' he said, ``because it is too
serious for both of us, for our national security and for the
international community because it involves a nuclear power, and
the Cold War is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
