u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT &LR;      08-21 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD CLOSING THREE FACTORIES FOR TWO WEEKS TO EASE TIRE SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ With Ford Explorer owners still crowding car
dealerships in search of scarce replacements for recalled Firestone
tires, and with sales of new Ford Explorers beginning to slip, the
Ford Motor Co. said Monday that it will close three assembly plants
for two weeks to make an extra 70,000 tires available.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will close the plants next Monday, and reopen them Sept.
11, Ford executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will shut down production of Ford Explorer sport utility
vehicles at its plant in St. Louis and shut down production of Ford
Ranger pickup trucks in St. Paul, Minn., and Edison, N.J. The
Ranger uses the same type of 15-inch tires as many Ford Explorers,
although virtually all of the 62 deaths that are possibly related
to flawed tires have occurred in Explorers, which outsell Rangers
by a wide margin. Regulators are still investigating accidents
reportedly connected with the tire problems.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Inglis, Ford's vice president for North American
automotive operations, told reporters about the plant closings in a
conference call Monday . An increase in tire production by
Bridgestone and other tire makers should ease Ford's current
shortage of 15-inch tires by mid-September, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief executive and president, prepared a
television advertisement that was scheduled to be broadcast on
``Monday Night Football'' on ABC, confirming the automaker's
decision to cut production and vowing to keep customers' trust.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will idle 6,000 unionized assembly line workers at the
three factories. Under Ford's union agreement, the workers draw 95
percent of their pay, excluding overtime, during the temporary
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had advertised in national newspapers on Sunday that it
would channel just 30,000 tires a month to dealerships, instead of
using them in the production of new Ford vehicles. The decision to
close the factories, releasing more tires into the market, was made
at 1 p.m. Monday, Ford executives said.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford might be able to catch up some of the production of
Rangers later this year, its St. Louis factory constantly runs at
full capacity and is unlikely to be able to make up the lost
production. Because Ford earns an average pre-tax profit of $8,000
on each Explorer, that will hurt the company's earnings for the
third quarter, financial analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows Ford is willing to put customer satisfaction before
profitability _ shutting down an auto plant where you make eight
grand a unit is a pretty bold statement,'' said Nicholas Lobaccaro,
an auto industry analyst at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   George Pipas, a Ford market analyst, said that Ford's sales of
Explorers had been running at 91 percent of the company's target
over the last four days after matching the company's target during
the first two weeks of the month. Ford's target had been a
4-percent increase in Explorer sales compared with those last
August, and overall sales of Explorers so far this month are
slightly ahead of last year's level, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is still short of Explorers, having struggled for years to
keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will keep open its Explorer plant in Louisville, Ky. That
plant makes more expensive Explorer models that are likely to be
equipped with 16-inch tires, which have not been recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Auto Safety, a nonprofit group sometimes allied
with consumers' lawyers, filed a lawsuit against Ford and
Bridgestone/Firestone on Monday, contending that the 16-inch tires
should also be recalled, a move that Ford and Bridgestone have
repeatedly dismissed as unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that it would lose the production of 10,000 Explorers
and 15,000 Rangers at the three factories closed. Lobaccaro
estimated that the loss of the Explorer production during the third
quarter would cost Ford up to $80 million in pretax profits and
about $52 million in after-tax profits. The lost Ranger production,
with a pretax profit of $4,000 each, will cost Ford about $60
million in pretax profits and $39 million in after-tax profits in
the third quarter, though he said about half that loss can be
recovered in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The lost profits could be smaller if Ford can adjust production
in the coming months to emphasize higher-profit versions of the
Explorer and Ranger. Ford earns $1.2 billion to $2 billion each
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford executives have consistently said that they are
paying attention now only to customer safety, and not to the
company's liability exposure, Ford's decision to close the
factories temporarily could help its legal position.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for consumers said last week that people injured in the
coming weeks in Ford vehicles equipped with recalled Firestone
tires would have strong cases in suing the company as long as Ford
continued putting new, 15-inch tires on vehicles instead of making
them available as replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Closing the factories for two weeks will make 70,000 15-inch
tires available, though 6.5 million tires have been recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that it could not adjust production to make only those
models of Explorers and Rangers that need other size tires.
</P>
<P>
   A national survey of 3,600 people published Monday by Automotive
News, a weekly trade magazine for auto executives, found that 47
percent of the people thought that Ford's honesty had been fair or
poor, and 49 percent said that the speed of Ford's response had
been fair or poor. Public perception of Bridgestone was
considerably worse. The image of Ford sport utility vehicles other
than the Explorer, notably the Expedition, had also eroded, the
survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Ford executives responded that their own focus groups showed
that people thought the automaker had handled the issue well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
