<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-NYT &LR;      08-21 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POSTCONVENTION POLLS, GORE BOUNCES JUST AHEAD OF BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six public polls conducted for news organizations
since the Democratic convention have all shown Vice President Al
Gore leading Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, though in two cases by
only a single percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The post-convention gains for Gore were generally larger than
the bounce recorded by the same polls earlier for Bush. But the
Bush gains generally fell off quickly. If Gore's also do, he will
find himself trailing Bush again. Moreover, in none of the polls
does Gore's lead exceed the margin of sampling error, a fact that
underlines the narrow, uncertain margins.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the polls were released Monday. A CBS News Poll of 956
registered voters conducted Friday through Sunday showed Gore
leading Bush, 45 percent to 44 percent, with 6 percent for Ralph
Nader of the Green Party and 1 percent for Pat Buchanan of the
Reform Party. A comparable poll taken two weeks earlier, just after
the Republican convention, gave Bush 50 percent and Gore 34
percent. Gore had never led Bush in a CBS News or CBS News/New York
Times Poll this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen A. Frankovic, director of surveys for CBS News, said
the advantage for Gore extended beyond the horse-race numbers. ``He
improved the public's assessment of him as having strong qualities
of leadership and someone who could be trusted. Overall, the
favorable evaluation of Gore is now the same as that for Governor
Bush,'' she said. Each is rated favorably by 45 percent of the
public and unfavorably by 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a Zogby International Poll for Reuters, conducted on
the same three days among 1,004 ``likely'' voters, gave Gore a 44
percent to 41 percent lead, with 5 percent for Nader and 2 percent
for Buchanan. A week earlier, the same poll had Bush up, 43 percent
to 40, with 7 percent for Nader and 2 percent for Buchanan. The
last time a Zogby Poll showed Gore with any kind of lead was at the
beginning of February, when he had a 1 point margin.
</P>
<P>
   In an ABC News/Washington Post Poll of 896 registered voters,
Gore has 46 percent to Bush's 44 percent, with 4 percent for Nader
and 3 percent for Buchanan. Before the Democratic convention, Bush
led Gore in that poll, 48 percent to 40 percent, with 5 percent for
Nader and 2 percent for Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Three polls conducted and released earlier pointed in the same
direction. A Gallup poll of 697 ``likely'' voters for CNN and USA
Today, taken Friday and Saturday, had Gore leading Bush, 47 percent
to 46 percent. Nader had 3 percent and Buchanan 2 percent. One week
earlier, before the Democratic convention, Bush had 55 percent,
Gore 39 percent and Nader 2 percent, with only a scattering for
Buchanan. Gore last led in one of these polls at the beginning of
April.
</P>
<P>
   Another Friday-Saturday poll, done for Newsweek by Princeton
Survey Research among 806 registered voters, gave Gore a 48 percent
to 42 percent lead, with 3 percent for Nader and 1 percent for
Buchanan. Eight days earlier, that poll found Bush leading, 48
percent to 38 percent, with 3 percent each for Nader and Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The first post-convention poll, conducted among 508 registered
voters Thursday night for NBC News, showed Gore with a 46 percent
to 43 percent lead over Bush, with 2 percent for Nader and 1
percent for Buchanan. Just before the convention, Peter D. Hart and
Robert Teeter, who conduct the NBC polls, found Bush with 44
percent, Gore with 41 percent, Nader with 5 percent and Buchanan
with 2 percent. None of their previous polls had found Gore ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Frankovic said the Gore bounce measured by the CBS News Polls
had been exceeded only once in her polling, by Bush's father. In
1988, she said, Vice President George Bush went from a 17 point
deficit to a 6 point lead over Gov. Michael Dukakis. Bush never
trailed again.
</P>
</TEXT>
