<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-WOODS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHEN WOODS BECOMES A TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By   CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ To understand the genius of Tiger Woods, you
must appreciate not only his skill, but also his will.
</P>
<P>
   Like truly great athletes in any sport, Woods possesses
something deep within that allows him to focus clearly in the most
chaotic and challenging situations. Those who watched Woods and Bob
May battle Sunday during the final round of the PGA Championship
saw a classic moment in sports. It was like watching Muhammad Ali
vs. Joe Frazier at the Thrilla in Manila, like watching Michael
Jordan's last game, against the Utah Jazz, in which he ended his
career with a textbook jump shot that clinched another
championship.
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday's finishing holes, Woods' putting stroke under
pressure was as pure as Jordan's shooting stroke at the buzzer.
Woods faced two difficult putts that he could not afford to miss _
the 15-footer to save par at No. 15 in regulation and the 5-footer
for birdie at No. 18 to force the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Was anyone surprised that Woods sank them both? Was anyone
surprised when Woods opened the playoff with another birdie putt,
chasing the ball into the hole like a jockey riding a horse down
the backstretch? Those putts reflected another quality shared by
Woods and Jack Nicklaus. Both are good putters. But in pressure
situations, they become great putters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great battle, and I enjoyed it,'' Woods said
afterward. ``You learn something about yourself in situations like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of learning something, Woods actually reinforced
something he already knew. Not only is he the world's most talented
player, but he may be the toughest mentally.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is 5-0 in majors when he leads entering the final round.
There were people who actually wondered how Woods would react if he
were challenged during the back nine of a major championship. After
all, he had run away with both the U.S. Open and the British Open,
turning the final holes into a victory lap. Would Woods crack if
someone finally pushed him to the final hole and played against him
without fear?
</P>
<P>
   The answer came Sunday. May played remarkably well, and his
performance was more impressive when you consider that he had never
been in that situation before. One could argue that he would have
beaten any other player in the world except Woods. On the back
nine, May turned in the performance of his life, shooting a
five-under-par 31. All weekend, May played the tournament of his
life, shooting 66 in each of the final three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   No, May was not perfect, and his missed 4-foot birdie putt at
No. 15 was huge. But he played well enough to force Woods to make a
5-footer on No. 18 just to force a playoff. Who expected that when
the day started? Yet, May still lost because Woods would not let
anyone else win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you shoot 66 in the final three rounds of a major, you're
supposed to win,'' May said. ``But it wasn't good enough to beat
Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   When Woods blitzed the field at both the U.S. Open and the
British Open this year, it was a tribute to his talent and his
preparation. When Woods won Sunday, it was a tribute to his grit.
He never came close to hitting the ball as well here as he did
during his romps at Pebble Beach and St. Andrews. For most of the
PGA, his putting was erratic.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment May went two strokes up on Sunday, however,
Woods became a different player. When he senses a tournament
slipping away, Woods truly becomes a tiger. That was true during
his amateur days, when he won three consecutive U.S. Amateur
championships, and it remains true today. Competition does not
scare Woods, it inspires him. When May opened the door by missing
his crucial 4-foot birdie attempt at No. 15, Woods sensed an
opening and seized it.
</P>
<P>
   So Woods added to his lore, becoming the first player to win
four out of five majors, and only the second to win three
professional majors in one year, matching Ben Hogan's feat from
1953. By dueling into a playoff, Woods and May made the PGA
Championship the most dramatic of the year's four majors.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Woods dominate at Pebble Beach and St. Andrews was
compelling in its own right because nobody had ever seen anything
quite like it. But at those two events, it became obvious that
Woods would win. There was not the heart-pounding excitement that
Sunday's final round contained, when people were afraid to turn
away, fearful they might miss a dramatic shot.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere at Valhalla Golf Club was electric, with people
in the gallery screaming for both players. Television viewers tuned
in and could not turn it off. It was another great moment for golf,
and once again, Woods was the focal point. With Woods still only 24
years old, there should be many great moments to come.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he does the rest of year is gravy. The majors are over,
and there is no doubt who will win the money title or the Player of
the Year award. For Woods, the next great achievement could come
next year at Augusta, where he will try to win the Masters and
become the first player to win four consecutive professional
majors, the consecutive Grand Slam, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it would be wise to appreciate what Woods has done
over the past 12 months. Even he may never enjoy another run like
that. By finding a way to win Sunday, Woods proved again that both
his skill and his will are enormous. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
