<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLERS COMBINE WITH WHITMAN PURCHASE OF PEPSIAMERICAS
</HEADLINE>
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Furthering a consolidation among bottlers of Pepsico beverages,
the Whitman Corp. said Monday that it had agreed to acquire
PepsiAmericas Inc. for about $331.7 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the transaction, Whitman will pay $3.80 a
share in cash and stock. In addition, it will assume $330 million
in PepsiAmericas debt.
</P>
<P>
   The deal unites the second- and third-largest Pepsi bottlers in
the United States. Executives at Whitman said the combined company
would have 20 percent to 21 percent of the market for Pepsi
products.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi's largest bottler, the Pepsi Bottling Group, has about 55
percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Last year PepsiCo, which owns about 40 percent of Whitman's
outstanding common stock, transferred several of its bottling
franchises to Whitman. The transfer came just before the Pepsi
Bottling Group went public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger is a giant step forward in the consolidation of our
business, which will translate into greater efficiencies and
increase the likelihood that we will participate in other deals,''
Bruce Chelberg, Whitman's chief executive, said in a teleconference
with reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Chelberg, who is 66, will step down once the transaction is
completed, Whitman said. He will be succeeded by Robert Pohlad, 46,
PepsiAmericas' chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidation makes sense in terms of increased scale, but the
key point is that the deal solves the management issue at
Whitman,'' said Bill Pecoriello, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein
&AMP; Co. `` Pohlad is well respected within the industry. And Whitman
will build its management bench'' with PepsiAmericas executives.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Minneapolis, PepsiAmericas does business in nine
states, many in the South, and in Puerto Rico. The company has
annual sales of about $576 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is publicly traded, 70 percent of PepsiAmericas
shares are owned by Dakota Holdings LLC, a private enterprise
controlled by the Pohlad family.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, which operates from headquarters in Rolling Meadows,
Ill., produces and distributes Pepsi products in 10 central states
as well as a number of foreign countries, including Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic. Whitman has revenue of about $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``PepsiAmericas is not a huge company, but it is very well
located relative to Whitman,'' said George Thompson, an analyst at
Prudential Securities. ``The deal not only allows Whitman to
increase its leverage with big food retailers, but puts the company
in a position where they are the only game in town in that
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation among supermarket chains is a big reason both
Coca-Cola and Pepsi have been seeking to cut the number of local
bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots and lots of very small bottlers still out
there,'' said John D. Sicher, publisher of Beverage Digest, an
industry newsletter. ``Consolidation among both Coke and Pepsi
bottlers slowed down in the last year, but I would anticipate that
it will pick up over the next two to three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Whitman and PepsiAmericas together employ 14,700
people.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives spoke generally yesterday about anticipated
cost savings as a result of the merger, but declined to talk about
specific cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are synergies in this combination,'' Pohlad said, ``but
the focus of this merger is on accelerating growth.''
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange on Monday, Whitman shares closed
at $14.13, up 38 cents a share. Shares of PepsiAmericas fell 81
cents, to $3.94 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
