<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FENCING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENCING SISTERS GLAD TO BE COMPETING TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Iris Zimmermann dreamed about the possibility for
four years, the thought that she might one day walk into Sydney's
Olympic Stadium, stride for stride next to her older sister,
Felicia.
</P>
<P>
   So whatever happens later this month, whether the U.S. women's
foil team wins an unexpected fencing medal or not, the Zimmermann
sisters will shed no tears of sadness or regret. Each one's dream
will have already come true, simply because of the presence of the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so awesome,'' 19-year-old Iris Zimmermann said.
``(Felicia) is my role model, sister, best friend in the world,
confidant, psychologist and shopping partner. It is just so
wonderful that she and I are able to share this experience
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicia is the closest thing to me on this earth, and it is so
amazing that we are going to Sydney together. I can't ask for much
more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably for the best, since America's chances of
winning a medal in any of the eight fencing categories are slim, at
best. No American has medaled in fencing since Peter Westbrook's
sabre bronze in 1984, which broke a 24-year U.S. medal drought.
</P>
<P>
   No American individual is ranked in the top five in the World
Cup rankings, which means that the Zimmermann sisters and Ann
Marsh, the three athletes who make up the women's foil team, have
the best shot at a medal in Sydney. The team earned an Olympic
berth by finishing seventh in the 1999 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really excited about our prospects as a team,'' Felicia
Zimmermann said. ``We are a very dangerous team to many countries
because of our mental toughness and physical strength. I don't
think we need to win a medal to feel successful. I feel that as
long as we prepare and do our thing, we will be ready for anyone
and everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The team certainly doesn't lack for camaraderie, or experience.
Marsh, 29, is one of Felicia Zimmermann's best friends. The two
women were Olympic teammates four years ago in Atlanta and Marsh,
who also works in a hospital emergency room in Buffalo, N.Y., also
competed in the 1992 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Zimmermann, 25, is a recent graduate of Stanford, where
she won three NCAA Division I fencing championships. It is a legacy
she now hands over to her sister. Iris has already reached the
semifinals of the World Championships, a feat she accomplished in
1999, and is delaying the start of her sophomore year at Stanford
because of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I have to say there are no words to describe what I
feel about representing my country at the Olympic Games,'' Iris
Zimmerman said. ``I am so overwhelmed when I take time to step back
and check out my accomplishments that I just break down in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters, six years apart, grew up in Rochester, N.Y.,
where they still train, and have become better friends over the
past few years. The Olympic experience is special enough, but the
joy of being accompanied by a sibling is unmatched, according to
the sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew that being on the Olympic team together was in
the future for us,'' Iris Zimmerman said. ``My sister and I have
gotten closer over the years since I have been getting older and
experiencing more of the things she has experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   And now comes the ultimate in shared experiences, medal or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love having my sister with me at this Olympics,'' Felicia
Zimmermann said. ``She brings so much to the team and we are a
package when it comes to fencing. We work well together, pushing
each other and supporting each other. It is really special to be
with her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
