u s BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     08-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL REQUIRES NO ALTERATIONS   TO FIT INTO YANKEES' LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Glenallen Hill squeezed his shoulders through the
doors to the press room the other day, striding steadily along a
shortcut to the home clubhouse at Yankee Stadium. A picture hanging
on the wall seized his imagination and he stopped suddenly. ``Look
at that,'' he said. ``Look at those arms.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a black-and-white picture of a Yankee hitter, his face
contorted at the end of a massive swing, his pinstriped jersey
barely restraining the muscles of his shoulders and biceps. Hill
was fascinated. ``That's amazing,'' Hill said. ``Who is that?''
</P>
<P>
   The picture is of Mickey Mantle, a long-reigning heir to the
Yankees' heritage of power hitters, a tradition Hill is embracing.
He hit his 11th home run in his 18-game Yankee career Monday, a
12-3 blowout against Texas. Orlando Hernandez won for the first
time since July 7, surrendering six hits and three runs over seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   All five of the Yankees' starters have now contributed solid
outings in the last trip through the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada ripped a two-run homer and drove in four runs, and
Clay Bellinger contributed three hits. Bellinger has reached base
in his last seven plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees played without Bernie Williams, who has a strain in
the right side of his rib cage, but who might return Wednesday .
They were also without David Justice, a late scratch from the
starting lineup because of stiffness in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   In their absence, Hill, the designated hitter, slid into the
cleanup spot naturally, and by the time he chipped in with his two
hits, the Yankees' rout of Brian Sikorski was well under way.
Sikorski had shut out the Yankees for seven innings last week, and
after the right-hander held them scoreless in the first two innings
Monday, Manager Joe Torre loudly chided his players in the dugout
for swinging at bad pitches. By forcing Sikorski to throw 41
pitches in the third inning, the Yankees scored six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Hill batted in the fourth inning and ripped a line drive toward
left, where the Rangers' Rusty Greer _ one of the best fielders at
his position _ moved to cut off the ball. But Hill's liner, moving
much faster than Greer thought, got past him, allowing Paul O'Neill
to score.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was on first again for Hill's next at-bat, in the sixth,
and Hill laced another line drive, this one carrying over the
left-field fence. While Hill jogged around the bases, the small
afternoon crowd roaring, the batboy, John Viola, retrieved Hill's
bat and noticed a deep crack in the handle, just above the place
where Hill places his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had broken his bat and still hit the ball about 420 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Viola showed Hill the crack when he returned to the dugout, and
the bat was examined by teammates. ``That just shows you how strong
his wrists are,'' Viola, 17, said.
</P>
<P>
   Torre joked: ``I said to him, `It was easy; with your hands you
were able to hold the bat together.' It's amazing what he's done.
It's fun to watch on our side because if you make a mistake, he's
going to hit it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Tino Martinez said: ``He's obviously a strong guy.
He's got a short, compact swing. He's not overswinging; he's short
and compact to the ball, and he's hitting it hard. Even when he
strikes out, he's taking good swings.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill has been with the Yankees for less than a month and he is
already known to his teammates as something of an eccentric
personality. He plays music loudly _ ``all kinds,'' Derek Jeter
said _ and speaks softly. He wears eye black for both night and day
games. He dresses elegantly, but swings his bat viciously, quickly,
powerfully. ``Like Muhammad Ali's left jab,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there are ways to get Hill out. He came into the
2000 season with a .271 career batting average, striking out often,
once for every 4.5 at-bats. If he gets behind in the count, Hill
inspires opposing pitchers to throw breaking balls down and away,
or fastballs high and inside to finish him off.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill, 35, is batting .446, with four doubles and 11 homers
in 56 at-bats. His slugging percentage is 1.107. ``I don't know _ I
don't want to jinx it,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   He swings hard and is hitting everything very hard; this is not
a fluke, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's explosion is reminiscent of Shane Spencer's run at the
end of the 1998 season, when he bashed 10 homers in 67
regular-season at-bats and added a couple more in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lot stronger than Shane is,'' Martinez said of Hill.
``He can hit the ball out anywhere in the ballpark. When he hits
the ball hard, it's going out. It doesn't matter where. Shane
turned on his a lot. This guy is hitting them out to right field,
left field, center. This guy is just ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez often follows Hill in the lineup. ``It's definitely
fun,'' he said, smiling. ``But it makes me feel like a Little
Leaguer after a while.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
