<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEPSI BOTTLERS TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman Corp., the No. 2 bottler of Pepsi Cola behind the
Pepsi Bottling Group, has agreed to buy the No. 3 bottler,
PepsiAmericas, for $331.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, which will have about 20 percent of
Pepsi's bottling market, will be run by Robert Pohlad, 46, the
chairman of PepsiAmericas, settling Whitman's problem of who would
succeed its 66-year-old chairman. Shares of Whitman rose 38 cents,
to $14.13, while PepsiAmericas fell 81 cents, to $3.94.
</P>
<P>
   DE BEERS MEETS CHALLENGES
</P>
<P>
   De Beers is ascending the diamond industry once again by
reducing a huge stockpile it had accumulated in an attempt to keep
prices high and by supporting moves to keep diamonds produced by
war-mongering African rebels off of the legitimate market.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS RISE SLIGHTLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose as investors expected the Federal Reserve to leave
interest rates unchanged on Tuesday. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 33.33 points, to 11,079.81, while the Nasdaq
composite index rose 22.81 points, to 3,953.15, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index gained 7.76 points, to 1,499.48.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE PROGRESS ON AIR DELAYS
</P>
<P>
   A meeting of airline executives, labor unions, industry
executives and government officials produced scant progress in
addressing the record delays and cancellations that hit air travel
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER VIRUS CHARGES DROPPED
</P>
<P>
   Philippine authorities dismissed charges against the college
dropout accused of being responsible for a destructive computer
program known as the ``I love you'' virus.
</P>
<P>
   TELUS BIDS FOR CLEARNET
</P>
<P>
   Telus, the largest telecommunications company in western Canada,
moved to become the country's biggest wireless telephone network
with a $3.1 billion bid to acquire Clearnet Communications of
Toronto. Darren Entwistle, chief executive of Telus, said his
objective was to become the Canadian leader of the wireless and
Internet markets.
</P>
