<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN TELECOM BIDS TO BECOME COUNTRY'S BIGGEST WIRELESS
NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Telus Corp., the largest telecommunications company in
Western Canada, made a brash move to become the country's biggest
wireless telephone network Monday with an offer worth $3.12 billion
for Clearnet Communications Inc. of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover would greatly accelerate the expansion of Telus and
pose a competitive challenge to two other big Canadian
telecommunications providers, the Bell Mobility division of
Montreal-based Bell Canada, the country's largest
telecommunications company, and Rogers AT&AMP;T Canada, a unit of
Rogers Communications Inc. based in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Like other wireless phone companies around the world, the
Canadian competitors are scrambling to gain geographic reach,
partly in anticipation of a boom in demand for Internet services
accessibly by wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless and Internet applications are the two fastest-growing
areas in telecommunications,'' said Darren Entwistle, president and
chief executive of Telus, based in Burnaby, British Columbia. ``Our
objective is to become the Canadian leader of this market.`
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cant, an analyst at Renaissance Strategies in Waltham,
Mass., said Telus had strengthened its hand by moving quickly to
gain a national wireless network. But he also expressed caution
that with so many wireless networks under construction around the
world, companies like Telus may find themselves in tough
competition with new marketers who are able to buy capacity at
inexpensive rates.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of Clearnet have been offered 70 Canadian dollars,
$47.18, in cash, or 1.636 of a Telus nonvoting share for their
stock. The total offer amounts to about 4.6 billion Canadian
dollars, about $3.12 billion at Monday's exchange rates. Telus will
also assume Clearnet's debt of 2 billion Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The offer has been endorsed by the boards of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   The offering price is a 53 percent premium to Friday's closing
price of 45.80 Canadian dollars on the Toronto Stock Exchange. In
trading Monday, Clearnet shares surged 42 percent to 64.95 Canadian
dollars, $44.05, still below the 70 Canadian dollar per share
offer. Telus shares fell 10 percent to close at 40.05 Canadian
dollars in Toronto, $27.16.
</P>
<P>
   Telus said the offer, which requires shareholder and regulatory
approval, is expected to be completed by October. George Cope,
president and chief executive of Clearnet, would head Telus'
wireless division.
</P>
<P>
   Clearnet shareholders would own 18.5 percent of Telus under the
deal. Shareholders with 86 percent of the voting stock and more
than 30 percent of total equity shareholders have agreed to the
bid, including the family of founder David Simmonds, Nextel
Communications Inc. of Reston, Va., and Motorola Canada Ltd. of
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   While Motorola may sell its shares after a one-year holding
period expires, Nextel may remain as a strategic investor. Through
Nextel, Clearnet links its Canadian wireless customers with the
United States, just as Verizon Communications' network in the
United States ties in with Telus.
</P>
<P>
   Previously based in Edmonton, Alberta, Telus was owned by the
provincial government and called the Alberta Government Telephones
Commission before it was privatized in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Clearnet was formed in 1984 and has raised more than 3.2 billion
Canadian dollars _ $2.17 billion _ to build two digital networks _
Clearnet PCS and Mike, which integrates PCS phone service with
two-way radio, data and other communications services for
businesses. With Clearnet, Telus avoids having to build its own
cross-country wireless network, and it will become a national
competitor three years earlier than many had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will have 26,000 employees and revenue of
6.5 billion Canadian dollars _ $4.41 billion _ a quarter of it from
the mobile phone operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
