A8466 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-GOLCLUB0822-COX     08-21 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLCLUB0822-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dancer cuts plea deal, will tell of sex with celebrities for
money
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Federal prosecutors now have a potential star witness
in the racketeering case involving the Gold Club _ a dancer who
admits to being paid for having sex with professional athletes and
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Pelnis, a Gold Club stripper, pleaded guilty Friday to
reduced charges in return for her cooperation against fellow
defendants, including club owner Steve Kaplan, according to court
documents unsealed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan and 14 co-defendants had maintained a united front since
the case was first indicted in November. But Pelnis becomes the
first employee of the Buckhead club to plead guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never ceases to amaze me what people will say to get
themselves out of trouble,'' said Atlanta lawyer Steve Sadow, who
represents Kaplan. ``On many occasions, even up to today, she has
indicated that Steve Kaplan was not involved in any wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadow promised to produce several witnesses to discredit Pelnis'
allegations. ``This will not simply be her word against his word,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Club trial is tentatively set for February. In a
sweeping federal indictment, Kaplan and other club officials are
charged with illegal ties to organized crime, money laundering,
credit card fraud, police corruption and prostitution. Prosecutors
have said Kaplan paid his dancers to provide sexual favors to
celebrity and high-roller customers to give the club a high
profile.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have been investigating the club, at
Piedmont Road and Lindbergh Drive, since 1996. The indictment
alleges that Gold Club management provided dancers to have sex with
celebrity customers at the club and Atlanta hotels and flew the
dancers to the 1999 Super Bowl in Miami and to Las Vegas,
Minneapolis and Charleston, S.C., for prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Pelnis is one of two dancers charged in the case, along with two
Atlanta police officers and two Delta Air Lines employees. Former
floor manager Jeffrey Johnson also is cooperating and is expected
to enter a guilty plea, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before U.S. District Judge Willis Hunt, Pelnis, 28,
said she is pregnant with her first child. She pleaded guilty to
aiding a racketeering conspiracy, which carries a maximum sentence
of five years in prison. But Pelnis, in return for her cooperation,
could receive a possible misdemeanor sentence of less than one
year.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Assistant U.S. Attorney Art Leach outlined
to Hunt what he expects Pelnis to say when she takes the witness
stand.
</P>
<P>
   With Hunt's permission, Leach kept under seal the names of
athletes and high-roller customers who allegedly had sex with club
dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Leach only referred to them by their initialsamous
individuals and it will obviously sensationalize this situation if
these names behind the initials were to become public.''
</P>
<P>
   One athlete from out of town, Leach said, came to the Gold Club
in Atlanta and was taken to a Gold Room where there was another
athlete ``and there was a variety of sexual activity that was going
on in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan then asked Pelnis to enter the room and she engaged in
sex with an athlete, Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   That athlete ''ended up providing (Pelnis) some funds after that
and it was clear that Kaplan remained throughout much of the sexual
activity that was occuring in the room,'' Leach told the judge. He
added that he believed that Kaplan paid Pelnis money as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I accurate on that?'' Leach asked the dancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion in the Gold Club, Leach said, Pelnis and
another dancer engaged in sex with an athlete. While this went on,
Kaplan was ``in and out of the room,'' the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   When the sexual activity was finished, Kaplan directed that the
room be cleared because he wanted to meet with all of the
entertainers and waitresses who had been in the room, Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked everyone present if they were treated all right,''
Leach said. ``Everyone responded that they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan soon arranged for these women to be paid, Leach said,
stating this is what Pelnis is expected to testify on the witness
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
