<SLUG> BC-REITS- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAND GRAB: INVESTORS SEEK SOLID GROUND IN REAL-ESTATE
INVESTMENT  TRUSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; They're baaaaaack!
</P>
<P>
   Remember real-estate investment trusts, those high-flying
stock-market darlings of 1996 and 1997?
</P>
<P>
   If you do, then you must also remember that their stocks went
into a harrowing 28 percent decline during 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Today, REITs _ closed-end funds that own real estate rather than
securities _ are hot again.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they are hotter than almost any other type of stock.
They have risen 22.4 percent this year _ as measured by the Morgan
Stanley real estate investment trust index _ and have recovered
virtually all the ground they lost in the two previous years.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index is up 1.5 percent
for the year, while the Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq
composite index are down roughly 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   REITs have become a fad again in great part because the nation's
real-estate markets are booming.
</P>
<P>
   A voracious demand for space in industrial, office and apartment
buildings _ especially along the East and West coasts _ has pushed
rentals and property values sky-high.
</P>
<P>
   REITs also are benefiting from the backlash against technology
and Internet stocks that began in March. Many investors have grown
wary of companies that are heavy on hype but light on earnings and
are attracted to the steady and reliable earnings growth and the
generous dividends available from REITs.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the stock market's ups and downs, the real-estate
industry has been faring quite well, notes Bill Schaff, manager of
the Undiscovered Managers REIT Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The REITs have averaged strong, 10 percent annual gains in their
flow of funds from operations _ the customary measure of their
earnings power. (Flow of funds from operations _ known in the
industry as FFO _ consists of earnings plus depreciation.)
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the industry's growth appears to be accelerating, says
Jay P. Leupp, an analyst with Robertson Stephens in San Francisco.
He figures that FFO will increase by 11 percent to 13 percent per
year during the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Couple that with the average REIT dividend _ amounting to 7
percent of the share price _ and you have what Leupp calls ``a
magnet for investors.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter earnings reports of most REITs have been
``just stellar,'' Leupp remarks. ``The average REIT is running
about 2 percent ahead of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   With REITs hot again, should investors worry about another
cooling-off period just ahead?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   At their peak in late 1997, REITs were selling at an average of
20 percent above their net asset values _ the per-share value of
their real-estate holdings, minus any debt.
</P>
<P>
   That, in retrospect, was too good to last. By the time they hit
bottom in December, they were selling at 25 percent to 30 percent
below net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   Today, even after this year's strong surge, REITs typically
trade at a discount of 5 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still a good buy,'' says Ken Rosen, a widely
respected real-estate expert and portfolio manager in Berkeley.
``They will do very well unless we begin to see signs of
overbuilding _ and right now there are no signs of overbuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   Some kinds of REITs seem more attractive than others.
</P>
<P>
   Those that specialize in office buildings, apartments and
industrial buildings are riding high in these economically buoyant
times. Such prominent REITs as Equity Office Properties, Archstone
Communities and AMB Property fit in those categories.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of REITs that specialize in malls, shopping centers
and other retail properties have performed worse than other types
of REITs. Analysts attribute this to investor concerns about
competition from Internet retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Simon Property Group, the biggest shopping-mall
REIT, has gained less than 5 percent since the end of last year.
Another leading mall REIT, Mills Corp., is actually down slightly
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Leupp points out that Mills could be an attractive buy
if only because of its extraordinarily high dividend yield _ a
juicy 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no doubt that the Internet is cutting into the
amount of shopping done at malls, experts say most malls are doing
well enough and are not threatened with extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the perception that the big malls won't grow as fast,
which is true,'' says Schaff. ``But there will be a place for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Leupp says the proliferation of successful Internet retailers
actually could be good for the malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most e-tailers are realizing that they need to have some kind
of bricks-and-mortar presence as part of their operating
strategy,'' he observes. ``The REITs are perfectly positioned to
fulfill that role.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
