r f BC-CONFLICT- &LR;      08-21 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFLICT- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE CONFLICT OF INTEREST PERPLEXES OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD WALLACK  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State officials were scrambling yesterday to
determine whether a public utility commissioner should be
sanctioned for investing $10,000 in a cellular phone company his
agency regulates.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Attorney General Bill Lockyer said his office
is still trying to determine whether it should get involved. And
Peter Arth, chief lawyer for the Public Utilities Commission, said
the other PUC commissioners haven't decided yet whether they should
investigate the apparent conflict of interest or refer it to
Lockyer.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Public Utilities Code specifically bars
commissioners from investing in companies the agency regulates,
including wireless firms.
</P>
<P>
   But the law is vague over what the penalty is for someone who
violates the rule and who should enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   John Symkowick, a spokesman for the Fair Political Practices
Commission, said his agency would have the power to investigate if
the matter violates the state's more general conflict of interest
rules. Symkowick declined to say whether the commission will
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a statement yesterday, PUC Commissioner Henry
Duque said he immediately sold his shares in Nextel Communications
after he was advised it was an ``apparent conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have taken, and am taking, appropriate action,'' Duque said
in a statement issued late yesterday. Duque bought the stock in May
1999, but said he didn't realize it could be perceived as a
conflict until a Chronicle reporter asked him about it on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Duque said he didn't believe there was a
conflict of interest because the PUC has never set rates for Nextel
and the company largely falls under jurisdiction of the Federal
Communications Commission. Duque also noted that he included the
investment in his financial disclosure forms.
</P>
<P>
   Arth said PUC officials normally do not review the completed
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Duque's Nextel investment, first reported in The Chronicle
yesterday, drew mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Carl Wood called it an honest mistake. ``I think
it's unfortunate that such a big deal is being made over what, if
anything, is an oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates considered the error serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Duque's) statement recognizes the reality of
what has occurred,'' said Robert Gnaizda, general counsel for the
Greenling Institute, a San Francisco consumer group. ``A
commissioner has a position at least of equal importance to a U.S.
or California Supreme Court justice, and therefore appearance is
almost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers even went so far on Sunday as to urge Duque to
resign. Still, even liberal watchdog groups, who often disagree
strongly with Duque's conservative voting record, called him honest
and a straight shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he (violated the rules) deliberately,'' Gnaizda
said.
</P>
<P>
   The topic didn't come up at all in a PUC meeting yesterday. PUC
President Loretta Lynch said yesterday afternoon that she hadn't
had time to talk with anyone about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates also expressed concern that Duque and Wood
accepted two-week European tours _ described as educational _ in
the past few years that were paid for by the California Foundation
on the Environment and the Economy. The group receives much of its
funding from utilities and related corporations, including Sempra
Energy, parent of San Diego Gas and Electric, and Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it always creates the appearance of public officials
being given something by the industry which undermines public
confidence,'' said Jocelyn Larkin, chairman of California Common
Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Although the trips were legal, some critics said they thought
they raised the appearance of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Duque accepted a $7,849 trip to England, Sweden and Eastern
Europe in late March and early April of 1996. Wood went on a $9,060
excursion to Ireland, Germany and Spain. Many legislators also went
on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's chairman, Donald Vial, a former PUC president,
said the trips are important for educating state officials.
</P>
<P>
   On the 1996 trip, for instance, California lawmakers got an
on-site look at energy deregulation in Europe. He said the group is
a nonprofit charity and doesn't support any particular position. He
said it receives money from so many different companies that it is
independent of any one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said his trip was a wonderful opportunity to get to know
state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   But staffers at Greenlining and The Utility Reform Network said
they thought the group was too closely tied to industry. ``I doubt
the educational viewpoint they get out of these trips,'' said
Regina Costa of TURN, a San Francisco consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
