<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUSH-IMPACT-AID-NYT &LR;      08-21 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IMPACT-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BACKS SCHOOL PLAN OPPOSED BY EVERY PRESIDENT SINCE TRUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis.)  (With BUSH-AD-BOX) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fifty years ago next month, on Sept. 23, 1950,
President Harry S. Truman signed legislation to provide federal
money to schools overcrowded by the children of federal workers and
military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Every president since then has tried to abolish the program or
at least cut it to the bone. And every one has failed.
</P>
<P>
   They failed because every senator and most representatives in
Congress have schools in their districts that receive money under
the program, called impact aid, and have not been willing to let
the program die.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. In a speech in Milwaukee
on Monday to the Veterans of Foreign Wars, Bush proposed adding
$310 million to the impact aid program, increasing the budget by
more than a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our men and women in service put their lives on the line to
defend our freedom,'' Bush said. ``We have a special obligation to
rebuild the schools that educate their children. As president, I
will ensure that this obligation is met.
</P>
<P>
   ``This funding means that thousands of students who are
dependents of military personnel and attend public schools located
near or on military facilities around the country will learn in
better school environments.''
</P>
<P>
   The justification for the program has always been that school
districts need compensation because the children of federal workers
and people who work on military bases attend public schools that
are supported by property taxes, but the federal government does
not pay local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That may have posed a burden in Truman's day. But for decades,
budget experts have put the impact aid program in the same category
as federal subsidies for the producers of honey and mohair: relics
of the past that exist entirely because of pork barrel politics.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of authorities who have studied the matter is that
parents who work for the federal government today more than pay
their own way. Most of the parents nowadays live in the community,
pay property taxes and state and local sales and income taxes, and
contribute to the local economy by buying goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   And military bases must be an economic boon to communities or
they would not fight so hard to keep them when base-closings are
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas M. Corwin, the acting deputy assistant secretary for
elementary and secondary education, said Monday that over the
years, some presidential candidates have been more eager than
others to do away with the program. But Corwin said he could not
think of a single one before Bush who proposed expanding it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
