A8475 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON-COLU     08-21 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROS SEEM TO BE LOSING THE STOCK PICKING WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What percentage of U.S. stocks are owned by mutual funds? By
individuals? By institutions other than funds?
</P>
<P>
   A: A Federal Reserve report for the third quarter of last year
indicates that mutual funds owned $2.7 trillion of the $16 trillion
worth of U.S. stocks. That is nearly 17 percent. Only a decade ago,
their share was less than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other institutions, notably pension funds and insurance
companies, held about $5.3 trillion worth of stocks, or 33 percent
of the total _ up from 18 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is no breakout exclusively for individuals, but the stake
held by ``households and nonprofit organizations'' amounted to $6.6
trillion, or 41 percent. That is down from 51 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you view stock investing as a form of competition _ which
it is _ then individual investors who pick their own stocks are
competing more and more against professionals.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably a good thing for individuals, because
professional investors can't seem to get the hang of stock picking.
Just witness the failure of 80 percent of mutual funds to match the
performance each year of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you buy or sell a stock, you ought to hope that an
institutional investor is on the other side of the transaction. If
that's the case, there's a strong chance that you made a good
choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Stock Splits 101
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: I own 50 shares of RF Micro Devices. The company is
splitting its stock 2 for 1, with the split shares payable on
August 25 to shareholders of record on August 8. Since I was a
shareholder of record on August 8, why can't I sell my stock at the
full, presplit value before August 25, then get 50 free split
shares from the company on August 25? This seems like a nice
opportunity to get something for nothing. Why doesn't everyone do
this?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Repeat this to yourself rapidly, until your hormones
stabilize: There is no such thing as a free lunch.
</P>
<P>
   You certainly can sell your 50 shares before August 25, if you
wish. But in doing so you also will be selling your claim to the 50
split shares to which you would be entitled if you held your stock
beyond the August 25 payout date. The `'of record'' cutoff is a
formality, allowing the company's transfer agent enough time to
process and distribute the split shares by the `'payable'' date.
</P>
<P>
   If your shares are held for you by a broker, the broker will
automatically relay the split shares to the new owner of the stock
you sold.
</P>
<P>
   If you hold your own stock certificates, chances are you will
indeed receive a certificate for 50 shares from the company after
you sell the original shares. But you won't be entitled to keep or
sell them. You will have to return them so they can be credited to
the rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Long and Short of Losses
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: You mentioned in a recent column that a taxpayer can
claim no more than $3,000 in net capital losses on his tax return
for any given year and that anything more than that has to be
carried over to the next year. Does it matter whether the net loss
is long-term, short-term, &LR;  or a combination?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, it doesn't matter, according to Internal Revenue Service
spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   A loss is a loss is a loss. (Long-term capital gains, on the
other hand, are taxed at lower rates than short-term gains.)
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you have a $1,500 net short-term loss and a
$1,500 net long-term loss, they are lumped together to make a
$3,000 net loss _ the annual maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Another example: If you have $5,000 in net long-term losses and
$2,000 in net short-term gains, again you claim a net $3,000 loss
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   And the same would hold true if you have $5,000 in net
short-term losses and $2,000 in net long-term gains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag(at)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
