<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0526 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     08-21 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GOODBYE, BIG GUY 
</HEADLINE>
  By   HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a summer of so much trade talk that hovered over the city
like a suffocating blanket of stale hot air, a genuine Knicks'
legend answered the telephone in his Manhattan apartment Monday
afternoon and sounded amazed that the biggest deal of all might be
going down after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think it was going to happen,'' he said. ``To
be honest, I thought that you guys were just selling papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Frazier needed to be reminded that if he was traded when it
wasn't about the money, then Patrick Ewing could certainly be
dispatched to Seattle when it apparently is.
</P>
<P>
   He chuckled, obviously delighted with this spontaneous
historical perspective, and said: ``I guess we've all seen Ewing as
part of the Knicks for so long, we just assumed he would never play
anyplace else. And I guess people, even me, forget that it also
happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a long time ago, longer than I'd prefer to admit, as the
dealing of Frazier to the Cleveland Cavaliers (``Cleveland, come
on, man,'' is how he put it) occurred shortly before I was assigned
to follow the Knicks around with a suitcase and my trusty Olivetti
typewriter. I can still remember treading carefully into the
Cavaliers' locker room at the Richfield Coliseum one wintry night
in 1978, hoping this champion of my own adolescence, this one-time
embodiment of urban chic and cool, would cough up a few quotes on
life in the Cleveland `burbs.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier wasn't in the best of moods _ understandable
considering, as he recalled Monday, that he had been informed of
the 1977 deal for Jim Cleamons by his agent, who was waiting for
him when he returned to his apartment after having been out
shopping. More than two decades later, a modern multi-millionaire
star like Ewing at least had the power to engineer his potential
departure on more favorable terms, relative to his earning power
beyond next year.
</P>
<P>
   If Walt Frazier couldn't finish his career in New York, please
spare me any whining or wheezing about Ewing possibly moving on
after 15 fruitful yet also frustrating years. On judgment day in
the court of all-time greats, Frazier happened to be everything
Ewing was not. He was an improvisational genius, a master of
surprise, a showman who connected and communed with the crowd. And
when his team found itself in a seventh game, the championship
riding on one 1970 spring night against Wilt and the Lakers,
Frazier responded with the game of his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   If it is the end for Ewing in New York, no one should say the
1990s Knicks didn't do and spend all that they could to help put
him in the same position as Frazier, 30 years ago. The personnel
moves weren't always the best. The surrounding players were never
as good. The opposition, particularly in the person of Michael
Jordan, was almost always better. But Ewing did have Game 7 in
Houston, 1994, when it was him against Hakeem Olajuwon, and Ewing
stood passively back in the fourth quarter and watched his best
championship opportunity hoisted into oblivion by John Starks.
</P>
<P>
   The quest continued, with more plot twists than an afternoon
soap. Often, in the heat of the playoffs and in recent seasons
under painful conditions, it seemed courageous and real. But there
was always the other side of Ewing, the one who somehow seldom
seemed to have the big picture in focus, and whose stubborn streak
stretched well past the limits of pride. If Ewing is to leave New
York this week, he goes because the organization made the prudent
decision not to extend a contract that is already hopelessly
inflated in terms of his 38-year-old worth.
</P>
<P>
   Someone close to Ewing said Monday that once the Knicks made it
clear that a contract extension was not forthcoming, his immediate
response was to caucus with his agent, David Falk, to plan the
strategy to obtain it elsewhere. Falk made it clear that he was
unlikely to land with a serious title contender. That Ewing would
be willing to go to Seattle speaks volumes about what his primary
interest is at this stage of his career, 38 and without a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people said Patrick held back the Knicks, what would they
say about him out west?'' Frazier said. ``All those teams want to
run. That's why I'm surprised he would want to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics play in the conference of most recent champions, San
Antonio and Los Angeles, of Duncan and Shaq. Then again, they did
not make the playoffs two years ago and most recently lost in the
first round. Seattle is a place that will not frown upon being led
to the second or third round by Ewing, as was New York. It might
even be appreciative enough to pay him more millions to do it
again, and again.
</P>
<P>
   Cynicism of his motives must be tempered by those of the Knicks,
now maneuvering frantically to justify their consumer warfare on
the middle-class fan. In recent years, they paid Ewing whatever
they had to and catered to his every whim to protect the illusion
of contention around the man in the middle. Vin Baker? Glen Rice?
They are the available talent out there, not necessarily the stuff
of champions, of Walt Frazier three decades past. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
