<HEADER>
A8601 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-FIRM-COMPLAINTS-2NDTA     08-21 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRM-COMPLAINTS-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREER MARKETING FIRM DRAWS COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE and DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even so, critics say, it's hard to justify high counseling fees
when there are cheaper and equally effective ways to get
personalized career help to take advantage of a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   Many college-based programs, employment agencies and individual
advisers offer expert career coaching for $50 to $100 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Career Counseling Center at Johnson County Community College
offers services that range from life assessment and personality
tests to job search, resume writing and interview training. Clients
do mock interviews and get help networking through professional
associations.
</P>
<P>
   Even with extra coaching job seekers would be hard-pressed to
spend more than $500 on a custom program. ``There are different
pieces. Course work depends on where the person is at and what his
or her preference is,'' Laura Johannesmeyer, the community career
counseling coordinator, said. Last year the center helped 700
people make career decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hughes attended three job-coaching sessions at the college
at a cost of $50 a session. ``I didn't need a whole battery of
tests. What I needed to do was narrow my focus,'' he said. A
licensed psychologist, Hughes has been exploring jobs in the
nonprofit market.
</P>
<P>
   By far the cheapest way to finance a job search is to do it
yourself. And there are plenty of self-help guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need someone to hold your hand eight hours a day, maybe
the career counseling service is the way to go for you,'' said
Martin Yate, author of the national best-selling job-seeker's
handbook Knock 'Em Dead, used in many job-search courses. It
retails for $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you are a motivated person who can tell your elbow from
a hole in the ground, you can get all these things in books for a
few dollars or free on the Internet,'' Yate said.
</P>
<P>
   Yate's latest self-help effort is his Web site: careerbrain.com,
which features video lectures, resume advice, job links and a
six-page, free personality assessment.
</P>
<P>
   He said there is nothing exotic about a ``hidden market,'' which
he said has become a lucrative sales pitch used by career marketing
companies to make their services appear ultrasophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it refers to are jobs you don't happen to see in the
Sunday newspaper. Tapping the hidden job market is simply
networking, using the newspaper, the Internet, associations and
professional organizations, people you know and your references.''
</P>
<P>
   Costly career counseling might appeal to those who feel lost,
Yate said. ``But you have to ask, `Would I feel a little less lost
if I kept some money in my bank account?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Haldane is different from some other career counseling
firms. It is primarily a ``retail'' operation that prospects for
individual clients. In contrast, other career marketers work solely
for corporate clients who pay the bills. A company might pay for
``outplacement'' services for employees who are downsized or
executives who are let go.
</P>
<P>
   A company might also pay fees to placement or staffing agencies
that send them job candidates. In either case, the employer, rather
than the individual job hunter, pays the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Hoyt &AMP; Associates, another employment firm, charges
corporate clients a contingency fee to recruit employees. But it
also offers services to individuals at an installment or hourly
rate. ``You don't have to pay a large fee up front,'' said owner
Ron Like.
</P>
<P>
   Independent career counselors say services should seldom run
into the thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Rodenbough, a principal of Trouble at Work, charges
between $250 and $500 for individual services. ``I can't understand
how something like that could cost $5,000,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Russell, an individual career counselor, said job hunters
should look beyond the cost to check out the backgrounds of the
advisers, especially those who charge high-dollar fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the quality varies a lot,'' she said. It's
important, she said, to know if you are ``talking to a counselor or
a marketer.'' You should choose someone who will help ``focus your
efforts, help motivate and coach you, and give you practical
suggestions.'' Job hunters should be able to get all this and more
and for less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Boas, chief executive of Boas Associates, a human
resources and career development consulting firm, said consumers
should be skeptical of any firm that charges a large up-front fee.
</P>
<P>
   Boas, president of the Human Resources Management Association of
Greater Kansas City, said a fee of as much as $3,000 might be a
reasonable expense for extensive career advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that should cover everything from beginning to end,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Phelps, who is now searching for a job on her own: ``For
$6,000, I think I deserved something better.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0531 </DOCNO>
