u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-1STL     08-21 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' DEAL TO TRADE EWING TO SEATTLE FALLS THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS: Trade is called off. Pls. note story is no longer on Page
One)   
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing, the stoic 7-foot center who for 15
years tried to be the player to bring a championship to the New
York Knicks, was on the brink of being traded Monday night before a
four-team, 13-player deal collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, a 38-year-old veteran, was to be the centerpiece of the
blockbuster deal, a National Basketball Association official said
on condition of anonymity. But the Detroit Pistons, who were set to
acquire seven lesser-known players in the deal, called off the
trade because they did not want to assume four of the players'
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks were going to give the Pistons money, and the whole
deal was about to be done,'' said an Eastern Conference team
official, ``but the contracts became a mess. There were just too
many red flags.''
</P>
<P>
   In the proposed trade, Ewing would have gone to Seattle, while
the Knicks would have acquired forward Vin Baker from the
SuperSonics and forward Glen Rice and center Travis Knight from the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer of monster, multiteam deals that involved some of
the game's most prominent players _ Grant Hill ended up in Orlando
while Shawn Kemp is expected to be dealt to Portland _ the deal for
Ewing might have been the most immense and the most complicated.
</P>
<P>
   In the proposed trade, the Lakers would have received Chris
Dudley from the Knicks and Christian Laettner from the Pistons. The
Pistons, the fourth team in the deal, were trying to reduce their
payroll so that they could land a top-tier free agent next summer.
They were to take a number of role players from the three teams,
including Vernon Maxwell, Lazaro Borrell, Greg Foster, Vladimir
Stepania, John Celestand, Tyronn Lue and David Wingate.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dominating post players in the NBA's modern era,
Ewing was taken by the Knicks with the No. 1 selection in the 1985
college draft. New York fans were thrilled to get the scowling,
shot-blocking menace from Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has since led the Knicks into the playoffs 13 straight
years. With him, the Knicks advanced to the Eastern Conference
finals three times. In 1994, they came within a game of winning the
franchise's first title since 1973 before losing to the Houston
Rockets in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Holder of most major club records, Ewing ended last season as
the 14th-leading scorer in league history. He is fourth in blocked
shots and he played in his 1,000th game last season. Ewing is one
of seven players in NBA annals to spend 15 years with the same
team.
</P>
<P>
   If his longevity was impressive, though, his durability was
wearing thin. In the last three seasons, he missed 88
regular-season games because of injury. From a dislocated right
wrist to a partial tear in his left Achilles' tendon, his
production was severely limited by his health. He could not play in
the 1999 championship series against the San Antonio Spurs, a
series the Knicks lost in five games. He began last season on the
injury list.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ewing came back and silenced his critics for most of the
regular season. He started 62 games, and he dutifully took on a
reduced role in an offense suddenly powered by Allan Houston and
Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   But as the playoffs came, the old question began to re-emerge
outside and inside the locker room: were the Knicks better off
without Ewing? His plodding, halfcourt style came to be viewed as a
blight to the Knicks' new, high-octane outfit. He would miss two
games in the playoffs because of his Achilles' problem.
</P>
<P>
   In complete games without Ewing against the Indiana Pacers in
the past two postseasons, the Knicks went 5-1. Sprewell tried to
play down the controversy during the Indiana series in June,
saying, ``If we win the championship, Patrick has to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is scheduled to make $14 million this season, the last
installment of a four-year, $68 million contract signed in 1997.
But the Knicks balked when it came to talk of a contract extension,
a development that forced Ewing and David Falk, his agent, to
consider other options. Ewing's insistence on being compensated
beyond this season _ coupled with his growing disenchantment with
New York fans and news media _ made their decision to shop him NBA
more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   After giving Scott Layden, the general manager, a list of eight
teams he would not protest being traded to, Ewing waited for the
Knicks to make their move.
</P>
<P>
   There was much the conversation around the league on Monday as
the Knicks planned to part ways with their franchise center, the
oft-maligned, aging veteran who never delivered the championship to
New York he so desperately wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sad,'' O'Neal said before the trade was killed. ``You
always thought Patrick Ewing would retire in New York. That's what
everyone thought.''
</P>
<P>
   And it may still be the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
