<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-FIRM-COMPLAINTS-2TAKE     08-21 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRM-COMPLAINTS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREER MARKETING FIRM DRAWS COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE and DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Fluent in Portuguese, her college degree in
hand, Karol Phelps hoped to reap big bucks working for a
multinational company.
</P>
<P>
   What she didn't have was a big job offer.
</P>
<P>
   So she went to Bernard Haldane Associates in Overland Park,
Kan., one of 80 offices affiliated with the nation's largest career
counseling firm.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced by its ads that the company could place her in a
high-paying position, she plunked down $5,985 in advance on Nov. 5,
charging the fee to her credit card.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being introduced to a private network of
corporate bigwigs, Phelps spent hours copying names from newspaper
ads, Internet sites and databases. It was tedious work, much of
which she said she could have done on her own, and for far less
money.
</P>
<P>
   Now she wants her money back and has filed a complaint with the
Kansas attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make you feel they are very big and that they have a
secret network of people,'' she said. ``But they didn't have any
network that can help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for career counseling is growing as a robust economy
encourages professionals to seek new jobs or change careers. But
like Phelps, many job seekers say the services provided by some
career marketing firms fail to justify their large advance fees.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, California, Colorado and Kansas have taken legal
action against Bernard Haldane. The states alleged, among other
things, that the firm exaggerated its access to executives and
unadvertised jobs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 complaints against Bernard Haldane have been filed
with Kansas Attorney General Carla Stovall. No other large career
counseling service has been the subject of recent complaints in
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1999 national Bernard Haldane officials and the former
owners of the Overland Park franchise agreed to pay $80,000 to
settle complaints and legal costs. Without admitting wrongdoing,
the company agreed to refrain from using deceptive sales pitches in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Freeman, who bought the local franchise in November 1998,
said any problems were resolved. ``Certainly our record speaks for
the changes that have been made in the last two years,'' the
current owner said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Stovall said the attorney general is
investigating two new complaints against Bernard Haldane. ``Anytime
you get into this kind of money up front, consumers have to weigh
what this company is going to do for them that they can't do for
themselves,'' said Steven Rarrick, the deputy attorney general
overseeing the Kansas cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Haldane officials declined to discuss pending cases. But
they said their program is the best in the nation at teaching job
search skills, and they can point to many satisfied customers.
``Our commitment is to do everything we can for a client who puts
out the effort to be successful,'' said Stephen Briscoe, director
of career advising.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints, he said, result from misunderstandings. ``Our
contract specifically says in big print, we're not an employment
agency,'' he said. ``There are no guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lauri believed his contract with Bernard Haldane would
give him an edge in his search for a new job two years ago. The
warehouse manager had been laid off and his confidence was shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell you they have connections with almost every company
of any size in Kansas City. They say 90 percent of the jobs are
never advertised. It's the `hidden market.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But little panned out. His best offer was a job as a warehouse
rate clerk in Virginia at $9.50 an hour. ``By that time I was flat
upset with the whole situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tobin of Olathe said he approached Bernard Haldane after
the firm he worked for closed and he lost his sales manager job. He
said firm advisers told him they had ``special connections'' with
``decision makers'' in a wide range of professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was an exclusive employment agency, even though
they will tell you they are not an employment agency. It's like
they say, `We don't do this for everyone.' '' He paid $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lauri and Tobin filed complaints with the Kansas attorney
general's office and settled with Bernard Haldane more than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Local Bernard Haldane officials say, generally, that some
clients may become disgruntled after failing to take responsibility
for their own efforts. ``Those people who make an investment, make
it happen,'' said Briscoe, the director of career advising. ``Those
who don't, won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe said Bernard Haldane provides mentoring to people
uncertain how to search for a job on their own. ``Our goal is to
get you in front of people to network with,'' he said. He said he
can help a client get an interview in any of the city's biggest
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The program entails three main phases. The first includes
appraisals of a client's career goals and preparation for
interviews. A second phase entails assessing job offers. A third
phase assesses long-range objectives and career advancement. The
local office employs 12 persons, who include former educators,
military officials and sales people.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said the local office advises 450 clients annually. He
said a Bernard Haldane certificate makes a client ``specifically
more marketable.'' He compares the firm's advance fees and
no-refund policy to financing a college course: ``Why do you pay
for a college education up front?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Haldane has its staunch supporters, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were there when I needed them,'' said Craig Rodgers, who
said leads he developed through Bernard Haldane helped him land a
management job at a local Birch Telecom office after a yearlong
search.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, who moved from the military to the business world, said
he got help in preparing for interviews and in writing his resume.
``In the end,'' he said, ``I got the kind of job I was looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   L. Campbell Schutte said Bernard Haldane was ``a phenomenal help
in my decision to change careers'' from a vice president of a mail
order firm to an information systems consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Koranda, Overland Park's manager of international trade
development, said Bernard Haldane helped him polish his job
interviewing skills. ``I don't know if I could have successfully
changed careers without their assistance,'' said Koranda, a former
disc jockey.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed the cost is steep, but, he said, ``For myself, it was
worth it. I doubled my salary.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
