<SLUG> BC-FOSTER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9-YEAR-OLD STARTED FOSTER HOME FIRE, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
 HOME-FIRE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL and DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 9-year-old girl started the fire that
killed two sisters early Sunday at a group foster home, police said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said she squirted charcoal lighter fluid on a box of
stuffed animals in a first-floor classroom. She then ignited a
piece of paper on a gas stove and tossed it on the toys. Twelve
children were sleeping nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Missouri Division of Family Services on
Monday were investigating reports that only one staff member was on
duty when the fire started about 5 a.m. at the Early Childhood
Residential Center, 3911 Agnes Ave.
</P>
<P>
   They also said children would no longer be placed with the
agency if the family services division confirmed that only one
person was caring for 13 children.
</P>
<P>
   State regulations require that at least two staff members be
present overnight, with one awake at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this center was not in compliance, we will take the most
severe action we can,'' Denise Cross, director of the Missouri
Division of Family Services, said Monday from Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agency is very concerned,'' said Margaret Randle, Jackson
County administrator for the family services division.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities and neighbors said the employee _ with the help of a
good Samaritan _ ushered 11 children out of the burning building.
</P>
<P>
   Alexus Brown, 2, was found in her crib on the first floor.
Aliyah Brown, who turned 6 last week, was found in an upstairs
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Thompson, the center's treatment director, said Sunday that
the center had 18 to 20 staff employees, but that only one was
working at the time of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they were told that another employee was supposed to
be working Sunday but had called in sick.
</P>
<P>
   Directors of the center could not be reached for further comment
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Robert Beaird was out of town during
the weekend and learned of the fire Monday. He said he would meet
early today with staff to discuss possible charges.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the first time that the Early Childhood
Residential Center had staffing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cross said her agency suspended the center from child placement
earlier this year after complaints were filed alleging inadequate
staffing. The suspension meant that no new children were placed at
the center; those already there were allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension lasted about six weeks, from early March to
mid-April, Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked with them, and they made staffing changes,'' Cross
said. ``And we allowed them to resume taking children.''
</P>
<P>
   The victims and an older sister had been living in the home
since February, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the 9-year-old girl initially told them that a
masked man broke into the home and started the fire. The details of
her story, however, soon began to change.
</P>
<P>
   She altered the times of some events, the way the man broke in,
and his description. She then told detectives she started the fire
by squirting lighter fluid on the stuffed animals, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl told them that the fire blazed out of control and that
she went to alert the employee. She said that the woman was asleep
and that she did not want to wake her.
</P>
<P>
   Police had to stop questioning the girl at that time, and they
turned the girl over to juvenile authorities. State law prohibits
police from questioning juvenile suspects. They were allowed to
question the girl initially because they thought she was a witness.
</P>
<P>
   The employee told police she had folded clothes, watched
television and eaten a frozen dinner before falling asleep on a
chair in an upstairs room between 3 and 3:30 a.m. She awoke and
heard a man yelling.
</P>
<P>
   Two smoke detectors also sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Sean Jones, 27, had seen the fire from a nearby parking
lot and ran to the center, kicked in the front door and yelled,
``Fire!'' He helped herd 11 children outside.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to go back for the remaining two children, but the
smoke was too thick.
</P>
<P>
   According to its literature, the center was operated by the
Civic Registration Council, a community outreach organization
founded in 1977 to ``address the urgent and unmet needs of food,
clothing and shelter for low-income residents of Jackson County.''
</P>
<P>
   Children were placed at the center by the family services
division on a temporary or an emergency basis. Some had been abused
or neglected. Others came from families in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Randle said the center was the only emergency group foster home
on the Missouri side of the metropolitan area. The center was state
licensed _ which required it to meet standards, such as 24-hour
staffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to maintain staffing,'' Randle said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday division officials were studying files on the
surviving children and placing them in homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
