<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAYTON'S ERROR DOOMS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shortstop Royce Clayton has been the Texas Rangers'
most dependable defensive player this year. Manager Johnny Oates
has gone out of his way several times recently to make that point.
</P>
<P>
   But in a season that broke apart at the seams a long time ago,
nobody seems immune from the fate that has befallen the Rangers.
Clayton's bobble of Derek Jeter's third-inning potential
double-play ground ball went from a simple error to a disaster when
the New York Yankees scored six unearned runs and went on to beat
the Rangers, 12-3, at Yankee Stadium on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Brian Sikorski's second major-league start was a
complete reversal from his debut last week when he pitched seven
scoreless innings. This time he gave up nine runs in 41/3 innings
as the Rangers lost for the 13th time in 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just screwed up the play,'' Clayton said. ``I've played long
enough to know there are certain situations where you know an error
is going to come back to haunt you. The kid was pitching a pretty
decent game, he had worked out of some jams, and that play opened
up the inning. I'd rather strike out four times instead of making
an error that hurt my pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   This one did. The Rangers were leading 1-0 in the third when
Clay Bellinger led off with an infield single and Luis Polonia
walked. Jeter then hit a wobbly grounder, and Clayton hurried
trying to turn two, rather than settling for a force out. He
bobbled it, then pulled second baseman Frank Catalanotto off the
bag with his flip, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a play that requires a lot of effort,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sikorski got Paul O'Neill to pop out and struck out Glenallen
Hill, but he walked Tino Martinez to force in the tying run. Jorge
Posada then lined a two-run single to center, and the inning fell
apart. Singles by Luis Sojo, Scott Brosius and Bellinger _ two
bloops and a grounder through the right side _ made it 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking a run in doesn't help,'' Sikorski said. ``I felt good.
I felt for the most part I threw the ball where I wanted to. I
tried to control the damage, but they kept finding the holes.
They're not the defending champions for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton's superb year defensively has been marred by two costly
errors in the past five games. He had a key error with two outs in
the ninth inning Thursday night when he momentarily bobbled a
tricky grounder, allowing the Red Sox to rally with three runs
against closer John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively I've felt pretty good until the last couple of
games,'' Clayton said. ``I still feel good, but a couple things
happened that don't necessarily look good. But I was trying to make
some tough plays, and I don't think anybody can fault me for
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Oates, who said: ``Defensively he has been a bright spot.
Today he had a rough day.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been many like that for the Rangers, and Clayton
feels it as much as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, there's been a lot of frustration,'' Clayton said.
``It's been a rough year for the team and for me personally. I
haven't done what I'm capable of doing. Offensively I haven't
really been hot all year, but I'd like to get in a position where I
can finish strong.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about all anybody on the Rangers can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody here is giving up or throwing in the
towel,'' Clayton said. ``I go out there every day with my pride on
the line. You don't want to go out there and get beat on, make
mistakes or not do what you're capable of doing. Even if we're not
in the (playoff) picture, you still want to go out and win the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's getting harder and harder, and nobody seems immune in
any area. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
