<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ELECTRICITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CAPS ELECTRICITY RATES FOR SOME SAN DIEGO CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With electricity rates doubling or tripling for
some consumers in San Diego, the California Public Utility
Commission voted Monday to cap electric bills for some residential
and business customers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement left many people still unhappy, and several
experts said further regulations might be needed because of what
some have described as price gouging in the wholesale electricity
market and a system that leaped toward deregulation before
sufficient supplies were available.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision, on a vote of 3-2, would cap rates for many
residents of San Diego by about 43 percent, assuring that customers
who keep their consumption below certain caps would pay no more
than $68 a month through the end of the year. San Diego was the
first big market in California to be deregulated because its
principal gas and electric utilities merged earlier to form Sempra
Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Lynch, the president of the commission and an opponent
of the decision Monday, explained that the price caps would apply
only to individuals who use 500 kilowatts-hours or less a month,
about 60 percent to 70 percent of customers in the city. Customers
who use more than that will be charged the higher rates, she said.
The decision also applies to small-business customers that use
1,500 kilowatts-hours a month or less.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's mayor, Susan Golding, said one of her biggest
concerns was that the plan left important users, including public
schools and hospitals, at the mercy of a market that has seen
prices skyrocket. Golding said that while she generally favored
deregulation, it was ill-considered because the supply was clearly
inadequate to meet demand, particularly at a time when the economy
was booming.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even if demand weren't so strong, we still would be in
incredibly bad shape,'' Golding said.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's utility welcomed Monday's step as a temporary
measure that would be required only until new power plants become
operational, perhaps in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of deregulation on San Diego has been just awful,''
said Steve Baum, the chairman of Sempra Energy, which owns San
Diego Gas and Electric. ``This step as a smoothing mechanism has
been very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   The deregulation of the $20 billion electrical power industry in
the state resulted from a 1996 law that phases in the effects from
south to north. But the state has suffered power shortages that led
rolling ``brownouts'' in the San Francisco Bay area in June, in
addition to the price increases in San Diego. The average wholesale
price for San Diego electricity was $117 per megawatt-hour, up from
$25 per megawatt-hour at a comparable time last year, The
Associated Press quoted a member of the utilities commission, Carl
Wood.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time that the commission had retreated
slightly from its earlier decision to deregulate utilities in San
Diego, but it was seen as a larger move than in the past. It was
also characterized as a possible prelude to more restrictions
because of the soaring rates and concerns about inadequate
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said that an investigation was under way into why
wholesale rates had soared, and that the results of that inquiry
might be used to establish other restrictions, at least until new
supplies of electricity were built.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000821.0536 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-21 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     08-21 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A KNICKS LEGEND PAUSES TO REFLECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to change hed and rewrite throughout to reflect trade
collapse) 
By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a summer of so much trade talk that hovered
over the city like a suffocating blanket of stale hot air, a
genuine Knicks legend answered the telephone in his Manhattan
apartment Monday and sounded amazed that the biggest deal of all
might go down after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think it was going to happen,'' he said. ``To
be honest, I thought that you guys were just selling papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Frazier needed to be reminded that if he was traded when it
wasn't about the money, then why can't Patrick Ewing be dispatched
to Seattle when it apparently is?
</P>
<P>
   He chuckled, obviously delighted with this historical
perspective, and said: ``I guess we've all seen Ewing as part of
the Knicks for so long, we just assumed he would never play
anyplace else. And I guess people, even me, forget that it also
happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a long time ago, longer than I'd prefer to admit, as the
dealing of Frazier to the Cleveland Cavaliers (``Cleveland, come
on, man,'' is how he put it) occurred shortly before I was assigned
to follow the Knicks around with a suitcase and my trusty Olivetti
typewriter. I can still remember treading carefully into the
Cavaliers' locker room at the Richfield Coliseum one wintry night
in 1978, hoping this champion of my own adolescence, this one-time
embodiment of urban chic and cool, would cough up a few quotes on
life in the Cleveland 'burbs.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier wasn't in the best of moods, even months after being
informed of the deal by his agent, who was waiting for him when he
returned to his apartment late one Friday night. More than two
decades later, a modern multimillionaire star like Ewing at least
has the power to engineer his potential departure on more favorable
terms, relative to his earning power beyond next year.
</P>
<P>
   If Walt Frazier couldn't finish his career in New York, please
spare me any whining or wheezing about Ewing possibly moving on
after 15 fruitful yet also frustrating seasons. On judgment day in
the court of great players, Frazier is remembered as everything
Ewing is not. He was an improvisational genius, a showman who
connected with the crowd. And when his team found itself in a
seventh game, the championship riding on one 1970 spring night
against Wilt and the Lakers, Frazier responded with the game of his
adult life.
</P>
<P>
   If the 11th-hour edges of the proposed four-team trade are
resolved, if it is the end for Ewing in New York, no one can say
the 1990s Knicks didn't spend all they could to help put him in the
same position as Frazier, 30 years ago. The personnel moves weren't
always the best. The surrounding players were never as good. The
opposition, particularly in the person of Michael Jordan, was
almost always better. But Ewing did have Game 7 in Houston, 1994,
when it was he against Hakeem Olajuwon, and Ewing stood passively
back in the fourth quarter and watched his best championship
opportunity hoisted into oblivion by John Starks.
</P>
<P>
   The quest continued, and in the heat of the playoffs and in
recent seasons under painful conditions, it seemed courageous and
real. But there was always the other side of Ewing, whose stubborn
streak stretched well past the limits of pride. If Ewing is to
leave New York _ and it is difficult to imagine the Knicks pulling
him back now _ he will go because the organization made a perfectly
prudent decision not to extend a contract that is already
hopelessly inflated in terms of his 38-year-old worth.
</P>
<P>
   Someone close to Ewing said Monday that once the Knicks made it
clear that a contract extension was not forthcoming, his immediate
response was to caucus with his agent, David Falk, to plan a
strategy to obtain it elsewhere. That Ewing would be willing to go
to a team that is the fifth- or sixth-best in its conference speaks
volumes about his primary interest at the stage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle plays in the conference of the most recent champions,
San Antonio and Los Angeles, and of Duncan and Shaquille. But here
is the catch: the Sonics did not make the playoffs two years ago
and most recently lost in the first round. Seattle is a place that
will not frown upon being led to the second or third round by
Ewing, as was New York. It might even be appreciative enough to pay
him more millions to do it again, and again.
</P>
<P>
   Cynicism of Ewing's motives must be tempered with those of the
Knicks, who now maneuver frantically and perhaps foolishly to
justify their continuous warfare on the middle class fan. Over the
past decade, ticket prices have swelled, along with the franchise
player's head, as the Knicks indulged him every which way to make
him happy and maintain their illusion of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated when I got traded,'' Walt Frazier said. ``But
you know what? It turned out better for me. People equated the
Knicks' decline with my leaving, even though we were declining
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining or retooling, the Knicks won't be Patrick Ewing's
problem anymore if this deal is made, and he won't be theirs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
